<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE'S `HOUSE OF HORRORS' AWAITS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The celebration will begin at the Kingdome
should the Rangers win the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario reflects irony at its best.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome remains the Rangers' ``House of Horrors,'' and yet
that facility will serve as the site for their four remaining
regular-season games with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   One other matter: The division title will be at stake, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough place for us to play,'' Rangers right
fielder Juan Gonzalez said. ``I don't have any answers, and I can't
explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will enter tonight's game with only six victories
during their past 32 games at the Kingdome, and that includes the
Mariners' sweep of a two-game series there July 13-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' troubles at the Kingdome so troubled manager Johnny
Oates that he sought professional help during the 1997 season from
Dr. Don Beck, a sports psychologist for Denton's Human Values
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Beck suggested the Rangers create a different atmosphere at the
Kingdome, Oates recalled. Beck recommended that players change
lockers with one another, listen to different music in the
clubhouse and alter their menu at the stadium in an attempt ``to
change the routine,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The manager opted for none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in that stuff,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Why seek Beck's advice then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to see if he would say anything I agreed with,''
Oates replied. ``You know how stubborn I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Scott Bailes, who joined the Rangers during August
1997, continues to be puzzled by the amount of attention their play
at the Kingdome receives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happened in the past is so overblown here,''
Bailes said. ``Teams change so much from year to year with free
agency now that you can't put any validity on what's happened in
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   History, though, continues to repeat itself there, and Oates
pinpoints one reason for the Rangers' repeated failures at the
Kingdome. The Mariners' lineup includes shortstop Alex Rodriguez,
center fielder Ken Griffey Jr., designated hitter Edgar Martinez,
first baseman David Segui and catcher Dan Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been able to get them out,'' Oates said. ``We
haven't gotten that lineup out in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, will draw two breaks this time in Seattle.
The Mariners traded one noted Rangers pest _ second baseman Joey
Cora _ to the Indians earlier this summer, and right fielder Jay
Buhner underwent season-ending surgery Sept. 9 to repair his right
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, that will make a difference,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not embrace discussing their lack of success in
Seattle and often dismiss it as meaningless history.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened in the past is in the past,'' second baseman
Mark McLemore said. ``You can't rely on that. You can't. You just
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Can't also describes the Rangers' ability to win at the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refuse to believe that,'' McLemore said. ``All of it means
absolutely nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
