<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KEEPING AN EYE ON THE TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Late in the afternoon, long before a spare
outfielder named Brant Brown made a bid to initial Bill Buckner's
legacy, Al Leiter didn't see the point in wasting time with the
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing Sammy Sosa had already caught Mark McGwire by
homering twice. The Brewers were trailing, 7-0, and seemed deep
into the process of post-season dispersal. Leiter was making hasty
arrangements to get his wife and daughters out of Fort Lauderdale
and up to Atlanta before the airports in southern Florida closed
for a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like they'll win,'' he said, motioning to the bank of
televisions suspended from the Mets' clubhouse ceiling, in the
middle of the room. ``But think about it, what's the point of
watching? What can you control? You can control tonight. You can
control Friday night in Atlanta. Forget what they're doing over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Get to Atlanta, physically safe, mentally sound, before some
dreadful act of nature strikes, the way a tailing fly ball to left
field, the sun field, hit the Cubs on Wednesday like the weight of
90 championship-less years. The Mets, however, couldn't control
Wednesday night any more than they could hit a rookie pitcher, Carl
Pavano. They couldn't beat the Montreal Expos, again, losing by
3-0, failing to score after having the bases loaded with nobody out
in the seventh inning, and leaving two more runners on in the
eighth. The Mets go to play the Braves now, with no margin of
error, still tied with the pinching-themselves Cubs, the Giants
suddenly one loss behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two teams of destiny,'' Turk Wendell, the Mets' hyper
reliever, had called the Mets and Cubs before the game. After
Wednesday, who would swear they aren't destined to lose?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves would love to knock the Mets out so that they can
avoid San Diego in the first round. That this September happening
concludes with the Mets in Atlanta is deliciously fitting, another
twist in a season we can't take our eyes off. The Mets fight for
survival now against the ruler of their division, a team supposedly
out of their league.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Mets won on Wednesday night, accepted Brant Brown's
gift, they might have gone to Atlanta on Thursday thinking it was
their destiny to be this year's Marlins, who clouded the Braves'
confidence last September by winning three of four in Atlanta
before eventually leaving them awash in playoff tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see some similarities here, but to compare this club to the
Braves isn't fair,'' said Leiter, one of the many emigres from the
Marlins' 1997 World Series champions. ``They've done it and we
haven't. We've got to go down there now and be completely focused
on ourselves, not get caught up in all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   He made another sweeping motion with his left pitching arm,
without looking back at the screen, where the Brewers were in the
process of pushing across four runs to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I want the Cubs to lose, but I'm pitching Saturday
and, in my mind, I'm already working the Atlanta lineup,'' Leiter
went on. ``I'm thinking about Ozzie Guillen, Michael Tucker,
Chipper, Galarraga. Looking at who's doing what recently, looking
for anything that will get me an edge. If every player can focus on
their position, on what they have to do, that's the issue. That's
the only issue; all this scoreboard stuff isn't going to help you
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when it comes to playoff-race baseball, we are all
kids at heart, staring at the scoreboard, fiddling with the radio,
bracing for the bad news while praying for the good.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Mets Manager Bobby Valentine looked, distracted and
nervous, as he chatted with reporters near the Mets' dugout during
batting practice, the Brewers' Geoff Jenkins batting in Milwaukee
against Rod Beck with the bases loaded and two out in the ninth. A
30-year-old fan from Union, N.J., Michael Adler, held a radio to
his ear and offered play-by-play from the first row, courtesy of
WFAN's drive-time hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy dropped the ball!'' Adler screamed, after Brown made
what was, for a few hours, an error for the ages. Valentine turned,
looking into the face of the fan who was now telling him the Cubs
had, incredibly, lost. When he turned back, his eyes were teary.
His voice was choked. His body was charged. Word spread quickly to
the field. And then, from the tunnel leading to the clubhouse,
bounding up the dugout steps, came one Met who believed he was
delivering headline news.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lost, Cubs lost,'' cried Al Leiter, who now had to admit
that the point of watching every part of what is once again a
three-team race is that you simply must. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
