<HEADLINE>
NO SLOWDOWN FOR BOWDEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Florida State was coming off a three-year period
of futility when Bobby Bowden showed up on the Tallahassee campus
in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   When Bowden finally leaves Tallahassee, the program will be in
much better shape, to say the least. But when will Bowden, who
turns 69 on Nov. 8, take his whistle and head home?
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the question, for what was certainly not the first
time, Bowden took a second to chuckle before predicting that it
could be 5, 10, 15 years before he's ready to quit worrying about
X's and O's and start working on the household chores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have the desire, anxiety and enthusiasm I've always
had,'' said Bowden, whose Seminoles play host to USC on Saturday.
``I have no desire to retire. I'd just as soon die out on the field
than pulling weeds in my wife's garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State was 4-29 in the three seasons before Bowden took
over and 5-6 in his first season. The Seminoles haven't finished
below .500 since. In his 22 years at FSU, Bowden is 210-52-4, and
his 1993 team won the national championship. The Seminoles have won
at least 10 games every year since 1987 and were ranked in the top
four in the final national poll each season during that span.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great coach,'' linebacker Lamont Green said, ``but what
I should say first is he's a great man. What stands out most is
he's a role model for the college athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one of Bowden's players have been selected All-American
and 70 have been picked in the NFL draft, including 17
first-rounders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always watched Florida State when I was growing up,'' said
USC safety Rashard Cook. ``I watched Charlie Ward, Warrick Dunn
(and) guys like that. They were always fun games to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook saw Florida State up close last year when the Seminoles
visited the Coliseum for a 14-7 season-opening victory over USC. On
Saturday, the Trojans visit Tallahassee's Doak Campbell Stadium,
where Florida State hasn't lost since Nov. 5, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   And Bowden says this Florida State team ``may have more speed
than we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   That's saying something when you consider this is the same
program that produced players like Deion Sanders and Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a choice of fast or slow, fast wins nine times out of
10,'' FSU defensive end Tony Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   The team speed is spread all over the field and both sides of
the ball. Receiver Peter Warrick is this year's Seminoles Heisman
Trophy candidate and sophomore running back Travis Minor is a
bigger, just as speedy version of Dunn. Green is a
sideline-to-sideline talent at linebacker and the defensive
backfield is full of sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles also already have a loss _ a shocking 24-7 setback
to North Carolina State on Sept. 12. That defeat, only the second
Florida State loss in the ACC in six years of conference
membership, caused the Seminoles to slide out of the top 10 for the
first time in 61 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Florida State, you are allowed one error,'' said Bowden,
whose team fell to No.11 after the loss. ``With one error, you
might still win the big one. This is the first time we've lost this
early in the year since (1989). The thing you have to do when you
lose is not look down the road. You have to look at the next
Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting to the next Saturday, at least last week, made for a
long seven days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the five years I've been here,'' Green said, ``it's
probably the toughest week I've had. We didn't think a team like
North Carolina State should beat us. We know we can't slip up any
more the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles used the week full of bad feelings to whip up
enough anger to pound Duke 62-13 on Saturday. Sophomore quarterback
Chris Weinke, who threw six interceptions against N.C. State,
rebounded to hurl three touchdowns passes and no interceptions
against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The N.C. State loss) shows they are beatable,'' Cook said.
``But that means nothing to me. We didn't do it. If anything, it
may make them play harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, Bowden is worried about getting his team
healthy. Weinke is one of 10 players hit with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 10 players that couldn't practice today and eight of
them were receiving IVs during practice,'' Bowden said
``Practically the whole offensive line and Weinke are out.''
</P>
<P>
   And the gardening duties will wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
