<HEADLINE>
ANGELS USE SCREAM THERAPY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Several Anaheim Angels players came to the
defense of pitching coach Marcel Lachemann on Wednesday, saying his
reported outburst Tuesday was nothing more than strong words of
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Lachemann and pitcher Chuck Finley took turns talking to the
team after Tuesday's 9-1 loss to the Rangers. And though the noise
level was significant, none of it was to rip the players or put
them down, players said.
</P>
<P>
   Angels closer Troy Percival said too much was made of the
postgame events, and that Lachemann reminded everybody that in 1995
the Angels rallied from a three-game deficit with five to play,
forcing a one-game playoff with Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Lachemann said his comments were meant to make the players
believe in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins was speaking with reporters in a separate
room when some of the yelling was going on. When he found out it
was Finley, Collins was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I liked about (Tuesday) night was that we've got a
guy who really cares,'' Collins said. ``I don't care if Chuck
Finley tore the clubhouse up. This guy really cares. You want to
find 25 guys who care so much, everything else is secondary. If
everybody's on the same page and cares that much, you're going to
win a lot of ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Left-field shuffle: Outfielder Gregg Jefferies told Collins
that he could play Wednesday, but Collins started Todd Greene in
left field instead. Jefferies had to come out of Tuesday's game
when he aggravated his strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `If I only get you for one at-bat, I'll pick my
spot for that,' '' Collins said. ``He plays the game real hard.
He's been a great addition, but his leg's in bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferies, who has hit .352 in 18 games with the Angels, also
has a sprained right ankle and a bruised right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' decision to start Greene in left field over Orlando
Palmeiro left the Angels without a leadoff hitter. So Collins put
Garret Anderson in the top spot, the second time he's hit leadoff
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we need a leadoff hitter and Palmeiro's done a good job
for us,'' Collins said. ``But one thing we need is someone to drive
in runs. We've got this guy (Greene) sitting here and we had been
waiting for him all year. He's got power, so let's get him in the
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Closing time: Percival had not been in any of the previous
four games between the Angels and Rangers, simply because the
Angels haven't had a ninth-inning lead. But he says it's not
driving him crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game,'' he said. ``My job is to go in when
we've got a lead. I want the ball as bad as anybody, but it's not
my job unless we're winning.... But I want to be on the mound when
we win this thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
