<HEADLINE>
DODGERS REPLACE FARM DIRECTOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Charlie Blaney, the longtime Los Angeles Dodgers
farm director who oversaw the development of rookies of the year
Eric Karros, Mike Piazza, Raul Mondesi and Todd Hollandsworth,
stepped down Wednesday as part of general manager Kevin Malone's
front-office reshuffling.
</P>
<P>
   Blaney's ouster was the first of many moves expected from
Malone, who will hold a staff meeting today to discuss the future
of key positions, including manager Glenn Hoffman and his coaching
staff and scouting director Terry Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are very sensitive issues and the answers will not come
out of that meeting,'' Malone said. ``But it is important to let
everyone know where they stand and we will do that as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Those announcements are expected Monday or Tuesday. Blaney, who
was given a three-year personal services contract last winter when
Fox purchased the club from the O'Malley family, learned his fate
Wednesday. He officially accepted an early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud of what I accomplished here and proud of what
the Dodgers have done in the minor-league department,'' Blaney
said. ``Kevin and I had discussed doing some special projects in
the future. I look forward to helping any way I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to replace Blaney with his own man was one of
Malone's top priorities when he took over two weeks ago. Bill
Geivett, hired last week as an assistant to the general manager,
will take over Blaney's responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Geivett has unique talents and expertise in the area of
player development,'' Malone said. ``We can now use those talents
in strengthening our minor-league system as we prepare to take this
organization to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaney, who worked for the Dodgers since 1966, became farm
director in 1987, replacing Bill Schweppe. He was recognized as a
talented administrator and the Dodgers' minor-league system was
consistently graded among the best in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned so much from Charlie about the organization it takes
to run things,'' said Hoffman, who was Blaney's minor-league field
coordinator and Triple-A manager before his promotion last June.
``His attention to detail was unsurpassed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a string of five consecutive rookies of the year (Hideo
Nomo was not developed in the Dodgers farm system), Blaney's
undoing came from not being an evaluator of talent. That is one of
Geivett's strengths. Blaney also received criticism for twice
attempting to release Piazza early in his minor-league career.
Piazza, a 62nd-round pick in the 1989 draft, went on to become the
club's top player before getting traded last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one out of 10 players make the major leagues,'' Blaney
said. ``I am glad to have known the other nine, the coaches and the
scouts. It was an honor to work with so many dedicated people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
