<HEADLINE>
HELLING PUTS ASIDE THE BUBBLY, AND THE INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There's something about the fragrance of
champagne in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true when it's the stale stench of bubbly that
thoroughly soaked into your clothes 10 hours earlier during the
delirium of a championship celebration.
</P>
<P>
   It stings the eyes, chills the skin, and, when taken orally,
enhances the giddy feeling of an agonizing mission finally
accomplished. Given a few hours to ripen, it can turn a brand new
golf shirt into a reeking souvenir in need of serious fumigation.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the champagne belongs to Rick Helling, that is.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, an hour after a commanding performance had
carried the Rangers to a huge 9-1 victory against the Angels and
Helling to his 20th victory of the season, a magnum of bubbly lay
on its side in a stainless steel bowl of melting ice in front of
his locker.
</P>
<P>
   It was a gift from Helling's appreciative teammates to mark the
occasion. It was a nice gesture, even though the 27-year-old
right-hander doesn't drink alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do with it,'' Helling said.
``Maybe I'll save it and give it to someone, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, there's a lot of bottles (of champagne) spraying
around in here in the next couple of days, or whatever locker room
we're in. That'll be the sweetest champagne anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. Helling is all about winning and he knows
that, by winning 20 games, he has crossed the invisible Rubicon and
into the realm of pitching glory. He is only the third pitcher in
Rangers history to win 20 games _ Ferguson Jenkins and Kevin Brown
were the other two _ and becomes just the third pitcher in the
majors to win 20 this season, joining Roger Clemens and Tom Glavine
in that select company.
</P>
<P>
   But if ever a 20-win season was the product of an entire team,
this one is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the team I play with,'' Helling said graciously. ``If I
was pitching for a lower-echelon team, a team below .500, then I
wouldn't have 20 wins. I've pitched some good games this year, but
you've got to give all the credit to this team and the way it
scores runs and plays defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not all the credit. Helling, with his burr haircut and
broad, square-jawed face, doesn't just bear a striking resemblance
to a bulldog, he pitches like one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it all year,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``Rick
pitches to whatever level he needs to. If we've scored six, he
might give up four. But if we've scored one, he won't give 'em
any.''
</P>
<P>
   That was exactly the case Tuesday night, when Helling held the
Angels in check for seven innings, protecting a 1-0 lead. He didn't
allow a run until the Rangers had blown it open with eight more
runs in the seventh and eighth innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was a point of pride for Helling that he did it despite a
sharp pain between his shoulder blades that has persisted for
almost a week now. Rangers trainers suspect a possible stress
fracture in one of his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main goal (Tuesday night) was to just go out and pitch the
game and let whatever happens happen,'' Helling said. ``I wasn't
going to let the pain stop me. I was able to focus it out a little
bit better than I did at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to concentrate because of the pain, Helling lasted less
than two innings against the Angels last week in a game the Rangers
rallied to win, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   If you were watching on television, you may have seen him
sitting alone in the dugout after he was pulled from the game,
holding his head in his hands, rubbing a hand over his bristly
hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `What a night to have my worst game of the
year.' It was the first time I've ever pitched in pain like that,''
Helling said, ``and I'm thinking, `Why does this happen now?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was feeling a little sorry for myself, sitting on
the bench, thinking, `This can't be happening.'''
</P>
<P>
   The worst, though, was hearing the whispered suggestions that
maybe the pressure was too much for him. Pressure? This was the guy
who'd once stared down the Cubans in the '92 Olympic Games when he
was just 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the little mumblings, `He's not a big-game pitcher;
he's never pitched in a game like this before. That had nothing to
do with it,'' Helling said, ``but everybody wants to figure out why
I pitched a bad game.''
</P>
<P>
   The important thing was that it didn't happen Tuesday night,
when his dominating performance helped the Rangers extend their
American League West lead to two games.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the magnum of champagne sat in Helling's locker,
still unopened, destined to eventually find its way to his trophy
case.
</P>
<P>
   But consider this fair warning: The next bottle he gets his
hands on ... well, you might not want to come around unless you're
wearing a raincoat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
