<SLUG> BC-BABY-BOOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCKY FERTILITY TICKET YIELDS QUADRUPLETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ For three years, Tony and Shawna Brino tried just
about everything, from home remedies to fertility treatments, to
get pregnant. But in the end, the secret to their success was a
door prize.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as his daughter and three sons curled and
stretched their tiny bodies in their incubators at the hospital's
neonatal intensive-care unit, Tony Brino recalled how their journey
to life began.
</P>
<P>
   Shawna Brino, 29, gave birth to healthy quadruplets Monday at
Kaiser Permanente Medical Center in the L.A. suburb of Woodland
Hills almost a year after the couple, from Rosamond, Calif., landed
the winning raffle ticket for one free in vitro fertilization
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   His wife tricked him by inviting him to attend what he thought
was a real estate seminar, he joked. Instead, the meeting was a
fertility seminar at the Antelope Valley Fertility Institute in
Lancaster. At the door, everyone was handed a ticket for a free
chance at an $8,500 procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, I didn't even know what in vitro fertilization was,''
quipped Tony, 40, an avionics technician for the government. ``All
I knew was the old-fashioned way.''
</P>
<P>
   When the winning number was called, Shawna jumped for joy,
knowing they had won a chance at having children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at our ticket and asked: What do we get? A TV?'' Tony
said. ``She said, No, even better. The rest is history.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that when he learned exactly what he and his wife had
won, he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I didn't realize that it would come to this,'' he
said, smiling as he watched over Nikolas, Lorenzo, Zachary and
Myrinda, who were born by Caesarean section with no complications.
</P>
<P>
   For Shawna, the raffle ticket was the couple's salvation for a
procedure they had considered, but could not afford. Typically, in
vitro fertilization is not covered by medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is used when there is an impediment to the union
of sperm and egg in the uterus. The process involves giving hormone
treatment to the mother-to-be to produce several eggs, removing the
eggs from the ovaries and mixing them with sperm until a blastocyst
_ an embryo in its early stages _ is formed. The blastocyst is then
implanted in the mother's uterus and the pregnancy proceeds
normally.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of children born in multiple births is rising
nationwide, quadruplets remain relatively rare in Southern
California. For instance, 11 sets of quads were born in 1992 in Los
Angeles, according to the most recent statistics from the county
Department of Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstatic at her luck that night, Shawna Brino rushed home and
began calling friends and family with the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into debt hundreds of thousands of dollars wasn't
something we really wanted to do,'' said the new mother, who worked
as a cashier at Sears before entering Kaiser Permanente in June for
full-time supervision. Dr. Patricia Schmidt helped her make it
through the pregnancy, which lasted almost 34 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Brinos learned early on that they would have multiple
babies, but they were shocked when they were told of the
quadruplets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was astounding,'' said Shawna. ``I didn't even know what to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband said the quads would be in keeping with their
houseful of pets, which includes five dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's no big deal,'' he said. ``We have a lot of fish,
we have a lot of dogs, we have a lot of kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we'll be able to handle it. We're overwhelmed, sure.
But we'll just have to go through a period of adjustment. No more
tennis for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As his children came into the world Monday afternoon within a
span of two minutes, Tony Brino was left speechless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I have things to say in my life,'' he said, ``but in
that moment I had nothing to say. I was in a state of awe.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple won't be alone in caring for their brood. Shawna's
mother is on her way from Colorado to stay with the family. And
Antonio, Tony's 16-year-old son from a previous marriage, already
has been designated as part-time nanny.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be our helper now, whether he knows it or not,''
Tony said. ``I told him: Get a few girlfriends. You have my
permission now.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing the quadruplets will be a challenge for the couple, who
have sold their three-bedroom home and are searching for a bigger
one.
</P>
<P>
   As news of their babies spread, the couple began receiving gifts
like bassinets, car seats and other baby products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even people that didn't like me called me up saying, I have
this for you,'' Tony said. ``People reach down into their hearts.
I've been so overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Donations can be sent to St. Mary's of the Desert Catholic
Church, 3100 15th St. Rosamond, CA 93560. Or call (805) 256-4505 on
Wednesday through Friday from 3 to 6 p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
