<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO EITHER THE CUBS OR THE METS WANT THE WILD-CARD SPOT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Milwaukee Brewers had just wiped out more than
half of the Chicago Cubs' 7-0 lead and had runners at first and
second with only one out. Felipe Alou, the Montreal Expos' manager,
sat in the visiting manager's office at Shea Stadium and didn't
take his eyes off the small television set.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the game in Milwaukee, Sammy Sosa had electrified the
County Stadium crowd by slugging his 64th and 65th home runs,
catapulting himself into a tie with Mark McGwire for the running
home run record and sending a message to the Mets, who would have
to beat the Expos later in the day to match what looked like a sure
Chicago victory and maintain their wild-card tie with the Cubs. But
now, in the seventh inning, the Cubs led, 7-4, and Alou was
intrigued with the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they blow this game,'' the veteran manager said, ``they
don't win another game. This is a game of momentum. Everybody's
celebrating two home runs by Sosa and suddenly you get beat, it
takes two weeks to recuperate. And they don't have two weeks to
recuperate.''
</P>
<P>
   In his homeland, the Dominican Republic, Alou is called
``profeta,'' the Spanish word for prophet. He is known as a deep
thinker, and his pronouncements are taken seriously. The Mets were
ready to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs got two fly balls and escaped the inning with their
shrunken lead. But before long, the game was in the ninth inning,
the lead was down to two runs and the Brewers had the bases loaded
with one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we were talking about,'' Alou said to his
visitor, who had returned to watch the denouement. ``You lose a 7-0
lead and you have to take a four-hour plane ride to Houston. It
would be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs got the second out on a foul pop and appeared to have
the victory in hand when Geoff Jenkins lofted a seemingly routine
fly ball to left field. Brant Brown went back toward the warning
track, circled the ball, came in a couple of steps and put his
glove up for the game-ending catch. Clank.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the ball that hit in the glove and popped out was
rolling away, and all three Milwaukee runners were scampering to
the plate. Without a play there, all three scored and the Cubs,
dazed and stunned, walked lifelessly off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Could the wind have carried the ball just far enough away from
Brown to cause that incredible finish? Shaking his gray-topped head
no, Alou said simply, ``Pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, thinking of the game ahead, he said, ``That should be a
lift for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alou's Expos wound up giving the Cubs a lift instead. Just
when a Mets victory could have inflicted additional psychic damage
on the Cubs, irreparable damage perhaps, the Mets inexplicably
cowered before mighty Montreal and lost, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way a team in the Mets' advantageous position should
lose a game like this, but the Mets found a way. Just as they did
when John Franco squandered a lead on the threshold of victory in
Houston last week, the Mets squandered a chance to take the
wild-card lead on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The lead was theirs to take, and they did not take it. Did
someone say pressure? This failure might have been worse because
the Cubs handed the Mets the opportunity of a September. Failing to
capitalize on it, the Mets, despite thier recent rash of
late-inning heroics, have to question their desire, their character
and their ability. This was their eighth loss to the Expos in 12
games. The Expos played 10 other teams this season that have
winning records. But the Expos don't have a winning record against
any of those other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McRae was asked why the Expos played so well against the
Mets this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like us,'' the Mets' outfielder said. ``Their
coaches don't like Bobby. They don't care too much for us. Not only
do they want to beat us just to beat us, but they don't like our
manager. That gives them incentive. They like to beat Bobby. They
enjoy beating us. You can tell. You talk to players on other teams
and you hear a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae wouldn't say what the Mets hear or why the Expos don't
like Bobby Valentine, though Valentine is probably one of the least
liked managers in baseball. But Alou denied that he harbored any
ill feeling toward Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Valentine very much,'' he said. ``I don't talk to all
of the managers. He's one guy I talk to. I owe him favors for use
of their facilities. He asks about a number of players. I give him
my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou felt the explanation for the Expos' mastery over the Mets
lay in the pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some well-pitched games against them,'' Alou had
said, ``and when you have well-pitched games, you have a shot at
winning the game.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest one was pitched so well it took six Expos pitchers
to complete the game. The platoon of pitchers held the Mets to
three hits. Do not look for any of the pitchers' names on any
future Hall of Fame roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' effort was as dismal as that of their fans, whose
reaction to them has been as inexplicable as their inability to
beat the Expos. The attendance was 29,728 for the final home game _
final regular-season home game? _ meaning Shea had more than 20,000
empty seats. If the Mets' enthusiasts have no more enthusiasm than
they demonstrated by their absence on Wednesday night, maybe they
don't deserve playoff games anymore than the Mets do.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
