<HEADER>
A1432 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-SCHOOLPROMO-LADN     09-24 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SCHOOLPROMO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR SIGNS BILL TO ENFORCE RULES FOR CHOOL SOCIAL PROMOTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gov. Pete Wilson has signed into law a bill that
will stop California schools from promoting failing students to the
next grade, calling the practice a massive deception by the
education system.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law that will first apply in the 1999-2000 school
year, students who are not performing at grade level at the end of
the term will have to attend summer school or take other remedial
tutoring. If they do not progress, they will be held back, Wilson
told a crowd of children during the bill's signing Wednesday at La
Ballona Elementary School in Culver City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   California schools have in the past participated in a ``massive
deception where they graduate high school students that are
functionally illiterate,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Wilson, ``Yes, some children will be held back and that
can be painful. But, it is nowhere near the pain they will suffer
being held back from a good job or a college education.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many students are passed on every year
even though they are performing below grade level. Los Angeles
Unified School District officials estimate anywhere from 20 percent
to 80 percent are permitted to advance even though they do not meet
academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   An LAUSD task force, already examining the elimination of social
promotion, welcomed the governor's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared and ready to move forward,'' said Brad Sales,
an LAUSD spokesman. ``Recommendations will be brought to the
superintendent next month. And, we're looking at resources and how
to align them to begin ending social promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   The LAUSD immediately will begin to offer more remedial programs
and might decide to retain students as early as the end of this
school year.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson also signed legislation Wednesday that would provide
additional funds for summer school or other tutoring programs _ for
a total of $155 million to be made available to California schools.
</P>
<P>
   But LAUSD officials have said the money they could expect, some
$18 million, will not begin to fund the amount of remedial classes
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education member David Tokofsky, who said he believes
as many as 80 percent of Los Angeles students are not performing at
grade level, said the task will require Herculean efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to need a focused, intense, singular effort with
the mission of improving literacy,'' Tokofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Tokofsky said the district must totally re-examine the way it
spends its federal money for underprivileged children, and divert
much of it to remedial programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sales said the district also could seek additional legislation
to provide more money to fund the remedial programs.
</P>
<P>
   The law states that a student's performance will be gauged on
grades and scores on the Stanford 9 standardized test, which is now
given to every child in California in grades 2-11.
</P>
<P>
   Districts will be required to hold back poor performing students
in grades 2, 3, 4 as well as the grades between elementary and
middle school, and middle and high school. In the LAUSD, those are
grades 5 and 8.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers will have more authority to determine whether a child
should not be held back, but must provide an achievement plan to
improve the student's grades.
</P>
<P>
   Marni Anderson, a third-grade teacher at La Ballona said she
welcomes the mandatory remediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've offered summer school in the past, but a lot of parents
don't take advantage of it,'' Anderson said. ``This law will put
pressure on the families to give children the help they need.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
