<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDS-HNS &LR;      09-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ST. LOUIS _ While Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa compete for one of
baseball's most revered individual accomplishments, the Astros
reached a team benchmark Wednesday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They joined the Century Club.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won their 100th game of the season with a 7-1 victory
over the St. Louis Cardinals at Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are the third team this season to reach 100, joining
the New York Yankees (110) and Atlanta Braves (103).
</P>
<P>
   Since 1962, only 18 National League teams have won 100 games in
a season. Before this season, the closest the Astros had come was
96 victories in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, when you talk about the really fine teams, you don't
talk about teams that won 99,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``I
think this reaffirms what we believed _ that we're as good a club
as there is around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had to be at the top of their game Wednesday because
Randy Johnson needed some help. Johnson won his seventh straight
decision, despite allowing a first-pitch home run to Pat Kelly and
six walks, tying a season high.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the walks were to McGwire and drew loud boos from the
crowd of 38,997.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way you can say he was tenacious, and another way you
could say he was lucky,'' said Dierker, whose club won for just the
fourth time in its past 10 games. ``He just really didn't have good
control, and at the beginning he didn't have very good stuff, for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the innings went on, he began to pick up velocity, but he
never did really find his control.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros found their bats, which had been missing in a
4-0, five-hit loss to St. Louis on Tuesday. They needed only 10
batters to reach that total Wednesday, staking Johnson to a quick
3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can get runs early in the game, it makes a
pitcher's job that much easier,'' said Johnson, who allowed eight
hits and struck out eight in seven innings in his final tuneup for
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Sosa tied McGwire earlier in the day with home runs
No. 64 and 65 at Milwaukee. The Astros kept it that way, but just
barely.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went 1-for-3 Wednesday with a single and two walks. But
in his last two at-bats, his long, high fly in the seventh inning
was caught at the warning track, and he went deeper _ but in the
wrong direction _ in flying out to the center-field track in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went 1-for-7 with two strikeouts in the two-game series
with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled all night with my mechanics and control,'' Johnson
(10-1) said. ``Not only did I walk him (McGwire) twice, but I
walked four other guys. I walked the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans obviously wanted to see him hit a home run. I wasn't
trying to walk him. I always relish an opportunity to pitch against
someone like him. That's how you base your performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was aware that each time McGwire stepped to the
plate, a special ball, stamped in the event of a home run, was
used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take my warm-up pitches when he was on deck, and when
he came to the plate they would switch the balls,'' Johnson said.
``You warm up with a ball, and all of a sudden you get another ball
and it's not rubbed up. You have to make a little adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sent St. Louis starter Darren Oliver out early,
scoring three runs in the first inning and another in the second as
the Cardinals had their six-game winning streak snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo was 3-for-4 with a pair of doubles, and Moises
Alou had three singles.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who beat St. Louis for the second time in 11 days,
improved to 7-0 with a 1.16 ERA in his last seven starts. He has
allowed only seven earned runs in his last 54 innings.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis had the bases loaded twice against Johnson and had two
runners on base on five occasions. But each time the Cardinals
threatened, Johnson answered.
</P>
<P>
   One-hundred victories was a special occasion for the Astros _
and Johnson has accounted for one-tenth of the total in his short
stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to show you what type of pitcher he is,'' Craig Biggio
said. ``He really never gives in and makes quality pitches when he
has to. That's one thing I noticed when he came over here. He's not
a thrower; he's a pitcher. He throws 96 to 97 mph, and he pitches.
It's kind of nice to have on your side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not have had his best stuff, but he gave us a
chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
