<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1437 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC--HARDEMAN-HNS &LR;      09-24 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC--HARDEMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Texas A&AMP;M fullback D'Andre Hardeman was declared ineligible
Wednesday, forcing A&AMP;M to forfeit a win over Louisiana Tech and
sending the Aggies' bowl contention into a confusing jumble that
could become an NCAA test case.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hardeman, a senior from North Shore, was ruled out for the
season because of a clerical error in which the wrong grade for a
summer course was recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a posting error in the grades over the summer,'' Texas
A&AMP;M athletic director Wally Groff said. ``It was discovered once it
came up in a computer. He would have been ineligible if it was
discovered in August, but it wouldn't have been near as
embarrassing to him, his family and his teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   It also wouldn't have caused the potential ramifications to the
A&AMP;M season.
</P>
<P>
   If A&AMP;M wins seven games on the field this season but the forfeit
reduces the Aggies' record to 6-6, A&AMP;M would not qualify for a
bowl, said Mark Jones, an NCAA enforcement director and liaison to
the NCAA football certification subcommittee. With the forfeit, A&AMP;M
is 1-2 (Hardeman was held out of Saturday's 24-6 victory over
Southern Mississippi) and must win six of its remaining nine games
to qualify for a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language is six wins and a winning season,'' Jones said of
the bowl-qualification requirements. ``On the face of the rule
itself, if there is a forfeiture it's designed to say we're giving
up this victory, and then it wouldn't satisfy the rule. If you end
up 6-6 by virtue of a forfeiting, you wouldn't be a `deserving
winning team' as required by the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forfeiture is supposed to mean just that. It could be
something that is appealed, or subject of a request for
interpretation. I don't think this has ever happened. A school in
this spot might want to test that rule and see what is really
intended.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said it would not be considered relevant that one of the
A&AMP;M losses was in an extra game, the Kickoff Classic against
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   But there is language in the NCAA Manual to allow for exceptions
to the ``winning season'' requirement. A conference may request a
waiver if its champion does not have the required six Division I-A
wins or a winning record, and its league has only one guaranteed
bowl spot. The Big West earned such a waiver last season to allow
Utah State to play in the Humanitarian Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many teams have forfeited games after accepting bowl bids
and have been allowed to compete. More often, forfeits are
announced after the season (including Big 12 members Texas Tech and
Colorado last season) and have no bearing on bowl ramifications for
the teams forfeiting games or winning in a forfeit.
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 senior associate commissioner Donnie Duncan said it was
too early to know if the Big 12 would, if necessary, request such a
waiver for A&AMP;M because the entire league membership would have to
vote on such a request by A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to just win at least six of them and make it a moot
question,'' Groff said. ``It might be something to pursue at a
later date.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Hardeman, a senior, never has redshirted, A&AMP;M could
request an additional season of competition should he regain his
academic eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed to learn that Tiki Hardeman will be
ineligible this season,'' A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said. ``This is a
loss for our team and a big disappointment for this young man.
Hopefully, he can turn this into a positive by rededicating himself
in the classroom and regaining his eligibility for next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman had rushed for 105 yards and four touchdowns in the
first two games of the season, including three touchdowns against
Louisiana Tech. The 5-10, 232-pound fullback has been one of A&AMP;M's
all-time most prolific scorers with 30 career touchdowns, including
18 in 1996, one shy of the school record. His 95-yard run that
season is the longest in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I presented to the team a best-case scenario and a worst-case
scenario,'' Slocum said. ``The worst-case scenario is we know Tiki
will not be with us in the games and that (the forfeit) would be a
loss in the eyes of the bowls and the polls. We know we have to win
six more games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best-case scenario is if we continue to win and (the NCAA
certification subcommittee) would consider this, even though it's a
forfeit, like it's a win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
