<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1438 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA--YANKEES-HNS &LR;      09-24 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA--YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Joe Torre, his leathery face a visage of affability and
composure, is not the complaining type. His favorite word is an
approving ``Wow.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   TorreBut last week the low-key manager of the New York Yankees
delivered a stern lecture to his players. The themes he emphasized
were sloppiness and waning concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can just turn it on,'' he said. ``You always want to
stay focused, to stay sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-August, baseball's most mythologized franchise was on
pace to break the major-league record for victories in a season.
It's a record many people assumed the Yankees, with their
pin-striped pantheon of Ruth, Gehrig, DiMaggio, Mantle and Maris,
possessed.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one of baseball's ironies that the 116 wins were
accomplished _ in 1906 _ by those enduring symbols of futility, the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs' standard survives only because the Yankees have been
curiously average over the past month and a half. They have won
only 18 of their past 36 games.
</P>
<P>
   They put away the American League East on Sept. 9 _ the earliest
clinching by a Yankees team since divisional play began in 1969.
After the champagne shower, Torre expected ``a falloff _ but not
the sort of fall-down we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   He was happier Wednesday night, after his team won 8-4, its
third consecutive victory over the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The four-game series in Yankee Stadium might have been a preview
of the AL Championship Series, although it was no indicator of team
strength. Torre and Cleveland's Mike Hargrove were ``hiding'' their
best pitchers and resting star players.
</P>
<P>
   As Torre said, ``I think Mike and I are doing the same thing,
asking players when they come into the clubhouse, `Do you want to
play?'''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Wednesday's game resembled spring training (the
starters were Jason Jacome and Mike Jerzembeck), it had historic
value. It was the Yankees' 110th victory, which tied the club
record set in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' Torre said. ``That's Babe Ruth's team. If that's the
only record we get, being mentioned in the same breath as the 1927
Yankees, I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have four more games to reach their next goal, which
is the AL record of 111 wins, set by the 1954 Indians _ in 154
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing with enough intensity right now,'' Torre said.
``Since our team meeting last week, I've felt better about our
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, questions linger about the pitching rotation. Torre
hasn't decided who will be in it and in what order.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells, 18-4 with a perfect game and a 3.48 ERA, is the
obvious ace. But the round-bellied lefthander is undergoing back
therapy, and he looks more suited to leading the pitching staff to
the buffet line rather than into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Torre has hinted that Orlando ``El Duque`` Hernandez, 11-4 with
a 3.18 ERA, could start No. 1 because he can be counted on to
bounce back and pitch a second time in a five-game series, if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Wells a health risk, so is David Cone. Torre wants
to take it easy with the big-game specialist who has won 19 this
season but has a history of arm ailments. Cone will pitch only once
in the best-of-five opening round.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest concern with this team is Andy Pettitte, the
dimple-chinned lefty from Deer Park. Pettitte is 16-11, but in his
past seven starts he's 2-5 with 33 earned runs allowed.
</P>
<P>
   His velocity has slipped from 90 mph to 86-87, and his sinker,
curve and changeup are hanging like a dark cloud. His ERA has
fattened to 4.30.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN analyst Harold Reynolds, a former major-league second
baseman, attributes Pettitte's demise to ``flinching'' and
shortening his follow-through _ a habit Reynolds says developed
after the pitcher was bruised by a line drive.
</P>
<P>
   Other theorists say Pettitte is throwing too many cutters and
not enough curves and fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's so smart and got it all figured out,'' Pettitte
said, understandably weary of this topic.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who thinks Pettitte is ``worrying too much about his
mechanics,'' has refused to affirm the pitcher's starting status
for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't have confidence in Andy,'' Torre said.
``But let's give it a couple of games.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of games were all it took for Hideki Irabu to return
from oblivion and force his way into the playoff picture. Irabu
(13-9) has had an up-and-down season. His ERA rose from a
league-leading 2.47 in July to 4.40, before he chopped it back to
3.99 by allowing no earned runs in his past two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Irabu is a favorite of omnipresent owner George
Steinbrenner, the Japanese righthander conceivably could edge
Pettitte for the fourth and final turn in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   If Torre goes with Wells, Cone, Hernandez and Irabu, then
Pettitte, the hero of the 1996 World Series, could be excluded from
the postseason roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see myself helping us much out of the bullpen,''
Pettitte said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said he would be shocked if he's not in the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've won more games in the last three years than anyone in
baseball,'' he said. ``So I don't think it's an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the resurgence of Irabu, it is an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any manager would welcome Torre's problems, which are
caused primarily by a surfeit of talented athletes. Consider that
rookie Shane Spencer, the team's sixth outfielder, has seven home
runs and a .423 batting average in 52 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Torre have six pitchers with double-digit wins, he
has nine hitters with at least 10 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Five Yankees are in double figures in homers and stolen bases.
Derek Jeter, Bernie Williams, Paul O'Neill, Scott Brosius and
Bellaire's Chuck Knoblauch combined to set that major-league
record.
</P>
<P>
   But even with all the Yankees have accomplished, their erratic
final quarter-season has fans fretting, muttering about the
possibility of a postseason meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   By most measures, the Yankees are having a remarkable season.
But over the past few weeks, it has acquired a taint of
bittersweetness. And anything short of a World Series championship
will be considered a tragedy. If the Yankees can't surpass the
past, they will be haunted by it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
