masters of the universe appears to be falling to earth. Creditors
of Long-Term Capital Management LP, a hedge fund run by John
Meriwether, a former chairman of Salomon Brothers, are in talks to
try to salvage the firm beset by losses in its huge bond portfolio.
By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   COINS-DISPUTE (Undated) _ William Koch once dreamed about owning
an ancient coin collection so magnificent it might be called the
hoard of the century. Now he does and he can't stand it. ``I've
never had more trouble with anything,'' said Koch, a member of one
of the richest families in America. ``I just wish I had never seen
these coins.'' By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-MARKETPLACE _ Coca-Cola Co. executives have summoned Wall
Street analysts for a hastily scheduled meeting Friday morning in
New York, suggesting that the leading soft-drink company is about
to deliver ominous news about earnings. Coke derives most of its
fortunes from overseas, where economic crises have ravaged the
earnings of many American multinational companies. By Constance L.
Hays.
</P>
<P>
   FED-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan encouraged investors to anticipate a small interest-rate
cut when he noted that ``deteriorating foreign economies and their
spillover to domestic markets'' are slowing the economy and tilting
the Fed's concern from inflation to recession. Yet many economists
side with Allan Meltzer, a professor of economics at Carnegie
Mellon University, who labels a rate cut premature. At most, a
plausible case can be made for a middle ground. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
