<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ WORTHY OF MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Juan Gonzalez was set on being a social worker
before he signed his future over to baseball. Maybe he hasn't
changed the world as he once dreamed he would, but he is leaving a
big imprint on the American League-West pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, the Texas Rangers' rangy right fielder, has been
hotter than a Texas jalapeno all season but particularly since
bidding adieu to August. He brought a loaded 35-ounce bat into
Wednesday's battle at Edison Field, otherwise known as Anaheim's
last stand.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had every reason to run for cover when Gonzalez came
to the plate; he was batting .395 for the month at the night's
start. In four previous games against the Angels in that span he
had struck for seven hits and four RBI in 16 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   That would make him more dangerous than lightning, which rarely
hits the same place twice. Without question, he has charged the
Rangers down the stretch as they've gained 5{ games on the Angels
since Sept. 1 to take a three-game division lead with four games to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is so electrifying, he belongs right up there in this
year's baseball Mount Rushmore alongside Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa
and Ken Griffey Jr. In a season that has seen more than one
monolith toppled, Gonzalez has wielded his bat like a chisel with
the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, the Yankees' Derek Jeter and Boston's Nomar Garciaparra
are all having fine seasons, and Cleveland right fielder Manny
Ramirez has been generating more buzz of late than the new
television drama ``Felicity.'' But we'd be happiest to see Gonzalez
win his second American League MVP award in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Who else has carried a contending team with all the patience and
diligence of a woman with child? Gonzalez has distinguished himself
as only the 12th player in history to hit 40 home runs in five
seasons while driving in more runs (157) than any player in the
major leagues since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   He had an incredible 101 RBI at the All-Star break and people
wondered if Hack Wilson's 68-year-old record of 190 wasn't headed
the way of Roger Maris' 61 home runs. Wilson's record is safe for
at least another season. But Gonzalez, 28, has gone where neither
Willie Mays nor Mickey Mantel tread in RBI land and is closing in
on Ted Williams and Lou Gehrig, who finished with 159 RBI in 1949
and 1937, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness gracious, Gonzalez has been averaging an RBI every 3.8
at-bats. We should all be so productive.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball insiders have been gaga over Gonzalez since he belted
43 homers in 1992 at the age of 22 and added 46 for an encore in
1993. When former Cincinnati Reds great Joe Morgan penned his
recently published book, ``Baseball for Dummies,'' he listed
Gonzalez among the game's top players. To Morgan's mild surprise,
his collaborators, all of them baseball fans, called him on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had these baseball people asking me, `Why Juan Gonzalez?'
Morgan, an ESPN baseball analyst, said before the game. ``I told
them, `This guy is the most consistent RBI guy in the league.' Of
course, he's made me look like a prophet this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has had a heavy cross to bear since hitting twice his
age in homers in 1993, his third full season in the majors. He felt
a lot of pressure to produce and the stress left him susceptible to
injuries. It didn't help that Gonzalez insisted on playing winter
ball in his native Puerto Rico, where he is widely idolized.
</P>
<P>
   He essentially played for free, giving all of his paychecks to
charities that helped HIV-positive children in his homeland. But
he'd pay a price every September when his body would inevitably beg
for rest and rebel if it wasn't forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   His ambitious offseason schedule nearly cost him and the Rangers
dearly in 1996. Gonzalez led the team to the brink of its first
division title, then batted .246 in September to turn a foregone
conclusion into a cuticle-biting race to the finish. In the end,
the Rangers held off Seattle and Gonzalez held off the Mariners'
Alex Rodriguez for MVP honors in the closest finish in AL history.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has bypassed winter ball the past two years but hasn't
stopped giving money and his time to charities in Puerto Rico and
his adopted city of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great when I'm helping people,'' Gonzalez said. ``I see
a lot of poor people. A lot of people who are suffering. I feel
happy in my heart when I can do something for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing would give Gonzalez more bliss right now than to have
his season extended well into October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is talking about the MVP (award), but right now it's
more important to me for my team to win the division and try to get
to the World Series,'' Gonzalez said. ``I'm trying the best I can
to be patient and have concentration because I want to finish
strong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
