u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI     09-24 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY, A-ROD ENOUGH TO KEEP MARINER INTEREST UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Tuba Man, God bless his soul, was still playing.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Kingdome Wednesday night _ with the Mariners on the
eve of their final series of this long, lost season _ the plaintive
puffing of The Tuba Man could be heard all down King Street and
around the corner to First Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lonely sound, too, since the crowds have dwindled to
pre-Miracle of '95 proportions. About 15,000 bothered to come down
for Wednesday's game against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The din and clatter and crowd cacaphony surrounding a team
headed for the post-season can be deafening. Remember '95 and '97?
But all is quiet on this most Western front, except for our boys
who seem all but destined for the Hall _ Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darn, am I still in the line-up?'' Griffey joked Wednesday
when he saw manager Lou Piniella's lineup card get posted.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you are, Junior. And thank goodness, since Griffey and
Rodriguez are still homering and driving in runs at a rate that is
making Cooperstown call for bats or balls and whatever will serve
as ever-lasting proof that at least two notable M's were alive and
kicking in '98.
</P>
<P>
   In such a disappointing season, you have to figure it's a good
thing that the reigning AL MVP Griffey and 1996 AL Player of the
Year (and shoulda been MVP) Rodriguez have made these final days of
September worth something here in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey tagged home runs 54 and 55 Tuesday, with No. 54 giving
him and his dad, Ken Griffey Sr. a combined 500 career homers.
Number 55 gave Griffey 140 RBIsthis season _ making him the only
player besides Lou Gehrig and Babe Ruth to have three consecutive
seasons with 140 or more RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey said Wednesday he did not bother to track down the No.
55 home-run ball _ pretty unusual in this Mark McGwire/Sammy
Sosa-inspired frenzy about retrieving important home-run balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only one that mattered was No. 54 because that's the one
that got me and my dad the 500,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the police officer to try and get the ball. The guy
who caught it was great. Gave it right back. His name was Mike. He
just said `Here, you've worked hard all season for this and I
didn't do anything.' I just ran into the clubhouse, got him a bat,
signed it and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey did say that since reaching 50 homers, his bats have
become very hot property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed the bat I hit 51 with for Marzie _ (catcher and team
goodwill ambassador John Marzano.) Number 52 went to Alex, but
that's because he hit his No. 40 with it. Number 53 went to the
Hall of Fame (after a request was made for a bat from the AL's
leading home-run king.) And I'm keeping the one I got 54 and 55
with,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rodriguez _ with a wondrous 40/40 under his belt _
also tagged home run No. 41 Tuesday, making him the home-run
hittingest AL shortstop in history. Wednesday night he bolstered
that total by ripping No. 42. With that homer, Griffey and
Rodriguez have combined for 97, making them major league baseball's
third all-time leading homer duo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting for me. People said after '96 that I would have
a hard time putting up those kinds of numbers again. The thing that
drives me is consistency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was not willing to conceed that his 40/40 was that
much less of an accomplishment than hitting 61 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty close to being as challenging. I mean, how
many people have hit 61 homers or more in a season now? Four? And
how many players have hit 40 homers and stolen 40 bases? Three. So,
you know ...''
</P>
<P>
   To prove his point, we get the feeling Mr. A-Rod just might like
to have a go at hitting 61 or 67 homers. But that's in the future.
And let's hope all of Rodriguez's future _ and Griffey's _ is in
Seattle, even though it's going to take a ton of Microsoft and
Nintendo cash to pull off that dream.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey suggested a plan for keeping both All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to hold Seattle hostage,'' he said, giggling.
``We want a package deal. If he goes, I go. And vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was any jealousy or competition between the two
superstars, Griffey said no way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on totally two different pages. He's young, single. He
doesn't have to worry about certain things. Besides, he gets to hit
in front of me. One day, I'd like to hit in front of me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said he would like to believe that the two All-Stars
have a mutually beneficial effect on each other.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the awesome achievements of these two players
bittersweet is that 1998 MVP votes won't be cast for Griffey and
Rodriguez, since any chance for the M's to contend in '98 was lost
in the Randy Johnson disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite his absence for in homer derby, it is nice to see
Griffey end the season with such a bang. Same for Rodriguez. It's
too bad it has to end so soon.
</P>
<P>
   Lost was any chance for baseball's biggest 1-2 punch (or 2-3
punch as the case may be) to showcase themselves, their team, this
city in the post-season. What a shame, since Rodriguez and Griffey
are two of the reasons why 1998 was one of baseball's greatest
seasons ever.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
