<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ANGELS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKETT DOMINATES IN 7-1 VICTORY AS RANGERS SWEEP ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Rangers relied on the most unreliable
member of their rotation to pitch this organization to the verge of
its second American League West title in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander John Burkett, whom manager Johnny Oates recently
considered removing from the rotation, delivered during the
Rangers' 7-1 victory against the Angels last night at Edison
International Field of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Rangers a three-game advantage on the
second-place Angels in the AL West and reduced their magic number
to two with four games remaining. The Rangers will capture that
division title on any combination of their victories and losses by
the Angels that total two.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, who surrendered one run on two hits in eight innings,
made the Rangers' precarious lead stand by outpitching Angels
right-hander Ken Hill (9-6).
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile and second baseman Mark McLemore
provided Burkett (9-13) a two-run advantage with a fourth-inning,
run-scoring single and a seventh-inning sacrifice fly,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won 10 all year when we've scored three or less,'' Oates
said. ``We've got a chance to win some of those games with the way
we're pitching now.''
</P>
<P>
   Muscle spasms prevented Burkett from making his scheduled start
Sept. 15 against the Orioles, and that resulted in nine days' rest
before his start Friday against the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett surrendered only one run through eight innings during
the Rangers' 3-1 victory Friday against the Athletics, and that
performance gave Oates the confidence to stay with a five-man
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, who all along preferred staying with a five-man rotation,
entertained thoughts of removing Burkett from the rotation and
starting right-handers Rick Helling, Aaron Sele, Todd Stottlemyre
and Esteban Loaiza on three days rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a blessing in disguise that he missed Baltimore and
Seattle and got bumped to Oakland and Anaheim,'' Oates said.
``Those are the two teams in the American League that he matches up
against best. His numbers say that, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett entered last night's start 3-1 with a 3.16 earned-run
average in four career starts against the Angels, and delivered the
goods again despite little run support.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered last night's game ranked second only to the
Yankees in runs scored, but their lineup does not excel in the art
of manufacturing runs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Rangers manufactured their first run without the
benefit of a base hit. Center fielder Tom Goodwin drew a five-pitch
walk from Hill and utilized his greatest asset _ speed _ to steal
second base with second baseman McLemore at-bat in the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore advanced Goodwin to third base with a ground ball hit
to the right side of the infield, and left fielder Rusty Greer
drove home the game's first run with a one-out, sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, though, pulled even for the first time in this
series in their third inning. Switch-hitting catcher Chad Kreuter
laced an opposite-field, ground-rule double to left field for the
Angels' first hit and scored on the ensuing single by third baseman
Craig Shipley. Burkett, though, retired the next 14 batters the
Angels sent to the plate after Shipley's single.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
