<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITTSBURGH'S COWHER A MAN OF STEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ The jaw juts out on the NFL landscape like the
Matterhorn and is as solid as the Rock of Gibraltar.
</P>
<P>
   The glare can melt the face mask of the biggest, baddest
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   The mouth can spew a venom-laced tirade, offer point-making
proposals or provide words of encouragement _ sometimes in the same
brief conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The gait is always deliberate but also can be unrelenting or
relaxed depending on where he is heading, and why.
</P>
<P>
   That is the anatomy of a football coach, and a very successful
one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cowher has been with the Pittsburgh Steelers since 1992,
when he was hired to replace Hall of Fame coach Chuck Noll. In
Cowher's first six seasons, the Steelers have been to the playoffs
each year, won five division titles and hosted the AFC Championship
game in three of the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers team that faces the unbeaten Seahawks at Three
Rivers Stadium on Sunday is owned by the Rooney family; run with
the guidance of director of football operations Tom Donahoe, who
interviewed for but was not offered the job of Seahawks general
manager in February; and filled with some players who are
redefining the way their positions are played _ center Dermontti
Dawson, quarterback Kordell Stewart, linebacker Levon Kirkland,
defensive back Carnell Lake and nose tackle Joel Steed.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, the Steelers are Cowher's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts from the top,'' said linebacker Chad Brown, who
played with the Steelers for four seasons before signing with the
Seahawks. ``Cowher is a very hard-nosed, players' coach. It sounds
kind of contradictory. But he's not so far removed from being a
player that he doesn't know what we're feeling and what's going on.
But at the same time, he insists upon and demands a hard-nosed,
aggressive style of football.''
</P>
<P>
   Insists? Cowher revels in it.
</P>
<P>
   Brown recalls training-camp practices, which were held under the
lights and in front of several thousand fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last drill was goal-line. It is a serious, 100-percent,
game-like drill,'' Brown said. ``Coach Cowher is standing behind
the linebacker like the umpire, slobbering and going at it. It is
frightening. It is absolutely frightening. Cowher's got the
whistle, and it's not coming early. They're running the option with
Kordell (Stewart). Kordell is getting hit. It is the real deal.
That hard-nosed attitude starts with the head guy and works its way
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowher, who turned 41 in May, says he doesn't like talking about
himself. But he is quick to point out that the guy you see stalking
the sideline each Sunday is not the same man who is married to a
former professional basketball player, Kaye, and father to three
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even then, I'm not one who's going to hide my emotions,''
Cowher said Wednesday. ``It's a lot more love at home than when you
see me screaming on the sideline. But I've just always believed
that's the way to be. It doesn't do any good to gunny-sack things.
I never thought that was healthy to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that people know where you stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Make a mistake, and you will find Cowher and that jaw of his
right in your face. But if the attack comes from outside the
Steelers' family, that would be Cowher you see standing behind his
players.
</P>
<P>
   The latest and most visible example of Cowher on the defensive
came after Sunday's 21-0 loss to the Dolphins in Miami. Asked about
Stewart's 11-for-35, three-interception performance while
discussing the Steelers' on-going offensive problems, Cowher
whirled to face the questioner and erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not point out Kordell Stewart. Maybe you may have tried
to put the words in my mouth. But I'm not. I'm not. I'm looking at
everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a milder, more-controlled Cowher on the other end of the
telephone Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I try to do is be very up front with players
and be very up front with people,'' he said when asked about his
fiery reputation. ``I think the most important thing is that
everybody kind of knows where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people understand what you expect from them, they know what
their role will be. While they might not like it, I think the one
thing people will do is respect you if you can be up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowher and his team have the respect of Seahawks coach Dennis
Erickson. The Steelers are 2-1 and their offense ranks 28th in the
league after being shut out last week for the first time since
1993. But then, the Steelers have started 2-2 in four of their
first six seasons under Cowher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is a fiery guy, a very emotional guy, and that's how they
play,'' Erickson said. ``Obviously they had disappointment last
week against Miami. But if you look back at Pittsburgh over the
last three or four years, some time early in the season ... that
happens to them. Then all of a sudden, they catch on fire and end
up winning the AFC Central.''
</P>
<P>
   This run of success has come despite yearly raids of Cowher's
players and assistants. In the past two offseasons, the Steelers
have lost half a Pro Bowl team to free agency _ Brown, cornerbacks
Willie Williams, Deon Figures and Rod Woodson, defensive end Ray
Seals and wide receivers Ernie Mills and Andre Hastings in 1997;
tackle John Jackson, wide receiver Yancy Thigpen and strong safety
Myron Bell this year. Assistant coaches Dom Capers, Dick LeBeau and
Chan Gailey also have left.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the correlation between the offseason losses and the
slow starts, Cowher offered, ``I like to think that's not the case.
But I think there's a degree of accuracy in that statement. When
you have new faces and you have new people involved in integral
parts of what you're trying to do ... it does take some time.''
</P>
<P>
   There really is a method to what could be perceived as Cowher's
madness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
