r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     09-24 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE THREE FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Just the other day, Gary DiSarcina said all
the pressure to win the AL West was on the Texas Rangers, not the
Anaheim Angels. After all, the Angels shortstop said, it was the
Rangers who made the big trades that were supposed to put them over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   And after Wednesday night's game, which the Rangers led, 7-1, in
the eighth inning, the Rangers were at the summit, looking down.
</P>
<P>
   A win Wednesday would give the Rangers a three-game sweep and a
three-game lead with four to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' magic number would be two, meaning even if the
Angels swept a four-game series in Oakland, the Rangers would need
only a split of their four-game series in Seattle to clinch the
crown.
</P>
<P>
   For the third night in a row, the Angels offense was nowhere to
be found. They were shut down by Todd Stottlemyre and Rick Helling
in the first two games, which is understandable. But Wednesday it
was John Burkett, who entered the game with an 8-13 record and 5.87
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett looked like Roger Clemens the way he thoroughly
dominated the Angels' hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett retired the first six batters of the game before giving
up a double to Chad Kreuter and an RBI single to Craig Shipley. But
after Shipley's hit, Burkett retired 13 in a row before Darin
Erstad walked with two out in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels could not have asked for more from starter Ken Hill,
who pitched well despite a sore elbow. Hill gave up three runs (two
earned) and four hits in 61/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Angels defense, which had been so good for so long,
played poorly for the third night in a row, making two errors. And
the bullpen had another tough night. When Hill left, the score was
2-1. Troy Percival gave up three runs himself in the eighth inning,
two on Todd Zeile's home run.
</P>
<P>
   If the Angels didn't feel the pressure, it would be difficult to
understand what happened to them seemingly so suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really feel that much pressure,'' DiSarcina said
Tuesday. ``We're not supposed to be here. Everybody knows we didn't
make a move before the break. Texas has pressure because they made
all the moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure I feel is we've had a great year, you don't want
to end it on a sour note. You battle through so many things,
overcome so many obstacles, I don't want it to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Like they did in the first two games of the series, the Rangers
scored before the Angels even came to bat. And they did it without
getting a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin led off the game with a walk, stole second, went to
third on Mark McLemore's grounder to first and scored on Rusty
Greer's sacrifice fly for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett retired the Angels in order in the first two innings,
but the Angels got on the scoreboard in the third inning, the first
time this series they've scored before the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter opened the third with a double into the left-field
corner and scored when Shipley followed with a single to center.
Shipley was the Angels' third third baseman to start in the series.
The others were Paco Martin and Troy Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   If the Angels had gained any momentum at all after tying the
game, Hill allowed the Rangers to take it right back in the top of
the fourth. Will Clark doubled with one out and took third on Ivan
Rodriguez's flyout to deep right.
</P>
<P>
   After Lee Stevens walked, Zeile bounced a single up the middle
to score Clark for a 2-1 Rangers lead.
</P>
<P>
   Though it seemed many had given up on the Angels after they lost
the first two games of the series, Angels manager Terry Collins
insisted his players had not given up on themselves. Not when they
hadn't all season despite an inordinate number of injuries to key
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have players not willing to lay down,'' Collins
said. ``Players that are not going to give up no matter how bad the
situation is.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's helped that the guys who have come up to replace
injured guys have stepped up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels not only didn't give up, but they got angry. At least
pitcher Chuck Finley did. Finley's loud and vocal pep talk after
Tuesday's loss was just what the Angels needed, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got to play angry,'' he said. ``We've got a
good clubhouse, guys like each other. But you don't need that to
win. The Oakland A's in the '70s hated each other. You want guys
who play mad. You've got to play the game (ticked) off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
