<HEADER>
A1464 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      09-24 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
  
 UW's LOOKER GAINS RESPECT WITH RECEPTIONS, NOT CONNECTIONS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He was ``Brock's Boy.'' He was allowed to come into
the University of Washington football program because he knew the
quarterback, was his primary receiver in high school. He was Brock
Huard's caddy.
</P>
<P>
   Or so some of the Huskies suspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure people actually believed I wasn't Brock's Boy
until after that first game,'' Dane Looker says. ``I came to the
sidelines, and I started to get different looks from guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The legend of Dane Looker grows, even when he misses a game.
</P>
<P>
   He surprised Arizona State with 11 catches in the opener, tying
a UW record. And then, when he missed the Brigham Young game with a
bruised thigh, the Huskies struggled on offense. They'd like to
think some of those abortive runs on audible calls will be quick
flips to Looker on Saturday at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having that H-back, that quick answer,'' said offensive
coordinator Scott Linehan, ``will help avoid unnecessary contact on
the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington is either very lucky with receivers, or the program
casts a very long shadow. On the heels of accepting a transfer from
Acadia University in Nova Scotia, Jerome Pathon, the Huskies are
now home to a player who opted out of Western Washington, where his
sport was basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we had any idea that he was going to be this
good,'' Linehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Join the crowd. Nobody had that notion when Looker was catching
18 touchdown passes from Huard in 1994 at Puyallup, except maybe
Looker. He ran a modest 4.7 40 then and was on the skinny side,
only 160 pounds. Oops, 159.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being on the scale, and coach (Mike) Huard was
there,'' Looker said. ``It said 159. I begged him to write down
160. `Please, coach, it looks so much better.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote down 159.''
</P>
<P>
   The receiver who caught Arizona State off-guard wasn't recruited
by the Pac-10, or even the Big Sky. Washington, limited by Pac-10
sanctions, had one scholarship earmarked for a receiver, and it
went to Gerald Harris.
</P>
<P>
   So Looker's recruitment was a death struggle between Central
Washington, Pacific Lutheran and Western Washington. He accepted a
partial basketball scholarship from Western.
</P>
<P>
   He played point guard for Brad Jackson's team, and he and the
coach had a great relationship. Looker reminded Jackson of himself
20 years ago, when Jackson was a fiery guard at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day two years ago, Looker and Huard happened to be home
in Puyallup on a weekend. Huard, who had stayed in touch, gave him
a call. It was past 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Huard wanted to go down to the Puyallup High gym, where, Looker
says, ``He has a key.''
</P>
<P>
   The two began throwing a football, connecting once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Huard said, ``you still have what it takes to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Looker began getting excited. He thought about a reunion at
Washington with Huard, a chance to play college football on the
rebound. He and Jackson had long talks that were more constructive
than prickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it as a situation at all where he was letting us
down,'' Jackson says. ``I've enjoyed coaching almost all the guys
I've had, but every now and then, an athlete comes through that you
really connect with. We had not only a good professional
relationship but a good personal relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was torn.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington welcomed him, but with a disclaimer. He would be
walking on without a scholarship, living the hard life on the scout
team. There was nothing to suggest to the Huskies they had Antonio
Freeman on the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Says Jackson, ``I think a lot of people probably counseled Dane:
`You're crazy.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Looker loves it when somebody says he can't. He made the
transfer, arriving last fall, weighing close to 180. He made a
positive impression on the top Husky defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was anxious every day to prove I could go out there and play
against them,'' Looker says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always liked to compete,'' says his dad, Dan. ``He'd much
rather have the opportunity to be the hero than not get the
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was still Brock's Boy. Indeed, there are three Looker
boys who caught passes at Puyallup from three different Huards.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the Looker kids, there was a lot of personal pride,''
says Mike Huard. ``They never backed down from any situation _
maybe even sometimes when they should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Looker, now 6-foot-1 and 190 pounds, certified his toughness
after a horrific hit in Washington's first fall scrimmage from
safeties Brendan Jones and Nigel Burton. A facemask sandwiched
Looker's hand against the ball, and when everybody got up, the hand
was a mess, lacerated in 11 places and swollen to twice its size.
</P>
<P>
   The longest 150 yards of his life were spent walking up the
tunnel to the trainer's room. Everybody was sure the hand was
broken, including Looker.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. In what might have been the biggest stroke of fortune
this year for the Huskies, Looker had only broken blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Recalls Linehan, ``You knew you were dealing with one of the
toughest kids on our team when he came back (two days later), with
a lineman's glove on it, and he was reaching for the ball with his
hands, and catching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson remembers that sort of fire in Looker when Western would
get ready to play Central Washington, clenching his fists, telling
the coach how great this was.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, it's not Central, it's Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I hear, they're real susceptible to the pass,''
Looker said, recalling how Troy Edwards of Louisiana Tech ran up
record numbers against the Huskers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great athlete. As a receiving corps, we can do the same
thing, go out there and catch all kinds of balls. That's what we've
got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Looker was irked to be held out of the BYU game, especially as
the Huskies struggled. The other side of him realizes the prudence
of having him ready for Nebraska and Arizona. He can see the big
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it's worked out has been incredible,'' he said. ``If
it ended tomorrow, it'd be more than I expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Looker wouldn't necessarily recommend the route he has taken.
Still, he says, ``You've got to chase your dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The chase continues in Lincoln, having wound through Seattle and
Tempe, by way of Bellingham.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
