<HEADLINE>
FRESHMAN GETS NOD AT LINEBACKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Cal State Northridge had a scholarship to
offer, freshman linebacker Lewis Blanton would get it. The coaching
staff thinks that much of him.
</P>
<P>
   However, none are available this year, so Blanton will wait
until 1999 for one. In the meantime, he expects to work his way
into this week's starting lineup as the Matadors (1-1) host
defending Big Sky champ Eastern Washington (0-2) at 3:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blanton gives us a very good athlete at the Mike (middle)
linebacker spot,'' CSUN coach Ron Ponciano said. ``He was a player
we got lucky with because he wanted to stay close to home.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if linebacker Quinton Reed gets the start, Blanton, who is
sixth on the team with 10 tackles, will see his playing time
extended markedly because of the loss of starter Cos Abercrombie
with a broken jaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even see myself playing up to Cos' level now, but
hopefully one day I'll get there,'' said Blanton, a Murphy High
graduate. ``He's like my mentor and he always calls me his prodigy.
I look up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The word on Brady: Eastern Washington coach Mike Kramer said
he's received calls from numerous Big Sky teams about the exploits
of CSUN quarterback Marcus Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to know how good he is because we've now seen him on
film,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Brady pushed himself into the Big Sky limelight by going 20 of
26 for 236 yards and three touchdowns last week against Northern
Arizona, and he did so by demonstrating great scrambling ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's nasty on turf because he can really cut, but we haven't
seen him on grass,'' said Kramer, pointing out North Campus Stadium
has real grass. ``We've been trying to catch chickens, and we took
our most slippery athlete (defensive back Mario Sweet) and put him
in the backfield.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Date in Dallas?: It's a complex ordeal trying to fit a team
into one open date on the schedule, but the latest talks have moved
away from Wisconsin and toward Southern Methodist as CSUN tries to
secure a substantial guarantee to play against a Division I-A
opponent next year.
</P>
<P>
   However, instead of it being an early-September, premiere game
for SMU, not to mention a litmus test for CSUN, the game might be
played in November.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have discussed it and agreeing on a guarantee
price could be the last obstacle. CSUN's other two nonconference
games next season are set to be at Southern Utah and home against
Southwest Missouri State, both return games from this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Short yardage: Before the season the CSUN coaching staff held
its breath hoping that senior cornerback Steve Forte would be
eligible because the Matadors lacked depth there. But after Mel
Miller and Chazz Moore transferred in, Forte fell back on the
two-deep and didn't play the first two games. So Forte was moved to
safety Wednesday.... Ponciano said safety Hassan Abdul-Malik's
shoulder is better and he will play against Eastern Washington....
CSUN running back Melvin Blue and Eastern Washington
cornerback/return specialist Bashir Livingston played together at
Utah State last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0028 </DOCNO>
