u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT     09-24 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TIE CLUB RECORD FOR VICTORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Miller Huggins, manager of the 1927 Yankees, weighed
140 pounds, small enough for Babe Ruth to dangle him from a moving
train. Huggins had been an average player, an average hitter who
relied on his speed. Joe Torre, manager of the 1998 Yankees, is
thickly built, a former Gold Glove catcher and winner of a most
valuable player award in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The only apparent similarity between Huggins and Torre is that
both managers led their respective teams to 110 victories, a club
record. The Yankees reached that mark on Wednesday night, beating
the Cleveland Indians, 8-4, at Yankee Stadium with Shane Spencer
banging three hits, including his third home run in two days. Chad
Curtis also slugged a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 110-48, the most victories by a team since
baseball switched to a 162-game schedule in 1961. The '27 Yankees
won 110 games in a 154-game season. With one more victory, the
Yankees will tie the American League record of 111, set by the 1954
Indians, in a 154-game season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very special,'' Torre said. ``The '27 Yankees are the
standard all Yankee teams are compared to.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned repeatedly about how he manages a team with one of
the best records in the 20th century, Torre responds with a
well-practiced line. ``I just stay out of the way,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Torre is telling the truth, in a sense. Derek Jeter hits and
Orlando Hernandez pitches; Torre stays out of the way. But he is
always prepared to get involved, when necessary. Torre is like a
professor overseeing an honors course _ those charged to him are
all talented and will generally thrive. But if they need a nudge, a
compliment, someone to talk to, someone to listen, Torre makes
himself available.
</P>
<P>
   While pitching erratically in May, David Cone passed Torre in
the dugout and said, ``Don't give up on me.'' The next day, Torre
walked past Cone in the clubhouse and said, ``You're just
frustrated because you know how good you're supposed to be.'' Cone
considered this, and Torre's words resonated perfectly in his
psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Andy Pettitte pitched on Monday, with speculation
rampant that Pettitte might not start in the playoffs, Torre
stopped by the pitcher's locker and said: ``Just relax. Just go out
and pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   They were the words, Pettitte said the next day, that he needed
to hear _ at exactly the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill boils with helmet-throwing intensity, and sometimes
Torre will say something light-hearted, something to ease his mood.
When David Wells pitched poorly and then complained in a
closed-door meeting with the manager that Torre did not demonstrate
faith in the pitcher, Torre began muting his slight criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   Torre doesn't call many meetings, either, but when he does, Cone
said, nothing is said unnecessarily, the tone is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   When Torre called a team meeting on April 7, when the Yankees
were 1-4, he asked Cone and O'Neill and others to speak. ``If
you've got anything to say, say it now,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   He called a meeting in August, after the Yankees had committed a
series of base-running mistakes. Torre was livid after the Yankees
drifted through a 7-0 loss to Tampa Bay last week and immediately
challenged their effort.
</P>
<P>
   But he trusts the players, with the expectation that they play
hard, concentrate and respect each other. If they do not, they will
get the Stare.
</P>
<P>
   Homer Bush, a rookie, got the Stare last week. He was on second
base when a ball was driven to deep center and Bush thought it
would be a home run, so he slowed slightly nearing third. But the
ball bounced off the top of the wall, a double. Bush knew Torre had
seen him slow down and would not be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had to walk by him in the dugout,'' Bush said. ``It was
trying to sneak into the house, by your mother, after you've stayed
out too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines, at 39 the oldest Yankee player, got the Stare last
week in Florida. It was late in the game, the Yankees were getting
wiped out, and Raines was joking in the dugout. He looked up into
the Stare. ``I sat on the bench the rest of the game and I didn't
say another word,'' Raines said.
</P>
<P>
   Torre doesn't stare often. Rather, he sits and watches,
outwardly calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look down there at the end of close games,'' Bush said,
``and I'm thinking, `Doesn't this guy see those cats are about
ready to come back?' But he looks so relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre is staying out of the way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-24 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ Back when, the hitter was ahead of the pitcher. Way
ahead. As college prospects, there was no comparison between USC
Trojans Randy Johnson and Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark was already hitting monster home runs when I got to
USC,'' Johnson recalls. ``As a sophomore, you sort of knew what he
was going to accomplish in his career. Me? I could throw real hard,
but about every third pitch hit the backstop on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more physically mature, too. I was 6-10 and about 180
pounds, all arms and legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson weighs in at 230 these days, but with all due respect,
he still appears to be far more arms and legs than torso. The
obvious difference is his ability to pitch, which, coupled with his
formidable throwing, can reduce the best batters to a whimpering,
quivering state.
</P>
<P>
   He's human, though. He will make the occasional mistake. His
first pitch Wednesday night, for example. Pat Kelly, who came to
the plate with 62 fewer home runs than McGwire, parked it in the
left-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Uppity runt.
</P>
<P>
   But all Kelly succeeded in doing was to harden Johnson's
resolve. Despite lacking his best stuff, or even decent stuff a
good bit of the time, the Big Unit had enough stuff to put away the
Cardinals. His velocity increased as the cool fall evening wore on,
and while his control never improved appreciably, his subsequent
135 pitches over seven innings yielded nary a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy was either very tenacious,'' manager Larry Dierker said,
``or very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of both, actually. And the Astros did give him six early
runs with which to play. Johnson won't come up short too many times
with such gracious support.
</P>
<P>
   Although he set down the former fellow Trojan horse McGwire only
once in four plate appearances (two walks, one single, one
stratospheric fly ball to Moises Alou on the warning track in
left), he wriggled free from several scary jams and thus did his
part to provide the Astros with a historic 100th victory. It took
them 37 seasons to reach the century mark, but, ah, who's counting?
</P>
<P>
   As for Johnson, he finishes the regular season 10-1 in an Astros
uniform, which fits his Giacometti-sculpted body like he was born
to wear it. But it's his remaining starts _ you hope there are at
least five _ that will be the ones for which he was reeled in only
moments before the trading deadline passed the night of July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have been to the playoffs. They've just never gone
anywhere, once there. It's hoped _ assumed, even _ that Johnson's
supporting cast is potent enough for him to go forth and contribute
to yet more important history-making.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker fretted over his team's lethargy of late during his
postgame comments, but he expects a ``renewed intensity and
aggressiveness'' when the second season kicks off Tuesday or
Wednesday. In the interim, he will ``manage to win'' against the
Cubs on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Should Sammy Sosa prevail in the again-knotted home-run derby,
it won't be because the Astros gave it to him. If the Cubs somehow
survive to win the wild-card race, they'll have earned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe that much to the game,'' Dierker said. ``And there's no
downside to our trying as hard as we can. I'll give a few of our
regulars a day off _ but not all at once. We need to take momentum
into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago series might have been beyond huge if the Astros
hadn't, against impossible odds, pulled off the Johnson trade.
Ironically, it was exactly the same time a year earlier when the
Cardinals had acquired McGwire in an effort to put them over the
top, where the Astros stand instead today.
</P>
<P>
   For all his homeric feats, St. Louis is twice a non-factor
also-ran with Big Mac. In The Show, good pitching generally beats
good hitting. There's simply so much more of the latter than the
former.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference,'' Dierker said, ``is almost always in the
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, favored by many to reclaim the Central Division
title the Astros wrested away in 1997, lost Andy Benes during the
offseason and found themselves buried early when they were without
Matt Morris, Donovan Osborne and Alan Benes.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros would themselves have to tell Darryl Kile goodbye,
then send Chris Holt and Ramon Garcia to the DL as well, a
potentially troublesome scenario. But, unlike St. Louis, they
rustled up a full complement of suitable replacements.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson _ let's call him Mr. Coup de Grace _ joined them,
the magic-number countdown effectively began. With a 1.28 ERA, 116
strikeouts in 84 innings and four home shutouts in a row, he hardly
could have contributed more than he did. Except, OK, to get that
11th ``W'' in his other start at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   His extreme early-season unhappiness in Seattle must feel like
it was part of a different lifetime, one closer in proximity
perhaps to his Trojan period even than the fun-filled here and now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road,'' Johnson said. ``I've taken a lot of
lumps, but I'm very proud of where I'm at. As for tonight, I'm not
too satisfied with how I pitched, but I got an important win. I've
never played for a ballclub that won 100 games.''
</P>
<P>
   And we had never had one, either. A fine fit, this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
