u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-     09-24 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX JUST ABOUT THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Strip away the possible playoff permutations and
coin-flip ramifications, Jim Corsi said.
</P>
<P>
   Set aside yet another record performance by closer Tom Gordon,
who saved his 41st straight game, and yet another big night for
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, who wiped out a dubious error in the
top of the third with a three-run home run in the bottom of the
inning, then doubled and scored the deciding run two innings later.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, this is what Wednesday night's 5-4 win over the
expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays in the 158th game of the 1998 season
means to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we don't have to look at scoreboards anymore,'' Corsi
said after the Sox ensured that their season will last beyond
Sunday by clinching at least a tie for the American League
wild-card playoff spot. ``Only our games matter now. We're in
charge of our own destiny. I'd rather look at our scoreboard than
somebody else's, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, when Pedro Martinez takes the mound against the
Baltimore Orioles, attention on Yawkey Way will no longer be
divided between the action on the field and the large white numbers
hung on the out-of-town scoreboard by Chris Elias, the kid inside
the Green Monster.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the Toronto Blue Jays, the team that remained in
desperate pursuit of the Sox Wednesday night with their fourth
straight win, a 6-3 decision over the Orioles, will not be in
action Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And with the magic number for clinching a playoff spot down to
one, the Red Sox no longer have to concern themselves with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Win once in their last four games and they return to the
playoffs for the first time since 1995, regardless of what the Blue
Jays do. A Toronto loss, of course, in its last three games would
accomplish the same goal. Lose all four while the Jays sweep three
from the Tigers in Toronto and there will be a one-game playoff in
SkyDome Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will clinch tomorrow,'' said DH Midre Cummings,
eavesdropping on Corsi's discourse. ``We will win.''
</P>
<P>
   While his manner conveyed as much confidence as Cummings's
declaration, Martinez was offering no such guarantees. But he also
assured his interrogators that he would have no trouble sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about talking, it's about doing,'' Martinez said.
``It could be a lot of fun tomorrow, but you can't drink a lot of
champagne because there will be another game the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big game? I have goals that are a lot higher. I dream of the
World Series, which is what this game is all about. This is just
one game to get us to the playoffs. I'll go pitch, but if I don't
do it, I have so much confidence in this team, I know somebody will
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   By 7:28 p.m., when Elias put a ``2'' next to ``Tor'' and a ``0''
next to ``Bal,'' the crowd of 23,240 had an inkling there would be
no party in the Fens Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   By 7:51, when a ``5'' was placed next to ``Tor'' and a ``1''
next to ``Bal,'' it was apparent that the Red Sox would be on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, charged with his 25th error because he refused to
eat Mike Kelly's grounder into the hole and bounced his throw past
first baseman Mo Vaughn, made amends for the three-run uprising
that ensued by following Vaughn's RBI single in the bottom of the
third with his 33d home run, a screen shot into a stiff wind.
</P>
<P>
   With one swing, Garciaparra produced as many RBIs as he had in
his last 20 games. He also presented a 4-3 lead to Steve Avery, who
was credited with his 10th win by going five innings. The
lefthander weathered Wade Boggs's two-run triple and Fred McGriff's
RBI single after Garciaparra's alleged misplay in the third. He
struck out Bobby Smith and McGriff to end his stint before yielding
to Derek Lowe, who pitched a scoreless sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon entered in the eighth, when an infield hit by Smith, an
infield out, and a single to center by Bubba Trammell against Corsi
made it 5-4. Trammell was thrown out stealing by catcher Scott
Hatteberg, an out that increased in magnitude when Aaron Ledesma
reached on an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Corsi made his exit and Gordon struck out pinch
hitter Paul Sorrento to end the inning. He then struck out the
first two batters he faced in the ninth, Miguel Cairo and Mike
DiFelice, before Quinton McCracken singled and took second on a
wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But Boggs, with boos ringing in ears that were Bostonized long
ago, grounded out to Vaughn at first to end it, giving the Sox
three wins in the four-game set against their expansion cousins,
whose arrival in these environs could not have been more
expeditious.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who already holds the record for most consecutive saves
in one season, now has 41 straight, which ties the record for most
consecutive saves shared by Rod Beck (over three years) and Trevor
Hoffman (over two).
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he expects to feel Thursday night should he save the
clincher, Gordon remained in low-key mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought about it,'' he said. ``I've never been in a
playoffs, never been in that situation. I wouldn't know what to
think.''
</P>
<P>
   He should know soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
