<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1488 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-SUSANA-LADN     09-24 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-SUSANA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKE INTO HISTORY AT SANTA SUSANA PASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT PURDUE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's not much ``new'' about California's newest
state park, which is exactly what makes it one of the San Fernando
Valley's hidden treasures. In fact, Santa Susana Pass State
Historic Park in Chatsworth is a unique window into Southern
California's past _ thousands of years worth.
</P>
<P>
   Designated by the state in January, its 670 acres of sandstone
ramparts, dense chaparral and riparian woodlands have long been
crisscrossed by wildlife, American Indians and early Californians
who traveled a famed stagecoach route through the area as late as
100 years ago. The footsteps of these diverse visitors are easy to
explore on the web of unsigned trails that lace the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much history and it's not just the (park's
signature) Stagecoach Trail, which was one of the main connectors
between San Francisco and L.A.,'' said Judy Garris, an avid hiker
and member of the Santa Susana Mountains Park Association. ``The
area was also a gathering place for three Native American tribes
and there's even a burial ground within the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been bobcat sightings and a mountain lion was
spotted not too long ago. It's the edge of a main wildlife corridor
and there are some very pristine areas there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the lobbying efforts of local conservationists that
led to state park status, hikers can enjoy this suburban slice of
wilderness. But until resources are found to maintain and mark
trails, a morning walk along the Stagecoach Trail _ a 2{-mile
round-trip _ and its optional 12/3-mile loop might prove a bit
confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a closer look at the course:
</P>
<P>
   Begin the journey at the entrance to the park on the signed
Stagecoach Equestrian Trail. Follow this path around the edge of
the park for a quarter-mile, scanning for a gravel trail on the
left between a sign that reads ``CAUTION MOUNTAIN LIONS'' and a
water tank. Ascend the gravel path and turn right onto a paved road
for 100 yards, then turn left onto a fire road.
</P>
<P>
   Begin climbing steadily, keeping an eye out on the left for
large formations of blood-red sandstone resembling downtown
Bedrock. Turn right at the first fork onto a footpath, then turn
right again after another 100 feet, avoiding a section of deeply
eroded trail. Walking west-northwest on this wide, level road,
notice the gargantuan rocky ridge to the south, floating like a
sandstone battleship on a sea of chaparral.
</P>
<P>
   The park's crags are actually the Simi Hills; the Santa Susana
Mountains for which the park is named are located to the northeast.
Topping out at about 1,700 feet, the Simi Hills are geologic
youngsters, dating back about 5 million years.
</P>
<P>
   From this viewpoint, it's 200 yards to the junction with the
Devil's Slide, leading up to the left. Huffing up the huge blocks
of sandstone bedrock, it's easy to imagine coach drivers cursing
this route, which seems more like Satan's StairMaster.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, stagecoaches were lowered by hand here,
with passengers paying for first class if they rode, a cheaper fare
if they walked down and even less if they actually helped lower the
coach. An 800-foot climb leads to a sign commemorating the stage
road, which states the route was used from 1859 to 1890. By 1895,
an easier road was blazed over Santa Susana Pass, which today is
traversed by the Simi Valley-San Fernando Valley Freeway (Highway
118). Gaze south and east for head-spinning views of the
smog-cloaked Valley, indicating how far we've come _ unfortunately
(cough) _ in the last century.
</P>
<P>
   The road climbs another 600 feet, leveling off at a three-way
junction about 1\ miles from the trailhead. The main route _ the
``stick'' on the lollipop-shaped trail _ ends here. Turn around and
head back. Or continue straight toward a distant stand of dark
eucalyptus trees on the optional 12/3-mile loop _ the ``sucker'' of
the lollipop _ around the western corner of the park.
</P>
<P>
   Veer left at the next fork and spot the trees on the other side
of a gate. Crawl through, hike out to Lilac Lane, turn right and
walk 100 feet to a kiosk marked ``Historical Stagecoach
Trailhead.''
</P>
<P>
   The trail ascends a hill to the left, heading northwest, then
meanders through brushy swales. After a half-mile it abruptly ends
on the blacktop of Santa Susana Pass Road. Turn right, walk 200
yards and turn right again at a gated fire road. Walk past the
trash and graffiti-scarred rocks and ascend southeast along the
narrowing path carved into the hillside. Flora fans should keep an
eye peeled for the yellow flowers of the threatened Santa Susana
tarweed that bloom July through October and the rare maroon monkey
flower (March through July). After nearly a half-mile the trail
reaches a gentle hilltop and descends gradually. Look for a faint
trail on the right and follow it due south.
</P>
<P>
   This is where things get nasty. Thick chaparral clings at
clothing and scratches exposed skin as the trail loses altitude.
Step lively over a small gully and scramble around a laurel sumac
and scrub oak, then climb through a wall of coastal sage and
chamise as the pencil-thin path reaches another ridgeline. The
trail flattens out, then climbs to the crest of a knoll under a set
of power lines. The well-earned payoff is a stunning 360-degree
look at the Valley and the Simi Hills.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a breather, light out on a path going right and
after 500 feet take a left near an old wooden post. This fork soon
winds back to the top of Devil's Slide; retrace your steps down to
the trailhead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
