</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA TIGHT-LIPPED ABOUT LATEST HEROICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ How exhilarating it must feel to hit for power in the
clutch, to erase a deficit and silence naysayers with one smooth
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra is not the sort who will share such a
sentiment. It's not his way. That leaves one to only imagine what
it must have been like for the Red Sox shortstop to make up for a
third-inning throwing error _ which led to three unearned runs _
with a three-run home run in the bottom of the inning that
obliterated a 3-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   By feasting on Tampa Bay righthander Bryan Rekar's 3-1 fastball,
Garciaparra powered the Red Sox to a 5-4 victory Wednesday night at
Fenway Park that clinched at least a tie for the American League
wild-card playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate for the AL Most Valuable Player Award, Garciaparra
entered with just just three RBIs in 20 games since he hit a
game-winning grand slam against the Mariners Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough one (the error), and I was just trying to make
the play whenever I can. Then I just went out and tried to score
some runs,'' said Garciaparra, whose 33d home run was estimated at
380 feet and who is now batting .320 with runners in scoring
position. ``I was just patient. I managed to get a ball I could hit
and it just went out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all the drama you'll get from a player who doesn't talk
much about his feats or their impact. Asked what a win Thursday
night would mean to him personally, Garciaparra responded, ``We
have to win and I will find out tomorrow. I just want to win to get
into the playoffs, and we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was more expansive on other subjects. He praised winning
pitcher Steve Avery's effort. When asked about the team's ability
to come back, he said, ``We've done that all year. And it's nice.
We go out there and we do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too many people can talk about us anymore. We go out there
and we win. We're in a position right now (to clinch). We went out
there and proved it to everybody, and that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for May, when he separated his right shoulder and had
eight RBIs in just 10 games, Garciaparra had knocked in at least 19
runs in every month until this one. But Wednesday night he regained
his clutch status, going 2 for 4; in the fifth inning, he doubled
down the left-field line and scored the decisive run on a single by
Troy O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said he didn't worry about the error _ on a hard
shot by Mike Kelly _ and he wasn't trying to make up for it at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I going to do?'' he said. ``I can either hold on to it
or I can throw it and try to make the play regardless and see what
happens. I'm going to take my chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had stuff like that happen all year. You go out there and
make the play and you go out there and force it. But if you hold on
to the ball, you never know what's going to happen. I'm just glad I
caught it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Red Sox close in on the wild-card berth, it's apparent
Garciaparra won't deviate from the norm. That meant he didn't check
the score of Wednesday night's game between Baltimore and Toronto,
a Blue Jays victory that delayed a Red Sox clinch for at least a
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't looked all year,'' said Garciaparra. ``Why should we
look now? All we should look at is ourselves. That's all we need to
concern ourselves with. That's the way it's been until now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
