A1505 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-B     09-24 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ CAN APPLY FINAL TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Pedro Martinez saw the reporter approaching, but he
wasn't interested in obliging.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' 5-4 win over the Tampa Devils Rays Wednesday night,
coupled with the Blue Jays' 6-3 triumph over Baltimore, left Boston
one game away from clinching the American League wild-card playoff
berth.
</P>
<P>
   That means Martinez can do the honors Thursday night against
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't want to discuss it. ``It's too close to the
game,'' he said. ``I'm not going to talk about the game before I
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams understands. So does pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan. Their ace righthander wants to concentrate fully on this
start. He wants to make sure nothing gets by him. Most important,
he wants to shake off the September doldrums _ an 0-3 record in his
last four starts _ that have cost him a shot at his first 20-win
season and, in all likelihood, a chance to become the first pitcher
to win the Cy Young Award in each league in consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has faced the Orioles once, dropping a 3-2 decision
July 10 in Baltimore in which he went eight innings, allowing five
hits with one walk and five strikeouts. He fell victim to his major
nemesis of 1998, surrendering homers to Mike Bordick and Eric
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Of more concern is the recent winless stretch, during which
Martinez has allowed 11 runs, all earned, in 21 1/3 innings against
the Blue Jays, Yankees, and White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had his stuff; he's been throwing well,'' Williams
said. ``He's had his good pitches against tough clubs. He's pitched
better than his numbers. He's pitched well. His overall numbers
speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan also believes no tinkering is necessary. He feels
Martinez's overall numbers _ an 18-7 record, 2.77 ERA, and 245
strikeouts _ are more relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro's thrown the ball well the last three games,'' said
Kerrigan. ``We just haven't had enough runs for him, just seven
runs in those games.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Martinez probably won't wind up with a bookend for
the 1997 National League Cy Young Award he won when he went 17-8
with a 1.90 ERA and 305 strikeouts for Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been pitching to the level I can, even though I've
been doing an acceptable job,'' Martinez said of his last four
games. ``The runs haven't been enough to win games. And then there
have been the pitchers I've gone against _ David Cone and Orlando
Hernandez of the Yankees, Woody Williams of the Blue Jays, and John
Snyder of the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night he can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
