A1507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN'SHALLOFFAME-BOS     09-24 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIONEER SPIRIT SPICES HALL OF FAME INDUCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 HALL OF FAME-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Mary Carew Armstrong rose Wednesday night to
accept the Trailblazer Award from the New England Women's Fund, the
crowd of 800 rose with her. For many, it was undoubtedly the first
time they'd heard of her, but what they heard _ 84 years old,
Olympic gold medalist as anchor of the 4x100-meter relay at the
1932 Olympics, longtime fitness advocate _ they loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created it for her,'' said Ann Sanders, executive director
of the fund, which sponsored the Women's Sports Awards reception at
the Roxy. As the 3,000 ballots for the organization's new New
England Women's Sports Hall of Fame were being counted, an
unfamiliar name kept popping up as a write-in candidate for track
and field. ``I said, `I've got to find out more about this
woman.'''
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday night the Medford native, who has long been out of
the spotlight, shared the limelight with Olympic swimming gold
medalist Donna de Varona (Pioneer Award), broadcaster Robin Roberts
(Media Award), and the gold-medal Olympic women's ice hockey team
(New England Today Award).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so old, nobody remembers anymore,'' Armstrong said
afterward, her bright smile competing with the Olympic medal she
wore around her neck. ``I'm delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the special awards, 11 women became the first
class of inductees into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Hall will consist of photos and biographies
displayed at the Square One Mall in Saugus, with hopes to expand
the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The inductees _ all with ties to New England _ included:
</P>
<P>
   --Jane Blalock (golf): Won 29 LPGA tournaments during a 17-year
career; first woman golfer to earn more than $100,000 four years in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   --Maddie English and Mary Pratt (baseball): Both played in the
All-American Girls Professional Baseball League, English as third
baseman for the Racine Belles and Pratt as a pitcher for the
Rockford Peaches.
</P>
<P>
   --Tenley Albright (figure skating): Her gold medal at the 1956
Olympics was the first by an American woman in skating.
</P>
<P>
   --Rebecca Lobo (basketball): Led the University of Connecticut
to a 35-0 season in 1995 before becoming a 1996 Olympian and member
of the New York Liberty in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   --Jenny Thompson (swimming): Five-time Olympic gold medalist in
relays at the 1992 and 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   --Joan Benoit Samuelson (track and field): Won the Olympic gold
medal in the marathon in 1984, the first time women were allowed to
compete at the distance in the Games.
</P>
<P>
   --Diana Golden Brosnihan (skiing): Gold medalist in the giant
slalom for disabled skiers at the 1988 Olympics; named Female Skier
of the Year by the US Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   --Kristine Lilly (soccer): 1996 Olympic gold medalist; has
played in more international matches than any other man or woman.
</P>
<P>
   --Barb Marois (field hockey): Two-time Olympian who played
internationally for a decade; captain of the 1996 Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   --Ernestine Bayer (rowing): Established first women's rowing
organization in the country back in the late 1930s after winning
over her husband, who insisted that women couldn't row.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer Wednesday night recounted that a friend of her husband's
told him that if he permitted her to row, she would get
tuberculosis and die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived,'' said Bayer, now 89.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
