<HEADER>
A1508 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN     09-24 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT LOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Martin Dugard's description of eco-challenge races
in ``Surviving the Toughest Race on Earth'' (Ragged Mountain
Press,$19.95) proves in its 200 pages that the bar in such
``extreme'' competitions has been raised. Now what's next?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wonders how anything could be more difficult than a
triathlon _ or a double triathlon, for that matter _ should read
Dugard's riveting account.
</P>
<P>
   He traces the evolution of such races, from marathons to the
Badwater 146, which wends its way through Death Valley in the
summer heat, to the Raid Gauloises, a notorious eight- to 12-day
contest over grueling terrain. His participation makes the reader
feel the pain of kayaking, rock climbing, canoeing, skydiving,
hiking and even spelunking through 200 to 300 miles of some of the
world's most inhospitable places _ dusty deserts, steamy jungles
and forbidding mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Raid Gauloises is not only an almost inhuman test of endurance.
It is, more than anything, a test of determination, teamwork and
map-reading. All five members of each team must finish for the team
to remain in contention. What's more, each team must pass
checkpoints and negotiate terrain, which means that the most studly
team will lose if members can't avoid getting lost _ an easy fate
to suffer because the Raid crosses vast wilderness that is often
poorly charted. And, as Dugard found out, a team with poor personal
chemistry will not stick together.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County author, who left a marketing-executive post to
achieve his lifelong goal of becoming a freelance journalist, first
covers the Raid and then, seduced by the challenge, takes part in
two events. He is forced to quit one event in Patagonia, Argentina,
after tearing a knee ligament but finishes a later one in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Dugard does a fine job showing what it's like to be in the
event: the exhaustion, injury, stress, near-madness. And more.
Being lost and having to retrace steps when you're panting. Heat of
120 degrees. Walking for 24 hours straight. Sleep deprivation.
Contending with crocodiles, dirty water, blisters upon blisters
upon blisters.
</P>
<P>
   Some competitors hallucinate. Many are forced to choose between
continuing _ even risking death _ and quitting and feeling shame
and a sense of failure as tormenting as any of the pains felt in
the events.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Dugard writes, the event was a hallowed, almost
mystical experience: ``The Raid is about looking into your soul,
something modern man finds uncomfortable. We are distracted
constantly by telephones and television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiritual serenity I have never witnessed in competitions
ever, anywhere.'' Our rating: three and a half stars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   City dwellers want it both ways _ the rewards of country living
in the middle of a metropolis. It's hard to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most practical ways of enjoying nature in the
``concrete jungle'' is to lure birds to our homes, and Donald and
Lillian Stokes have done just this in ``Bird Gardening Book: The
Complete Guide to Creating a Bird-Friendly Habitat in Your
Backyard'' (Little, Brown and Co.; $12.95). In a succinct 94 pages,
the Stokeses, hosts of a television series on birding, reveal their
secrets of drawing 140 species of birds to their property in the
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The process involves more than just birdhouses, birdbaths and
bird feeders. It also helps to have tall grass shrubs, lawns,
berries, flowers; the book lists which birds to attract to each
type of flora.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its brevity, ``Bird Gardening Book'' _ one of many with
similar titles _ is an ideal guide for city slickers sick of seeing
only pigeons and crows. Our rating: two and a half stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National parks are not a big secret. They're easy to reach,
beautiful ... and often as crowded as L.A. freeways during rush
hour. Who needs a SigAlert when we're on vacation from such
stresses?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to be that way. ``Beyond the National Parks: A
Recreation Guide to Public Lands in the West'' (Smithsonian
Institution Press, $19.95), edited by Mary E. Tisdale and Bibi
Booth, shows many of the best sites of the lesser-known Bureau of
Land Management.
</P>
<P>
   BLM employees and members of other participating outdoor and
conservation organizations list their favorite places, with the
location, description, directions and visitor activities (even dog
mushing) all listed. Nice stretches of California desert and
coastline are included. Also exhaustively detailed in the 394 pages
are any necessary permits and fees, accessibility and nearby
camping, lodging and food supplies. The book boasts gorgeous
photos, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's a suitable point of departure to reach unknown, uncrowded
areas. Our rating: three stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
