<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND ANSWERS MARINER COMEBACK; RANGERS UP NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Cases of champagne will be delivered to the Kingdome
sometime today, but the shipment is headed for the visitors'
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will try to delay what appears inevitable: a
division-clinching party for the Texas Rangers, who open a
season-ending, four-game series here Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   On the one-year anniversary of their second American League West
Division title, the M's failed to secure a third-place finish,
dropping an 8-3 decision to the Oakland Athletics Wednesday night
before 21,182 fans.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time in Anaheim, Calif., the Rangers lowered their
magic number to two with a series-sweeping victory against the
Angels. Any combination of two Texas wins or Anaheim losses settles
the only undecided division race in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 365 days ago Wednesday, Heathcliff Slocumb recorded the
final out in the Mariners' 4-3 victory over the Angels at the
Kingdome, giving the M's a week to prepare for the AL Division
Series, which they lost to Baltimore in four games. Wednesday
night, the right-hander surrendered the fall-behind run in the
eighth inning as the A's averted a three-game sweep and kept their
hopes alive for finishing higher than the M's.
</P>
<P>
   Any chance of a Mariner comeback Wednesday was squashed in the
ninth when three Seattle relievers _ Bobby Ayala, Steve Gajkowski
and Greg McCarthy _ combined for four walks, two hit batters and a
wild pitch to fuel a four-run Athletic uprising without benefit of
a basehit.
</P>
<P>
   Slocumb absorbed the loss, but any of the relievers were
deserving.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Ken Cloude worked the first 61/3 innings and entered the
seventh with a 3-2 lead, compliments of a two-run Mariner sixth
inning off Oakland starter Mike Oquist.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez tied the game with his 42nd homer of the season,
Ken Griffey Jr. singled and later scored the go-ahead run when Raul
Ibanez grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also stole his 44th base of the season, making him the
most prolific 40/40 player in major-league history. He has as many
homers as Jose Canseco hit in 1988 and Barry Bonds in '96. But
Canseco and Bonds finished their seasons with 40 steals.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude finished his first full big-league season with an 8-10
record, winning one of his last six starts. Although the
right-hander doubled his win output from last season, his earned
run average climbed from 5.12 to 6.37.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty informative year, to say the least,'' he said.
``I expected it to be a pretty big learning experience in my first
full season in the big leagues. I actually expected to do a little
better than I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I learned enough that I can get to the point where I want
to be next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude left Slocumb with a bases-loaded, one-out jam in the
seventh. The Mariners escaped without allowing a run, thanks to a
leaping catch by second baseman Giomar Guevara on a scorcher hit by
Jason Giambi and a Slocumb strikeout of Matt Stairs.
</P>
<P>
   But a one-out walk to Scott Spiezio, pinch-runner Rickey
Henderson's stolen base and Eric Chavez's two-out single to center
put Oakland ahead to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an ugly ninth inning,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
``It brought some memories of way back when. Basically, we have
been pitching pretty well, but that ninth inning, walks, hit
batsmen. I don't think they had a hit, did they?''
</P>
<P>
   On Cloude, Piniella said, ``I see him in the rotation next year.
He has a good arm. He gained a lot of experience this year. We feel
he'll be better with one (full) year under his belt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
