<HEADLINE>
SOUTHLAND PRIMED FOR STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The professional golf season might be winding
down, but that's hardly relevant to Southern California fans. This
is the time of year they get to attend most of their pro events.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch run starts with the Oct. 8-11 Nike Tour Inland
Valley Open at Moreno Valley Ranch, near Beaumont. Then comes the
Pacific Bell Senior Classic (formerly Ralphs Senior Classic), Oct.
26-Nov. 1 at Wilshire. That's followed by the Nov. 11-15 Franklin
Templeton Shark Shootout at Sherwood Country Club, the Nov. 16-22
LPGA Tour Championship at the Desert Inn Resort in Las Vegas, the
Nov. 28-29 Skins Game at Rancho La Quinta and Dec. 19-20 Lexus
Challenge at the La Quinta Citrus Course.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famers Chi Chi Rodriguez and Lee Trevino have committed
to the Pacific Bell senior event at Wilshire, joining a field that
includes two-time defending champion Gil Morgan and senior tour
rookie John Mahaffey, the 1978 PGA champion who turned 50 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Other top seniors expected to play include past Ralphs champions
Raymond Floyd, Dale Douglass and John Bland, 1996 Senior U.S. Open
champion Dave Stockton and former PGA superstar-turned-broadcaster
Johnny Miller. Miller could add serious interest to the event. In
1994, he stepped out of the broadcast booth to play in the PGA
Tour's Pebble Beach National Pro Am and won _ at age 47.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Nike update:!off! Former area stars David Berganio, Jason
Gore, Chris Zambri and Bob Burns will play in the Nike Inland
Valley Open.
</P>
<P>
   All rank in Nike top-10 statistical categories through this week
_ Berganio and Burns for scoring average and all-around play,
Zambri for sand saves and Gore for driving and eagles. Berganio
also leads the Nike Tour in total driving and is tied for sixth in
greens in regulation. With two events left before the season-ending
tour championship, Burns (13th), Zambri (16th) and Berganio (37th)
are all within reach of a top-15 season money finish that would
earn exemption to next year's PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   How tough is the Nike Tour? Consider this: Two players _ Notah
Begay Jr. and Doug Dunakey _ shot rounds of 59 this year and
neither won in that tournament. Another player, Chris Couch, is
averaging 302.1 yards off the tee and doesn't lead the tour in
driving _ Stiles Mitchell does, at 307.8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty tough,'' said Dave Lancer, the Notre Dame High
alumnus who works as PGA Tour director of information. ``The
difference between players on the Nike Tour and PGA Tour is
marginal.''
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying tournaments for the Nike Inland Valley Open are
scheduled for today (amateur only) at Soboba Springs and for Oct. 5
(open qualifying) at Sun Lakes in Banning and Soboba Springs. Entry
fee for the open qualifiers is $225, with a deadline of Wednesday.
The top seven finishers in each open qualifier and the top amateur
in today's qualifier earn berths in the Nike event. Information:
(909) 924-6004.
</P>
<P>
   __ Shark sighting: Greg Norman, who missed most of this season
because of shoulder surgery, will return to competitive golf at the
Franklin Templeton Shark Shootout he hosts each November in
Thousand Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   The annual event at Sherwood Country Club, featuring 10 two-man
teams of top pros, was started 10 years ago by Norman and his wife
Laura to help raise funds to fight childhood cancer.
</P>
<P>
   __ A tournament worth winning: When Jeff Freeman of Tamarisk
Country Club in Rancho Mirage survived a final-round, 17th-hole
double bogey to win this year's Southern California PGA Section
championship last week, he came away with more than a trophy and
some atta-boys.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, who finished 69-68-69_206 to win by two strokes over
Steve Sear of Jim McLean Golf School, also earned exemptions into
three PGA Tour events next year _ the Bob Hope Desert Classic in
Palm Desert, Nissan Open at Riviera and Buick Invitational at
Torrey Pines.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern California PGA is one of 41 sections of the PGA of
America and includes more than 1,500 men and women who work as golf
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   A field of 134 started the 54-hole section championship at
Mission Hills CC in Rancho Mirage, with 60 advancing to the final
two rounds. John Sanhamel of Oakmont led area finishers, tying for
25th at 219.
</P>
<P>
   Other area pros who made the cut included Roger Gunn of Lake
Lindero, Ted Lehmann of Westlake Village, Rick Garboski of North
Ranch, Don Fiala of Wood Ranch and regular-season money and points
leader Paul Holtby of Los Robles.
</P>
<P>
   __ Names in the game: Alice Cooper, Hootie and the Blowfish, Van
Halen ... and Grayson Taylor Eleftheriou? The first three are
rockers turned golfers. It's too early to know yet about No. 4, but
2-week-old Grayson Taylor, born Sept. 11, has the genes: His dad,
former heavy-metal bandsman and current Scholl Canyon head pro Ted,
is combining diaper duty with giving 60 to 70 golf lessons a week
and hopes to qualify for the Nike Inland Valley Open....
</P>
<P>
   Rich Contreras, who shares the course record of 9-under-par 51
at Scholl Canyon, is the man to beat in this week's final round of
the men's club championship at Verdugo Hills three-par course.
Contreras, a teaching pro at Verdugo Hills, shot 8-under par _
three shots off the course record _ in the second round of that
54-hole event and came within a lipped-out putt of shooting 6-under
on the back nine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
