<SLUG> BC-MANDELA-MEDAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, GINGRICH BOTH CLOSE TO TEARS AT CAPITOL CEREMONY
FOR  MANDELA 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ As cheers and applause echoed through the Capitol
Rotunda, President Clinton awarded Nelson Mandela the Congressional
Gold Medal Wednesday, making him the first African to receive
Congress' highest award.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The South African president, who met with Muhammad Ali and
Evander Holyfield earlier in the day, said the only accomplishment
that he regretted not achieving was becoming heavyweight champion
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I feel like the heavyweight champion of the world,''
said Mandela, who was an accomplished amateur boxer until he was
sentenced to life imprisonment when he was 43.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela became the 100th person to receive the award, which has
been granted to figures ranging from George Washington to Mother
Teresa. The event was filled with deep emotions, as politicians
from both sides of the aisle tried to draw on the lessons of
Mandela's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``No medal, no award, no fortune, nothing we could give him
could possibly compare to the gifts he has given us and to the
world,'' said Clinton, who appeared close to tears. ``The only true
gift that is true recompense is to continue the mission and to live
by the power of his profound and wonderful example.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich was also overcome by emotion and
appeared to cut short his speech to avoid breaking into tears.
``When you contemplate 27 years in prison, when you imagine walking
out of that isolation with your heart larger and not smaller,
President Mandela, you give every person on the planet a personal
witness to how valuable freedom must be, to be worthy of such a
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Gingrich singled out former Rep. Ron Dellums
of Oakland, Calif., for championing anti-apartheid legislation in
Congress for 15 years until it was finally approved by Congress in
1985. ``We should take just a moment to honor the member of this
Congress who I think without question did the most, day in and day
out, year in and year out, to maintain the fight to end apartheid,
our friend Ron Dellums,'' said Gingrich, as Dellums rose to a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   And as Mandela stood to acknowledge his award, Dellums bounded
up to the podium and embraced Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   The South African leader was accompanied by Graca Machel, whom
he married on his 80th birthday last month. Mandela will leave
office in May, and he has said that this will be his last visit to
the United States while president.
</P>
<P>
   The event marked the first time Clinton had been on Capitol Hill
since independent counsel Kenneth Starr sent his report on the
Monica Lewinsky scandal to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   There were only veiled references to the political crisis
gripping the capital. ``Politics in a free society is a very
rough-and-tumble business, involving at times great personal
pain,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton said to Mandela, ``Americans as one today across all
the lines that divide us, pay tribute to your struggle and to the
inspiration you have given us to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the audience were the parents of Amy Biehl, the
26-year-old Stanford graduate who was stabbed to death by rampaging
youths outside Cape Town, nine months before South Africa's first
democratic elections in April 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through her, our people have also shared the pain of
confronting a terrible past as we take the path toward
reconciliation and healing of our nation,'' said Mandela. He also
paid tribute to the ``countless ordinary American citizens'' who
participated in the anti-apartheid movement. ``In all these ways,
the United States and its people have played a significant role in
the birth of our new nation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
