<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN_DODGERS2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOHANON PONDERS HIS FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (WRITETHRU) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brian Bohanon took his ball and went home.
</P>
<P>
   Will he be back? Will the Los Angeles Dodgers look at the
journeyman left-hander who has put together the best 2{ months of
his nine-year career and decide he is worth the free-agent money he
can finally command?.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon hopes so. He hopes games like Wednesday's 3-2
complete-game loss to the National League West-champion San Diego
Padres aren't forgotten during the Dodgers' offseason purge.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they are or not, Bohanon will always remember catching
Quilvio Veras' popup with two outs in the ninth that ended his
season. Bohanon walked off the mound clutching the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Although he went the distance twice in his last three starts,
and lost both times, Bohanon left with his head up. He came into
manager Glenn Hoffman's office to offer thanks for giving him a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about the possibilities,'' Bohanon said. ``I
would love to stay here. They gave me the opportunity. I showed
people that I come to pitch every time out. I can give you 32-34
starts a year. Most of all, I have the confidence in myself to
close out games. That is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was 5-7 in his 14 starts with the Dodgers, Bohanon
had a 2.40 ERA during that stretch. He pitched at least six innings
in 12 consecutive starts. All this from a guy who had a 7.77 ERA in
1996 when he pitched in relief for the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence is the difference,'' said pitching coach Charlie
Hough. ``He has taken this opportunity and really taken off. He
knows and you know that when he goes out there it is going to be a
quality performance.''
</P>
<P>
   But what will it mean at free-agent time? Three years
guaranteed, two years and an option for more than $4-5 million. The
Dodgers will have a staff meeting today headed by new general
manager Kevin Malone to start addressing issues such as Bohanon's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Bohanon started slowly, but he made only one mistake
in the final seven innings, a fifth-inning home run to Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres used five pitchers in relief of starter Andy Ashby
(17-9), who went six innings for his first victory since Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them pitched as a tuneup for the postseason, which
begins Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It might seemed like a waste of time for the Dodgers at the end
of a miserable season, but for the Padres it was critical.
Situation pitching is an important part of playoff baseball.
Longtime Angel Mark Langston, for example, is being asked to come
out of the bullpen after spending his entire career as a starting
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego also used top left-handed set up man Randy Myers with
two outs in the eighth after Dan Miceli walked Raul Mondesi. Myers
gave up a pinch single to Charles Johnson, putting runners at first
and third.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres turned to closer Trevor Hoffman, their sixth pitcher,
and he got the final out of the eighth when Mark Grudzielanek
popped out to first. Hoffman also pitched the ninth to get his 52nd
save.
</P>
<P>
   All the moves also were important because the Padres, who
clinched the NL West on Sept. 12 in San Diego, have not played well
in September.
</P>
<P>
   With Wednesday's victory, they are just 8-13 in the month,
ruining any chance of going into the playoffs with the league's
best record. If Atlanta keeps the best record and the New York Mets
win the wild card over Chicago, the Padres will play the Braves in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cubs win the wild card, San Diego will open against
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably saw a few more guys in there than normal,''
Padres manager Bruce Bochy said, ``but I wanted to prepare guys for
situations they might see in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be a postseason for Bohanon or the Dodgers. But both
hope there have been lessons learned this season that will get them
there in the future.
</P>
<P>
   For Bohanon, one of the turning points this season was a
suggestion from Hough that he focus more on his throwing between
starts. He would go to the bullpen and work on situations. He also
would hit the weights hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preparation has been the key for me since I got here,''
Bohanon said. ``Throwing between starts became very important. I
learned there how to concentrate and how to pitch the seventh,
eighth and ninth innings. That has been the difference for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
