<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARIJUANA-PAINKILLER-     09-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARIJUANA-PAINKILLER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY EXPLAINS HOW MARIJUANA KILLS PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Researchers say they have identified a new way
to explain how THC, the active ingredient in marijuana, acts on the
central nervous system to kill pain.
</P>
<P>
   Laboratory experiments at the University of California at San
Francisco have revealed that tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) taps
circuitry at the base of the brain, modulating pain signals in much
the same way as morphine and other opiates.
</P>
<P>
   The findings seem to corroborate reports from some doctors and
marijuana users who claim that smoking pot helps keep pain under
control. Skeptics, however, still insist that marijuana's medicinal
value has yet to be proved.
</P>
<P>
   The UCSF experiments were conducted on rats given doses of a
synthetic form of THC _ one in a family of drugs called
cannabinoids. Led by Ian Meng, a postdoctoral fellow at UCSF
working in the laboratory of neurologist Howard Fields, the
researchers took precise measurements of electrical activity to
determine how the marijuana-like drug affected circuitry in the
brainstem and spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   Pain responses were gauged by a standard routine that measures
how long the rats take to move their tails from a heat source. The
experiments were designed to keep THC's direct effects on movement
and coordination from masking the drug's analgesic effects.
</P>
<P>
   Results were detailed Wednesday in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Meng and his colleagues Barton Manning and William Martin
focused on a region deep in the brain called the rostral
ventromedial medulla, or RVM _ a kind of relay station for pain
signals which Meng likened to ``the volume control on a stereo.''
</P>
<P>
   Both morphine and cannabinoids turn down the volume _ minimizing
the intensity of pain sensations reaching other parts of the brain
_ by switching on or off certain cells in the same region.
</P>
<P>
   Meng found that the marijuana-like drug acted on the same cells
as morphine, but through a different mechanism. Although
preliminary, that finding carries important implications for the
potential medical uses of cannabinoids.
</P>
<P>
   Opiates generally are much more effective than cannabinoids at
reducing pain symptoms. But the opiates also can cause nausea and
other unwanted side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana-like drugs tend to counteract nausea in many people
while at the same time stimulating appetite. Thus, Meng said, the
two types of painkillers might be used in combination, presumably
with reduced dosages of opiates needed to achieve the desired pain
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point would be to enhance the pain-suppressing effects of
the drugs while reducing the side effects,'' he said. ``The
potential is there to reduce some of the nausea you get with the
opioids.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ethan Russo, a neurologist in Missoula, Mont., who recently
concluded a detailed historical study of marijuana's therapeutic
role, said the new findings bolster the notion that cannabinoids
are ``genuine medicine with clear pharmacologic effects.''
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics said the mere discovery of a new brainstem circuit
adds little to the controversy surrounding the herb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly interesting and praiseworthy to elucidate a
mechanism of action,'' said Dr. Peter Wolfe, an associate clinical
professor of medicine at the University of California at Los
Angeles. ``But it would be even more interesting to see how this
drug really stacks up against what's already available.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that morphine's side effects can be minimized by using
other drugs already on the market that lack the disorienting
effects linked to the cannabinoids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
