<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bring on Georges; this time we're ready
 &HT;    (For immediate release.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In August 1992, neither our house nor the houses on
either side of us had hurricane shutters, a ruinous omission likely
caused by lethargy toward hurricanes rather than by financial
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   It took the monstrous winds of Hurricane Andrew to shatter our
roofs and windows and race destructively throughout our houses to
make us understand the power of a hurricane, a weather phenomenon
that had been absent from the Miami area for a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   As Hurricane Georges roared across Puerto Rico, Hispaniola and
Cuba this week, those who recalled the days, weeks and months of
recovery just six years earlier moved almost by rote to prepare for
what this time was expected to be a minimal hurricane; certainly
minimal compared to Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   For me and my neighbors, no longer was there a need to rush to
the home supply store to purchase paneling to board windows. We
avoided the long, testy lines because we had properly constructed
aluminum shutters in place.
</P>
<P>
   We had learned our lesson.
</P>
<P>
   With local TV and the Weather Channel bleating at us about
Georges ever since it showed up as a zephyr off the west coast of
Africa, preparations for it have been methodic and without panic.
</P>
<P>
   (I don't know which was more of a video deluge: local hurricane
weather reports or the continuing soap opera surrounding the
president. For the most part, around-the-clock local TV coverage of
creeping hurricanes is as repetitious and non-revealing as were the
Clinton tapes.)
</P>
<P>
   The danger of Georges is not so much the damage it can inflict
on the U.S. mainland, having already been stripped of much of its
power over Hispaniola and Cuba, but the fact that it is not the
scope of an Andrew. For the many thousands who have moved to South
Florida in the past six years, a mild bump by Georges might create
a lack of fear.
</P>
<P>
   No hurricane, no matter how mild, will reinstill a lethargy in
those of us who barely survived Andrew. To us, the start of the
hurricane season each June 1 is a time to begin preparation,
whether or not anything has slipped off the African coast.
</P>
<P>
   It's all bought, then _ the water, canned goods, batteries,
paper goods, etc. The storm shutters are checked, and anything
having to do with a hurricane is put in working order by June 1,
not when a hurricane watch is being posted.
</P>
<P>
   We were complacent once, and we suffered the consequences. We
will never again be caught so off guard. In my neighborhood, and
with my family, we treat Hurricane Georges with the same awe as we
gave Andrew _ after it hit us.
</P>
<P>
   So prepared were we now that we completed whatever we had to do
by Wednesday night. As I write this on Thursday, I have nothing to
do _ it's all done.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left is to sit around and watch weather experts on TV
telling us how to prepare for a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   That must be for the people who weren't around for Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
