<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-INTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL GIVES $6 MILLION TO WHITNEY FOR A SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Intel Corp. has contributed $6 million to the
Whitney Museum of American Art to stage its mammoth overview of
20th century art and culture, which is scheduled to open next
April.
</P>
<P>
   The gift is thought to be the largest made to an art museum for
a specific exhibition and will be accompanied by the further
contribution of staff and technology for computer enhancements for
the show, ``The American Century: Art and Culture 1900-2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, the museum's signature offering to mark the end of the
century, will include more than 1,400 works _ paintings,
sculptures, photography, architecture and design _ and will present
related materials in music, dance, literature and film. The aim is
to explore the changing nature of American identity through the
eyes of artists across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The show will be presented in two consecutive parts and will
fill the Whitney's main Marcel Breuer building for nine months. The
first part, covering 1900 to 1950, will run from April 22 to Aug.
30; the second, covering the last half of the century, will run
from next October to February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The show will then go to the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art,
where it will be from May through September 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The gift comes as corporate giving for specific shows is
declining. Intel, the world's largest manufacturer of microchips,
said it was attracted by the opportunity to identify with the
educational aspect of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology can give museumgoing a different dimension,'' said
Andrew S. Grove, chairman and chief executive of Intel. ``It has
been such a big part of the American century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``About this collaboration,'' he added, ``you could say all the
stars lined up in the right way.'' Among the features being
developed are an advanced Web site and computers at the exhibition
to give visitors access to information about specific artworks and
related topics.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney officials said the technology would offer the visitor
crystal clear three-dimensional images, several ways to quickly
call up audio and video information and customized programs
tailored to a viewer's interests and level of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The computers are to be in a room much like the reading rooms of
many exhibitions, where visitors can delve into catalogs and books
that provide more information than the wall texts do. ``We will
update the concept of the reading room as a marvelous pause in an
exhibition,'' said Maxwell L. Anderson, director of the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Intel executives said they were also experimenting with portable
computer devices to be used in the museum with access to the Web
site, which would also make most of the information available
outside the museum as well. The company is working with the museum
to develop an online curriculum for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the company and the museum said they were sensitive
to concerns that computers could seem intrusive and that technology
would reduce the desire of visitors to focus on the art objects
themselves rather than representations on computer screens. They
said the computers were intended to enhance rather than substitute
for the museum experience.
</P>
<P>
   But Grove said that scanning a Web site from outside a museum
had its advantages. ``As a museumgoer, you don't have the ability
to zoom into things because you are always dodging heads,'' he
said. ``Being seen in a home or office without crowds or time
pressures will add a different dimension to the public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
