<HEADER>
A1775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GODOT-THEATER-REVIEW-     09-24 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODOT-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STREET-SMART `GODOT' IN A CULTURAL WASTELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end)  
(gm) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If ever a pair of Beckett clowns were made for each
other, it would have to be the Vladimir and Estragon who run amok
in Joy Zinoman's hip new staging of ``Waiting for Godot.''
</P>
<P>
   Played by a pair of elastic and dynamic actors, Thomas W. Jones
2d and Donald Griffin, they're so merrily in sync that it's easy to
see why they hang out together in perpetuity, waiting at the
appointed time and place for someone who never comes. (With a White
House itself in perpetual crisis, waiting seems a particularly apt
stage metaphor in Washington these days.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in Ms. Zinoman's liberty-taking and immensely enjoyable
production, Godot is practically superfluous. Who needs the
intrusion from that metaphysical no-show? Didi and Gogo, as they're
more familiarly known, are happy to keep themselves occupied with
their own skills as performers, even if their performance space is
as experimental as they come: the middle of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The added value is that you'll be entertained, too. While
they're unable to avoid the occasional lapse into cuteness in this
revival by Ms. Zinoman's Studio Theater, Jones and Griffin are
agile showmen, the kinds of resourceful physical performers who can
get a laugh with a gesture even when the words don't always hold
up.
</P>
<P>
   They play Beckett's heroes as a pair of dancing fools, distinct
from one another and yet bound so tightly it's impossible by the
play's end to think of one without the other. They beautifully
execute a central theme of this work, that regardless of outward
circumstances, one's existence has no meaning unless it is
validated by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zinoman, the longtime artistic director of the Studio
Theater, a 20-year-old subscription playhouse located off 14th
Street N.W., just north of midtown, infuses her ``Godot'' with an
up-to-the-minute urban sensibility. The play begins with a few
jazzy notes on a saxophone; the black actors who play the leads _
the supporting roles of Pozzo and Lucky are portrayed by whites _
perform bits of hip-hop and, in the kinds of improvisations that
would have driven Beckett up the wall, embellish the text with
caustic asides, resort to black slang and even flirt and banter
with the audience. ``What's wrong with white people?'' Jones ad
libs in mock-irritation at one point, when he fails to elicit the
desired response from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The actors charm their way through most of it, but making
``Godot'' interactive leaves some questions for the continuity
department: Are Didi and Gogo alone on that barren landscape? Or
are we out there with them? Either way, this is a ``Godot'' that
means to explore the relationship between the entertainer and the
entertained.
</P>
<P>
   The pleasingly simple set by Russell Metheny suggests the
symbolic edge of America's vast cultural wasteland: Didi and Gogo
hold their vigil on a bare tract behind a drive-in movie screen so
big it blacks out the sky, and the actors wear a trace of white
makeup around their mouths, hinting at their own theatrical
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   You could imagine this Didi and Gogo one day in side-by-side
rocking chairs in an old-age home for over-the-hill hoofers; in the
meantime, they derive pleasure (and kill time) doing bits of stage
business, deftly juggling turnips, for instance, or running through
Abbott-and-Costello-style comedy routines.
</P>
<P>
   The warmth between them grows as the actors explore the nooks
and crannies of their companionship, and the dimensions of their
mutual admiration and dependence take shape. Griffin is the
stockier, earthbound yin to Jones' lighter-than-air yang: the
rounder of the pair is sadder, more reflective, the taller more
carefree and frenetic.
</P>
<P>
   Their felicitous bond, of course, is in bold contrast to the
perverse master-slave relationship of Pozzo (Michael Tolaydo) and
Lucky (Hugh Nees), who cross paths with Didi and Gogo for no
particular reason at all. Tolaydo's self-infatuated Pozzo is a
distant relation to the puffed-up Master Thespian character Jon
Lovitz used to play on ``Saturday Night Live,'' and Nees' Lucky,
tethered, as always, to the rope Pozzo controls, deftly navigates a
course between hapless prisoner and beast of burden.
</P>
<P>
   Had Jones and Griffin not been such attractive headliners, Nees
might have walked away with the play. His slobbering, stuttering
declamation of Lucky's long, run-on speech, consisting entirely of
non-sequiturs, is a show-stopper, funny and at the same time
utterly pathetic. It's the best of Beckett, a lover of both words
and the grotesque, and Nees' nimble rendition makes the spoken aria
an event unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   Showing off, after all, is what this production celebrates, and
the only drawback is that once the actors finish with all the
riffing, they have no recourse, no bridge to the play's darker
dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is so show biz that the poignancy of Didi and Gogo's
lonely plight, the echo of the tragic element in all of human life,
has no chance to sink in. There's a feeling as the less satisfying
second act winds down that something deeper in the play has been
glossed over.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Zinoman and her excellent players have performed a
vital service, liberating ``Waiting for Godot'' from the
airlessness and pretension that often afflict productions of
Beckett. The Studio Theater revival is an enthusiastic vote in
favor of a great playwright's lasting relevance.
</P>
<P>
   WAITING FOR GODOT
</P>
<P>
   By Samuel Beckett; directed by Joy Zinoman; sets by Russell
Metheny; costumes by Helen Q. Huang; lighting by Joseph Appelt;
music by Fred Karns; sound by Neil McFadden; properties, Contessa
Riggs; dramaturge, Daniel Gallant. Presented by the Studio Theater,
Ms. Zinoman, artistic and managing director. At 1333 P Street,
N.W., Washington.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Thomas W. Jones 2d (Vladimir), Donald Griffin (Estragon),
Michael Tolaydo (Pozzo), Hugh Nees (Lucky) and Jonathan P. LeFlore
(The Boy).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
