<HEADER>
A1784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEETHOVEN-MUSIC-REVIE     09-24 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEETHOVEN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MASTER STEEPED IN THE CORE WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nine Beethoven symphonies are colossal works of
seminal importance to the classical repertory. No one worth paying
attention to disputes this.
</P>
<P>
   But they are also terribly familiar. Subjected to such
overexposure, the startling, inventive qualities of the symphonies
simply fade away. The challenge to musicians is to present these
works in a programmatic context _ alongside contemporary works, for
example _ that might help us hear them in fresh ways.
</P>
<P>
   There is no especially compelling reason for the conductor Kurt
Masur's current Beethoven symphony cycle with the New York
Philharmonic to be happening right now. All nine works are being
played in order in a series of five programs. If, say, the
orchestra at the Manhattan School of Music were doing this, it
would at least be a chance to experience the Beethoven symphonies
with young musicians playing them for the first time. Perhaps
Masur's target listeners are those classical-music neophytes who
have boxed-set recordings of the Beethoven symphonies, but have
never heard them performed complete in concert. Such audiences
members will likely be thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   But the main reason for this series would seem to be Masur's
desire to make a statement in repertory that he has a special claim
to through heritage, and that he has steeped himself in. Of course,
there is a well-documented legacy of similar statements from the
great conductors of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Masur is a fine Beethoven conductor, as his program on
Tuesday night of Symphonies Nos. 2 and 3 made clear. He conducts
this music with insight, energy and an exceptional sense of
structural cohesion, and he conducts it from memory. The musicians
responded with technically accomplished, supple and incisive
playing.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up with an old recording of the Symphony No. 2 conducted
by Sir Thomas Beecham that made it seem affable, humorous and
delightfully clever. Masur was more intent, it seemed, on making
the Second Symphony seem a warm-up for the Third, the mighty
``Eroica.'' This was a bold, big-gestured, sonorous performance.
</P>
<P>
   Some conductors highlight the burgeoning Romanticism in the
``Eroica'' Symphony. Masur treated it like a masterwork of high
Classicism. Structure and direction were paramount. The long
passage in the development section of the first movement _ a
buildup of offbeat, accented, increasingly dissonant chords _ was
handled as a bold structural block, not milked for dramatic effect.
Overall, this was a strong, vigorous performance.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback to the program was that something more
adventurous was not happening instead. But Masur believes
passionately that the New York Philharmonic must maintain the core
classical masterworks. And he is well suited to the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
