</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEPHERD-CABARET-REVIEWNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBILL SHEPHERD: `MOUTHING OFF' AS ART, TO SAY NOTHING OF SONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``At this moment, I'm surgically uncorrected,''
Cybill Shepherd boasted from the stage at Tuesday's opening night
show of her two-week engagement at Rainbow and Stars. ``Who knows?
In five years, I could have my whole self done.''
</P>
<P>
   The blond 48-year-old star also boasted about her new
multimillion-dollar contract with Revlon representing Ultima 2 and
delivered an impromptu sales pitch. She rattled on cheerily about
her years of bad reviews, especially for her singing, and bragged
about the companies that went out of business after she recorded
for them.
</P>
<P>
   Yada yada yada. If you want to experience an uncensored close-up
encounter with a star who enjoys ``mouthing off,'' as she put it,
Ms. Shepherd's act may be your cup of tea. Mouthing off on Tuesday
meant touting her coming autobiography, ``Cybill Disobedience,''
which Ms. Shepherd promised would be the literary equivalent of
``turning over a rock and looking under it.'' Its revelations, she
promised, would include a description of Elvis Presley's anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   Her anecdotes also included stories about Bruce Willis (he
enjoyed mooning the cast and crew of ``Moonlighting'') and Orson
Welles (he was her house guest for five years when she was living
with Peter Bogdanovich, and once nearly set the place on fire with
a lighted cigar he left in his bathrobe).
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. Ms. Shepherd also sang. Or tried to. Accompanied by a
mediocre quartet, she plowed through a program that included
everything from Gershwin (``But Not for Me'') to Memphis-style
rhythm-and-blues, all performed in the thin, wobbly voice of a
tone-deaf teen-ager blissfully unaware of her own lack of talent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 0956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYONS-DANCE-DIENNIAL-     09-24 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYONS-DANCE-DIENNIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: DISCOVERING A COOL ESTHETIC FOR BURNING ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYONS, France _ Social protest and conceptual cool have come to
the fore in ``Mediterranea,'' the 1998 presentation of the Lyons
Dance Biennial.
</P>
<P>
   Diversity in a theme festival, which focuses this year on dance
from countries around the Mediterranean, could be expected.
Nonetheless, contrasts in the 14-year-old biennial, which closes on
Sept. 29, have been more than striking.
</P>
<P>
   The pain of Algerian choreographers, exiled from their country
because of civil strife, has been strongly expressed in works that
speak of violence, religious fundamentalism and the despair of
immigrants. But a distinctly post-modern esthetic has also made
itself felt, mainly in modern-dance pieces from Spain and Israel
and especially in a high-tech mixed-media super-spectacle presented
by the Lyons Opera Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the National Front, France's extreme-right
political party, have continued to rail against the biennial for
its multicultural theme. During a National Front meeting in Paris
last weekend, Bruno Gollnisch, ranked No. 3 in the party's
leadership, announced on national television that he would oppose
any subsidy for the next Lyons Dance Biennial, in 2000, ``if it
continues in the same direction.'' This year, pressure from the
National Front caused the cancellation of a regional subsidy for a
parade. Gollnisch added that he would also oppose the Contemporary
Art Biennial to be held in Lyons next year because the previous one
was ``ugly and dirty.'' So much for esthetics.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder of this year's dance festival is that politics has
not intruded on the choreographers and performers, who have been
judged on their own terms. Guy Darmet, the biennial's artistic
director, has again brilliantly created a fresh context to view the
familiar and the new.
</P>
<P>
   The festival has brought into relief a revealing connection.
Many of the choreographers have studied in the United States and
some, like Abou Lagraa, a 27-year-old French choreographer of
Algerian descent, have lauded their participation in the American
Dance Festival's International Choreographers Workshop in Durham,
N.C. Such workshops gave choreographers a springboard for their
work in countries where modern dance was just developing.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one in the biennial has imitated American dance, the
experimental choreographers (and that includes the protest genre)
exhibit a firm knowledge of international trends.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, ``Murs-Murs de la Mediterranee,'' which speaks of violence
and hopelessness among Algerian youth at home and in French
immigrant slums, has some affinity with works by black American
choreographers like Talley Beatty. Raza Hammadi, one of the
choreographers, was a longtime disciple of Matt Mattox, the veteran
American jazz-dance teacher who worked in France for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, presented by Ballet Jazz Art Productions (a modern
dance group), and ``Faster than the Wind,'' a work in which Elhadi
Cheriffa, former artistic director of the National Ballet of
Algeria, creates images of exodus, are less illustrative than
abstract or symbolic. ``Murs-Murs,'' which incorporates hip-hop,
ballet, jazz and modern dance, is a series of vignettes, some
uneven.
</P>
<P>
   But it pulls no punches. By the end, a traditional but
relatively free society is taken over by black-robed
fundamentalists who rush in to pray repeatedly and mechanically. A
government official, symbolized by a uniformed man who becomes the
puppet of a fundamentalist, is not left blameless. The walls
(``murs'') of the title are screens moved around to change spatial
relationships. They symbolize North African architecture and the
walls of French ghettos, against which the young people beat their
fists.
</P>
<P>
   This is a strong, moving piece whose sophistication comes from
its team of collaborators, the Algerian film director Belkacem
Hadjadj; the company's co-directors, Hammadi and Cherif Chikh, and
two other choreographers, Brahim Arbia and Sadok Khechana. The work
could use some editing, but its raw verve expresses strong opinions
about issues that most Americans, at least, know little about.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme is a double bill, ``EJM 1-EJM 2,'' created
for the Lyons Opera Ballet by Frederic Flamand, a Belgian who has
never been a dancer but has used movement in his multimedia
Conceptual spectacles in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   This latest work, which has no Mediterranean connection but is
an excuse to include the Lyons Opera Ballet in the biennial, is
easier to admire than to like. The inspiration, albeit calculated,
comes from the movement analysis and early photographic experiments
of two pioneers with the same initials and the same life span
(1830-1904).
</P>
<P>
   Eadweard James Muybridge, an American, is best known for his
filmstrip motion studies of horses and nude men or women walking or
performing domestic tasks. Etienne-Jules Marey, a French physician,
used his knowledge of physiology in his photography and in
efficiency studies.
</P>
<P>
   Flamand's collaborators, the American architects Elizabeth
Diller and Ricardo Scofidio, have created a mixed-media
installation with a mobile video camera. The interplay of filmed
images and live dancers is a super-polished version of older
techniques. Part I of the work, ``EMJ1,'' performed by Flamand's
company Charleroi-Plan K, uses Muybridge's ideas as a springboard
to question the veracity of contemporary images. Yes, the camera
can lie.
</P>
<P>
   The camera tricks are fascinating but the choreography too
simple. However, Part II, ``EMJ2,''the Marey section, which will be
performed later independently by the Lyons Opera Ballet, is an
updated machine dance of the 1930s. This time, a giant computerized
figure on a screen orders an assembly line of dancers to imitate
its movements. The choreography was reportedly created by the
dancers. Hence its energetic and descriptive attention to detail. A
high-tech production that questions high-tech has its virtues, even
if it goes on too long.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the experimental Spanish choreographer Vicente Saez
used repetition too often but his essay on Spanish and Indian
mysticism, ``Lilah or God's Game,'' shows his sure touch in
structure and idiom.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed-bag approach was dominant in the work of Israeli
companies recently seen in the United States. Barak Marshall's
pieces were notable mainly for their high energy, and the Batsheva
Dance Company's ``Anaphase,'' by Ohad Naharin, has been the hit of
the festival so far.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition has been represented by La Tannoura, whirling
dervishes from Cairo. The flamenco dancers Antonio Canales and,
especially, Antonio El Pipa, have shown a creative edge. On to
``The Silk Road,'' the theme of the next Lyons Dance Biennial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1809 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27-C     09-24 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: SHALL THE PENITENT SINNER PASS?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``None of us in this room are perfect,'' a grand
juror told Monica Lewinsky on Aug. 20, three days after President
Clinton had finally 'fessed up to what he termed ``inappropriate
contact'' with the young witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference between my age and when I was your age is
now I get up faster,'' the unidentified juror went on to say. ``If
I make a mistake and fall, I get up and brush myself off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr's massive document dump to the Congress makes it
quite evident he was never of a mind to allow Clinton to get up,
brush himself off and serve out the final two years of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many Americans appear ready to give the
brush-off to the relentless independent counsel. When it comes to
Clinton, they may see some troubling ``misdemeanors,'' but no
genuine ``high crimes'' that would justify his ouster. Why?
</P>
<P>
   As some psychobabble artists would have it, Clinton, as the
nation's first Baby Boomer leader, gets off the hook because he
reflects a generation that lacks a clear moral compass. But, if
that's so, why is church attendance among Americans aged 40 to 60
on the rise?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps further revelations will make most folks, including
Boomers, only too glad to see Clinton go. Indeed, by the time
Congress completes a full inquiry, such a scenario could play
itself out.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, more than three out of five voters
agree with Clinton that ``it's time to move on.'' If those polls
stand up, and if the November elections focus on Starr's fierce sex
police, then Clinton could wind up lighting another cigar to mark
his escape from impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, precisely because Clinton remains in such big trouble,
he has, in the minds of some people, become more ``real'' _ and a
more sympathetic figure.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Clinton took the presidency by default, with a
plurality of the popular vote, because George Bush, his Republican
opponent, had run out of ideological gas after becoming political
road kill for Pat Buchanan and Ross Perot. In 1996, a time of peace
and prosperity, Clinton won re-election because most Americans
thought Bob Dole lacked a presidential aura.
</P>
<P>
   But neither those elections nor Clinton's cautious centrist
approach to governance won him the kind of devoted personal
following once enjoyed by such other multi-term presidents as
Franklin Roosevelt, Dwight Eisenhower or Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   It's simply amazing what a president can do to lift people's
attention spans by breaking a couple of biblical commandments. The
mainstream media, which not so long ago saw Clinton as a boring
figure in a boring capital, offers up intense coverage of his
imperiled presidency. On balance, viewers like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr's grand jury wound up its work with Lewinsky, the
forelady offered her ``a bouquet of good wishes that includes luck,
success, happiness and blessings.'' Whereupon, Monica began to sob.
</P>
<P>
   If, as one suspects, Clinton is looking for some good cards to
play, he could do worse than to similarly embrace the role of a
penitent sinner. Then, after a good cry all around, he might just
win yet another free pass.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
