<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1830 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFGHANI-OPTOMETRIST25     09-24 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHANI-OPTOMETRIST25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    West Palm Beach optometrist risked his life to help Afghan
people see
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Dr. Clifford Parker has come back to
West Palm Beach from Afghanistan with two stories to tell. One is a
thrilling adventure. The other is more important, an invaluable
lesson in culture clash that nearly cost him his life.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, 54, gave up his optometry practice here 25 years ago to
help some of the world's poorest people. He could perform what
seemed like miracles against glaucoma or cataracts or myopia, but
he could do nothing to stop the ancient distrust that finally
destroyed much of what he'd helped build.
</P>
<P>
   He is left now to think about a ruined hospital and ruined
lives, about friends taken by police. He knows the end could not
have been delayed much longer: Weeks after he and nearly every
other foreigner fled the capital of Kabul, America launched cruise
missiles at the Afghan headquarters of terrorist Osama bin Laden.
Now, Iran's army is massed along the border, threatening invasion.
</P>
<P>
   And still, Parker wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back and think about whether we should have done this
or that,'' he says. ``We all made mistakes. So much of what happens
is just misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   It is small comfort, but Parker knows Afghanistan and the world
have misunderstood each other for centuries. Poised at the center
of Asia, Afghanistan has endured attacks from the earliest days of
empire.
</P>
<P>
   Its languages and customs bear evidence of Doctor `knew it was
what God wanted me to do' invaders from Darius to Alexander to
Brezhnev. But although it has been often occupied, it has rarely
been conquered. It is the land that made the British army's stiff
upper lip quiver, where The Man Who Would Be King lost his head.
</P>
<P>
   More than one friend thought Parker had lost his senses when he
moved there in 1973. It was not a quick or casual decision.
</P>
<P>
   Raised a Baptist, Parker held no affiliation but kept strong
faith into adulthood. After graduating from an optometry college,
he spent two years treating evacuees from Vietnam at a Tokyo field
hospital and became intrigued by the idea of overseas charitable
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was fear or wisdom, but I came back here
instead and opened a practice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But when an old contact brought news of an ambitious eye-care
project in Afghanistan, Parker felt certain of his course. ``I had
a sense of calling,'' he said. ``I knew it was what God wanted me
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in Kabul during a brief period of tranquility and
went to work for Christian Blind Mission International, an
organization founded by a German pastor in 1909 and now supporting
eye-care programs in more than 100 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital, large and modern, stood in contrast to nearly
everything else. ``Afghanistan was and still is medieval,'' Parker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to develop an eye-care system for a country that
had none. Patients traveled for days, often on foot: nomads,
farmers, shepherds. Parker examined them, treated them, made their
eyeglasses and acted as the hospital's chief administrator while
training local doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
   The International Assistance Mission, an umbrella organization,
brought help from 25 other countries. ``We had Irish nurses, Swiss
nurses,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's future was determined in Moscow. A Soviet-backed
coup in 1979 forced Parker and his colleagues to evacuate. The
Russians invaded later that year. Parker returned to work for the
friend who took over his practice and waited for another overseas
assignment. It was two years before he was dispatched to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the States in 1991 and settled back into his West
Palm Beach townhouse and his old routine. He didn't hesitate when
the call came in July 1997 to help revive the Afghanistan project.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians were gone, but Kabul was far from tranquil. The
country was convulsed by a struggle between the Taliban militia,
drawn from Sunni Moslems of the south, and the Shiite's Northern
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Bombs had destroyed the hospital, but Parker and others
converted a house into a substitute. Parker shared a two-story
house with another hospital worker. The ground floor was surrounded
by sandbags.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bullets fly, you go downstairs,'' Parker said. ``And
when the rockets come in, you go to the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   Attacks became daily annoyances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be outside playing volleyball, and suddenly there'd be
an airstrike,'' Parker said. ``What you worry about is the
anti-aircraft fire. The shrapnel falling on you. So you'd run
inside. Like waiting for a rain cloud to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting supplies depended on which road was open, which faction
controlled the airport, as well as the temper of local officials.
``You might find that the way to get the medicine released is to
suggest that the man's family all come in for free checkups and
eyeglasses,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   The most persuasive gesture was a job. The hospital needed about
70 workers but employed twice that. Parker had no doubt that
patients and trainees were thankful for the hospital, and he began
to feel that the goodwill was spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Talibs strengthened their grip on the country, and on
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   There were new rules and dire warnings. The Talibs suspected
several forms of foreign subversion, from gunrunning to
proselytizing, and warned that all would be punished severely. Male
doctors could no longer examine female patients.
</P>
<P>
   Parker felt the Talibs didn't understand the hospital's goal and
would be less hostile if they did. Although he worked for an openly
Christian organization, Parker said there was no attempt to convert
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But as official inquiries increased, he realized this would not
be cleared up by a friendly chat. ``To the Talibs, the year was
still 1377, and the Crusades happened the day before yesterday,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, he realized that Talib questions about politics and
corruption could have serious?Xrepercussions. What if the jobs
given to officials' relatives were seen as bribes?
</P>
<P>
   Parker began to feel fear for the first time when an Afghan
co-worker whispered, ``Some people are saying bad things about
you.''
</P>
<P>
   He began to think about all the people who didn't get jobs, or
who didn't get paid as much as they wanted. The ones he had to fire
or discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a country where thousands of people still gather for
public hangings,'' Parker said. ``I began to think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a country with no American embassy. Parker's only
guidance came from other foreign agencies' officials, sharing
thoughts in the lounge at the United Nations compound.
</P>
<P>
   One day in late July, the security police took seven of Parker's
Afghan colleagues. Then the religious police searched the offices.
A senior official ordered Parker to move his staff out of Kabul. He
decided it was time to leave the country and found that other
organizations were also packing. A rented van carried him through
the Khyber Pass to Peshawar, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks his seven colleagues were released but can't be sure.
Some fellow missionary workers have already inquired about going
back, but Parker won't join them, at least for now. He doesn't rule
out a return some day, if the politics will ever let him
concentrate on the work he set out to do 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said he doesn't resent the Talibs for doing what they
believe is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, they're honorable people,'' he said. ``Desperate
people do desperate things.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll probably rest a while and then take a new assignment in
Jordan or New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a death wish,'' he said. ``I don't even have a
discomfort wish. But it's a rush to have a blind person see and
know that if you didn't do it, it wouldn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
