<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1836 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AQUIFER-RULES25-COX     09-24 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AQUIFER-RULES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rules on Edwards Aquifer tightened
 &HT;    By Dylan Rivera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state's top environmental agency recently
approved new rules intended to reduce pollution in the Edwards
Aquifer, a source of drinking water for 1.75 million people and
lighting rod for debate over growth and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   The rules extend state regulation to thousands of acres from
Georgetown to San Antonio, and they have drawn fire from builders
who say the rules are too strict and will increase the cost of
housing.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, on the other hand, have criticized the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation Commission for not including all the
land they say needs protection and for not regulating all types of
pollution that they say need to be mitigated.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are intended to protect the Edwards Aquifer, an
underground limestone formation that feeds Barton Springs and
supplies San Antonio with its only source of drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation Commission Chairman Barry McBee said that
development in the Austin area and elsewhere indicates that the new
rules will prevent pollution of the water source.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lessons to be learned from Central Texas and in
other places,`` McBee said. ``A lesson I don't want to have to
learn is that we didn't do the right things at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules extend restrictions on development to the aquifer's
contributing zone, which contains rivers and streams that flow into
the aquifer's recharge zone. Previous rules applied only to the
recharge zone, where water seeps directly into the aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules contain a large range of requirements, which vary
depending on the type of development, whether certain exemptions
apply and other factors. Among the more controversial elements are
restrictions on how much sediment can be caused by construction and
requirements that subdivisions build and maintain retention ponds
to control runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations are not as stringent as Austin's Save Our
Springs ordinance, but cover a vastly broader area.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Capitol Area Builders Association, which lobbied
against the rules, estimates that compliance will increase housing
costs from $800 to $3,000 per house.
</P>
<P>
   McBee conceded that the commission does not have a study that
shows specific evidence of water-quality degradation as a result of
development in the contributing zone.
</P>
<P>
   However, research on development in Central Texas and evidence
of degradation in other watersheds indicate that some new
regulations are in order, McBee said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Mike Krusee, who represents most of Williamson
County, said the rules will increase the cost of housing and dense
development, for uncertain environmental benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to have any impact on someone building a
mansion on five acres, but in an apartment complex where you have
middle-class working people _ that's where it's going to have the
largest impact,'' Krusee said. ``Anderson Mill-type subdivisions
are now going to be more expensive to build and buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules take effect June 1. Krusee said he wants to question
environmental officials during the spring legislative session about
the financial impact of the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the commission added rules encouraging
developers to limit impervious cover _ the impermeable surfaces,
such as driveways and rooftops, that cover much of a building site.
That language adopts an approach long advocated by Austin's Save
Our Springs Alliance. The rules say that developments that restrict
such cover to 20 percent can avoid other requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who would advocate that we take an
S.O.S.-like approach and just lay down a flat
impervious-cover-oriented rule,'' McBee said. ``We are not for
that, but we did concede here that as one of many options that may
be made available for development that an impervious-cover
calculation does have its place.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't satisfy the Save Our Springs Alliance, however.
Grant Godfrey, staff attorney for the alliance, said the state
should set stricter limits on nitrogen or phosphorous, which can
diminish water quality.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions will cover all areas inside or outside city
limits, but do not apply to the entire contributing zone _ a point
that irks both developers and environmentalists. The newly
regulated territory extends from the recharge zone to the county
line in eight counties, but excludes nine counties, including Bell
and Lampasas in the Austin area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're regulating such a marginally larger area than they
were before, it is such a tiny step,'' Godfrey said. ``What this
step means is that they want to be able to say to the public that
they've been listening, but without actually doing anything that
the public has been asking them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McBee said the commission excluded those counties because they
tend to contain less-sensitive parts of the contributing zone and
have had less dense development than areas closer to Austin. Those
counties also don't have the political support among local elected
officials for new regulations, McBee said.
</P>
<P>
   That decision has drawn heat from environmentalists who want the
entire contributing zone regulated. And then there are opponents
like Krusee who say that excluding other counties treats Williamson
County unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in Williamson County have a different view than
Krusee, said George Gregory, president of the Ethel Barnes
Association, a group of rural homeowners who depend on the aquifer
for well water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that it wasn't representing the people's best interest
_ (Krusee's) concern was more of a tax base concern, bringing more
revenues in,'' Gregory said. ``And that rubs me wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
