A1837 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PHILLIES-PORTUGAL     09-24 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILLIES-PORTUGAL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Like zoo elephants, Portugal doesn't forget
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ When Mark Portugal was in the employ of the
Cincinnati Reds in 1996, he wasn't one of CEO Marge Schott's
favorite people.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal was far down the list behind St. Bernards and zoo
elephants.
</P>
<P>
   In the magazine article that helped get her suspended for two
years, she was quoted as saying about Portugal, ``Look at him, we
pay him $3 million and he isn't worth a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal smiled slyly when he heard about the quote, muttered a
few expletives and said, ``Tell her it's $4 million. . .she doesn't
even know how much she pays her players.''
</P>
<P>
   The soon-to-be 36-year-old right-hander, signed to a $2.2
million contract for this season by the Philadelphia Phillies, held
the Reds to one hit over five innings and ended up the winner in
recent a 4-2 Philadelphia victory in front of 13,376 in Cinergy
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who spent considerable time on the disabled list this
year, won his 10th game, giving up two runs and four hits with four
walks and six strikeouts over 7 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a coincidence that when Schott moved from her private
glassed-in box to her first-row blue seats next to the Reds dugout
that Portugal weakened?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was no different from any time I pitch against the
Reds. It's no secret. I'm going to be 37 next month. I've been hurt
and I'm getting old. It's also no secret that I can still pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds avoided a shutout by scoring twice in the seventh
inning on a pair of run-scoring hits by Dmitri Young and Aaron
Boone, but even then Portugal was put in trouble when third baseman
Scott Rolen made an error on Sean Casey's hard ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portugal knows how to pitch,'' Reds manager Jack McKeon said.
``He changes speed a lot and that gives us trouble. If you wait on
him and his change-up, you can get him. If you don't be patient,
he'll get you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati starter Steve Parris retired the first three
Phillies, but ran into second-inning problems that put him 3-0
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Rolen led with a single and Bobby Abreu walked. Kevin Sefcik
pushed two across with a triple to right field and Sefcik scored on
Desi Relaford's fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal helped himself in the fourth by leading the inning with
a double (he has a nine-game hitting streak) and later scored on
Doug Glanville's sacrifice fly to make it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they lost, Pittsburgh also lost, assuring the Reds
they won't finish last in the National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought about finishing last,'' McKeon said. ``We had
people tell us we'd lose 100 games. We're in fourth place (out of
six) and we hope to stay there if we can get some pitching and
defense in our last three games against the Pirates.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
