<HEADER>
A1838 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS25-COX     09-24 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photographer captures beauty of the manatee
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chronicle books has published Manatee ($14.95), a collection of
lovely photographs by Rei Ohara. The underwater photographs of the
sea cow have that melancholy beauty we all know and love, but Ohara
has some interesting shots where his lens is half-submerged in the
water, showing the manatees underwater on the bottom half of the
picture, and Florida cypress and pine trees on the top half. The
effect is similar to those kitschy prints of marine life advertised
in every Key West shop window, but more pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   The book also puts in an entirely appropriate plea for manatee
preservation.
</P>
<P>
   On a different note, Norton is re-publishing the novels of
Iceberg Slim in its Old School Books series. Slim (real name Robert
Beck) was a pimp with a vaguely literary bent, and his novels about
The Life, including Trick Baby, achieved great popularity in the
'60s and '70s as a corollary to blaxploitation movies.
</P>
<P>
   Mama Black Widow ($13), originally published in 1969, is the
story of Otis Tilson, a black drag queen living on the fringes,
slowly descending into madness and death.
</P>
<P>
   The works of the late Mr. Beck (he died in 1992) are lurid,
melodramatic, disreputable and the absolute antithesis of the
literary books about the black experience first established by the
Harlem Renaissance and Zora Neale Hurston. He's also the
best-selling black novelist of all time. Make of that what you
will.
</P>
<P>
   SOME THINGS TO LOOK FORWARD TO . . . I mentioned last week that
it was high time someone published the screenplay of Sunset
Boulevard. I'm still waiting, but Faber &AMP; Faber is bringing out a
couple of scripts nearly as good: The Apartment and Sweet Smell of
Success. The former is the classic Billy Wilder comedy; the latter
is the Burt Lancaster/Tony Curtis movie based on Walter Winchell
and written by Clifford Odets and Ernest Lehman. It's just about
the most savage thing ever written for Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The scripts will be published separately and be available at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   LIVES OF THE SAINTS . . . Penguin will be offering a new series
of short biographies starting this January. The first batch of what
is called Penguin Lives, out in January, offers Larry McMurtry on
Crazy Horse and Edmund White on Proust. Other pairings are Carol
Shields on Jane Austen and Peter Gay on Mozart. The books will be
small-format hardcover, top out at around 250 pages and sell for
$19.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``Instead of having faith, which is a
virtue, and therefore nourishes the soul and gives it a healthy
life, people merely have a lot of opinions, which excite the soul
but don't give it anything to feed it, just wear it out until it
falls over from exhaustion.'' _ Thomas Merton
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
