<HEADER>
A1840 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PORT-PALMBEACH25-COX     09-24 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORT-PALMBEACH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Port of Palm Beach remains open through storm
 &HT;    By Michael Utley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ The Port of Palm Beach will be the only
major port in South Florida to remain open as federal authorities
shut down the Port of Miami and Port Everglades as a Hurricane
Georges-related precaution.
</P>
<P>
   The closings aren't expected to create greater shipping traffic
at the Port of Palm Beach: Its channels are too shallow to handle
many of the giant cruise and cargo vessels that frequent the larger
ports in Miami and Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   Shutting down the two ports is necessary because large ships
that are tied to a dock are more likely to sink in a major storm,
said Petty Officer Scott Carr, in the Coast Guard's Miami office.
Only a few sunken vessels would paralyze the ports, he said, making
it impossible to ship emergency supplies to storm victims.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard ordered the Port of Miami and Port Everglades to
close at 6 p.m. on September 23. The facilities are expected to
remain closed to large ships until the hurricane threat subsides.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the displaced ships will anchor offshore or head to
larger ports in Cape Canaveral, Jacksonville or Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these ships will fare better at sea than they would in
port,'' Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Port of Palm Beach in Riviera Beach, shippers were
cleaning up their yards and storing equipment, just in case Georges
heads this way. But there weren't many other disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're open for business as usual,'' said Martin Metz, deputy
port director for operations. ``When you have a hurricane like
this, the ships just divert around it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only tangible effect so far on the Port of Palm Beach, said
Metz, is that a weekly oil shipment from Houston has been delayed
until the storm path becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Shipping &AMP; Construction Inc., the port's largest tenant
and the biggest volume shipper to the Caribbean, said Wednesday
that its operations have been disrupted but that all deliveries are
going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ships had to be rerouted to avoid the storm,'' said
Richard Calcote, Tropical's vice president for finance. ``That set
them back anywhere from a few hours to a day and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Tropical's clients are waiting to hear about conditions
in the Caribbean before they resume shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got 150 T-shirts waiting to go to St. Thomas, and I don't
even know if the customer exists anymore,'' said Neal Jain, vice
president of Riviera Beach-based Simply Tropics Inc., which sells
custom-designed shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise operators at the port have so far been unaffected by the
storm. The Palm Beach Princess is undergoing maintenance in South
Carolina until Oct. 2, and the Contessa is following its normal
schedule of two coastal cruises a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may get some strong winds, but I don't think it'll be that
bad,'' said William Nurthen, chief executive of Contessa
International Cruise Line. ``We will continue to evaluate the
situation, and if it looks like it will be an uncomfortable ride,
we will begin to cancel cruises.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STORM-DINING25-COX     09-24 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-DINING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents eat and wait for Hurricane Georges
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If the storm rolls in, how will John
Alfeo tell?
</P>
<P>
   His Hurricane Grill restaurant on 25th Street has the decor of a
full-force gale. The ceiling is hung with lanterns, stools, oars
and a Cabbage Patch doll in flight. A palm tree is frozen in
mid-bend. The shutters are askew.
</P>
<P>
   There's a storm tracking chart by the cash register, but it
shows Andrew's path.
</P>
<P>
   Georges, schmorges. ``It's not coming here!'' Alfeo says.
``What's the big deal?''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges is nothing but a special on the menu. Spinach
salad with grilled chicken, bacon and balsamic vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Alfeo's only fear is the massive lines at Costco, where he goes
to restock.
</P>
<P>
   The floor of the Hurricane Grill is a swirl of green paint, and
on the walls are murals from 1947, when the place was a bar and an
artist named Phil Brinkman swapped work for free beer.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkman painted himself in one of them _ a man sitting at a
bar, holding his hat to his head as a house and boat blow by. The
mural's bartender, hair blown back, consults a barometer and rubs
his chin. A woman, smiling, fills a glass at the tap.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hurricane-proof building,'' Alfeo says. ``I'm
willing to serve food until the end!''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. The place is in a flood zone.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane supply check on aisle three!
</P>
<P>
   Water, yes. Batteries, yes. Eight-ounce box of milk chocolate
truffles, of course. (It was the next-to-last box.)
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Burtoff doesn't know if she'll pass the storm in her
Palm Beach home or in a hotel, but at least she'll have the
truffles and a box of Pepperidge Farm Milano cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time of stress, always have chocolate,'' she says at the
Publix checkout.
</P>
<P>
   As of 11 a.m. Wednesday, the store's supply of Whitman's
Samplers is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Burke of Palm Beach strolls the candy aisle, picking
out two bags of tiny Snickers and one of Nestle Crunch. She adds
them to the box of Fig Newtons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have to get the ice cream, too!'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Two boxes of milk chocolate Dove Bars. ``No vegetables for me!''
</P>
<P>
   Sprite. ``I'm not a healthy person.''
</P>
<P>
   Two containers of Haagen-Dazs _ vanilla and cherry vanilla.
Done!
</P>
<P>
   She's new to hurricanes. She summers in Connecticut. ``I just
got home too soon this time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Other hot hurricane sellers? Paula Stankunas leans across her
counter, her hands cupped to her mouth. ``BOOZE!''
</P>
<P>
   She's the manager of ABC Liquors on Dixie Highway. ``I guess
they figure if you're stuck at home, you might as well drink.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cassandra, the manager at the Boynton Beach Publix, reports
the same. He can tell how Georges is going by watching the flow of
customers after storm warning updates. ``The next big one is at 11
a.m.'' he says. ``Then 5 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   (FYI: The ingredients for a ``hurricane'' are iffy. ``It's
basically a rum drink, rum and fruit juices,'' says Gloria Gould,
bartender at The Hawaiian restaurant in South Palm Beach. ``I would
use light rum and dark rum, and pineapple juice, orange juice and
grenadine.'')
</P>
<P>
   Tom Travaglini understands the storm. But he doesn't understand
what the storm is doing to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Paula is expecting their baby boy, Adam, in four weeks, but her
doctor told her to get ready now. The low barometric pressure
during the storm can induce labor, some say.
</P>
<P>
   The maternity ward at St. Mary's Medical Center is preparing for
at least two dozen women. During Andrew, 28 showed up with their
own food and blankets. They'll get the extra beds, says Valerie
Christian, assistant patient care manager. ``I'll probably sleep in
my office.''
</P>
<P>
   Most doctors just want to make sure their patients are near. But
it does seem that the low pressure causes water breaks, Christian
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were kidding me,'' Travaglini says.
</P>
<P>
   He is the assistant bakery manager at the Palm Beach Publix.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, he says, apple turnover sales are brisk.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Janis Fontaine contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
