<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer heat still upon us
 &HT;    By Mike Kelley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ September 23, said the calendar, was the first
day of fall. The high temperature in Austin was 94. The only leaves
turning were those in classrooms and public libraries where air
conditioning insures that the first frost of the season comes in
May and lasts for months.
</P>
<P>
   The overflowing cornucopias of artists' imagination, which mark
the fall and harvest time, are today reduced to plastic pumpkins
painted to look like jack o'lanterns, advertising the still-distant
Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   A maple tree, surely, would be eager for the season's change and
the chance to dress in its autumnal glory. But at Lost Maples State
Natural Area, northwest of San Antonio, the park ranger says,
``It's way too early. It's way too hot yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And up in Winnsboro, in northeastern Texas, where Autumn Trails
tours are the big attraction, the lady at the Chamber of Commerce
says the sweet gums and oaks are ``still pretty green. Maybe in
another month.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the sweet smell of smoke from the cotton gins, which used
to signal the start of school and the long-awaited beginning of
football, no longer drifts over Texas in September. The smoke came
from burning hulls _ ``burrs'' _ which farmers today plow back into
the fields for compost.
</P>
<P>
   So, for anyone wondering, ``Where is fall?'' the answer is that
Texans are a judicious lot, don't like to be rushed into something,
and will have fall when it's time for it. For now, gone are the
100-degree days of summer, and the harshness of the sun. These days
are warm and breezy and soft. Soon enough, when snow has already
begun to fall in other climes, we will have our clear, winey days
and deliciously cool nights of October.
</P>
<P>
   And if, for some reason _ El Nin(tilde)o, La Nin(tilde)a _ the
meteorological norms are out of kilter, consider that the first day
of this year's second season came with a high temperature of 64
degrees. So we will have fall, even it takes until spring to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
