<SLUG> BC-BBN-BASEBALL-CARDS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire/Sosa fever over?
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan O'Kane isn't a collector or a memorabilia dealer, just a
Dayton salesman who happened to have two Mark McGwire 1985 rookie
cards lying around.
</P>
<P>
   Told such items were selling for $350 in some cases, he placed a
newspaper advertisement offering each for the more reasonable price
of $115, ``the true book value,'' he says. After six days, he still
has one left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to be the hottest thing ever and I've had two
calls in six days,'' O'Kane said, amused but frustrated. ``Maybe
nobody looks at the classifieds anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, despite reports to the contrary, the mania surrounding
all things McGwire and Sosa has reached its zenith. After Sammy
Sosa's two recent home runs in Milwaukee, he and McGwire are tied
at 65 with four days left to crown a new single-season king.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get caught up in the excitement, but if someone
pays $200 for a card, they should be aware that it'll be down in
value by about $50 in a year,'' cautioned Jason Young, manager of
Maverick's Baseball Card Center in Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   Maverick's had six McGwire and four Sosa rookie cards for sale
as of Wednesday afternoon. Young said McGwire's is selling for
between $140 and $200, depending on the card's condition, while
Sosa's goes for about $80.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for bargains? Young suggested perusing the Internet.
Failing that, there's always the classified section of any major
newspaper. One ad, nestled among those for Beanie Babies in the
Akron Beacon-Journal, offered a collection of McGwire cards,
including the Topps rookie release, for $750.
</P>
<P>
   For a week after McGwire eclipsed Roger Maris' record of 61 home
runs, Maverick's fielded about 200 calls a day from people looking
to buy or sell. ``Now it's down to about five or 10,'' Young said.
``When it's over, the one who ends up with the record is going to
sell a lot better than the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, let the buyer _ and the seller _ beware.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think the value is going to skyrocket,'' O'Kane said,
still holding one card. ``But everything has its limit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
