<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell to offer custom access to Internet
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the latest sign of the Internet's growing
influence over the personal computer industry, Dell Computer Corp.
said recently it is joining Excite Inc. and AT&AMP;T Corp. to offer
customers simple and highly personalized access to the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which uses AT&AMP;T Worldnet Service as the access to
the Web and Excite as the initial site, or portal, for customers,
is perhaps the most detailed linkage of technologies in the rapidly
changing PC industry, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very much a convergence announcement between hardware,
telecommunications and media,'' said Henry Blodget, a stock analyst
at CIBC Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Accessing the Internet is cited as a primary reason for nearly
three-fourths of computer purchases, industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the program, called ConnectDirect, Dell was slower
than Compaq Computer Corp. and Gateway to create Internet linkages,
but Dell officials say their program goes farther than competitors'
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bell, senior vice president of Dell's home and small
business group, said Dell's build-to-order system allows the
company to customize the system before it is shipped to the
customer. That means, for example, consumers will see news,
weather, product reviews, their horoscope and other information
tailored to their requests when they first log on to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, AT&AMP;T Worldnet's software will be installed before
shipment, sparing customers of that task and speeding their arrival
on the Internet, Bell said. Other national Internet service
providers, such as GTE, will be available to customers by next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, which has been the most loyal customer of Microsoft Corp.
among the major PC makers, also for the first time offered a free
Web browser other than Microsoft's Internet Explorer. The package
includes a simplified browser created for Dell that performs basic
Web browsing and e-mail but has fewer features than Internet
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think most customers want IE, but we know from talking to
customers, (some) want less options,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that offering a simplified browser does not signal a
change in Dell's strategy of focusing on more sophisticated
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a recognition that we have a half-million customers and
they have a range of needs,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer sales account for about 10 percent of Dell's revenue
and the company is targeting that sector more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to broaden our base, we need to grow in all
sectors,'' said Robert Langer, director of Dell's online program in
the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to revenue from increased business, each participant
in the agreement expects to benefit from the joint branding that
ConnectDirect offers when their names appear together on the
customers' screens, executives of the companies and analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   While terms of the agreements were not disclosed, Dell likely
will receive payments from the other companies for every Dell
customer that follows the ConnectDirect script, industry sources
said. They also said Dell may receive payments based on advertising
that Excite is able to sell on the customized pages.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to adding other Internet service providers to the
package, Dell will team with SBC Communications Inc. to push the
use of technology that allows existing phone lines to offer
data-moving speeds 30-50 times faster than a 56-kilobyte modem.
</P>
<P>
   Known as asymmetrical digital subscriber line, or ADSL, the
technology is not expected to be offered widely to SBC customers in
Texas until sometime next year, a spokesman for SBC Communications
said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, where the SBC-owned Pacific Bell already offers
ADSL, the service costs about $89 a month in addition to a one-time
installation fee of $324, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
