<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSU-WOODARD25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paralyzed father helps son push through injury
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like at every high or low point in his life, Lonnie Woodard
turned to his father the day his right leg was twisted into an
L-shape on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard's father, Lonnie Sr., remembers the day well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me while he was sitting on the trainer's table,''
Lonnie Woodard Sr. said of his son, a Dunbar High School graduate
and reserve defensive lineman for No. 1 ranked Ohio State. ``The
first thing he told me was, 'Daddy, they're cutting these expensive
shoes off me _ and these expensive shorts.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'Lonnie, look: Like me, they aren't thinking about the
expensive equipment. They're thinking about you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Once the graveness of the injury _ three torn knee ligaments and
a dislocated knee cap _ struck the younger Woodard, his spirits
sank: ``I told him, 'You can come back from that,' '' his father
said. ``And he said, 'I'll never play again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Woodard, a 6-2, 263-pound OSU sophomore, smiles at his father's
recollection of that devastating day 14 months ago. It's much
easier to smile now that the injury which kept him sidelined all of
last season is nearly healed and he's back on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   He only wishes his father's injuries could heal as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Sr. is severely paralyzed. He spends most of his time in
a hospital bed in the middle of the Woodard's dining room in their
West Dayton home. The only time he gets up or out, his family says,
is when an ambulance arrives to take him to the doctor or young
Lonnie comes home and lifts him from the bed and carries him to a
living room chair or onto the front porch for some fresh air .
</P>
<P>
   It's been this way for much of the last four years, Woodard's
wife, Betty said, since complications after a pinched nerve surgery
left him paralyzed. Insurance initially paid for homecare and
therapy but no more, she said. Now Betty must wake at 3 a.m. each
weekday morning to feed and medicate her husband and prepare his
lunch before she heads to her job in the shipping department at the
Veterans Administration Medical Center a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Until she returns home at 3 p.m., her husband often remains
alone. A television screen with a view of the Woodard's front porch
enables him to monitor the door and a larger-screen TV keeps him
entertained with music and shows. A telephone, tissues, various
medications and a list of important phone numbers sit within his
reach on a tray near his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Although remarkably pleasant and high-spirited, the senior
Woodard, a former Dunbar football player and Meadowdale Pee-Wee
coach, gets frustrated with his immobility, his family says. When
his son's 1984 white Corvette broke down during a visit home
earlier this week, for example, Woodard could only dispense advice
over the telephone rather than run out to help. And traveling to
Columbus to attend Ohio State games or just to have dinner with his
son is out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems content to watch (the games) on TV, but I know he'd
be thrilled to go see little Lonnie play,'' his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was Woodard Sr. who encouraged his son to follow
his dream and attend Ohio State. An All-City offensive lineman in
high school, the younger Woodard received scholarship offers from
some Mid-American Conference schools and several service academies,
he said. Schools such as Ohio State and Michigan showed interest
but told him he was too small to play on the offensive line. If
he'd walk on as a defensive lineman, they said, he'd be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   As a walk on for the Buckeyes, Woodard does not receive athletic
scholarship money and spends each practice on the ``scout team,''
football's equivalent of the punching bag. It is the scout team's
job to simulate as best as possible the opponent's game plan for
the starters to face in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard, who got a chance to play in OSU's 49-0 blowout against
Toledo Sept. 12, doesn't mind the job _ for now. His goal, of
course, is to earn a spot on the Buckeyes' starting roster. His
coaches say that's within his reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed at how he's come back,'' OSU defensive line coach
Jim Heacock said. ``Usually when you come back from an injury like
that, you're a little bit hesitant. But from the day we started
fall camp, he gave no indication of any fear or any hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real high on Lonnie. As a person, his effort and attitude,
they're as good as it gets. I wouldn't count him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodard said he would not have made it back without the support
of Heacock, OSU teammates Joe Montgomery and Jerry Redmond, both of
whom have suffered similar knee injuries, and of course, his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was just my total inspiration,'' he said. ``All the
things he's been through? Compared to him, I've been through
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodard's own rehabilitation as well as his father's condition
have inspired him to consider pursuing a degree in physical
therapy. But Woodard also hasn't lost sight of trying to make good
on a prediction his father made a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father told me in high school that Ohio State would win a
national championship in my career,'' he said. ``He might be
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
