<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-TEXAS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intel to open Austin chip center
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Now Austin really has Intel inside.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp., the world's largest and richest semiconductor
company, is opening a site in Austin where engineers will design
microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has has reported slower sales this year, Intel is
still the dominant maker of the chips that power personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Texas Development Center, the Austin operation will
be one of seven such Intel sites throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Intel declined to say how many employees it would have at the
center. Design centers usually involve teams of engineers that can
be very small or range up to hundreds of people. Somerset, the
best-known chip design center in Austin, had peak employment of
more than 300 designers and other workers. Intel recruited Mark
McDermott to head the operation. McDermott was in charge of the
Somerset project, where IBM Corp. and Motorola Inc. design PowerPC
chips for Apple Computer Corp.'s Macintosh computers. Motorola took
sole control of Somerset earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott's first job will be to determine what the center will
work on and to hire engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's announcement comes as Motorola is expected to cut jobs
in its continuing efforts to regain profitability in its chip
business.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said one of the primary reasons for creating the Austin
center was the availability of McDermott, a well-regarded design
project leader. Others, however, noted that this appears to be a
good time for picking up Motorola engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Austin is a very ripe source for any company that
wants to aggressively recruit to staff a complex logic design
center (for processors and other chips),'' said Kim Butler, a
high-tech job recruiter. ``It's no secret that Motorola is looking
at further cutbacks and it looks like they are going to be pretty
deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Zieber, president of Pathfinder Research, a San Jose,
Calif. semiconductor market research firm, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chip designers are a scarce resource when you are looking for
the really good guys and Austin has a lot of (good design)
people,'' he said, ``And it's not a bad area to live. It's a
natural place for Intel to expand. It's also a natural place to
raid Motorola.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, AMD Inc. and Cirrus Logic Inc. have substantial design
operations in Austin. In addition, more than a dozen satellite
design centers and start-up companies are designing chips in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's Austin operations are contributing to the design of the K7
chip, its next-generation competitor to Intel's chips. Even though
Austin may be one of the world's leading chip design centers
outside California's Silicon Valley, Intel's arrival gives it a
boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel is the biggest semiconductor company in the world,''
said Will Strauss, analyst for Forward Concepts technology market
research in Tempe, Ariz. ``This lends more prestige to Austin. You
could call it the Intel seal of approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides access to Austin's talent, the center brings it closer
to key customers Dell Computer Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp.,
Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I've expected for a long time,'' Butler said
of Intel's move. ``I'm surprised it took them this long.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel has had its own problems this year. It has said it would
cut 3,000 jobs this year. On Wednesday, it cut 675 of its 1,600
workers at its plant in Hudson, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares closed up $3.50 to $87.06 1/4 on Wednesday.
McDermott will report to Albert Yu, Intel's senior vice president
for the microprocessor products group.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a super technology manager,'' Yu said of McDermott this
week. ``I am excited to have him on board.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a fun place to work,'' said McDermott, an
11-year veteran of Motorola, who also worked briefly for Cyrix
Corp. in the early 1990s. ``It will be a great place to work. We
will do state-of-the-art, leading-edge work. And no BS.''
</P>
<P>
   Yu said it may take a few months to determine the right role for
the Austin center. Intel operates processor design centers at its
Santa Clara, Calif., headquarters, in Portland, Ore., Folsom,
Calif., Chandler, Ariz., DuPont, Wash., and Haifa, Israel.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Intel's first presence in Austin. When it acquired
Digital Equipment Corp.'s semiconductor business this year, Intel
also acquired Digital's small Austin design center for StrongARM
microcontrollers.
</P>
<P>
   Both StrongArm and the new design center will be at 5000 Plaza
on the Lake on Loop 360.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
