<SLUG> BC-STORM-INSURANCE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insurance agencies stop new coverage for storm
 &HT;    By John Murawski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most major insurance carriers, State Farm Fire and Casualty
stops writing new home and auto policies when a hurricane watch has
been posted.
</P>
<P>
   Some Floridians didn't find out until it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few people calling who haven't paid their bills,
and their policies lapsed a long time ago,'' said agent Doug Bohner
of State Farm, the state's largest home insurer with more than a
million homes covered.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm wasn't alone. If you live in an area where you think
you might need insurance within a few days, you probably can't get
it. Most companies stopped writing new policies in South Florida by
Sept. 23. And one company _ Nationwide Mutual, the state's
third-largest home insurer with about 240,000 policies _ suspended
writing new policies for the entire state on Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   But as the new-policies arm of the insurance industry ground to
a halt, emergency preparations went into full-throttle. Armies of
claims adjustors are getting ready to swoop into the state to
survey the damage left by Hurricane Georges. Major insurers set up
``induction units'' to handle the arrival of the adjustors and to
deploy mobile claims-processing centers in areas hammered by
Georges.
</P>
<P>
   The desperate few calling Bohner at his Boca Raton office were
slated to be transferred to the Florida Residential Property and
Casualty Joint Underwriting Association and the Florida Windstorm
Underwriting Association, the state-created insurers of last resort
commonly known as the JUA and the windstorm pool.
</P>
<P>
   But they were out of luck there, too. Those insurers stopped
writing new policies at 1 a.m. Wednesday, when Hurricane Georges
crossed into an area known as ``the box.'' When a tropical storm or
hurricane blows into the box _ stretching from the Gulf of Mexico
to the Dominican Republic and from North Carolina to Honduras _ the
JUA won't issue new policies.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate Floridian, the second-largest home insurer with about
625,000 policies, also freezes writing new policies during
hurricane watches and warnings, though most Florida homeowners
won't be affected. That's because neither Allstate nor State Farm
have written new policies in Palm Beach, Broward and Miami-Dade
counties for years.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies, though, started amassing claims adjustors
Wednesday who'll assess the damage wrought by Georges once the
hurricane passes. State Farm's induction center near the Orlando
airport will handle adjustors from the company's 2,000-member
National Catastrophic Team.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate has put 1,000 adjustors on standby nationwide and has
sent an advance team of 100 to Miami and St. Petersburg to begin
making preparations. Allstate also is moving three mobile claims
centers to Orlando. From there, they'll be sent to areas damaged by
Georges.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of power failures, State Farm agents also are
making backup copies of their computer files and printing out all
policies on paper. Bohner's office started printing out 7,000
policies on Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
