<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's Delray Beach Tennis Center named to host Davis Cup
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke and Chuck McGinness
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Haul out the flags and practice the U-S-A
chants.
</P>
<P>
   The Delray Beach Tennis Center was named to host the loudest and
most emotional event in professional tennis: the Davis Cup final.
It's the only time tennis fans can let their passion override their
manners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not go, (John) McEnroe! It's go USA!'' said tennis center
manager Brahm Dubin. ``The chill you get ... it's unbelievable.
It's like the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, the United States must beat Italy, and Sweden must
defeat Spain in this weekend's semifinals for the United States to
host the year's biggest international tennis event. Top Americans
aren't playing this round, but the U.S. remains favored. Spain and
Sweden are fairly evenly matched.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day final round will begin Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can say this is the Super Bowl of tennis,'' said
Pam Gerig, executive director of the Palm Beach County Sports
Commission, which helped Delray Beach outbid New Orleans and Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Delray Beach was chosen _ despite submitting a bid just three
weeks ago _ because of its world-class tennis facilities, the
county's commitment and the business community's support, said Russ
Cline, Davis Cup producer for the United States Tennis Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bid and this enthusiasm that we felt from down there ...
There's no place we can be that would be better than Palm Beach
County and the Delray Beach Tennis Center,'' Cline said.
</P>
<P>
   USTA officials predict the final to bring $13 million to $15
million into the county, Gerig said. The county's Convention and
Visitor's Bureau has agreed to cover half of the $200,000 cost of
hosting it. City and county officials are looking for sponsors to
pay the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a fair amount of heat the last few years, and
this is the moment we want to enjoy for a few minutes,'' Dubin
said. ``I usually don't get overwhelmed, and I'm just
overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets will not go on sale until about a week after this
weekend's results are known. Tickets will cost from $90 to $450 for
three-day passes. Single-day tickets will not be sold unless the
three-day passes to the 8,200-seat stadium do not sell out.
</P>
<P>
   Landing the Davis Cup final is the biggest thing to happen at
the tennis center, which opened five years ago to host the
now-defunct Virginia Slims of Florida tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's telling me we created a facility which has a reputation
that's noteworthy to tennis professionals, the tennis public and
tennis promoters,'' Delray Beach Mayor Jay Alperin said.
</P>
<P>
   The $5.8 million venue has lost money the past three years: In
1995, it lost $128,828; in 1996, $56,476; and last year, $127,447.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders said an event such as the Davis Cup finals will
help the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're going to have people here buying knick-knacks
and things in our stores, eating in our restaurants. You're going
to have people staying in hotels throughout Palm Beach County,''
said Bill Wood, president of the Delray Beach Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, three days of international television coverage on
ESPN and other channels could help the city attract other
tournaments and events to the center, local leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
