<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1851 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIVERSITY-DRINKING25     09-24 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-DRINKING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alcohol deaths spur anti-drinking effort
 &HT;    By Christian Davenport and Rebeca Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Chad Connally remembers what partying at
Southwestern University used to be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``My freshman year you could walk into a place and there would
be beer and alcohol everywhere,'' said Connally, a senior who is
the student body president. ``We got hammered.''
</P>
<P>
   By its own admission, the administration looked the other way
when it came to much of the drinking on campus. Without fear of
getting caught, students partied to relieve stress, get drunk, and
have the kind of mindless fun that sharing a bunch of beers with
100 of your closest friends can provide after a week of pounding
the books.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at one of the state's oldest universities, that's all
changing.
</P>
<P>
   Like colleges and universities across the country that fear the
horrific tales of fraternity hazing and stories of students
literally drinking themselves to death, the administration at
Southwestern University is cracking down on drinking this year as
no time before.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us want to believe there is this magic glass bubble
over us,'' Mike Leese, Southwestern's vice president for
Residential Services, told a student meeting Tuesday. ``We did look
the other way for too long, and we can't do that any more.''
</P>
<P>
   A grand illustration of the administration's new dedication to
enforcing the law and its own policy came last week, when the Kappa
Sigma fraternity held its weekly ``Study Break'' party, a
university tradition that fraternity members said goes back 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   But this time there were several uninvited guests: eight law
enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented raid, police arrested one student, charging
him with providing alcohol to minors, cited 49 minors with
possession of alcohol, and set off a wave of student fury that
climaxed in a student-organized meeting Tuesday in the student
commons.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the campus' 1,200 students showed up to air their
concerns with what they thought was an illegal and unnecessary
crackdown at a small, cozy private college known more for its
staunch church spires and vaunted academic reputation than for its
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much does the university care about its student body when
you're organizing sting operations?'' asked one student to
resounding applause.
</P>
<P>
   But university officials say that's precisely why they're
enforcing the drinking rules more than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let one of you go into an alcoholic coma and
die,'' said Deborah Brown, Southwestern's chief of police, at the
student meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a student at Louisiana State University died after a
night of drinking when he pledged Sigma Alpha Epsilon. His
blood-alcohol level was 0.588, nearly six times the legal limit for
intoxication. And last September a Massachusetts Institute of
Technology freshman died after a night of heavy drinking at Phi
Gamma Delta, an MIT fraternity which has since been shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a wake-up call for people in student affairs,'' said
Sherri Babcock, Southwestern's dean of students. She said that last
year for the first time she can remember, two of her students were
hospitalized for alcohol poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Death from drinking, while so harrowing and tragic that it grabs
the media's attention, is also relatively rare. What also worry
Babcock and other academics are the more common and less
talked-about problems: Drunken trysts that lead to rape or the
spread of sexually transmitted diseases, driving while intoxicated,
and lapses in judgment that spur normally responsible students to
jump off cliffs or ride on the top of speeding cars.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring a Southwestern student who had been drinking jumped
off a cliff into a swimming hole and drowned. In 1995, a University
of Texas student drowned in the Colorado River after a night of
drinking games.
</P>
<P>
   The mounting student death toll has prompted Southwestern and
other universities across the country to re-evaluate their alcohol
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a trend nationwide,'' said Nancy Schulte, the
coordinator of drug education services at George Mason University
in Virginia. Referring to the John Belushi movie, she said, ``We're
trying to bury 'Animal House,' and that is going to take some
time.''
</P>
<P>
   That state's attorney general, Mark Earley, sent out brochures
to all freshmen at public schools detailing the dangers of alcohol
abuse, including the deaths last year of five Virginia students.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Southwest Texas State University in San Marcos, a
campus with more than 21,000 students, was known as a party school.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here (24 years ago), that was the kind of
tradition and reputation the school had,'' said John Garrison,
assistant vice-president and dean of students. ``But that's not the
reputation we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, SWT president Jerome Supple sent a letter to all
faculty and staff outlining plans for a sweeping alcohol education
program to change that image. Beginning this fall, all student
leaders must attend workshops on alcohol education and pass that
information on to members. Officials also are distributing an
interactive CD-ROM called Alcohol 101 that teaches students how to
recognize their drinking limits and deal with peer pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In the classroom, faculty are being asked to help change the
school's Thursday-night drinking tradition by giving tests on
Fridays. And at the football stadium, the university is drawing up
a policy to regulate tailgate parties at football games, where
underage and excessive drinking frequently occurs.
</P>
<P>
   A more comprehensive campaign may not eradicate heavy drinking,
but it could help to avoid tragedies like the LSU and MIT drinking
deaths of last year, Garrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller schools, like Lutheran-based Concordia University, say
bigger campuses tend to have more problems with heavy drinking. Of
Concordia's 750 enrolled students, only about 230 live on campus.
When students do go drinking, they look after each other, said
William Driskill, vice-president of student services.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Concordia has no fraternities or sororities cuts
down on heavy drinking, Driskill said, but it still exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students at this age are in the experimental stage, no matter
what their background,'' he said. ``Somebody would be naive to
think a religious school will cure alcohol abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   At St. Edward's University, drinking is allowed only in private
rooms, not in the common areas of dorms, said Dennis Poust, a
spokesman for the university.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the St. Edward's community plays a role in the
lowered incidence of excessive drinking. Of the 3,400-strong
student population, fewer than 1,000 live on campus. And for those
that do, there are no fraternities or sororities to throw wild
bashes at the Catholic institution.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no alcohol-related deaths or sexual assaults in
recent memory, Poust said. ``Our alcohol policies seem to be
working fairly well.''
</P>
<P>
   At Southwestern, officials in 1993 banned kegs, beer-filled
party balls, and ``trash can punch.'' Hard liquor is also not
allowed to be served on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Students are required to keep a guest list of all party
attendees, and parties where alcohol is to be served must get prior
approval from the dean of students. If approval is granted, the
hosts must ensure only those 21 or older are drinking alcohol, and
the hosts must provide nonalcoholic beverages for minors.
</P>
<P>
   All 378 first-year students were taken on an orientation retreat
where they were briefed on the university's strict policy, said
Dean Babcock. Chief Brown was there to hold a session on the
drinking laws. The chief also addressed the student government,
three of the four campus fraternities, and a council of fraternity
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We warned and warned them,'' Babcock said
</P>
<P>
   And last week's raid sent the message that the university is
serious about underage drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fraternities are more concerned with not getting trouble,''
said Charles Boehm, a 20-year-old junior and a member of Phi Delta
Theta.
</P>
<P>
   While the enforcement of the rules may be stricter, he said, the
rate of students drinking remains the same. Only now, drinking has
moved off campus and is more clandestine, he said. ``The strict
rules are just making it more illicit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
