<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1853 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MYSTERY-FOOD25-COX     09-24 2322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-FOOD25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Killer cuisines
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dark and stormy night. Glass breaking. A thud.
</P>
<P>
   A figure flees, leaving behind a plate of roast venison loin; a
body, and worse: a prized magnum of '28 Bordeaux shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The chef/caterer/gourmet is on the scene, solving
the crime _ and reciting a recipe for the venison's sauce, as well
as finding a new source for the Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea behind culinary mysteries, one of the hottest
genres to hit the whodunits in years, according to Otto Penzler,
owner of The Mysterious Bookshop in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Penzler, whose store specializes in crime stories, says the
books are the mystery-genre-du-jour. ``They sell wonderfully well _
almost relentlessly.''
</P>
<P>
   The books have chefs or other food pros somehow embroiled in a
crime, with lots of cooking as the plot twists.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Cut (Bantam Books), on The New York Times bestseller list,
was written by Diane Mott Davidson, a Colorado author considered
tops in the culinary mysteries. She has seven others to her credit.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the other writers, who have a food writing
background, she came to the genre as a mystery writer. Her first
book, Catering to No One, however, took an unexpected food turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started writing my story in the Evergreen (Colo.) Cafe,
where I met this caterer. I put her in the story, and my critique
group liked her so much, they suggested I make her the
protagonist,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With a caterer as lead character, food had to follow, so
Davidson volunteered to work free with a local caterer to learn the
business. She had an interest in upscale cooking, but had never
worked in the business. ``It was very, very hard work. People have
no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldy Shultz, caterer cum sleuth, is now her main character. ``I
try to get across how tough it is'' being a caterer, Davidson said.
With each new plot, Davidson works with the real caterer, still at
no charge, cooking, serving at events _ and taking copious notes.
</P>
<P>
   The job is perfect for her protagonist, she said, since Goldy
can go into all kinds of settings. ``She's catering at a ski resort
in the one I'm writing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Other authors bring a food background to their writing.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Richman is the restaurant reviewer and food writer for
The Washington Post. Writing her witty 1997 book, The Butter Did It
(Harper Paperbacks), was a fantasy come true, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The book, about the death of a highbrow chef catering a Capitol
charity event, has inside foodie tidbits tossed in for spice. Savvy
readers can read about the chefs she favors in real life
(Jean-Louis Palladin, Patrick O'Connell and Robert Donna) and may
recognize the ones she doesn't (she won't tell). Her protagonist is
a sassy food reviewer, Chas Wheatley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always wanted to write mysteries. I've been doing food
reviewing and food editing for 22 years,'' she said. ``People don't
realize how tedious it is to write about the same thing day after
day. One more `crisp and juicy' . . . The vocabulary gets so
tiresome. In the mysteries, I'm getting to use a whole new
vocabulary, or use old words in new way.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't fun being on the receiving end of a review.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a newspaper review in the Midwest that tore me to
shreds,'' she said. ``My first reaction was, this is personal _ a
personal attack. Then I thought, this is exactly the way a chef
feels when I review his restaurant. I know I'm not writing a
personal attack, but when it happens to you, well . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The foods she mentions are ones she's eaten in restaurants, and
the chefs are based on real-life chefs and restaurateurs, too, she
said. ``Fortunately, most of them didn't recognize themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Culinary mysteries have a history _ Rex Stout put his gourmet
detective Nero Wolfe to work in the late '30s, and Robert Parker
still has his Spenser tantalizing readers today. Virginia Rich was
first to include recipes in her Eugenia Potter books in the '80s;
now they all have them.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes range from the gourmet chocolate-hazelnut calzone in
Richman's book to the simple but tasty Boston baked beans in Tamara
Myers' book, Eat, Drink and Be Wary (Signet Mystery Books).
</P>
<P>
   Davidson says her publisher may take it one step further:
``There are whisperings about a cookbook collecting all the recipes
from my books, but they're just rumors right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Richman, always the critic, said she prefers recipes from fellow
food writer Lou Jane Temple, a culinary mystery writer from Kansas
City, Mo. She's author of Death by Rhubarb and Revenge of the
Barbecue Queens. ``I have the artichoke hummus from one of her
books in the freezer all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers includes several Pennsylvania-Dutch dishes at the end of
her books. The prolific writer with Amish parents sets her
mysteries in the country, peopled with Amish and Mennonite cooks
who are constantly whipping up mountains of sauerkraut, pickles and
rich cakes.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes have a French background in Cecile Lamalle's
culinary mystery, An Appetite for Murder, due out in a few months
from Mysterious Press. Lamalle was former food writer for The New
York Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I'd like to write a mystery,'' she said. ``As
for the food angle, well, it's really all I know. I developed my
lead character, Charlie Poisson, to be chef and owner of a little
French restaurant in the Hudson Valley. He's loosely based on my
father _ who was a real character.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamalle grew up with French food served by her father, a
restaurateur, so most of the dishes in her books are classic
cuisine. ``But I've become a vegetarian, so I've added that in my
next book. There's a young sous chef who does tae kwan do, and he
becomes a vegetarian,'' she said. It also gives her an angle to
include Asian recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Readers, primarily women, want to discuss the recipes from the
books at book signings, or critique the foods, Davidson said.
``They're great. Occasionally, I've asked the readers to help with
a mystery of my own. Once when I couldn't find the right malt to
make a malted milk chocolate cake, I asked the readers to help and
they sent all this malt! I had mail-order, health-food and every
other kind of malt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cake never did work out _ you have to have too much milk
to make it work,'' she said. ``But it was fun trying!''
</P>
<P>
   Here are recipes from some of the culinary mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Peter's Scrimshaw Inn rum pie
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark Myer's rum
</P>
<P>
   9-inch graham cracker crust
</P>
<P>
   For topping:
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Grated bittersweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   Combine 1 1/4 cups milk, sugar and salt in medium saucepan;
bring to a boil. In small bowl with pouring lip, mix 6 tablespoons
milk, flour, cornstarch and two egg yolks. Slowly beat in some of
the boiling liquid, stirring constantly. Once mixture is heated,
pour into saucepan, and cook over medium-low heat, stirring until
thick.
</P>
<P>
   Cook slightly, then beat in vanilla, butter and rum. Turn
mixture into graham cracker crust. (Note: To prevent collapse of
pie pan, set into a glass or metal pie plate before filling.)
</P>
<P>
   Chill pie until set.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving top with whipped cream and sprinkle with
grated chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 9-inch pie.
</P>
<P>
   (Above recipe from The Nantucket Diet Murders by Virginia Rich,
Dell Books, Mysteries, 1985.)
</P>
<P>
   Artichoke hummus
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked garbanzo beans
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   About 1/2 teaspoon each: paprika, cumin, kosher salt, white
pepper
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil (approximately 1/3 cup)
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except oil in the bowl of a food
processor or high-speed blender. Turn on machine, and slowly
drizzle in olive oil as the ingredients are being processed to a
creamy consistency. (Note: mixture should be thick enough to
spread, not pour.)
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 3 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   (From Death by Rhubarb by Lou Jane Temple, 1996, St. Martin's
Dead Letter Mystery Books.)
</P>
<P>
   Great-granny Yoder's onion cheese soup
</P>
<P>
   1 cup onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 stick butter
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded sharp cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   Croutons for serving
</P>
<P>
   Saute onions in butter, salt and pepper until transparent. In
measuring cup or small bowl, whisk together 1/2 cup cold milk with
cornstarch. Pour mixture over onions, stirring constantly. Add
chicken broth and remaining milk. Add dry mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle shredded cheese over top while continuing to stir. Cook
over low heat until the cheese is melted. Serve in bowls, and
garnish with croutons.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (
</P>
<P>
   Blondes' blondies
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peeled and diced Granny Smith apples
</P>
<P>
   1 cup firmly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans or walnuts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   Creamy citrus frosting (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees. Butter a 9-by-13-inch metal
(not glass) pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, mix the chopped apples with the brown
sugar. Set it aside while you prepare the other ingredients. In a
small pan, melt the butter and set it aside to cool. In a small
mixing bowl, beat the egg slightly. Sift together the flour, baking
soda, salt, cinnamon, nutmeg, and allspice.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the melted and cooled butter into the egg, stir this
mixture into the apple mixture. Stir the flour mixture into the
apple mixture, mixing just until incorporated. Stir in nuts and
raisins (note: batter will be thick). Spread batter in prepared
pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 18 to 22 minutes, or until the blondies test done with
a toothpick. Cool in the pan, then frost. Slice and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 to 32 servings, depending on size of slices.
</P>
<P>
   Creamy citrus frosting
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ( 1/4 stick) unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 cups confectioner's sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   Beat butter with orange juice until butter is very soft (note:
they will not mix completely). Add sugar until desired consistency
is reached. Spread on cooled brownies.
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough to cover a 9-by-12-inch pan of cake or brownies.
</P>
<P>
   (
</P>
<P>
   Coppi's chocolate hazelnut calzone (with peanut butter
variation)
</P>
<P>
   For the dough:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup warm water (110 degrees, or slightly warm to touch)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup warm milk
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope ( 1/4-ounce) active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 cups flour, more if needed
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup Nutella chocolate-hazelnut spread
</P>
<P>
   OR:
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup smooth peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   Confectioner's sugar
</P>
<P>
   Make the dough: Put warm water and warm milk in a large bowl,
and sprinkle in yeast. Let stand 3 to 4 minutes, then stir to
dissolve. Stir in the salt and 2 cups flour. Gradually stir in
about 1 more cup of flour, using only enough to form a soft,
slightly sticky dough. Knead 5 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil the bottom of a clean bowl, and roll dough into it
to coat with oil. Cover with a towel and set in a warm spot _ 80
degrees to 100 degress _ to rise for 2 hours, or until doubled in
bulk. Punch down and knead for 1 minute. After rising, dough can be
used immediately or formed into a ball, wrapped tightly in plastic
and refrigerated for a few days before being brought to room
temperature for baking.
</P>
<P>
   If not using Nutella for filling, make peanut butter filling: In
a medium saucepan, stir the sugar and cocoa powder until blended.
Gradually stir in the milk. Bring to a boil over medium heat,
stirring constantly. Lower heat and simmer for 2 minutes. Remove
from heat and let cool for at least 5 minutes. Add the vanilla and
peanut butter, stirring until smooth. Cool thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Make calzone: About 45 minutes before serving, preheat the oven
to its highest temperature, up to 500 degrees. If you have a pizza
tile, heat it in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the dough into six pieces. Roll each piece into a circle
6 to 7 inches in diameter, about 1/4-inch thick. Spoon 2
tablespoons chocolate-peanut butter filling or the Nutella in the
center of each piece. Fold dough into a half-moon over the filling.
Pinch the edges together and fold bottom edge over top, crimping to
seal well.
</P>
<P>
   Place on an ungreased cookie sheet, leaving 2 inches between
each calzone. Bake until well browned, 12 to 20 minutes, depending
on your oven.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and sprinkle with confectioner's sugar. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 calzones.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from The Butter Did It by Phyllis Richman, Harper
Paperback, 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   `BITTER SWEETS' AND OTHER HAUTE TITLES
</P>
<P>
   Crime writers never hurt for titles, but the culinary mystery
writers seem to take great glee at the puns used to name their
books.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sample:
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Richman: The Butter Did It
</P>
<P>
   Lou Jane Temple: Death by Rhubarb, Revenge of the Barbecue
Queens
</P>
<P>
   G.A. McKevett: Killer Calories; Bitter Sweets; Just Desserts
</P>
<P>
   Tamar Myers: Eat, Drink, and Be Wary; Parsley, Sage, Rosemary
and Crime; No Use Dying Over Spilled Milk; Between a Wok and a Hard
Place, Just Plain Pickled to Death
</P>
<P>
   Peter King: Spiced to Death
</P>
<P>
   Diane Mott Davidson: Catering to Nobody; Dying for Chocolate;
The Cereal Murders; The Last Suppers; The Main Corpse; The Grilling
Season; Prime Cut
</P>
