</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-PECKER-REVIEW25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Instead of outrageous, 'Pecker' is just cute
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Waters puckishly calls his latest movie Pecker, after the
nickname of his main character, a guy with a reputation for picking
and pecking at his food. Why, did you think it referred to some
other attribute?
</P>
<P>
   The attention-getting title is merely a prank, but an amusing
one. The first movie in four years from the master of the
outrageous, however, rarely rises above the level of cute. What
might be considered very promising from a first-time filmmaker has
to be viewed as a limp disappointment from the director of such
cult classics as Pink Flamingos and Polyester.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes, has Waters gone and matured on us while we weren't
looking?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, only by Waters' own standards could Pecker be deemed
as low-grade offensive. After all, it includes an extreme close-up
of female genitalia and shots of male strippers gyrating at a gay
go-go club. Pecker's ventriloquistic grandmother uses a Virgin Mary
statue for her dummy, and his sugar-craving little sister has to be
sedated with Ritalin. Forrest Gump, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these walks on the tasteless side, Waters has come up
with one of his most accessible, audience-friendly films, a playful
sendup of the New York art world.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker (a well-cast, sweetly naive Edward Furlong) is a
Baltimore shutterbug, merrily roaming his blue-collar neighborhood,
capturing everyday oddities on film. When his perceived artistic
talent is discovered by a New York gallery owner (Lili Taylor) at
his Sub Pit sandwich shop solo show, Pecker becomes the toast of
the Manhattan art scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Apple sophisticates just adore his ``art is everywhere''
snapshots. In an amusing sendup of those overnight success
montages, Pecker gets featured on the cover of every important art
magazine. He even is offered a show at the Whitney Museum of Art
(``A Peek at Pecker'') but cancels it in a fit of pique when media
pressures get too intense for him. As Dorothy Gale once observed,
``there's no place like home,'' so Pecker decides to return to
Baltimore. But wherever he goes, the art-adoring Beautiful People
follow him there.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has become a low-rent Woody Allen, able to attract a
stellar cast of independent film actors. In addition to
wheeler-dealer Taylor, there is the omnipresent Christina Ricci as
Pecker's Baltimore-loving girlfriend who works at the nearby Spin
'n' Grin laundromat. Mary Kay Place is strictly apple pie as
Pecker's adoring mom, and a shrill Martha Plimpton shows up under a
dark wig as his sister, toiling industriously at the Fudge Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Actual photography artist Cindy Sherman appears as herself,
fuming with jealousy over Pecker's acclaim. She clearly has a sense
of humor, but, alas, no acting ability. And Waters film veteran
Patricia Hearst _ yes, formerly of the Symbionese Liberation Army _
glides through a few scenes, typecast as a wealthy art patron. Stir
well, and you have an amusing but hardly scabrous stew.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Pecker comes off as amateurish, but that has always been
true of Waters' movies. As with Pecker's photographs, if you find
art in Pecker, then it's art. But don't rule out the possibility
that it is just one person's well-meaning put-on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
