<HEADER>
A1855 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBP-RONIN-REVIEW25-CO     09-24 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-RONIN-REVIEW25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's in the briefcase? 'Ronin' wants you to care
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ronin is a curious action-thriller for the post-Cold War era,
when nearly everyone seems world-weary, including writers of
action-thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not directors. Veteran John Frankenheimer gasses up
the genre by providing more action, more atmosphere, more shady
characters and more double-crosses than a library of John le Carre
novels.
</P>
<P>
   To what purpose, however? It is hard to tell whether this movie
is a postmodern goof, or the case of a done-that director _ one who
has taken his lumps from critics _ pulling out all the
old-fashioned stops: ``Watch this, you pups.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer? Probably a bit of both. But trying to answer this
while keeping track of the plot is exhausting. Better to just enjoy
the low-life action and set aside the highbrow musings for later.
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens, some rough characters circle each other
suspiciously in a seedy Paris bistro. This tense, neatly
choreographed scene reminds us that Frankenheimer cut his teeth on
the tight ``stage'' of live television.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out these folks are ex-spies and military specialists from
around the world. They don't know each other. They're at loose ends
with the Cold War over. But they've been offered a job and have
come to the bistro to meet their contact, Deirdre (Natascha
McElhone).
</P>
<P>
   They learn that their mission is to recover a heavily guarded
metal briefcase. Never mind how. Never mind what's in it.
</P>
<P>
   Sam (Robert De Niro) is a former CIA operative. There's also an
ex-KGB iceman (the Swedish actor Stellen Skarsgard); a skittish
Brit (Sean Bean); a wary Frenchman (Jean Reno); and an American
wheelman (Skip Sudduth). Shadowing the gang is a mysterious
character whose allegiance and motives are unclear (Jonathan
Pryce).
</P>
<P>
   So the game's afoot, and it leads from Paris to Nice to the
ancient Roman amphitheater at Arles. They are shootouts and setups,
skulduggery and assassinations. And long, breathtaking car chases
through the tunnels of Paris and the narrow streets of the south of
France.
</P>
<P>
   All this in order to acquire that mysterious briefcase. Despite
the twisting, overcharged plot, there is only one crucial surprise.
But what if there's a different sort of surprise at work? A kind of
cerebral surprise? What if the audience is left to wonder whether
there really is anything at all in that briefcase? Maybe it's an
empty grail for which people are willing to scheme, cheat and die
to acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Then that would be irony (or commentary on international
intrigue). And that leads us to Richard Weisz. Turns out that is a
pseudonym for the fine playwright David Mamet. He cowrote the
screenplay with J.D. Zeik, and it bears Mamet's characteristic
terse, circular dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   It's a kind of dialogue suited to De Niro, and you wonder why he
has never appeared in a Mamet play. He brings his familiar
hard-nosed gangster persona to his role as a CIA tough guy,
although he's not quite as bonkers as he usually seems. It largely
works, although De Niro doesn't seem to have to work very hard to
pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   The film itself works intermittently. Some scenes depicting the
pensive interaction of these men are intriguing _ these specialists
with different personalities who pride themselves on their skill,
even if that skill is put to dubious ends. Frankenheimer (The
Manchurian Candidate) always has a neat touch for psychological
thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   A good stretch of the plot, however, seems as elliptical as
Mamet's dialogue. That may be the point. But Ronin _ the Japanese
name a type of ex-samurai warrior _ is best enjoyed as a
straightforward action picture. Just go along for the ride. Leave
the briefcase for later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
