<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-PROTECTION25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floridians calm in face of Georgess
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven-dollar pieces of plywood gained new value as local
residents competed with Broward, Miami-Dade and Monroe county
residents to buy storm supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But most Palm Beach County and Treasure Coast residents remained
calm, figuring the brunt of Hurricane Georges wouldn't come this
far north.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really concerned, I just want to be ready,'' said Mike
Cundiff, a West Palm Beach resident who wheeled 30 jars of baby
food and ten gallons of water in his grocery cart at a West Palm
Beach Publix.
</P>
<P>
   Still, water, wood, batteries and flashlights were selling fast
as delivery trucks hustled to refill shelves. Space at animal
shelters was scarce. And electrical generators were not available
at all, most merchants said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped in West Palm Beach, but there was no plywood to be
found,'' Kendall resident Robert Hill said Wednesday afternoon as
he loaded a van with 25 sheets at Home Depot in Jensen Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now heading north to Fort Pierce to find a couple
generators,'' he said. ``They're out of them here.''
</P>
<P>
   Salesman Robert Brown said the Lake Worth Home Depot sold more
than 1,000 sheets of plywood in an hour and 15 minutes. When that
ran out, customers bought weaker waferboard for $10.75 or more
expensive wood siding for $19.80.
</P>
<P>
   Sales clerks limited customers to 15 sheets to keep people from
hoarding. For the same reason, store employees wouldn't say which
stores generators were being shipped to or from or whether any
would be available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to protect people from scalpers and it's a tough
thing to do,'' said Kenny Nevad, who works in the hardware
department.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery store managers have not been limiting water sales,
though Scott Bates had a few questions for a group from Miami that
bought 15 cases of water Tuesday night. Bates said he was satisfied
they were bringing the scarce supply to friends and family and not
reselling it.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Mayhew, an investigator for the Florida Attorney General's
economic crimes office in Fort Lauderdale, spent Wednesday posting
notices at home-supply stores, supermarkets, police stations and
other locations in Palm Beach County. The notices reminded
potential gougers they faced civil fines of $1,000 per incident, up
to $25,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Dan Stermer said he had already
received calls from across South Florida Wednesday but not from
Palm Beach County or the Treasure Coast. Most gouging occurs after
a storm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Harrison, a spokesman for Home Depot's Southeast region,
said 125 truck drivers, each carrying 750 sheets of plywood, were
descending on South Florida. Although stores keep a seven-week
supply on hand, all of it disappeared Tuesday and Wednesday, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company monitors the storm constantly, trying to keep
delivery ahead of its path. ``Like everyone else in South Florida,
we went to school and saw what happened during Hurricane Andrew,''
he said, referring to the 1992 storm.
</P>
<P>
   In Publix stores in Palm Beach County and across South Florida,
the hottest commodity is water, said Carmen Millares, community
affairs manager for the Miami division, which covers from Vero
Beach to Key West.
</P>
<P>
   The chain's Deerfield Beach center, the main water bottler for
the Miami division, is operating around the clock. She wouldn't
give production figures, citing competition concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Like many customers at the Publix on Southern Boulevard, Maxine
Browlee grabbed a few jugs from boxes marked ``storm stock, for
emergency use.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will need water regardless of the wind and the rain,'' said
Browlee, who survived two hurricanes in the '30s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations from worried pet owners had already filled
veterinarian Ken Simmons hurricane-safe clinic in Greenacres by
Wednesday, Simmons said. Most of the owners were told to bring
their animals to the clinic sometime Thursday to avoid the worst of
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic will actually be more than full when all the animals
arrive, Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were boarding these animals for luxury vacations, we'd
be full right now,'' he said. But he's willing to keep some of the
animals in pet carriers and put several together in a cage _ with
the owners' permission _ to make more room for the short duration
of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Eliot Kleinberg, A. Scharnhorst and Pat Moore
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
