</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVREVIEW-JESSE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Star gives sitcom tender touch
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine this scenario on Married . . . With Children.
</P>
<P>
   Hot, dim-bulb Kelly Bundy (Christina Applegate) meets a hot,
broad-shouldered hunk. Before you start crooning Love &AMP; Marriage,
trashy Kelly's steaming up the back seat with the hot hunk.
</P>
<P>
   OK, fast-forward to 1998 and Applegate's new sitcom Jesse.
Single-mom, but still pretty hot, Jesse meets Diego (Bruno Campos),
her hunky next-door neighbor. But, instead of fogging up the car
windows, the responsible Jesse takes things slow. She even turns
down the poor guy's date request.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, folks, Applegate is all grown up. Clearly the former
Married . . . With Children star yearned to shed her sexpot image.
Mission accomplished. In Jesse, Applegate is Jesse Warner, a
harried single mom who works in her dad's bar while raising her
10-year-old son, caring for two goofy brothers (one dreams up
get-rich-quick schemes, the other refuses to talk) and fighting off
guys who call her ``sweet cheeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Jesse is light on laughs (it's not Frasier),
Applegate's character is a winner and one with whom many single
moms should identify. Like most unmarried moms, Jesse puts
everyone's priorities ahead of hers. She deserves happiness _ and
that square-jawed neighbor _ but just doesn't know it. Expect her
to strike an Ally McBeal-like chord with women viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Applegate and Campos are sweet in there their scenes together,
especially when doing laundry on their first date. Least appealing
are Jesse's dad (George Dzundza) and her brothers. That non-talking
guy routine gets old fast.
</P>
<P>
   Once you strip away the kooky family and time-worn cliches,
you'll find a tender sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
