r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURES-BJT25-COX     09-24 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FRIDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Friday, September 25, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SHANIA _ Profile of country singer Shania Twain, currently
touring. (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RONIN-REVIEW _ Review of ``Ronin,'' starring Robert De Niro as a
gun for hire. We like. It's either an A- or a B+. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SOLDIER-REVIEW _ Review of ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries.''
Kris Kristofferson stars as the father of a cold family. (Ringel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-REVIEW _ Review of ``Urban Legend.'' A thriller in which a
killer tries to make true urban legends. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PECKER-REVIEW _ Review of ``Pecker.'' (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FIRELIGHT-REVIEW _ Art film. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA
6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FRANKENHEIMER-Q&AMP;A Q&AMP;A with storied director John Frankenheimer,
who just won an Emmy for his ``George Wallace'' miniseries and
whose ``Ronin'' opens today. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TUCKER-Q&AMP;A _ Q&AMP;A with Chris Tucker. (SoMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PBP-RONIN-REVIEW _ Ronin _ the Japanese name a type of
ex-samurai warrior _ is best enjoyed as a straightforward action
picture. Just go along for the ride. Leave the briefcase for later.
(Schwan, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PBP-PECKER-REVIEW _ John Waters puckishly calls his latest movie
Pecker, after the nickname of his main character, a guy with a
reputation for picking and pecking at his food. Why, did you think
it referred to some other attribute? The first movie in four years
from the master of the outrageous, however, rarely rises above the
level of cute. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEW _ Take a big breath: it's a big weekend with 15 new and
returning shows. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ ABC takes a stab at Saturday nights with two
inventive series that might score well with audiences _ ``Cupid''
and (believe it or not) ETA 6 p.m. ET.``Fantasy Island''; roundup
of ``Homicide,'' ``Two of a Kind,'' ``Boy Meets World,''
``Sabrina,'' ``Brother's Keeper,'' ``Kids Say ...'' ``Candid
Camera,'' ``Buddy Faro,'' ``Nash Bridges,'' ``Early Edition,''
``Walker Texas Ranger'' and best drama Emmy winner ``The
Practice''. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MARTIAL _ What Jackie Chan has done for films, CBS hopes to
do with his sometimes co-worker Sammo Hung, who karate chops his
way through the cop series ``Martial Law.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ROBERTSHAW _ ATLANTA _ Last week he set Washington on its ear.
Last night, it was Boston. Choral master and Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra conductor emeritus Robert Shaw was flown into Boston at
the eleventh hour Thursday to conduct the Boston Symphony when
their conductor Seiji Ozawa became ill. He drew standing ovations
(not an everyday occurence up north, y'all) and rave notices in
today's Boston Globe. Trying for quick interview with Shaw. (Brock,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ Chronicle books has published Manatee ($14.95),
a collection of lovely photographs by Rei Ohara. And other news on
books. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY-FOOD _ A dark and stormy night. Glass breaking. A thud.
Not to worry. The chef/caterer/gourmet is on the scene, solving the
crime _ and reciting a recipe for the venison's sauce, as well as
finding a new source for the Bordeaux. That's the idea behind
culinary mysteries, one of the hottest genres to hit the whodunits
in years. (With recipes.) (Norris, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   OPENHAND _ ATLANTA _ Project Open Hand, the remarkable meal
delivery program for AIDS patients, celebrates its 10th anniversary
in September. Everything, from preparation of meals to their daily
delivery to clients, is done in house, largely through volunteers.
A look at the operation, its impact, and some of the volunteers
(100 per day) who make it possible. (Henry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-WEBSITES _ Most travelers aren't satisfied to merely
travel _ they want to foist their photographs and memories upon
their family, friends and any other poor saps they can take
hostage. But just as jet travel has opened up the world, the
Internet is allowing vacationers to air their exploits in front of
the whole wide plugged-in universe on special travel Web pages.
(Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-WEBSITES-SIX _ Meet six metro Atlanta families that have
posted their own travel Web pages, from a Cumming teen's wry
observations of the Cayman Islands to a Decatur twosome's
passionate odes to Venice, Italy, to an Alpharetta 2-year-old who
narrates family trip to Sanibel, Fla. (OK, posted by Dad). We
provide links. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-WEATHER _ So, for anyone wondering, ``Where is fall?'' the
answer is that Texans are a judicious lot, don't like to be rushed
into something, and will have fall when it's time for it. For now,
gone are the 100-degree days of summer, and the harshness of the
sun. (Kelley, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UT-WELLNESS-DORM _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Beginning this year, students
entering the University of Texas have a unique housing option: One
that is alcohol-, tobacco- and drug-free. The Wellness floor was
inspired by students and other residents who pointed out that not
everyone comes to college to get falling-down drunk, said Daniel
Ostick, residence coordinator. (Rodriguez, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY-DRINKING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Like colleges and
universities across the country that fear the horrific tales of
fraternity hazing and stories of students literally drinking
themselves to death, the administration at Southwestern University
is cracking down on drinking this year as no time before.
(Davenport/Rodriguez, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANI-OPTOMETRIST _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dr. Clifford
Parker has come back to West Palm Beach from Afghanistan with two
stories to tell. Parker, 54, gave up his optometry practice here 25
years ago to help some of the world's poorest people. He could
perform what seemed like miracles against glaucoma or cataracts or
myopia, but he could do nothing to stop the ancient distrust that
finally destroyed much of what he'd helped build. (Kalajian, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   AQUIFER-RULES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The state's top environmental
agency recently approved new rules intended to reduce pollution in
the Edwards Aquifer, a source of drinking water for 1.75 million
people and lighting rod for debate over growth and environmental
protection. (Rivera, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
