   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81. e-mail: nyt &LR; calva.net
</P>
<P>
   _ Mexico, Central America, South America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los
Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax, 310-996-0089.
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2484 -- Sept. 24, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. CHEATING HUSBANDS Divorce used to be the first option when
women found their husbands cheating. Not any more. Rosanne Rosen
talks to wives and psychologists to find out why. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
THE CASE FOR A GLOBAL BANK Jeffrey Garten, dean of the Yale School
of Management, explains why the IMF remains the best agent for
dealing with international financial crises. New York Times Op-Ed.
800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
PAST OR FUTURE? KOSOVO ECHOES BOSNIA Only a few months ago, the
U.S. and its European partners proclaimed sternly that they would
``not allow another Bosnia'' in Kosovo. Once again, everybody is
shifting the blame, the human disaster spreads, and the Balkans
remain the most endangered place in post-Cold War Europe. By Flora
Lewis. 800 words. 4. WHAT KIND OF A GRANDPARENT ARE YOU? The whole
world has turned to Dr. Ruth for answers to sex-related questions.
In her new book she takes on the loosely defined role of
grandparent. In this excerpt, she defines the various styles of
grandparenting and helps readers find the ones best suited to them
-- and their grandchildren. By Dr. Ruth K. Westheimer and Steven
Kaplan. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
STANDARD TREATMENT MAY NOT HELP ULCERS CAUSED
</P>
<P>
   BY ANTI-INFLAMMATORY DRUGS The standard treatment doctors
prescribe for peptic ulcers may not help when ulcers are caused by
nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDS) commonly used to
treat low back pain, arthritis and other chronic conditions. Many
NSAIDS are available without prescription, but they can damage the
stomach lining and up to 30 per cent of people taking these drugs
long-term will develop ulcers. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News
Service. 1,500 words. (Embargoed 23h30 September 24, London time.)
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
HOW TO CARE FOR YOUR BABY'S SKIN From itchy rashes to flaking skin,
a number of conditions can affect your child in the first year of
life. The good news is that most of them can be diagnosed easily by
your baby's doctor and treated at home. By Leah Ingram. From Child
magazine. 1,000 words.
__________________________________________________________________
7. NEW HYBRID ROSES ARE BEAUTIFUL WITHOUT BOTHER The results of a
seven-year study by the Chicago Botanic Garden on new hybrid roses
reveals which are the best for a low-maintenance garden. By Susan
McClure. 800 words + photos. 8. FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A
Australia, New Zealand, Brazil) A. SENSITIVE FLOWER : Plants have
feelings too, says Andy Coghlan. They can see, touch, smell, taste
and hear, and we are finally beginning to work out how they do it.
2,500 words. B. THAT'S ME IN THE MIDDLE : With a Personal Roving
Presence robot, you can stroll through a building in some distant
location, attend meetings, or pop into offices. By Brandon Brown.
1,200 words. C. ON THIN ICE : Perched on a shifting skin of ice
over the ocean, braving sub-zero temperatures and hungry polar
bears, researchers are unlocking the secrets of the Arctic climate
and the implications for global warming. Gabrielle Walker joined
them. 2,000 words. 9. SCIENCE SQUINTS AT A FUTURE FOGGED BY CHAOTIC
UNCERTAINTY Scientific sages depend not on tea leaves or the
positions of planets, but on tools like mathematical modeling,
statistical analysis, complexity theory, celestial mechanics,
geology, economics and epidemiology. Scientists discount the naive
paradigms of fortune tellers, ancient and modern. Alas, rational
approaches to prediction also fail all too often, and it may be
that there are some phenomena for which predictions will remain
forever out of reach. By Malcolm Brown. New York Times Science
Times. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
MAURITANIA UNDERMINED BY RACKETEERING AND
</P>
<P>
   RESURGENT TRIBALISM There are a number of subjects better
avoided in the West African country of Mauritania. The most
sensitive of these taboos is slavery, which was officially
abolished only at the beginning of the 80's. By Jean-Pierre Tuquoi.
Le Monde. (English translation available.) 1,000 words.
