<HEADER>
A1939 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMANUS-OUTRAGE-NYTSF     09-24 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-OUTRAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MORAL CORRUPTION AND 'THE DEATH OF OUTRAGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    After tens of millions of Americans watched President Clinton
defend himself on TV this week, his approval ratings largely
remained unchanged or even rose a bit. Why?
 &HT;    According to William J. Bennett's landmark new book, ''The Death
of Outrage: Bill Clinton and the Assault on American Ideals,'' the
president's corruption has corrupted the nation.
 &HT;    ''Once in a great while a single national event provides insight
into where we are and who we are and what we esteem,'' he writes.
''The many Clinton scandals ... reveal insights into how we view
politics and power; virtue and vice; public trust and respect for
the law; sexual morality and standards of personal conduct.''
 &HT;    The picture of the American people is not a pretty one, because
too many of us have bought the rationalizations Clinton and his
sympathizers are peddling. Bennett's breakthrough is that he takes
those arguments seriously and systematically reveals their moral
corruption.
 &HT;    --''If the president's wife forgives him, why shouldn't we?''
 &HT;    Bennett says the core of this argument is that Starr's
investigation is just about sex, and ''sexual misconduct is none of
our business.'' However, Clinton's own attorney general asked Starr
to investigate ''credible evidence of criminal wrongdoing by the
president of the United States -- possible perjury, obstruction of
justice, and job offers for silence -- not accusations of
presidential philandering,'' he writes.
 &HT;    Viewers could see multiple examples of Clinton's perjury in his
testimony. In his opening statement he claimed that oral sex ''did
not constitute sexual relations.'' When it was noted that his
attorney, Robert Bennett (Bill Bennett's brother) claimed there
''absolutely no sex of any kind in any manner, shape or form,''
Clinton said, ''I wasn't paying much attention to this
conversation.'' And in more than 140 instances, this man with a
photographic memory could not remember.
 &HT;    --Because the economy is good, presidential character and
conduct don't matter.
 &HT;    Yes, unemployment and inflation are the lowest in decades.
However, a nation founded on ''self-evident'' truths has had a
''moral purpose defining our highest goals and highest
achievements,'' Bennett writes. We proudly ended slavery in one
century and embraced the civil rights revolution in our era in a
campaign for justice.
 &HT;    Polls show that 87 percent of the public fear something is
fundamentally wrong with America's moral condition.
 &HT;    The person who is privately corrupt will make publicly corrupt
decisions. Clinton could have avoided the danger of impeachment,
had he confessed his sin in January. Instead, he lied in court, to
his friends and employees who defended him in public and helped
find her a job to shut her up.
 &HT;    Bennett recalls that ''Reelection avarice appears to have
compromised national security by permitting the transfer of
sensitive satellite technology to China'' in order to raise illegal
''soft money'' for the campaign.
 &HT;    --They all do it. Presidents and politicians are expected to
engage in corruption or sexual misconduct. Franklin Roosevelt,
Eisenhower and Kennedy are accused of adultery (though Ike's family
denies it).
 &HT;    According to a University of Chicago study, only 21 percent of
men and 11 percent of women have ever committed adultery. Within
the past year, only 3.6 percent of men and 1.3 percent of women did
so. And ''only a small percentage of those who commit adultery are
serial adulterers,'' writes Bennett.
 &HT;    ''Most presidents do not commit illegal acts or lie under oath
or thumb their nose at the law. Most presidents do not chronically
deceive, obfuscate and stonewall federal investigators.''
 &HT;    --''Judge not, lest you be judged.'' Another Scripture often
used: ''He who is without sin cast the first stone.''
 &HT;    But in this case of the woman caught in adultery, Jesus told her
to ''Go and sin no more.'' And the woman ''did not deny the charge,
stonewall or lie to cover it up,'' Bennett asserts.
 &HT;    Jesus clearly did judge others. He called the Pharisees a
''brood of vipers'' full of hypocrisy and wickedness. Bennett says
the person forgiven ''should still be held accountable for his
acts.'' The pope forgave the man who shot him, but did not suggest
he be freed from prison.
 &HT;    The danger of this rationalization is ''that we are giving
license not only to Clinton's corruption but possibly to our own as
well.''
 &HT;    There IS objective right and wrong. Proverbs Chapter 5 warned
3,000 years ago:
 &HT;    ''For the lips of an adulteress drip honey,
 &HT;    and her speech is smoother than oil;
 &HT;    but in the end she is as bitter as gall,
 &HT;    sharp as a two-edged sword.
 &HT;    Her feet go down to death;
 &HT;    her steps lead straight to the grave.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
