<HEADLINE>
WILDLIFE ABOUNDS IN LOUISIANA'S GREAT OUTDOORS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW IBERIA, La. _ The ``fais do-do'' isn't the only wildlife to
be found in Cajun Country.
</P>
<P>
   With its diverse habitats and mild winters, southwest Louisiana
brims with natural wonders, both flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
   Trust us, gators aren't the only critters here.
</P>
<P>
   Near New Iberia at Spanish Lake, a shallow lake with just five
miles of shoreline, more than 240 species of birds have been
spotted.
</P>
<P>
   From airboat tours to bird sanctuaries, opportunities for
exploring nature abound. Here are some places to start:
</P>
<P>
   _ The floodwaters of as many as 38 states find their way each
year to the Atchafalaya Basin, which covers more than 70 miles of
south-central Louisiana, roughly from Simmesport to Morgan City.
Its continually changing maze of bayous, streams and lakes is a
complex flood control system under the direction of the U.S. Army
Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Of interest to visitors is the beauty and diversity of the
basin, which features dense stands of cypress, oak, willow and
other trees that provide a habitat for deer, rabbits, squirrels,
turtles, birds, snakes and alligators. The basin is home to 300
species of birds, 65 species of reptiles and 46 species of mammals.
More than 90 species of fish live in its dark waters, and each year
the swamp gives up millions of pounds of crawfish to commercial
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Allemond and his family offer tours of the Atchafalaya
Basin daily from February through December. The open-air boat tours
give visitors a chance to peek at not only the secrets of the swamp
but also the lifestyle of the Cajuns who depend on the basin.
</P>
<P>
   Houseboats and stilt houses dot the swamp, as do egrets and
gators. While snaking around the basin, the boat captain offers a
continuous narrative of life on the swamp, including its history as
home to the Chitimachas Indians and as a hiding place for pirate
Jean Lafitte. Logging and the oil industry also have left their
mark on the basin.
</P>
<P>
   The Atchafalaya Basin Tours depart from McGee's Landing in
Breaux Bridge. After the tour, you can feast on crawfish, catfish
and other Cajun fare at the McGee's Landing restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cajun Country is a bird lovers' dream. For the purist, swamp
tours provide many opportunities to see and photograph migrating
species. For the rest of us, attractions such as Jungle Gardens and
Bird City are great places to flock.
</P>
<P>
   Jungle Gardens was the brainchild of Edward Avery McIlhenny,
whose father, Edmund, developed Tabasco sauce. The gardens are
about six miles outside New Iberia on Avery Island. The island is
where Edmund Avery cultivated the pepper crops and mined the salt
that are still used in the production of Tabasco.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Avery McIlhenny was a naturalist and conservationist who
wrote several books, including ``Autobiography of an Egret'' and
``Life History of the Alligator.'' A world traveler, he began
bringing back exotic plants from around the globe to his burgeoning
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   A driving trail winds around lagoons, pools and wooded tracts.
Along the drive, visitors can see a world of vegetation: soap trees
and junipers from India, finger bananas and wisterias from China,
lotus and papyrus from the Nile region of Africa and papayas from
the tropics.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can drive through, but to appreciate the scope of the
gardens, you need to take advantage of the walking trails, which
lead to Bird City and the Chinese Garden with its centuries-old
Buddha statue.
</P>
<P>
   Bird City is a heron and egret sanctuary created by McIlhenny.
</P>
<P>
   McIlhenny heard the story of a prince in India who had built
bamboo cages to hold his collection of exotic birds, which had been
gathered from all over India. When the prince died, the cages were
neglected and rotted away. But the winged creatures, descendants of
the prince's original birds, remained in their nests.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired, McIlhenny built a wire cage over a small lake on Avery
Island in 1892. Then he captured seven young snowy egrets in the
swamps. Around that time, the egrets were becoming increasingly
endangered because of plume hunters.
</P>
<P>
   McIlhenny cared for his birds for a year, and then when the next
migratory season came around he dismantled the cage. The birds
headed south. The next spring, as in the Indian story, McIlhenny's
egrets returned.
</P>
<P>
   Now each spring, this scene is repeated, but today as many as
20,000 egrets, herons and other migratory birds call on Bird City.
There are so many birds that the McIlhenny family has built piers
of bamboo to accommodate the nesting masses.
</P>
<P>
   The egrets and herons begin returning in mid-February, and the
families begin their migration with the first blast of cold wind.
Some birds _ the old and stubborn _ make Bird Island their home
year-round.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Jefferson Island, about a 15-minute drive west of New
Iberia, Rip Van Winkle Gardens _ previously known as Live Oak
Gardens _ is situated on 25 semitropical acres. Flowers abound, and
the property also includes a small bed-and-breakfast, a restaurant
and the 1870s home of actor Joseph Jefferson. Self-guided walking
tours, home tours and boat tours are available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another stop on this nature tour of Cajun Country is the Zoo
of Acadiana, located on Highway 90 about 10 miles south of
Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   The pretty little zoo is home to more than 750 exotic animals,
including zebras, leopards, camels and Bengal tigers. A raised
boardwalk offers terrific views of ostriches, muntjacs, cranes and
mangabeys.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is Louisiana, it's no surprise that the biggest
crowds are found at the alligator exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
