<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAJUN-DINING-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAJUN FOOD HAS A CHARACTER LIKE NO OTHER IN THE WORLD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
(Eds.: Accent marks needed over first e in sauteed, over e in glace
and over first and second e in etouffee) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAFAYETTE, La. _ Think Cajun food, and the prevailing images for
many people are blackened catfish, gumbo, boudin, jambalaya and
spicy fried shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   You can find the best of each in southwest Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   But the regional cuisine has evolved into a much more complex
bill of fare, with innovative and well-skilled chefs concocting new
Cajun-accented adaptations of classic dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Care for veal piccata cooked in wine and butter, laced with
Louisiana crawfish tails and shiitake mushrooms sauteed in a
roasted garlic, capers and herb ``beurre blanc''?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a filet mignon surrounded by French mushrooms sauted in a
roasted garlic veal demi-glace, on Cajun potato hay and laced with
Creolaise sauce?
</P>
<P>
   Or a king-cut tuna steak seasoned with cracked peppercorn mix
and roasted garlic, pan-seared medium rare on a bed of sauteed
julienned red onions and peppers in a herbed ``Cajun Power'' garlic
sauce?
</P>
<P>
   These are among chef-owner Ken Vernon's specialties at
Lafayette's Cafe Vermilionville (phone 318-237-0100), a stellar
restaurant that maintains a tradition established in 1818 with the
opening of an original inn on the property.
</P>
<P>
   Even Vernon's appetizers represent a mouthwatering adventure:
Oregon black truffle slices sauteed in a champagne and herb butter
sauce with lobster claw meat on garlic croutons; alligator
medallions with Dijon mustard sauce; crawfish eggrolls with honey
mustard. And who could resist a crawfish Caesar salad?
</P>
<P>
   Desserts include bananas Foster cheesecake and homemade pecan
pie.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour's drive to the south at leRosier Country Inn and
Restaurant (888-804-7673 or 318-367-5306) in New Iberia, Hallman
Woods III has earned national acclaim for his ``New Acadian''
cuisine, including recognition by Food &AMP; Wine magazine as one of
America's Best New Chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Woods uses the freshest local ingredients _ among them sweet
shrimp, mirlitons, okra and Creole tomatoes _ in beautiful and
delectable presentations. He does wonders with duck, lamb, veal and
beef; pan-roasted tilapia is a favorite; and on special occasions,
Woods has been known to serve gourmet dinners that include crawfish
in every course: perhaps crawfish spring rolls with ginger and
``beurre blanc''; marinated crawfish salad with spicy creole
mustard dressing; even crawfish strudel.
</P>
<P>
   A bonus is that bedrooms in the modern, comfortable inn are only
steps away from the 50-seat restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Catfish corn bread topped with fresh fish lures diners to Cafe
Des Amis (318-332-5273), situated in historical downtown Breaux
Bridge east of Lafayette. Other specialities include duck glazed
with hot corn syrup and pepper jelly.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast is an institution here: Try couche couche, an old-time
Cajun staple made with cornmeal, or ``pain perdue'' (French bread)
made with bread, eggs, sugar, milk and salt. Or start your day with
crawfish etouffe served atop biscuits or eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Among other leading area restaurants: Mulate's (800-422-2586 or
318-332-4648), also in Breaux Bridge; Pat's Fisherman's Wharf in
Henderson (318-228-7110); Catahoula's (318-662-2275) in Grand
Coteau; and Enola Prudhomme's Cajun Cafe (318-896-3646), Prejean's
(318-896-3247), Randol's (318-981-7080) and the original Don's
Seafood and Steak House (318-235-3551), all in or just north of
Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Prejean's menu can be mind-boggling:
</P>
<P>
   Starters include a mini-eggplant wheel, fried and topped with
three garlic shrimp and draped with a creamy au gratin sauce; a
``Whistling Dixie venison'' tenderloin mesquite-grilled, set in
brown butter shiitake wine sauce and sprinkled with oven-roasted
pine nuts; and popcorn crawfish tails dipped in sherry wine sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Entrees include pepper-crusted Colorado elk served in an
Andouille and chanterelle mushroom sauce and white alligator tail
meat wrapped around crab and shrimp and served with macque choux
and dirty rice.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenge saving room for Acadian bread pudding served
with Jack Daniel's butter sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Favorites at Enola Prudhomme's Cajun Cafe include catfish
courtboullion, eggplant pirogue and low-fat entrees _ among them
chicken tomato basil, shrimp fettucine and grilled or sauteed
catfish fillet _ featured in cookbooks authored by Paul Prudhomme's
sister.
</P>
<P>
   The Lafayette Convention and Visitors Bureau can supply
brochures that point the way to these and numerous other
Cajun-oriented eateries. Or to restaurants that focus on French,
Italian, Chinese and other cuisines. Call 800-346-1958; or access
http://www.lafayettetravel.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
