<HEADER>
A2001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAJUN-EVANGELINE-HNS &LR;      09-24 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAJUN-EVANGELINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL CAJUN TOWN BEARS REMNANTS OF FACT, LEGEND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark is needed over first e in Derangement, over
first e in Jerome, and over second e in Bebe) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. MARTINVILLE, La. _ Come hear the stories of this little town
on Bayou Teche.
</P>
<P>
   Some of its tales are fact, others merely myth. Many likely are
a combination of the two. All are worth sharing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ACADIAN MEMORIAL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the newest attractions in Louisiana's sixth oldest city _
situated about a 30-minute drive southeast of Lafayette _ is the
Acadian Memorial, where a plaque reminds visitors that ``a people
without a past are a people without a future.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of this memorial is a 12-foot-by-30-foot mural
by Robert Dafford titled ``The Arrival of the Acadians in
Louisiana.''
</P>
<P>
   The mural recalls one of the happier-ending tales of pioneer
America: the Acadians' _ or ``Acadie,'' as they called themselves _
first settlement in the French colony of Louisiana after being
ousted by the British from their rich farmlands in what is now Nova
Scotia, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands among the exiled died on overcrowded ships. The
survivors became outcasts in cities along the Atlantic coast. Many
fled back to France, where as defiant refugees from a strange land
they were even more unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually they began gathering in Louisiana. The first group
arrived in 1765, having begun their journey in Nantes, France.
</P>
<P>
   The mural depicts scores of immigrants arriving into a promising
world of moss-laden trees and life-giving waterways. Among the
crowd are 39 figures who represent actual Acadians. The mural takes
liberty with history, though, depicting many who arrived years
apart and settled throughout the area. In many cases, direct
descendants of the Acadians modeled for Dafford.
</P>
<P>
   Among the figures represented: Jean Baptiste Semer and Joseph
Semer, father and son who were separated for more than 30 years;
Olivier Terriot, a shoemaker in Nantes who recruited more than
1,500 Acadians to travel to Louisiana; and Olivier Benoit, whose
off-course ship made him one of the first ``Texas Cajuns.''
</P>
<P>
   An exhibit lists about 3,000 Acadian refugees whose names have
been culled from early Louisiana records. The memorial's research
center hopes to be a starting point for people interested in
genealogical information.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EVANGELINE OAK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One story that came from the early days of Acadian immigration
to Louisiana is that of the Evangeline Oak.
</P>
<P>
   According to legend, a young ``Acadie'' named Evangeline was
separated from her betrothed during ``Le Grand Derangement.'' After
years of searching, she finally found her betrothed, who had in her
absence married another. Evangeline died of a broken heart while
sitting beneath the huge oak.
</P>
<P>
   That's the legend. The real story is just as tragic.
</P>
<P>
   Emmeline Labiche and her fiance, Louis Arceneaux, were placed on
separate ships during the exile. Both eventually made their way to
Louisiana, but Emmeline arrived _ still toting a wedding gown _
three years after Louis. Her appearance was greeted with news of
Louis's marriage to another. Exhausted and brokenhearted, Emmeline
died just a few months after arriving in St. Martinville. She is
believed to be buried in a plot behind the nearby St. Martin de
Tours Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   This story might have died with the early Acadians had it not
been the inspiration of Henry Wadsworth Longfellow's long narrative
poem ``Evangeline.'' In Longfellow's version, Evangeline arrives in
St. Martinville just a day behind her lover, Gabriel. She sets out
to find him but is sadly unsuccessful. The two are finally united
years later when Evangeline, now a nun, and Gabriel share an
embrace as he dies of the plague.
</P>
<P>
   Its huge branches stretching in all directions, the Evangeline
Oak is one of the most popular stops in Acadiana. A small visitors
center is located in the park that surrounds the tree. Nearly every
day, those who pause beside the Evangeline Oak are entertained by
the Romero Brothers. Lennis Romero is 81, and his accordion-playing
brother Ophe, also known as Bebe, is in his late 70s.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers perform traditional French music in the park six
days a week. They work for tips and genuinely enjoy the attention
of camera-toting, hand-clapping tourists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PETIT PARIS MUSEUM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to separate fact from myth in some of the tales at
the Petit Paris Museum.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the small museum is a splashy collection of
elaborate Mardi Gras costumes and the story of a rich, eccentric
plantation owner named Jerome Charles Durand.
</P>
<P>
   There are many stories about the colorful Durand, an extravagant
man who married twice.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife died after bearing him 12 children. In his grief,
he erected a monument that showed him crying beside his wife's
tomb; an inscription vowed that he would never love again. But
Durand married his second wife within the year. The second Mrs.
Durand bore him 12 children as well, because he felt it was
important to be fair to both his wives.
</P>
<P>
   That story is well-known, but the most-oft-told tale about
Durand is that of the Spider Web Wedding.
</P>
<P>
   In 1870, two of Durand's daughters accepted marriage proposals
from fine young men. Durand immediately made plans for an elaborate
double ceremony at his sugar-cane plantation.
</P>
<P>
   The plantation had a three-mile alley of pine and oak trees,
which Durand had planted years earlier. Several days before the
wedding, plantation hands released large spiders into the trees.
For days, the spiders wove enormous webs, many of which linked the
trees.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the wedding, the workers used bellows filled
with gold and silver dust to ``paint'' the cobwebs. A shimmering
canopy awaited the wedding guests. There were dancing and long
tables covered with food under the trees until dusk. Fireworks
capped the expensive celebration.
</P>
<P>
   A re-creation of the Spider Web Wedding is the main exhibit at
the Petit Paris Museum. Each year the St. Martinville Rotary Club
hosts a Mardi Gras Ball. The Spider Web Wedding was the theme for
Mardi Gras in 1984, and the elaborate, handmade costumes created
for the ball are presented here.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to the museum is St. Martin de Tours Catholic Church,
established in 1765. The building, which features French
chandeliers and a replica of the Grotto of Lourdes, was completed
in 1844.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the church is a statue of an American Indian, who is
wearing a skirt. Not a loincloth but a skirt.
</P>
<P>
   It's just another St. Martinville story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
