<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2014 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAJUN-LAND-2NDTAKE-AR     09-24 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAJUN-LAND-2NDTAKE-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURAL TOURISM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
LAFAYETTE, La.: into their cars.'''
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was, and is, no Big Boudin amusement ride. But we discover
a Cajun Haven or Cajun Way or Cajun Mart in almost every southwest
Louisiana hamlet. Swamp tours promise close-up encounters with live
alligators; Prudhomme clones _ some highly skilled, others mere
imitators _ deliver alligator on a plate. Other tours provide
insight into the making of Tabasco at Avery Island, Tony Chachere's
seasonings in Opelousas and Konriko Rice in New Iberia. Almost
every weekend, a festival celebrates Cajun cuisine, Cajun arts and
crafts, Cajun music or Cajun humor.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's clear that these Acadians, both as cordial hosts and
savvy entrepreneurs, have figured out what to do with us. But not
without a period of adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   When tour buses began arriving, Ancelet says, ``The first
question people would ask was, `Where do I go to meet some Cajuns?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say, `Oh, I don't know, maybe you could go get your hair
cut or your flat fixed. You find us in the normal places people go
in their everyday lives. We don't have a zoo for us yet.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We had all these people suddenly coming here from New York and
New Jersey and Pennsylvania, and they had no idea what to do. So
the tour bus took them to a dance hall, and they loved the music
and had a good time. And the dance-hall owner thought it was great,
too, because the place was full and the tourists were buying a lot
of beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the regular customers _ the people who had been coming to
the dance hall every week for years _ were pushed against the wall.
Then, the next week, the tour bus wasn't there, and the regulars
weren't there either because they didn't have such a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, residents and tourists mingle easily on dance floors at
Randol's and Prejean's restaurants in Lafayette and at scores of
other establishments throughout the region. But there is a
significant lesson in this learning process, suggests Ancelet:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cultural tourism comes at a price,''he says. ``People are no
different from our natural forests in that we have to be very
careful not to trample what we come to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, when we talk about cultural tourism, one thing
we've learned is that we are dealing primarily with smart people.
They've usually read in advance about the things (and people) they
visit. They are eager to engage in intelligent conversations, eager
to learn. They are not cultural polluters, especially if they're
well-guided.''
</P>
<P>
   And, says Ancelet, ``We want them to have a good experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RESPECT FOR TRADITION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly any ``good experience'' incurred here can be
attributed in large part to the Cajun philosophy of living every
moment to the fullest. ``Laissez les bons temps rouler,'' people
proclaim. Let the good times roll.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Acadians' savor the present, their respect for
tradition is unwavering.
</P>
<P>
   Conque makes a living telling Boudreaux-and-Thibodeaux jokes:
``Ralph Boudreaux is a good friend of mine, and he told me that any
time I'm in his hometown of Maurice to come see him day and
night,'' Conque tells audiences. ``So I knocked on his door at 2
o'clock in the morning, and his wife answered and I said, `Ma'am, I
know it's late, but is this where the great Ralph Boudreaux lives?'
And she said, `Yeah, if he's drunk again just bring him in and lay
him on the couch.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Boudreaux are fictional, though. ``I was driving down
the street the other day and saw a sign that read, `Boudreaux and
Son Lumber Yard,''' Conque says, ``and it struck me that I don't
often see that kind of family recognition today in other places I
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cajun family life is special. Our family bonds and our
friendships are close-knit, and again I think it goes back to our
forefathers. They had to stick together; it's all they had. We
still value that sense of togetherness.''
</P>
<P>
   Cajuns still value the language, too. More than 260,000
Louisianans speak a form of French either brought to New Orleans by
French nobility or to the bayous and prairies by Acadians.
Speculation is that Cajun French has survived, albeit with
linguistic changes, largely because of years of isolation and low
economic status and the family structure.
</P>
<P>
   Several venues provide rich insight into the Cajun heritage.
Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Jean Lafitte National Historical Park and Preserve's
Acadian Cultural Center in Lafayette features extensive exhibits
and artifacts. A 40-minute video chronicles the deportation from
Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearby, Vermilionville _ the original name for Lafayette _
authentically re-creates an 18th- and 19th-century Cajun and Creole
village with a series of dwellings, some dating back 200 years.
Costumed guides direct tours that introduce spinners, a quilter,
wood carvers, basket weavers and a blacksmith. Cooking schools and
musical entertainment are other features.
</P>
<P>
   _ Acadian Village, a folk-life museum surrounded by gardens and
woodlands on the outskirts of Lafayette, also displays homes,
stores and other landmarks of original Cajuns and Creoles.
</P>
<P>
   _ The University Art Museum and Alexandre Mouton House-Lafayette
Museum each provides diverse cultural exhibits. Small but
informative museums and workshops are found in many other
communities.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday evenings in Eunice, northwest of Lafayette, the
Liberty Theater, a 1924 movie house, is home to a live
French-speaking radio and television show hosted by Ancelet.
</P>
<P>
   The show features two hours of Cajun and Zydeco music (though
Cajuns favor both, each has distinct characteristics, with Zydeco
emphasizing a ``frottoir,'' or washboard) and humor in the Grand
Ole Opry style.
</P>
<P>
   Next year Francofete '99 will commemorate 300 years of French
influence, with considerable emphasis on Acadian history and
culture. Events are scheduled throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Cajuns hardly need an excuse to party. To dance. To
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have another friend named Pistache Babineaux, the lawyer,''
Conque is still regaling his luncheon audience, ``and Pistache got
a phone call the other day from a man at Angola State Prison who
said, `Mr. Babineaux, I'm on death row, and in one hour they're
going to execute me in the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   ```You got some advice for me?'
</P>
<P>
   ```Yeah,' Pistache said. ``Don't sit down.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pistache could well have added, ``Lache pas la patate.'' Never
give up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
