<HEADER>
A2020 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAJUN-LAND-2TAKES-ART     09-24 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAJUN-LAND-2TAKES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO OTHER PLACE QUITE LIKE CAJUN COUNTRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Art available on NYT photo service) 
(Eds.: Accent marks needed over first e and second e in etouffee) 
 
 &HT;    ``Hey! Y'all got a flat tire?''
 &HT;    ``Naw, we were just riding around, and them other three swole up
on us.''
 &HT;    _ Acadian humorist Murray Conque
 &HT;     
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   LAFAYETTE, La. _ Our travels are inspired by diverse pursuits:
an appreciation for natural wonders and wildlife, a passion for
music and the arts, a quest for adventure, a desire to step back in
time.
</P>
<P>
   All these objectives _ and more _ are easily satisfied, too,
amid the murky swamps and bayous, the historical homes and gardens,
the spirited dance halls and food parlors of southwest Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt, however, what the single most-defining
characteristic within this fascinating slice of Americana is:
</P>
<P>
   It's the people. A people with an unfailing zest for life. Men
and women who treasure a rib-tickling joke, even if it's at their
own expense; who cherish a lovingly prepared meal accented by
conversation as free-flowing as the wine and as well-seasoned as
the crawfish gumbo; who step sprightly into the wee hours,
intoxicated by the beat of an accordion or fiddle.
</P>
<P>
   A people forever determined to infuse that elusive ``lagniappe''
_ signifying ``a little something extra'' in the distinct Cajun
French dialect _ into every element of their existence.
</P>
<P>
   But also a proud people whose heartfelt affection for each other
and genuine warmth toward guests is borne in large part by
generations of oppression and sacrifice and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lache pas la patate,'' they tell us. The literal translation:
Don't let go of the potato. The meaning here: Never give up.
</P>
<P>
   This is Cajun country. There is no other place quite like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our food is different; our humor is different; our people are
different,'' says Murray Conque, part-time insurance salesman,
part-time major-league baseball scout and a past champion in the
annual International Cajun Joke-Telling Contest in Opelousas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My home town of Carencro is so small that our phone book only
has one yellow page,'' Conque delights a luncheon audience
assembled from all over North America. ``But we're finally getting
our first traffic light,'' he continues. ``Everybody in Carencro is
so excited; they've already picked out the colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Much later, far removed from the crowd, Conque reflects on the
roots of his humor. ``Our forefathers were thrown out of France and
thrown out of Canada,'' he says. ``They came down here with nothing
except their pride and love of family and their ability to laugh at
whatever life threw at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like them, we work hard. We play hard. But we never forget how
to stop and laugh with and at each other. And we love sharing our
laughter with our guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know, the stories we tell could almost be true.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter where we pause _ on a guided boat excursion through
the Atchafalaya basin, at a Friday night Downtown Alive!
celebration in Lafayette, mingling with ``ghosts'' at beautiful
Chretien Point Plantation B&AMP;B in Sunset, feasting on crawfish
touffe at a re-creation of an early Acadian village _ good humor
pervades.
</P>
<P>
   And locals and visitors mesh almost as if they have been friends
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, cultural tourism, as travel industry professionals label
this phenomenon, thrives today in Cajun country. Especially for
those who take the time to learn about the rich Acadian heritage.
And about how we came to appreciate each other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A TRAGIC HISTORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Acadians' long and tragic path to southwest Louisiana dates
to 1604 when they began migrating from rural homes in western
France to Acadie, now Nova Scotia in eastern Canada.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, they prospered as farmers and
fisherman. But in the early 1700s, Britain gained control of Acadie
from France, and the Acadians were trapped in a power struggle
between two strong nations. Ordered to declare allegiance to
Britain, they refused.
</P>
<P>
   In 1755, the British, in what became known as ``The Grand
Derangement,'' began removing Acadians from their adopted homeland,
dispersing them to British colonies along the East Coast and in the
Caribbean and Europe. Six thousand Acadians put out to sea in small
boats; almost half perished from typhoid, smallpox or other
diseases. Hundreds more escaped deportation by hiding in the woods,
only to die of starvation. Those who arrived in the colonies were
unexpected and _ as devoted French Catholics _ unwelcome. They
languished in misery.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, survivors set sail again, bound this time for a
new Louisiana territory then under Spanish rule. They brought few
material possessions _ only a blossoming culture and language that
blended French, Celtic, Scotch-Irish and American Indian
influences.
</P>
<P>
   Joining other displaced descendants of Africans, West Indians,
Europeans and American Indians known as Creoles, they settled in
the wetlands west of New Orleans, fishing and hunting for survival,
and on prairies where they raised cotton, rice, sugar cane and
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Some eventually returned to Canada, where another Acadian
culture now thrives on Cape Breton Island in Nova Scotia. But their
Louisiana numbers continued to expand.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even as they emerged into a respected and important
segment of the Louisiana population, most Cajuns _ as the name
evolved _ lived happily and modestly in relative obscurity until
the past few decades.
</P>
<P>
   Until Justin Wilson began spinning yarns on national television.
Until Cajun music became a hit at venues nationwide. Until Paul
Prudhomme and Emeril _ ``Bam! Let's kick it up another notch'' _
Lagasse started cooking. Until New Englanders began dribbling
Tabasco sauce on their lobster.
</P>
<P>
   And until the construction of Interstate 10 provided millions of
travelers easy access over the Atchafalaya swamp and into the heart
of Cajun country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Gov. Edwin Edwards signed a bill designating a
22-parish (county) area as Acadiana, with Lafayette at its
geographic heart.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Ancelet, professor of French and folklore at the
University of Southwestern Louisiana in Lafayette, remembers well
the outside world's initial mass discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '80s, we began stressing what we called our
cultural system,'' Ancelet says. ``All of a sudden, people weren't
coming here to Louisiana just to see geysers or forests; they were
coming to see us. And we started to realize that when they find us,
we ought to try to figure out what to do with them so they don't
end up in our living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people wanted to start a Cajunland theme park,'' Ancelet
says. ``I just shook my head and said, `Yeah, let's put it at the
corner of Interstates 10 and 49 (the area's busiest intersection).'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `When people are ready to leave Cajunland, we'll just
put them on a ride called the Big Boudin that will squeeze them
through a giant tube and into their cars.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
