<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Sept. 24, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
    NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON-FUNDRAISING (San Francisco) _ For Democratic candidates
needing fundraising help for the last six weeks of the campaign,
there's only one name to turn to: Clinton. Hillary Clinton, that
is. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVE-HOMICIDES (San Francisco) _ While he wrestled with the
financial difficulties of his software company, Vladimir Pokhilko
was apparently pushed to the edge, Pokhilko brutally murdered his
38-year-old wife, Elena Fedotova, and their 12-year-old son, Peter
Pokhilko, before killing himself, according to police. By MATT BEER
and JACOB FRIES.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-PROMOTION (San Francisco) _ Putting an end to what he
deems the ``worst form of false kindness,'' California Gov. Pete
Wilson has signed legislation ending so-called social promotion of
students. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   MARIJUANA-PAIN (San Francisco) _ A circuit in the brain stem
that is switched on and off by the active ingredient in marijuana
is the latest in a mounting pile of scientific evidence pointing to
the drug's ability to kill pain, according to a new study. By
ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   BODE-OBIT (San Antonio) _ Mary Jane Bode, an award-winning
journalist, former Texas legislator and first female press
secretary for a statewide office in Texas, died at the age of 71.
By CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GONZALEZ-RETURNS (Washington) _ Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
returns to Congress after nearly a year-long absence due to
illness. Gonzalez, 82, is retiring at the end of the year after 19
terms in the House of Representatives. By JAIME CASTILLO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PENNY-PINCHERS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Money 2000 is a modest Cornell
Cooperative Extension program that helps participants nationwide
set a goal of saving $2,000, or reducing their debt by that amount,
by the year 2000. Money 2000 methods are purposely simple and
realistic, participants in the program say. By MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BAY-AREA-ECONOMY (San Francisco) _ The Bay Area managed to
squeeze out some good economic news amid stock market turmoil,
military base closures and Asian financial woes, according to new
survey. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'')
</P>
<P>
   MAKEUP (San Francisco) _ Makeup is the form that follows
fashion. And fashion this fall is very, very gray and luxuriously
textured. Cashmere on suede. Crushed velvets. Menswear stripes with
lace. Sequins glinting quietly under organza. The clothes are also
deceptively simple, mostly linear takeoffs on American sportswear,
gussied up in luxury fabrics. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION (San Francisco) _ San Francisco designer Jessica
McClintock has come a long way from dimity-and-lace empire hippie
dresses like the one Hillary Rodham was married in. But her focus
has remained the same _ romantic dresses for young women. By
CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAGIC-CRUISE (Aboard the Disney Magic) _ When it comes to the
family Caribbean cruise, Disney is, well, Magic. The ship Magic has
the look and feel of the great ocean liners of the 1930s.
Reportedly, a classic look was demanded by Disney chairman Michael
Eisner _ and he got it. Yet there are disappointments, including
the food and service. By JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNT-KATAHDIN (Mount Katahdin, Maine) _ Since early times,
artists and writers have sought to capture the mystique of this
great mass. Unlike native Americans who respected the mountain
spirits and stayed away, 19th-century white men set foot on
Katahdin, then encouraged other adventurers to join them. By FRED
STETSON.
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-LAND (Lafayette, La.) _ A look at Cajun life and its
people. A people with an unfailing zest for life. Men and women who
treasure a rib-tickling joke, even if it's at their own expense;
who cherish a lovingly prepared meal accented by conversation as
free-flowing as the wine and as well-seasoned as the crawfish
gumbo; who step sprightly into the wee hours, intoxicated by the
beat of an accordion or fiddle. By HARRY SHATTUCK (Photo available
on NYT photo service)
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-DINING (Lafayette, La.) _ Think Cajun food, and the
prevailing images for many people are blackened catfish, gumbo,
boudin, jambalaya and spicy fried shrimp. You can find the best of
each in southwest Louisiana. By HARRY SHATTUCK (Photo available on
NYT photo service)
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-WILDLIFE (New Iberia, La.) _ With its diverse habitats and
mild winters, southwest Louisiana brims with natural wonders, both
flora and fauna. By SYD KEARNEY (Photo available on NYT photo
service)
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-EVANGELINE (St. Martinville, La.) _ Come hear the stories
of this little town on Bayou Teche. Some of its tales are fact,
others merely myth. Many likely are a combination of the two. All
are worth sharing. By SYD KEARNEY
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-COUNTRY (Undated) _ A listing of where to go and what to
do when you go to Acadiana. Compiled by SYD KEARNEY and HARRY
SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Thanks to the
Clinton-Lewinsky-Starr-Drudge-CNN-MSNBC gang, this nation is one
big hostile environment. Out at Candlestick on Wednesday a guy kept
telling the jokes of the moment, including one about President
Clinton wearing a pair of panties on his sleeve. A reporter asks
why, and Clinton says it's like the patch _ he's trying to quit. By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEWS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Like a prisoner scraping X's on
his cell wall, the president of the United States would check off
the calendar days he could not be with ``other women.'' This
graphic picture of Bill Clinton's dual life is among the more
arresting of 2,800 pages of material collected by the independent
counsel and released by the House Judiciary Committee. By
CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Ever since 1972, when I was a
new reporter at Sports Illustrated magazine and the annual swimsuit
issue came out, I have wished I had a huge button to wear on
certain occasions. The button would say: I DON'T MAKE POLICY, I
JUST WORK HERE. This past Monday, a giant sandwich board would have
been more in order. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   HUMANE-TREATMENT (Washington) _ In the Humane Society's view,
requiring students to engage in practices harmful to animals is
unfair to students and inhumane to animals. Change, especially when
it involves an established tradition like dissection, doesn't come
easily. But it doesn't come at all until someone is ready to rock
the boat. By JONATHAN BALCOMBE.
</P>
</TEXT>
