<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-MAGIC-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY MAGIC DOESN'T ALWAYS LIVE UP TO ITS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE DISNEY MAGIC _ Maybe the best thing about this
brand-new, 85,000-ton, 2,400-passenger ship is the cabin bathroom,
er, head.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are gleaming teak decks, the ESPN sports bar, Palo's
adults-only restaurant, a colorful comedy and Western-themed dance
club and, of course, Mickey Mouse's likeness.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``bath and a half'' in my cabin made a lasting
impression. The two-room john with a toilet/sink and
sink/shower/tub combination can be found in most of the 875 cabins
on the $350 million Magic. The generous bathroom space is unusual
in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention that the cabins also are 25 percent bigger than
industry average, and 75 percent are outside cabins.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the family Caribbean cruise, Disney is, well,
Magic.
</P>
<P>
   The ship Magic has the look and feel of the great ocean liners
of the 1930s. Reportedly, a classic look was demanded by Disney
chairman Michael Eisner _ and he got it.
</P>
<P>
   Even the music that wafts through the ship takes you back. Any
minute you expect Fred and Ginger to come gliding by. Then Kenee
Ledford in the Sessions lounge plays ``Night and Day'' on the grand
piano, and the mood is sealed.
</P>
<P>
   While adults enjoy the popular hangout, one of several on the
ship, the kids can immerse themselves in Disney's Oceaneer Club
(3-to-8-year-olds) or the Oceaneer Lab (9-12).
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty on board to keep the kids busy. This is Disney,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Activities for the 3-12 set begin around noon and last until
midnight. Teens can enjoy the run of the ship or enjoy music videos
and games in Common Grounds, a coffee and music bar. Pagers are
provided so parents can keep in contact.
</P>
<P>
   At Mickey's Children's Pool on Deck 9, a lifeguard named Mary is
watching the kids come down the water slide. Only small fry _ ages
4 to 12 _ can use the slide, and the water is shallow. There also
are Goofy's Family Pool and the Quiet Cove Adult Pool.
</P>
<P>
   While the kids are kept busy in organized activities, Mom and
Dad can wander the ship. Finding the way around isn't too hard, not
like the new class of megaships that other cruise lines are
churning out.
</P>
<P>
   Guests get a ``Magic Passport'' and a ``Guide to Magic'' that
answers questions and includes maps. A ``Personal Navigator'' is
provided with a daily list of activities on board.
</P>
<P>
   Want to see a first-run movie or play bingo for prizes? How
about checking out the shops or watching a big-big screen game in
the ESPN Skybox? Tough choices, especially on a short cruise.
</P>
<P>
   For entertainment, there is a wide variety found on Beat Street.
Off Beat has a coed improv troupe from the Midwest and a 1970s
retro decor. The Rockin' Bar D rotates live rock 'n' roll with
country music for the dancers. Jazz fans will gravitate to the
Promenade Lounge, where a stylish trio mixes it up with a vocalist.
</P>
<P>
   The whole family can dance to top-40 tunes at Studio Sea, which
doubles as a TV game show set for daytime entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Three Broadway-type musicals take turns on stage at the Walt
Disney Theater, three times a night. ``Hercules _ A Muse-ical
Comedy,'' ``Voyage of the Ghost Ship'' and ``Disney Dreams'' are
all G-rated. The swashbuckling hero-meets-the-princess story of
``Ghost Ship'' has special effects, but not enough to keep the
small ones glued to their seats or the older folks from yawning.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the Disney feeling is too much, such as when the
ship's horn blasts the opening lines to ``When You Wish Upon a
Star.'' You don't want to be sitting around the pool deck when it
blows because it is LOUD.
</P>
<P>
   While Mickey's physical presence is limited _ having a picture
taken with embarking passengers and joining Minnie for a stroll
around deck _ his likeness is found in many places, from the soap
in the cabin baths to the mouse-ear shape on walls and light
fixtures. Just as at Walt Disney World, there are a multitude of
tie-ins with other Disney products and films.
</P>
<P>
   Lumiere's, the main dining room, has a ``Beauty and the Beast''
theme complete with roses under glass on the tables. The
restaurant's motto may be ``A dinner here is never second best,''
but neither the service nor the food was very impressive. The menu
of seafood platters, ravioli, lamb and sirloin was uninspiring and
sometimes inedible. It certainly wasn't the ``exquisite continental
cuisine with a French flair'' touted in the publicity materials.
</P>
<P>
   The Animators Palace restaurant was praised for the quality of
the food and the special effects; the black-and-white room
eventually comes to life as a color palette.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   At Parrot Cay, the theme is Caribbean, and Jimmy Buffett music
permeates. Palo's, a Northern Italian restaurant for adults only,
requires reservations and you can't make those in advance of
sailing. A $5 per person charge is added for Palo's dining.
</P>
<P>
   Rotation dining guarantees that you will sample three of the
dining rooms, and the wait staff moves with you. (This makes it
easy come tipping time.) For casual dining or lunch, there is the
buffet at Topsiders, Pluto's Dog House, Pinocchio's Pizzeria (it
tastes like frozen pizza) and Scoops Ice Cream. There also is
24-hour room service with a menu limited to eight items.
</P>
<P>
   Another adult experience is the Vista Spa &AMP; Salon. Passengers
aboard the first few cruises stampeded the spa, snapping up the
reservations the minute they boarded, so now the reservations desk
opens at 3 p.m. Offerings include massages, aromatherapy, sauna,
steam room and facials (all treatments cost extra).
</P>
<P>
   The first stop for Magic is Nassau, where there is an abundance
of real Bahamian excursions to sample _ casinos, fishing,
snorkeling, scuba tours, the Straw Market, Crystal Cay Marine Park
and the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Castaway Cay, the private Bahamian island that Disney has
developed, is the last stop on the cruise. The island might have
been the brainchild of Gilligan, if only he had been an idea man.
It's Sea World's Lost Lagoon, only bigger _ 1,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Imagineers came up with the idea that a crew of
oceanographic explorers chasing a giant whale settled on the island
with their families. There's an air of 1940s nostalgia, with old
prop planes on the landing strip.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Durham, senior development manager for Disney Imagineering,
developed 55 acres on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The island, which houses 30 to 35 full-time Disney employees,
will be a model eco-resort with recycling or ``clean''
incineration.
</P>
<P>
   Durham's favorite spot? ``Heads-Up Bar, you get to see
everything else,'' Durham says.
</P>
<P>
   During a typical eight-hour stop at the island, visitors can
rent a bike ($5), a Kargo Kart or stroller ($5), a float ($5) or
just lie on the sandy beach. There also are sailboats, kayaks,
paddle boats, rafts and inflatable motorboats for rent. Eventually,
fishing charters will be added.
</P>
<P>
   Castaway Cay is divided into family, teen and adult beach areas.
Parents will be happy to see so many lifeguards on duty, both on
shore and out in the water on floating lifeguard chairs/stands.
</P>
<P>
   Beach-side bands play island music _ heavy on the Buffett songs
again _ and dining is buffet-style with sheltered picnic tables at
Cookie's Bar-B-Q. There also are beach bars and roaming wait staff
selling water ($1.95) and sodas ($1.50).
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who missed a massage at Vista Spa &AMP; Salon might want to
book one in one of the cabanas at Castaway Cay (massages do cost
extra).
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about carrying cash on board the Magic or at
Castaway Cay; there is a plastic guest card (the Key to the World
card) that not only serves as cabin key, but works as a credit
card. Luckily, parents can put a dollar limit so the kids don't OD
on sodas or video games. The card works the same way at Walt Disney
World resort as part of the seven-day cruise/land package.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Magic, which departs from Port Canaveral, Fla., is
sailing at 100 percent capacity, says Amy Foley, manager of public
relations, but travel agents are holding many blocks and
re-selling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information, prices and reservations for the Disney Magic
contact your travel agent or Disney Cruise Lines, 210 Celebration
Place, Celebration, FL 34747-4600; 407-566-3500. The Web site is
www.disney.com/DisneyCruise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
