<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPING THE MEDIA MIASMA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On the day the U.S. news media lost their
collective mind, I made a brief stop at my office, ran out the
door, jumped into my car and tried to get as far away from
journalism as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Like every other mainstream newspaper and every large radio and
TV network in this country, my newspaper had prepared for the day
as though World War III had begun: Strategy sessions. Extra
personnel. Early starting times. Staff on red alert.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, it was not World War III. It was instead the
public airing of a 4-hour-and-3-minute videotape of the president
of the United States testifying before a grand jury about an
extramarital affair he had with a woman over the age of consent.
</P>
<P>
   Heading across the Golden Gate Bridge, I listened on my car
radio to the last 20 minutes of the president's testimony. When it
was over, two reporters talked about how he hadn't blown up, lost
his cool or stomped out of the room as had been widely rumored _
and reported. When legal ``analysts'' began to dissect the
testimony, I switched to a classical music station.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, a treasured friend and I sat down at an outdoor
table, overlooking a picturesque little town square. When our
waitress asked, ``How are you folks today?'' I said, ``We're great.
We're not watching any videotapes.''
</P>
<P>
   The waitress narrowed her eyes and put her hands on her hips.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got up today, I turned on the TV like I always do while
I'm getting ready for work,'' she said. ``But I had only two
choices: That video or `Sesame Street.' I picked `Sesame Street.'
God, the media make me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the effect it might have on poverty, homelessness,
cancer research, relations with China, teen suicide, gender pay
inequities, the disintegrating ruble, the disappearing ozone layer
or public schools if the nation's entire news media focused solely
upon that one subject for four straight hours on a weekday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But, no. As if all life and freedom depended upon it, mainstream
journalism chose to spend four hours _ uninterrupted by commercials
_ on a married man's account of a half-baked affair.
</P>
<P>
   After my lunch, in which my friend and I turned our backs on
Monica and Bill and talked of such trifles as Kant, Catholicism,
God, compassion and love, I drove a few miles to visit another
treasured friend. A retired editor, this man knows more about
journalism than any 50 people in any American newsroom today.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, how much do you miss the biz on a day like this?'' I
asked.
</P>
<P>
   The man cackled and began an angry but erudite diatribe that
lasted nearly 30 minutes. One by one, he shot down every offered
rationale for the wild excess of news coverage we have witnessed
over the last several months.
</P>
<P>
   His best shot was this: ``They keep saying, `We're not covering
this because of the sex but because he's the president and he
lied,''' the editor said. ``The lying makes it a big story. OK.
Fine. Let me ask you this: Let's say Clinton's doctors tell him he
shouldn't eat any more cheeseburgers. They're bad for him and
they'll make him fat. Clinton stands up and gives a big speech
vowing never to eat cheeseburgers again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, along comes Monica. She says, `Hey, you know you love
cheeseburgers. Go ahead. Just once in awhile. I'll make them for
you. Nobody ever has to know, it's just between us.' Clinton starts
eating cheeseburgers, but any time he's asked, he lies and says he
isn't. You still interested in that story? You going to put it on
A-1? Is Sam Donaldson going to stand up at every news conference
and ask the president about cheeseburgers? Why not? This story is
big because of the lying, not the sex, right?''
</P>
<P>
   As I said, the editor is retired from journalism. On Monday
night, that status never looked more attractive to me.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
