r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATTHEWS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-24 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTHEWS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL CLINTON'S CHECKERED COUNTDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like a prisoner scraping X's on his cell wall, the
president of the United States would check off the calendar days he
could not be with ``other women.''
</P>
<P>
   This graphic picture of Bill Clinton's dual life is among the
more arresting of 2,800 pages of material collected by Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr and released this week by the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president told Lewinsky that it was difficult for him to
resist being with other women ... that he kept a calendar on how
long he had been good. The president explained that during his life
he had been two people, and kept up two fronts, that starting in
the third or fourth grade he was a good boy with his mother and
stepfather, but also began telling stories and leading a secret
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The question for the U.S. Congress this autumn of discontent is
whether that ``secret life'' can ever be truly separated from the
public life of the president or the country. Can we entrust Bill
Clinton, commander in chief, to send men to their deaths in battle
overseas knowing his deceit on a matter so close to home? Can we
trust Clinton's ``secret life'' not to jump out and scuttle, as it
has these past nine months, his on-camera performance?
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Hillary Clinton argue we can. History argues otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that the minute there was no longer any contact, she
would talk about this. She would have to. She couldn't help it. It
was ... part of her psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I put myself at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the president sharing with grand jurors his dread
premonition that the young West Wing employee with whom he'd struck
up a relationship would one day loom before him as a terrifying,
real-life antagonist straight out of ``Fatal Attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he sensed from the outset that Monica would ``talk,'' why
did he risk it? Why did he begin an affair so dangerous that he
would feel compelled to lie about it under oath?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advocates will say that he was simply unlucky _
unlucky to become involved with someone who would tell at least 11
people about her presidential affair, unfortunate to face
adversaries so ruthless they would tape Monica telling her story,
an independent counsel so goody-two-shoes that he'd nail him for
perjury in a sex matter.
</P>
<P>
   But what a streak of bad luck! First, Gennifer Flowers goes to
the Star _ a tabloid in this case _ with her hot story of Little
Rock love. Then came Paula Jones with her lawsuit. Then came
Kathleen Willey with an account of Oval Office harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Why, we have to ask, does Clinton's sex life merge so
continually with his public life? If he wanted to keep affairs away
from the office, why has he continued to forge ahead with them at
the office? If he believes his sex life is none of our business,
then why does he so predictably make it part of his?
</P>
<P>
   ``Humpty Dumpty had a great fall,'' goes the nursery rhyme,
``and all the king's horses and all the king's men couldn't put
Humpty together again.''
</P>
<P>
   The question before us now is whether we can ever pull the two
Bill Clintons _ the official and the ``secret'' _ apart again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Matthews is the Washington bureau chief for the San Francisco
Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
