as a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Clinton had been elected on the basis of his moral
credibility, many analysts contend, the blows to his leadership
might well be mortal.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bill Clinton was elected with people clearly knowing he had
moral failings, so this isn't a great shock,'' said Frank Newport,
editor in chief of the Gallup Poll. Its national surveys
consistently show that while many Americans 49 percent, according
to Gallup's latest poll of 631 adults taken Sept. 21 claim they
don't trust Clinton, a large majority 66 percent believe he's doing
his job well.
</P>
<P>
   That's the explanation for the gap between the personal
confidence the public claims to have, or not have, in the
president, and the polls suggesting that 66 percent, according to
