as they think he means well.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a reasonable person,'' said political scientist Terry
Sullivan. ''He is a likeable guy, he appears to be sincere and
genuine and he does tell us what is right and what is wrong and he
does tell us what we need to do as Americans, what we ought to be
doing if our better angels were running our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton exemplifies, ''leadership which is moral in intent it's
intent is to accomplish good things,'' said Sullivan, an associate
professor at the University of North Carolina in Chapel Hill. ''I
think that kind of moral leadership has a powerful influence on
most Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all that a nation asks of its leader, there may be no more
less forgiving a requirement than that they mirror those ''better
angels'' to which Sullivan refers. As Clinton has demonstrated,
perhaps even learned, Americans don't elect leaders to remind us of
our many shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, is it fair, is it even meaningful, for this country, a
sometimes morally-disoriented television nation largely inhabited
by an anything-goes culture that looks mostly to the Dow as a
measure of its collective worth, to hold Clinton to the gold
standard of presidential leadership?
</P>
<P>
   Or are we as nation simply fooling ourselves into believing that
personal character can truly be separated from the job of leading a
country that was, after all, founded upon a set of ideals, embodied
in the documents that bind us as one, enshrined in the faith of
generations now gone, and sanctified by the sacrifice of those who
gave, in the words of Abraham Lincoln, ''the last full measure of
devotion...that that nation might live.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
