<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-24 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDUMS: NATURE'S GIFT TO THE GARDENING-IMPAIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's important to always have something to look foward to in
the garden, the failure of one thing redressed by the success of
another,'' wrote Thomas Jefferson 200 years ago. This is especially
true in autumn, when the end of the growing year is nigh. Fall
conjures up asters and chrysanthemums and, more recently, sedum
``Autumn Joy,'' a workhorse that has become a goodwill ambassador
for its entire genus.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to find more obliging plants than sedums that are not
made of plastic. Still, they are an acquired taste. While lilies
nod and peonies billow, sedums seem to hunker down in the garden,
squat and solid. Even the celebrated ``Autumn Joy'' is a plant few
would fall in love with at first sight. But like the entertainer
Madonna, it keeps our interest by constantly changing appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The foliage emerges in early spring as a tight head of blue-gray
leaves. Through the summer the lengthening stalks suggest broccoli.
Even in its green phase, ``Autumn Joy'' complements ummer stars
like perovskia and globe thistle. In August, the flat flower heads
gradually assume a pink coloration that deepens into a showy
salmon-red through September, when they attract butterflies and
bees. In October they turn russet and finally chocolate as the
flowers morph into seedheads. If not removed, these remain standing
like a dried arrangement through most of the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the mid-'70s the Washington landscape firm Oehme,
van Sweden &AMP; Associates exploited this last characteristic by
combining drifts of ``Autumn Joy'' with black-eyed Susan and
ornamental grasses that also maintain attractive skeletons through
winter. This signature tableau offered four-season interest without
being static.
</P>
<P>
   The look was an instant hit and insured that both ``Autumn Joy''
and grasses such as miscanthus gracillimus, pennisetum, and
calmagrostis got a try-out in many American gardens. Home gardeners
gave the grasses mixed reviews, but ``Autumn Joy'' passed the
audition. Now people are looking for new types of sedums to try.
</P>
<P>
   The genus' biggest attraction is that these plants don't need
watering. Each fleshy succulent leaf stores water like a cactus.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are using a much wider range of sedums because they're
becoming interested in drought-tolerant plants. They lend
themselves to window boxes and all sorts of hot dry spots,'' said
Dianne Ford, mananger of Niche Gardens, a well-regarded mail-order
nursery in Chapel Hill, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Sedums also work well in coastal plantings where water quickly
drains away in sandy soil, according to Kathi Herrick, owner of
Rock Spray Nursery in Truro, Mass., which specializes in heaths and
heathers. ``Sedums are not great for erosion control or for
stepping on, and they're not salt-spray resistant, but they're
tough and durable in other respects, tolerating lack of water and
full sun.''
</P>
<P>
   In his definitive book ``Sedum: Cultivated Stonecrops'' (Timber
Press, 1995), Ray Stephenson says there 400 varieties in
cultivation. Most are not hardy in New England. California, with
it's plentitude of heat and dearth of water, is where sedums are
most popular in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a strong movement toward succulents in general on the
West Coast because the climate is milder here,'' said Jeff Cox, the
California-based author of 13 garden books and host of a cable-TV
show.
</P>
<P>
   Though New Englanders may have fewer sedums to chose from, there
are more available than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The hot newcomers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most sought-after newcomer is ``Frosty Morn,'' a striking 1
1/2-foot sedum with chalky white buds that open into white flowers
(in bloom now) on fleshy green leaves edged with white. Introduced
from Japan by plant explorer Barry Yinger a couple of years ago,
it's a mutant of Sedum alboroseum. It's especially effective
mulched with white or pinkish gravel, or planted in containers.
Like most sedums, it prefers sun and good drainage, but is
amazingly unfussy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matrona'' sedum, new from Germany, has a small red rim around
the edges of the foliage and is 3 feet tall. ``It will not last as
long in the seedhead stage as sedum `Autumn Joy,' but the stems
have a maroon tint. It's going to become popular in the next few
years,'' predicted Fred McGourty, who grows more than two dozen
kinds of sedums at Hillside Gardens, in Norfolk, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Not all new varieties are winners, of course. McGourty
scornfully describes a recent selection called ``Mohrchen'' as
``UPS truck brown'' in color. He has nothing but praise, however,
for 15-inch tall Sedum specacular ``Stardust'' with white fall
flowers in September and October.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, shorter sedums have also been overlooked. But
these are also fine for the front of the borders, as ground covers,
or in containers.
</P>
<P>
   McGourty calls Sedum sieboldii ``the October plant'' because
it's five-inch pink flowers bloom throughout that month. It is also
one of Herrick's favorites because of its disc-shaped leaves. Plant
this one where you can see it from a window, because you might not
be spending much time outdoors by then. The little round radiating
glaucous blue leaves are beautiful throughout the season,
especially planted around stone walls or with blue caryopteris or
Veronica ``Goodness Grows.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Sweden recommends sedum ``Ruby Glow.'' ``The color is
beautiful cascading over stones or crawling between rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all sedums bloom in the fall. There are also spring- and
early summer-blooming varieties, which tend to be low growing and
to have yellow flowers such as goldmoss stonecrop (Sedum acre).
</P>
<P>
   Sedm alboroseum ``Mediovariegatum,'' more easily called striped
sedum, has a gold to creamy-white center to each leaf. It flowers
white in early summer and looks best with blue-flowered companions.
As with ``Frosty Morn,'' you have to pick it over a couple of times
a year, cutting out any all-white or all-green shoots.
</P>
<P>
   Sedum spurium ``Dragon's Blood'' was the most widely grown sedum
until ``Autumn Joy'' came along. Only 3 inches tall, with bright
crimson flowers in midsummer, it's a spreader. But McGourty's
favorite sedum ground cover for hot dry areas is the lesser known
S. spurium albumsuperbum, which will produce its white flowers even
in considerable shade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Easy to propagate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you try a new sedum and want more of it, propagation couldn't
be easier. In spring just cut a couple of inches off the tips of
growing shoots with some stem attached and stick them in the garden
where you want them to grow. By summer they'll be rooted and
thriving.
</P>
<P>
   And if you have lovely urns and flower boxes but you're tired of
all the fertilizing, pinching, and daily watering most flowers
require in containers, fill them with sedums next year and you
won't have to do a thing. Not even water.
</P>
<P>
   Like the word ``sedentary,'' the name ``sedum'' comes from the
Latin word for sitting. And that's what sedums do. They just sit
there and make the gardener look good, unlike the rest of the
perennials, which demand staking and deadheading as fall
progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one had a whole garden of sedums,'' wrote the late great
garden author Henry Mitchell, ``people would think one was a superb
cultivator of plants, because they always look band-box fresh,
whether there have been droughts or floods or gas fumes or
plagues.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOME SOURCES FOR SEDUMS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some local and mail-order sources for sedums:
</P>
<P>
   Hillside Gardens, 515 Litchfield Road, Norfolk, CT 06058. Sells
a wide selection of sedums and uncommon alliums and perennials on
site. Send a SASE for a plant list. Phone: 860-542-5345.
</P>
<P>
   Joy Creek Nursery, 20300 NW Watson Road, Scappoose, OR 07056.
Perennials and rock garden plants. Phone: 503-543-7474. Catalog is
$2 with a fall supplement.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney's at Arrowhead, 115 Boston Post Road, Wayland,
Mass.,sells two dozen types of low-growing sedums and eight types
of tall growing varieties. Phone: 508-358-7333. Also available in
Massachusetts at Mahoney's in Winchester, Cambridge, Tewksbury,
Osterville, Falmouth and Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Niche Gardens, 111 Dawson Road, Chapel Hill, NC 27516, carries
unusual sedums for both fall and spring planting, plus
nursery-propagated wildflowers, southeastern natives, selected
perennials, ornamental grasses and underused trees and shrubs.
Descriptive catalog $3. Phone: 919-967-0078; Fax: 919-967-4026;
E-mail: mail(at)nichegdn.com; Web: www.nichegdn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Plant Delights Nursery Inc., 9241 Sauls Road, Raleigh, NC 27603.
Hard-to-find sedums and other perennials. Amusing and comprehensive
descriptive catalog costs 10 stamps or a box of chocolates _
really! Phone: 919-772-4794; fax: 919-662-0370; e-mail:
office(at)plantdel.com; web: www.plantdel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Siskiyou Rare Plant Nursery, 2825 Cummings Road, Medford, OR
97501. Sells many rare sedums, especially for rock gardens. Phone:
541-772-6846; color catalog $3 with spring and fall supplements;
fax: 541-772-4917; e-mail: srpn(at)wave.net
</P>
<P>
   Wayside Gardens, 1 Garden Lane, Hodges, SC 29695-0001. Wide
selection of sedums and other perennials plus shrubs, trees,
grasses and bulbs. Free color catalog and free staff
horticulturalist to answer growing questions. Phone:
1-800-845-1124; fax: 1-800-817-1124.
</P>
<P>
   Weston Nurseries, Rte. 135, Hopkinton, sells a large assortment
of sedums and other perennials, as well as woodies. Phone:
1-800-322-2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
