<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2166 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KERRY-BOS &LR;      09-24 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KERRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRY WARNS: LONG PROCESS MAY BRING A BACKLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator John F. Kerry, emerging as a key broker in
the early stages of the impeachment process, warned Republican
congressional leaders Wednesday that their insistence on holding
months of impeachment hearings may backfire in the November
elections and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry refined and repeated his proposal that calls for President
Clinton voluntarily to testify before the House Judiciary Committee
in exchange for an expedited vote on impeachment. Under the plan,
Clinton would testify within weeks, and a vote would be taken by
the full House just weeks after that, averting the need for a
lengthy hearing that some lawmakers have estimated may spill from
1999 into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not necessary to have another long, protracted
investigation,'' said Kerry, appearing at a Capitol news
conference. ``I think the question has to be fairly asked, is the
Republican leadership of the Congress prepared to enter into a
serious effort to reduce the agony for this country, to streamline
this process in a dignified and appropriate way?''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's proposal, made Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press,''
captured attention at both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials lauded the Kerry proposal publicly and
privately Wednesday. Democratic leaders offered their own carbon
copies at various gatherings on Capitol Hill. And Republicans
leaders, though dismissive of the plan Wednesday, had held
discussions with Kerry early in the week.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal provides Kerry an odd place in the unfolding
political drama. He is neither an acknowledged party leader nor is
he regarded as any great ally of the White House, and he has
virtually no channels to the House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But his proposal has made him an instant draw on the television
circuit, garnering him appearances on network newscasts Monday,
followed by ``Larry King Live.'' Wednesday, his news conference
broadcast live on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, he has said he still believes a brokered deal is
possible. In public, he has said senators and House members from
both parties have offered him support, though few Republicans have
come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Given his reputation in Washington as a publicity seeker, allies
and enemies were immediately skeptical of his suggestions for
speeding House action. But they then rendered a judgment that was
widely favorable. At the White House press briefing Wednesday,
Press Secretary Michael McCurry implicitly backed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are trying to bring this matter to closure by
putting forward what are reasonable ideas, like Senator John Kerry,
are getting drowned out by those who seem to want to let this
matter go on and on and on,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a telephone interview, White House counselor Paul
Begala went even further.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy with a safe seat,'' Begala said. ``He's a war
hero, he's a former prosecutor. No one believes he is doing this
for political reasons. He is making a good faith effort. This
looked like something that could lead to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   The offer of Clinton's testimony had actually been quietly
floated on Capitol Hill by White House aides late last week, but
did not crystalize until Kerry endorsed the concept on television
Sunday and pursued it with congressional leaders Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To throw all kinds of political calculations inside this is a
mistake,'' said John Marttila, a longtime consultant to Kerry in
Boston. ``This is an absolutely unpredictable outcome when the
crisis is so grave. His proposal feels right, and it is a clear and
simple idea, which makes it more appealing. The country wants this
to be dealt with quickly and promptly.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Republicans could not find fault with the motivation,
though they did reject the plan. Some strategists said a broker's
role between Clinton and the House Republicans was fraught with
danger, and any self-serving motivations would eventually be bared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you try a brokering role, it's high-risk,'' said Ron
Kaufman, a former political director in the Bush White House and
now a consultant and lobbyist. ``If his risk is: `this will help
elevate me for some stature as candidate for president,' its
high-risk. You pick up the enemies of those who lose out in the
end. But if this is honest, it could be a good thing for him.''
</P>
<P>
   KerryWednesday made repeated references Wednesday to the serious
decisions ahead. He chastised Republicans for their own political
motivations in stretching out the impeachment process, warning that
such a tactic would come with a price, both immediate and in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply concerned that when you are brandishing around the
potential of impeachment of a president of the United States, you
are doing so much more than pursuing a political strategy,'' said
Kerry. ``You are putting our institutions on trial _ the House, the
Senate, the Congress, and the presidency, and the reputation of all
who serve therein.''
</P>
<P>
   He added later: ``The bottom line is this is bigger than any of
us. This is not about any person's individual journey. This is
about our country's journey.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that nearly all the facts in the case are already
known through sworn testimony and records compiled by independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr, meaning much of the remaining disputes
come down to who touched whom where.
</P>
<P>
   As he was leaving, a reporter asked why he was trying to chart
the uncharted, and he replied, ``It's called leadership, good faith
efforts, bona fide approach to the problems of the country. And in
the end, the American people will make their judgment at the
polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps with that thought in mind, a Kerry aide Wednesday called
the Iowa state Democratic Party to inform the chairman that the
senator would be appearing on live television, and provided the
date and time, according to a state party official who declined to
be named.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-PHONES-BOS &LR;      09-24 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-PHONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYNCHRONIZE YOUR LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SIMSON GARFINKLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frequent readers of this column know that I've been spending a
lot of time experimenting with cellular telephones. One thing
that's made this task particularly difficult is the electronic
phone book that each of these phones contains. A built-in address
book can be both a timesaver and a moneysaver. Unfortunately, the
tiny keyboards and cryptic user interfaces that these phones all
share makes programming more than a few names and phone numbers
into the phones quite an arduous task.
</P>
<P>
   For years I've been telling Motorola and the other cell phone
vendors that they need to create some way for people to edit their
address books from a desktop computer, as well as to download a
list of names and numbers from the computer into the cellular phone
and upload it back. The manufacturers have been slow to respond.
After all, the lack of telephone management software hasn't really
hurt their sales, has it? Thankfully the wireless communications
marketplace is now going through a period of hyper-competition, and
some vendors have realized that integration with computers is a
competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The first crop of wireless integration tools combine telephones
and two-way pagers with the 3Com PalmPilot. This is a curious
choice, considering that there are more than 100 million desktop
computers in the United States alone and less than 2 million Pilots
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first integration products to hit the market is a
nifty little device called the Snap-On. Manufactured by Option
International, a Belgian company, the product lets you control a
telephone using the GSM standard (Europe's standard for digital
cellular service) from a PalmPilot. In the Boston area it's being
sold by OmniPoint, a digital cellular carrier that uses the GSM
technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems in building integration software is that
every cellular phone has a different arrangement of contacts across
its bottom. Option solves this problem with a variety of cables
that let you connect the Snap-On with more than 22 different GSM
handsets. You can find more information at
http://www.option.com/snapon.htm.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the Snap-On with an Ericsson 788 GSM phone. The
Snap-On's Phone Manager software let me view both the GSM
telephone's phonebook and the second phonebook that's stored inside
the GSM telephone's built-in smart card. I could move address-book
entries between the Pilot and the telephone, or edit the numbers in
place. Believe me, using the Pilot is a lot easier than trying to
deal with the 788's user interface.
</P>
<P>
   But the Snap-On provides a lot more than simple address book
synchronization. The system's enclosed Short Message Service
software lets you use GSM's built-in paging capability to send
short messages to other GSM users (or to Internet e-mail
addresses). Normally, sending a page from a cell phone is quite
difficult, but when you can compose the message on your Pilot it is
quite easy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Snap-On comes with an application that lets you use
your GSM telephone as a wireless modem. With the software,
originally designed for the Minstrel wireless modem, you can use
the Pilot/GSM combination to browse the Web, check your e-mail, or
send full-blown e-mail messages. You can even synchronize your
Pilot with your desktop computer over the air, provided you have a
modem on your desktop machine and have set it up for remote
synchronization.
</P>
<P>
   Another company that's developed some exciting PalmPilot
software for wireless devices is Texas-based JP Software. Called
BeamLink, the program lets you send pages and update the address
book in the new AccessLink II two-way pagers manufactured by
Glenayre. These pagers work with the SkyTel nationwide two-way
paging service.
</P>
<P>
   As its name implies, BeamLink makes use of the infrared port
that's built into both the new Palm III and the AccessLink II
pagers. The infrared system avoids the need to carry around another
cable. Although it's a lot easier to compose a long message on the
Palm Pilot than on the pager's tiny six-button keyboard, the real
benefit of this software is for businesses: Using BeamLink, a
company can download the same address book into 10 or 20 pagers at
the same time, guaranteeing that each member of an organization
will have the same copy of the address book.
</P>
<P>
   BeamLink is still a little rough around the edges _ and the
rough spots are instructive for others who are thinking of
developing software for the two-way wireless market. For example,
while the software can download names, pager numbers, and e-mail
addresses to the two-way pager, it doesn't let you upload the
information from the pager into your Pilot. As the folks at Palm
Computing have known for years, synchronization is the key to
making mobile computers with relatively limited user interfaces
extremely useful.
</P>
<P>
   A more serious problem with BeamLink has to do with the
software's registration procedure. When I first started up the
program, BeamLink asked me for my serial number; it then sent a
two-way page with my number to JP Software. Although it's
understandable that JP Software wants to track the use (and
possibly the unauthorized use) of its software, a feature like this
one that transmits information over a network without the user's
permission sets a dangerous precedent. Computer users have the
right to use software without revealing information about
themselves to the people who wrote the software.
</P>
<P>
   Users have a right to expect that their personal information
will be kept secret. It's all too easy for software that integrates
computers with two-way wireless communication devices to become
automated surveillance tools. The way to stop this Orwellian
possibility is to loudly protest the companies that are taking the
first steps today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Simson L. Garfinkel can be reached at
plugged-in(AT)simson.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
