<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_DRUG FOR OSTEOPOROSIS SHOWS GOOD RESULTS   
 _COMBAT SAID TO PLAY SMALL HEALTH ROLE LATER   
 _GENES MAY EXPLAIN DAY OR NIGHT PEOPLE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Drug for osteoporosis shows good results
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts General Hospital researchers are reporting
promising results from using a hormone treatment to improve bone
density in women suffering from osteoporosis, a common symptom of
menopause that causes about 1.3 million bone fractures in the
nation annually.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the current Journal of the American Medical
Association, Dr. Joel S. Finkelstein of the MGH endocrine unit, Dr.
Robert M. Neer of the hospital's osteoporosis center and his
colleagues found that women undergoing premature menopause from
drug treatments experienced measurable improvements in spine and
hip bone density from injections of parathyroid hormone. The
hormone is normally produced by four tiny glands inside the
thyroid.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a year, women given daily injections of the
hormone had about 4 to 7.5 percent better bone density in their
spine and femur than women who did not get the hormone, which helps
build up calcium levels in the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've shown that'' the hormone ``can
prevent bone loss in the hip,'' Finkelstein said. ``Although we
still have to answer a lot of questions before'' it ``can become an
approved therapy, it may give us an entirely new approach to
preventing this serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The 43 women studied were aged 21 to 45 and were undergoing
treatment for endometriosis, a disease of the uterus, with a drug
that dropped their estrogen levels, triggering early menopause
symptoms. Half got the hormone and half did not.
</P>
<P>
   Finkelstein said that ``it is extremely plausible'' that the
treatment would work with similar results on older women undergoing
natural menopause. His group has won federal funding to start
enrolling 100 postmenopausal women for a three-year test of the
treatment. Anyone interested in participating can call
617-724-8069.
</P>
<P>
   If the treatment proves workable for all menopausal women, it
could have major benefits: About 15 percent of elderly patients who
suffer hip fractures die as a result, according to MGH researchers.
Many of those fractures are caused by osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Combat said to play small health role later
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not a study that claims war is good for your health by any
means. But combat experience in Vietnam played a surprisingly small
role in affecting whether veterans later suffered hypertension,
respiratory illnesses or other health problems, according to a new
study by researchers from the Veterans Administration and the
Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, led by Dr. Seth A. Eisen, studied 4,700 pairs
of identical and fraternal twin brothers of whom at least one
fought in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, combat experiences explained fewer than 10 percent of
the health problems reported by veterans, with the biggest impact
on hearing loss and skin illnesses. Inherited genetic factors and
environmental exposures were much more important in explaining
hypertension, arthritis and gastrointestinal disorders, Eisen's
team writes in yesterday's edition of the journal Psychosomatic
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   One limitation, Eisen acknowledged, was that the average age of
the veterans and their twins was 38 when they were given an initial
30-page questionnaire in 1987. ``If individuals do have low levels
of persistent psychological turmoil, they may have difficulties
after a period of years because many of these diseases develop over
decades'' so the findings ``do not preclude the possibility that
they will develop problems later on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Genes may explain day or night people
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hate to get up in the morning? Your genes may explain the
reason, according to new research by doctors from Stanford
University and the University of Wisconsin. In this month's journal
Sleep, which reports on sleep disorders, Dr. Emmanuel Mignot and
colleagues found that a specific variation in the so-called clock
gene seems to explain consistently why some of the 410 people
studied were more likely ``evening people'' whose bodies tell them
to go to sleep later at night. The researchers hope someday people
could get a genetic test that would advise them whether to seek a
job where they go to work later and can sleep later in the morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
