<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2173 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-MARCH-BOS &LR;      09-24 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-MARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVISTS PRESS FOR IMPROVEMENT IN CANCER RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She knew little about cancer before her husband, Michael, was
stricken with it. But now Carole Seigel has become something of an
expert on pancreatic cancer, urgently following every lead, surfing
the Internet, reading everything she can find.
</P>
<P>
   And she has concluded this: ``There is a lot of raw science in
the laboratories, and the pipeline for getting that science to the
patients is woefully small in spite of the war on cancer. They need
more resources.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Brookline, Mass. woman and her family, and tens
of thousands of others afflicted or affected by the dreaded
disease, are storming Washington this weekend, hoping that The
March _ expected to be the largest cancer rally ever _ can propel
the nation's commitment to fighting cancer to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity-studded Saturday and Sunday event brings together
cancer patients, advocates and volunteers, researchers, doctors,
politicians and others to honor those who've died in the struggle
and to demand more money for better anticancer weapons.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 organizations have endorsed the event, whose full
title is ``The March ... Coming Together To Conquer Cancer.'' Its
president, Ellen Stovall, a survivor of recurrent cancer, said in a
recent Internet press conference, ``There are many opportunities in
research and questions that need to be answered, but there is not
enough funding to pursue these issues. The March is about demanding
of our elected officials that we answer these questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and retired Army General H. Norman
Schwarzkopf are slated to participate in the rally, which has
attracted wide support not only in the lay community but among
clinicians and researchers and medical centers, and the American
Cancer Society. The American Society of Clinical Oncology,
representing about 12,000 physicians who treat cancer, issued a
briefing paper last week calling for a 35 percent increase in the
National Cancer Institute's fiscal year 1999 budget, from $2.54
billion to $3.19 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, said ASCO's president, Dr. Allen S. Lichter, the
organization sees an urgent need for more funding for the clinical
trials that test for new treatments, from chemotherapy agents to
new ``targeted'' drugs pouring from the laboratory to preventive
compounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can do more studies and put more patients in them faster
and finish them sooner, we get more results and that translates
into lives saved,'' he said in a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Senator Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, a sponsor
of the 1971 National Cancer Act that launched the war on cancer,
said in a statement Wednesday, ``I`m optimistic that the March will
spur Congress and the country to even greater progress'' than has
already been made with an investment of over $36 billion by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer is the nation's second-leading killer after heart
disease, and although the rate of new cases and deaths has finally
begun to decline, it still kills over half a million people a year
_ about 1,500 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of The March are unashamedly lobbying for their cause,
despite concerns by some health experts about the loudest voices
setting research agendas. ``The March has been unfairly
characterized as seeking to take attention and funding away from
other diseases, like Alzheimer's or diabetes,'' says Stovall, the
event's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling is that no money should be taken away from any
fields of medicine where there are opportunities to conduct
research,'' she said, adding that the goal regarding cancer funding
is the same _ not to boost support for any one form of cancer but
to ``create a bigger pie'' for the entire field.
</P>
<P>
   Names of people across the nation who have died of cancer are
being sent to Washington where they will be inscribed on an honor
roll. ``I've been beating the bushes to get friends to participate
in the honor roll,'' said Seigel. ``It is a dramatic and impressive
way of showing how this touches everybody's life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1322EDT &QL; 
