<HEADER>
A2175 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOYCOTT-SLATE-NYTSF     09-24 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYCOTT-SLATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T READ THIS 
</HEADLINE>
  By TIMOTHY NOAH 
 (www.slate.com) 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We who think Flytrap encompasses at least a few matters of
genuine public importance are struck by the newsworthiness of a
certain e-mail chain letter making its way around the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, titled ``Reclaiming Our Dignity,'' calls for a
one-day boycott on Oct. 1 of all newspapers, magazines, TV news
programs, and (gasp) ``any of the Internet sites that have
information on the Starr report.''
</P>
<P>
   The boycott is not being ginned up by fringe crackpots. It's the
brainchild of three thirtysomething yuppies who were having dinner
together in Cambridge, Mass. One works for a publisher, one is
studying to be a teacher and one works for a foundation. All three
agreed that they needed some respite from the Lewinsky scandal,
which they felt had engulfed the national conversation.
</P>
<P>
   First they contemplated a national strike. Too radical, they
concluded (``We decided we couldn't get people to stay home from
work.'') Then they talked about a boycott of all consumer products.
But what did Prell Concentrate have to do with Monica Lewinsky? (In
fact, we would add, Monica probably wouldn't be caught dead near
the stuff.) Finally they settled on a one-day media boycott.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation of the President has gone too far,'' the
letter begins. Release of ``unnecessarily graphic details of the
President's sexual life, the recent release of the Starr Report
over the Internet and the videotapes of the President's testimony
to the grand jury has eroded our dignity as a country. The efforts
to humiliate the President, humiliate us all. Therefore, please set
aside October 1, 1998 as a day of reflection on our country and the
democratic process.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter asks readers not to buy newspapers or magazines on
that day. ``If you subscribe to a newspaper, tape it to your window
and door, with a large circle and slash, indicating your
displeasure with the level of reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of watching the news, ``take a walk, say hi to your
neighbors, or write a letter to Congress.'' Above all, it says,
``reflect about the type of community you want, the characteristics
of a government that would make you proud to participate, and what
you can do (or not do) to reclaim the dignity of the democratic
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, we won't be participating, but we go weak in
the knees whenever people start calling for civic virtue. (Mario
Cuomo's speech to the 1984 Democratic convention still sets our
heart aflutter.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2177 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-24 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIME IS NOW FOR 56K MODEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the things that makes this job worthwhile is the fact
that sometimes my readers do as I tell them.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years ago, I warned you not to buy one of those new
56K modems for your computer. And to judge by the anemic 1997
revenues of modem makers like 3Com Inc. and Boston's own Zoom
Telephonics Inc., you heard and obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   Good for you. You've saved yourselves a lot of trouble and a
good deal of money as well. Now here are your new orders. The time
has come for 56K. Go forth and buy.
</P>
<P>
   The new modems can receive data at speeds approaching 56,000
bits per second, nearly twice as fast as the previous generation of
modem. These 56K modems originally came in two different flavors,
called X2 and K56Flex.
</P>
<P>
   But the two types were incompatible. If your Internet provider
had one kind of 56K modem and you had the other kind, you could
connect at low speed, but not at the higher speeds.
</P>
<P>
   You can see how this would be a problem, and not just for
consumers. Some Internet providers chose up sides. In the process,
they drove away customers with incompatible modems. Other providers
offered both types, spending a small fortune on extra phone lines
and different phone numbers for X2 and K56Flex lines. Still others
sat on their hands, waiting for a universal standard to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   And so did many consumers. The result was a price war, as modem
makers tried to overcome buyer resistance with a relentless
campaign of markdowns. It worked, sort of. According to the market
research firm Dataquest, the modem industry sold 11 million more
units worldwide in 1997 than in the year before. But their revenues
fell by nearly $500 million, because of price cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty bad loss last year,'' laments Zoom Telephonics
president Frank Manning. For sure _ a $7.1 million loss, after a
$2.5 million profit the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Poor fellow. He's suffered enough. It's time to start buying
modems again. Here's why.
</P>
<P>
   First, the standards war is officially over. One week ago, the
International Telecommunications Union ratified a worldwide
standard called V.90. All future 56K modems will comply and most of
the older ones can be upgraded. As a result, you can buy a new 56K
modem with confidence, as long as your Internet provider has
installed a V.90 modem on its end.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few still haven't. My main provider, Concentric Network
Inc., is still making the changeover. But America Online is already
on board. That's 13 million potential V.90 customers right there.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's price. When 28,800 bit-per-second modems first
appeared in 1994 they could run you $300. That kind of pricing is
history. With consumers now accustomed to cheap modems, they won't
pay those kinds of markups. And manufacturers are smart enough not
to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom sells an external V.90 modem for $99 with rebate.
Meanwhile, 3Com charges a premium for its US Robotics modems, but
$160 or so isn't too shabby, and you can probably do even better
with a bit of shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Federal Communications Commission is offering
encouragement. Today's 56K modems actually top out at 53,000 bits
per second, because of an FCC regulation that limits the power
output of modems. Now the FCC is proposing to abolish that rule. In
a few months, 56K modems could really become 56K modems.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the new modems have their limits. They'll only receive
data at the highest speeds; when you send data, it'll travel at
33,600 bits per second tops. And only about 80 percent of American
homes have phone lines that will allow the modems to work properly.
The modem maker 3Com offers a handy test that will let you
determine whether your phone line can handle 56K. For details, go
to http://www.3com.com/56k.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you with the good fortune to live in cable-modem
country will greet this news with smiles of pity. You've got 1.5
million bits per second to play with. But millions of others are
years away from cable-modem access. For them, 56K modems are the
best access deal around. So go ahead and get one. You have my
permission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2178 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOYCOTT-SLATE-NYTSF     09-24 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYCOTT-SLATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T READ THIS 
</HEADLINE>
  By TIMOTHY NOAH 
 (www.slate.com) 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We who think Flytrap encompasses at least a few matters of
genuine public importance are struck by the newsworthiness of a
certain e-mail chain letter making its way around the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, titled ``Reclaiming Our Dignity,'' calls for a
one-day boycott on Oct. 1 of all newspapers, magazines, TV news
programs, and (gasp) ``any of the Internet sites that have
information on the Starr report.''
</P>
