<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      09-24 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREFULLY PREPARE DRY WALL BEFORE PAPERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the best way to prepare new dry wall for wallpaper?
My concern is not ony with paper adhesion but also wih stripping
and repaparing or repainting. I'd like to start with a painted
surface so I can paper the rooms several times. I have little
confidence in the typical builder's flat paint.
</P>
<P>
   LYNDA BEDARD, Palm Harbor, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You are right; dry wall is tough to paper without proper
preparation because it is impossible to remove without ruining the
paper of the plasterboard.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a proper way to prepare, and this is it: Paint the
walls with a latex enamel undercoater, also called primer-sealer,
then apply one, possibly two coats of an eggshell finish (neither
flat nor shiny) latex wall paint. Be sure to glue size the walls
before putting up the paper.
</P>
<P>
   This hard, washable finish (the primer and paint) will make the
dry wall water resistant, and much easier to remove the paper
without messing up the paper of the plasterboard.
</P>
<P>
   The enamel undercoater is not normally used on walls, but for
added waterproofing, it is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you apply the undercoater and two coats of the
eggshell finish, you might find it handsome enough to keep it that
way for a while.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The aluminum siding in our 100-year-old house is 20 years old
and beginning to look pretty shabby. We'd like to go back to wood
clapboards (original siding), but were told that when the aluminum
was installed, the installers cut the window sill ``horns'' to the
size of the sash, then installed the siding over the casings. We're
afraid that when the siding comes off, under each of 30 windows
there will be a gaping hole. Replacing windows does not make sense
because the windows are OK. Is there a way to replace or repair
those exterior sills without dismantling the entire window? Should
the siding be taken off before any sill work is done or should the
sills be fixed before the siding?
</P>
<P>
   CALVIN WELS, Portsmouth, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Oh, what aluminum and vinyl siders do to people's houses.
It's a shame, but at least you are going in the right direction to
get rid of that fake siding and go with something that belongs on
the house.
</P>
<P>
   Siders used to cover window casing with their fake siding. It
was called ``jumping the casings,'' and cutting the horns of the
sills was included. They also often cut off or covered decorative
trim. At least they don't do that any more.
</P>
<P>
   The horns you speak of were at each end of the sills, and
generally that was all they cut. If that is all they cut, you can
cut new horns from a 2 x 4 and screw, nail or glue them onto the
ends of the cut sills.
</P>
<P>
   If the siders cut off the front edge of the sill for its full
length, you may discover a gap, but not necessarily. Even so, you
can still cut a new piece and attach it to what is left of the
sill. Be sure to caulk the joint where you attach the new part of
the sill; it has to be waterproof. All this can be done without
disturbing the window itself.
</P>
<P>
   That's better than replacing whole sills, which you could do if
you had to, but it is a lot more work. I suggest you do this after
the aluminum siding has been removed; you might find some of the
clapboards and/or window casings in bad shape under the siding, and
if so you can make all your repairs at the same time before
treating the clapboards. If the clapboards are in good shape, I
suggest you apply two coats of a latex solid stain, not a paint,
after heavy sanding. The stain is less likely to peel than paint.
</P>
<P>
   If the siding is in such bad shape that it cannot be saved, I
suggest replacing it with new red cedar clapboards, rough side out,
and treating with one coat of a semitransparent stain. Or, put up
white cedar shingles and let them weather; there is no need for any
treatment, and they will turn to that Cape Cod silver and last for
40 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This past spring I put a white wicker sofa on our front
porch. After a hot, dry summer, when I took a good look at it I was
amazed to see how weatherbeaten it was. My wife wants me to paint
it, but no one here in Florida can tell me how to do it or what to
use. It is a lovely piece but now rather dried out. What if
anything can I do to restore this piece?
</P>
<P>
   WALTER POMAROLE, Ocala, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the best thing you can do for your wicker sofa is to
paint it. And, I don't think there is any harm is the sofa seeming
too dry. Wood is supposed to be dry, and stay dry.
</P>
<P>
   First, dry scrub it to remove loose dirt, then wash with a
strong solution of Spic and Span and water and let dry. Treat with
a mild bleach/water solution if there is any mildew present. Rinse
and let dry. Rinsing is important if you use bleach, because bleach
and any finish _ varnish, paint, stain _ are incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   Apply a latex enamel undercoater, also called primer sealer. Use
a cheap brush; any brush will be worth throwing away after painting
wicker. Remove or cover upholstery or cushions, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Now here comes the best part. Paint with a spray enamel; Krylon
makes an aerosol spray enamel that works wonders; it is not too
shiny and not too dull, and spraying is the best way to do wicker.
It will also make the wicker a little more water resistant. I have
done it and am very happy with the results. Spray outdoors on an
calm day, if possible. You should be able to find the undercoater
or primer-sealer and the Krylon at any paint store.
</P>
<P>
   Wicker does not belong outdoors, even under a roof. Keep it in
the house or in a sunroom, or where it is protected from the
elements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
