<HEADER>
A2183 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-WEEDS-BOS &LR;      09-24 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-WEEDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING UP CLOSE WITH THE WEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I weed, you weed, we all weed. And then we weed again.
</P>
<P>
   Weeding is to gardeners what suffering is to great artists _
painful and necessary. It gets us in touch with our soil, our
plants, our gardens, in ways no other endeavor can _ on hands and
knees, up close.
</P>
<P>
   I recognize its philosophical and practical worth, achieving a
laborious, Zen-like oneness with our garden, as well as a
beautiful, healthy garden. Besides, if you don't do it, the garden
quickly succumbs to the weeds, plants that by and large are (and I
am speaking frankly now) better than those we choose to grow.
</P>
<P>
   What makes them better? What makes a great weed? What is it
about certain weeds that makes our blood boil, or at least our
backs ache?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a person who loves to maintain a perfect lawn, or
if you are a person who wants to maintain a perfect garden bed, you
probably dislike crabgrass, because it seeds about with abandon,''
said Deborah Swanson, a specialist with the extension service in
Plymouth County. Crabgrass, Digitaria sanguinalis, is what I spend
most of my time excising _ or is it exorcising? Ignore it and it
spreads wide with tenacious fibrous roots, tangling itself with
desired plants and hogging the soil's nutrients and moisture
</P>
<P>
   Dandelions also would bedevil the lawn nut, Swanson said,
especially ``if you had one or two neighbors who had lawns with a
more natural look.'' Dandelions (Taraxacum officinale) not only pop
up all over, they have deep tap roots. Unless you remove all, or
nearly all, of that tap root, the plant will regenerate. (They pull
up more easily in moist soil.)
</P>
<P>
   Pokeweed (Phytolacca americana) also has a tap root. ``Pokeweed
is a very large weed,'' Swanson said. It grows up to 6 feet and is
fleshy, though its stalk gets somewhat woody as it matures, and it
has purple, stain-your-shirt berries. Oh, and it is poisonous.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly more benign would be black bindweed, Polygonum
convolvulus. A twiner, it has thin stalks and small, arrow-like
leaves. It pulls out easily. The one I just yanked started among
the nicotiana, climbed through the shed door, and went up a broom,
perhaps seeking shelter inside for the winter. Swanson said a
Norwell man recently sought identification of a weed. It was a
bindweed, and it covered his blueberry bushes, sucking up their
sunlight, as well as nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Also using the strategy of climbing is Oriental bittersweet,
Celastrus orbiculatus. People like its pretty yellow and orange
berries, Swanson said, but it can reach 20 to 40 feet and strangle
whole trees.
</P>
<P>
   Like Rosa multiflora (a mass of which I will be tackling out
back in the next few weeks) and many honeysuckles, Oriental
bittersweet is an escapee from gardens, said Ron Kujawski, a
nursery crop specialist with the University of Massachusetts
Extension in Amherst. He is personally, as well as professionally,
familiar with weeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up working on an onion farm, and most of our growing
year was spent on our hands and knees going up and down the rows
pulling out the weeds,'' he said. ``You really get intimate with
your plants that way. It makes us humble.''
</P>
<P>
   His pick for worst garden weed is quack grass (Agropyron
repens), ``because it has these underground runners and you can
pull up the weed or, if you're hoeing, you always leave fragments
behind, and you never seem to get rid of them.'' The underground
runners are rhizomes, a modified stem, and whacking them is a great
way to propagate. (Deborah Swanson noted that rototilling yucca
will give a gardener a whole lot of little yucca headaches.)
</P>
<P>
   Kujawski also dislikes thistles, for obvious reasons _ ``you
really have to take care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From a weed's standpoint, being rhizomatous helps, producing
an abundance of seed helps, having a high survival rates of seeds,
seeds that remain viable for a long time, things like lamb's
quarters and pigweed,'' Kujawski said. ``It seems like every time
you turn over the soil, you have more.''
</P>
<P>
   That raises a point. People make weeds. People imported to
America, deliberately or accidentally, many of the worst weeds,
among them dandelions, Oriental bittersweet, Japanese knotweed,
kudzu (in the South, but it's been found at the Arnold Arboretum),
and purple loosestrife. And people plant them. Every time a
gardener clears a bed, the way is cleared for weeds. Plant tender
vegetables, and the competition is lowered for weeds. Cultivate the
soil, and more weed seeds are exposed. Some weed seeds, Kujawski
said, require a flash of light before they can germinate;
gardeners, in working the soil, often provide that.
</P>
<P>
   Weeds, Swanson said, ``outcompete the other plants for light and
water and nutrients and space.'' Their strategies include taproots
to maintain a hold in one spot, super-seeding to spring up in other
places, and the ability to travel by climbing or sending stolons
across the ground or rhizomes under it.
</P>
<P>
   Antiweed strategies include hacking them to death, pulling them
out, forking them out, spraying with chemicals, mulching, and
avoiding turning the soil _ none of which works universally, all of
which have drawbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
