<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMNART-     09-24 1580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST PROP FOR PLAYING WITH YOUR CHILD IS YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whoever coined the expression ``baby's play,'' to refer to
something simple, didn't know much about babies. Their play is not
only complicated and intricate, but also as important to their
lives as good nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's serious work for them,'' says child psychiatrist Arnold
Kerzner. ``It's how they learn to regulate themselves, to develop
trust, handle stimulation, excitement, separation, loss, a sense of
self. ... It's a long list.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because there's all this work to do, doesn't mean we need
to work at it. When we act instinctively, lovingly, and
attentively, a baby's learning comes naturally, without our even
realizing it. Expensive toys, baby classes, videos marketed to make
babies smarter sooner _ these are unnecessary props.
</P>
<P>
   ``All your young baby really needs is you _ your face, your
fingers, your voice, your attention,'' says developmental
psychologist Marilyn Segal of Nova Southeastern University in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. Even the 6- to 12-month-old needs mostly only
items you probably have around the house.
</P>
<P>
   The truth of that has been a pleasant surprise for Karen
Ward-Kaplan of Cambridge, Mass. and her husband, Elliot Kaplan.
When their daughter, Jess Avery, was born, they kept their
toy-buying to a minimum. Nonetheless, they've been surprised that
the few toys Jess has are not what capture her attention.
</P>
<P>
   Now 7 months old, Jess's favorite toy was invented by her
grandpa: wadded-up newspaper. ``She drops it on the floor, slings
it around, crinkles and uncrinkles it. It's great for noise and
texture,'' says Ward-Kaplan, who wisely lets her daughter lead the
way in how they play. She sings to Jess's musical accompaniment (a
wooden spoon on a pot) and delights in Jess's glee at the passing
game, where an object, usually mom's sunglasses, go back and forth
from one lap to another.
</P>
<P>
   For parents like Ward-Kaplan, this play time is sheer joy. Under
researchers' analyses, it takes on another dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Jess's passing game. According to Segal, it teaches
predictability and trust: ``If I give it to mom, she gives it back
to me, every single time! Let me try again. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Turn-taking is the earliest form of play, typically beginning
when a newborn catches your gaze, looks away, then looks back. This
isn't just random, says child psychologist J. Kevin Nugent,
director of the Brazelton Institute at Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to do with an infant's need for securty,'' he said.
``It's as if baby is thinking, `If I get overwhelmed and look away,
can I rely on you to still be there when I'm ready to look back?'''
The patient parent is soon rewarded with a smile, not just a gaze;
without even realizing it, parent and baby have played their first
game.
</P>
<P>
   What's most important in these early months is learning to read
your baby's signals during play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babies are easily over-stimulated. They let you know they need
a rest by turning away,'' Kerzner said. This gaze aversion
sometimes is brief; if she turns back in seconds full of smiles,
that amounts to turn-taking: She's ready for more. Otherwise, she
needs a longer break. Not catching the signal is what leads to
overload and crying, said Kerzner, who is in private practice in
Belmont and Wellesley, Mass. He is president emeritus of the Boston
Institute for the Development of Infants and Parents.
</P>
<P>
   So what, exactly, constitues play? ``It's play as long as the
baby is having fun,'' said Segal, who is co-author of a four-book
series, ``Your Child at Play, From Birth to Five Years'' (Newmarket
Press). For instance:
</P>
<P>
   _Two to four months. Your face is the best toy of all. She'll
reach for your eyes, nose, and mouth and play with them. Games like
``I'm gonna get you,'' ``How big is the baby,'' and ``This little
piggy'' are full of sensory stimulation and also introduce the
element of the unexpected. ``That teaches about resiliency,'' says
Kerzner. ``It's as if you're saying, `There are going to be a lot
of unexpected things happening in your life. I'm going to introduce
that notion to you gradually, so you won't be overwhelmed.''' Sing
often, make up rhymes, imitate her sounds. Verbal play is important
for neurological growth; music is a precursor to language, speech,
and math skills. These games can continue to be played for many
months.
</P>
<P>
   _Five months. Almost any object that he can't swallow and that
can't hurt him can be a toy; look for objects that offer a variety
of textures and shapes: sponges, wooden spoons, metal measuring
cups. Grasping is instinctive at two months; now he's more
purposeful, using thumb and finger to pick things up. He wants to
see what he's holding and pass it from hand to hand. Play with his
feet. Continue to capitalize on all his senses with colorful
mobiles and with music.
</P>
<P>
   _Six to seven months. Put objects slightly out of reach so she
can maneuver to get them. Lavish praise for her success. Introduce
cause-and-effect with objects that respond to being pushed, pulled,
poked, punched, or squeezed. Point to objects and name them. ``Now
she's beginning to internalize two concepts,'' says Nugent. ```I'm
fun and worth playing with,' and, `I can influence the world.'''
</P>
<P>
   _Eight to 12 months. Build on the ``I can be successful''
concept: Hide an object in your hand or under the blanket, put
several items in a bowl or a small box so she can dig them out.
``This kind of play empowers her learning and her imagination,''
says Kerzner. Play ``Peek-a-boo;'' it helps her begin to deal with
loss, separation, and trust, issues that loom large as stranger
anxiety sets in. If she cries at ``Peek-a-boo,'' back off, and try
again in a few weeks. ``This game introduces anxiety: `Where is
mommy? Is she coming back?''' Kids have different thresholds for
tolerating it,'' says Kerzner. Once she likes it, it's a sign she's
increased her capacity for stronger stimuli; she's building on what
she's already learned, namely, that the world is a predictable,
pleasurable place.
</P>
<P>
   About nine months, you'll see signs of frustration, usually when
something is just out of reach. You're also moving into prime time
for the drop-the-spoon-from-the-high-chair game. How many times do
you pick it up? As many as you can stand.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent explains why. First, he says, ``You want him to know this
is a physical law. You drop it and it goes in the same direction
every time.'' Then there's the matter of trust: ``You need to
continue to demonstrate he can trust you to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about frustration? Isn't that a part of life you need
to build tolerance for? Indeed it is, says Nugent, but there's no
good rule of thumb to guide you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good play keeps a balance of pushing forward slightly but
waiting for baby to tell you you're going in the right direction or
not,'' says Nugent. ``It's a delicate balance that takes judgment
and instinct each time.'' If he's trying to reach something, don't
make it impossible for him. After a while of the dropping game, set
a limit: ``That's all now. We'll play again another time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerzner sees all baby play as symbolic of life. ``Life is full
of highs and lows, and in play, the fun part is mixed with anxiety
and loss. The message a baby takes from this is, `I can cope.' In
that way, each stage of play lays the foundation for the next level
of development.'' As long as you keep the play at your baby's level
and pay attention to her cues, there's really no mistake you can
make.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for Jess Avery, her parents aren't shy about baby play.
``Recently, I finished a box of crackers and bunched the plastic
wrapping into a wad,'' says her mom. ``Before I realized it, she
grabbed it and looked to me to play her game.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days, it's hard to tell who's having more fun, Jess Avery
or her parents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Although playing with your baby is what builds a bond of trust,
it's also good for her to engage in solitary play. When she's
bored, she'll let you know.
</P>
<P>
   _When choosing caregivers, look for one who understands how
important play is, even for a baby.
</P>
<P>
   _Babies are less fragile and more capable than we tend to
realize. Except for over-tickling or inappropriate physical play
(don't ``toss'' a baby in the air until she has good shoulder and
head control, about 5 months), parents' different styles of play is
to a baby's advantage because it increases his repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   _Every time you play with your baby, you're telling her, ``I
like to be close to you, you're special and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   _Toys worth buying: For the newborn, a few rattles; for under 6
months, toys that squeak and have bells; for the 6- to
12-month-old, a soft ball, a toy that fits into itself (like
stacking blocks), a push-and-pull toy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended reading: ``The Family of Adoption,''
by Joyce Maguire Pavao (Beacon Press).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
