<HEADLINE>
THANKS, BILL AND KEN, FOR THIS HOSTILE ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thanks to the
Clinton-Lewinsky-Starr-Drudge-CNN-MSNBC gang, this nation is one
big hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
   Out at Candlestick on Wednesday a guy kept telling the jokes of
the moment, including one about President Clinton wearing a pair of
panties on his sleeve. A reporter asks why, and Clinton says it's
like the patch _ he's trying to quit.
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall staff meetings, San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
sometimes refers to Monica Lewinsky as ``Monica Will-insky.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant owner Vince Calcagno said, ``My parents never talked
to me about sex, and suddenly my mom calls and says, `What do you
think about the blue dress?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Mom? Hello, National Organization for Women? This thing
has gotten completely out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe what we need is a class-action of the people of the United
States against Kenneth Starr, assorted members of Congress and the
media for downloading, televising and printing more than anyone
ever wanted to know about sex in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Especially include the media for creating an environment in
which you have to explain oral sex to your children and, in some
cases, your parents.
</P>
<P>
   Calcagno said that Tuesday, the day after the House Judiciary
Committee's giant data dump, a friend said he had to buy the San
Francisco Examiner with the X-rated excerpts from the Starr report.
He said, ``Do I have to show ID?''
</P>
<P>
   I want to sue Bill Clinton, Monica Lewinsky and Linda Tripp for
starring in the national defacement that launched a million bad
jokes on the Internet and at office water coolers.
</P>
<P>
   I want to sue Henry Hyde and all those Republicans who want to
censor all the pornography on the Internet but their own.
</P>
<P>
   Sue them all, and let Judge Judy sort them out.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is ground zero of the national hostile environment,
and the normally uptight city has undergone a collective bout of
Tourette's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel they have perfect license to talk loudly and
dirtily in public places,'' said Annie Groer, who co-writes the
Washington Post's gossip column called The Reliable Source. ``In
restaurants, on the street and in stuffy clubs, they feel they can
talk about the most intimate things.''
</P>
<P>
   You know things are really bad when a gossip columnist is sick
of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Groer said that the other day she was dining with friends at the
elegant Capitol Grill near the White House, and the waiter,
bartender and restaurant manager kept butting into their Monica
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it was our private tacky conversation,'' she
said. ``I think that all the rules are out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to ask. Was Groer sick of it all because Ken Starr had
become the uber-gossip columnist and eclipsed gossip and innuendo
with true, gritty dirt? No, she said she has even more work,
chasing rumors of a mythical second intern and such, and breaking
the news of Larry King's wife's pregnancy and other gossip
perennials. She also dropped items like Monica's favorite drink,
the Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Shirley Temple martini,'' Groer cracked in her snappy
``Front Page'' style.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she seems ready to crack completely. ``It's a good thing
I read the dictionary and thesaurus when I was young. That's all
that allows you to conduct a conversation in public anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete cesspool. I couldn't wait to get home,'' said
John Jacobs, political editor of the Sacramento Bee, who just
returned from a week in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs talked about Washington as a town in the midst of a
religious war. ``I think Starr and his people are behaving like
they're in a cult, and when you're in a cult you're out of touch
with reality. ... Their blood lust is so up they don't realize the
country thinks they're nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are right. We have no standards. They've
destroyed them _ to save their majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to make sense  &LR; out of this nonsense, I called Michael
Crosby, a San Diego lawyer who specializes in employee
discrimination and sexual harassment. Crosby said he had just
finished listening to the Harry Shearer show on public radio.
Shearer had just run a tape of Ted Koppel saying sex words, all
spliced together from Monica-Bill-Linda-Ken ``Nightline'' episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby agreed that the nation was one big hostile environment _
and because of that it may be harder to win sex harassment suits in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that 25 to 30 years of jurisprudence have been
trumped by ABC news,'' Crosby said. He anticipates that anytime he
goes in against an executive who exposed himself to an employee,
the guy's lawyer will say the president did it too.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby also said that the sheer weight of sexual material dumped
by Starr on America reduces the ability of people to win lawsuits
against those whose behavior creates a hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the plaintiff has to show that the type of
behavior would offend the average person. Unfortunately, the
average person has been beaten senseless with sexual material.
</P>
<P>
   As our government has been dumbed down, our sensitivities have
been numbed down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as we go on,'' said Crosby, ``it becomes harder and
harder for people with genuine sensibilities to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Mr. President, champion of feminism. Thank you, Mr.
Special Prosecutor, champion of family values. We're in hostile
environment hell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
