<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-AT-HOME-BOS &LR;      09-24 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AT-HOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR J.D., WITH LOVE AND SQUALOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
AT HOME IN THE WORLD 
By Joyce Maynard 
Picador, 347 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week's New Yorker has a cartoon that shows a woman looking
up from her book and saying, ``I think we should all be thankful
that Bill Clinton never had an inappropriate relationship with
Joyce Maynard.''
</P>
<P>
   Maynard is taking some hard knocks for her memoir ``At Home in
the World.'' Long before it was published, the idea that she would
reveal the intimate details of her teenage affair with reclusive
literary demigod J.D. Salinger was enough to give some critics the
vapors. They didn't even have to read the book to know that it
would be awful.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``At Home in the World'' isn't awful. It's not
wonderful, either. It's earnest, and rough around the edges.
Maynard has made a career of sharing her life _ marriage, children,
divorce, breast implants, tennis lessons, middle-aged dating, etc.
_ in magazines, a syndicated newspaper column, a newsletter, a
website, National Public Radio, novels, and memoirs. Her fans
follow her the way some people follow a favorite soap opera, a
genre her life tends to resemble.
</P>
<P>
   She's clearly trying to work things out in this memoir, to
achieve self-understanding. She has some insight, but she should
have thought longer and dug more deeply before she sent the
manuscript to the publisher. ``At Home in the World'' is
fascinating, the way certain disasters are fascinating. It's a
mess, but a riveting mess. You really don't want to look, and yet
you can't help wanting to see it all.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she entered Yale, Maynard says, she was an anorexic,
insecure overachiever, the product of a high-pressure childhood
with a mother and a father who, in their separate ways, defined the
word dysfunctional. This is the first time Maynard has written
honestly, in book form, about her horrible childhood. She has an
intellectual understanding of how abnormal her parents were, but
she still doesn't seem to fully comprehend the ways in which they
continue to shape her life.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, Max and Fredelle Maynard were doting parents who
prodded Joyce and her older sister, Rona, to excel. Max taught
English at the University of New Hampshire. Fredelle, a Harvard
PhD, was a devoted wife and mother who supplemented the family
income writing for women's magazines. In private Max was a bitter
drunk who blamed his wife for thwarting his career as an artist.
Fredelle was sexually frustrated, fiercely ambitious, resentful of
the fact that even though she was better qualified than her
husband, she couldn't get a university teaching job because she was
a woman. Fredelle may be the most interesting person in this book,
Salinger included.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard's relationship with Salinger started in the fall of
1972, when she was 18 and he was 53. A freshman at Yale, she wrote
a piece for the New York Times magazine, ``An Eighteen-Year-Old
Looks Back on Life,'' expressing, she recalls, ``a profound sense
of world-weariness and alienation.'' A picture of the big-eyed,
waif-like Maynard that appeared on the cover of the magazine is
reproduced on the jacket of ``At Home in the World.'' She looks no
more than 15.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of letters Maynard received from readers was
one from Salinger. She'd heard of him, but she'd never read his
work. ``Still, I am impressed with the name,'' she writes in
retrospective present tense. ``The fact that a famous man has
conferred approval on me thrills me.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinger was concerned that she might be exploited in the months
to come. Apparently he didn't understand, or didn't choose to
understand, that Maynard longed to be exploited by the forces of
commerce and criticism he'd spent much of his life avoiding. They
exchanged letters, telephone calls. She visited him, dressed up
like some virgin sacrifice in a childlike dress her mother made for
the occasion: ``stiff, white broadcloth, printed with ABC's in
primary colors.'' Years later, when her own daughter Audrey turns
18, Maynard finally realizes how strange it was that her parents
sent her off at the same age to spend the weekend with a man 35
years her senior.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard quit college and moved into Salinger's gloomy
ranch-style home in Cornish, N.H. Her description of their life
together is absurd and depressing, and oddly touching. His
obsessive interest in homeopathy. His diet of raw foods. Their
Saturday evenings fox-trotting in the blue glow of Lawrence Welk's
television show. Their unsuccesful attempts at sex.
</P>
<P>
   Salinger really cared for her, at first. And she adored him. She
clung to him desperately, even when it should have been clear that
he'd had enough of her. In March of 1973, during a trip with his
children to Daytona Beach, Fla., he told her to go back to New
Hampshire, pack her things, and leave his house. ``It's over that
quickly,'' Maynard writes.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't over, for her. She continued to adore him for
20-odd years, and long for some kind of reunion even though he made
it clear he wanted nothing to do with her. Given Salinger's
reclusive nature, his decision to woo Maynard was a
self-destructive impulse of nearly mythic proportions. But you get
what you deserve when you use the New York Times magazine as a
dating service. What was he thinking of? Maynard speculates that
the photo of her in the Times reminded him of one of his own
creations, 13-year-old Esme, from ``For Esme _ with Love and
Squalor.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinger has nobody to blame but himself for this violation of
his privacy. Up to a point, at least. Maynard's final chapter is
gratuitous, if perversely fascinating. In 1997 she went back to
Cornish to confront Salinger, to ask him, ``What was my purpose in
your life?'' His reaction is so vituperative she's reminded of
Rumpelstiltskin in a rage.
</P>
<P>
   He knows she's writing a book. She wants to tie things up. ``My
mother schools me young to view my writing as valuable,'' Maynard
writes early in this memoir. ``She conveys another lesson too:
Whatever happens in my life, I can look at it as material.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone may be rueful, but Maynard's career speaks for itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
