<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2200 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-24 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING TO JUST WHAT IS APPROPRIATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Erik Wensberg says he's amazed at how many ordinary citizens
want to talk like lawyers, even as they heap scorn on the
profession. Take ``venue,'' said Wensberg, ``The word is very
popular now. Location, place, spot, none of these common words is
good enough for us. We must have venues. It means the place of a
trial. Now the kitchen, the vacant lot, the cellar, all have become
venues among our fancier speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wensberg, a veteran magazine editor who spent the last few years
revising Wilson Follett's classic reference book ``Modern American
Usage,'' takes a dim view of fancy speech. Legal language isn't
fancy in its place, he said. For example, he wouldn't accuse the
president of linguistic hair-splitting when he said, ``It depends
on what the meaning of the word `is' is,'' in his grand jury
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a legal proceeding, he wasn't in a television
show,'' Wensberg said from his home in Manhattan. ``He was talking
before a grand jury and to prosecutors. Legal proceedings turn on
the definition of a word. Language is the currency of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   One might say the president's statement was appropriate, to use
a fashionable word. But would that be an appropriate use of
``appropriate''? To put it another way, would it be fitting? Yes.
But ``appropriate'' is not always appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When President Clinton said his dalliance with Ms. Lewinsky
was `not appropriate' it sounded terribly prim and fancy,''
Wensberg said. ``He sounded like his own psychotherapist. It was
doubly silly because in the next breath he said that it was
`wrong,' a word everyone understands.''
</P>
<P>
   What about ``dalliance''? Isn't that an example of fancy speech?
Wensberg says it isn't. ``Dalliance is a wonderful old word for
hanky-panky, whoopee, whatever you want to call it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex'' perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally I wonder whether words are the best means for
talking about language,'' Wensberg said. ``But they're all we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The verb ``address'' is rampant now. ``Nobody ever thinks about
anything anymore, or discusses something, they address
everything,'' he said. ``Especially politicans, to whom the word is
very useful because all it promises is that one will turn one's
attention to something, or possibly just turn one's head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Speak to'' is the evil twin of ``address,'' Wensberg says.
``Your attitude doesn't speak to my feelings. Your actions don't
speak to my needs. It comes straight out of the law,'' he said.
``It's terribly vague and windy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wensberg said he became ``almost painfully aware'' of other
people's speech while he was researching and revising the book.
``Although my friends say I don't go around correcting people,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes earlier I'd said, ``We seem compelled to use
florid language.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd question your use of `compel,''' Wensberg said. I deserved
that.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of ``Modern American Usage'' is to help people think
about the words they use. If they did, he says, perhaps they
wouldn't use so many evasive, fashionable, silly words.
</P>
<P>
   ``The infant imitates what he hears, and thereby learns words,''
Wensberg said. ``The instinct stays very strong. The media have a
terribly powerful effect. I think sometimes, on very bad days, that
we are coming down to a vocabulary of about 17 words. I listen to
politicians and broadcasters to see how swiftly they get from
`focus' to `address' to `frustrated' to `issues.' They're boring
the public to death and any experienced writer or speaker knows
that's failure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
