<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSE COMPROMISE OVER COERCION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We introduced our friends Judith and Michael with a warning.
``We're not fixing you up,'' I said when I invited them both to
dinner. ``We think you'll enjoy each other's company, but that's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith and Mike were both unconventional, outspoken, and
exuberant, far too similar to fit well together. I not only thought
they'd each probably do best with a quiet, soft-spoken partner, I
had an additional reservation. I'd been in both Mike's and Judith's
kitchens. There was no way these two could ever share the same
space.
</P>
<P>
   Mike's kitchen in Wellesley, Mass. was lined with bookcases,
each filled with mysterious large glass bottles. In them were
chilis he'd brought back from Arizona, beans of all colors, exotic
condiments, and strange spices. Mike's kitchen was part laboratory,
part work of art, and in it he created elaborate meals from
scratch. Having often lingered over mouth-watering meals at his
kitchen table, I'd come to the conclusion the last thing he needed
was another cook.
</P>
<P>
   Judith, herself, was a whirlwind in the kitchen. All you ever
noticed in her kitchen was Judith, bustling from sink to
refrigerator to oven, hauling out stacks of Hanukkah latkes, baking
chocolate desserts so rich they could have made the Fortune 500
list, mixing, stirring, and energetically tossing scraps from the
cutting board onto the compost heap right outside her kitchen door.
Judith was Betty Crocker on steroids, prepared to feed a dozen
guests at the drop of a hat. Having watched her work miracles in a
kitchen stuffed to the gills with the implements of her trade, I
couldn't imagine another cook in her kitchen either.
</P>
<P>
   But what do I know? Mike and Judith saw stars the minute they
laid eyes on each other and married without a thought as to whether
there was a kitchen in this world big enough to hold them both.
Sure enough, I was right. The course of love never runs smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike couldn't get over the fact that I don't wring out the
sponges when I finish doing the dishes,'' Judith told me as we
chatted after an exercise class. ``In the meantime, I've been
amazed that he never notices when he spills things on the kitchen
floor. We were both trying to change in order to please the other,
but without much success. Then one day I said to him, `Look, I'll
wring out the sponges if you'll clean the floor,' and it's
working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is?'' I said, feeling a sense of deja vu. My friend Lynn
and I used to argue about this all the time. We could never resolve
the question of whether asking tit for tat is a form of barter or
blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn always advocated giving love freely, without ever measuring
what you got in return. She didn't approve of adding an element of
coercion to negotiations, or of withholding any loving act as a
spur to action. For my part, l was in favor of all the leverage I
could get.
</P>
<P>
   I've come to see, however, that there's a difference between
withholding a service you're already providing and moving into
brand new territory. If you've already agreed without protest, say,
to act as the hostess to your husband's business collegues, it
isn't really fair to suggest that unless your husband is willing to
meet some demand of yours, you'll have to rethink those dinner
parties. That is a threat. Still, if you ask for what you want
without results, must you leave it at that? Isn't there something
more you can do?
</P>
<P>
   Forget the if-you-loved-me routine. No matter what you attach to
it, the perfect comeback is ``If you loved me, you'd accept me
exactly as I am.'' Emotional outbursts with no discernible results
turn out in the end to be a waste of everybody's time. Punishments,
like sulking or not speaking, usually create a whole new cycle of
resentment.
</P>
<P>
   I'm growing more and more fond of straight-forward transactions
like Judith's. The proposition goes: ``Look, hon, I really want you
to do this for me. What would I have to do in return to make that
attractive?''
</P>
<P>
   This only works, of course, if the people involved are
reasonable and caring. There's no room for cruel jibes, like ``How
about losing 25 pounds?'' There's no place for folks who want
something without being willing to give something in return. You
need a certain generosity of spirit to suceed at this marital
version of, ``Let's Make a Deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Now let's see. Jack's beaten me at gin rummy the last 11 times
we've played. I wonder what it would take to get him to throw a few
games my way?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
