<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MASSACRE-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO RECALLS 1968 STUDENT MASSACRE WITH NEW DEMANDS FOR TRUTH
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    EDs: Oct. 2 is the 30th anniversary of the 1968 student
massacre.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Sept. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It began with a police crackdown on students
playing football and ended in a horrific massacre that has scarred
Mexico for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans call it Tlatelolco (pronounced, tla-tay-Lol-ko), one of
the names for an ancient plaza here where scores, perhaps hundreds
of students and others were shot down by soldiers during a peaceful
rally on Oct. 2, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how many really died in the sudden attack, carried
out on the eve of the 1968 Olympic Games here. And nobody was held
accountable for the carnage, which tarnished Mexico's reputation
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a generation later -- as Tlatelolco's 30th
anniversary approaches -- Mexicans emboldened by a more democratic
era are demanding answers and an end to official secrecy about what
really happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still victims of Tlatelolco,'' said Ana Ignacia
Rodriguez, who was a 22-year-old law student who survived the
massacre only to be detained at gunpoint and sentenced to 16 years
in prison on trumped up sedition charges.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was released after two years, but black-listed from
jobs. Trained as a lawyer, she rejected the profession because she
forever lost faith in Mexico's justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Aguayo, a champion of fair elections in Mexico, said
Tlatelolco ``was a parting of the waters, especially because of the
violent methods of repression that were used.'' He is author of
``1968: Archives of Violence,'' one of a number of new books about
Tlatelolco that are now being published.
</P>
<P>
   A committee established last year in Mexico's newly pluralistic
Congress is expected to issue a report on Tlatelolco in October. It
has been investigating recently unsealed archives belonging to
Mexico's Interior Ministry, which is charge of domestic security.
</P>
<P>
   Some committee members are opposition politicians who are
Tlatelolco survivors; they were elected to Congress last year,
breaking nearly 70 years of monopoly by Mexico's dominant
Revolutionary Institutional Party.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the student protests that swept the world in 1968 -- for
democracy, against the Vietnam War -- Mexico's was perhaps the most
violently repressed, investigators say. The brutal attempt to
establish total control stripped away an image of benevolence the
government was struggling to project during the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Today, military records on Tlatelolco remain sealed. But Aguayo
and others have pieced together accounts of how -- and who -- was
behind the bloodshed by reviewing unsealed Mexican archives and
thousands of memos produced by the American CIA, the FBI, the U.S.
Embassy in Mexico and other U.S. agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for clues and international reaction, Aguayo also
found a treasure of information among International Olympic
Committee records in Europe and in the Lyndon Baines Johnson
Library archives at the University of Texas in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a plan mounted by the government to get rid of the
student movement before the Olympics. There's no doubt,'' Aguayo
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government of then-President Gustavo Diaz Ordaz, considered
a stern authoritarian, didn't plan on killing so many students,
Aguayo said. But it was willing to use violence to stop the student
movement before the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest bombshell Aguayo found in archives is an apparent
pattern of international support for Mexico's decision to act
harshly.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, stories swirled that the students were financially
supported or armed by Cuba or the Soviet Union. Versions of these
tales appear in Cold War-influenced FBI memos dispatched to the
United States from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Aguayo said, ``evidence of outside support for the
students doesn't exist. All the evidence is that the outside
support was for the government of Mexico. This is very noteworthy
because the Soviet Union, Cuba, Washington, they all supported the
government of Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely spark for the 1968 protests was a fight that broke
out that summer between two schools engaged in a casual game of
touch football. Police brutally intervened, angering students
throughout Mexico City. Even current Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo, who was 16, joined in some protests and was photographed
confronting police.
</P>
<P>
   Students were also primed by growing discontent over a lack of
freedom of speech and concern for political prisoners, including
imprisoned labor activists who were trying to break from Mexico's
government-controlled unions.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the summer, students marched for the repeal of a law
that gave authorities sweeping power to imprison dissidents. They
also wanted the dissolution of a repressive special police unit
they considered unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the consciousness of the young people and people in
general, the idea was growing that in Mexico there were no
democratic freedoms,'' recalled Rodriguez, the former law student.
``And we wanted freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Police occupied high schools and universities and began
imprisoning students. On Oct. 2, Rodriguez said, students gathered
for a legal assembly in Tlatelolco. The site is also called the
Plaza of the Three Cultures because it is surrounded by Aztec
pyramids, a colonial church and modern high-rise apartment
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   As dusk fell, investigators say, a secret police force known as
the Olympic Brigade opened fire on the crowd, provoking soldiers to
begin shooting. People of all ages were killed, indiscriminately,
while others ran for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The official version of the story was that armed students fired
on soldiers. Aguayo said some of a hard core of protestors may have
returned fire, but his research shows that they were few and not
responsible for the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers were censured in the aftermath of the shooting and
surviving student leaders were rounded up. The government offered
three different numbers -- none over 50 -- for how many died. The
figure is probably closer to 200 or 300, according to reporters who
attempted to independently investigate the death toll.
</P>
<P>
   Some survivors are calling for military officers from the era to
be forced to testify before Mexican or international investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the special congressional committee vainly attempted
to glean new information from former President Luis Echeverria, who
was Diaz Ordaz's interior minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need the truth,'' said Elena Poniatowska, a Mexican
journalist and novelist who in 1971 published ``The Night of
Tlatelolco,'' a shattering account of survivors' experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez believes Mexico's archives on Tlatelolco have probably
been sanitized, although she supports opening up all information as
well as investigating foreign archives.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after the massacre, Rodriguez was kidnapped by
police, blindfolded and interrogated and sentenced to prison in an
unconstitutional trial with fabricated evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine, a girl of 22. I pinched myself and told myself this
couldn't be happening to me,'' said Rodriguez, who now helps run a
Mexico City center that teaches women new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Tlatelolco, Rodriguez said, frightened Mexicans and forced them
to accept authoritarian rule for a time. But it also inspired
massive outrage over voter fraud in the 1980s as well as the
country's current movement for greater democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico before 1968 was one country,'' Rodriguez said, ``and
after 1968 it was another.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
