<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2215 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARTER-BOX-$ADV26-COX     09-24 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTER-BOX-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CASHLESS SOCIETY: A BARTER DEAL IN RUSSIA IS BORN
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-BARTER-$ADV26.
 &HT;    EDs: Saratov is on the Volga River about 450 miles south of
Moscow.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Sept. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOV, Russia _ ``It involves a lot of time and nerves and
risks,'' Fyodor Shimchuk says of barter. He is general director of
Sapkon/Neftemash, a company in southern Russia that makes pumps and
valves for the oil and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, it took a dozen negotiators from his company
and others more than two months to complete a barter deal involving
$100,000 worth of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it unfolded:
</P>
<P>
   1. A natural gas drilling facility in Yamburg, above the Arctic
Circle, needed replacement parts: $100,000 worth of safety valves
and pumps.
</P>
<P>
   2. In Saratov, about 1,500 miles southwest of Yamburg, a company
called Sapkon/Neftemash makes the pumps and valves.
</P>
<P>
   3. The two companies began negotiations after Yamburg said it
did not have the cash to pay for the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   4. Yamburg is a subsidiary of Russia's natural gas monopoly,
Gazprom, headquartered in Moscow. Yamburg asked Gazprom to give
Sapkon/Neftemash $100,000 worth of natural gas in return for the
pumps and valves.
</P>
<P>
   5. Gazprom agreed, ordering its subsidiary in Saratov to provide
the gas.
</P>
<P>
   6. But Sapkon/Neftemash, the pump manufacturer, had no use for
natural gas. However, it owed about $100,000 to the local electric
company, Sarenergo.
</P>
<P>
   7. Sarenergo didn't need natural gas either. But its subsidiary
did -- the power plant that actually produces the electricity.
</P>
<P>
   8. So the chain was completed. Simply put, the Arctic drilling
station paid Sapkon/Neftemash for the valves and pumps with
$100,000 worth of natural gas. But four other companies and
affiliates also were involved in the complex circle of bartering.
</P>
<P>
   Since no cash traded hands, Sapkon/Neftemash is hard-pressed to
pay its workers. Also, under Russia's tax system the company will
have to record the value of the transaction -- $100,000 -- and pay
taxes on the sale, money it does not have.
</P>
<P>
   Without barter, the company would survive, but would be forced
to make major layoffs and pay cuts, Shimchuk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the barter negotiations reach a critical point where
our suppliers can do nothing else but pay cash,'' says Shimchuk,
``and for that we are very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
