<HEADLINE>
`FARMER'S WIFE' FAMILY DOING WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Everything's a lot better,'' says Darrel Buschkoetter, the
Lawrence, Neb., husband/father/farmer whose rollercoaster family
struggles with his wife Juanita and three young daughters were
dramatically recounted in the acclaimed three-part PBS
``Frontline'' and Independent Television Service special ``The
Farmer's Wife,'' which concluded Wednesday night PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Buschkoetter, speaking by phone from the busy kitchen of his
home last night, updated the family fortunes since the filming
concluded. ``Juanita saved us,'' he said, referring to his wife's
emotional and financial rescue efforts for the family. ``Our
finances are in order. My dad retired and I bought his equipment.
Everything's going great.'' As for the public's reaction to the
series, he said, ``it's been real positive from all over the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   He was awaiting the arrival of Juanita from her job in town.
She'd just returned after going on a round of media appearances
surrounding the broadcast of the special.
</P>
<P>
   Independent filmmaker David Sutherland of Newton, Mass., who
filmed the family over three years, said Juanita's successful
takeover of the family fortunes at their bleakest has transformed
her. She's become so confident and proficient that ``she could run
for public office.'' And ``Darrel is a changed man, thanks to
therapy,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland said he talked to Juanita by telephone Monday night
and that she was ``very excited'' by the response to their story.
The response included a letter of greetings from Hillary Rodham
Clinton and regret that she missed Juanita's testimony in
Washington Sept. 15 before a Democratic hearing on agricultural
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The family was invited to Washington by Senator Bob Kerrey
(D-Neb.). They've also been presented the National Catholic Rural
Life Conference's first St. Isidore and Maria Award honoring a
rural couple's ``fidelity to a dream, to a vocation and to love
combined with family integrity, stewardship, and religion.''
They'll receive the award in November in Des Moines. Willie Nelson
also invited them to ``Farm Aid'' in Illinois, Oct. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
