<HEADLINE>
`JESSE''S SINGULAR STRENGTH IS CHRISTINA APPLEGATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
JESSE 
Starring: Christina Applegate, George Dzundza, Bruno Campos, David
DeLuise, John Lehr, Eric Lloyd 
On: NBC 
Time: Thursday at 8:30 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We may as well go ahead and order up the bouquets for Christina
Applegate and her new sitcom, ``Jesse,'' in celebration of their
preordained landing in the Nielsen Top10. Blessed by NBC with the
time slot between ``Friends'' and ``Frasier,'' their ratings
success is one of those TV sure things. But let's put FTD on hold
regarding flowery critical praise for this unformed single-mom
comedy, a very maybe proposition that could get a whole lot funnier
(see: ``Just Shoot Me''), if it doesn't get a whole lot freakier
and more foolish first (don't see: ``Veronica's Closet'').
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, NBC premiered ``Conrad Bloom,'' about a Mr.
Nice Guy who is suffocated by the many women in his life. ``Jesse''
sets up the opposite situation, with a heroine much in demand with
the boys _ big and little _ in her life. She's a waitress at Der
Biergarten, a Buffalo establishment owned by her gruff dad, and she
lives nearby with her 10-year-old son. Her two brothers are
frequently on hand, one of whom is a witless entrepreneur, and she
is facing her first romance in years with her new neighbor, Diego,
who comes a-courting in episode 2 bearing Pablo Neruda poems.
Meanwhile, deadbeat dudes at the bar keep hitting on her, despite
the fact that her outfit makes her look ``like the girl from the
Ricola commercial,'' as Diego points out.
</P>
<P>
   It's a working-class slice of life, although this is Thursday
night after ``Friends,'' so the hipness level (and the haircut
standard) is definitely higher than a ``Roseanne''-type show such
as ``The King of Queens.'' Applegate's Jesse looks like a less
coddled version of Jennifer Aniston, and her brother, John Jr., is
a classically cool slacker figure. Philosophical and long-haired,
he has taken a vow of silence ``until he can find a way to use
language in a more efficient manner,'' Jesse explains. John Jr.'s
wordlessness is an obvious gimmick, but one that, if handled with a
light touch, could push the show's family scenes beyond cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rest of Jesse's gang are fairly stock characters,
particularly Jesse's father, John Sr., played by George Dzundza. He
is a gross bigot, given to amazement that William Shatner is Jewish
since he ``never pictured those people in space,'' and yet he's
presented as lovable and cuddly _ the 1990s,
can't-we-all-just-get-along answer to Archie Bunker. He's openly
displeased that his daughter is dating Diego, who is from Chile.
Also, Jesse's thick-headed brother Darren has the not-very-original
problem of being hooked on get-rich-quick schemes, which tonight
finds him in possession of far too many unpainted garden gnomes.
</P>
<P>
   Applegate emerges from this mixed bag as a real natural. Best
known for her years as the slutty Kelly Bundy on ``Married ... With
Children,'' she projects intelligence, sanity, and vulnerability as
Jesse. She's believable as both an assured, loving mother and a
single woman terrified of getting hurt by a man. The show's
creators, the same folks behind ``Friends'' and ``Veronica's
Closet,'' need to resist using her relationship with Diego as an
ongoing romantic tease (like Ross and Rachel on ``Friends,'' or
Caroline and Richard on ``Caroline in the City''). Applegate plays
the only single mother on the big network sitcoms, and she's strong
enough to carry the show without relying on silly wedding high
jinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
