<SLUG> BC-MA-HMO-RATINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED SEEN FOR IMPROVEMENT IN MASSACHUSETTS HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Gauging the HMOs text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Although Massachusetts is home to some of the best
health maintenance organizations in America, there is plenty of
room for them to improve, according to three reports released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, from the National Committee for Quality Assurance,
the Massachusetts Medical Society and US News &AMP; World Report,
reflect efforts to make HMOs more accountable to an increasingly
skeptical public.
</P>
<P>
   The most comprehensive of the three comes from the National
Committee for Quality Assurance, which released detailed
information on nearly 300 health plans across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While Massachusetts HMOs as a whole performed considerably
better than their peers nationwide, the report showed considerable
variation in the quality of individual health plans. For example,
the percentage of patients given follow-up care after they are
discharged from hospitalization for mental illness ranged from 69
percent for patients of United Health Care of New England in
Providence to 93 percent at Fallon Community Health Plan in
Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   A second report from the Massachusetts Medical Society suggested
that while doctors were generally satisfied with health plans, they
are annoyed with the administrative hassles of dealing with HMOs.
The survey of 1,685 doctors also reported dissatisfaction with the
quality of mental health care provided by HMOs, as well as the
managed care industry's use of financial incentives to mold
physician behavior. Physicians also gave health plans low marks for
the quality of information HMOs give consumers, and in the plans'
ability to coordinate care between specialists and primary care
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs took the comments as constructive criticism, saying they
are already looking at ways to improve care and reduce red tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``If managed care works better for doctors, they will work
better for patients, too,'' said Dr. Kathryn J. Goonan, chief
medical officer for Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts plans fared well in a third report, from US News &AMP;
World Report, capturing five of the top 10 spots in the magazine's
third annual list of the nation's best HMOs. Fallon was ranked No.
1, Tufts Health Plan in Waltham was No. 3, Harvard Pilgrim Health
Care in Brookline ranked No. 4, Healthsource Massachusetts in
Worcester was No. 6, and Blue Cross was No. 10. Even so, the plans'
scores on member satisfaction, though higher than their national
peers, averaged 70 out of a possible 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
