   &UR; OTHER WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-POVERTY (Washington) _ President Clinton announces new
census numbers on income and poverty: For the third year running,
American household income rose and poverty rates fell in 1997,
returning the nation to pre-recession 1989 levels. Last year, 13.3
percent of Americans lived in poverty, down from 13.7 percent in
1996, a drop led by blacks and Hispanics. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-COAL (Washington) _ The EPA issues a final rule requiring
Midwestern coal-fired power plants and other polluters to reduce
smog-producing emissions. The big difference will be seen in lower
smog levels in 22 eastern states. By John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SUICIDE (Washington) _ The House expects to debate and
vote today on a measure, sponsored by Rep. Henry Hyde, that would
undercut Oregon's new law allowing doctors to assist patient
suicides. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
