<P>
   MORGAN-EARNINGS (New York) _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which
said at the start of the month that trading losses from tumbling
markets around the world would cut quarterly net income by $110
million, posts a 4.9 percent decline in net for the fiscal quarter,
a smaller decrease than analysts had expected. By Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other financial &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-AUTOS (Taubate, Brazil) _ The Brazilian car industry is
slamming on the brakes. Next week, 20,000 Volkswagen workers in the
country will start 10 days of forced vacation, while those at Ford
will have to stay home for 12 days. Mercedes will send workers home
for two days, and workers at General Motors will stay home for 11
days in October. Just two years ago, Brazil was viewed as the most
promising new market for car makers, the natural gateway to more
than 300 million consumers in Latin America. But now that the
international financial crisis is buffeting Brazil and the rest of
Latin America, all bets are off. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:50 p.m., the industrial average was
down 49 points, the Nasdaq index was off 12 points. Overseas,
prices rose 3 percent in Tokyo and 4.4 percent in Hong Kong. They
fell 2.4 percent in Frankfurt, 0.7 percent in London and 0.8
percent in Brazil, but they rose 1.2 percent in Mexico. On the
American debt market, the long bond was off 6/32 point at midday,
with the yield at 5.18 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
