<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESSES THAT ARE UNABASHEDLY ROMANTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Designer Jessica McClintock has come a long way
from dimity-and-lace empire hippie dresses like the one Hillary
Rodham was married in. But her focus has remained the same _
romantic dresses for young women.
</P>
<P>
   The Holiday collection McClintock showed at the American Cancer
Society high tea in San Francisco Wednesday afternoon was romance
personified. Big foufy skirts, boned bustiers, acres of black
velvet and discreet sparkle. Gowns not only for high school
sweeties, but for their mothers who have kept their waistlines.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock's aim has never been haute couture although many of
her clothes are reminiscent of Vera Wang's more linear looks,
particularly a cloth-of-gold, strapless, floor-length sheath shown
with a notched lapel duster. Instead, she has dressed prom queens
and bridesmaids. Now, she's dressing the young woman who has more
taste than money. Her most expensive looks run $450 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   The prettiest dresses were quite Belle Epoque in feel,
particularly taffetas (especially a deep ruby-cranberry, perfect
for Christmas parties) worn with glittery collars of pearls or
rhinestones. These clothes, by the way, require nice shoulders,
slim backs and a straight carriage.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's show, McClintock presented a lot of the same
shapes in different fabrics like sleek, light-catching velvets in
black, deep plum, bottle green, chocolate brown and anthracite;
rusty taffetas in midnight blue, cranberry, green and champagne;
lace over taffeta, poly-silk and velvet. Or lace over sequins for a
twinkle hint of sheen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sequins are soooo '80s,'' said McClintock's niece, Jessica.
</P>
<P>
   The best looks are separates so tops and skirts could be mixed
and matched. There were boned bustiers or bateau-necked,
long-sleeved, corsetry-boned tops over bustled skirts, either
straight with ruched backs or full-on ball skirts. What slip
dresses there were (we call them sheaths now) were cut very low in
the back, some with rhinestone or jet-beaded straps. Then there
were the nipped waist, Shakespearean-style jackets with faux-fur
(mink, Persian lamb or nutria) collars and cuffs.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, this is a line that mothers and daughters will fight
over.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Neiman Marcus Christmas wish book is in the mail and this
year there are affordable presents among the outlandishly expensive
ones. But no one really wants to know about $10 stocking stuffers,
now, do they? We'd rather imagine what it would be like to be able
to afford a pound of Petrossian Beluga just as an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   This year's fantasy gifts are a hodgepodge of the affordable
versus the ridiculous. What they all have in common, however, is
boomer nostalgia. There are, for instance, blue-painted benches
from Ebbets Field for $2,750 (seats two tushes) and $3,750 (a
three-seater). Then there is Neiman's yearly piece de resistance, a
one-of-a-kind carousel with six animals including a goat, a lion
and three different horses; 270 lights; an emergency-stop button;
solid brass poles, but no brass ring. It can be yours for $300,000,
first dibs, first served. And finally, a real childhood memory:
Cracker Jacks. His and Hers with fine jewelry prizes inside. For
her (at $950): a gold and ruby ring; for him (at $400): enamel
cufflinks in the shape of Cracker Jack boxes. Memories don't come
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do Paola Quadretti's cashmere jackets, created from Loro
Piana cashmere fabric. The teensy, blond, Florentine women's wear
designer was at Gretchen DeWitt's Sausalito aerie last week after
spending three days at Laura Fay's, showing her fall line to the
faithful who include Norah Stone, Sandra Mosbacher Lloyd, Vaughn de
Guigne and Frances Bowes. Quadretti's clothes are created from
couture fabrics, mostly Ungaro and Valentino. They cost one-third
of the price they'd be in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Clients enjoy selecting the fabric for one-of-a-kind outfits
which Quadretti tailors to their measurements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAKEUP-HNS &LR;      09-24 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKEUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL COLORS DRESS UP A GRAY SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Makeup is the form that follows fashion. And
fashion this fall is very, very gray and luxuriously textured.
Cashmere on suede. Crushed velvets. Menswear stripes with lace.
Sequins glinting quietly under organza. The clothes are also
deceptively simple, mostly linear takeoffs on American sportswear,
gussied up in luxury fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   And to carry them off, the face must be fresh and vivid. Color
has to cut through all that fashionable gray fog.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the lips. All of the big cosmetic houses have
done lipsticks in the burgundy/plum/deep red families. Lips,
however, are not as defined by pencil as before. These lipsticks
can be daubed on with the finger (Chanel's new LipBlush in Bizarre,
a satisfying velvet stain in dark cabernet). Francois Nars' Colette
is the purplest in a crop of plums and burgundies. It's a sheer
that either glosses on alone or over another color or builds into a
stained-glass shine with double application.
</P>
<P>
   Chanel's special ``Temptress'' fall collection features
Sorceress, a dark burgundy brown lipstick; Lauder's ``Bejeweled''
collection has two baroquely gem-like lip colors including Antique
Amethyst, a purply fuchsia which is great for blondes, and Simply
Red, a deep brown-scarlet, which was brought back from last year.
Yves Saint Laurent's ``In Love Again'' collection presents a sunny
coral red (Rouge Pur No. 41) and a blue red (Rouge Pur No. 42).
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the most outrageous collection was makeup artist Fred
Faruggia's ``Rouge'' for Lancome. The lipsticks are volcanic and
intense reds, particularly Rouge Thermique, a scarlet of great
depth and vivacity. Faruggia, brought in last year to enliven the
line, has created an avant-garde specialty line, reportedly
``walking off counters,'' says Women's Wear Daily.
</P>
<P>
   The entire look _ red, red lips, highly rouged cheeks and red
eye shadows, liners and mascaras _ in the wrong hands could turn
you into a Kabuki bunny. Which is why it's nice to get to know your
sales staff and have them teach you how to wear it. The red liner
alone is a great accent, but the shadows that come in three
textures (frosted, matte and cream) are like TNT in the hands of a
baby. Better used in small doses.
</P>
<P>
   Eyelids in general have invited lots of deep and interesting
color this fall. YSL's In Love Again Eyes No. 5 compact is
definitely redhead colors with a smoky blue, a hunter green, a
violet and a burnished gold. Shadow deeply or fluff on for sheer
color. Chanel's Quadra Shadow compact, Mysteres, is a child's
palette of jade green, cider-cognac, topaz brown and gold worn with
a brandy-hued eye pencil and scads of black mascara. Dior's
Visionary Violets fall eye compact from the ``Les Tenebreuses''
Shadow and Light collection mixes up a smokier scheme with dark
blues, juxtaposed against chocolate brown and highlighted with
golden beige and deep, grayed lilac.
</P>
<P>
   Texture and depth of color are important new fall trends,
particularly on the lips.
</P>
<P>
   There is a new category of lip shine _ Industrial Strength Lip
Gloss _ which has the depth of car paint on the lips. Dior's
Plastic Shine really says it all. As thick and rich in pigment as
lipstick, it goes on like a gloss with a foam-tipped applicator but
looks like vinyl instead of some wimpy no-hue pastel. YSL's comes
in two forms _ Lip Lacquer which leaves a deep, mirror-shine of
intense color and Intense Lipcolor, which is a velvety matte.
</P>
<P>
   Prescriptives, meanwhile, has reformulated its lip gloss in a
tube into a high-shine formula made to last a long time on the
lips. And L'Oreal's Rouge Pulp has gotten some good results in the
lower-priced makeup category.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BeautyMart: Glitter and be gay: Coming for the holiday _ glitter
gels and fluff-on powders of pure glitter. Lancome's
Micro-Paillettes are holographic specks of shine that pick up light
and sparkle like crazy, just like fairy dust. Designed to light up
Fred Faruggia's all-red face, the Micro-Paillettes look extra
glittery fluffed on over Poudre Blanc Neige, Lancome's sheer
compact powder which goes on with a fiber-optic brush. Look for
face and body glitter from Chanel (a gel), YSL (gold and silver
glide-on creams and bright silver glitter); Maybelline (lavender
and golden glitters) and Lauder (an entire line of golden face
gleamers, lipsticks and nail glazes).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turn up the heat: Thermasilk hair products, developed by Helene
Curtis gives you a lot of bang(s) for the buck. These products are
heat-activated, starting with shampoo and conditioner. The Light
Conditioning Mist leave-in conditioner is a good protectant against
the thermal heat of hair dryers and the Shape &AMP; Hold Spray holds
without build-up. The price is right, too: $2.99 to $3.49.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Portable practicality: Francois Nars, whose runway looks for
Nicole Miller and Anna Sui were quite shiny and Barbie-like for
fall, has developed two very practical all-in-one makeup compacts,
called Artists' Palates. One is Skin Deep, in warm neutrals, and
the other is Lust for Life, a compendium of cooler burgundies,
roses and grays to match this fall's major gray color story. Using
existing colors from his extensive line, Nars has grouped three
lipsticks, two blushes and three eye colors in one flat black
rubber compact with a huge mirror. Says Nars' makeup artist at Saks
Fifth Avenue in San Francisco, Robert Williams, ``You don't have to
carry brushes. You can use it all at your fingertips for a quick
makeup that always looks perfect. The only thing you have to add is
mascara.'' For the privilege of packing light, the Artist Palates
are $58, Saks only.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
