<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
RONIN-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ It's no surprise that ``Ronin,'' John
Frankenheimer's new thriller about a group of post-Cold War
mercenaries pursuing a mysterious briefcase, contains some
electrifying car-chase scenes that wind through the streets of
Paris and Nice. After all, auto racing has always been a passion
with him. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
NATASCHA-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ Natascha McElhone, who has
co-starred with heavyweights like Harrison Ford, Anthony Hopkins,
Brad Pitt and Jim Carrey, gets to be the only female in John
Frankenheimer's action thriller starring Robert De Niro. It's a
heavy-duty ensemble, which suited McElhone fine, since she's not,
as she puts it, a ``popcorn actress.'' By Bob Strauss. 
. 
DEATH-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ Death was the common denominator at the
recent Los Angeles International Short Film Festival, though the
two major category winners took a different slant on this most
universal theme. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
CLAY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ A decent though not exactly inspired
black comedy, ``Clay Pigeons'' boasts just enough grotesquerie and
gallows humor to sustain interest. However, it doesn't make much of
a point beyond the obvious one that very bad things can happen when
you mess with your friends and neighbors. 3 stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
MONUMENT-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Monument Ave.'' is a potentially
engrossing tale of working class Irish Americans fighting yuppie
encroachment on their Boston neighborhood by, mainly, stealing the
yups' stuff. But the script stumbles almost immediately and never
regains its footing. 2 stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
PECKER-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Pecker,'' the latest from John
Waters, is packed with indie movie scene stars and built around an
actually cinematic idea. Though this film has some merit, it just
doesn't deliver the fun it thinks we're having with it. 2{ stars.
By Bob Strauss. 
. 
RONIN-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ John Frankenheimer's stylish new
thriller, ``Ronin,'' wears its ambiguity like a badge of honor. Its
world-weary characters never spell out their motives or their
allegiances while chasing a mysterious briefcase. Frankenheimer
succeeds in turning all this mystery to the film's advantage,
though. 3 stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
SHADRACH-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Shadrach'' is a pleasant,
exceedingly minor feature film that works best as an anecdotal
memory piece set in the Depression Era South and less well when it
gets condescending and preachy. 2{ stars By Bob Strauss. 
. 
URBAN-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Urban Legend'' follows in the
footsteps of ``Scream'' and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,''
with enough blood and suspense to go along with the complete lack
of logic to satisfy most fans of the horror genre. 2{ stars. By
Glenn Whipp. 
. 
DEATH-STAGE (Los Angeles) _ Jack Klugman's intensity and the strong
ensemble cast make ``Death of a Saleman'' at the Falcon Theatre a
production worth seeing. By Reed Johnson. 
. 
MEMORY-STAGE (Los Angeles) _ Even Oedipus might conclude that the
unexamined life isn't so bad after all, if he had to face the
dilemma confronting Russell Burke, the troubled hero of Jonathan
Tolins' ambitious but erratic new play about the culture of
victimology, ``If Memory Serves,'' at the Pasadena Plyhouse. By
Reed Johnson. 
. 
MASSIVE-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Call it trip-hop, English psychedelia
or just plain dance music for shut-ins. Whatever you dub it,
Massive Attack has stumbled upon one of the most seductive pop
confections of the decade. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ British music author Simon Reynolds, a
senior editor at Spin magazine in New York, wrote the fascinating
``Generation Ecstasy'' (Little, Brown; $25), which traces the
history of the rave scene and, by extension, electronic music forms
such as techno, drum 'n' bass, trip-hop and jungle, as well as
pirate radio and the illegal speed-based drug Ecstacy. By Fred
Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ ``Titanic,'' the blockbuster that
declares love means never having to say you're soggy, has spawned a
soundtrack sequel, this one featuring Celine Dion's ubiquitous
radio-only version of ``My Heart Will Go On'' with dialogue from
Jack and Rose. Also included is composer James Horner's new
``Titanic Suite'' and ``Epilogue: The Deep and Timeless Sea,'' two
symphonic works with themes from the main score interwoven. By Fred
Shuster. 
. 
DANGEROUS-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ ``Dangerous Beauty'' is a historic
sexual romp that's both light and fun and with enough witty
rapartee, swordplay and boudoir high jinks to be entertaining. At
other times, though, the film can't seem to decide if it is itself
sexploitation or is about the serious theme of the suppression of
women. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
