<HEADLINE>
PLOT TAKES BACK SEAT TO ACTION IN `RONIN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ John Frankenheimer's stylish new thriller,
``Ronin,'' wears its ambiguity like a badge of honor. Its
world-weary characters never spell out their motives or their
allegiances while chasing a mysterious briefcase, the contents of
which are never revealed to them or to the audience. (Maybe it's
the same items contained in that case from ``Pulp Fiction.'') If
you were confused by the often incoherent complexities of
``Mission: Impossible,'' you might as well throw up the white flag
here. Plot takes a back seat to action and atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer succeeds in turning all this mystery to the film's
advantage, though, creating a gritty, stark, old-fashioned
international action caper that offers the pleasure of frenetic car
chases and scenic French locales in place of digitally driven
special effects. A solid international cast that includes Robert De
Niro, Jean Reno, Natascha McElhone and Jonathan Pryce lends the
needed emotional weight to their often interchangeable characters,
a ragtag group of covert operatives called together to steal the
cryptic case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronin'' begins with an unnecessary written prologue that
explains the film's title, some mumbo-jumbo about shamed samurai
warriors who have failed to protect their masters. It's a metaphor
that is used again later in the film to lend some kind of
psychological motivation to the jaded, exhausted spies in the
movie. It's a nice try, but the screenplay by J.D. Zeik and Richard
Weisz (the latter a pseudonym for David Mamet, who did a complete
rewrite) never quite manages to make flesh out its characters and
make them into real people who resonate with the audience.
Ambiguity is one thing, confusion another entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Ronin'' bristles with the sort of post-Cold War
skulduggery that informs a good John LeCarre novel. The early part
of the movie finds De Niro wandering through the dimly lit streets
of Paris' Montmartre district, arriving at a small bar where the
patrons regard him and each other with open suspicion. Soon,
they're moving to a warehouse where McElhone, the Irish ringleader,
tells them about the briefcase and their mission to steal it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, given the level of subterfuge here, it's obvious some
of these free-agent rogues might have their own agendas. To the
movie's credit, you never know whom to trust (or for that matter,
what exactly is going on), which sets into motion some thrilling
high-speed chases through the streets and tunnels of Paris (you
can't help but think of Princess Diana's final ride) and the tight,
winding roadways surrounding Nice. Frankenheimer is an old pro at
such stuff, having been a racer himself and having made the classic
car movie ``Grand Prix,'' so the scenes crackle with an excitement
typically lacking in chase scenes.
</P>
<P>
   In a movie where the action, not the dialogue, reveals
character, the actors have enough of a presence and allure to keep
their performances interesting. De Niro is always fun to watch, and
here, he gets to blow up things. His character, an old CIA agent
who's apparently on the run, seems perpetually both tired and
amused, even in the most dire of circumstances, such as when he's
on a makeshift operating table having a bullet removed from his
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scene that will make even the most hardened moviegoer
squirm, but De Niro somehow makes it a pleasure, albeit a gruesome
one. Happily for audiences, ``Ronin's'' diversions are many and
varied, and you don't have to be a masochist to like it. Unless, of
course, you need to have every little plot detail spelled out for
you. In that case, you'd be a masochist to see it. &UR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
