<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLAY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLAY PIGEONS' HAS A FEW GOOD GASPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A decent though not exactly inspired black comedy,
``Clay Pigeons'' boasts just enough grotesquerie and gallows humor
to sustain interest. But unlike the recent ``Your Friends &AMP;
Neighbors'' or the upcoming ``Very Bad Things,'' this film doesn't
have much of a point to make beyond the obvious one that very bad
things can happen when you mess with your friends and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the kind of thing you remember as all that outrageous
afterward, even if you enjoy a few good gasps and jolts in the
watching. There's a certain passion missing from its studied
wickedness.
</P>
<P>
   Set in and around a flyspeck Montana town, the film opens with
two buddies target shooting in the middle of nowhere. One of them
knows his wife's been cheating with the other one; he kills himself
but makes it look like his two-timing pal committed murder.
</P>
<P>
   Though not the brightest bulb under the Big Sky, Clay Bidwell
(Joaquin Phoenix) has a kind of unconscious genius for covering up
the trouble he lets himself get dragged into. He makes his friend's
death look like an accident, then tries to talk the
anything-but-grieving widow, Amanda (Georgina Cates), into backing
up his alibi. She refuses; what would the neighbors think, she
supposed to be grief-stricken and all? But if he can stay out of
jail, the brazen hussy would still like to pay Clay a discreet
visit now and then.
</P>
<P>
   As if he didn't have enough to be paranoid about, Clay is soon
the target of a new best friend. Lester Long (Vince Vaughn, the
``You're Money!'' guy from ``Swingers'') is an affable
cowboy/trucker who breezes into town with a rigload of charm and a
bit too much mystery. Initially, he's just the kind of supportive
distraction Clay needs, always up for a fishing trip or
commiseration about woman troubles.
</P>
<P>
   But as female corpses pile up around Clay, you start to wonder
just what Lester really is _ even if he's really real, or just an
extension of Clay's twisted psyche. Anyway, the good ol' local
sheriff (Scott Wilson) is getting mighty suspicious. Tart-tongued
FBI agent Dale Shelby (Janeane Garofalo) arrives suspicious, too.
Suddenly, Lester isn't around when Clay needs him to be _ and is
way too there when he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Director David Dobkin comes from advertising and music videos
and writer Matt Healy was a newspaper graphics designer. Both make
their feature debuts with ``Clay Pigeons,'' and they acquit
themselves professionally. The story's told clearly, builds
suspense well, and the gags and the gross stuff are effectively
staged. But the film feels more like it was built to a sound plan
than like something that its creators were vitally engaged with.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are what really carry ``Clay Pigeons.'' Phoenix
plays Clay passive-aggressive-passive, so numbed by the absurd
mayhem surrounding him that fear and guilt are the only things that
can still spur him to action. The big, blustery Vaughn is great at
mixing camaraderie with menace; he's so much fun to be around, he
makes you very nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Her usual arch, sophisticated self, Garofalo gives Agent Shelby
a superior attitude toward all the rubes she has to work with, but
the tough cop's vulnerable side is activated nicely when the
seductive Lester turns on the attention. And although Amanda is
written as your typical, amoral hot potato, Cates goes so
enjoyably, lewdly over the top with her, the stereotype doesn't
interfere with the fun.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
