A2286 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATASHA-MOVIE-LADN     09-24 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATASHA-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
 
McELHONE KEEPS GOOD COMPANY IN `RONIN' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   los angeles - Natascha McElhone has kept some pretty good screen
company in her feature films, playing modern art's muse opposite
Anthony Hopkins in ``Surviving Picasso,'' Brad Pitt's sympathetic
squeeze in ``The Devil's Own'' and Jim Carrey's inspiration in
``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in John Frankenheimer's new thriller, ``Ronin,'' McElhone
plays an Irish terrorist who may or may not have eyes for Robert
DeNiro. She's pretty much the only woman in the cast, an
international boy's club that includes French actor Jean Reno,
Swede Stellan Skarsgard and Brit Jonathan Pryce. It's a heavy-duty
ensemble, which suited McElhone fine, since she's not, as she puts
it, a ``popcorn actress.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she wouldn't accept a part in a Jerry Bruckheimer film.
Her name just hasn't been suggested in casting discussions. Trained
at the London Academy of Music and Drama, McElhone came up through
the theater ranks, starring in London and Manchester productions of
``The Cherry Orchard,'' ``Richard III'' and ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream.'' It was during the latter two productions that she caught
the eye of James Ivory and Ismail Merchant, who cast her opposite
Hopkins in ``Surviving Picasso.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's gorgeous, so beautiful, so good, such great poise,''
Hopkins raves. ``I hope she's going to be a big, big movie star. I
have a corrupting influence on her. I say, `Don't go back to the
theater.'''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no danger of that happening any time soon,
although McElhone does hope to perform on Broadway someday. But
acting in movies just seems ``right'' to her. Strange, but right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a nomad, a gypsy,'' she says. ``I like to live somewhere
for a short period and then move on. That's why movies suit me so
perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Born near London (where she still keeps an apartment), McElhone
had never acted professionally before enrolling in the London
Academy when she was 18. The move, though, was hardly a surprise.
McElhone has wanted to act since the age of 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least, that's what my parents tell me; my memory isn't that
good,'' McElhone says with a laugh. ``But I did always suspect that
acting was my destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Her choices in movie roles certainly haven't hurt her prospects.
``Surviving Picasso'' provided McElhone her meatiest role, and
turns in the high-profile ``Truman Show'' and the troubled
``Devil's Own'' fixed her star with Hollywood studios. ``Ronin'' is
her first action turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``At its heart, certainly, that's what it is,'' McElhone says of
the film. ``But there's a lot of ambiguity to it that I like, both
with the characters and the plot, and I think it takes the movie to
another level. It was certainly a challenge as an actress, and I
don't think you could say that about too many of these films.''
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge for McElhone was keeping her sanity during the
movie's frenetic car chase scenes through the streets of Paris and
Nice, a couple of which featured her behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the cast members, she was the best in the car,''
Frankenheimer says. ``She really does have nerves of steel. The
faster the car went, the more she seemed to be enjoying herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Says McElhone: ``Sometimes I was actually driving, but mostly we
had a stunt driver sitting next to me doing the steering. This man
was a master; I've never been in a car with someone who had such
quick reflexes. So, it was fairly hairy, but great fun, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for working with DeNiro. One scene called
for McElhone and DeNiro to make out passionately in a car, not the
kind of thing you normally associate with a DeNiro action film.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's everything he's made out to be _ challenging, intense and
very involved in every aspect of what he does,'' McElhone says.
``He tells his part of the story brilliantly, and you're there just
trying to keep up. But it's like playing tennis with a great
player. They make you better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that that happens to me,'' she adds laughing. ``I can't
hit the ball. I just get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In tennis, maybe. With acting, her form just keeps on improving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
