</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RONIN-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALIGNED DIRECTOR BACK IN DRIVER'S SEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When director John Frankenheimer finished his
senior year at Williams College, classmates voted him ``Highway
Menace'' for his unnerving need for speed behind the wheel. For a
while, Frankenheimer even toyed with the idea of becoming a race
car driver, competing in amateur races until the money gave out. He
still indulges now and again, going to drag-racing school (top
speed, 217 mph) and airing out his collection of modified Mercedes
cars, one of which is equipped with a 750 horsepower engine.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise, then, that ``Ronin,'' Frankenheimer's new
thriller about a group of post-Cold War mercenaries pursuing a
mysterious briefcase, contains some electrifying car-chase scenes
that wind through the streets of Paris and Nice. His fluid camera
work is a natural extension of the techniques he used in his 1966
homage to Formula One racing, ``Grand Prix,'' a film that
Frankenheimer remembers as ``the happiest time of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everything has been as wonderful for the 68-year-old
director, whose impressive screen career includes ``The Manchurian
Candidate,'' ``The Days of Wine and Roses'' and ``The Birdman of
Alcatraz.'' Personal problems, including a long bout with
alcoholism, took their toll on his career, as did a series of
mediocre movies in the late '70s and '80s. That Frankenheimer
survived and continues making movies is an achievement, the
greatest one of his life, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beach is littered with bodies that this town has ground up
and spit out,'' Frankenheimer says from his Beverly Hills home.
``I've had films that have worked and films that haven't. But I've
never given up. I've always sucked in my gut and kept plugging
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Of late, Frankenheimer's career path has brought him back to
television, the medium with which he began some 45 years ago.
Following a stint in the Air Force making training films,
Frankenheimer worked for ``Playhouse 90'' and other anthology
series, directing 152 live television dramas between 1954 and 1960.
(We'll do the math for you _ that's one show every two weeks.)
</P>
<P>
   He returned to TV in 1994, winning an Emmy for his direction of
HBO's ``Against the Wall,'' a tense retelling of the 1971 Attica
prison uprising. He has won three subsequent Emmys in the past four
years, the latest just recently for his work on the TNT biography
of George Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rebirth for me, no question about that,''
Frankenheimer says candidly. ``I had done a series of movies that
hadn't done very well, and my phone wasn't ringing. I was about to
do a crummy action movie with a second-rate action star when the
offer for `Against the Wall' came in. That changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What it did,'' Frankenheimer continues, ``is it altered my
perception of myself and the town's perception of me. I woke up and
realized I had a lot more work in me. I remembered why I got in
this business to begin with _ to do the work, to create something
that's good. And people around here saw I wasn't some old fart who
couldn't handle the job anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always thought of those early years in television as the
greatest in my life. And now with these past four movies, I feel
I've topped that. It's been incredibly rewarding on every level.''
</P>
<P>
   The rewards are about to increase with an exclusive deal with
TNT to produce and direct movies for the network. Frankenheimer
would also like to continue making feature films, too, and he has
his eye on a CIA drama called ``The Good Shepherd,'' written by
Eric Roth of ``Forrest Gump'' fame. Age doesn't seem to be a
problem. If anything, approaching his 70th birthday only seems to
make Frankenheimer want to work harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has so much energy, he's really unstoppable on the set,''
says Natascha McElhone, who stars with Robert De Niro and Jean Reno
in ``Ronin.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Reno, ``His experience is so vast that he knows exactly
what he wants and is able to accomplish it quickly. He gives actors
a lot of room, though, giving them the freedom in rehearsals to get
comfortable and find their own rhythm so once the shooting begins,
he can request precise variations from them. His set is very
disciplined, and I think most actors really appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even that kind of discipline couldn't save
Frankenheimer during his last feature film, ``The Island of Dr.
Moreau,'' which has become a certified cult classic for an enormous
Marlon Brando's strange and campy performance as the mad title
character. Frankenheimer replaced the original director, Richard
Stanley, who was fired three days into the shoot and later sneaked
back on the set wearing a disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got paid a fortune for taking it on, but a couple of days
into it, I realized I was still grossly underpaid,'' Frankenheimer
says, laughing. ``Every wild thing you heard about that set was
true. But I still think it turned out to be a pretty good movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean he has some fond memories of ``Moreau'' despite
all the publicized difficulties?
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer pauses for what seems like an eternity before
answering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only good thing I remember about that movie was when the
check cleared the bank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
