<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2290 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URBAN-REVIEW-LADN     09-24 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`URBAN LEGEND' SCARES UP MODERN-DAY CHILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2{ Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Urban Legend'' follows that now-familiar,
self-referential path blazed by writer Kevin Williamson in the
``Scream'' movies and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer.'' Only
here, all that post-modern irony is directed toward modern-day folk
tales, not classic horror films. So instead of talking about Jason
and Freddy Krueger (more on him later), the well-scrubbed,
attractive young people spend their time (what little they have
left) dissecting urban legends _ like Life cereal's Mikey exploding
from Pop Rocks and Pepsi, and doggies melting in microwave ovens.
</P>
<P>
   While the formula is only a couple of years old, it already
seems tired. But director Jamie Blanks is able to coax some thrills
and chills from Silvio Horta's occasionally smart and funny script.
Certainly, no new ground is broken. But there's enough blood and
suspense to go along with the requisite complete lack of logic to
satisfy most fans of the horror genre.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's action takes place on a gothic college campus that,
legend has it, was the scene of a gruesome massacre courtesy of an
abnormal-psych professor 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The frat boys are, naturally, celebrating the anniversary, but
they're soon distracted by the fact that their current classmates
are dropping like flies around them. Each death follows the ritual
of a different urban legend, most of which are conveniently
discussed in an American Folklore class led by the creepy Professor
Wexler (played by Freddie Krueger himself, Robert Englund).
</P>
<P>
   While the subject of urban legends is ripe for satire, director
Blanks too often follows the tried-and-true path here in his
feature debut. ``Urban Legend'' contains every genre convention you
can imagine. Sometimes the air is so thick with cliches that you
feel you're watching a David Zucker movie, but instead of sight
gags, it's the fright gags flying fast and furious just to see what
sticks. There must be a couple of dozen instances where characters
turn into some object just off screen to goose a cheap thrill from
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is populated mostly by young actors from television,
including Alicia Witt (``Cybill'') as the Smart Girl, Rebecca
Gayheart (``90210'') as the Pretty Girl, Jared Leto (``My So-Called
Life'') as the Pretty Boy and Joshua Jackson (``Dawson's Creek'')
as the Smart Aleck. They all scream with the proper conviction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
