A2294 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PECKER-REVIEW-LADN     09-24 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PECKER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOOKY SEND-UP MORE MILD THAN WILD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 2{ Stars. 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; When it comes to state-of-the-art bad taste, the
culture has kind of passed John Waters by. From ``There's Something
About Mary'' to the Starr Report, the general tone of things has
gotten so raunchy that the onetime king of outrageous kitsch seems
positively quaint nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is his own doing. Ever since his best film,
``Hairspray,'' 10 years ago, Waters has been trying to mix the
subversive, scuzzball humor of his earlier midnight movies (``Pink
Flamingos,'' ``Female Trouble,'' ``Desperate Living'') with a kind
of camp naivete (``Cry Baby,'' ``Serial Mom'').
</P>
<P>
   It only really worked for ``Hairspray'' because it was fresh at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   If he could somehow get the mix to mesh as hilariously as his
straight gross-out comedies played, he'd be onto something. But
``Pecker,'' Waters' latest, is another one that's low on laughs.
Packed with indie movie scene stars and built around an actually
cinematic idea, the film has some merit. It just doesn't deliver
the fun it thinks we're having with it.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Furlong, the kid from ``Terminator 2,'' plays the title
character. He's the son of a lower-middle-class family _ Mom (Mary
Kay Place) runs a used ``fashion'' store for homeless people, Dad
(Mark Joy) tends a neighborhood bar _ who exults in taking
photographs of downscale life in Waters' beloved Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker _ he got the nickname because, as a child, he ate like a
bird, which wouldn't have been the reason in a '70s Waters film _
smiles a lot because, presumably, he's surrounded by amusing
eccentrics. His grandmother does a lame ventriloquist act with a
``miraculous'' statue of the Virgin Mary. His sister (Martha
Plimpton) loves her ``career'' as the only female employee at a gay
disco. Pecker's best friend, Matt (Brendan Sexton III), is a
compulsive _ but lovable! _ thief. And his girlfriend, Shelley
(Christina Ricci in the film's funniest performance), is a
humorless careerist obsessed with running the perfect coin-operated
laundry.
</P>
<P>
   When a snooty New York art dealer (Lili Taylor) sees Pecker's
work, she turns him into a gallery sensation. But success has its
price. Every picture Pecker snaps triggers dire consequences for a
friend or relative.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Ricci and Furlong, everyone plays it in broad, ironic
strokes. Waters slings some tame satire at class pretensions,
commercial exploitation and uptightness in all its forms. But
``Pecker'' is, at best, a celebration of marginal kookiness. Anyone
expecting a full-frontal assault on good taste will be better
served by the Farrelly brothers or the government. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
