<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLINTON, BUT NOT THE PRESIDENT, IS POPULAR ON THE HUSTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For Democratic candidates needing fund-raising
help for the final six weeks of the campaign, there's only one name
to turn to: Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, that is.
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton struggling to ward off impeachment,
Democrats are asking for the first lady, whose support in polls has
grown since her husband admitted having an affair with Monica
Lewinsky, the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton launched a three-day national campaign tour
Wednesday by campaigning for Rep. Charles E. Schumer, who is the
Democratic nominee for Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady will be the featured guest Friday at a
$250-per-person fund-raiser for Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif. Boxer
faces a hard-charging challenge from Republican state Treasurer
Matt Fong.
</P>
<P>
   The president also will be in the San Francisco Bay area, but at
a lower profile, if bigger money, event: a $25,000-a-couple
fund-raiser in San Jose for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's visit is welcome news to Boxer, who has been
dogged throughout the campaign by questions about the president's
scandal. Though Boxer has called the president's behavior wrong and
indefensible, she has said she still supports his policies and has
tentatively scheduled a fund-raiser with him in late October.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is that (Mrs. Clinton) would be the
hottest ticket on Earth at this moment for the Democrats,'' said
Gale Kaufman, a Democratic political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton always has been a strong draw at party fund-raisers
in California. Her most fervent supporters _ liberals, feminists
and partisan Democrats _ remained loyal even when her standing in
the polls was low.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's televised admission of infidelity have made
her a more popular figure even among those less likely to support
her, including moderate Democrats, Republicans and men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think people, regardless of how they come down on the
conduct of this president, and I don't care what gender they are,
really feel for her,'' Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Merksamer, a Republican lawyer and strategist who ran
Bob Dole's 1996 campaign in California, noted that the sympathy for
the first lady might not translate into real political power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can believe that she did not know about (the affair),
then she shares something in common with the Congress and the
American people, and that's that they all were betrayed by the same
man,'' Merksamer said. ``That makes her a sympathetic figure. That
doesn't necessarily make her a popular figure.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's problems have created a quandary for Democratic
candidates: They need his fund-raising muscle, yet fear his support
could give their opponents ammunition and may alienate some voters.
After the release of the Whitewater independent counsel's on Mr.
Clinton's conduct was released, Gov. Parris N. Glendening of
Maryland canceled a fund-raiser with Clinton, fearing the
association could hurt the Democrat in a tight race for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Inviting Mrs. Clinton provides an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hugely committed to her, especially those in
contested races,'' said Troy Edwards, a Democratic fund-raiser in
Los Angeles. ``They want to have her out, they want to have her in
their homes, they want her to speak at events for them. I don't
think you'll see that change.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, 26 congresswomen met with Mrs. Clinton at the White
House to discuss the Nov. 3 elections. Many expressed concern that
turnout among women could be low. According to those who attended,
the first lady agreed to use her popularity to help Democrats get
out their message about education, health care and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Her public role in the campaign comes in sharp contrast to the
1994 congressional elections, when her failed drive for a
comprehensive health system became an issue that hurt Democrats at
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Clinton has softened her image as a feminist,
focusing her attention on issues like children's health and safety,
education and child care. In trips abroad, however, she continues
to champion women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her public stands on women's issues, her willingness to
stand by her husband has surprised even some supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, I'm amazed that she is able to hold herself
together and hold her family together,'' said Helen Grieco,
president of the California chapter of the National Organization
for Women. ``On the other hand, I'm saying, how does she deal with
all of this? It certainly wouldn't be my choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Malcolm, president of Emily's List, a national group that
raises money for Democratic women who support abortion rights, said
she hoped the first lady could help refocus voters' attention away
from the scandal and back on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Democratic candidates are extremely frustrated at
their inability to cut through all the media coverage and talk
about issues,'' Malcolm said. ``The first lady is a very effective
force at reminding women that voting is, in fact, about issues that
make a difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
