<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2296 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHADRACH-REVIEW-LADN     09-24 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHADRACH-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS GET SOUTHERN-STYLE STICKY IN `SHADRACH'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 2{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; ``Shadrach,'' a pleasant, exceedingly minor
feature film based on a William Styron short story, works best as
an anecdotal memory piece and less well when it reaches for
significance it doesn't actually possess.
</P>
<P>
   Co-adapted and directed by the author's daughter, Susanna
Styron, the film has a nice, languorous feel for the Depression-era
South. When it's focused on ornery, bathing-impaired moonshiners
and their kin, the film is fun and frisky. But its racial elements
are handled much less assuredly. There's a liberal piety to the
piece that's simultaneously hard to take, condescending and, worst
of all, unnecessary; the story's basics make its humanistic points
just fine, no preaching necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Styron stand-in for this kinda-sorta autobiographical tale
is Paul Whitehurst (Scott Terra), a 10-year-old only child from a
comfortable family. His mother is in poor health, which is perhaps
why he's irresistibly drawn to a rude, robust clan across the
tracks, the Dabneys.
</P>
<P>
   Also, unexpectedly, drawn to them is Shadrach, a 99-year-old
African-American gentleman. Played, in his movie debut, by
octogenarian John Franklin Sawyer, Shadrach is a former slave who
walks all the way from his home in Alabama to Virginia's Tidewater
country so he can be buried on the old plantation land where he was
born.
</P>
<P>
   That property is still owned by the once-aristocratic,
now-trashy Dabneys. Vernon (Harvey Keitel) apparently hasn't held a
legitimate job since the stock market crashed six years earlier; he
supports his large, semi-civilized brood by selling homemade
whiskey. Ma Trixie (Andie MacDowell) lovingly oversees her
rambunctious horde _ three boys named Mole, four daughters on
various stages of the road to unwed parenthood _ with a bottle of
beer constantly at her side.
</P>
<P>
   Paul is staying over the weekend (one of the Moles is his best
friend) when Shadrach shows up. His final request becomes a kind of
family project, especially when the local sheriff informs Vernon
that it's illegal to bury people on private land. Prone to swearing
every other minute about that blinkin' Franklin Roosevelt, who he
blames for all his financial problems, this gives the easily
agitated Vernon more cuss-worthy material.
</P>
<P>
   The kids, meanwhile, get to learn stuff about kindness and
mortality and the dignity of the human soul _ not to mention
sleeping outside and visiting the ol' swimming hole. Shadrach
doesn't get to do much more than need help and die, though. This is
another one of those unfortunate movies that isn't really about the
title African-American character but uses him as a catalyst for
white folks to find out how decent they can be.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Keitel and MacDowell have an infectiously amusing
time getting in touch with their inner rednecks here. She, being
from the South, convinces more than he does, but it's still fun to
watch Keitel's Methody approach to Vernon, especially when the
man's rasslin' with his inbred prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   Styron the director captures the film's rural, '30s ambience as
well as she evokes its swampy summer heat _ that is, with
atmospheric precision. Still, this slight story is PBS, not
feature, material, Vernon's foul mouth notwithstanding. The
``Sophie's Choice'' author has sketched an incident here, not woven
a narrative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
