<HEADLINE>
`MONUMENT AVE.' LIMPS DOWN WELL-TRAVELED ROADS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 2 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Consider the curse of Denis Leary. He has great
comic timing, decent enough dramatic chops, an edgy magnetism,
outstanding ability as a monologuist, an instinct for the unusual _
in short, everything a movie star should have.
</P>
<P>
   Except, fatally, the ability to distinguish an interesting
concept from a well-conceived project. ``The Ref,'' ``Love Walked
In,'' ``Suicide Kings''; all films that Leary did fine work in, but
that his contribution was not enough to make work.
</P>
<P>
   Add ``Monument Ave.'' to the list. It's a potentially engrossing
tale of working-class Irish Americans fighting yuppie encroachment
on their Boston neighborhood by, mainly, stealing the yups' stuff.
But the script stumbles almost immediately and never regains its
footing.
</P>
<P>
   From sub-Tarantino dialogue about Brat Pack movies to
boilerplate blarney and increasingly grim, ``Mean Streets''
cliches, ``Monument Ave.'' is always limping down roads too often
taken.
</P>
<P>
   Leary's performance, however, is a sizzler. He's Bobby O'Grady,
33 years old and relatively sensible for a guy who steals luxury
cars for a living. He snorts too much coke _ but then, so does
everyone in Charlestown _ and has a secret affair going with Katy
(Famke Janssen), a restaurateur who's also the moll of neighborhood
godfather Jackie O (Colm Meaney).
</P>
<P>
   A devoted mother's son, Bobby is showing his Irish cousin Seamus
(Jason Berry) the organized petty crime ropes when another cousin,
the speed freak Teddy (Billy Crudup) unexpectedly is released from
prison. Fearing his former associate's motor mouth, Jackie O orders
Teddy gunned down. Bobby resents this, of course, but when an
intrusive cop (Martin Sheen) dares to investigate the murder, Bobby
sticks to the neighborhood code of silence. He isn't happy about
it, though.
</P>
<P>
   Things get worse, loyalties fray, more and more old women weep
over their dead sons and nephews. Director Ted Demme (``Beautiful
Girls'') douses the proceedings in persuasive, dead-end atmosphere.
But there have been dozens of movies that have done that, and many
to more illuminating or jarring effect. This one, for the most
part, just adds a bit of brogue to the street pathology.
</P>
<P>
   Except, occasionally, for Leary. In his best scene, Bobby
maniacally threatens an African-American who's wandered unaware
into the territorial neighborhood. It's a performance designed to
get an annoying, racist buddy to shut up, but Leary has so expertly
built up Bobby's angry, coked-out state of mind by that time, we're
not sure if his basic good sense is still in control.
</P>
<P>
   A couple more movies like ``Monument Ave.,'' and we'll be
worrying the same thing about Leary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
