A2303 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASSIVE-MUSIC-LADN     09-24 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASSIVE-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSIVE ATTACK HAILS FROM MUSIC-CRAZY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Call it trip-hop, English psychedelia or just
plain dance music for shut-ins. Whatever you dub it, Massive Attack
has stumbled upon one of the most seductive pop confections of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The music collective comes from the only metropolis located
between London and coastal Cornwall _ Bristol, a cliquey little
city that once played host to cigarette factories and a
particularly downtrodden dockland.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the dock is notable for sleek art galleries, and the
town's factories churn out Rolls-Royce engines. Lloyd's Banks is
based there.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing that never changed is the hunger among the Bristol
populace for the latest, edgiest pop music trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a weird little place,'' admits Grant Marshall
(Daddy G) of the pioneering dance/trip-hop trio known simply as
Massive. ``It's so remote we developed our own little scene over
the years. It's a place that's been heavily obsessed with reggae
and always had an eye for good taste. People are quite obsessive
about music there.''
</P>
<P>
   That good taste is evident in Massive's third and latest record,
``Mezzanine'' (Virgin), in which dub bass, languid, reverb-laden
guitar, eerie percussion, darkly atmospheric electronics and such
high-profile vocalists as veteran reggae star Horace Andy and
ex-Cocteau Twins chanteuse Liz Fraser help put this hypnotic sound
across.
</P>
<P>
   Massive Attack got together in 1983 as the Wild Bunch, a
portable sound system that spun reggae and post-punk rock at
parties and outdoor events. Four years later, the group _ which
included Neneh Cherry, Tricky and Nellee Hooper (who would later
produce Madonna, U2 and Bjork) _ started work on the highly
influential ``Blue Lines'' album, which boasted the standout track
``Unfinished Symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   That first Massive album can be viewed as the beginning of so
much of today's most resonant pop music. Tricky, Portishead, Roni
Size, Goldie, Hooper _ all are linked in some way to the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bristol was always on the verge of a musical explosion,''
Marshall says. ``It just had so much potential, even before us. The
music we were doing was unique. Nobody else was doing it when we
started. We were influenced by dance and soul, but `Blue Lines' was
so far removed from the dance floor. It was music for the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Massive Attack _ which also includes singer-DJ Robert del Naja
(3-D) and DJ-keyboardist Andrew Vowles (Mushroom) _ appears Sunday
at the Hollywood Palladium with young Brit rapper Lewis Parker
opening. The New York Times said a recent Massive gig in Manhattan
was ``magnificent'' and ``brooding.''
</P>
<P>
   On stage, the trio is augmented by a band, including such
players from ``Mezzanine'' as guitarist Angelo Bruschini, bassist
Winston Blissett, drummer Pete Lewinson and keyboardist Michael
Timothy, plus vocalists Debbie Mira and Andy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken years to figure out how to adapt this music for the
stage,'' Marshall said. ``We started out using turntables, but that
was too rigid. The problem was how to perform studio-based music.
Slowly but surely, the band reinterpreted the albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``With nine people on stage, the focus is always changing.
There's a lot of things happening, a lot of experimentation. Things
happen by complete accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Massive was due to open the recent Verve stadium
tour. Asked if he was disappointed those plans fell apart, Marshall
says no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't work things out between us,'' the DJ says.
``Everyone involved went a bit crazy, I suppose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
