<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-FILMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT FILMS DEAL WITH DEATH AND WIN AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Death was the common denominator at the recent Los
Angeles International Short Film Festival, though the two major
category winners took a different slant on this most universal
theme. The sobering ``Luz de la Mission'' took the top prize for
Best American Film while the comedic ``Tombstone'' won for Best
Foreign Film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luz de la Mission,'' by Martin Garcia Flores, is the account
of a prisoner's coming to terms with his grandmother's death. In
``Tombstone,'' by Brazilian director Paula Morelli, an
argumentative couple fights about love, death and especially the
choice of a headstone.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Pelletier, whose submission ``New Testament'' screened,
was judged to have the most potential as a director of a commercial
spot and given the Commercial Director's Award.
</P>
<P>
   Certificate Awards went to Mike Johnson (``The Devil Went Down
to Georgia''), Best Animation Film; Kia Simon, Eve Conant and
Jonathon Crosby, Best Documentary for ``Looking for Sly''; Swiss
director Vincent Pappalardo, Best Comedy for ``Electric Baby
Cleaner''; Erik Knight, Best Experimental Film for ``Dread Night
Folk''; and director Marty Keegan, Best Drama for ``Has Been.''
</P>
<P>
   The second annual L.A. International Short Film took place Sept.
11-13 at Barnsdall Park in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL LEADING LADY: Actress Sharon Stone and the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences will host a retrospective of
films by French actress and director Jeanne Moreau on Thursday
night in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Moreau brought an aura of femininity and sensuality to the roles
she played, beginning in Louis Malle's ``The Lovers'' (1958) and
Francois Truffaut's ``Jules and Jim'' (1961). This international
star's career, which started in 1948, continues today. Most
recently, she appeared in Ismail Merchant's ``The Proprietor''
(1996) and had a cameo in this summer's hit ``Ever After.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreau is scheduled to attend. Doors open at 7 p.m. and the
program starts at 8.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets cost $5 for the public, $3 for academy members and may
be purchased at the academy during business hours. The theater is
at 8949 Wilshire Blvd. Call (310) 247-3600 for information.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute officially opens a retrospective of Moreau's career
at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art's Bing Theatre, running
Oct. 4-25. ``Bay of Angels'' (1962) and ``Lillian Gish'' (1983),
the admiring portrait of the silent screen's first lady, directed
by and starring Moreau, will be shown 7 p.m. Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   For tickets, call the LACMA box office at (323) 857-6010 or
Ticketmaster at (213) 480-3232.
</P>
<P>
   BLOCKBUSTER WRITING: So you want to write for Hollywood. First
you might want to check out the Screenwriters on Screenwriting
course starting Oct. 12 at the UCLA Extension Writers' Program.
</P>
<P>
   Writers of some of the summer's blockbusters are lined up as
speakers, starting with Jonathan Hensleigh (``Armageddon''). He'll
be followed by Patrick Smith Kelly (``A Perfect Murder''), Rita
Hsiao (``Mulan''), Michael Tolkin (``Deep Impact''), Harry Elfont
and Deborah Kaplan (``Can't Hardly Wait'') and Scott Frank (``Out
of Sight''), who will talk about their experiences in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriters on Screenwriting is designed for writers of all
levels and for the general public. The course meets from 7 to 10
p.m. Mondays through Nov. 6 at UCLA. Tuition is $210 for the course
or $35 per class at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Call (310) 206-1542 for information, or e-mail at
writersunex.ucla.edu. Call (310) 825-9971 or visit the Web site
www.unex.ucla.edu/writers to register.
</P>
<P>
   YOU DIRTY RATS: Long before ``in your face'' got into modern
language, Jimmy Cagney and his snarling mug showed what bravado was
all about in ``Public Enemy.'' In the role of a Prohibition-era
gangster, Cagney was the poster boy for mean.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Prohibition ended and tavern beer taps flowed again,
films about crime bosses and thugs stuck around. Laemmle's Sunset 5
and Monica 4-Plex are running weekend screenings of gangster flicks
from the 1930s to the present-day ``GoodFellas'' and ``New Jack
City.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday and Sunday, ``Public Enemy'' (1931) plays at 10 a.m.
at the Sunset 5, 8000 Sunset Blvd. in West Hollywood, and at 11
a.m. at the Monica 4-Plex, 1332 Second St., Santa Monica. Not only
is Cagney one bad customer, but he smushes that grapefruit right in
Mae Clarke's face in a fit of rage that is cinematic lore.
</P>
<P>
   Films to follow include ``G Men,'' ``Key Largo,'' ``White
Heat,'' ``Bonnie &AMP; Clyde'' and ``Mean Streets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
