<HEADER>
A2306 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARO-TV-LADN     09-24 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARO-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FARO' AIMING FOR COOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Friday's new faces are about as different as you
can get, with a guy who's been missing since the '70s and some kids
who weren't even born until a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   For the younger set, ABC adds two new shows to its TGIF lineup.
Coincidentally _ or, maybe not _ they're both about single fathers
who happen to be college professors, with the kids tended to by
nontraditional care-givers.
</P>
<P>
   CBS attempts to steal that stay-at-home audience with the return
of ``Kids Say the Darndest Things'' and ``Candid Camera'' at the 8
o'clock hour, followed by newcomer ``Buddy Faro.'' Will the
transition work? You'll decide. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BUDDY &UR;  &LR; FARO &UR;  &QC; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Stylish, retro-chic and ring-a-ding.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Faro (Dennis Farina), the private investigator who wrote
the book on the business, scrammed to Mexico 20 years ago to escape
from a mad mobster. He had it all _ money, women, a cool car and
bartenders who knew his name.
</P>
<P>
   Think of an American version of Austin Powers with better teeth
and a suaver wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   A crisply written show packed with humor and a soundtrack with
non-Frank Sinatra versions of the Chairman's standards add up to a
deliciously entertaining show.
</P>
<P>
   The mob picks Bob Jones (Frank Whaley), a modern-day private
eye, from the phone book and tricks him into finding Faro so they
can kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Jones succeeds and locates the scraggly-bearded Rip Van Winkle
and gets him back to Los Angeles, where he finds that not much has
changed in style and attitude from the '70s. Swing is back, and the
martinis are flowing.
</P>
<P>
   Faro proves too slick for the gangsters and turns their little
scheme around on them. Faro and Jones then form an agency that will
be intact for episodes to come.
</P>
<P>
   Farina inhabits the most interesting new character on prime-time
television.
</P>
<P>
   Faro, a one-time friend of the Rat Pack, uses throwback language
such as ``kooky scene,'' ``toots,'' ``rub-a-dub-dub,'' ``doll
face,'' ``double sawbuck'' and ``funny face.''
</P>
<P>
   He dresses cool, and you'll never see him sweat.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot does drag a bit in the middle, but it picks up toward
the end.
</P>
<P>
   As Faro says, ``Buddy is back in town,'' and that is a good
thing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TWO OF A KIND &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Olsen twins may have grown up, but their audience will
remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   Playing 11-year-olds, they will appeal to an audience younger
than themselves. Kids their own age will be too busy trying to
sneak into PG-13 movies and watching MTV to catch this sweet
sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   The twins, who shared a role on ``Full House,'' each get their
own part this time. Mary-Kate plays a tomboy and jock, Ashley plays
a princess who wants to wear makeup and date boys.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, Kevin Burke (Christopher Sieber), is a widower who
teaches science at a local college.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot has the girls tricking Dad into dumping the old baby
sitter _ an old neighbor (``She's like Generation A'') _ for a
26-year-old worldly and brash college student, Carrie Moore (Sally
Wheeler).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the girls prevail and Carrie becomes their female
role model and confidant. Through conversations with her, you get
the girls' innermost thoughts. Think of it as ``Ally McBeal: The
Early Years.''
</P>
<P>
   The producing team of Thomas L. Miller, Robert L. Boyett and
Michael Warren have been working with the Olsens since they were 6
months old and have not lost the touch of writing for them.
</P>
<P>
   When talking about poker, Ashley jokes, ``When we were little,
Full House beat everything.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks like the twins have another winner on their hands here.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting footnote (and an indication of how long pilots
sit around before they make the air): Carrie and Kevin, while
watching a Cubs game from her roof, complain about Sammy Sosa's
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see you earn some of that $10.2 million,'' Carrie yells
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was more than 60 home runs ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BROTHER'S KEEPER &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Porter Waide (William Ragsdale) is living a dandy life, raising
his whiz of an 8-year-old son, Oscar, all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is going as planned for the stuffy English professor
... until his wild brother Bobby (Sean O'Bryan) moves in.
</P>
<P>
   In a stretch that would hurt a gymnast, Bobby Waide, the bad boy
of the National Football League, is traded to the San Francisco
49ers and has a clause in his $1 million contract that forces him
to live with his responsible, uptight brother.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby is a place-kicker and looks as if he couldn't even kick a
habit.
</P>
<P>
   The two brothers clash on everything from food to child-rearing
(like Bobby would care).
</P>
<P>
   O'Bryan tries too hard to act irreverent in the pilot, and plot
twists _ such as his getting his brother a date with an
emergency-room nurse _ are preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   This show's idea of a big comedy moment is Porter getting a
board-game piece stuck up his nose. Don't bother letting your kids
stay up late for ``Brother's Keeper'' _ it's definitely not worth
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2307 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANGEROUS-VIDEO-LADN     09-24 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANGEROUS-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC SEXUAL HIGH JINX REVISITED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``God made sin so we might know his mercy,''
declares a character in ``Dangerous Beauty,'' a historic sexual
romp that's out on video this week.
</P>
<P>
   So, it seems, we're talking wickedness and redemption here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dangerous Beauty'' tells the story of a young woman, Veronica
(Catherine McCormack), who falls in love with the wrong man (Rufus
Sewell) _ the son of a wealthy aristocrat _ in Venice in 1583.
Unable to marry him because her family could not provide a
sufficiently rich dowry, her mother (Jacqueline Bisset) offers an
alternative _ become a courtesan like she was in her youth. A
courtesan, her mother says, has the best of both worlds _ she can
be educated, have the man she wants when she wants and not be a
slave to stifling convention that the good wives of Venice are.
Veronica, though repulsed at first, quickly outdoes her mother,
becoming the darling of Venice and even saving the city with her
particular skills.
</P>
<P>
   For much of ``Dangerous Beauty,'' the tone is light and fun as
the couple perform their sexual dance, with enough witty rapartee,
swordplay and boudoir high jinks to be entertaining. At other
times, though, the film can't seem to decide if it is itself
sexploitation or is about the serious theme of the suppression of
women. (There is some irony that one of ``Beauty's'' main
commercial selling points is that there are a number of scenes with
women with their clothes off.)
</P>
<P>
   The lovely McCormack (Mel Gibson's doomed wife in
``Braveheart'') gives a lively performance, and Sewell (``Hamlet'')
is appropriately uppercrust while still being a hunk. The rest of
the cast, including Moira Kelley and Oliver Platt, is solid, and
the scenery is sumptuous.
</P>
<P>
   The last part of ``Beauty'' grows predictably serious as forces
of the Inquisition catch up with our heroine, and she becomes a
scapegoat for the ills of a city hit by the plague. This being the
Middle Ages, her accomplices (male clients) were not accused.
Although it is called a true story, the film's ending is a bit too
contrived, which undermines its earlier tone.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the most famous and successful historic sexual romp
of all time was ``Tom Jones'' (1963), which won four Academy
Awards, including Best Picture. Directed by Tony Richardson and
written by playwright John Osborne, ``Tom Jones'' may seem a little
overly cute today with its Keystone Kops-style chases, officious
off-screen narrator and silent-film-style titles, but there is
still much fun in this bawdy satire in which the hypocritical prigs
get their comeuppance.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Henry Fielding's 1749 sprawling episodic novel, ``Tom
Jones'' tells the story of the bastard son of the sister of a
wealthy country squire. Jones (played with delightful wit by Albert
Finney) is a wild youth whose love of drink and carnal pleasures
can't hide his good heart. Eventually he falls in love with Sophie
(Susannah York), the daughter of a neighboring squire (Hugh
Griffith).
</P>
<P>
   Being a bastard, Jones is not high on the squire's list of
perspective sons-in-law, and forces soon conspire against ``our
hero,'' as the narrator refers to him.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding's intent was to skewer all levels of English society at
the time, but Richardson's film makes it timeless. There are
hypocrites in every age after all.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who would like to see a more fleshed-out
version of ``Tom Jones'' (we're not talking literally only length),
earlier this year A&AMP;E released on videotape its miniseries version,
starring Max Beesley.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few other films that fall into the historic sexual
category that you might want to rent:
</P>
<P>
   ``Queen Margot'' (1994), starring Isabelle Adjani, revolves
around the intrigues and incestuous relationships of the French
court in 1572. It's not much of a romp, since the film tells the
story of the St. Bartholomew's Day massacre of thousands of
Protestants, but Adjani is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moll Flanders'' (1996) is a feminist retelling of Daniel
Defoe's 18th-century novel about an orphan girl who triumphs over
her impoverished upbringing and servitude in a house of ill repute.
Robin Wright (Moll) is luminous, but there is not much humor. The
story never gets too sudsy, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restoration'' (1996), starring Robert Downey Jr., is a true
sexual romp, at least for the first half. Set in 1660 England,
``Restoration'' is the story of a hedonistic physician (Downey)
whose debauched life leads him to ruin (this is where the romp
stops), but he eventually finds redemption. Meg Ryan has a nice
turn as a slightly mad woman who helps Downey recover.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the soon-to-be-released videotape of Bill
Clinton's grand jury testimony. Not exactly a historical romp, but
historical anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
