<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-HURRICANE-092     09-24 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-HURRICANE-0925-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: GEORGES' UNCERTAINTY BRINGS JITTERS, FRAZZLES NERVES
 &HT;    With a photo mug of Emling available in the International folder
on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    With HURRICANE-GEORGES-0925.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Like a gripping soap opera, Hurricane Georges had all of
Miami on the edge of its seat Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who've never lived through a hurricane before,
it was actually more like sitting through a trailer for a very
scary movie -- a lot of anxiety-causing teases, but no ending.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges spent Thursday hugging Cuba's northern coast,
confounding forecasters who weren't 100 percent certain whether the
deadly storm would strike Miami or skirt past the Florida Keys and
into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Sustaining winds of just 80 mph by lunchtime, the storm no
longer packed much of its earlier punch.
</P>
<P>
   So my biggest question was: How bad can it be?
</P>
<P>
   Pretty bad, judging from the frantic actions of friends and
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, many had boarded up their homes as tightly as Fort
Knox; so much so that I wasn't sure there was still life inside
some of them.
</P>
<P>
   They had smothered china and other valuables on beds under a
mountain of quilts, and had stocked up on enough food and water to
last through the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   I was doing good to get my plants inside.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't live through Hurricane Andrew. Many of them did.
</P>
<P>
   ``My yard was a mess and I was without water and electricity for
two weeks,'' one friend recounted. ``The heat, particularly at
night, was unbearable with no air-conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   How's that for a calming effect?
</P>
<P>
   Andrew is the bullet Miami had dodged since 1965, when Hurricane
Betsy sliced through the upper Florida Keys and cruised across the
Gulf of Mexico to slam the Louisiana coast, killing 75 people.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1992, most residents here paid little heed to hurricane
warnings that were broadcast whenever a storm would roar out of the
Caribbean because, in general, most hurricanes failed to deliver
the promised blows.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane David, for example, threatened to strike Miami in
1979, but zigzagged away at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   But then came Andrew, which shook the city by the throat, and
out of its complacency.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was the costliest natural disaster in U.S. history,
inflicting some $30 billion in damage on southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, residents are no longer apathetic.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane warning posted for the Miami area and much of South
Florida early Thursday prompted a rush of activity in this city of
oceanfront condominiums and smoked-glass towers.
</P>
<P>
   Schools and daycare centers were closed, leaving parents in a
crunch. Offices shut down, and stores were overwhelmed with
frazzled homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic jams were no where to be found in a maddeningly
congested city that has numerous commuters traveling hours to get
to and from work.
</P>
<P>
   But for me, the worst part was the uncertainty of not knowing
what would come next.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters raised stress levels even higher by warning just
before 1 p.m. EDT that Georges was finally headed away from Cuba
and out over the open waters of the Florida Straits, which -- from
everyone's dire predictions -- appear to be the warmest waters
outside of Hades.
</P>
<P>
   Warm water, it seems, heats up a hurricane's intensity faster
than fire heats up a marshmallow.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't alarming enough, television stations that began
broadcasting around-the-clock Thursday morning peppered their
coverage with testimonials from those who had been through Andrew,
building tension even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man who tried to film the storm with his camcorder was
ripped right off his balcony, completely sucked away by the
storm,'' one woman interjected.
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon, folks were being prompted not only to have
well-stocked first-aid kits, but also ``signal flares'' in case of
they get into ``serious'' trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the grim words of an official from the National
Hurricane Center, who had this warning for those residents of Key
West planning to ride out the deadly storm: ``This could be the
worst night of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   So under deceptively gorgeous, sunny skies, I was growing
increasingly concerned, but still thinking Thursday that the storm
couldn't possibly be as bad as everyone warned it might be.
</P>
<P>
   Or could it?
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
