<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIONS FOR REMOTE E-MAIL AND LAPTOP SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a previous column a reader wanted to know how to get his
e-mail during an extended stay in Finland. While the suggestions I
made will work, a number of readers suggested additional options.
</P>
<P>
   I suggested having his current Internet service provider (ISP)
forward his mail to the local Finnish ISP. A lot of readers pointed
out that it was not necessary. One reader even said his ISP told
him it would not forward his mail when he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The one option most often mentioned was to set different
incoming and outgoing e-mail servers via one's e-mail reader. This
works for a majority of e-mail users if your software supports it.
Check with your two ISP's for the correct information to make it
work. And check your e-mail program's documentation on how to enter
the correct information. Not every one, however, has software to
support it. Lots of users have older e-mail readers that may not
support multiple accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Another suggestion was to Telnet from the alternative ISP.
Telneting is not difficult, but, depending on the type of server
and your Telnet software, it can involve some arcane Unix commands.
For the Telnet-savvy, it is especially useful if you are traveling
sans laptop and need to access your e-mail from someone else's
system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Security in Carrying Cases &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Port Inc., has a new carrying case that protects your laptop not
only from damage but also from theft. The company has integrated
its Defcon 1 security system into a bag. It has been dubbed the
Defcon 3. It operates with a remote control similar to the one that
is popular with car alarm systems. When you arm the system, anyone
who picks up the bag will cause a loud alarm to sound. If you
forget to arm it and someone snatches the bag, there is a panic
mode that will set off the alarm if the bag is within 40 feet.
</P>
<P>
   You can set the sensitivity of the alarm so that it takes more
than just touching the bag to kick it off. It is for those of us
who use the slide-the-luggage-forward-with-the-foot-method when
standing in the airline check-in line.
</P>
<P>
   The Defcon unit is built into the side of the bag and when it is
armed, a blinking red light is visible -- a subtle way of telling
would be thieves that this is no easy target.
</P>
<P>
   My only complaint is that the remote control is quite small. I
worry about losing it because it does not have enough heft to
remind me that it is in my pocket. It does have a ring so that you
can attach it to the ring with the rest of your keys.
Unfortunately, my key ring contains way too many keys and, on
trips, I often put it inside my laptop's zippered inner pocket,
leaving me no way to hit the panic button if the button is in the
bag, in the hand of the thief who is running down the concourse.
The Defcon3 sells for $129.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PowerBook Update &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A number of readers pointed out that Apple has discontinued the
