<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2400 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEA-CYBERTIMES-ARTS-N     09-24 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEA-CYBERTIMES-ARTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS(AT)LARGE 
 NEA CHIEF VOWS TO SUPPORT INDIVIDUAL ARTISTS  
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Endowment for the Arts will strive to expand its
support for individual artists, according to its new chairman, Bill
Ivey -- a step that could ultimately benefit the digitally creative
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my goals as chairman is to work with Congress and other
interested parties to move the agency back into funding individual
artists more completely than we do now,'' Ivey said in an interview
Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the federal arts agency has a history of financing
artists who use technologies such as video in their work, Ivey
added: ``We certainly need to find a way to get back into
supporting individual visual artists. And I think that, in
supporting the individual artist, you tend to get a quicker handle
on new technologies because the individual artist tends to take on
these things more quickly than organizations do.''
</P>
<P>
   The NEA's program of grants to individual artists was curtailed
in 1996 after a handful of controversial works prompted members of
Congress to threaten to eliminate the agency. Although the
endowment still awards a few individual fellowships out of its $98
million annual budget, the NEA's guidelines have been changed so
that most grants now go to arts institutions, not-for-profit
organizations and regional arts agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Because, as Ivey observed, these groups are often slow to make
use of new technology, online projects rarely receive support. The
situation is worsened by many online artists' embrace of the
democratic, do-it-yourself spirit of the Internet. For example, the
NEA's rules on literature fellowships flatly exclude self-published
projects, which means most works of hypertext fiction would be
ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   During a telephone interview to herald the relaunch of the NEA's
Web site, Ivey acknowledged that ``we may not be as far into
supporting the digital arts as we might be,'' although he
speculated that some computer-based projects might already be in
the grants pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are somewhat application-dependent,'' Ivey explained.
``It's up to the artists' organizations to come to us with projects
in the digital realm, so it's a little bit of a waiting game for
the endowment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey said that the NEA is seeking to hire a technology
specialist in the next few months to help assess grant proposals in
this area. The agency is also considering convening a panel of
experts from across the nation that, he said, ``could really allow
us to enter the field with some authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, the NEA has yet to make a strong commitment to digital
media. Reading through the NEA's program descriptions and
guidelines, it is difficult to find references to the electronic
realm, just as one is unlikely to see a Web-based work of art in a
museum or gallery in the United States. Although more innovations
in the technology industry come from the United States, digital art
is more widely accepted in Europe. Government-sponsored
electronic-art centers and festivals like Ars Electronica in Linz,
Austria, routinely showcase Internet projects and digital works.
</P>
<P>
   Apprised of this situation, Ivey said: ``If we as a nation are
leading in technology but somehow lagging in the most creative
parts of the use of that technology, that's something we at the
endowment and the other entities that are involved in either
nurturing or regulating life on the Internet should get into. There
may well be some kind of a positive intervention that some agency
could accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   The NEA does subsidize Open Studio, a national program to
provide technology tools and Internet access to nonprofit arts
organizations and the artists they serve. Last Friday, Ivey visited
Space One Eleven, an arts center in Birmingham, Ala., that has
received Open Studio grants. While there, he viewed Piotr
Szyhalski's Web-based Ding an sich project, commissioned by the
Walker Art Center in Minneapolis. Ivey described the work as
``pretty interesting and pretty exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   While most artists are eager for additional income sources, not
all welcome government sponsorship. Robbin Murphy, a New York
artist and one of the founders of artnetweb, said: ``When
politicians here face the voters, they have to say whether they
support sissy, elitist art or serious science that the kids will
like. My fear is that if government does give more support, it will
be for art that looks like science projects.''
</P>
<P>
   David Feit, the artistic director of the Seattle-based NEA Army,
has an unusual twist on the government's role in the intersection
of art and technology. His four-man group applied earlier this year
for a grant the size of the agency's total budget. The group plans
to use the money to build a portion of a B-2 Stealth bomber that
would be toted across the country bearing a sign that says
``Priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To get the most bang for their buck, the NEA should coordinate
with the Pentagon, which already uses cutting-edge technology to
project American creativity around the globe,'' Feit said. ``The
high-tech arts are here already. For $1 million each, the Tomahawk
cruise missile can generate a beautiful high-tech fireworks display
in the skies of any country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey, 54, was selected by President Clinton to succeed the
actress Jane Alexander as head of the NEA. Unanimously confirmed by
the Senate in May, he was sworn in on July 17, after 27 years at
the helm of the Country Music Foundation in Nashville. He has
computers at work and at home, and sometimes carries a laptop when
he travels. A pilot, he enjoys flight-simulation software, but as
an amateur musician, he prefers guitar-instruction videotapes over
the one CD-ROM tutorial he has.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey said he is not much of an Internet surfer, preferring to
visit specific online locales like book-retailing sites, which he
uses as a convenient way to check whether a title is in print. He
praised the Library of Congress' American Memory Web site, a
collection of historic photographs, sound clips and other source
materials, and he voiced support for the plans of Robert Pinsky,
the nation's poet laureate, to build an online archive of citizens'
favorite poems.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey said he had ``very little'' input on the NEA's Web site,
which was quietly relaunched last week. Compared to the original
site, which went up in April 1996, the updated version is more
functional, with a structure than enables faster access to basic
information about the NEA.
</P>
<P>
   The site also sports more images than the previous incarnation,
although its plain appearance is unlikely to earn any
graphic-design prizes. As before, there are feature articles on
contemporary artists, including an interview with Julie Taymor, the
director of the Broadway musical ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   The site gets between 1,200 and 1,600 visits per day, with most
visitors seeking grants-related information. So far, the galleries
and other areas for the general public are less trafficked,
something Ivey would like to see change.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ivey does not foresee the site becoming an art archive,
a children's area is under discussion, and he would like to see
other public areas expand and add more fun elements over the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that our Web site would be a gateway to some of
the magic of making art, learning about art, participating in art
and viewing art,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
