<HEADER>
A2402 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CYBERTIMES-LA     09-24 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CYBERTIMES-LAW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TO IMPEACH? FIND OUT ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  By CARL S. KAPLAN 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sept. 8, 1787, following a muggy summer, the delegates to the
Federal Convention in Philadelphia turned their attention to the
impeachment clause of the proposed Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates had already decided that treason and bribery
should serve as two grounds for prosecuting the president before a
jury of senators. But according to notes taken by James Madison,
George Mason of Virginia asked for the addition of a broader
category: ``maladministration.''
</P>
<P>
   This term was rejected as too vague. Gouverneur Morris of
Pennsylvania quipped that ``an election of every four years will
prevent maladministration.'' Eventually, the framers of the
Constitution, borrowing language from English common law, hit upon
a phrase that has been very much in the news during a muggy
September 211 years later: ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   People rushed to the Web last week to read the details of the
Starr report, which detailed President Clinton's possible
impeachable offenses. Now that some of the more salacious details
have sunk in, Web surfers who wish to ponder the deeper meaning of
impeachment can visit the Web again to immerse themselves in the
past. There are a wealth of primary and secondary historical
sources on the Internet that shed light on the meaning and context
of the term ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great thing'' that relevant historical
documents are on the Web, said Bernard J. Hibbitts, a professor at
the University of Pittsburgh law school who teaches legal history
and serves as associate dean for communications and information
technology. ``It allows history to speak for itself. Why not go
back and read what the framers of the Constitution had to say?''
</P>
<P>
   James Madison's notes from the Federal Convention are available
on Yale Law School's Avalon Project Web site, an eclectic trove of
legal history, as well as from the Library of Congress' ``A Century
of Lawmaking for a New Nation'' site, which collects records of the
young America from 1774 to 1873. Surfers may click on the key date
of September 8, 1787 in the Madison notes and stir their historical
imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   The framers also discussed the need for impeachment as a check
on the power of the president on July 20, 1787. On that date,
Madison said it was ``indispensable that some provision should be
made for defending the Community [against] the incapacity,
negligence or perfidy of the chief Magistrate.''
</P>
<P>
   The grounds for impeachment were also discussed authoritatively
by Alexander Hamilton in The Federalist, No. 65, dated March 7,
1788 and also available at the Avalon and New Nation sites. In that
essay, which is part of a series of articles penned by Hamilton,
Madison and John Jay supporting ratification of the Constitution,
Hamilton concluded that grave ``misconduct of public men''
warranted impeachment. In the opinion of Michael J. Gerhardt, a
professor at William and Mary Law School and an expert on
impeachment, Hamilton believed this was not a category that could
be neatly tied down, meaning that a case-by-case determination
might be required.
</P>
<P>
   During President Nixon's impeachment inquiry, the House
Judiciary Committee issued a 60-page report on the constitutional
grounds for presidential impeachment. Available on a special
impeachment Web site prepared by the library of the University of
North Texas, the report surveys the English and American historical
record on the practice of impeachment. It is written in clear
language that can be appreciated by non-lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Shane, who teaches constitutional law at the University
of Pittsburgh's law school, cautioned that the historical documents
have their limits. ``I don't think the Federal Convention debates
or The Federalist No. 65 are precisely attuned'' to Clinton's
alleged offenses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shane noted that Madison's notes were not published until after
his death, partly so that the framers' subjective understanding of
the words used in the Constitution would not have too great an
influence over subsequent generations. ``Still, it's inherently
fascinating'' to read the original documents on the Web, Shane
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhardt noted that the term ``high crimes and misdemeanors,''
adopted on Sept. 8, 1787, is a phrase borrowed from English
impeachment practices. It refers to political crimes and is
generally understood to mean ``serious offenses against the U.S. or
the republic, serious breaches of trust or of one's duty,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhardt said it was an open question whether, assuming Clinton
lied under oath about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
such perjury would fit squarely within the term ``high crimes and
misdemeanors.'' On the one hand, he said, it could be argued the
president's perjury does not relate to his performance in office --
and thus isn't constitutionally significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument on the other side is that perjury is a serious
business, especially for the president, who takes an oath to
faithfully execute the laws,'' said Gerhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the latest historical impeachment document on the
Internet is the Starr report itself, which spread with
unprecedented speed upon its release. ``Never have so many read so
much so soon,'' said Hibbitts.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the report, which could affect the constitutional
history of the country, also represented a maturing of the Web as a
mass medium, said Hibbitts.''The Web can go where other media can't
go. It provided a forum for the Starr Report. If it weren't for the
Net, I think the Starr report would have been edited, expurgated
and published (on paper).''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Jurist Online: jurist.law.pitt.edu/impeach.htm
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Carl S. Kaplan, a New York-based lawyer and journalist, was a
business reporter for New York Newsday.)
</P>
