<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2421 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALL-REVIEWS-SPI &LR;      09-24 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-REVIEWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KICK BACK AND REVEL IN THE COOLNESS THAT IS `BUDDY FARO'' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Owing to the largess of CBS, Friday night now means two, two,
two crime-busters with classic convertibles. In addition to ``Nash
Bridges,'' now in its fourth season of enforcing the law from a
ragtop, CBS tonight introduces ``Buddy Faro,'' a
Thunderbird-driving, martini-sipping, rug-cutting private eye whose
swagger would give normal people whiplash.
</P>
<P>
   But Buddy isn't normal. He's got panache. He's got chutzpah.
He's got style.
</P>
<P>
   Substance is another matter, but CBS tried ``Style &AMP; Substance''
last spring and it didn't work. Besides, this is Friday night on
CBS, where, in addition to the ``Nash Bridges'' brand of Cop Lite
macho posing, the schedule offers such mind-expanding fare as
``Kids Say the Darndest Things'' and ``Candid Camera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy Faro'' fits right in. And it sure beats the possibile
alternative: another network newsmagazine. So kick back and revel
in the coolness of the hippest Faro since Sam the Sham.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Farina, flat Chicago accent and all, is the Budster with
the bluster, and quite enjoyable in a you-love-him-you-hate-him
sort of Rat Package. However, he wouldn't be back in circulation
without the unwitting assistance of Bob Jones, a swaggerless,
plain-vanilla private investigator who is duped into locating Faro,
the former king of the L.A. scene who dropped from sight 20 years
ago to avoid an acute case of small-caliber lead poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Whaley is appropriately self-effacing as the nondescript
Jones, the guy who eventually becomes guide and interpreter for
someone who's stuck in the '70s. Allison Smith is also aboard as
the required female assistant with the setup lines.
</P>
<P>
   Despite adherence to the revered formula, or maybe because of
it, ``Buddy Faro'' is slick, well-paced and fun to watch _ a nice
piece of light entertainment for starting the weekend. But any
attempt to compare it with the ABC series ``Vega$,'' which just
happened to debut in 1978, would be preposterous. Dan Tanna's
Thunderbird was cherry red. Buddy Faro's is jet black.
</P>
<P>
   'Course, we all know Jim Rockford's gold Firebird would leave
'em both in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Over at ABC, the TGIF juggernaut continues to roll with a couple
of new entries that are just about par for the course. ``Two of a
Kind,'' featuring the Olsen twins, kicks off the Friday night
kidfest with another of the many single-parent shows so popular
this season. ``Brother's Keeper'' wraps up the two-hour TGIF block
with yet another.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Two of a Kind,'' Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen play Mary-Kate
and Ashley Burke, very different twin daughters of science
professor Kevin Burke (Christopher Sieber), who is looking for the
right person to supervise them when he's away. The least likely
candidate, at least in his mind, is a 28-year-old headstrong
freshman named Carrie Moore (Sally Wheeler), who doesn' exactly get
off on the right foot with the professor on the first day of class.
</P>
<P>
   Natuarlly, the girls love Carrie because she can relate to the
tomboy in Mary-Kate and the princess in Ashley and, well, you
pretty much know the rest of the story.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing here that will go down in the annals of TV lore,
but for ABC's intended audience of pre-teens, ``Two of a Kind'' is
quite acceptable, and a vast improvement over last year's failed
entries, ``Teen Angel'' and ``You Wish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Brother's Keeper'' isn't half-bad, either, though the similar
premise may wear thin after a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Porter Waide (William Ragsdale) is a college professor (history
this time) who is trying to raise his 8-year-old son Oscar (Justin
Cooper) alone. Waide seems to be faring well until his
ne'er-do-well brother Bobby, a pro football placekicker, arrives
one day. It seems Bobby (Sean O'Bryan) is such a well-known
troublemaker that his new team has required that he live with a
responsible party to stay on the straight and narrow _ and be
assured of getting his million-dollar salary.
</P>
<P>
   Little Oscar thinks it's cool having another juvenile around.
His dad isn't so sure, but he allows Bobby to stay, meaning he
occasionally has two children to contend with, and that Oscar has
two very distinct _ and distinctly different _ authority figures.
</P>
<P>
   O'Bryan is especially appealing in the role of the irresponsible
lout knowing he should be a good camper but more inclined to
mischief-making.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buddy Faro. Hourlong drama about a private investigator who
resurfaces after a 20-year, self-imposed exile. Starring Dennis
Farina, Frank Whaley and Allison Smith. Premieres Friday, CBS.
Check local listings. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Two of a Kind. Half-hour comedy about a widowed dad trying to
raise identical _ but very different _ twins. Starring Kevin Burke,
Mary-Kate Olsen, Ashley Olsen and Sally Wheeler. Premieres Friday,
ABC. Check local listings. Parental guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Brother's Keeper. Half-hour comedy about a rambunctious
football player who moves in with his uptight brother, a single
parent who is trying to provide appropriate role models for his
8-year-old son. Starring William Ragsdale, Sean O'Bryan, Justin
Cooper and Bess Meyer. Premieres Friday, ABC. Check local listings.
Parental guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send an e-mail
message to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
