<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS SAN FRANCISCO AREA'S ECONOMY CONTINUES TO BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Bay area continues to show
steady growth and low unemployment despite the eventual loss of 13
military bases in the region and the financial instability in Asia,
according to a survey released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly everyone has concerns about the developments in Asia
and who knows what will happen in Latin America but, at this point,
the Bay area has shown its economic resilience,'' said Alexander
Winslow, spokesman for the Bay Area Council, a regional nonprofit
organization of corporate leaders. The survey was published in the
council's quarterly Economic Pulse newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The one area where the Bay area has felt the Asian flu has been
in merchandise exports, which fell 4.4 percent in 1998's second
quarter from the previous quarter and 8.2 percent from the same
quarter last year. Winslow said the numbers were still in line with
national export figures.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay area's unemployment rate of 3.5 percent is well below
the state's rate of 5.7 percent and the nation's 4.5 percent rate.
Meanwhile, the Bay area's 1998 annual growth rate of 3 percent
slowed slightly from 4.5 percent in 1997 and 3.3 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Housing prices, another indicator for a region's economic
strength, were 8.8 percent higher than the previous quarter and
15.2 percent higher than the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   This quarter's report focused on how the Bay area's seven
military bases that began closing in 1994 and the six others slated
to be shut down through 2008 affect the economy. The bases
represent more than 45,000 military and civilian jobs lost, or 1.3
percent of all jobs in the area.
</P>
<P>
   R. Sean Randolph, president of the Bay Area Economic Forum and
co-author of the base portion of the report, said the Bay area is
the most heavily affected part of the country for base closings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is not the closures, but how rapidly those
bases can be converted to productive civilian use,'' Randolph said.
``It's going to take a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   While the closings can eventually have a positive effect on the
economy, Randolph said the process may be delayed by environmental
cleanup problems and confusion over who controls the military bases
for lease purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
