<SLUG> BC-FOLKLORICO-DANCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLET FOLKLORICO DE MEXICO TAPS COLORFUL ARRAY OF CULTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Long, long ago, in the days before Riverdance, there
was a dance company that evoked the native culture of a country by
blending classical technique and folk traditions.
</P>
<P>
   It's still around. And despite being 46 years old, Ballet
Folklorico de Mexico remains popular.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it finds itself on the leading edge of the
fastest-growing market in the United States: the Hispanic
community.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ballet Folklorico de Mexico appeals not only to Hispanics,
says co-producer Adam Friedson, but to Anglos who want to move
beyond a concept of Mexican culture that stops at serapes and
tacos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The various dances in the show come from the daily lives of
people in Mexico, and each dance is unique to the culture of the
region it comes from,'' says Friedson, a Los Angeles-based producer
who describes himself as ``the Anglo half'' of the production team.
</P>
<P>
   Not many people, for example, would think ``Mexico'' and conjure
a sea pageant with French and African influences. Yet the Mexican
state of Veracruz, home to the eponymous port city, harbored
African slaves who jumped ship on the way to the United States in
the 19th century. It was also home to many French families during
the reign of Maximilian, the Austrian made Emperor of Mexico by
Napoleon III.
</P>
<P>
   Add Dutch traders to this polyglot, mix them with the Spanish
and Native American ingredients that are Mexico's backbone, and
what's the result?
</P>
<P>
   `` `Fiesta de Tlacotalpan' is the dance from Veracruz state,''
Friedson says. ``The women are undersea creatures, and the men come
out and capture them with huge white nets. There's also a great big
Carnival scene with huge puppets of papier-mache and iron. It
really expresses the cultural lifeblood of the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Mexican states represented in the current version of
Ballet Folklorico de Mexico include Chiapas, Chihuahua, the Yucatan
and Jalisco. Though the dances change from year to year and from
tour to tour, the most enduring is that from Sonora: the
extraordinary Deer Dance of the Yaqui Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first dance to define the company, back in the
1950s,'' Friedson says.
</P>
<P>
   The Deer Dance was choreographed by Ballet Folklorico's founder,
Amalia Hernandez, who single-handedly originated not only Ballet
Folklorico de Mexico, but the very idea of folkloric dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She created the concept of training the dancers in classical
technique first and then giving them the folk traditions. She
started the company in 1952, vigorously researching the traditions
herself, drawing all the designs for scenery and costumes. For many
years, her company was presented in the United States by the great
impresario Sol Hurok,'' Friedson says.
</P>
<P>
   But when Hurok died in 1979, there was nobody ``to treat Amalia
as the incredible diva she is,'' according to Friedson. For almost
a decade, Ballet Folklorico de Mexico did not tour the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hernandez remembered the son of a friend, a young man who
had produced concerts in Mexico and in the United States with an
American partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I became involved,'' Friedson _ the American
partner _ recalls with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my friend, Julio Solorzano, she called to produce the
company's reintroduction to the United States. I said to Julio,
`But you've never produced anything like this.' He said he knew
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first efforts, a pair of concerts in Southern California in
1987, failed to make expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can remain friends with a producing partner when you're
losing money, you can make it. Julio and I laughed through those
first traumatic concerts,'' Friedson says.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the losses, Hernandez asked the team to produce the
company's future tours of the United States, which have
subsequently been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we came to understand was that the Hispanic market has
had a sudden transformation. It now desires high-quality
entertainment on a world-class level.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, now 81, is in semi-retirement, but she's creating a
dance based on Mexican Christmas traditions for the company, to be
premiered in December. The newest addition to the present tour is
nearly in sync with Egypt-mania:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing a 30- by 30-foot pyramid that weighs about a
ton,'' Friedson says. ``It's for the new opening number about Aztec
gods.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
