<SLUG> BC-BODE-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TEXAS REPORTER, LAWMAKER DIES AT 72 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARMINIA DANINI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Mary Jane Bode, an award-winning journalist,
former state legislator and first female press secretary for a
statewide office in Texas, died Wednesday morning in Barrington,
Ill., where she had been visiting her daughter. She was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Bode died at Good Shepherd Hospital of complications from
cancer, said her daughter, Georgianne Harms.
</P>
<P>
   During a journalism career that spanned more than 30 years, she
was a political reporter and worked for the Long News Service, the
Austin American-Statesman, the Corpus Christi Caller-Times, the Del
Rio News-Herald, the Houston Chronicle and the San Antonio
Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   She played flag football in George Bush's back yard and covered
the first presidential press conference on the environment, but her
most memorable assignment occurred the day the infamous Berlin Wall
came down.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1989, Bode was assigned to follow the West German
ambassador for the day _ the same day the East German government
announced it would open the border with the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him (the ambassador) at 9:30 and by 3 o'clock, my notes
were obsolete,'' she recalled in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Bode went to work for then-Attorney General John Hill
as his press secretary and speechwriter. She stayed with Hill until
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, a former chief justice of the Texas Supreme Court, said
Bode was his right arm in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am saddened because she was very skillful and talented and a
wonderful source of strength,'' said Hill, now a Houston lawyer.
``She saved me a lot of steps and we had so much fun working
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Bode was born in Chicago on July 28, 1926, but moved with her
family to Galveston, Texas, when she was a baby. She was still in
high school when she began working for the Galveston News.
</P>
<P>
   She married a doctor while she was a student at the University
of Houston but he died early in their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Following her husband's death, she went to work at the Houston
Chronicle. While there, she met and married Winston Bode, a
reporter for the Houston Press. The couple later divorced.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Bode ran in the Austin special election to fill the
seat in the Texas House of Representatives left vacant by Sarah
Weddington, who resigned.
</P>
<P>
   She defeated her opponent by 64 votes. The day of her
swearing-in, she joked that her staff referred to her as
``Landslide Bode'' and ``Marginal Mary Jane.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Legislature, she pushed programs to fight child abuse and
to deter juvenile delinquency. She served two terms.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Bode won the Chrysalis Award from the Texas Women's
Political Caucus for ``excellence in continuous coverage of issues
vital to women and humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgianne Harms said her mother always shared her experiences
and knowledge with younger women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any woman who worked hard in Texas politics and journalism was
a friend of hers,'' Harms said.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial services are planned in Austin and in Barrington.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her former husband, Winston Bode of Austin;
two daughters, Georgianne (Dennis) Harms of Barrington and Vera
Alexander of San Marcos, Texas; and one son, Todd (Charmaine) Bode
of Austin; and five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Her oldest child, a son, Cori Carmignani, died in 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
