<SLUG> BC-WILD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD WOMEN: FEMALES FLOCKING TO LEARN OUTDOORS SKILLS  
 (WITH WOLD WOMEN-SIDE) 
</HEADLINE>
 WOMEN-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE NEWBERG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Looping a line in the graceful arcs of fly-fishing, a
woman coaxes trout from a stream.
</P>
<P>
   Another picks her way through the forest using a topographic map
and compass.
</P>
<P>
   Women across the country are banding together through private
companies and clubs to experience the outdoors as much as their
male counterparts traditionally have.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure companies and programs catering to women in the
outdoors have evolved during the '80s and '90s. Many report full
classes and trips that take as many women as slots allotted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge demand,'' said Nicole Leiria, coordinator of
the California State Parks program Women in the Outdoors. ``It's
taken off.''
</P>
<P>
   California's program is modeled on Becoming an Outdoors Woman,
started by Christine Thomas, a professor of resource management at
the University of Wisconsin. Thomas conducted research in the early
1990s that showed women face a number of barriers to outdoor
activities, from not knowing lingo that enables them to shop for
supplies to a culture that assumes males are more suited to
outdoors training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming an Outdoors Woman was developed as a program to break
down the barriers,'' said its assistant director, Diane Lueck.
Currently it exists in 44 states and nine Canadian provinces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response is so positive. Women look forward to it. They
beg for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Women who participate are often leery, wondering whether they
must sleep outside or if they'll be thrown out into the wild and
expected to co-exist with nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in new territory,'' Leiria said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than roughing it in rustic style, women typically stay in
cabins or similar accommodations, with meals included as part of
the purchase price. Classes offered teach women new skills _
backpacking, outdoor survival, map and compass skills.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to any of the women's outdoor companies and one theme is
dominant: Women who learn new skills come away with a boosted sense
of self-confidence. Part of it stems from participating in a
learning environment that is nurturing rather than competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you gain a little bit of knowledge and a little bit of
experience . . . it makes them feel like they're so empowered, and
they can do anything that they want to do,'' Leiria said.
</P>
<P>
   Some needed that boost to help them through tough times. Many
women who come through the program are in transition _ kids have
left the nest, a divorce has left them lonely, perhaps they simply
feel a need for something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women are there not just for the outdoors skills part of
it. There's a change going on in them,'' Lueck said.
</P>
<P>
   Women who participate have a stubborn streak when it comes to
sticking out the experience. When a foot of snow fell during a
Becoming an Outdoors Woman conference in March in Arizona, only
seven of about 100 who came left early.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were canoeing in the snow. They were fly-fishing while it
was snowing,'' said Valerie Nelson, office manager at the Arizona
Wildlife Federation, which coordinates the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly few complaints come from male partners. One Montana
husband paid for his new bride to attend a workshop during their
honeymoon so they could do more outdoors together. Another woman
who was left immobile by illness came to a California conference
after her health improved. Her husband bought the trip for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really apprehensive about coming. . . . By the end of
the weekend, she was doing everything and just having a great,
great time,'' Leiria said. ``It really had changed her way of
thinking about the things we fear and the things we avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically the three-day weekends go something like this: Women
check in. Greetings by organizers follow, perhaps over lunch, then
it's off to the first session. Sample classes: fly-fishing, camp
cooking, rifle marksmanship, beginning archery, canoeing, mountain
biking and horse sense.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most popular classes are those normally associated
with the most macho of men. So many women at an Alaska workshop
wanted to take game cleaning that organizers had to double the
number allowed in the class.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Wisconsin, it is the class that filled first,'' Lueck said.
``The shooting classes are very popular.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're breaking down the barriers,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The women are there not just for the outdoors skills part of it.
There's a change going on in them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
