<HEADLINE>
`RONIN' IS OLD-FASHIONED FARE IN THE SPIRIT OF `BULLITT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you find yourself nostalgic for an old-fashioned,
no-holds-barred car chase _ on the scale of those signature moments
of 1968's ``Bullitt'' and 1971's ``The French Connection'' _ then
John Frankenheimer's ``Ronin'' is your movie.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the director promised ``the granddaddy of all
car chases'' and he's delivered the goods _ not just one, but two
lavishly suicidal crunch-a-thons: one through the narrow streets of
the Parisian Left Bank, the other along the broad corniches of the
French Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   And the movie itself makes an entertaining thriller, though _ as
always with Frankenheimer, the director of such classics as ``The
Manchurian Candidate'' and ``The Train'' _ it has an off-beat and
enigmatic edge that could frustrate anyone expecting a more
traditional action movie.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about a band of mercenaries recruited in Paris by a
pretty Irish terrorist (Natascha McElhone) for a particularly
difficult caper: the snatching of a valuable, highly protected
suitcase of undisclosed contents in the south of France.
</P>
<P>
   The men are all ex-intelligence agents from various countries
who have been put out of work by the end of the Cold War (``like
ronin samurai without a liege lord,'' one of them explains): an
American (Robert De Niro), a Frenchman (Jean Reno), a Brit (Sean
Bean) and a Russian (Skellan Skarsgard).
</P>
<P>
   It's an art house cast and, at times, it seems like an art house
movie. The various characters' foreign accents _ especially those
of McElhone and Bean _ are so hard to follow they need subtitles,
and it's easy to get lost in the bewildering array of
double-crosses and double-double crosses that drive the plot.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other time in his 40-year career, Frankenheimer's
design seems to be to subordinate everything in his film _
character, story, dialogue, humor _ to his fast-paced style and
disjointed, existential mood. In a way, it's quite demanding, and
it often helps to just turn off the mind and go with the
exhilarating flow.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, everyone and everything do eventually add up and make
sense, and the film ultimately pays off with considerably more
story satisfaction than we usually get in big-budget Hollywood
action spectaculars. All told, ``Ronin'' is a clever piece of
visual story-telling.
</P>
<P>
   It does, however, invite criticism for one bizarre moment: the
unmistakable recreation (in the midst of its second chase sequence)
of the pursuit of Princess Di through the Seine tunnel one year
ago, with the exact same flip-over crash against the tunnel wall.
What is this? A bad-taste in-joke? A ghoulish anniversary tribute?
</P>
<P>
   Ronin. Directed by John Frankenheimer. Screenplay by J.D. Zeik
and Richard Weisz. Cast: Robert De Niro, Jean Reno, Natascha
McElhone, Stellan Skarsgard, Sean Bean. United Artists. 118
minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
