A2477 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-URBAN-SPI &LR;      09-24 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-URBAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`URBAN LEGEND'S' HUMOR JUST DOESN'T CUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all know an urban legend: there's the one about the famous
actor who did something gross with a gerbil; or about the
babysitter who, after being beleagured by frightening phone calls,
discovers the stalker is upstairs in the house.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of using modern, weird tales as the basis for a horror
film must have sounded intriguing on paper and, for the first half
hour or so, ``Urban Legend'' has some potential.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it quickly erodes into a mean-spirited,
ridiculous and sadistic gore-fest that includes a scene with a dog
and a microwave.
</P>
<P>
   True, horror is hip at the box office. Witness the success of
``Scream'' and its sequel and the recent ``Halloween: H2O.'' But
``Urban Legend,'' which actually features a better-than-average
cast, is dull-witted by comparison. It makes a stab at humor but
doesn't cut it. The only amusing character is Loretta Devine, who
plays a campus cop named Reese who practices gunplay while watching
a video of Pam Grier in ``Foxy Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone has lost more than their mind at the peaceful,
gable-and-stone New Hampshire-based Pendleton College campus. A
young coed has just lost her head _ literally _ in a murder that
bears a striking resemblance to an urban legend. Soon the peace and
serenity of the school known as ``the safest in the country'' is
shattered as students and faculty alike begin dying in mysterious
ways based on all kinds of modern myths.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to a young journalism student, Paul (Jared Leto), and
Natalie (Alicia Witt), for whom the killings have become perilously
personal, to discover the reason for the serial murders and the
identity of a killer who has a very sick sense of ``moral
admonition.'' They're aided by Professor Wexler (Robert Englund),
who teaches a class on American Folklore and who is the only
survivor of the Stanley Hall Massacre, a black spot in the school's
stellar history.
</P>
<P>
   Leto and Witt, who are both capable, likeable actors, are wasted
in this outing. The 24-year-old scriptwriter, Silvio Horta, and
director Jamie Blanks give them very little to do except stand
around and look worried and perplexed while they utter some
dreadfully bad lines.
</P>
<P>
   At least supporting actors Devine, Rebecca Gayheart and Joshua
Jackson understand they're not exactly making high art and camp it
up wildly, adding a little spice. But the film itself is eminently
forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Legend. Directed by Jamie Blanks. Written by Silvio Horta.
Cast: Jared Leto, Alicia Witt, Rebecca Gayheart, Natasha Gregson
Wagner. TriStar Pictures. 100 minutes. Rated R for graphic
violence, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
