<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CRIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A SOLDIER'S DAUGHTER' IS THE ANTITHESIS OF `MOMMIE DEAREST' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of his writing career, James Jones suffered from having
his work compared unfavorably to his landmark first novel, ``From
Here to Eternity.'' Esquire Magazine once even made the morbid case
(``James Jones and the Critics'') that he was possibly the most
critically lambasted American novelist of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   But he's definitely getting the last laugh. His critical
reputation has steadily grown since his 1977 death until he's now
almost universally considered the greatest novelist of the World
War II generation. More recently _ thanks largely to Terrence
Malick's upcoming film version of Jones' 1962 novel, ``The Thin Red
Line'' _ he's once again the hottest writer in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a half-dozen biographies and memoirs that have
appeared in the last 20 years have all made the case that Jones was
that rarity in American letters: a successful novelist who was also
a successful human being. As gifted as he was as a novelist, he was
even better at being a father, husband and friend.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, this unique American success story is not going to be
tarnished by ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries,'' the
Merchant-Ivory film version of a family memoir written by Jones'
daughter, Kaylie. As a portrait of the artist as a parent, it's the
very antithesis of ``Mommie Dearest'' and the whole
celebrity-parent bashing genre.
</P>
<P>
   The film is also more than just a valentine to Jones' parenting
skills. It's an unusually rich, unconventional and highly original
coming-of-age-in-the-'70s drama, and a bittersweet meditation on
the expatriate life. Frame-for-frame, it's the most totally
satisfying Merchant-Ivory production since ``A Room With a View.''
</P>
<P>
   The script, by James Ivory and Ruth Prawer Jhabvala, is divided
into three segments, and opens in the late '60s as the Jones family
_ father (Kris Kristofferson), mother (Barbara Hershey) and young
daughter (Luisa Conlon) _ have left America to live more or less
permanently in a luxury apartment on Paris' fashionable Ille St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The first segment deals mostly with the James and Gloria Jones'
adoption of a French orphan boy: opening with the young mother's
decision to give up her son, his conflict with his slightly jealous
new sister, his difficulties adjusting to his posh new school, and
his gradual bonding with the American family.
</P>
<P>
   The second section follows the daughter, now a teenager (Leelee
Sobieski), through her early adolescence, concentrating on her
problems being an American in a French school, and her relationship
with her best friend and soulmate: an effeminate, illegitimate boy
(Anthony Roth Costanzo) who aspires to be an opera singer.
</P>
<P>
   The third section chronicles the family's decision to return to
their native land in the early '70s, the two teenagers' shaky
adjustment to suburban American life, the death of the
author-father from a congenital heart problem, and the impact this
incomparable loss has on each surviving member of the family.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, this could be the most authentic film biography
ever made of a famous writer. Nothing seems to have been invented,
scenes were filmed in and around the actual Jones apartment on the
Quai d'Orleans, and _ though there's not much physical resemblance
_ the performances of Kristofferson and Hershey could hardly be
more authentic.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaylie Jones wrote her family story as a novel, she changed
the characters names (from Jones to Willis), and she really doesn't
go into any of the famous particulars of Jones' literary life. The
film maintains the limited point-of-view of the daughter character
throughout, and claims the protection of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   And its real power comes less from biographical accuracy than in
its poignant universality as a family drama. Even without the Jones
connection, the film comes off as a splendid collection of
vignettes tracing the childhood of a young American girl in an
alien, often hostile, always magical Paris of the '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly effective are the scenes tracing the young
heroine's difficult sexual awakening _ including a pre-adolescent,
quasi-rape by a young neighbor boy that is boldly, yet sensitively,
handled _ and her growing awareness of her famous, rather gruff
father's total, unquestioning love and acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, and in its own unique way, ``A Soldier's Daughter''
is wonderfully reminiscent of the 1962 ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
Like that classic film, it's about the power of a successful
father-daughter relationship, and it's a celebration of an
unorthodox but completely functional family unit.
</P>
<P>
   A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries. Directed by James Ivory.
Screenplay by Ivory and Ruth Prawer Jhabvala. Cast: Kris
Kristofferson, Barbara Hershey, Leelee Sobieski, Jane Birkin.
October Films. 124 minutes. Rated R for mature themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
