<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISED BOOK REVEALS DARK SIDE OF FUNERAL INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick, name the third-largest single household expense after the
house and the car. A pool? A grand piano? A Jacuzzi?
</P>
<P>
   How about your funeral?
</P>
<P>
   The average cost for an adult funeral is a whopping $7,800,
according to the funeral industry. That makes the funeral business
big business.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Houston-based Service Corporation International, a
major chain in the funeral business, took in more than $1.5 billion
in 1995. In 1996, the company sold more than $2.3 billion in
pre-arranged funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funeral seller, like any other merchant, is preoccupied
with price, profit, selling techniques,'' who wrote Jessica Mitford
the definitive industry expose, ``The American Way of Death,'' in
1962. ``Thirty years later, the situation seems worse,'' Mitford
writes in an updated version of the material.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Mitford, a self-proclaimed muckraking journalist, saw the
need for an update of her original bestseller. Although Mitford
died last year at age 78, her book is now out and could be just as
popular as the last.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``The American Way of Death Revisited'' (Alfred A.
Knopf, 296 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   In her cut-to-the-chase style, Mitford describes the funeral
industry as an overpriced, unregulated sham that plays on the
public during one of life's most difficult moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sellers of funeral service have, one gathers, a
preconceived, stereotyped view of their customers,'' she writes.
``To them, the bereaved person who enters the funeral establishment
is a bundle of guilt feelings, a snob, and a status seeker.''
</P>
<P>
   Most consumers are not in a mood to shop, are generally
uninformed about the products and are forced into an impulse buy.
Why else would they buy such items as Ko-Zees, shoes for the dead
described as having ``soft, warm, luxurious slipper comfort, but
true shoe smartness.'' Or the Beautyrama Adjustable Soft-Foam Bed,
a quality mattress inside the casket.
</P>
<P>
   And don't get Mitford started on caskets. She discusses topics
from casket arrangement in the showroom to the latest models,
including Batesville's Burping Casket with a permeable seal
designed to ``burp'' out the buildup of methane gas from the
decomposing body, thus avoiding a casket explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Mitford discusses how funeral home personnel and their products
seek to manipulate customers, often quoting directly from trade
publications, annual reports and such publications as the
``Successful Mortuary Operation Service Manual.''
</P>
<P>
   She also provides a good overview of the death industry,
including some interesting statistics. One of the reasons the
industry is so high-priced is because there are approximately
22,000 nationwide, when less than 10,000 are needed, according to
the Funeral and Memorial Societies of America. Based on the death
rate, most funeral homes conduct only one or two funerals a week.
</P>
<P>
   But consolidation, a major industry trend, doesn't seem to be
lowering prices. Corporations such as SCI may own many funeral
homes in a given area but are not passing on economies of scale to
their customers, Mitford writes.
</P>
<P>
   The author also looks at the failings of the industry's primary
regulator, the Federal Trade Commission. In 1995, after years of
inactivity, the FTC conducted what it termed a ``nationwide
crackdown'' on the industry that actually covered just three
states, even though the agency estimated that less than 30 percent
of all mortuaries complied with the pricing disclosure rules.
</P>
<P>
   Mitford ends her book with a chapter on the growth of such
nonprofit watchdog
</P>
<P>
   organizations as the Funeral and Memorial Societies of America.
She includes a state-by-state directory of nonprofit funeral and
memorial societies that provide price surveys and discounts for
members, and she includes toll-free phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mitford leaves readers with two helpful consumer tips.
One, send a friend to two or more mortuaries to get general price
lists and casket prices, plus the cost of direct cremation or an
immediate burial.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Mitford writes, ``remember, above all, that many funeral
homes have a `no-walk' policy, which means simply that if and when
you start to walk out, the price will come down, down, down until a
level acceptable to you is reached.''
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
