<SLUG> BC-FILM-PECKER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATERS GOES GENIAL IN OFF-THE-WALL `PECKER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Waters is going soft. His latest comedy is the not-so-black
``Pecker,'' a homage to Waters' hometown of Baltimore and a sweet
little satire of the New York art world.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Furlong, who starred as the kid in danger in ``Terminator
2 _ Judgment Day,'' brings a loopy grace to the title role, playing
a compulsive photographer who's called Pecker because he pecks at
his food. Eating isn't his thing. He'd rather watch and record.
Everywhere he goes he snaps pictures.
</P>
<P>
   What fascinates him? His family and hometown. His mother (Mary
Kay Place) runs a clothing store for the homeless: ``We know how to
make a dollar hollar.'' His dimwitted dad (Mark Joy) runs a bar and
his grandmother (Jean Schertler) sells pit beef sandwiches from a
stand in front of the family home and talks to her statue of the
Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Grandma makes Mary's rubbery mouth move, but instead of the
traditional ``full of grace,'' Grandma has her say, ``full of
grease,'' which is more in keeping with Grandma's line of work.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker's girlfriend Shelley (Christina Ricci) runs a notably
strict laundromat and his best friend Matt (Brendan Sexton III)
shoplifts for a living. Add his big sister Tina (Martha Plimpton),
who hosts a gay strip bar, and his little sister Chrissy (Lauren
Hulsey), the sugar addict, and Waters has a scene that makes the
blighted version of L.A. in Quentin Tarantino's ``Jackie Brown''
look decidedly upscale.
</P>
<P>
   And yet everybody here gets along. Nobody's mad, nobody's
wasting his life, abusing illegal substances, mulling over his
problems or aspiring to greater things. It's one big happy family,
until Pecker's pics hit the big time. New York art dealer Rorey
(Lili Taylor) sees his stuff, loves it and makes him a star.
</P>
<P>
   In loving him, New York patronizes him and unsettles not only
his life but the lives of everybody around him.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the movie's been fun to watch, but predictable. Now
Waters hits his stride, turning the cultural tables in a fun and
inventive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pecker'' sounds no depths, offers few real insights in art but
creates a happy glow of a good time, full of zinging one-liners and
credible camera work. It isn't Waters at his best, but Waters at
his most relaxed and genial. And the actors are terrific,
especially the deadpan Ricci and darling boy Furlong as Pecker.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker. Directed and written by John Waters. Cast: Edward
Furlong, Christina Ricci, Martha Plimpton, Lili Taylor. Fine Line
Features. 87 minutes. Rated R for language and partial nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
