<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; tth-z
r E &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CLAY-SPI &LR;      09-24 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CLAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLAY PIGEONS' IS INCORRIGIBLY MEDIOCRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an interview last month, director Gus Van Zant said he cast
Vince Vaughn for the Norman Bates role in his upcoming remake of
Hitchcock's ``Psycho'' because he wanted ``someone who would take
you off guard'' _ an actor you wouldn't expect to be a serial
murderer.
</P>
<P>
   But it now looks as if Vaughn could be typecast in that role
before the film's December release. Because in ``Clay Pigeons,'' he
plays a vicious murderer of helpless women in a story that seems to
be inspired, ironically enough, by Hitchcock's ``Strangers On a
Train.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not exactly an auspicious matching of actor and role,
either. In fact, he gives a fairly hammy performance in what is an
incorrigibly mediocre movie. If his ``Psycho'' turn isn't quite a
few notches above this one, Anthony Perkins can continue to rest in
peace.
</P>
<P>
   The film is about a smalltown Montana auto mechanic named Clay
(Joaquin Phoenix), whose best friend (Gregory Sporleder) _
devastated by his discovery that Clay is having an affair with his
wife _ kills himself in the opening scene and makes it appear that
Clay is the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   When the wife (Georgina Cates) starts to sexually blackmail him,
she in turn is murdered by an affable stranger named Lester
(Vaughn) who _ as in Hitchcock's ``Strangers'' _ commits the murder
to ingratiate himself with the hero, expecting friendship, approval
and reciprocation.
</P>
<P>
   Out of this situation, first-time director David Dobkin tries to
construct a typical Hitchcockian drama that gets more ironic and
darkly humorous as the innocent hero struggles desperately to get
out of his mess, and only looks more and more guilty to the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the film somehow manages to lose its way in the first act,
and never recovers. Indeed, it's so incompetent that it plays its
big dramatic scene _ Phoenix, locked up in jail and thus
agonizingly unable to prevent Vaughn from murdering a young girl _
in a cell with bars set so wide apart that Orson Welles would slip
through them!
</P>
<P>
   The cast has a few bright spots _ the usual good work from Scott
Wilson and Georgina Cates. But the two leads are weak: Phoenix
simply looks too malevolent to be very credible as a wronged
innocent, and Vaughn is at a loss to find that element which made
all the great Hitchcock villains come alive _ a point of sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Pigeons. Directed by David Dobkin. Written by Matt Healy.
Cast: Joaquin Phoenix, Vince Vaughn, Georgina Cates, Scott Wilson,
Janeane Garofalo. Gramercy. 104 minutes. Rated R for violence and
sex scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
