<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JUSTWRITE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WRITE' TRAPPED IN A PEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold McMurphy is a nice guy, a good son _ and he perceives
himself as such a loser, even his daydreams end with him getting
dumped.
</P>
<P>
   Harold is a Hollywood tour-bus driver who would be happy with
his job if only people cared more about film history than about
contemporary action heroes. His low self-esteem leads him to take a
lot of bad advice _ none of which includes ``be yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that when Harold meets Amanda Clark, his favorite
actress, he leads her to believe that he's a hotshot screenwriter.
Or rather, she leads herself to believe it _ and he doesn't stop
her.
</P>
<P>
   That's the premise of ``Just Write,'' which _ despite likable
characters and performances _ just doesn't feel quite right. It
seems like a screenwriter's daydream, one in which he gets the
pretty actress, who's really just a person like everyone else. But
it's a daydream built on a shaky foundation. Take away any one
element _ Harold's lie, Amanda's gullibility, the pigheadedness of
Harold's father, the unusually understanding writer's agent, the
self-absorption of the Hollywood players who don't want to admit
they've never heard of Harold _ and the whole thing would fall
apart.
</P>
<P>
   The movie provides a few reasons to forgive its contrivances,
but they're not quite enough to put it in the win column. Like
``Second Chances,'' another small-budget indie released this year,
its primary virtue is its lack of cynicism _ this movie wants to
entertain more than it wants to make big bucks. Although Stan
Williamson's script is formulaic, it does get in some funny digs at
Hollywood _ enough that you wish it would go further _ and it
appreciates the past: You don't see too many movies these days
where the characters sing the praises of ``All About Eve'' and
``Sunset Boulevard.'' And, to the movie's credit, it doesn't think
it's on the same plane as those classics.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Piven, dropping his wiseacre act, and Sherilyn Fenn, in a
sweet role that's far from the weirdness of ``Twin Peaks'' and
``Boxing Helena,'' are charming in the lead roles, and JoBeth
Williams is funny as Amanda's cell-phone-addicted agent. Director
Andrew Gallerani keeps a loose hand on a fairly large cast, unusual
for a graduate of directing commercials _ they usually want to show
all the flash they can. His lack of self-consciousness is another
point in the movie's favor.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was produced by former Arlington resident Heath
McLaughlin, whose own story (not to mention initials) echoes
Harold's a little: After longtime work as an extra, the former
military pilot decided to produce a script himself, and with
investments from some Wisconsin dentists, picked this script out of
350 submitted in response to an ad in trade publications. The film
has played well at festivals, and it has an appealing innocence
that borders on naivete. McLaughlin's working on another film _
time will tell what he has learned from experience.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Just Write''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Andrew Gallerani
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jeremy Piven, Sherilyn Fenn
</P>
<P>
   Length: 106 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Not rated _ PG equivalent for language, most of which is
about the level of a prime-time TV show
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
