<P>
   &UR; PLACES AND DESTINATIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SMOKIES-COX (Fontana Village, N.C.) _ It took a village
to make our family's summer vacation a fun one. The Historic
Fontana Village, that is, a sprawling resort in northwest North
Carolina. The nearest town is a 22-mile, twisting, rolling drive to
the south. To the north looms the Great Smoky Mountains National
Park. By Angel Bedinghauszent.
</P>
<P>
   MCMURTRY-HOMETOWN-TEX (Archer City) _ Archer City, Texas, offers
visitors a museum, good home-cooked food, a new bed-and-breakfast,
and homeboy Larry McMurtry's rare-books bookstore, Booked Up _
along with McMurtry himself. By Liz Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ALASKA-BOS (Juneau, Alaska) _ It's a rare day in Alaska
when you can sight a pod of Orca moving about the waters off Juneau
for an extended period of time. By Robert F. Cutting.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TAHITI-BOS (Papeete, Tahiti) _ Is paradise possible in
just over a week's vacation, and would it be worth it? The answer
to both questions is, ``Yes.'' By Jerry Morris.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DISNEY-BOS (Undated) _ Would you or should you sail on a
ship with mouse ears rather than some fanciful logo on its
smokestacks? Welcome to the Disney Magic. By Jerry Morris.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRUISING-BOS (Boston) _ The Star Clipper and the Star
Flyer sail the world; one ship is usually found in the Caribbean.
Passengers can participate in sailing. By Jerry Morris.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COCKPIT-SAFETY-NYT (Undated) _ Asleep in the cockpit?
Automation's nightmare. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GREECE-NYT (Undated) _ Love among the ruins: Naxos'
ancient landscape. By Benedict Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LIGHT-PACKING-NYT (Undated) _ Leaving the right stuff
behind can lead to the best of times. By Jan Benzel.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-CRUISE-COX (Aboard the Disney Magic) _ Disney's special
touch is everywhere on the company's maiden voyage into the cruise
business. By Paula Crouch Thrasher.
</P>
<P>
   MAGIC-CRUISE-HNS (Aboard the Disney Magic) _ When it comes to
the family Caribbean cruise, Disney is, well, Magic. The ship Magic
has the look and feel of the great ocean liners of the 1930s.
Reportedly, a classic look was demanded by Disney chairman Michael
Eisner _ and he got it. Yet there are disappointments, including
the food and service. By Julie Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNT-KATAHDIN-HNS (Mount Katahdin, Maine) _ Since early times,
artists and writers have sought to capture the mystique of this
great mass. Unlike native Americans who respected the mountain
spirits and stayed away, 19th-century white men set foot on
Katahdin, then encouraged other adventurers to join them. By Fred
Stetson.
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-LAND-HNS (Lafayette, La.) _ A look at Cajun life and its
people. A people with an unfailing zest for life. Men and women who
treasure a rib-tickling joke, even if it's at their own expense;
who cherish a lovingly prepared meal accented by conversation as
free-flowing as the wine and as well-seasoned as the crawfish
gumbo; who step sprightly into the wee hours, intoxicated by the
beat of an accordion or fiddle. By Harry Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-DINING-HNS (Lafayette, La.) _ Think Cajun food, and the
prevailing images for many people are blackened catfish, gumbo,
boudin, jambalaya and spicy fried shrimp. You can find the best of
each in southwest Louisiana. By Harry Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-WILDLIFE-HNS (New Iberia, La.) _ With its diverse habitats
and mild winters, southwest Louisiana brims with natural wonders,
both flora and fauna. By Syd Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-EVANGELINE-HNS (St. Martinville, La.) _ Come hear the
stories of this little town on Bayou Teche. Some of its tales are
fact, others merely myth. Many likely are a combination of the two.
All are worth sharing. By Syd Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-HILTONHEAD-COX (Hilton Head, S.C.) _ There is something
about a fall beach vacation that feels a little like rebellion. By
Nick Tate.
</P>
