<SLUG> BC-FILM-PECKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNPARALLELED BAD TASTE, DONE BY THE MASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer/director John Waters was disgusting when disgusting
wasn't cool. Before the Pythons were vomiting in restaurants,
before Mel Brooks found flatulence funny and before the Farrelly
Brothers discovered a new kind of hair gel _ the granddaddy of the
gross-out was outdoing them all. And with the arrival of his latest
picture, ``Pecker,'' this weekend, Waters proves he can still turn
a stomach while getting a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Furlong is an amiable amateur photographer called
``Pecker'' _ a nickname he supposedly earned from pecking at his
food as a child. Armed with an old camera rescued from the junk
shop run by his mother (Texan Mary Kay Place), Pecker patrols his
lower-class Baltimore neighborhood snapping shots of angry
suburbanites, copulating rodents and his twisted little family.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the young shooter couldn't ask for better subject
matter than his Catholic grandmother talking to her ventriloquist
Virgin Mary doll; his foul-mouthed sister (Martha Plimpton)
introducing male strippers at The Fudge Palace, the local gay bar;
his best friend Matt (''Welcome to the Dollhouse's'' Brendan Sexton
III) showing off his shoplifting prowess; or his sullen-but-sexy
laundromat worker girlfriend Shelley (Christina Ricci).
</P>
<P>
   After he throws together a makeshift show at his day job _
slinging burgers in the local greasy spoon _ Pecker's pictures
capture the attention of a visiting art dealer (Lili Taylor) who
brings his twisted visions to folks who might really appreciate
them ... New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   He's an overnight sensation, of course, along with his
less-than-willing photo subjects, but after riding high on the
crest of big-figure sales, loquacious boot-licking from the
art-critic set and celebrity hobnobbing, Pecker and his pals are
given a crash course in the high price of fame.
</P>
<P>
   But fear not, Waters isn't about to let the Big Apple get the
last bite.
</P>
<P>
   Waters fans from way back have watched the filmmaker's wilder
days give way to more mainstream fare. After such tasteless titles
as ``Pink Flamingos'' and ``Desperate Living,'' Waters' more
contemporary films like ``Hairspray'' and ``Cry-Baby'' seem tame by
comparison. ``Pecker'' is his first picture in a while that should
please his hard-core fans while remaining approachable (albeit
disturbing) to the arthouse set.
</P>
<P>
   Professional brooder Furlong actually seems cheerful in this
one, and Ricci is delightful, as always. But Waters has never been
big on realistic portrayals. He likes his performers to take a cue
from their tacky surroundings and play it larger than life _ and
they don't disappoint. Throw in Waters' regulars Patricia Hearst
and Mink Stole, and you've got a deliciously tasteless, satirically
silly and unnervingly hilarious night at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Would you expect anything less from the man who literally wrote
the book on bad taste?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Pecker''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Waters
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Edward Furlong, Christina Ricci, Lili Taylor
</P>
<P>
   Length: 87 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ nudity, rude humor, adult situations and subject
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
