<HEADER>
A2502 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-RONIN-TEX     09-24 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RONIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEREST IS KILLED OFF EFFICIENTLY, QUICKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ronin'' has a brisk and merciless pace _ it's like a movie put
together by an assassin. It has its moments, but director John
Frankenheimer boils the ingredients _ action, international
terrorism, desperate men down on their luck _ until the film
collapses into a muddled stew.
</P>
<P>
   Robert De Niro takes a rare turn as an action hero. De Niro has
lately developed an indistinct quality; he's become the Unabomber
of performers, efficient, but making you wonder if you'd spotted
him on the premises or just someone who suggests him.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ronin,'' he's Sam, a former CIA operative who joins a group
of dispossessed experts hired by a no-nonsense boss (Natascha
McElhone) to get their hands on a mysterious suitcase. These men _
Vincent (Jean Reno), Gregor (Stellan Skarsgard), Larry (Skipp
Sudduth) and Spence (Sean Bean) _ mossy with three-day growth, are
the ``Ronin'' of the movie, soldiers without a cause.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie appears to be ``Mission: Impossible'' for the
AARP, it makes sense to assemble a group of misfits with
experience. (Reno, however, looks like he was born resembling a
45-year-old.) ``Ronin'' is reminiscent of ``The Dirty Dozen'' or
``The Wages of Fear.'' Each of the guys is a loser who's
unemployable in the intelligence/underworld community in Europe,
probably after the collapse of the Cold War; there's no place left
for them in the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronin'' could be looked upon as a metaphor for older leading
men and directors in Hollywood; Frankenheimer is in his 70s.
Wisely, the picture doesn't belabor that point; it's left for us to
discover this on our own.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro's Sam nods and snarls his lines as if he's doing an
imitation of the De Niro impression that Alec Baldwin toted out on
``Saturday Night Live.'' Many of them, all-business wisecracks,
were penned by David Mamet (under the pseudonym Richard Weisz).
</P>
<P>
   When De Niro tried a turn as an action hero 10 years ago, in
Martin Brest's ``Midnight Run,'' he seemed lost in The Land That
The Method Forgot. In ``Ronin,'' a movie that's whittled away to
mere filigree, he's a better fit, but it's not a role written for
him. And when one of the group turns out to be a traitor, the first
of several meaningless twists, the tension level is cranked up
superficially.
</P>
<P>
   The movie ends up resting on the shoulders of Jean Reno, who's
patient, loyal and sad, a ratty pooch who sticks with his pals.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer proves he's better at action set pieces than any
young, music video-reverent director; there's a draftman's
confidence in his camera framing, even when the pursuit is on foot.
But it's not his low-key approach that makes the movie less than
what it could have been. It's that ``Ronin'' lacks emotional
undercurrents. It's cynical and uninvolving.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Ronin''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Frankenheimer
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Robert De Niro, Jean Reno, Jonathan Pryce
</P>
<P>
   Length: 121 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
