   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-HOLIDAYS-NYT (Undated) A memoir: September is the month
when my mailbox is jammed with fall fashion catalogs and glatt
kosher caterers have signs in their windows urging, ``Place your
holiday orders now.'' For me, the coincidence of these two rituals
inspires a single unifying drive _ to select a wardrobe for Rosh
ha-Shanah and Yom Kippur. By Elizabeth Hayt.
</P>
<P>
   HEBREW-REVIVAL-BOS (Undated) _ With estimates that as many as 80
percent of American Jews have virtually no knowledge of Hebrew, a
national program is launching ambitious 5-week courses at more than
1,000 sites. By Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The matter-of-fact way in
which Ruth Elias tells her Holocaust story only serves to magnify
the horror she endured at Auschwitz. By Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-ROSH-COX _ The Jewish High Holy days are upon us, a
time for members of the Jewish community to take a hard look at the
past year and attempt to figure out how to live their lives as
better people in the coming year. We take a look at the traditions
and rituals surrounding the eight-day period. By Gayle White.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-NOUWEN-COX _ He was a Catholic priest whose writings
reached across denominational and even religious lines. He was a
world-class academic who taught at such prestigious schools as
Harvard and Yale. He was courted by the rich and famous, but liked
to spend most of his time living with and helping the disabled.
Now, two years after his death, Henri Nouwen is becoming even more
popular. By John Blake.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RABBI-NYT (New York) _ Few of the United States' rabbis
will be able to resist the allusive New Year's gift President
Clinton offered to them this month. By David Firestone.
</P>
