<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following auto &QL; 
features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CARS-COX (Austin) _ Before there was a Motor Mile, back
when U.S. 183 was considered in the far reaches of Austin, before
Austinites had ever heard of a car named KIA, downtown was the
place to car shop. In the early 1900s, East Fifth Street, Texas,
was lined with dealers that sold Cadillacs and Chandlers, Indiana
Trucks and Studebakers. In recent years, downtown was home to such
dealers as McMorris Ford, Covert Buick and Capitol Chevrolet.
Today, they've all but disappeared. By R. Michelle Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-WHEELCHAIR-CARS-NYT (Undated) _ All adaptive equipment for
people with disabilities is considered specialty equipment, but
within this category are the specialty's specialties. If most
automotive adaptive equipment helps people get into and drive
vehicles, these devices help make that experience more pleasant. By
Robert P. Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-COX _ Review of the Mitsubishi Galant. By Russ
DeVault.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ Forget everything you ever
knew about the Mercury Cougar, that overpriced, bulky, stodgy,
rear-drive midsize coupe that Mercury dropped last year because of
slow sales and general buyer apathy. In its place, picture this: a
youthful-looking, compact, front-drive hatchback coupe with
cutting-edge design, an available V-6 engine and a price that
youthful buyers of all ages can afford. By G. Chambers Williams
III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-AZR (Undated) _ OK, all you wealthy dudes
contemplating a midlife crisis, listen up. Here's a road-burning
hot rod that won't offend Aunt Tillie or cause your ritzy neighbors
to roll their eyes. For the paltry sum of $50,000, you can drive a
275-horsepower ``wunderkind'' that accelerates like a rocket and
handles like a bobsled, all the while looking like any
standard-issue sedan from the Mercedes-Benz E-class. By Bob Golfen.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-BOS (Undated) _ Lexus LS400 is a luxury car that is
boringly close to perfect and quietly becoming the stuff of legend.
By John R. White.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Say goodbye to Buick Riviera. Once
again, having perfected a car, General Motors will kill it. If it's
anything the General can't stand, it would seem to be class. With
the '99 model year, Riviera enters the realm of collectible _ well
maybe the name is already there, at least when it's on a ragtop.
Although Buick has turned out more than a million cars bearing the
Riviera badge since the Riviera first showed up as a ``concept'' in
1963, only 3,000 convertibles were built spanning 1982-1985. By
John R. White.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-AUTOMOBILES-BLOOM (Undated) _ General Motors Corp. will
post a third-quarter loss because of recent strikes by the United
Auto Workers, while earnings will rise at Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. on strong sales of high-profit trucks. The 54-day
strikes against GM at two Michigan parts plants, settled in late
July, had ripple effects throughout the industry. A shortage of GM
cars and trucks, for example, allowed all three companies to cut
third-quarter rebates to an average $1,300 a vehicle, down 23
percent from the second quarter. The lower price discounts and
continued cost-cutting helped profitability for all three
companies. Still, Detroit automakers' earnings are increasingly
threatened by economic problems that are damping demand in Latin
America and Asia. By John Lippert.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-DEALS-LADN (Los Angeles) _ Consumers shopping for a new car
this fall are in for a dose of sticker shock. But it won't be
painful; indeed, they should leave the dealerships smiling and
maybe with some cash in their pocket.  &QL; 
They will be reaping the benefits of a rare autumn buyers' market
as automakers offer lucrative incentives on the last of the 1998
models and, on numerous lots, are slashing prices on new 1999
models just hitting showroom floors. By Gregory J. Wilcox.
</P>
