<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA COP DRAMA `BUDDY FARO' SIZZLES WITH STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a season that was supposed to be wall-to-wall silliness,
insanity and intellectual insults, how pleasing it has been to
watch a number of fall pilots roll off the network assembly line
looking polished, promising and even, dare I say, mechanically
daring.
</P>
<P>
   The latest series worth at least a three-episode look-see is
``Buddy Faro'' (8 p.m. CDT Friday), the CBS drama starring Dennis
Farina as the legendary '70s detective named in the title.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy ran Los Angeles a couple of decades back, moving and
grooving like a Brat Packer, the town's inside-outside man, a
private detective with all the angles, not to mention colorful
lines and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   After disappearing without a trace in 1978, he became his own
Trivial Pursuit question, a man who'd created his own ultimate
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   He resurfaces when a young, brainy investigator, Bob Jones
(Frank Whaley), is hired to find him, which he does in some tiny,
dusty Mexico town. Jones brings Buddy back to LA, where the two
solve a crime and, by episode's end, team up.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of the quick-trigger remote, tonight's episode is
bound to lose viewers early on while it's laying the foundation for
Buddy's entrance. But hang tough. ``Buddy Faro'' starts to crackle
as soon as a bearded Farina appears and opens his mouth, looking
like an alcoholic wolf man, sounding like what he is: a '70s man
living in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Mark Frost (''Twin Peaks'') with Charles Haid as one
of the executive producers, ``Buddy Faro'' looks good (it's as
close to film noir as a TV series will venture) and is well cast
with Farina and even Whaley as the smart but socially clueless
private eye.
</P>
<P>
   But style does not a series make. The drama's success will hinge
on whether writers can come up with interesting, engaging plots to
keep things humming. Otherwise, Farina's swagger will be the only
thing worth returning for, and, in large doses, even the most
pleasurable pursuits get old.
</P>
<P>
   Also debuting Friday night:
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of a Kind'' (7 p.m. CDT, ABC) features the Olsen twins,
Mary-Kate and Ashley, who first came to prominence on ``Full
House'' as 9-month-olds. Here, they play pre-teens giving dad a
hard time. Mary-Kate is the tomboy with a passion for curve balls;
Ashley is the straight-A student whose passion is the boys who
throw curve balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of a Kind'' is merely an updated ``Full House'' without
the sappiness. OK, without so much sappiness you want to drive a
dagger through your heart.
</P>
<P>
   Again, their father, Kevin (Christopher Sieber), is widowed, yet
there's another adult around. Carrie (Sally Wheeler) is a cute
college student hired as a baby sitter. Carrie's insistence on
telling Kevin that she's ``older than the usual student'' screams
out love interest!
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Olsen's built-in audience, decent writing and a
time slot in which ``Full House'' was a ratings winner, ``Two of a
Kind'' can't miss.
</P>
<P>
   If only the same could be said of ``Brother's Keeper'' (8:30
p.m. CDT, ABC). Porter (William Ragsdale) and his 8-year-old son,
Oscar (Justin Cooper), are living life blissfully when Porter's
brother, Bobby (Sean O'Bryan), arrives. He's a rich football player
who gets in trouble and must live with his brother or end his
career. (Yeah, right.)
</P>
<P>
   Since Porter is uptight and Bobby is loose, the culture-clash
jokes fly. Too bad none are all that funny.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
