<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONUMENT-FILM-REVIEW-     09-24 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONUMENT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONUMENT AVE.': GRITTY PALS WHO PREFER CAR THEFTS TO A JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of pals in Charlestown, a dingy Irish-American enclave
of Boston, are sitting around one night smoking cigarettes, downing
beers, sniffing cocaine and shooting the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, their rough-and-tumble conversation turns to movie
star breasts (real ones versus silicone), the Hollywood brat pack
(this is the mid-1980s) and the physical attributes of celebrity
dream girls. When the macho banter hits a lull, one of the friends
wearily allows that even if they were the last men on earth, their
fantasy lovers still wouldn't give them the time of day.
</P>
<P>
   The aimless, sullen bull session is one of many scenes in
``Monument Ave.'' that capture embattled, despairing camaraderie
with a force and naturalness that match anything you'll find in a
film by Martin Scorsese or Quentin Tarantino.
</P>
<P>
   So powerfully does the movie evoke the characters' mixture of
working-class desperation, defensive ethnic pride and love-hate
feelings toward their ingrown community that you begin to feel
trapped in this drab claustrophobic world from which booze and
drugs offer the only respite from a lurking hopelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monument Ave.,'' which stars Denis Leary, in what may be the
role of his lifetime, is really a portrait of a proud but unhappy
community struggling to hold on. It is a world whose characters all
seem related to one another by blood and who maintain close family
ties abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The friends killing time together belong to a loosely-knit ring
of petty criminals who support themselves through organized car
theft.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps them in business is their fierce mutual loyalty and a
rigid code of silence whenever the law sticks its nose into their
business. The group's vague half-hearted justification for its
crimes is a Robin Hood attitude toward the much-despised
neighboring yuppies on whom they prey.
</P>
<P>
   But even more threatening than yuppies are blacks. In the film's
most hair-raising scene, the group, while driving around one night
in a friend's taxicab, spots a young black man on the sidewalk.
Leary's character, Bobby, who is already in an amphetamine-fueled
rage, insists they stop and drag the stranger into the car, where
he is terrorized with racial slurs and death threats before being
set free.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is as ugly and believable as any episode of racist
thuggery to be found in a recent film, and it insures that we not
view Bobby as the movie's nominal hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monument Ave.'' has a plot of sorts. One evening while the
group is sitting around in a neighborhood bar, an old pal named
Teddy (Billy Crudup), who has just been released from prison and is
already jittery from cocaine, shows up unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   There is lingering bad blood between Teddy and the group's
paranoid ringleader, Jackie (Colm Meaney). When Jackie suddenly
turns on Teddy and shoots him to death, the friends are horrified
but still maintain their code of silence when the police arriving
asking questions. (All claim to have been in the bathroom when the
shooting took place.)
</P>
<P>
   The story follows the escalating power struggle between Jackie
and Bobby, who is regarded as the leader's next in line.
Heightening the tension is the fact that Bobby is having a secret
affair with Jackie's girlfriend Katy (Famke Janssen), an alcoholic
coke-addicted wreck given to fits of violent jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby has also taken under his wing a cousin from overseas named
Seamus (Jason Barry) and acted as his mentor in petty crime.
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by Ted Demme from a screenplay by Mike
Armstrong, is remarkable for the skill with which it gets under the
skins of its largely unsympathetic characters and makes you care
about them despite their bigotry and criminal tendencies. The
dialogue and the ensemble acting maintain a near-perfect pitch.
</P>
<P>
   By interspersing snippets of old home movies and color snapshots
of the men when they were children, the movie suggests the depth of
the ties that have bound these friends since they were born, as
well as the tragic downward trajectory of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   How quickly those grinning little boys dressed as cowboys and
aiming guns into the camera turned into glum blue-collar desperados
packing real guns in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're unlucky to be stuck on these mean, shabby streets
for the rest of your life, is there an alternative to crime? Yes,
but it's not pretty. As Jackie warns Bobby, if he were banished
from the group he'd end up like his now-deceased father working at
a dead-end job in a wire foundry. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONUMENT AVE.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ted Demme; written by Mike Armstrong; director of
photography, Adam Kimmel; edited by Jeffrey Wolf; music by Amanda
Scheer-Demme; production designer, Ruth Ammon; produced by Joel
Stillerman, Demme, Jim Serpico, Nicolas Clermont and Elie Samaha;
released by Lions Gate Films. Running time: 90 minutes. This film
is not rated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jason Barry (Seamus), Billy Crudup (Teddy), John Diehl
(Digger), Greg Dulli (Shang), Noah Emmerich (Red), Ian Hart
(Mouse), Famke Janssen (Katy), Denis Leary (Bobby), Colm Meaney
(Jackie O'Hara), Martin Sheen (Hanlon) and Jeanne Tripplehorn
(Annie). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-IMPEACH-$ADV2     09-24 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-IMPEACH-$ADV27-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT KIND OF JUDICIARY COMMITTEE IS THIS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My fellow Americans: This isn't going to work, this presidential
impeachment business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it way too cumbersome, but _ worse _ it requires the
services of other human beings, and almost all of them bring to the
process far too much baggage to ignore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a quick look at the House Judiciary Committee reveals a
panoply of oddness so compelling that the American people have
every right to be suspect of this collection of folk. After all,
they look a lot like the American people themselves, and name me a
stranger lot than us. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For starters, many of the Judiciary Committee members are
lawyers. And if that isn't scary enough, one of them was married to
the late Sonny Bono. And if that doesn't give you pause, six of
them are from California. (Why, it makes me quake.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But here's a real killer: One of the members of the Judiciary
Committee was born and reared in Milwaukee. Don't they drink a lot
of beer in Milwaukee? Do you trust the future of this country to a
guy who represents a bunch of beer drinkers? (Well, yes, I do, too,
but I was just checking on what your own standards are.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My incomplete survey of a few of the individuals on the
Judiciary Committee will, I think, show you why _ even if you think
the president should be impeached _ this may not be the right
collection of folks to move that process forward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And let's not even include the chairman, Henry Hyde, who
recently acknowledged that he, too, had an extramarital affair some
years ago. The most telling fact to me about Hyde is that he
represents, among other Chicago suburbs, Park Ridge, where Hillary
Rodham Clinton grew up. So there you have it. What do we have? you
ask. Well, I don't know exactly, but I'm sure we have something.
And, anyway, as I said, I won't even include Hyde in this rundown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But consider Bill McCollum, a Republican who represents the
Orlando area. Do you know what that means? It means McCollum is
Mickey Mouse's congressman. Friends, surely we can do better than
that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or think of the ranking Democrat on the committee, John Conyers.
He's been around Congress since LBJ mercilessly whipped up on Barry
Goldwater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conyers, who represents part of Detroit, served on the Judiciary
Committee through the Watergate scandal. Now consider this: Detroit
has one of the worst baseball teams in the American League. And you
want a man who represents a bunch of losers like that helping to
make crucial decisions about the future of the presidency? Come
on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's another committee problem: Elton Gallegly. He represents
the Simi Valley in California. Yes, THAT Simi Valley, where Ronald
Reagan's presidential library is located and where several years
ago a jury acquitted the police officers charged in the Rodney King
beating case _ an acquittal that sparked rioting in Los Angeles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you want a guy from a district like that passing judgment
on the libidinous leader of the Free World, but I don't. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another guy from a district with an inappropriate past is Bill
Jenkins, who represents part of Tennessee that was home to Andrew
Johnson, the only president ever impeached. (Though the Senate, by
one vote, failed to convict him.) How can anyone from Johnson's
district think about impeachment clearly? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, it just goes on and on. There's even a fellow on the
committee from New Jersey, of all places, Steven Rothman, who makes
the ridiculous argument that he's ``not going to make my decision
about whether to impeach the president from newspaper accounts.''
Why not? The rest of us do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for release Sunday, Sept. 27.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
