<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RONIN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     09-24 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RONIN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RONIN': REAL TOUGH GUYS, REAL DERRING-DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A crew of tough customers assembles at the start of John
Frankenheimer's top-notch thriller, ``Ronin.'' Each of them is
seasoned and shrewd, but they've got nothing on the man behind the
camera when it comes to gritty professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   Directing like a world-weary Hitchcock with a taste for the
breathtaking car chase, Frankenheimer propels this tale of intrigue
through its tightly plotted paces with such conviction that he even
makes an action hero out of Robert De Niro. During this film's
moments of fiercest tension, I watched viewers at an early
screening quite literally biting their nails.
</P>
<P>
   Named for Japanese samurai shamed by the loss of their feudal
masters, ``Ronin'' presents a band of mercenaries who are assembled
for the mysterious mission of stealing a metal carrying case and
its unknown contents.
</P>
<P>
   The job is clearly deadly, since the case is desperately wanted
by Irish terrorists, scheming Russians and doubtless many others.
Working strictly for money, the mercenaries soon find themselves
gripped by deeper motives, not least of which is curiosity about
the tough-talking Irish beauty (Natascha McElhone) in charge of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Being genuinely worldly and unconventional, ``Ronin'' lifts a
knowing eyebrow at such provocative touches without becoming too
distracted from the job at hand.
</P>
<P>
   An extraordinary cast of actors, all on the same formidable
wavelength, match wits most impressively throughout the story.
Robert De Niro and Jean Reno form a camaraderie early in the story,
making this the most distinguished of buddy pictures, while
Jonathan Pryce and Stellan Skarsgaard give the story's maneuverings
a few more sinister shadings.
</P>
<P>
   With Sean Bean and Skipp Sudduth as two more of the hard cases
recruited for service, the early part of ``Ronin'' offers many
interesting opportunities for testing mettle. (One man's reflexes
in catching a coffee cup can be another man's key to his
character.) While carefully sizing up one another, the principals
sustain their cagey detachment in ways that give the film a
genuinely European flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer borrowed loosely from ``The Battle of Algiers'' in
creating a hard-edged, credible look that heightens mood without
overwhelming the action.
</P>
<P>
   That action is overwhelming in its own right, especially when
these gentlemen start their engines. Proving that the greatest
excitement an action film can offer is the spectacle of real
derring-do performed by real people, Frankenheimer stages three
sensational French chase sequences in settings that prove
astonishing, under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Whether screeching through the narrow, twisting streets of
Nice's picturesque old district or (later) cutting a furious swath
through Paris at high speed (and against traffic, even in tunnels),
these scenes are nothing short of sensational. Frankenheimer
directs them in fast, efficient, no-frills fashion because no extra
frills are needed.
</P>
<P>
   With a cast that also features the commandingly dour French
actor Michael Lonsdale as a doctor with a fascination for samurai,
``Ronin'' can be watched as appreciatively for its hard-boiled
performances as for its visceral excitement.
</P>
<P>
   As Reno grows ever more comfortable and emblematic in American
action films, De Niro shows off a brooding, hard-guy panache with
its own brand of international appeal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronin'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It includes starkly ruthless gunplay and a grisly
scene showing surgical extraction of a bullet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RONIN
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Frankenheimer; written by J.D. Zeik and Richard
Weisz, based on a story by Zeik; director of photography, Robert
Fraisse; edited by Tony Gibbs; music by Elia Cmiral; production
designer, Michael Z. Hanan; produced by Frank Mancuso, Jr.;
released by Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. Running time: 121 minutes. This
film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Robert De Niro (Sam), Jean Reno (Vincent), Natascha
McElhone (Deirdre), Stellan Skarsgard (Gregor), Sean Bean (Spence),
Skipp Sudduth (Larry), Michael Lonsdale (Jean-Pierre) and Jonathan
Pryce (Seamus). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
