<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2576 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOUNT-KATAHDIN-HNS &LR;      09-24 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNT-KATAHDIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONQUERING THE SUMMIT OF A BAXTER STATE BEAUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED STETSON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT KATAHDIN, Maine _ A soft, summit breeze nudges my face. In
the bright, midday sun, Millinocket and Moosehead lakes are distant
patches of blue amid an ocean of evergreens.
</P>
<P>
   A raven glides by, riding updrafts high over the great basins
below. My stomach turns as I look down into the deep, deep gray and
lichen-green rock amphitheaters. My pulse quickens at the thought
of balancing across the Knife Edge. This sharp ridge extends about
a mile from Pamola to Baxter peaks. In places, it narrows to two or
three feet. A misstep here means a fall of 1,000 feet _ or more.
</P>
<P>
   Indians called this Katahdin, the ``highest mountain.'' Today,
the mountain spirits _ one, a nasty creature with a terrible beak
and claws; another, a gigantic human form with stony eyebrows and
cheekbones _ are quiet. These mythical creatures do not throw
storms of rain, snow or sleet. They do not shroud the mountain with
chilling fog or blinding clouds. And they do not wrap the high
peaks in a killer hurricane. Instead, this day, Katahdin is but a
whisper. Katahdin is as calm as the two black ravens pecking about
on nearby slopes.
</P>
<P>
   On days like these, a hiker on the Knife Edge can talk downslope
with another some 2,000 feet below.
</P>
<P>
   Since early times, artists and writers have sought to capture
the mystique of this great mass. Unlike Native Americans who
respected the mountain spirits and stayed away, 19th-century white
men set foot on Katahdin, then encouraged other adventurers to join
them. As one historian wrote, Henry David Thoreau, who attempted an
ascent on Katahdin, ``...stood at the gateway of the woods and
opened them to all future comers with the key of poetic insight.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding were noted American landscape artists such as
Frederic Edwin Church and Lockwood deForest. In a 1944 Appalachia
magazine article, U.S. Navy Cmdr. Myron H. Avery of Lubuc, Maine,
eloquently described Katahdin's appeal: ``The wildness, the
ruggedness of the area, the unbroken forest expanse, the complete
absence of human invasion, and that which still fascinates today _
the varying aspects of sheer-walled cirques with the play of light
and shadow from the moon, the rising and setting sun. ...''
</P>
<P>
   From the south, Katahdin rises abruptly from the forest floor. A
series of connected peaks, the highest Baxter Peak at 5,267 feet,
form the mountain. Loose rocks cover the summit and look, as
Thoreau said, ``as if some time it had rained rocks.'' From another
perspective, a few miles to the east, the mountain resembles a
great pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Percival Baxter hiked Katahdin in the 1920s and vowed to
preserve this piece of wilderness. He tried, without success, to
convince the Maine Legislature to purchase the mountain peaks and
nearby terrain. So, from 1931 to 1962, he bought the land himself
and gave it to the state piece by piece, eventually totaling
201,018 acres. This is a massive 134-square-mile hunk of
northern-central Maine. Not only does Baxter State Park embrace
Katahdin with its alpine flora and unusual geology, but it also
encompasses more than a dozen peaks above 3,000 feet, some 175
miles of trails and acres of ponds, lakes and bogs.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of his gift, Baxter asked that the area ``shall
forever be left in its natural wild state, forever be kept as a
sanctuary for wild beasts and birds and forever be used for public
forest, public park and public recreational purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening before hiking Katahdin, I stayed at the Sweet
Lillian, a bed-and-breakfast in Millinocket. After a night of
tossing and turning (my bedroom window was less than 75 feet from a
state highway), I walked downstairs and joined other guests for a
hearty breakfast of pancakes, eggs, coffee and orange juice. The
Appalachian Mountain Club's ``Maine Mountain Guide'' described the
Abol Trail up a rock slide as ``dangerous.'' The AMC guide called
the 5.2-mile Hunt Trail ``steep and rough.''
</P>
<P>
   I preferred ``steep and rough.'' And, by 7:30 a.m., I was in my
car, headed north up the park road for the start of the Hunt Trail.
Four others joined me, including a father and son from Georgia who
planned to hike Katahdin, then walk south on the 2,000-mile
Appalachian Trail to their home state.
</P>
<P>
   After a 45-minute drive, we arrived at the Katahdin Stream
Campground, a beautiful, peaceful spot. The stream fed down into a
dark, calm pool, which was about 100 feet across and surrounded by
wooded campsites. Katahdin's southwest ridge rose up in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   The final northernmost section of the Appalachian Trail, the
Hunt Trail climbs gently for about a mile, then reaches Katahdin
Stream Falls. Here, water spills over four or five stages, each
about 25 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the trail steepens and passes through spruce trees. Coming
above the treeline, I faced a hump or ridge of boulders strewn down
the trail. Some boulders were so big I could not see over them.
They formed the crest of Katahdin's southwest shoulder. Dashes of
white paint marked the trail, which I followed closely. Deviations
of a few feet often led to dead-ends or blind alleys. In a couple
of places, boulders were so large that metal hand holds pounded
into the rocks were needed to continue an ascent.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, I began to breathe heavily. I even wondered if this
climb were possible for a slightly out-of-shape 53-year-old. But,
in a few minutes, voices came down the trail, and a hiker paused
for a welcome chat. The worst was behind me, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Continuing along, I noticed a curious sight: rows of trees
laying on their sides, trunks exposed. From afar, they looked like
long, wavy rows of aligned porcupine quills. Later, I learned these
are ``fir waves,'' unusual growth patterns of balsam fir. Once
through the boulders, I walked over a sandy, level shelf and
completed one more half-mile-long, steep spine.
</P>
<P>
   Then I started across the broad, flat Tablelands. Here, the
trail crosses solid, serrated and loose granite, tinged by lichen
to a greenish hue. After another half-mile-long incline, the trail
reaches Thoreau's Spring. A few inches deep and small enough to
leap over on this day, the spring sits clear and still where the
Hunt and Abol trails intersect. During drier months, the spring may
disappear. From here, the Hunt Trail curves northeast, rising
gently to Baxter Peak and passing alpine flowers and sedge grasses.
</P>
<P>
   Though only a mile from Thoreau Spring to Baxter Peak, the
summit seems elusive. The more you hike, the more the final goal
appears out of reach. The trail continues northeast, past the
flanks of the aptly named Tablelands. Finally, I reached the summit
and looked over the great, rocky basins.
</P>
<P>
   To the south was Millinocket Lake, a vast pool dotted with green
islands and ringed with an irregular shoreline of bays and coves.
White smoke billowed from the Great Northern Paper Co. plant.
</P>
<P>
   Today, I would not attempt to cross the Knife Edge. A few years
ago, I struggled over a similar ridge in Hawaii. I came away somber
and chastened. On the descent, the biggest worry was finding steps
over the boulders. How inconsequential. How trivial compared to the
struggles of those who confront dangerous weather.
</P>
<P>
   Upon reaching an inviting, flat granite slab, I lay down, sucked
the last drops of water from a plastic jug, and finished off my
carrots and a few handfuls of gorp. When I stood up, my legs felt
loose and rubbery _ as loose and rubbery as a puppet's. Once back
at my car, after nearly 10 hours of hiking, I flopped into the
front seat, drove out of the park and returned to The Sweet Lillian
bed-and-breakfast in Millinocket.
</P>
<P>
   Though I had no reservation, the owner welcomed me, found a room
(away from highway traffic) and offered a glass of red wine. I took
a long shower, ate a slow, relaxing meal at a nearby restaurant,
then went straight to bed. I fell into a deep sleep, as writer
Christine Jerome once said, as if I'd been ``poleaxed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
