 &UR; By LAURA MANSNERUS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Countless small-business owners have forged ahead
optimistically, ignoring the fact that they should have gotten
legal and accounting guidance before entertaining customers.
Lawyers are usually not a happy part of the plan for a new
business. Neither are accountants, investment advisers or other
professionals whose job it is to protect a business from the things
entrepreneurs would rather not think about. Laura Mansnerus, a
staff writer for The New York Times, explains why the suits should
be consulted before the grand opening.
</P>
