<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PECKER-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PECKER': HMM, IS IT BECAUSE HE EATS LIKE A BIRD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding hilarity in John Waters' latest movie title is the basic
prerequisite for enjoying the goofy ingenuity of his new film.
Remember that Waters proudly establishes himself as perhaps the
first filmmaker to accompany his directorial credit with a shot of
rats mating, and you'll be nicely attuned to ``Pecker'' and its
ebulliently trashy fun.
</P>
<P>
   As the title character, allegedly nicknamed Pecker because he
eats like a bird, Edward Furlong plays the happy, innocent
shutterbug at the center of this giddy satire. Pecker takes
pictures just because he loves to, and because, like Waters, he
thinks art is anywhere and everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The film watches what happens when Pecker's photographs of his
inner-city Baltimore neighborhood somehow catch the fancy of
Manhattan's art establishment (where Lili Taylor sums up the local
attitude by telling Pecker that she loves his look). ``Flavor of
Month Causes Tizzy in Art World'' reads the newspaper headline that
nicely summarizes this plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they call art up in New York, young man, looks like just
plain misery to me,'' says one stalwart in Baltimore (a city so
deeply revered here that Christina Ricci, as Pecker's girlfriend,
kisses the pavement at the Baltimore bus station after returning
from a trip to Manhattan). The film finds its share of amusement in
that attitude, too.
</P>
<P>
   The film watches as Pecker's pictures of his loved ones _
including the raucously funny Martha Plimpton as his sister, who
works in a gay bar where she calls everyone Mary, and the
grandmother (Jean Schertler) whose own Mary is a religious statue
she treats like a ventriloquist's dummy _ become famous as
``Pecker's delicious photographs of his culturally challenged
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ricci, whose character runs a laundromat and who takes to
Waters' lowlife milieu with the perfect, faux-naove ease, is
shocked to read that ``some paper named the Village Voice called me
a stain goddess!''
</P>
<P>
   When the fallout gets worse than that and Pecker's artistic
freedom starts to evaporate, the film shows hints of seriousness
without jeopardizing its jokey tone. In fact, Waters himself is the
best evidence that it's possible to wow the pretentious without
sacrificing a Pecker-like aesthetic at all.
</P>
<P>
   Drifting mischievously through ``Pecker'' are Mary Kay Place as
Pecker's mother, who runs a thrift shop and advises a homeless
couple not to be afraid of fashion; Lauren Hulsey as a little
Baltimore girl who has an eating disorder and is terrified by
fashionable vegetables in New York City; Brendan Sexton III,
Pecker's best friend, who's made his own art form out of
shoplifting; Cindy Sherman as herself, and Patricia Hearst as the
Warholian epitome of tacky New York glamor.
</P>
<P>
   Raunchy gay bar scenes contrast with the film's homey kitsch in
Baltimore and ratchet up its culture clash quotient an extra
notch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pecker'' is rated R. It includes nudity, strip bar scenes and
as many sneaky double-entendres as Waters can come up with. He can
come up with a lot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PECKER
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by John Waters; director of photography,
Robert Stevens; edited by Janice Hampton; production designer,
Vincent Peranio; produced by John Fiedler and Mark Tarlov; released
by Fine Line Features. Running time: 87 minutes. This film is rated
R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Edward Furlong (Pecker), Christina Ricci (Shelly), Martha
Plimpton (Tina), Brendan Sexton III (Matt), Lauren Hulsey (Little
Chrissy), Mary Kay Place (Joyce) and Lili Taylor (Rorey Wheeler).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
