<SLUG> BC-FILM-URBANLEGEND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`URBAN LEGEND' AUDIENCE WILL HEAR ECHOES OF `SCREAM'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to tell who's dumber at Pendleton College: the
students, who frequently walk alone even though a homicidal maniac
is on the loose; or the faculty, who won't believe that there's a
homicidal maniac on the loose despite overwhelming evidence and the
school's troubled past.
</P>
<P>
   The dumbness is part of ``Urban Legend's'' appeal. Watching this
movie, you can't help but feel intellectually superior to its
characters. It's the type of movie you enjoy not because it's fun,
but because you can make fun of it. But although the characters and
the script are pretty stupid, the movie isn't as dumb as it looks.
Sure, you might enjoy mocking it, but you'll spend YOUR money to
get in _ money that will wind up in the filmmakers' pockets. A lot
of money, judging from the success of ``Scream'' and ``I Know What
You Did Last Summer,'' the obvious inspirations for this movie.
</P>
<P>
   It's a neat trick: Making you feel smart while insulting your
intelligence, playing to the lowest common denominator and copying
what has already worked. You know what screenwriter Silvio Horta
did last summer (well, last fall): He saw a hit slasher movie,
screamed ``I can do that!,'' and by Halloween, he had a deal on his
hands. Then 26-year-old director Jamie Blanks hopped on the terror
train, raided teen-oriented TV shows for his cast, threw in a
couple of veterans like Robert Englund and John Neville, and added
some self-referential in-jokes (a couple of which are admittedly
very funny) to the script.
</P>
<P>
   It's as assembly-line as the plot, in which the one smart,
virginal student (Alicia Witt, as if four years on ``Cybill''
wasn't punishment enough) starts seeing her friends die in ways
straight out of urban legends. Because half of Horta's work was
done for him, all he had to do was come up with some linking scenes
to chain the killings together. Not to spoil anything, but these
include a bit about scratching on a car roof and another about a
dog in a microwave. Apparently, the killer has a thing against
anyone who has sex, fresh skin or a Stabbing Westward CD on the
boom box.
</P>
<P>
   The attractive young cast _ Jared Leto, Rebecca Gayheart,
``Dawson's Creek's'' Joshua Jackson _ is ... well, attractive and
young, giving mostly by-the-numbers performances. Although when the
killer is revealed, that particular cast member's acting switches
to an over-the-top style that has to be seen to be believed. It's
so enjoyably bad that it has to be intentional, a deliberate
attempt to get laughs by looking ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is just absurd enough to be entertaining _ although
its eyes-on-the-box-office cynicism is more disturbing than its
slasher-film content. It's hard to imagine the movie getting much
praise, even if you cut its youthful writer, director and cast a
lot of slack. Those bad reviews will have them licking their wounds
_ all the way to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Urban Legend''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jamie Blanks
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Alicia Witt, Jared Leto, Rebecca Gayheart
</P>
<P>
   Length: 99 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ graphic violence, sexual content and strong language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
