<HEADER>
A2604 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-KIDS-$ADV28-K     09-24 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-KIDS-$ADV28-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A COLUMN COMPLETELY SAFE FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents, you need not worry even a little about diverting any
young person's eyes from this column. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike nearly every other column in every paper in the country
in the last few weeks, this one will make no mention of oral sex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nor will you find a word here about that disgusting Oval Office
cigar incident that would require you to dream up some lame
explanation to tell your curious kids about what in the world was
going on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there won't be a single word printed here having to do with
when sex is really sex and when, by contrast, it's simply
inappropriate intimate contact, whether engaged in by a president
and an intern or by anyone else in the whole wide world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This being a safe-lex column, it will contain no ponderous
discussion at all about marital infidelity or sexual addiction, two
topics that have filled nearly every time slot on radio and TV in
recent weeks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nor will I offer you a detailed and disgusting history of
presidential prevarication _ starting with that ridiculous story
about George Washington allegedly confessing a cherry tree
massacre, passing on to Lyndon Johnson's many fibs about Vietnam,
plowing through Richard Nixon's non-denial denials in Watergate and
winding up with Bill Clinton looking us in the eye and denying he
had sexual relations with ``that woman.'' None of that. Not a
whisper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And sex and lies aren't the only icky topics I will avoid just
so you may feel free to let your kids read my words today, if you
want. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, sex and lies are the biggies I'm avoiding, but I am
determined to child-proof this entire column by skipping any
discussion of several other frightening topics that would require
you to answer your kids' embarrassing questions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So today _ and maybe today only _ you will find nothing in here
about international terrorism. No pipe bombs, no sarin nerve gas,
no biological weapons of any kind that keep you and your children
up at nights worrying. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You will find no full passenger airplanes exploding in this
column, either because of terrorists or from simple, if mysterious,
mechanical failure. Beyond that, no graphic words will paint
pictures here of deadly car crashes on our interstate highways,
killing more of the thousands of people we knock off in that way
each year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And here's something for which to be profoundly grateful: This
column will contain not a peep about the appalling level of
substance abuse in this country. You will find no mention here of
marijuana or crack, no word about underage drinking or the carnage
that adult alcohol consumption causes in our culture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying by my silence that those and other issues aren't
worthy of attention. Rather, I'm saying that you will not need to
worry about finding those difficult topics discussed here in this
column, which I've made safe for the tender eyes of the younger
generation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White-collar crime, too, will go uncommented upon here today.
There is no reason to give youngsters ideas about using their
computers to rip off corporations and individuals or using their
higher math skills to defraud employers by clever use of numbers on
expense reports and such. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And while we're avoiding things, this column also will skip past
environmental disaster, divorce and the breakdown of family life,
the failures of our educational system, corporate welfare and
illegal insider trading. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's because today this squeaky clean column will be about
nothing that's in the news. Have a nice day. And give my best to
your precious kids. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for release Monday, Sept. 28.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
