 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, Sept. 25. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-NUKE (United Nations) _ India joined Pakistan on Thursday
in announcing that it was prepared to sign the international treaty
banning nuclear testing within the next year, but said it was still
discussing details with Washington. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-BRITAIN-RUSHDIE (United Nations) _ The Iranian foreign
minister publicly divorced his government Thursday from the death
threat imposed on the British author Salman Rushdie in 1989 by
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, and Britain responded by restoring
full diplomatic relations. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Vilamoura, Portugal) _ NATO asked its military
commanders Thursday to take the next step to prepare for air
strikes against Yugoslavia if it does not stop attacks on ethnic
Albanian civilians in the Serbian province of Kosovo. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLL (Undated) _ President Clinton's standing with
Americans has rebounded broadly in the days since the release of
his video-taped testimony before a grand jury, and, in fact, people
are so exasperated with the Lewinsky scandal that there are
stirrings of a backlash against the Republican-controlled Congress
as it presses forward with an impeachment inquiry, the latest New
York Times/CBS News Poll shows. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Seeking to repair political
missteps, Rep. Henry Hyde said Thursday it was he, not Speaker Newt
Gingrich, who would preside over impeachment deliberations, and
Hyde denied that Republicans were seeking to broaden the inquiry
beyond the Lewinsky matter. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-POVERTY _ The proportion of Americans living in poverty
declined last year, mostly because of reductions in poverty among
black and Hispanic families, the Census Bureau reported Thursday.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
