<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2619 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUILDING-WASTE0927-CO     09-24 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILDING-WASTE0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILLION-DOLLAR BUILDING PROJECT ALMOST HUNG UP ON $250 SHOWER
CURTAIN
 &HT;    FOR RELEASE SATURDAY, SEPT. 26
 &HT;    A PHOTO HAS BEEN PLACED ON THE NATIONAL FOLDER ON THE COX SERVER
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ But for a $250 shower curtain, the $1.3 billion
federal building project might have slid quietly toward a contract
award.
</P>
<P>
   That unexpected bump in the road came as a major annoyance for
Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who for years has been shepherding plans
for the new U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, proposed for his
state. Then citizens watchdog groups discovered the offending
shower curtain among hundreds of other extravagant items on a list
of $64 million in furnishings for the complex.
</P>
<P>
   The National Taxpayers Union, a 300,000-member organization,
took up a crusade on radio talk shows, and ABC-TV ran a news spot
earlier this month lampooning the project.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is unclear whether such criticism will force a
re-evaluation of the project, it spurred Warner to call a Senate
subcommittee hearing on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This went on the airwaves of America and it made us look like
fools,'' the senator said, glowering at a panel of consultants and
officials and demanding to know how a shower curtain could cost
$250. The grilling was held late in the afternoon, when news
coverage is usually unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel R. Collins, an accountant whose firm of Deva &AMP; Associates
had produced the furnishings list for the Patent office project,
tried haltingly to explain. ``The shower curtain is not a shower
curtain,'' he said, but an entire assembly of hardware for the
shower curtains for a planned fitness center. The $1,000 ``coat
rack'' was actually a coat closet, he said, and an item listed as
-- $309 ``ash urn'' included a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Patents and Trademarks Commissioner Bruce A. Lehman, who
reminded the senators that his agency is solely supported by the
fees that it charges, told Warner: ``I'm just going to swear to you
right now that we are not going to spend that kind of money for
those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Such explanations did little to satisfy skeptics, who have
dubbed the project the ``Taj Mahal'' and warned that it could
become the next major sinkhole for federal dollars, after the
costly new Ronald Reagan Office Building. The Reagan building,
first proposed to cost under $400 million, came in earlier this
year at $800 million. But that structure is at least owned by the
federal government. The 2.4 million-square-foot Patent headquarters
would cost almost twice as much for slightly less office space over
20 years. And it would be leased, not owned.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, supporters cite Deva &AMP; Associates findings to argue
that a new consolidated complex would save $72 million over the
costs of remaining in 18 older buildings scattered in Arlington,
Va., across the Potomac River from the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents fired back at Wednesday's hearing with a new private
study by the Arthur Andersen consulting firm projecting that,
rather than a saving money, the move would increase costs by $47.7
million. The review was ordered by Charles E. Smith Companies, the
current landlord, which is fighting to keep the Patent and
Trademark Office (PTO) in its buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The new study concluded that government estimates had not
anticipated cost overruns or delays that occur with most federal
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least, the Andersen study means more analysis is
necessary,'' said National Taxpayers Union official
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sepp in an interview. ``If this much money is at stake,
what's the harm in taking a few more months to see if the option
PTO wants to pursue is the best one?''
</P>
<P>
   Sepp told Warner's hearing that Congress should consider whether
it would be more cost effective to renovate the buildings now under
lease.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they expect a signed
contract by year's end under a lease plan that sets the rent at
$1.3 billion over 20 years, plus $135 million for relocating the
agency, which is scheduled to have 7,100 workers by the time the
building is constructed early in the next century. Supporters said
those ceilings were firm.
</P>
<P>
   However, at the hearing, Robert A. Peck, public buildings
commissioner for the General Services Administration was asked by
Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., ``Will you come back and ask for
more?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never say never,'' Peck said.
</P>
<P>
   Sepp said he plans to keep up his campaign against the project.
``I'm going to keep hammering on the air about this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
