<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKIN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SKIN AND BONE': HUSTLERS WITH CHICKENS? WAIT, THERE'S FANTASY,
TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ghislaine sounds pretty casual when she calls a client to say,
``I'm going to have to cancel your afternoon beating.'' The same is
true when she explains to someone else that a client used a
branding iron on poor Robby, and when she reports, ``One of my
chickens got kidnapped or something.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Skin and Bone,'' Ghislaine (Nicole Dillenberg), a brunette
with harsh makeup and an omnipresent car phone, runs a male
prostitution service in Los Angeles, specializing in fantasy
encounters. She seems to be a symbol for the hard-hearted city and
the show biz industry that keeps it alive.
</P>
<P>
   Everett Lewis, the writer and director of ``Skin and Bone,''
would probably say he was using the experiences of young male
hustlers, who are also, of course, would-be actors, to make a
statement about power, desire and self-delusion.
</P>
<P>
   But when this bleak, disjointed movie appears on the screen, it
often comes across as if it had been planned like a pornographic
feature: OK, this time let's make it a milkman and a lonely
housewife and we'll give them each three lines before they get down
to business. What other kind of thinking could produce the scene in
which Harry (B. Wyatt), the old pro, instructs Dean (Alan Boyce),
the new boy, in the proper use of a riding crop on a client?
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, many scenes require the male leads to be nearly
or completely naked.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis does one thing right, and he does it several times. He
effectively mixes us up as to what's real and what isn't. It's hard
to tell when a client-hustler interaction begins and ends, and
whether a particular scene, involving two men in police uniforms,
is a fantasy paid for by the hour, a television show being filmed
or a real-life crime.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the point. Real life has consequences, and the
question of whether the bullets _ literal or metaphorical _ are
real or blanks matters. Billy (Garrett Scullin), a young hustler
who gets his start posing for the 12 Months of Bondage calendar,
finds that out.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime moviegoers have seen the dehumanizing audition scene a
thousand times. The talented but unknown and unappreciated young
actor is asked, by a cavalier producer or casting director, to turn
around and to take off his shirt, and feels as if he's being
treated like a piece of meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skin and Bone'' has a scene like that, too, but it packs a
particular wallop because we've just seen the same character at
work as a hustler. And the audition is clearly 10 times as
demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   The film's strongest message is, in fact, a questioning of the
actor's trade. After a middle-aged customer changes his mind about
what he wants to do with the young hustler he has paid for, the
younger man shouts: ``I am not a whore! I'm an actor! I sell
fantasies!''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' point seems to be that it's all the same. What's the big
difference, he asks, between acting out the fantasies of one rich
old man or those of a few million ticket buyers? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SKIN AND BONE
</P>
<P>
   Written, edited and directed by Everett Lewis; director of
photography, Fernando Aruguelles; music by Geoff Haba and Mark Jan
Wlodarkiewicz, with songs by Pansy Division; produced by Claudia
Lewis and Gardner Monks; released by Jour de Fete Films. At the
Quad Cinema, 13th Street, west of Fifth Avenue, Greenwich Village.
Running time: 114 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: B. Wyatt (Harry), Alan Boyce (Dean), Susannah Melvoin
(Lovely Girl), Garret Scullin (Billy), Clark Brolly (Frankie) and
Chad Kula (Bruno).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
