<HEADER>
A2667 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXTRA-SEEK-ADVICE-FRO     09-24 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTRA-SEEK-ADVICE-FROM-THE-EXPERTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE SUITS CAN SAVE YOUR SHIRT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This is a special ``one-shot'' feature culled from
ENTREPRENEURS, a stand-alone news section from The New York Times,
which explores everything from the financial and management
challenges facing company owners and managers to reflections on the
culture of self-employment. For purchase information _ THE RATE IS
NOT PROHIBITIVE _ contact CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----------------ART FOR PURCHASE!-----------------
 &HT;     One color illustration showing small business owners hanging a
sign for their business, ``Hair Today,'' with the help of a team of
lawyers, accountants and investment advisers. Call White for more
information.  
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By LAURA MANSNERUS 
 c.1998 The New York Times Co.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Deborah L. Jacobs, lawyer-turned-writer, gave a heartfelt
compliment to the young man who arrived with his helper to clean
her house in Brooklyn recently: the name of his service was awfully
clever. But she wasn't going to leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you trademarked it?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   He had not, he told Jacobs, who happened to be the author of
``Legal Smarts for Small Business.'' And that answer worried her,
enough that she will not disclose the name of the young
entrepreneur's business until he has finished scurrying around to
obtain trademark protection.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a name that isn't trademarked can be used by someone
else unless the first person brings out expensive legal artillery
to stop the competition.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one example, Jacobs said, of how small-business
owners forge ahead optimistically, figuring that nothing can go
wrong, when they should part with a few hundred dollars, or a few
thousand depending on the legal task, for a lawyer who, by training
and temperament, can anticipate everything going wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far can an entrepreneur get without a lawyer?'' she said.
``Pretty far. But it can cost you a lot, a whole lot, later.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are usually not a happy part of the plan for a new
business. Neither are accountants, investment advisers or other
professionals whose job it is to protect a business from the things
entrepreneurs would rather not think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the typical entrepreneurial attitude,'' said Fred S.
Steingold, a lawyer in Ann Arbor, Mich., and the author of ``The
Legal Guide for Starting and Running a Small Business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to get along with their business, and they're not
detail-oriented,'' he said. ``They're impatient. That's what makes
them good entrepreneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tiny service businesses, of course, start and run fine
without professional advice; a dog walker or a window washer can
obtain a business license (and probably should in many cities, for
tax reasons), file a Schedule C and never pay for a consultation.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a retail or a professional business, Jacobs said, ``as a
sole proprietor you can absolutely hang out your shingle without
consulting a lawyer, although if you're operating out of your house
you might want to check the zoning rules.''
</P>
<P>
   But any other form of ownership _ partnership and any type of
corporation _ requires legal and probably accounting guidance.
</P>
<P>
   On the complexity scale, the simplest is a partnership, which
most experts say should begin with a written agreement spelling
out, for example, what happens if one owner dies or quits the
business. This is well-charted territory, especially since the
Uniform Partnership Act governs in almost all states, and by
following legal guides for the general public and form books that
contain standard agreements, most people can do the paperwork and
whatever modifications they want.
</P>
<P>
   But even Steingold, whose publisher, Nolo Press, produces
self-help books and software, suggests that a lawyer review an
agreement. He gives the same advice for forming a simple
corporation _ with the preliminary note that owners might want to
first ask a lawyer whether they need to incorporate.
</P>
<P>
   (The main advantage, ordinarily, is protection of the individual
owners from legal liabilities. There are tax advantages and
disadvantages, too, best sorted out by an accountant.)
</P>
<P>
   The paperwork _ state filing papers, articles of incorporation
and shareholder provisions _ is manageable for most people; Nolo
Press, among others, publishes general guides and versions specific
to several states, including New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   Having a lawyer review the documents is fairly painless: in
Steingold's case, about an hour of his time, or $175. For handling
the whole process, his flat fee in most cases is $600. (In big
cities, where costs are generally higher, charges can run as high
as $2,000.)
</P>
<P>
   As for buying a business, whatever you plan to do, Steingold
said, self-education and self-representation won't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need advice on whether to buy the assets or just the
corporate shell,'' he said. ``The typical purchase agreement is
pretty complicated. There are all kinds of decisions about how it's
going to be financed. Then there are 10 to 20 documents that show
up at a closing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people, he said, will come into a lawyer's office with a
proposed sales contract that originated with the seller or came
from a form book, ``but it would be difficult for somebody who
doesn't have any legal experience to go through a closing.''
</P>
<P>
   Do-it-yourself accounting is not recommended either, but
entrepreneurs can keep bills down by doing the prep work. Software
programs offer simplified bookkeeping tasks and enable people to
monitor cash-flow statements and projections.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone starting a business should be thoroughly immersed in
those numbers anyway, said Ginny Beauchamp, the vice president of
the National Association for the Self-Employed in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Beauchamp added, however small the business, ``having an
accountant do audits a couple times a year is a very good idea, and
if your business is growing by leaps and bounds, obviously you need
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the simplest sole proprietorships can do without
accountants for tax planning and preparation. Businesses can get in
trouble for failing to keep up with changes in tax law, as many did
several years ago when they failed to amend their Keough plans.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a quarter of small-business owners were delinquent in
filing new plans with the Internal Revenue Service, many because
they were unaware of the new requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said small-business owners, whether through
cost-consciousness or hopeful ignorance, make two mistakes in
circumventing lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   First, she said, they wave off legal advice until they are in
trouble. She mentioned the entrepreneur who spent hundreds of
thousands of dollars making a CD-ROM called ``The First Electronic
Jewish Bookshelf.'' His product brought a warning letter from
Microsoft, which was using the term ``bookshelf.'' At that point,
the entrepreneur had to get a lawyer and enter extremely expensive
settlement negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Second, she said, ``many attempt to play amateur lawyer.''
Jacobs recommends self-help books to pare legal costs and identify
business concerns. Nolo's, she advised, ``are very well researched
and well written and provide great background.'' Even after
practicing law for six years, she does not hesitate to hire others.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I need a specialized kind of legal help, I hire the best
expert I can,'' she said. ``I would no sooner be an amateur in the
legal field than I would be an amateur electrician and rewire my
house.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Laura Mansnerus is a staff writer for The New York Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
