imposing new taxes on the Internet has probably been caught up in
partisan wrangling over HMO reform. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA -- INTERNET. Sen. Bryan is pushing for legislation that
would restrict marketing practices on the Internet. An overview of
the bill and pros and cons. Preston
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- SMOG. The EPA today ordered Ohio and 21 other states to
curb smog-causing chemicals. Ohio is one of the hardest hit by the
national strategy, which EPA officials hope will cut the state's
output of smog-causing emissions 36 percent by 2007. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- OXLEY-INTERNET-PORN. The Commerce Committee sent a bill,
sponsored by Rep. Mike Oxley, R-Findlay, to the House today that
would prevent children from gaining access to Internet porn sites
by requiring commercial online pornographers to obtain proof of age
before granting users access to their sites. The bill has drawn
criticism from the ACLU and other free-speech advocates for
limiting the rights of adults to visit pornography sites. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- LIVESTOCK-WASTE. How would the proposed joint strategy
introduced last week by the USDA and EPA to manage livestock waste
differ from the regulations already in place in Ohio? Would it pose
a greater burden on livestock farmers? Would it effectively address
the waste problems threatening Ohio waterways? (Working.) Hurt
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA -- CENSUS. South Carolina's poverty rate fell by
more than 3 percent in the past two years, tying the Palmetto State
with Mississippi for the sharpest decline in poverty in the nation.
Williams
</P>
<P>
