<HEADLINE>
`FANTASY ISLAND': BREATHTAKING VIEWS, INSUFFICIENT WIT  
 `CUPID': A WISTFUL EXERCISE IN FANTASY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suppress that wish, buddy. You might have it hurled back into
your gut until you understand what an idiot you were to dream it in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bleak premise behind ``Fantasy Island,'' one of two
shows with vaguely supernatural themes that begin Saturday night on
ABC. ``Fantasy Island,'' of course, is a new version of the 1978-84
series, which cannot be recalled without involuntarily screeching
``De plane! De plane!'' in the manner of Herve Villechaize. Go
ahead. It cannot be helped.
</P>
<P>
   Some broad strokes of the original have been retained by the
producers, including Barry Sonnenfeld, who has made witty movies
like ``Men in Black'' and guided the ABC summer series ``Maximum
Bob.'' Here, each episode brings several travelers to an island
resort where the mysterious host, Mr. Roarke, promises to deliver
their hearts' desires.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of the suave Ricardo Montalban, dressed in white,
Mr. Roarke is now the brooding Malcolm McDowell, dressed in (you're
getting ahead of the story, aren't you?) black. He greets his
guests at the seaplane dock and tells them, ``You must never tell
anyone of your experiences on this island,'' because ``no one would
ever believe you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Roarke is assisted by the hulking Cal (Louis Lombardi) and
the delicate Harry (Edward Hibbert), who seem to be more prisoners
than staff members, and by the sleek Ariel (Madchen Amick), who
makes fantasies materialize by assuming the form of any person.
</P>
<P>
   The episode's visitors _ all young, attractive and as
interchangeable as light bulbs _ have arrived with selfish goals.
In the course of the hour, Mr. Roarke, who seems to know everything
and can change time and tide at will, grimly teaches them lessons
about life's true priorities. (Example of his wisdom: ``Death
doesn't hurt. It's life that hurts.'') So who is he? So who cares?
</P>
<P>
   The show, filmed in Hawaii, offers some breathtaking views of
vast open spaces. But it's the small open spaces in the concept,
where the wit should be, that knock ``Fantasy Island'' off the
itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   The most imaginative element of the show is confined to brief
opening and closing sequences, set in a rumpled travel agency
presided over by Fisher and Clia (Fyvush Finkel and Sylvia Sidney),
who greet startled strangers by name and trundle them off the
island. The real magic is in the sly glances of these veteran
character actors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   `Cupid,' ABC's other Saturday-night exercise in fantasy is much
more wistful, although it jumps off from the sad fact that romance
is in a sorry state these days. Cupid is falling down on the job.
This has not escaped attention on Mount Olympus, where the gods
have called Cupid on the carpet, stripped him of his magic powers
and banished him to earth until he unites 100 loving couples.
</P>
<P>
   Cupid (Jeremy Piven) lands in Chicago. Explaining his identity
and mission lands him in a mental hospital, where he meets Dr.
Claire Allen (Paula Marshall), a psychiatrist and advice author.
For him, life revolves around the heart. For her, it's the head. He
thinks she's wrong. She thinks he's crazy.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening episode, Cupid accepts a more conventional
mortal-type name, Trevor Hale, and is released from the hospital
with the proviso that his progress must be monitored by Claire. He
joins her therapy group for lonely singles, where she warns him not
to undermine her efforts. He retorts: ``And being the Roman god of
love for 3,000 years has prepared me for _ what? A desk job at
Hallmark?''
</P>
<P>
   Trevor also lands a bartender's job at an Irish pub. If he can't
make his 100 matches in those two settings, Cupid's in the wrong
line of work (not to mention his writers).
</P>
<P>
   Claire, too, is single, of course. Maybe there's a suppressed
romantic trapped within her cool, professional exterior. Could she
be smitten with this rumpled, balding guy who just wants everyone
to be in love?
</P>
<P>
   If you think with your heart and not your head, you might come
back to find out. Is it a date?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FANTASY ISLAND'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Saturdays on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Barry Sonnenfeld, Barry Josephson, Andrew Schneider and Diane
Frolov, executive producers. A production of Sonnenfeld Josephson
Worldwide Entertainment in association with Columbia Tri-Star
Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Malcolm McDowell (Mr. Roarke), Louis Lombardi (Cal),
Edward Hibbert (Harry), Madchen Amick (Ariel), Fyvush Finkel
(Fisher) and Sylvia Sidney (Clia).
</P>
<P>
   `CUPID'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. Saturdays on ABC
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
