<P>
   WOMEN'S SERIES, DAY SIX: SELLING OF FEMALE ATHLETES
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-REECE Gabriella Reece gained fame as a volleyball player
but is no longer in an organized league and isn't heard from much
because of her athletics. That doesn't seem to matter to her and
the markets, who plaster her all over magazine covers and in
commercials. She used sports as a vehicle to a modeling career.
While taking advantage of it, she bemoans the fact that her looks
are what got her here. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
PHOTO. ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-ENDORSEMENT-LIST _ List of endorsement money, top men and
women. ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-LPGA _ No women's sports entity is more closely associated
with lesbianism than the LPGA tour, and it has suffered because of
it. The organization, while not discouraging that aspect of the
tour, seems to be emphasizing the heterosexual side, which includes
day-care services for players. But they still welcome an
association with lesbian groups to one of their biggest events, the
Dinah Shore tournament. Since media focused on the tour after
homophobic remarks for a CBS announcer, the circuit has enjoyed
great growth. (Schultz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-PURSES-LIST - List of growth in purses. ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-LESLIE _ First person on Lisa Leslie on playing hoops with
guys. ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-HUMMER-COLUMN _ On Evander Holyfield. (Hummer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BASEBALL-CARDS _ Dan O'Kane isn't a collector or a
memorabilia dealer, just a Dayton salesman who happened to have two
Mark McGwire 1985 rookie cards lying around. Told such items were
selling for $350 in some cases, he placed a newspaper advertisement
offering each for the more reasonable price of $115, ``the true
book value,'' he says. After six days, he still has one left.
Maybe, despite reports to the contrary, the mania surrounding all
things McGwire and Sosa has reached its zenith. (McClelland, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES _ Braves-Mets advance with playoff impact. (Stinson,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK _ ATLANTA _ Inside the Braves' clubhouse.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-ONDECK _ ATLANTA _ A brief preview of tomorrow's
Braves game. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CANE-SPORTS _ Hurricane Georges forces postponement of
Marlins-Phillies game tonight; Calder race track closing Friday.
(Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GIBSON _ Negro leagues great Josh Gibson is credited by some
with hitting as many as 84 home runs in a year. But such a figure
is undocumented and would have included exhibition games against a
variety of opponents, including amateur teams. Gibson died in 1947
at age 35 because of a brain tumor. He was inducted into the Hall
of Fame in 1972. (Holcomb, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GIBSON-BIO _ Bio box.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS _ One of the Falcons' biggest concerns on Sunday
will be stopping Garrison Hearst, who is enjoying his day in the
sun with the San Francisco 49ers. Hearst, who played at Lincoln
County High and UGA, is another in a long line of Georgia backs who
are tearing up the NFL. (Pasquarelli, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-WEEKENDBEST _ Here's what to look for this weekend in NFL.
(Pasquarelli, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BENGALS _ Daily story on the Bengals. (Ludwig, Dayton Daily
News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-HAWKS _ Dikembe Mutombo, highly paid center for the Hawks,
has never forgotten his homeland. That's why he'll host a huge
benefit in Atlanta on Saturday in an effort to raise funds for a
hospital in Zaire. (Denberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-GATECH _ Georgia Tech football feature. The Jackets had one
of their worst rushing performances of last season against North
Carolina, rushing for 28 yards and committing two key turnovers. If
they hope to defeat the Tar Heels Saturday in Chapel Hill, an
improved running game will be one of the keys. (Rogers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-CLASSIC _ ATLANTA _ It's been an interesting college career
for Tennessee State receiver Tyrone Butterfield. Butterfield began
his career at the University of Michigan, but left Ann Arbor
searching for more playing time. Now in his second season at
Tennessee State, Butterfield has developed into one of the top
receivers in the Ohio Valley Conference and a legitimate pro
prospect. Butterfield will lead Tennessee State into Saturday's
Atlanta Football Classic against Florida A&AMP;M. (Reese, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-OSU-WOODARD _ Lonnie Woodard, a 6-2, 263-pound OSU
sophomore, smiles at his father's recollection of that devastating
day 14 months ago. It's much easier to smile now that the injury
which kept him sidelined all of last season is nearly healed and
he's back on the football field. He only wishes his father's
injuries could heal as quickly. Lonnie Sr. is severely paralyzed.
(Vinella, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-UCLA _ Feature on UCLA QB Cade McNown. (Milian, Palm Beach
Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-HUSKERS _ Cuero's Clint Finley, who is a backup safety with
Nebraska, is trying to make a comeback after missing the first
three games with an injury. Nebraska plays Washington Saturday.
(Riggs, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-DAVIS-CUP _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Haul out the flags and
practice the U-S-A chants. The Delray Beach Tennis Center was named
to host the loudest and most emotional event in professional
tennis: the Davis Cup final. It's the only time tennis fans can let
their passion override their manners. (Clarke/McGinness, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-TRES-DAVIS _ An introduction of Tres Davis and his family.
Tres is a 16-year-old phenom tennis player just moved to St.
Stephens. His father, Doug, is the new tennis coach. Younger
brother Brandon plays in 12s. Tres is on US teams of all sorts.
Spent May playing in Europe. Just got back from a world competition
in Italy. Plays this weekend in Dallas, next weekend in San
Antonio. (Klan, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
