<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANDLING KEEPS BUSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Garry Shandling finished the last season of his
television hit, ``The Larry Sanders Show,'' in high style. He was
not only co-writer of a finale that many critics described as
perhaps the best episode in the series (in contrast to the last
episodes of ``Seinfeld'' or ``Ellen''), but he also won his first
Emmy in the process. Even as he held the coveted award that
evening, he was being asked what would come next.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is an answer: movies.
</P>
<P>
   Shandling is filming ``Town and Country,'' which also stars
Warren Beatty, Diane Keaton and Goldie Hawn. (``I haven't asked,
but from my perspective, I'm the best-looking man in the movie,''
Shandling said.) He also plays a role in the forthcoming film
version of the play ``Hurlyburly,'' with Sean Penn, Chazz
Palminteri and Kevin Spacey.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more important, Columbia Tri-Star Pictures just
gave the green light to the first movie he has written, ``What
Planet Are You From?'' It is a comedy in which he expects to star.
</P>
<P>
   Shandling did not want to say much about the script, which he
said he had been developing for the last four years, except that it
involved an alien arriving on Earth to impregnate a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He discovers, of course, that it's more difficult than
expected, and he has to marry,'' Shandling said. ``He's not trained
for that, and all hell breaks loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Shandling said that he might eventually create more television
shows, but that he did not expect to star in them. ``In other
words, I would get someone better than me,'' he said. For now,
though, he said he was eager to explore a new medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really anxious to do a feature to see creatively what it
will be like to have a little more time to focus on the details,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   This has been an unusually productive time for Shandling. He
said that last week he finished the manuscript for a book, ``The
Larry Sanders Story: Confessions of a Late Night Talk Show Host,''
in which, among other things, he makes up fictional exploits with
real people, like an encounter with Cybill Shepherd, who made a
guest appearance on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped to take several months off after the show, but it
hasn't worked out,'' Shandling lamented.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said that he had been following the Clinton
scandals, and that, like many people, he was perplexed and
startled, but that it had made him think about the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``a really dumb person is someone who
goes to the White House and sees the president and says, `You know,
this office is not perfectly round.' And the president says, `It's
oval, which means something different.' But that's another
story.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a great deal of science to the art of moviemaking, and
one of the scientifically proven truths is that you never release a
potential blockbuster in September because people are busy with
school or the new television season, unless, of course, the movie
is what critics characterize as a formulaic action comedy from a
fledgling director.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone was surprised by the performance last
weekend of ``Rush Hour,'' which set records with a startling $33
million at the box office for its opening weekend. (Janet Maslin,
reviewing the movie in The New York Times, called it a ``lively but
routine action story.'')
</P>
<P>
   Never before has a film done so well in what is regarded as the
dead season of early fall, in between the high seasons of summer
and late fall and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is overwhelming,'' said Brett Ratner, the director of
``Rush Hour,'' which stars Jackie Chan and Chris Tucker and was
released by New Line Cinema. ``For myself, to be honest, I said
that I'll dance naked down Sunset Boulevard if this does $20
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the wonder of the success is the fact that Ratner is
just 28; this is his second movie.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Goldman, the president for marketing at New Line, a
Time Warner unit, said that he, too, was stunned by the figures,
but that for months the studio had worked hard to focus audiences
on the characters, not the story, and that was what seemed to have
made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in this movie you've seen before,'' Ratner
admitted. ``The way to make it work is the casting, and they really
did have great chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the degree of the success is the fact that the
movie cost roughly $35 million to make and now appears likely to
clear $100 million at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   For Ratner, who comes from a background of making music videos,
the results are both gratifying and liberating. He now has more
clout in Hollywood and thus the ability to make what he wants to
make.
</P>
<P>
   He said his next project was likely to be a remake of the
obscure 1976 movie ``The Killing of a Chinese Bookie,'' about
gangsters and lowlifes.
</P>
<P>
   For Ratner, who grew up in an affluent family in Miami Beach,
this is not just the fantasy of a young man with a dark
imagination. He said that as a youngster, he had met the gangster
Meyer Lansky. Ratner said he had often walked his dog with Lansky
on Tony Collins Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a Jewish kid from Miami Beach, but this stuff was
around me as a kid,'' he said. ``If I wasn't a filmmaker, I'd want
to be a gangster. Well, not really a gangster, but in the casino
business. That's what I knew as a kid.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everything about the movie ``American History X'' is serious,
from its subject, skinheads and racism, to its director, Humpty
Dumpty.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not really Humpty Dumpty, but it almost was. Yes,
something is amiss in this new movie, which is scheduled to be
released by New Line on Oct. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The movie stars Edward Norton and Edward Furlong and was
directed by the multimedia artist and powerful personality Tony
Kaye. Kaye, who is used to exerting a great deal of creative
control over his projects, from museum installations on the
homeless to television commercials for Volkswagen, Volvo and Nike,
was also the director of photography and camera operator on the
film, his first feature-length movie.
</P>
<P>
   But control has become the center of a dispute between Kaye and
New Line. Kaye produced an edited version of the film but then
asked to do further work reshaping it. New Line eventually lost
patience, saying it was going to release his last version, which
prompted Kaye to ask that his name be removed and the pseudonym
Alan Smithee be used.
</P>
<P>
   The Directors' Guild rejected that proposal, as well as Kaye's
next suggestion, that Humpty Dumpty be listed as the director. So,
against his wishes, he will be listed as the director.
</P>
<P>
   New Line is moving ahead and says it is proud of what it regards
as a powerful look at a difficult subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think what we're releasing represents Tony Kaye's
vision of the movie until he developed a whole new radical take on
what he wanted to do,'' said Michael DeLuca, the president of New
Line Productions.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye did not return repeated calls seeking comment, but he has
been quoted in news reports criticizing New Line, describing the
version to be released as a ``rape, a total abuse of creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie cost just $9.5 million, and DeLuca said it was never
expected to be a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we didn't make the movie to make a lot of money,'' he
said. ``Movies about race don't exactly burn up the box office. We
made this because it's important to talk about these things.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Norton plays a racist in Southern California who
goes to prison and emerges a changed man, seeking to redeem
himself. He clashes with his younger brother, Furlong, who is still
a member of a hate group. The film is filled with invective against
Jews, blacks, Koreans and other immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   For DeLuca, the experience has been an embarrassment, but not a
total surprise, given Kaye's reputation as an artist with a passion
for pursuing his vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the potential was there for these kinds of displays,''
DeLuca said. ``This was a first for me. Sure, I'd work with Kaye
again, if the conditions were right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
