<HEADER>
A2790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     09-24 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series currently playing in
theaters. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `THE AVENGERS,' starring Uma Thurman, Ralph Fiennes, Sean
Connery and Eileen Atkins. Directed by Jeremiah Chechik (PG, 100
minutes). Sometimes major movie studios should be afraid to screen
expensive fiascoes for the press, but they go ahead anyway. ``The
Avengers'' is Warner Brothers' would-be blockbuster that actually
had its light hidden beneath a bushel until opening day, and no
wonder. With pseudo-suave repartee that would make Austin Powers
blush and with so many shades of ``Howard the Duck'' that one scene
depicts man-size pastel teddy bears sitting around a conference
table, it's a film to gall fans of the old television series and
perplex anyone else. I can't remember another Friday morning show
where I heard actual cries of ``Ugh!'' on the way out the door
(Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `BLADE,' starring Wesley Snipes, Stephen Dorff, Traci Lords and
Kris Kristofferson. Directed by Stephen Norrington (R, 120
minutes). Vampires are plotting to take over the world, and the
only person who can save the planet is a vampiric half-human
superhero named Blade. So much fake blood drips, gushes, explodes
and congeals in this hyperkinetic science-fiction horror film
adapted from a popular comic book that there's barely a scene that
isn't drenched in red. Snipes' Blade is a low-rent Arnold
Schwarzenegger imitation dressed in a ludicrous mixture of black
leather and what look like car seat belts. There's lots of morphing
and Hong Kong action movie-style acrobatics. Dorff is the bratty
leader of the young vampire rebels. The visuals are garish, the
acting wretched (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `54,' starring Ryan Phillippe, Salma Hayek, Neve Campbell, Mike
Myers, Lauren Hutton and Michael York. Directed by Mark Christopher
(R, 89 minutes). Christopher's botched history of Studio 54, the
notorious late-'70s disco and celebrity hangout, should have been a
depraved Manhattan answer to ``Saturday Night Fever.'' Instead, it
is a juiceless mishmash that can't decide whether it's a nightclub
history, a comedy (Myers' crude ``Saturday Night Live''-style
caricature of Steve Rubell) or a contemporary variation on the
fable of the prodigal son. Phillippe, playing a 19-year-old Jersey
City nobody who ascends from busboy to star bartender at the club,
does throw off an occasional spark. But the movie is so afraid to
confront the character's self-promoting bisexuality that he never
really comes alive (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `FIRELIGHT,' starring Sophie Marceau and Stephen Dillane.
Written and directed by William Nicholson (R, 103 minutes). Stella
Dallas meets Jane Eyre in this high-toned Victorian-era
bodice-ripper about a beautiful Swiss governess (Ms. Marceau) who
is hired by a married English aristocrat to bear a child when his
wife is unable to conceive. Years later, she tracks him down and
becomes the governess to his spoiled young daughter, who doesn't
know that her teacher is also her biological mother. Using flash
cards, she tricks the intransigent little brat into learning to
read, among other good deeds. Ms. Marceau and Dillane strike
sparks, and the movie's canny mixture of sex and suds makes for
slick, low-grade ``Masterpiece Theater''-style entertainment
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE GOVERNESS,' starring Minnie Driver and Tom Wilkinson.
Directed by Sandra Goldbacher (R, 114 minutes). It is the early
1840s, and Rosina (Ms. Driver), a headstrong young Sephardic Jewish
woman living in London, poses as a Gentile to get a job as a
governess for the Cavendish family on a remote Scottish island.
Falling in love with the skittish, devoutly Christian head of the
household (Tom Wilkinson), a gentleman inventor with whom she has a
stormy affair, she becomes his collaborator in the invention of
photography. The ravishingly handsome film works on several levels:
as a proto-feminist fable, a meditation on still photography and
its relation to real life, and a portrait of lovers whose religious
difference becomes an unbridgeable emotional gap. Ms. Driver holds
the picture with a solid performance that falls short of great
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `A MERRY WAR,' starring Richard E. Grant and Helena Bonham
Carter. Directed by Robert Bierman (not rated, 101 minutes).
Skillfully adapted from George Orwell's satirical 1936 novel,
``Keep the Aspidistra Flying,'' the witty period piece, set in
1930s London, follows the descent into poverty of Gordon Comstock
(Grant), a successful London ad man who quits his copywriting job
to be a full-time poet. The subjects skewered include young artists
with delusions of grandeur and snobbish aristocrats with socialist
pretensions. Ms. Bonham Carter is Gordon's sweetheart who patiently
waits out a narcissistic seizure that Grant portrays with an
engaging comic buoyancy (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `NEXT STOP WONDERLAND,' starring Hope Davis and Alan Gelfant.
Directed by Brad Anderson (R, 111 minutes). Will Erin (Ms. Davis),
an attractive, introspective night-shift nurse, and Alan (Gelfant),
a plumber and aspiring marine biologist who was obviously meant for
her, collide on the streets of Boston and live happily ever after?
The setup of this romantic comedy about dating in the '90s may seem
cliched, but the witty, beautifully acted and edited film refreshes
the genre with the acuteness of Anderson's observations about
people and middle-class urban life in general. Ms. Davis creates a
wonderfully complex portrait of an idealistic introvert coping with
loneliness, disappointment and pressures from all sides, including
(in the movie's funniest scenes) some ardently self-centered
suitors who answer a personal ad. A rich Brazilian bossa nova score
gives the movie the mood of bittersweet longing (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `ONE TRUE THING,' starring Meryl Streep, Renee Zellweger and
William Hurt. Directed by Carl Franklin (PG-13, 120 minutes). This
film adaptation of the novel by Anna Quindlen _ a former columnist
for The New York Times _ about an ambitious New York journalist
forced to move back in with her parents to care for her dying
mother strikes a sad and universal chord. And Ms. Streep and Ms.
Zellweger are beautifully matched as a mother and daughter who
achieve a grown-up understanding during this anguished time. But
the movie treads the line between soap opera and serious drama and
has far too many cute and sentimental touches. Its structure _ the
story is told in flashbacks that make the mother's death a kind of
whodunit (she dies from an overdose of morphine) _ also cheapen the
movie without ruining it (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `PERMANENT MIDNIGHT,' starring Ben Stiller and Elizabeth Hurley.
Directed by David Veloz (R, 85 minutes). As Jerry Stahl recounts in
his 1995 memoir, drug addiction turned him into a skittish,
distracted, hugely self-involved individual. Since he happened to
be working as a television writer in Hollywood, no one really
noticed. The film version of his story plunges fearlessly into the
self-inflicted humiliations that went with this story. In a
first-rate, rivetingly caustic performance, Stiller plays a man on
a fashionably decadent slide all the way to rock bottom. The
character's clearest sign of dysfunction is his inability to
appreciate Elizabeth Hurley as his ravishing, high-powered wife
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ROUNDERS,' starring Matt Damon, Edward Norton, John Malkovich,
John Turturro and Gretchen Mol. Directed by John Dahl (R, 120
minutes). Though this tale of poker fever finally adds up to less
than meets the eye, what does meet the eye (and ear) is
mischievously entertaining. Inspired by Martin Scorsese's brand of
irresistible lowlife and aided by a splendid rogues' gallery of a
cast, the director of ``The Last Seduction'' takes his audience
into a poker demimonde of abundant color. As the actors make the
most of rascally roles (Malkovich has a field day with a Russian
accent), the story leads to settings as varied as the Elks Hall in
Binghamton and a Russian Turkish bath. Dahl may not have new
thoughts on the gambler's life, but he makes this guided tour worth
the trip (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `SAVING PRIVATE RYAN,' starring Tom Hanks, Matt Damon, Tom
Sizemore, Jeremy Davies, Edward Burns and Adam Goldberg. Directed
by Steven Spielberg (R, 168 minutes). Spielberg's soberly
magnificent new film is the finest war movie of our time. Turning
back the clock to restore passion and meaning to the genre, he
works in a spirit of urgent communication to look at war as if it
had not been looked at before. Tour-de-force battle scenes are
frank without sensationalism, and the same great storyteller who
made you believe there was an extraterrestrial hiding in the closet
has made this an irresistibly vibrant, gripping tale. Hanks
continues to astonish with admirable modesty, and the rest of the
casting is comparably inspired. As he did with ``Schindler's
List,'' Spielberg has made a landmark film of devastating power
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `A SOLDIER'S DAUGHTER NEVER CRIES,' starring Leelee Sobieski,
Kris Kristofferson, Barbara Hershey and Anthony Roth Costanzo.
Directed by James Ivory (R, 120 minutes). Working without a classic
at hand, the Merchant-Ivory team adapts a novel by Kaylie Jones,
James Jones' daughter, into a colorful panorama weakened by
autobiographical sprawl. With no real narrative shapeliness and a
loosely anecdotal pace, it vividly recalls the coming-of-age of a
sensitive young woman who (though well played by 14-year-old Ms.
Sobieski) remains a more slender, peripheral figure than the film's
ambitions require. Moving from Paris to America, it succeeds more
at evoking detail and atmosphere than in finding the heart of her
story (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY,' starring Cameron Diaz, Ben
Stiller and Matt Dillon. Directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly (R,
119 minutes). Sometimes Western civilization declines in
deliriously funny style. Hence this proudly obnoxious comedy is a
hoot in every sense, deserving a smidgen of disapproval and a whole
lot of helpless laughter. Set in motion by a prom, a crush and a
cruel, cruel zipper, this paean to low humor works ridiculously
well because it never stoops to being mean-spirited or (despite all
appearances) authentically inane. The principal cast is bright and
appealing, with Ms. Diaz at her most beautiful and blithe. Do note
that this film strives hard for something to offend everyone, and
that a tolerance for the Farrellys' zit jokes is unfortunately
required (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `WITHOUT LIMITS,' starring Billy Crudup and Donald Sutherland.
Directed by Robert Towne (PG-13, 118 minutes). In telling the story
of mercurial track star Steve Prefontaine, a screenwriter known for
enriching screenplays with unruly, unpredictable life, creates a
surprisingly resonant portrait. Thanks to Crudup's charismatic
performance as a runner with the attitudes of a rock star, this can
be watched as one more sports film, complete with exciting race
sequences. But it's not truly about winning, losing or even playing
the game; instead, Towne considers the philosophical distance
between the brash Prefontaine and his formidable coach, Bill
Bowerman (expertly played by Sutherland). The film's wisdom lies in
its thoughtful way of balancing these two (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `YOUR FRIENDS AND NEIGHBORS,' starring Jason Patric, Ben
Stiller, Aaron Eckhardt, Catherine Keener, Amy Brenneman and
Nastassja Kinski. Written and directed by Neil LaBute (R, 100
minutes). Three men obsessed with one another's sexual performance
are at the core of this second film from the director of ``In the
Company of Men.'' The new movie is so blunt at times, and so
unrelievedly talky and dark at others, that it cries out for the
velvet glove of ``Manhattan,'' a much more seductive film about
sexual opportunism and urbane cruelty. Yet even when LaBute's
material feels mannered or unremittingly sour, it sustains a
psychic ferocity that commands attention. The intricate web of
lies, failures and brutal revelations here is strong stuff, and
it's the work of an original filmmaker who takes no prisoners
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   `KEATON CLASSICS.' Buster Keaton in all his classic glory comes
to the screen of the Film Forum on Sunday in the start of a series
devoted to the great silent screen comedian. The opening bill
includes ``The General'' (1926), Keaton's spectacular retelling of
the Civil War's Great Locomotive Chase, and three of the master's
two-reel comedies: ``The Electric House,'' ``One Week'' and ``The
High Sign.'' In all, the series will present 13 features, including
``The Navigator'' (1924), ``Steamboat Bill Jr.'' (1928) and
``Sherlock Jr.'' (1923), as well as 19 of the two-reelers. Some of
the screenings will have a live piano accompaniment by Steve
Sterner; most of the others, synchronized musical scores. The
series will continue on nine Mondays through Nov. 23 at the Film
Forum, 209 W. Houston St., in the South Village. Tickets: $8.50;
$4.50 for Film Forum members. Screening schedule and information:
(212) 727-8110 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
