<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      09-24 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR LIMNS WOMEN'S LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viewed one by one on tape, a director's films usually follow a
gradual progression. In the case of Marleen Gorris, however, the
oeuvre sprints right up to the brink of oblivion before taking a
prodigious leap into the ranks of the acclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's hard to imagine a more radical shift in content
and style, accomplished in the space of 3 films made over 12 years,
from Ms. Gorris's harshly violent ``Question of Silence'' in 1983
(on video from First Run Features) to the elegant, deeply
reflective ``Mrs. Dalloway,'' her praised 1997 adaptation of
Virginia Woolf's novel, to be released on Tuesday by BMG.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two films, Ms. Gorris, who is Dutch, worked on other
projects and then wrote and directed ``Antonia's Line'' in 1995
(released on video by BMG), a richly pastoral and loving story
about four generations of women as seen through the recollections
of an aged matriarch.
</P>
<P>
   Often described as a feminist director, Ms. Gorris began as an
exceedingly angry one, and on the most rudimentary terms. In ``A
Question of Silence,'' three women _ one accused of shoplifting and
two others who don't know her or each other _ confront the store
owner and spontaneously stomp him to death, earning general
approval from women as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   In her next film, ``Broken Mirrors'' (1985), the lot of women in
a brothel is compared to the fate of a woman held captive by a
serial killer who starves his victims to death.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next decade her perspective changed. Rage had
dissipated. ``You have expressed something that is important to
you,'' Ms. Gorris said in a recent interview. ``You aren't so angry
and you go on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonia's Line'' begins and ends on the day Antonia (Willeke
van Ammelrooy) dies at age 90. In her reminiscences, her daughter,
a lesbian, wants a child, and Antonia arranges a fruitful one-night
liaison. (Bring on a man, handsome and wordless.)
</P>
<P>
   Her granddaughter is a prodigy and has her own daughter. With
men around as minor functionaries, the women bond and thrive down
the decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never talked about women's lives as happy occasions,''
Ms. Gorris said. ``I decided, wouldn't it be nice if they were
raised in a kind of harmony with life and death.'' The movie won
the Academy Award for best foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Mrs. Dalloway' was very much a result of having won the
Oscar,'' Ms. Gorris said. ``I was offered a lot of scripts, and
this was one of the few I thought was interesting.'' Written by the
actress Eileen Atkins, this is the first film Ms. Gorris directed
that she didn't write herself.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1923, and the matronly Clarissa Dalloway (Vanessa
Redgrave) reflects on a life that might have seen her married as
the young Clarissa (Natascha McElhone) to the adventurous Peter
Walsh (Alan Cox). Instead, she chose to play it safe with the
sweet, monied and pedestrian Richard Dalloway (played as an older
man by John Standing).
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes me feel less afraid,'' the young Clarissa explains.
So, as happens in Woolf's story, men are around, if only as
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``My films are about a woman's decision in a male-dominated
world,'' Ms. Gorris said. ``I will remain interested in that
issue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Box
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong, shrouded and caught in transition, provides
appropriately shifting ground for a frustrated affair between John
(Jeremy Irons), a reporter, and Vivian (Gong Li), the beautiful
mistress of a shady wheeler-dealer (Michael Hui).
</P>
<P>
   Wandering the city with a video camera, John, who has leukemia,
balances his infatuation with the city and his obsession with a
woman whose ambitions and background inhibit an open relationship.
And so it is with Hong Kong, evasive and unwilling to reveal itself
in a lyrical film, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times,
whose ``elegiac echoes linger long after the final credits have
rolled.''
</P>
<P>
   1997. Trimark. $103.99. 109 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Paulie
</P>
<P>
   Life isn't easy for a tart-tongued conure (a member of the
parrot family) who talks as much as Paulie. As the pet and friend
of a little girl with a speech defect, he is banished by her
family, which doesn't believe he talks at all. That lands him in a
pawn shop, where he is bought by a widow (Gena Rowlands) who takes
him cross-country in hopes of a reunion with the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Paulie works as a song-and-dance bird, is
kidnapped, becomes a cat burglar and ends up locked away in the
basement laboratory of an animal-behavior researcher (Bruce
Davison), where he tells his story to a sympathetic janitor (Tony
Shalhoub).
</P>
<P>
   ``This warm and witty family film is definitely a bird of a
different color'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $22.99. 91 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Players Club &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rapper Ice Cube made his directorial debut with a hearty
throwback to the blaxploitation films of the 1970s: cash, flash,
trash and violence. Diana (LisaRaye) is a single mom and college
student by day and, to put bread on the table, a stripper called
Diamond by night.
</P>
<P>
   Stripping in turn leads to appearances at bachelor parties and
Diana's transformation into a pistol-packin' mama. But the humor
stays broad and ``campy moments and a luridly colorful look (with
cinematography by Malik Sayeed) may give this no-flair, no-frills B
movie a healthy video afterlife some day'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. New Line. $100.71. 104 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hush &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Say hello to Martha Baring (Jessica Lange), a neurotic widow who
runs a Kentucky horse farm. During a Christmas visit by her son
(Jonathan Schaech) and his girlfriend (Gwyneth Paltrow), Martha
sabotages the young woman's birth control as part of a plan to get
her impregnated, kill her and keep the baby.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of a gloves-off psycho-killer romp, Jonathan Darby's
film ``hasn't the foggiest notion whether it's a soap opera or a
horror film, and wanders around in a generic fog'' (Stephen
Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 96 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE DEVIL IS A WOMAN.'' Josef von Sternberg's film (1935, 79
minutes) about a one-woman wrecking crew and the shambles she makes
of men's lives is the best known of four films starring Marlene
Dietrich to be released on Tuesday by Universal. The others are
Billy Wilder's ``FOREIGN AFFAIR'' (1948, 115 minutes), which sends
a congresswoman (Jean Arthur) to Berlin to investigate troop morale
and a nightclub singer with former Nazi connections (Dietrich);
Rouben Mamoulian's ``SONG OF SONGS'' (1933, 89 minutes), in which
Dietrich, as a country girl in her first Hollywood film not
directed by von Sternberg, inspires a sculptor (Brian Aherne) but
marries the rich fellow (Lionel Atwill), and Rene Clair's ``FLAME
OF NEW ORLEANS'' (1941, 79 minutes), in which Dietrich becomes
countess of the city while pretending to be her own look-alike
cousin, the better to carry on affaires d'amour. $14.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE VICAR OF DIBLEY.'' In a series currently on PBS, Dawn
French stars as Geraldine Granger, an ebullient clergywoman who
wakes up the sleepy village of Dibley with her sprightly and
unorthodox ways. 1998. BBC Video. Four 60-minute episodes on two
cassettes. $19.98 per cassette.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE IRISH R.M.'' In the ``Irish R.M.,'' a PBS Masterpiece
Theater production written by Rosemary Anne Sisson (``Upstairs,
Downstairs''), Peter Bowles stars as a retired army officer who is
appointed a magistrate in the west of Ireland before Irish
independence. 1986. Acorn Media. Six cassettes, $79.95. 325
minutes. Information: (800) 474-2277.
</P>
</TEXT>
