<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-N     09-24 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 4  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BYE WEEK (BUFFALO, MIAMI, NEW ENGLAND, JETS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GAME OF THE WEEK: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (3-0) vs. Pittsburgh (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Seattle (3) _ 100-yard rushing games. Pittsburgh (18)
_ Kordell Stewart career TD runs.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Seattle has surprised many fans. For many others, the
Steelers' showing in Miami on last Sunday was a big surprise.
Pittsburgh wasn't just shut out but were also shut down. All
around. Big turnovers and a pressing game by Stewart was where it
started. But QB Stewart turns things around with his arm and with
his legs. He should and will run more and his passing will improve,
too. The Pittsburgh run defense must deal deftly with backs Ricky
Watters and Ahman Green. The Seahawks put on a show, a talented
bunch at every turn, but Pittsburgh answers.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers, 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE (3-0) VS. TENNESSEE (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Jaguars (14-6) _ Brunell's record as starter. Oilers
(311.3) _ Yards allowed per game.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: When the Jaguars and Oilers meet, it usually means a
close game. All six games in their series have been decided by 8 or
fewer points and Jacksonville has won four. Rookie back Fred Taylor
will be asked to do more for the Jaguars in the running game and
Mark Brunell continues to do his thing: Escape the rush and make
zinging, accurate throws downfield. He is by far one of the
league's most accurate deep passers. The Oilers have high hopes and
need this game to build on those hopes. Look for receiver Yancey
Thigpen and the Oilers offensive line to be heroes. Oilers, 24-22.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA (1-2) VS. ST. LOUIS (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Cardinals (5) _ NFC-most fumbles earned. Rams (272.0)
_ Tony Banks passing yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: When Rams quarterback Tony Banks covered the football
and went running toward the end zone again in the closing seconds
and scored and beat Buffalo on last Sunday, it was a fun sight. The
week before, vs. Minnesota, Banks tried it in nearly an identical
situation and missed the goal line by inches as the clock expired,
forcing a Rams loss. It told you two things about Banks _ he has
courage and he is intent on doing things his way in becoming a
big-time NFL quarterback. This is another step _ lifting his team
to .500. Cardinals, 24-13.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER (3-0) VS. WASHINGTON (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Broncos (6.78) _ Avg. yards gained on 1st downs.
Redskins (-8) _ Turnover differential.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Washington can still move the football, just not far
enough or long enough and without turnovers arising. But the
defense is under siege. This team is in big trouble. It goes 0-4.
Broncos, 36-23.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BAY (3-0) VS. CAROLINA (0-2)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Packers (310) _ Offensive yards per game. Panthers
(346) _ Offensive yds. per game.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Could it be that the Carolina offense is averaging more
yards per game than Green Bay's? Who would think that possible? But
Carolina is also minus 4 in turnover differential while Green Bay
is plus 1. And another thing: Green Bay gives up an average of 76.3
yards fewer than Carolina on defense. Too much Brett Favre throwing
to Antonio Freeman for Carolina to handle. Too much Reggie White
and LeRoy Butler on defense for Carolina to handle. Too much Green
Bay. Packers, 27-20.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY (2-1) VS. PHILADELPHIA (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Chiefs (+8) _ Turnover differential. Eagles (-5) _
Turnover differential.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: The turnover game says plenty about these teams. The
Chiefs win turnover battles _ they protect the ball and steal it.
The Eagles lose turnover battles _ they toss it away and don't
steal it enough. Enough said. Chiefs, 20-9.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (2-0) VS. INDIANAPOLIS (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Saints (1) _ Turnovers in `98. Colts (8) _ Peyton
Manning interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: The Saints keep it simple. They run it and and stop the
run. They play hard and smart. At least, through two games. Playing
the Colts gives them a chance to be 3-0 for the first time since
1993. Jim Mora, the Colts coach, sees his old team, a team he
coached for 11 seasons. Sean Dawkins, now with the Saints, played
five years with the Colts, including last year. Dawkins gets to
enjoy the reunion more than Mora. For Dawkins, a nice homecoming.
Saints, 19-17.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND (1-2) VS. DALLAS (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Raiders (2-0) _ Record at Texas Stadium. Cowboys
(62-35) _ Record vs. AFC.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Dallas has earned 26 rushing first downs. That is the
most in the NFL. That means that Dallas coach Chan Gailey is
complementing nicely for the loss of Troy Aikman at quarterback.
Gailey is finding different ways to get his backs the ball in
different situations, up the middle, off tackle and around the
ends. And it is working, thanks to a hard-working offensive line.
Dallas sees the future when it tries to defend Raiders back
Napolean Kauffman. He can be a blur. But Dallas wins the game on
special teams. Cowboys, 29-21.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY 4 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (2-0) VS. SAN FRANCISCO (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Falcons (7-1) _ Record in last 8. 49ers (7.7) _
Garrison Hearst avg. yds. per carry.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Atlanta knows how huge this game is for its season and
its psyche. The Falcons cannot win the NFC West without beating the
49ers and they have not won in San Francisco since 1991. The 49ers
have won 12 of the last 16 in this series. Steve Young has passed
for more yards (4,055) vs. the Falcons than vs. any team. Running
back Garrison Hearst makes the 49ers running game energetic and the
49ers have won 9 consecutively at home. Chris Chandler, the Atlanta
quarterback, has thrown at least one touchdown pass in 14
consecutive games. This is a good show. 49ers, 27-10.
</P>
<P>
   GIANTS (1-2) VS. SAN DIEGO (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: _ Giants (12) _ Maynard punts inside 20. Chargers
(89.0) _ AFC No-1 rush defense.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Bad news for the Giants _ the punter, Brad Maynard, has
been a star so far this season with a league-most punts landing
inside the 20. Nice to have an effective punter, but when that has
been the highlight through three games, you are in trouble. The
Giants running game faces the best run defense so far in the AFC.
The last time the Giants visited the West Coast, they tripped all
over themselves in a loss to the Raiders and they have not played
in San Diego since 1989. No way rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf is as
horrible as he was last week vs. Kansas City. He and the Chargers
defense give the Giants more to ponder. Chargers, 23-16.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA (3-0) VS. CHICAGO (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Vikings (3) _ Robert Griffith interceptions. Bears (1)
_ No. 1 NFC pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: The Bears are actually good at something. They have the
best pass defense in the NFC. Actually, the Bears can take the ball
away on defense; they rank among the league's best there. So, why
haven't they won yet.? Not enough big plays. Not enough
consistency. Some tough luck. They battle a Vikings defense that is
tied with Miami with 10 takeaways; safety Robert Griffith has
three, on interceptions. Dennis Green is 9-4 vs. the Bears. He
makes a living beating them. Make it one more time. Vikings, 20-13.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (1-2) VS. BALTIMORE (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Bengals (+4) _ Turnover differential. Ravens (+5) _
Turnover differential.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: These teams are over the top in taking the ball away
more than giving it away. This bodes for an entertaining game and
also indicates that the team that makes fewer turnovers prevails.
That would be the Ravens. They start Eric Zeier instead of Jim
Harbaugh and Zeier is playing well (42 of 72 for 602 yards with 3
touchdowns and 1 interception, a 93.6 passer rating). Zeier's
passing rating is higher than Bengals quarterback Neil O'Donnell's
(91.1). Zeier even leads the AFC in fourth-quarter passing yards
(289). Zeier and the Ravens run defense wins it. Ravens, 14-6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY (1-2) VS. DETROIT (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   KEY STAT: Buccaneers (0) _ Trent Dilfer interceptions. Lions (0)
_ Interceptions earned.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Detroit is swirling in controversy (quarterback Scott
Mitchell's immaturity) and bad play. Notorious slow starters, this
is where the Lions begin to rise. Rookie quarterback Charlie Batch
settles in and Barry Sanders runs out of the Bucs' grasp. In the
end, it is decided on the Tampa Bay offense vs. the Detroit
defense. Detroit is such an emotionally-stressed team that the
glare of Monday night offers a salve to bruised egos. They respond.
Lions, 23-13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
