<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-STUDENTS0925-     09-24 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-STUDENTS0925-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American colleges and universities are slowly
losing their grasp of the world's international students as an
increasing number turn to other countries for their post-secondary
educations, a team of educators, businesses and government agencies
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of international students to the United States may
have stagnated because of high costs, lack of access to information
and maltreatment, said participants at the International Higher
Education Summit Conference held at the U.S. State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, the number of international students hosted by some
non-U.S. countries has increased by as much as 10 times, while the
rate in the United States has slowed from 5.3 percent increase in
1990-91 to a 0.9 percent rise in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition by other countries has ... increased
dramatically,'' said Nancy Cole, president of Educational Testing
Service, a nonprofit organization that develops and administers
achievement, occupational and admissions tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada, the United Kingdom, the European Union and Latin
America have all increased marketing efforts aimed at students in
Southeast Asia, the largest provider of international students,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the University of Texas at Austin, which ranks No. 7 in the
country in its number of foreign students, has seen its numbers
dwindle. After reaching a peak in 1994 of 4,200 students, that
number had gone down to 3,403 by 1996-97, said Richard Lariviere,
associate vice president for international programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lariviere was unsure what caused the decline, he said
the unversity has strict admissions standards for international
students, and UT has tried to limit the number of students it
accepts to keep enrollment under 49,000.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when there is an increased interdependence on other
countries for the nation's economic and cultural well-being, the
loss of foreign students can mean the loss of crucial contacts with
future world leaders, said Joseph Duffey, director of the U.S.
Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``International students bring unique features to American
colleges and universities which are important to U.S. relations and
the world, `` Duffy said. ``The knowledge of other cultures which
these students bring to American youth, and the understanding of
the U.S. which they take back to their own countries helps form the
basis for future contacts between the United States and the rest of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference participants said one reason for the slowed growth
may be that the foreign students often run into barriers when
coming to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, they said, universities assume foreign students
have access to program descriptions, course schedules and other
materials when they may not. Although many universities post such
information on the Internet, many students, particularly those in
some African countries, may not have access.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, participants said universities don't recruit
agressively enough and the U.S. government often makes it difficult
for students to obtain visas for themselves and their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   However, said Ralph Hines of the Department of Education,
although the government recognizes the rich resources international
students can bring, the federal agency is somewhat limited by its
own mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our standpoint ... our mandate is to train Americans,''
said Hines, acting head of the Education Department's Office of
Higher Education Programs.
</P>
<P>
   Some authorities suggested one way to solve the problem of
dwindling foreign students is for government, universities and
businesses to establish clear goals and policies on international
education, said Keith Geiger, director of USIA's Office of Academic
Programs.
</P>
<P>
   Such policies might include ensuring that enough informational
material is available in embassies, libraries and campuses
worldwide, creating special provisions that would allow foreign
students to work in the United States and developing a campus
atmosphere that reflects the interests of an international
community.
</P>
<P>
   Hines said the latter goal is of the utmost importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students go where they feel they're accepted and where there's
a level of mobile effort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
