<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GORE OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During his Watergate troubles, President Richard
Nixon argued that impeachment requires an indictable offense, a
tougher standard than that described by President Gerald Ford, who
said an impeachable offense is merely what Congress says it is.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoirs, Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., former minority
counsel of the 1973 Senate committee that investigated the
Watergate crimes, recalls that Democratic chairman Sam Ervin agreed
with Nixon on that high standard. ``I think you do have to have an
indictable offense before you can impeach him,'' Thompson quotes
Ervin as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury investigating charges of a cover-up and
obstruction of justice eventually set the stage for impeachment by
naming Nixon an unindicted co-conspirator in February 1974, five
months before he was forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars generally believe that the constitutional
separation of powers bars the judicial branch from indicting a
sitting president for wrongdoing. But a president could be
vulnerable to criminal charges after leaving office, which is why
Ford felt obliged to issue a pardon for his mentor Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   It is also why Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's office is
spreading the word in the legal community that he intends to indict
President Clinton if Clinton resigns. There is even the suggestion
that Starr may indict Clinton after his term ends in two years if
the president manages to survive a congressional impeachment
process.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot know whether Starr is actually determined to send
Clinton to jail, although it seems possible based on his enraged
pursuit of the president thus far. He could be merely using the
threat of indictment to scare the White House into refusing to
consider the resignation option, forcing the president to endure
the full long and painful process of impeachment hearings in the
House and a trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said his
panel will vote early next month on whether to ask the full House
to authorize impeachment hearings. With Congress set to adjourn
Oct. 9, Hyde's timetable would freeze the matter until after the
Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-controlled committee is very likely to vote for an
impeachment inquiry and the Republican-led House seems certain to
authorize such hearings. But nothing further would happen until
next year, under a new and perhaps more heavily Republican
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report to Congress lists 11 counts on which he believes
the president has committed impeachable and indictable offenses.
But several are extremely flimsy, particularly his outrageous
effort to distort the president's legitimate legal maneuvers in
self-defense into illicit obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Starr failed to include in his report any references to other
pending business in his office: Whitewater, misuse of FBI files and
travel office shenanigans. Increasingly credible leaks from Starr's
office indicate that despite four years of probing he has been
unable to prove presidential corruption on those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of all the controversy, the case against Clinton
basically comes down to the question of lying under oath about sex.
It's terrible stuff. Clinton ought to be punished, and will be.
</P>
<P>
   But the concept of putting behind bars a president or former
president _ the elected leader of the free world, mind you _ over a
personal issue that did not affect public policy is an obscene
distortion of our judicial principles.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that doesn't mean Starr won't try to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has moved from being a prosecutor to being a persecutor, a
dangerous maniac who defies due process, privacy and civil rights
and has set himself above the law.
</P>
<P>
   He could not get a conviction from a liberal, pro-Clinton
District of Columbia jury, but he has convened another grand jury
in suburban Virginia that might be more conservative and inclined
to be morally judgmental.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us to Vice President Albert Gore. If the
president does resign, he will need protection from his White House
successor against a possible indictment. It is impossible to
believe that Gore would not pardon his friend and mentor, just as
Ford pardoned Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Political legend has it that Ford lost the 1976 presidential
election because voters resented the Nixon pardon, but that is not
entirely correct. Ford lost the election because Ronald Reagan
mounted a strong primary challenge against him and badly damaged
Ford's reputation in the process. The coast was clear for Jimmy
Carter to defeat the incumbent Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Gore could probably pardon Clinton without undue electoral
retaliation; a majority of voters still tell the pollsters they
don't want Clinton impeached, let alone indicted. And people
understand loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has a lot to gain if Gore were to win the presidency in
the year 2000. If an unfriendly Republican disinclined toward a
pardon is in the White House in two years, when Starr will still
have the legal authority to go after him, Clinton would be in deep
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has other political problems as he faces a year 2000
presidential campaign, but that's a different subject.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1740EDT &QL; 
