u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-630(2     09-24 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANCY GOODS WITH AN AURA OF A BETTER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., N.Y.)  (js) 
 BY WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Social betterment may be a universal impulse, but Americans have
always taken the pursuit to a new level. Even in the 1750s, the
colonists eking out a living in Deerfield, Mass., were also busily
trying to improve themselves morally, intellectually and materially
_ between Indian raids and harvests, that is. We see this in
``Pursuing Refinement in Rural New England: 1750-1850,'' an
exhibition at the Flynt Center of Early New England Life, a new
museum run by Historic Deerfield that opens to the public Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The center is named for the Henry N. Flynt family of Greenwich,
Conn., which helped to save and restore 14 historic houses on
Deerfield's mile-long, tree-lined Main Street over the last 40
years. For the new center, situated in a field behind Main Street,
a Philadelphia architect, Tony Junker of Ueland Junker McCauley
Nicholson, designed a 27,000-square-foot building that looks like a
nearby Colonial tobacco barn. It is the color of the local
sandstone.
</P>
<P>
   For the new show, the curator of Historic Deerfield, Philip Zea,
was able to cull from Deerfield's 22,000 objects a number of
consumer goods that were especially prized at the time. They range
from fancy imported goods, like a man's salmon-colored silk
waistcoat from England, a porcelain soup tureen from China and
mirrors from northern Europe, to local wares: skillful
interpretations of high-style Boston furniture, silver tankards and
pewter teapots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show the way they really were,'' Zea said. ``And
why they placed so much importance on education, polite
conversation, manners and fancy goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's hard to imagine the isolation of the early settlers.
Leigh Keno, a Manhattan dealer who specializes in fine American
antiques, said: ``You have to remember _ Deerfield was 105 miles
from Boston, the center of the universe, the source of style and
fashion. It was a four-day trip by carriage, and it wasn't an
inexpensive trip.'' Were the settlers who acquired the games
tables, teapots, pianos and Chinese export porcelains _ all
evidence of leisure time _ social climbers?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Richard Bushman, a history professor at Columbia
University and author of ``The Refinement of America: Persons,
Houses, Cities'' (Knopf, 1992), the book that inspired the
exhibition. ``These objects represented a higher way of life, a
step up from the barbarians,'' he said. ``They also thought of law,
science, morality and even manners as evolving from this way of
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Bushman said: ``This whole culture was a culture of
presentation. Not that they were big-time entertainers _ they
weren't _ but there was an indication that you had cultivation if
you participated in the higher things in life.'' (Is this any
different from attending the opera once a year, today?)
</P>
<P>
   The yearning for refinement was felt at all levels of society.
At the top there were the rural elite, known as the ``mansion
people'' in western Massachusetts: magistrates, merchants,
ministers and militia officers. One of them, John Worthington
(1719-1800), ordered for his marriage the silver-embroidered salmon
waistcoat that is in the show.
</P>
<P>
   They were resilient, too. One minister, the Rev. John Williams
(1664-1729), was kidnapped by Indians with others in his
congregation during the famous 1704 attack on Deerfield. They were
taken to Canada. In 1707, after he was released in a prisoner
exchange, what did he do? As we see in the show, he commissioned
his portrait, at a time when only 2 percent of the population had
their portraits painted.
</P>
<P>
   The urge for refinement extended to society's lowest levels.
``Everyone had a little something,'' Bushman said. ``They would
start with a silver teaspoon or a teacup, then move on.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   When you realize how rare and precious each bolt of silk or
silver teapot was, you approach auctions and fairs with a fresh
eye. For example, you will look differently at the Early American
needlework, textiles and hooked rugs at the Decorative Arts and
Textiles Antiques Show this weekend. The Stella show begins Friday,
running from 11 a.m. to 7 p.m., and continues through 5 p.m. Sunday
at the Gramercy Park Armory in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Dodge of Montague Center, Mass., has a child's quilt, a
white-on-white Marseilles example from 1850, at the show. He
recently sold a woman's pocket _ the precursor of today's
pocketbook _ not unlike the one in the show at Deerfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman's pocket was an extension of her self-worth, pride and
fine skill with a needle,'' Zea writes in the catalog. ``She tied
it around her waist as a separate workbag rather than sewing it
into the lining of her gown. Pockets held personal items.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ziegler of Epping, N.H., is selling a hand-loomed,
multicolored runner at the show. Rugs were another opportunity to
show off one's skills. The Deerfield show has a circa-1825 wool and
linen rug that won a $1 cash prize in 1825 for its design.
</P>
<P>
   The coming auctions also feature objects that would have been
valued in Colonial times in Deerfield.
</P>
<P>
   One unusual cherry high chest in Christie's American furniture
sale on Oct. 8 is thought to have been made in Connecticut or
Massachusetts between 1730 and 1750. Instead of a bonnet top or a
flat top, it has three stepped shelves on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely rare to have a high chest with its original
steps,'' said Martha Willoughby, an American furniture specialist
at Christie's. ``The form has no English precedents. The steps were
meant to display china, to show off one's exotic imports from the
East.'' Estimate: $60,000 to $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's Fine Americana sale on Oct. 10 includes several pieces
that ``mansion people'' would have coveted. Lot 320 is a Queen Anne
cherry scallop-top dressing table made in Connecticut about 1740 to
1760. Leslie Keno of Sotheby's (Leigh Keno's brother) said the
extremely wavy curve of the overhanging scalloped top was a feature
of Connecticut River Valley furniture. ``To my knowledge, this
extreme degree of scalloping would not appear in England,'' he
said. ``It's purely American. The interplay of S-curves makes the
piece come alive.'' Estimate: $60,000 to $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Such pieces approach the apex of what New England colonists
considered refinement. It is a pity that Historic Deerfield does
not collect the artifacts of the settlers' Indian neighbors. In its
American Indian art sale in Boston on Oct. 3, Skinner is selling a
pair of exquisite Iroquois women's moccasins, made in New England,
that are tanned, beaded, stitched and intricately decorated with
porcupine quills colored red, yellow and blue. The lower part of
the design on the cuff is geometric and may represent a flowing
stream, said Lori Nevins, a Skinner specialist. Estimate: $8,000 to
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner also has a round birch-bark box from the Micmac tribe of
Maine. The tan, gray and white cover is designed with motifs
abstracted from nature that are pieced out in quillwork in
repeating geometric devices. Estimate: $1,800 to $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Historic Deerfield should peek outside the stockade in
examining refinement in rural New England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
