<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Sept. 25, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST for Friday, September 25, 1998. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Hurricane Georges wobbled into the open waters off the
north coast of Cuba, after spending nearly 18 hours over land.
After the interaction with land greatly disrupted the hurricane's
circulation, high resolution satellite images revealed a
strengthening trend as the storm drew warmth and moisture from the
tepid waters of the Florida Straits.
</P>
<P>
   Further strengthening is expected Friday, as Hurricane Georges
batters the Florida Keys and parts of South Florida with tropical
squalls and gusty winds. Tides will run several feet above normal,
especially in the Keys. Extensive flooding and overwash on Highway
One, which links the Keys with south Florida, is anticipated.
Hurricane force winds will occur within 50 miles of the storm's
center, primarily on its northern flank. Hurricane Georges will
reach the eastern Gulf of Mexico Friday afternoon, then continue on
a west-northwest to northwest path into Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Milder winds will develop over the Northeast and Middle Atlantic
States. A weakening disturbance will generate plenty of clouds, but
only a couple of showers are possible near the central
Appalachians. Overall, it will be much duller than Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A weak cold preceded by patchy showers will slice through the
Great Lakes into the central Plains. Scattered thunderstorms will
be triggered in the warm air ahead of the front in the western Ohio
valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest will be unsettled as a vigorous jet stream
disturbance approaches. Clouds and showers will be abundant from
the northern Rockies to the Washington Coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Crowded Atlantic &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Late on Wednesday, Tropical Storm Karl swirled to life 320 miles
east-northeast of the island of Bermuda in an already crowded
Atlantic Ocean. At the same time, Hurricane Georges was battering
Cuba, while Hurricane Ivan was heading northward over the eastern
Atlantic, and Hurricane Jeanne was strengthening west of the Cape
Verde Islands. This marks only the third time since the formal
naming of tropical cyclones began in 1953 that four named tropical
storms or hurricane have roamed the Atlantic Ocean simultaneously.
The record of four was first set in 1961 before being tied in 1995
and now in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
