<HEADLINE>
`COLD WAR': FROM THE BOLSHEVIKS TO THE BERLIN WALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A history of the Cold War, which ran for close to half a century
and was played out on several continents, is no small undertaking.
In recognition of the subject's scope, CNN's new series allows it
24 episodes, one a week beginning on Sunday with an introduction to
Soviet-American relations and concluding next spring with the fall
of the Berlin Wall. It's an ambitiously conceived, intelligently
executed project.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the main events, like the Berlin airlift, the Cuban
missile crisis and, of course, the Vietnam War have been treated
before on television, but they are infused with fresh drama by
newly unearthed and reconstructed newsreels, demonstrating once
again the ingenuity of enterprising researchers.
</P>
<P>
   An international team of historians has guided the producers in
getting the story, as British co-executive producer Jeremy Isaacs
puts it, ``roughly right,'' no small aspiration given so
wide-ranging and contentious a matter. They are abetted by hundreds
of interviews with important players, including former heads of
state, and the complex narrative is sharply written by the likes of
Neal Ascherson, Ian Buruma, Germaine Greer and William Shawcross
and delivered as effectively as you'd expect by Kenneth Branagh.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's opening hour begins with the Bolshevik Revolution
and the brief intrusion by U.S. and British troops on the side of
the White Russian counter-revolutionaries, signaling what would
prove to be decades of mutual suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   The uneasy World War II alliance against Germany having ended
with a divided Europe, the Cold War more or less officially starts
next week with Winston Churchill's resounding Fulton, Mo., speech:
``From Stettin in the Baltic to Trieste in the Adriatic, an Iron
Curtain has descended across the Continent.''
</P>
<P>
   As the subsequent episodes demonstrate, Churchill's imagery was,
if anything, modest. The chronicle carries us briskly through the
Marshall Plan and the Korean War; the rise of Joseph McCarthy and
the death of Joseph Stalin; the West's political commotions of the
1960's and the crushing of independence movements in Eastern
Europe. Hot wars in the Middle East, Africa and Latin America are
seen from a Cold War perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The chapters overlap, the themes are adroitly interwoven. Events
have moved so fast that the maneuverings over nuclear power, which
shadowed all Cold War calculations, now seem like ancient history,
and Mikhail Gorbachev, who presided over the breakup of what Ronald
Reagan memorably called an ``evil empire,'' seems almost a marginal
figure. Yet the half-century legacy of the Cold War continues to
reverberate in a shaky Russia and a United States trying to sort
out its responsibilities in a newly perplexing world.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers will have no trouble taking exception to the series'
slant on matters that have not lost their powers of controversy,
whether it be over Vietnam or Nicaragua or Star Wars, or, indeed,
the question of which side did more to incite the Cold War in the
first place. Nothing here is likely to put such disputes to rest,
(the judgments are pretty much mainstream American history). But as
an effort to give coherence and drama to the great ideological
conflict of our time, ``Cold War'' is an estimable television
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `COLD WAR'
</P>
<P>
   Comrades
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on CNN
</P>
<P>
   The first of a 24-episode documentary series. Written by Jeremy
Isaacs and edited by Shelagh Brady. Series associate producers,
Isobel Hinshelwood, Alison McAllan. Series producer, Martin Smith.
Senior producer, Vivian Schiller, and production manager, Michael
Thomas, for CNN Productions. Music by Carl Davis. Executive
producers, Pat Mitchell, Jeremy Isaacs. Narrator, Kenneth Branagh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
