a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV01-     09-24 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV01-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE MOVE TO SECOND GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday Oct. 1)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There we were, all the second-grade parents, sitting in those
Lilliputian chairs with our knees jammed up against the desks.
</P>
<P>
   It was curriculum night at Knight Elementary, and we were
getting a peek into the world our children inhabit when we drop
them off at 7:50 each morning.
</P>
<P>
   Our son's teacher, a grandmotherly steel magnolia who has been
teaching elementary school for 35 years, was explaining the
proposed topics for this semester.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the first unit's work _ a hand-colored map of the
continents, math work sheets, a ``night writer'' journal and the
reading text _ were on top of each desk. Each child had drawn their
house on top of their folder.
</P>
<P>
   Adam had done a fair rendition of our new home on yellow
construction paper, with birds in the sky and smoke coming from the
chimney, although the second floor had a medieval turret coming out
of the roof that I didn't remember seeing the last time I looked.
</P>
<P>
   In science, the class was learning the difference between Alive,
Not Alive and Once Living. Beside the example of Alive (a fish),
Adam had drawn a shark, a bat and a ``wall'' (whale). So far, so
good.
</P>
<P>
   Beside the example for Not Alive (a car), he had drawn a jet, a
ship and a car. OK, well, a little redundant, but at least his car
was green.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting part, though, was his take on Once Living:
Godzilla, a log, a feather, and a long rectangle with a fluffy
thing at the top and a stick figure frantically waving his arms
next to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A flower in vase?'' his teacher had written beside it,
optimistically.
</P>
<P>
   I thought not. But I had to ask when we got home just to be
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``A flower in a vase?'' Adam repeated, with disdain. ``That's a
guy in a building that was blown up. You know, Once Living. He's
not living anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep. I thought so. We'll just leave that as ``flower in vase''
in the teacher's book.
</P>
<P>
   During curriculum night, we also learned there would be 15 new
spelling words a week.
</P>
<P>
   The D'Nealian handwriting method would be used, to make the
transition to script easier. And, of course, there would be weekly
visits to the new computer lab, which will eventually make the
aforementioned handwriting drills obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   (This is the Class of 2008, after all, which will be doing high
school term papers by linking Web pages.)
</P>
<P>
   A collective gasp went up when we realized our 7 and 8 year
olds, just a few years out of nap time and finger paints, would be
receiving number and letter grades this year.
</P>
<P>
   The grading scale was the strict one: A, 92 to 100; B, 83 to 91;
C, 74 to 82; D, 70 to 73; U, 69 and below. I have never understood
this scale. Why do A, B and C have nine-point windows of
opportunity, while D has a narrow four-point window, and U has a
69-point football field?
</P>
<P>
   I've always preferred the rounder, more friendly 90 to 100, 80
to 89, 70 to 79 and 60 to 69, myself. U still covers a lot of
ground, but at least you have four 10-point cushions before you get
there.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the evening grew on, I warmed to the idea. If this is
the scale they'll have in middle and high school, why not start
now?
</P>
<P>
   At least they'll be used to it. This, of course, was before my
son brought home the math test where he missed two problems and got
an 82.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' I said to my husband, after the kids were asleep,
``do you miss two problems and get a C.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You do when there are only 11 problems on the test,'' Jim
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But look at how well he did on these nine. And he only missed
this problem by one, because he miscounted the fish. Hey, look at
this, one of the fish is hiding behind a log. That's not math. It's
underwater surveillance,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only one math paper,'' said my husband, with irritating
logic, as I kept looking for more dirty tricks on the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want him to get an image of himself as a C student,''
I said. ``Labels start young, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   I was starting to feel real antipathy for that renegade fish,
lurking in the seaweed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Adam will rally with self-esteem intact,'' Jim said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, he got 100 on the next spelling test, and I was
slightly reassured. I put the paper on the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Charlie. Tuna casserole for everyone, tonight.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a New York Times Regional Newspapers feature
writer. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
