<HEADER>
A2889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-BONDING-ART-     09-24 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-BONDING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLEST LEAGUER, 3, SHUNS THE OLD BAWL GAME AND GOES THE FULL 9 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By MICHAEL SHAPIRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You take a 3-year-old to a ball game at your peril.
That's what I heard. I had waited until my daughter was 5 before
escorting her to her first game. But with second children, things
always feel accelerated. My son had seen Eddie Murphy in ``Dr.
Dolittle.'' He laughed at the questionable jokes.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for a game. Friends told me I was mad. He will not
last to the second inning, one warned. And worse, said another, you
will never see the game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they were right. Perhaps I was pushing the child,
playing Leopold Mozart to my son's Wolfgang: ``Explain the infield
fly rule, boy!''
</P>
<P>
   But then I thought of all those little children you see on
television during games, sitting on the laps of their moms and
dads, wearing baseball caps that are about eight sizes too large
and clutching in their slender arms souvenir drink cups, pennants
and mascot teddy bears. And those were for night games. I was
thinking of a Sunday afternoon. Those children appeared to be
well-adjusted. Why not mine?
</P>
<P>
   I lowered my expectations. Two innings would be fine, I
reasoned. Three would be a triumph. Never mind how long we stay; we
will go to a game. He will see the great expanse of outfield green.
He will hear the crack of ball against bat. He will eat a lot of
bad food.
</P>
<P>
   So there we sat, in the upper deck of Yankee Stadium in the
Bronx: Jake, my son; Eliza, my daughter, and I. My wife, for whom
sports events hold all the appeal of a sea voyage in steerage,
begged off.
</P>
<P>
   We were joined by friends, Tommy and his son, Clayton, who at 4
had been to half a dozen ball games and would serve, I decided, as
the essential peer influence should Jake weaken and decide it was
time to go. (``Leave now? Before hitting up the old man for an
autographed baseball complete with its own display stand? Sit.'')
</P>
<P>
   I took along 10 apple juice packs. I bought popcorn, fries,
chicken fingers, a big pretzel and a hot dog at the stadium. All
this before the first pitch. We arrived for the tail end of batting
practice, with no less a show than Darryl Strawberry driving tee
shots into the bleachers. What a moment, I thought, for a quick
lesson on the rudiments of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy tries to hit the ball with his bat, Jake,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   My son turned to me with wide and innocent eyes and replied:
``Daddy, look. The sky is light blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Pity the poor Upper West Side parent who can let no event pass
without the search for meaning. The first baseball game is no
exception. My son was, after all, already a veteran of two New York
Liberty games. (These events are made far more accessible to young
children by the halftime and time-out shows, including one with the
dog who catches 100 frisbees.) But baseball games are different, if
only because they come with history, communal and personal.
</P>
<P>
   A first game is a rite of sorts, a formal induction into the
world of fandom. At the risk of sounding a bit too much like George
Will (``Did you see how he lay down that sacrifice bunt, my child?
That is America at its best''), first games with our children
inevitably evoke memories of first games with our parents.
</P>
<P>
   I was 9 on the Saturday morning my father suggested that my
brother and I head out to the Polo Grounds and see the Mets. This
was 1962, and I believe the Dodgers beat them, 10 to 3. And, yes, I
remember the first view of the endless and dazzling green of the
outfield and how everything else around us felt very dark and old.
</P>
<P>
   Now on the way to the ball park, I asked my daughter, who is 8,
what she remembered about her first game. ``How hot it was in the
sun and how you told me not to get ice cream because it would melt
and that I should wait until we move to the shade,'' she said.
``How you were rude to those people when you asked if we could move
to closer seats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know I gave that usher $10 so we could sit in those
seats?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   I once asked Carl Erskine, my father's contemporary who pitched
for the great Brooklyn Dodger teams of the 1950s, what he
remembered about his first game.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled how he and his family got up early for the long
drive to Crosley Field in Cincinnati, how they arrived just as the
players were arriving, how the players arrived by taxi and how they
looked ``sharp'' in jackets and ties. His family arrived before the
big iron gate opened, he said, because his father always liked to
be early.
</P>
<P>
   There, at the center of this 60-year-old memory, was his father,
just as I can recall my own father, standing between us. I suspect
that we would all like to believe that our children will remember
us at moments such as these, even if that memory is about our being
too aggressive in finding better seats.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot imagine what my son will recall from his first game. I
suspect that it will have little to do with the game itself. By the
second inning, he and Clayton were playing with dinosaurs. Hint:
pack more toys than you think you can carry _ and talking role
models.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter joined in the grown-up chitchat, offering such
asides as: ``Babe Ruth? The fat guy?''
</P>
<P>
   We were still there in the third inning. And the fifth. And on
through ``Take Me Out to the Ball Game'' and the seventh-inning
stretch. Miracle of miracles. Then Jake decided we needed to eat.
The ice cream man was nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, at this point, had cut a three-run Kansas City lead
to one and were poised to tie. No matter. I searched the aisles,
knowing that an ice cream bar, consumed in our shady perch, could
take me to the bottom of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The final, crucial innings of a 3-year-old's first ball game
recall Jon Krakauer's description of the final push to the summit
of Mount Everest: it is no longer a matter of skill but of
endurance.
</P>
<P>
   And timing. The ice cream man appeared. I called to him, as if
screaming for oxygen. He saw me and offered one final challenge.
Not for this vendor the simple passing of high-priced snacks. No,
he had to throw. I signaled for four. The dad in front of us
offered his son's mitt. I liked my chances better barehanded.
</P>
<P>
   They came flying. Butterfingers that I am, I could not afford an
error. And like the great team playing before me, I committed none.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tied and went on to win. And as Mariano Rivera
punched out the final Kansas City batter, there sat Jake, having
gone the distance, a complete game first time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, ``was great.'' What ``that'' was, however,
was not clear. Still, he was happy, and that was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Or almost. With ritual comes the desire to believe that the
memory of the event will endure. So risking the worst sort of
sentimentality, I found myself imagining a conversation, 50 years
hence, between my daughter and son.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter asks her brother: ``Do you remember when Dad took us
to see the '98 Yankees? You remember, Tino, Cone and Derek Jeter?''
</P>
<P>
   My son, now middle-aged and trying to recall memories of an age
when recollections come only in bits and pieces, smiles and
replies, ``Wasn't that the time he had to catch all that ice
cream?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
