u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FEMINISTS-HNS     09-24 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FEMINISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMINIST ORGANIZATIONS COME TO CLINTON'S DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of prominent feminist organizations joined
forces Thursday to decry the role of President Clinton in the White
House sex scandal but to urge that he not be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``While women are angry and do not condone his conduct, women
want President Clinton to remain in office,'' 12 feminist
organizations declared in a joint statement. ``We believe, and the
women of this nation concur, that Mr. Clinton's actions are not
impeachable.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Ireland, the president of the National Organization for
Women, told a news conference that while she was offended by the
president's behavior, ``it does not rise to the level of
impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioneering feminist activist Betty Friedan joined in, saying:
``It does not serve women to try to hound this president out of
office on charges of sexual misdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I fear that we are on the brink of an era of sexual
McCarthyism.''
</P>
<P>
   The group _ which also includes Eleanor Smeal, president of the
Feminist Majority, Dolores Huerta, co-founder of the United Farm
Workers, and Yvonne Scruggs-Leftwich, executive director of the
Black Leadership Forum _ called on their supporters to press their
elected officials to oppose Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   The women said Clinton has done more for women's rights than any
modern president, despite his alleged crimes and admitted sexual
misdeeds with a young intern in his employ.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we allow this (impeachment) process to continue,'' said
Kathy Rodgers, the executive director of the NOW Legal Defense and
Education Fund, ``the interests of women in particular will be
buried in the muck for generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Smeal warned that the sex scandal threatens to depress female
voter turnout in the Nov. 3 off-year congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not allow our disgust or disillusionment to keep women
from the polls in November,'' Smeal said.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the spokeswomen expressed concern about three Senate
races in which the female incumbents _ Sens. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., and Patty Murray, D-Wash. _
face tough fights. The three were voted into the Senate in 1992,
which feminists dubbed the Year of Women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We risk not only losing the gains of the Year of Women in 1992
in the 1998 congressional elections, but we risk years of
reactionary control of both Houses of Congress and perhaps the
presidency itself,'' Smeal said.
</P>
<P>
   If the three women senators lost their seats and if the
Republican majority in the Senate increased from its current 55
seats, Clinton's veto power would be diminished because of the
greater likelihood that his political foes could muster the 66
votes needed to override.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's veto of a bill banning late-term abortions was
sustained by only three votes in the Senate last week.
</P>
<P>
   The feminist leaders said their show of support for Clinton was
not coordinated with the White House or with the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations that signed the joint statement of support
for Clinton were: the National Council of Negro Women; the National
Council of Women's Organizations; the National Asian Pacific Legal
Consortium; Black Women United for Action; Wider Opportunities for
Women; the Black Leadership Forum; and the Women's Institute for
Freedom of the Press.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee will vote in early October on
whether to recommend that the House authorize an impeachment
investigation against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Any such probe would be based on Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr's 445-page report that centers around Clinton's affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and alleges 11 possible
grounds for impeachment, including allegations of perjury,
obstruction of justice, witness tampering and abuse of power in an
effort to conceal the relationship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
