A2897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-RONIN-COX     09-24 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-RONIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ronin: A crackling action-suspense-thriller that's fun and
smart.
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title ``Ronin'' suggests an old Japanese monster movie.
``Ronin Meets Godzilla'' or ``Rodan vs. Ronin.''
</P>
<P>
   The name is Japanese, all right, but it refers to debased
heroes, not inflated monsters. The ronin were shamed Japanese
samurai who had failed to defend their liege. Now masterless, they
were fated to roam the countryside as mercenaries, hiring out their
talents to whomever could pay them.
</P>
<P>
   The ``ronin'' in John Frankenheimer's crackling action-suspense
film are modern-day warriors. Formerly employed by the CIA or the
KGB _ or whoever _ they too are masterless now that the Cold War is
over. And they too are for hire.
</P>
<P>
   A multinational team of specialists _ Robert De Niro, Jean Reno,
Stellan Skarsgard (``Good Will Hunting'') and Sean Bean _ are
brought together by a young Irish woman (Natascha McElhone) working
for a mysterious boss (Jonathan Pryce). Their assignment, complete
with a Hitchcockian twist, is to retrieve a suitcase that has
become the object of a deadly cat-and-mouse game between Irish
terrorists and the Russian mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer tosses in some other Hitchcock touches as well:
the glamorous locations (Paris, the French Riviera); the action
scene that takes place at a well-known French landmark (the ancient
arena at Arles); the cool, keep-your-eyes-open professionalism
that's lacking in so many of today's paper-thin action-suspensers.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the movie is pure Frankenheimer. As in his famous
``The Manchurian Candidate,'' there's an important scene about the
whereabouts of a hidden sniper. The ``Grand Prix'' master also
treats us to two car chases _ one through the narrow, twisting
roads in and around Nice, the other through the heart of Paris,
including several omigosh dives into the city's crowded underground
tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   David Mamet's script _ he did the rewrite under a pseudonym _ is
a canny match for Frankenheimer's bold, self-assured visual style.
Asked if he's ever killed anyone, De Niro's character shrugs and
says, ``I hurt somebody's feelings once.'' And there's even a
terse, not-dwelt-upon moral. Sure, these people are in it for the
money, but they're also in it for something more. Something that
has to do with honor. And pride.
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``Ronin'' is all over, you may realize that it
doesn't necessarily all add up and that we don't really know much
more about the characters than we did at the beginning. But a great
ride is a great ride. And that's what ``Ronin'' gives us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronin''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Robert De Niro and Jean Reno. Directed by John Franken-
</P>
<P>
   heimer. Rated R for language and violence. At metro theaters. 1
hour, 58 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Solid, smart and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
