<HEADER>
A2898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHANIA-COX     09-24 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHANIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Country sensation Shania Twain has jolted a genre while making a
big splash in pop mainstream
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody's got a bead drawn on Shania Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get the checklist.
</P>
<P>
   She's the woman who _ thanks to her affection for hip-huggers
and midriff-exposing tops _ introduced the bellybutton to country
music.
</P>
<P>
   And though she thought herself homely as a child, Twain's
fashion-runway poise and wholesome, shapely good looks marked the
arrival of ``centerfold country'' made popular by singers suspected
to have been former spokesmodels.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Canadian vocalist, who performs Saturday in
Atlanta on her first-ever tour, has been dubbed ``Country Spice''
by one tweaky rock critic, but her appeal is more than skin deep.
Record sales of more than 14 million speak to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems natural at the moment, but it's hard to emphasize how
revolutionary this was, even a couple of years ago,'' says Bruce
Feiler, author of ``Dreaming Out Loud: Garth Brooks, Wynonna Judd,
Wade Hayes and the Changing Face of Nashville'' (Avon). ``Earlier
in the decade, you had Wynonna, Reba McEntire, Mary Chapin
Carpenter, all big, strong women. But Shania has brought sass and
sex into a pretty slow-changing genre. What Garth did was define
the country male persona as a huggable cowboy in a hat. Shania has
defined the female persona as an edgy woman with attitude. In the
way that Garth signaled the rise of the hunk, Shania signaled the
rise of the country babe.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain, who was not available for an interview, is married to
longtime rock 'n' roll producer Robert John ``Mutt'' Lange, who
made his reputation with hit pop and hard-rock albums by the Cars,
Bryan Adams, Def Leppard and AC/DC. Because of her husband's
influence (he shares credit on all of her songs), the implication
has been that the albums the couple has collaborated on, ``The
Woman in Me'' and ``Come on Over'' (both Mercury), are thinly
disguised Def Leppard epics that have been genetically (pro-woman
themes) and generically (a nod or two to country conventions, like
fiddles and corny double-entendres) altered to fool the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicious minds want to know: Can she really sing?
</P>
<P>
   ``As it turns out, (Twain) has a perfectly serviceable, if
unremarkable voice,'' wrote free-lance critic John T. Davis in the
Austin American-Statesman after a recent concert. ``That, combined
with a formidable store of energy, an ironclad determination to
ingratiate herself with the audience and a pre-existing string of
country and pop radio and video hits, was all Twain needed to keep
the crowd on its feet through much of a show that weighed in at two
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as on her wildly successful videos, Twain in person
projected a sort of unthreatening, PG-rated sexuality that kept the
guys rapt without ever threatening the women who determine which
records sell best in today's country music marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't want romance, / We only wanna dance, / We're gonna let
our hair hang down,'' she sings on the party anthem ``Man! I Feel
Like a Woman!'' Elsewhere on ``Come on Over,'' Twain's third and
latest album, the singer asserts her post-feminist independence,
counseling a would-be swain that ``If You Wanna Touch Her, Ask!''
and, on ``Honey, I'm Home,'' enjoying some role reversal: ``Honey,
I'm home and I had a hard day. / Pour me a cold one and, oh, by the
way, / Rub my feet, gimme something to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of her success and the nature of it, however, Twain
has caused controversy. But it may simply be that she's been
misappreciated because she launched her career as a country singer
and then became bigger than the genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she a valid pop artist? Without a doubt,'' says Chris
Marino, the Nashville-based Americana editor for the radio trade
journal The Gavin Report. ``A lot of country stations resent that.
They fostered this woman's career, and she sort of leaves. But she
is what she is, and she's a pop star.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino, whose beat is the ever more populous crossroads where
country meets alternative rock, places Twain's stardom as part of a
larger trend: country artists unblinkingly accepted by mainstream
pop radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith Hill, she's crossing over,'' he says. ``There's a really
huge, concerted effort right now to make Alan Jackson a pop star.
But they're so huge that they can transcend all sorts of barriers.
If (songwriter) Keiran Kane sang `I'll Go on Loving You' (Jackson's
new hit), they wouldn't even listen to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Marino continues. ``Country music's having a
tough time. The ratings are dropping all across the nation. So in
order for these record companies to sell huge numbers, they have to
take it to pop radio.''
</P>
<P>
   To millions of listeners cruising around between suburbia and
the sticks, though, there's no argument. ``You're Still the One,''
Twain's current single, is pure pop, a lilting ode to domestic
fidelity that is country mostly because of its theme _ and the
audience whose ideals, worries and shopping patterns it reflects.
The singer, whose crossover dreams come true on VH-1 and onstage
with big-time pop divas like Mariah Carey and Celine Dion, may not
be hip enough for Lilith Fair, but she's got a stronger link to the
demographics. ``Shania doesn't know what's going on in rural
Alabama,'' says Feiler, ``but she has a keen pop cultural sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The satellite dish is as much an accessory in the South as the
barbecue pit,'' he continues. ``Shania came to town and was who she
was and the moment was right for her.''
</P>
<P>
   TWAIN TIDBITS
</P>
<P>
   -- Born: Eileen Regina Edwards in Windsor, Ontario, on Aug. 28,
1965.
</P>
<P>
   -- Married: To record producer Robert John ``Mutt'' Lange, 46,
six months after meeting him in June 1993.
</P>
<P>
   -- Albums: ``Shania Twain'' (1993), ``The Woman in Me'' (1995),
``Come on Over'' (1997).
</P>
<P>
   -- How she got her stage name: It's an Ojibwa Indian word for
``on my way.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Dramatic true-life story: When Twain's parents died in a car
crash in 1987, she took responsibility for her four younger
siblings.
</P>
<P>
   -- What she has in common with Bruce Springsteen: They share a
manager, Jon ``I have seen rock 'n' roll's future'' Landau.
</P>
<P>
   -- On the (belly)button: ``Everyone and their brother bares
their bellybutton once in a while,'' the singer told writer Bruce
Feiler. ``There's nothing obscene. If anything, it's freeing and
fun and quite clean.''
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THE CRITICS SAY
</P>
<P>
   -- Chicago Sun Times: ``Opening with `Man! I Feel Like a Woman,'
Shania Twain strutted center stage and didn't hesitate to show off
a voice of stunning limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Newsday: ``Music often seemed secondary at Twain's show. Her
songs are a Frankenstein's monster of pop, rock and country. ... It
was Twain's display of affection for the audience that ultimately
charged her show with enough energy to bring the crowd to its
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The New York Times: ``Onstage, Twain was as skillful as she
needs to be. (She) placed herself at the center of a spectacle with
smoke bombs, motorized platforms and perpetually smiley musicians.
It's not a flexible or spontaneous show.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Boston Herald: ``Twain could stand to let it rip more
often vocally.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Boston Globe: Twain showed her inexperience at times _
she sounds better in the studio than onstage at this point _ but
she surely can't be accused of a lack of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Minneapolis Star Tribune: Twain was certainly pleasant,
well-meaning, attractive, but somehow just not that captivating.
Fun at parties, maybe, but kind of boring, and fairly graceless
over time.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Los Angeles Times: ``Twain showed she could handle all the
notes with ease and that the beauty in the videos wasn't just built
around careful camera angles. ... (But) what we're left with is
someone who, like so many artists in the '90s, has tapped into the
commercial momentum of country music but done little to enrich
it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- USA Today: ``Twain isn't a terribly polished performer, but
her overwhelming earnestness and honesty count for something. In
winning over the packed house _ which cheered her as if she were
Streisand _ those were her main weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
