<HEADER>
A2901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN27-COX     09-24 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Surest sign of autumn: Muscadines
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My neighbor Mr. James Bagwell said his muscadines are a sight,
and if my children and I hurry we can get in a picking before
they're gone.
</P>
<P>
   I started to explain the conflicts I have _ and they are many _
but I remembered the late summers of my childhood, when the Myers
children from across the creek and I got rich picking scuppernongs.
Five cents a quart they paid us, and, of course, all we could eat.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bagwell, who is not only an experienced man of the soil but
a graduate of the University of Georgia ag school, undertook to
educate me.
</P>
<P>
   All these native grapes are muscadines. The golden ones got
named scuppernongs by some mishap, but they are still members of
the same dark purple family. Muscadines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullaces,'' I put in. ``We called them bullaces at home.''
</P>
<P>
   He said they're still called that in South Georgia, but,
changing the subject, if my young'uns and I want some, come pick.
It's the best late summer-early fall invitation we've had since Roy
Wyatt got hold of a cider press and invited us over to press
apples.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I am partial to scuppernongs. I like the name. Some
say it was borrowed from a river in North Carolina. And I love the
sweet, tawny fruit. We had two ancient arbors at home. Grandmother
Sibley said she picked scuppernongs when she was a little girl, and
that was many, many long years before the Myerses and I came along.
</P>
<P>
   They always earmarked some for wine, which was made by an old
recipe handed down to the males in the family for generations. When
they ran out of males, they gave the recipe to the family doctor. I
often wonder what he did with it.
</P>
<P>
   The wine, a glorious golden brew, was saved for Thanksgiving and
Christmas and other ceremonial occasions. I remember that my
father, who was a teetotaler, broke out a bottle when the Mobile
boy I had been bringing to the country broke down and asked my hand
in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   To go to the Bagwells' and pick muscadines will be a suitable
beginning of fall for me. I remember that when the Myers children
and I scrambled over the scuppernong arbor, the opening of school
was imminent and there was almost always a hurricane brewing in the
gulf. Reliable signs of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have unmistakable signs in fields and woods. Goldenrod is
holding carnival in old waste places. Sweet gum trees wear bangles
of gold among their green leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The black walnut tree in my back yard is dropping its fruit in
the grass, where the power mower will beat me and the children to
it.
</P>
<P>
   The persimmon has produced bountifully. I've picked up one or
two of what Euell Gibbons called ``sugar plums,'' but not enough to
make a loaf of bread or a pudding, both wonderful dishes beholden
to the persimmon tree.
</P>
<P>
   White panicles of bloom on the ash tree are turning bronze, and
the dogwoods are suddenly no longer summertime green but veering
toward yellow and scarlet.
</P>
<P>
   Even the bittersweet berries by the chimney are turning from
green to gold, and a few have gone on to break open and spill their
bright red seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Now we will have muscadines to confirm the fall. I wonder if I
can get Mrs. Virginia Callaway's recipe for muscadine pie again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
