<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANKENHEIMER-QandA-C     09-24 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKENHEIMER-QandA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `At the end of the day, that's what I am. A professional movie
director.'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 40-year career, John Frankenheimer has directed more than
150 television shows, as well as such classic films as ``The
Manchurian Candidate,'' ``Seven Days in May,'' ``Grand Prix,''
``Black Sunday'' and ``Birdman of Alcatraz.'' In this decade alone,
he's won four best director Emmys for his TV movies ``Against the
Wall,'' ``The Burning Season,'' ``Andersonville'' and, most
recently, ``George Wallace.''
</P>
<P>
   His new movie, ``Ronin,'' opens in theaters today. The title
refers to samurai who have lost their masters. Robert De Niro stars
as a former CIA agent who, now that the Cold War is over, has
become a gun for hire _ a ronin, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer, 68, recently spoke about his new movie and his
career from his home in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've won four Emmys in a row. Why leave television now and
return to features?
</P>
<P>
   A: I didn't want to go out of feature films with ``The Island of
Dr. Moreau'' as the last one I did. I'm better than that. I didn't
want everyone to say, ``He couldn't make it in features.'' I wanted
people to know I do TV because I want to, not because I have to. I
choose to do cable TV. It's not something I do just because I can't
play with the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why choose ``Ronin''?
</P>
<P>
   A: What I wanted to do on my next film was something that plays
into things I do well. I've always done that kind of serpentine,
things-aren't-what-they-appear-to-be material very well. Another
strong point for me were the car chases. In 1951, in my college
(Williams) yearbook, where it says things like ``most likely to
succeed,'' mine says ``highway menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is ``Ronin'' somehow a tribute to professionalism, to the
idea of doing your job regardless?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it is. I really identify with the concept of
``Ronin.'' Picture my lord and master as being CBS television. When
they cut us all loose in 1960, we went out and earned our living
doing what we do. Which was directing. We became ronin.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could it also be said that professionalism is what your
career has been all about?
</P>
<P>
   A: At the end of the day, that's what I am. A professional movie
director. My definition of the difference between an amateur and a
professional is, an amateur does something only when he or she
wants to do it. A professional does it when he or she doesn't want
to do it. There are days when I haven't wanted to be on set, but I
go. I'm an amateur cook. An amateur race-car driver. An amateur
tennis player. But I am a professional movie director.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you worried that audiences won't understand the title?
</P>
<P>
   A: The title was the original writer's idea and I liked it. We
came up with other titles that we didn't like. And one advantage is
that it stays the same throughout the world. ``The Manchurian
Candidate'' became ``Un Crime dans la Tete'' (``A Crime in the
Head'') in France. So mention ``Manchurian Candidate'' in Paris,
and they don't know what you're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I think it's up to the MGM marketing department to
explain the title through ads and TV spots. That way people won't
think they're going to see a picture where De Niro plays a guy
named Ronin.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You once told me that director Henry Hathaway came on your
first movie set and warned you that making one compromise a day
meant that, over 25 days, you'd made 25 compromises. Did you make
any compromises here?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not a one. Though maybe I'll look at something five years
from now and say that was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you remember the first time you saw or heard the phrase
``veteran director John Frankenheimer?''
</P>
<P>
   A: (Laughs.) I think it was about eight years ago. I hate the
term, but you just get over it. In the '50s, I was ``young
director.'' Then there was a window where I was just ``director.''
Then it's ``veteran.'' But that beats the alternative, which is
``former.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Any feelings about George Wallace dying the same night as the
Emmy Awards?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was really ironic. Almost eerie. We didn't know until
after we'd won and were at dinner. But I remember he told me, ``I
hope I live long enough to see it,'' and I said, ``I hope so too,
and I hope you like it.'' As it turned out, he loved it. He ran it
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You made ``Andersonville'' in Georgia, just outside Newnan.
Any impressions of Georgia or Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A: Happy impressions. I loved shooting there. I loved the crew.
I loved where we lived. I loved Atlanta. I'm not just saying this
because I'm talking to an Atlanta newspaper, but if I didn't live
in Southern California, Atlanta is the only other place in the
States I might want to live. I love the climate. I love that they
play so much tennis. It doesn't have the intense claustrophobic
pressure that you find in New York or Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   There's a chance I'll be back next spring to shoot ``The Good
Shepherd.'' It's the best script I've ever read. By Eric Roth, the
guy who wrote ``Forrest Gump.'' It's the story of the first 20
years of the CIA, told through a family. Sort of a ``Godfather''
movie about the CIA. It takes place all along the East Coast, so
maybe we'll do something in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You had a close relationship with Bobby Kennedy. Have you
ever considered making a movie about him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but I haven't really got a handle on how to do it.
There've been so many good documentaries. There's so much film of
him available. What I'd like to do would be from JFK's death
through Bobby's death. That's the period that interests me. I saw
this man change before my eyes. I saw him become great. And that's
so hard to dramatize. Greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In 1991 you listed Martin Scorsese, Mike Nichols, Peter Weir
and, especially, Francis Ford Coppola as directors you admire. Any
new names?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'd have to add Anthony Minghella (``The English Patient'').
And James Cameron. Such an impressive job he did on ``Titanic.''
And Curtis Hanson (``L.A. Confidential''). I'm crazy about him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is ``The Iceman Cometh'' still your favorite of your films?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think so. I may be too close to it, but now ``George
Wallace'' is. And there are those who think ``Against the Wall'' is
the best thing I ever did.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's next?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm about to sign a long-term exclusive arrangement with TNT.
We're going to do a lot of stuff that I'm very excited about.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You once said that Fred Zinneman (the director of ``High
Noon,'' among other films) said that 65 to 75 were his best years.
How are they working out for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: So far, he's been right. So far, it's been a hell of a ride.
And I've got seven more years to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
