<HEADER>
A2903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-FIRELIGHT-COX     09-24 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FIRELIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome sparks illuminate `Firelight'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Firelight'' could use a little more fire and a lot lighter
touch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this thoughtful period drama from writer-turned-director
William Nicholson (``Shadowlands'') has some very good things to
offer: a solid dramatic core, a half-dozen intriguing characters,
serious themes, passionate romance and a beautifully effective
evocation of the Victorian world of the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   In a delicately mysterious prologue, a lovely young woman named
Elisabeth (Sophie Marceau) is undergoing an odd interrogation. An
older woman asks her questions fed to her by an unseen male behind
a screen. He wants to know her background (Swiss), her education
(drawing, French) and why she needs the money (to pay her father's
debts). An agreement is reached. Elisabeth will act as a surrogate
mother, bearing the anonymous man a child and handing it over,
along with any future claims on it. But during the three days the
two spend together, conducting their ``business,'' it slowly
becomes clear that both are more affected by their business partner
than either expected.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to seven years later. The child, a willful, sad brat named
Louisa (Dominique Belcourt), has the run of the baronial English
country house she shares with her doting father, Charles (Stephen
Dillane of ``Welcome to Sarajevo'').
</P>
<P>
   On a more obvious level, ``Firelight'' is a spin on the ``Jane
Eyre'' genre of Gothic romance. We have the handsome, imperious
master; the sensitive, loving servant; the inconvenient wife. But
the movie is actually about a different kind of bond, one between
parent and child.
</P>
<P>
   Charles' father (Joss Ackland, looking as if he stepped out of
``The Pickwick Papers'') is a party-loving spendthrift who neither
understands his responsible son nor cares to admit that he's
running through what's left of the family money.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there's Louisa and Elisabeth, the rebellious,
lonely child who so badly needs a mother and the reserved, loving
mother who cannot make herself known. Their battle of wills calls
to mind Anne Bancroft and Patty Duke in ``The Miracle Worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson is far too fond of swelling music and portentous looks
that slow the movie's pace. And a dollop of feminist wisdom blurted
out by Elisabeth to her charge is nice to hear but jarringly
anachronistic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on the whole, ``Firelight'' burns with intelligence,
craft and psychological resonance. It's a movie that respects both
its characters and its audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firelight''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sophie Marceau and Stephen Dillane. Directed by William
Nicholson. Rated R for brief sex and nudity. 1 hour, 44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Smolders rather than burns, but romantics won't
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
