<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PECKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More dumb jokes, keen satire from John Waters
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea of John Waters is always better than his movies.
Whether mocking mainstream films or lecturing about the subversive
joys of camp, he's an ideal fly in Hollywood's ointment. But while
his buoyant ``Hairspray'' (1988) suggested that he had finally
fused his outsider's viewpoint with a slick filmmaking savvy, his
subsequent flicks have been as doggedly second-rate as the
Baltimore thrift stores he adores.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about ``Pecker'' is the title, with that
schoolboy giggle built into it. (You know Waters picked it just
from imagining people saying it aloud at the box office.)
</P>
<P>
   Pecker is the nickname of a cheerful kid (Edward Furlong) who
earned the moniker from being a slight eater. A better name would
be Clicker, because he skips around Baltimore shooting grainy
photographs of real life: rats mating in a trash can, a woman
shaving her legs on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   His mother (Mary Kay Place) takes a look at his verite prints
and sighs, ``If only you could concentrate on pretty scenery or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The joke is that a New York art dealer (Lili Taylor) stumbles
onto Pecker's stuff and whisks him to Manhattan to be the next big
thing. Success unsettles his working-class family, alienates his
best pal, Matt (Brendan Sexton III), and makes his girlfriend,
Shelley (Christina Ricci), feel insecure about her life as a
laundry manager.
</P>
<P>
   This no-place-like-home plot line is merged with a mild parody
of the New York art scene, which comes about 10 years too late to
have any edge. Celebrity photographers Cindy Sherman and Greg
Gorman even show up as themselves, since the satire remains so
tame. Waters has also watered down his famed shock value, though he
goes for titters with jokes about pubic hair, drag kings and a
strip-club ritual called ``teabagging.''
</P>
<P>
   A few jokes come through on the strength of characterization.
Raucous Martha Plimpton struts around in a hot-curlered fright wig,
playing Pecker's sister, who works as the emcee in a gay strip
club. This doesn't sit well with her Catholic grandmother, who has
converted her Virgin Mary statue into a ventriloquist's dummy.
Another good running gag: Pecker's sister Little Chrissy (Lauren
Hulsey) is a pint-size demon fueled entirely by sugar products.
</P>
<P>
   Furlong is an amiable lead. But Ricci, so adept at humanizing
extreme roles (``The Opposite of Sex,'' ``Buffalo 66''), can't get
a handle on playing a simple girl who doesn't get this whole
``art'' thing. She comes off as stiff as some of the
``personalities'' that populate Waters' movies (Mink Stole and
Patricia Hearst make their obligatory cameos).
</P>
<P>
   But what can you expect? It's a John Waters movie. Like him or
lump him, he's unique. Besides, aesthetically, he's made himself
unassailable: How can you complain that he's in poor taste, or a
sloppy filmmaker, when he's turned those things into his signature?
</P>
<P>
   At the end of ``Pecker,'' someone offers a toast to ``the end of
irony.'' The moment rings false. That's because Waters' conflicted
mix of dumb jokes and keen satire, of the beer-hall gritty and the
fairy-tale fabulous, is in its way as self-conscious as the most
pretentious, unreal art you could hope to find in a New York
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pecker''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Edward Furlong and Christina Ricci. Written and
directed by John Waters. Rated R for profanity and sexual humor.
One hour, 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Another missed opportunity from the Baltimore
director who isn't Barry Levinson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
