A2905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SOLIDER-COX     09-24 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SOLIDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Soldier's Daughter' a subtle study of family
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Ivory's family study, ``A Soldier's Daughter Never
Cries,'' is as piecemeal as it is perceptive. It's more like
vignettes from a personal diary than a cohesive, linear film. But
what it lacks in narrative it makes up for in character and
emotional nuance.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is based on Kaylie Jones' semi-autobiographical
novel about growing up with a famous novelist father in the 1960s
and '70s. The famous dad in question was James Jones, best known
for ``From Here to Eternity'' and ``The Thin Red Line,'' both set
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the title. But as the main character, here called Channe,
says in a tearful tete-a-tete with her hospitalized father (Kris
Kristofferson), he's always told her that a soldier's daughter
never cries. But she's not a soldier's daughter, she protests;
she's a writer's daughter. Kristofferson takes a small pause, then
says, ``That's OK then. They cry all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Exquisite little moments like these give ``A Soldier's
Daughter'' its distinctive flavor. The movie is Channe's memoir
divided into three short stories, each focusing on someone
important in her life. The first, ``Billy,'' introduces us to
Channe's family, the Willises, living in Paris in the 1960s while
Dad works on a book. Mom (an excellent Barbara Hershey) loves their
glamorous expatriate life _ cocktail parties, poker games, visiting
intelligentsia, etc. So does their little daughter, Channe (Luisa
Conlon). But then they adopt a young French boy named Benoit
(Samuel Gruen). How he adapts to his new family _ and vice versa _
has the unforced charm of a Truffaut film about childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The second section, ``Francis,'' takes us into Channe's (LeeLee
Sobieski) teenage years. Still in school in Paris, her best friend
is Francis (Anthony Roth Costnazo), a flamboyant, sensitive,
self-dramatizing, opera-loving outcast. Channe is devoted to him,
even though she thinks he ``acts like a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third section, ``Daddy,'' the family returns to the
States and finds an America very different from the one they left.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's scattered approach may be off-putting for some.
There's no main relationship or story line to grab onto, just a
series of events, large and small, centering on this one family
which, compared with most movie families, is generally happy,
loving and pretty close to normal. The relationship between
Kristofferson and Sobieski stands out, simply because it's more
affecting and clear-cut by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   What counts here is the quiet accumulation of detail. We see how
the tapestry of memory is woven out of people and incidents that
may not, on an objective scale, deserve equal impact in our lives.
Ivory shows us how someone relatively minor _ say, a kid you knew
for one semester in junior high _ can have a place alongside
someone as important as your mother or father. The same might be
said of this thoughtful, imperfect movie. It's likely to stay with
you after showier, more immediately satisfying films have faded
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kris Kristofferson, Barbara Hershey and LeeLee
Sobieski. Directed by James Ivory. Rated R for language and sexual
situations. 2 hours, 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An imperfect but compelling coming-of-age diary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
