</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-URBAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Legend' a far-fetched fright fest
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the 1980s, we had Andrew McCarthy, Ally Sheedy, Rob Lowe
_ the Brat Pack. Now we've got the Splat Pack.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently it's illegal to make a Hollywood horror flick without
a cast member from ``Dawson's Creek'' or ``Party of Five.'' In
``Urban Legend,'' the ``Creek''-ster is Joshua Jackson, playing
Damon, a bleach-blond student at picturesque Pendleton College. In
case we miss the connection, at one point a car radio blasts the
``Dawson's Creek'' theme song.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a joke about Noxzema, because spokesmodel Rebecca
Gayheart plays another student, Brenda. Oh, and one last bit of
slasher-flick self-consciousness: The movie mimics the opening of
``Scream'' by offing a student played (like Drew Barrymore) by a
starlet from a famous acting family.
</P>
<P>
   The postmodern games don't get in the way of some OK suspense
and a clever concept: What if a serial killer decided to off
students by imitating urban legends? You know the ones. The baby
sitter and the goon calling from an upstairs phone. The gang
members driving without headlights, ready to kill the first driver
who flashes them. The dog/cat/baby in the microwave. And, of
course, the various awful things that can happen to couples parked
in Lovers' Lane.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks seem to center on Natalie (Alicia Witt, TV's
``Cybill''), who naturally has a dark secret in her past. Jared
Leto plays Paul, a dreamboat student whom Brenda also likes. The
older cast includes ex-Freddy Krueger Robert Englund as a professor
specializing in urban legends, John Neville as the dean and Loretta
Devine as a security guard who watches old Pam Grier movies for
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urban Legend'' is slickly made, amusingly played, instantly
forgettable. It mixes and matches plot devices and tricks from the
``Scream'' flicks and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer.'' While
it's scarier than ``Disturbing Behavior,'' director Jamie Blanks
leans on the tired trick of having people jump into the frame for
cheap shock value. You may wonder how a school with an enrollment
in the thousands seems to have only 20 students by its storm-tossed
ending. And honestly, would even the craziest killer ambush
somebody from the back seat of a car and ax the driver's head while
the car is zooming along at full speed?
</P>
<P>
   That's not scary, that's suicidal. And silly. But if you're
willing to suspend a huge amount of disbelief _ well, that's what
urban legends are about, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Urban Legend''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Alicia Witt, Jared Leto. Directed by Jamie Blanks.
Rated R for gore, profanity and attempts to make a dog drunk. 1
hour, 39 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Some laughs, some scares, nothing special.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
