A2908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEA-COX     09-24 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEA-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing tea is in the bag for owners of `plantation'
</P>
<P>
   (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
</P>
<P>
   By Celine Bufkin
</P>
<P>
   WADMALAW ISLAND, S.C.Mack Fleming greets his visitors with an
easy laugh and a little self-deprecating humor. There are hundreds
of them, pilgrims to his humble farm about 18 miles southeast of
Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   They come on the first Saturday of the month, April through
October, to learn about tea firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's only tea plantation,'' though a potentially
impressive claim, is no big, slick corporate operation. Calling the
127-acre plot a plantation might be stretching it a bit, even.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a farm,'' says Sarah Fleming, Mack's daughter, the CEO
(``chief executive offspring'') who works public relations and
tours and runs the company's mail-order business. With her two dogs
in tow, she shows up at the office on a busy Friday, preparing for
the Charleston Tea Plantation's monthly tour. The next day, more
than 600 people will take advantage of the free history lesson and
iced beverages and, she hopes, take home lots of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The Charleston Tea Plantation actually began in the early 1960s
as an experiment by the Lipton Tea Co. Tea wasn't grown in the
United States at all, but political and trade situations overseas _
particularly in China _ had threatened to stifle the tea supply
coming into the country. So Lipton acquired centuries-old tea
plants from China and Argentina and started working on making them
grow in the Carolina Lowcountry.
</P>
<P>
   Mack Fleming, a native South Carolinian and horticulturist with
two degrees from Clemson University, started with the Lipton
experiment in 1963 and became director of research in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   When trade with China reopened in 1972, Lipton lost interest in
its little project, says Fleming. So he and an acquaintance,
third-generation tea taster William Barclay (Bill) Hall, bought the
property from Lipton and started their own company, the Charleston
Tea Plantation.
</P>
<P>
   The two men have been compared often but mostly contrasted:
Fleming is the Southern gentleman, locally trained horticulturist,
neatly dressed and well-trimmed. Hall has wild, long hair and wears
nifty little spectacles. His accent is still primarily Canadian,
but long stays in England, Argentina and the United States have
rounded it out. Until recently, he lived on a boat in Charleston;
now he stays on the farm as a sort of self-described hermit.
</P>
<P>
   For Fleming, the key to the whole thing is the plants.
</P>
<P>
   The rows and rows of them look like the camellia bushes growing
in your own yard. Botanically speaking, the tea is camellia
sinensis, and these bushes comprise more than 300 numbered clones
from tea plants roughly 200 years old. Their genetic material has
been coddled and preened, encouraged to thrive in the particular
elevation and climate of its home here in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   As horticulturist and chief electrician, Fleming makes the tea
grow and gets it into production. He determines harvest days (about
twice a month from April to October), makes sure his 3-year-old,
computer-assisted underground irrigation system is working properly
and takes care of propagation.
</P>
<P>
   For Hall, who spent a four-year apprenticeship in England _
tasting between 800 and 1,000 cups of tea every day to be able to
determine what country, region and plantation each came from _ it's
all about freshness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea does not improve with age,'' says Hall. ``One of our
advantages is the tea gets from the field to the shelves in about a
month,'' as opposed to six months or more with most foreign teas.
Tea ordered through the plantation's mail-order company might be
only a week old, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over the plantation, Fleming and Hall have been
trying to get their home-grown tea varieties _ sold under the
American Classic Tea brand _ in grocery stores and pantries across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, American Classic Tea has been available in South
Carolina and most of North Carolina, and in Wal-Mart stores under
the Sam's Choice brand. The men recently sealed a deal with Publix
to carry the brand in Georgia; it's already at Harris Teeter and
Bi-Lo, plus specialty and gourmet stores.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   The Charleston Tea Plantation's last tour of the season is
October 3, every half-hour beginning at 10 a.m. with the last tour
at 1:30 p.m. Free. For information and mail orders, call
1-800-443-5987.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
