<HEADER>
A2909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUCKER-QandA-COX     09-24 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUCKER-QandA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comedian proclaims `I'm having fun' with new baby, movie, album,
and nightclub
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_The comedian, once described as so hyperactive that he
could make caffeine nervous, must have had something slipped into
his soda.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Tucker is still. And so quiet that you have to lean in to
hear him. That means he isn't speaking in the signature
high-pitched twang that broadcasts his Southern origins (Decatur,
Georgia). And he is not, at least at this moment, the motor-mouth
who made memorable appearances in the movies ``Dead Presidents,''
``The Fifth Element,'' ``Friday'' and ``Money Talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because the 26-year-old co-star of ``Rush Hour,'' now
in movie theaters and doing well at the box office, had his first
child two days earlier. And, as he says, he's feeling ``really
spiritual and just kind of blessed right now.'' Or is it that he's
been doing the promotional thing since stepping off the red-eye
flight from Los Angeles around 5 a.m.?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this may well be a glimpse of the ``feeling, magical,
`Forrest Gump' or `Color Purple' kind of role'' Tucker says he
wants to play.
</P>
<P>
   At the Chris Tucker Comedy Cafe in Midtown's Rio Mall, which he
plans to open in time for Laffapalooza, an urban arts festival
taking place Oct. 1-4, the comedian explains himself.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You seem really relaxed. Is this Chris Tucker unplugged?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, I'm just kind of taking this all in. I'm having fun. In
fact, I'm kind of surprised at how everything is coming together
with the club and the movie and everything. I'm screaming on the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What made you decide to open a club here?
</P>
<P>
   A: I decided like a year or two years ago that I needed a place
to work out when I came home. And then I wanted a place where the
kids could come. If a kid has a dream to be whatever he wants to
be, play the piano or do comedy or sing, this will be a place to
come and show off that talent. So we'll have a night for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You got your start a bit differently, though.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, I started doing comedy in talent shows at Columbia High
School(Ga.). I think I was like in the eighth grade. And when I
performed and got my first big roar, that's when I realized that
that's what I wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Before that realization, what were you thinking you wanted to
be?
</P>
<P>
   A: I didn't know what I was going to do. I knew I wasn't going
(in the) Army or Marines because that just wasn't me. And I didn't
know about college because I didn't even like high school. So I'm
just glad that I found out what I wanted to do early in my life.
And it's worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're co-starring in a big movie with Jackie Chan. And I've
read you're getting $7 million for this secret agent movie you
wrote that pop singer Mariah Carey will be in. What's happening
with ``OO-Soul''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it's in pre-production. So if that comes together,
we'll start filming it. But I have a lot of other projects in the
works, too. I have my stand-up comedy movie coming out. I'm getting
ready to shoot it. And we're going to release that in theaters
probably around Christmastime or the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Anything else?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've got a comedy album coming out. We're going to do a
soundtrack with the release of the stand-up movie. And there are
other movies I'm looking at, other roles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the new role you just took on: daddy?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, I just had my first baby boy. He was born on a Sunday,
so he's a blessed baby. We (he and his girlfriend of two years)
still haven't decided on a name. It might be Chris, Christian, we
don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There must be a lot going on in your head right now. Your
first child's in L.A., and you're here.
</P>
<P>
   A: All I'm really thinking is how much of a blessing he is,
because I see his birth as an opportunity to be better. When you
have a child, you have to be better than you were before they came.
You have to work even harder at not making mistakes, because you're
trying to teach him. So I think this is going to mature me and make
me a better person. Broaden my horizons personally and
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Not to be disrespectful, but don't you think you've been
basically playing Chris Tucker _ or at least who the public knows
as Chris Tucker _ in all your movies?
</P>
<P>
   A: I do. I do. I mean ... I play me. My main movies have been
``Friday'' and ``Money Talks.'' And ``Rush Hour,'' I think it's one
of the best movies I've done. And now I want to just keep venturing
out. I want to do dramas, something like ``Color Purple.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have to admit, though, Chris Tucker in ``The Color
Purple'' sounds like a comedy sketch.
</P>
<P>
   A: Let somebody laugh at me doing my serious role, and I'll
smack them upside the head.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Tucker has finally entered the building.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
