<HEADER>
A2910 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-BIGGIRLS-COX     09-24 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BIGGIRLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biting side of feminism revealed
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lack of imagination is not Fay Weldon's problem in her
hilarious, caustic novel about the British women's rights movement
in the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, several feminists hold a consciousness-raising session
in London. While one, Daffy, has sex with Stephanie's husband
upstairs, the others decide to start the feminist Medusa Press. So
liberated do they feel that they strip and dance until Zoe's
husband arrives and demands that she dress and bring their toddler,
Saffron, back home. Zoe succumbs to his chauvinist pigotry, but the
others bring Medusa to life.
</P>
<P>
   What a group they are: the heady Alice; the seductive and
wealthy Layla; Stephanie, who leaves her kids to be raised by
Daffy; and the sensible Nancy, who runs the office at a pittance of
a salary. Medusa thrives with the times, while the characters'
personal lives proceed in ironic fits and starts.
</P>
<P>
   When Zoe kills herself, it sets off a chain reaction that will
ultimately threaten Medusa. Saffron learns a harsher feminism and
grows up to become a mainstream publishing shark with the looks of
Ally McBeal and the instincts of a press baron. Weldon humorously
contrasts the difference between feminist generations but remains
sympathetic, if clear-eyed, in her characterizations.
</P>
<P>
   -- Big Girls Don't Cry. By Fay Weldon. Atlantic Monthly. $24.
346 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
