</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-WARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Explosive saxophonist takes jazz improv to new heights
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Branford Marsalis was at a jazz festival in France three years
ago when something caught his ear. It was a version of the standard
``Yesterdays,'' but the musician playing it wasn't making any nods
toward convention. ``He was going out,'' the saxophonist and former
``Tonight Show'' band leader recalls, ``but I could hear the
melody, dude. I thought, `Wow! This is the (stuff) I like.'''
</P>
<P>
   When he went to investigate, Marsalis came face to face with
David S. Ware, a tenor saxophonist who, more so than most of his
peers, has doggedly adhered to a strong, specific vision of what
jazz improvisation needs to be: raucous at times, big-shouldered,
ecstatic, yet laced with intricate details that require high levels
of musicianship and a buzzing psychic hotline between band members.
That Ware was, at the time, releasing albums on a record label
better known for its catalog of punk-rock titles didn't faze
Marsalis. Neither did the volatility of the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hear the tradition in his playing,'' says Marsalis,
who, as a new creative consultant to Columbia Records jazz
department made Ware the first artist he signed to the label.
``There's a parallel to classical music. People say they love
classical music, but they don't know Shostakovich. It's about
advanced melody. It's in the tradition and extends it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the public has a chance to investigate that thesis. ``Go See
the World,'' Ware's domestic major-label debut after a dozen prior
albums, hit record shelves last week. The New Jersey native, 48, a
former Manhattan cabdriver and teen protege of saxophone colossus
Sonny Rollins, is touring behind the disc. His quartet performs
Monday in Atlanta, at the First Existentialist Congregation in
Candler Park.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ware's live performances, the album aspires to be
mind-blowingly audacious, and is, partly because the musicians
never shirk the risks necessary to reach their goal. Given to
graceful interludes that can swiftly churn into galvanizing
exchanges of high-energy invention, the group is fluid enough to
briskly adapt to variations in Ware's gale-force gusts, yet remains
rooted in a mutual, fundamental grasp of structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We speak the same language, we're using the same alphabet,''
Ware says. ``We're able to balance our abstractions with our more
solid sense of melody and harmony. It's the girth of their
vocabulary, man. They have that ability to listen and hear, and
make the correct choices in any given situation. That's what talent
does, natural talent is capable of that.''
</P>
<P>
   An ideal example of the musician's thinking is his new album's
centerpiece, a 16-minute version of ``The Way We Were,'' which
redeems Marvin Hamlisch's treacly ballad _ a 1974 hit for Barbra
Streisand _ as an improvisational epic. It partakes of the
venerable jazz tradition of turning popular song into the raw
material of complex, melodic exploration. Ware takes two full
minutes before he introduces that melody. He teases it out as a
series of distinct fragments. Robust soul shouts, piercing cries,
roadhouse swagger, the spontaneous lyricism of birdsong, a fleet
sequence of notes that rushes by like the blurred glimpse of a
subway train: It's all there. Halfway through, pianist Matthew
Shipp recasts the theme on piano, taking it straight before a
brief, frenetic deconstruction _ Godzilla meets Bambi _ which leads
back to the original line. At various points, the rainbow flurry
that drummer Susie Ibarra conjures on the trap set _ a reflection
of her training in such Indonesian percussive traditions as gamelan
and kulintang _ and the eerie, theremin-like effect of bassist
William Parker's bowing create an unusual range of harmonic
textures.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's the kind of person, like Cecil Taylor or Sonny
Rollins, that does not need a band,'' says Parker, 47, who first
met the saxophonist in 1973. ``If you take away their band, you can
just listen to them. Whenever you play with people who don't need a
band, it's a particular challenge as to what to do. There has to be
a reason for you to be up there playing.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Parker notes, ``the quartet is definitely a family,''
and its collective strengths mark it as formidable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
