A2914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERTSHAW-COX     09-24 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTSHAW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shaw strikes up band for Boston's ailing Ozawa
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somebody get Robert Shaw a Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Just four days after wrapping up the National Symphony
Orchestra's Beethoven Festival in Washington, Atlanta's senior
maestro had to hail a jet to Boston on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Symphony Orchestra conductor Seiji Ozawa, who was
suffering from a viral infection he caught in Russia, had dropped
out of his season opener at the last minute. Still a wunderkind at
82, Shaw hopped a plane, went straight to the hall and conducted
without a rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the fun and games part, to see if we could start and
finish together,'' said the chuckling maestro, calling from the
Boston airport Thursday before returning to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it, it was Ozawa's 25th anniversary concert,
and the gala dinner had sold about $500,000 in tickets. ``To say we
were fortunate is an understatement,'' said Boston Symphony
managing director Mark Volpe. ``I'm not sure there is another
conductor who would have conducted the Beethoven Ninth with no
rehearsal.''
</P>
<P>
   Pshaw. It was a piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   In his review Thursday, Boston Globe classical music critic
Richard Dyer hailed Shaw as ``the godfather of American choral
singing'' and rhapsodized: ``Shaw's professional experience with
the Beethoven Ninth now exceeds half a century; his view is
spacious, lucid, humane, and surpassingly humble; he does not
impose himself on the work, but instead tries to share all the
qualities his experience has found in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said his rendering would have been a lot less nuanced if
United Parcel Service hadn't been able to track down the musicians'
orchestral markings, which were headed to Atlanta from Washington.
The parcel service got the music to Shaw about an hour before he
left Atlanta. He arrived in Boston around 4 p.m., warmed up his
four soloists and made the 6:30 p.m. curtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a buzz by the fourth movement,'' Volpe said. ``You
could feel the excitement building. He was in great form. He was
certainly appreciated by all in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
