<P>
   GEORGES STORIES THAT HAVE ALREAY MOVED . . .
</P>
<P>
   PORT-PALMBEACH _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ The Port of Palm Beach
will be the only major port in South Florida to remain open as
federal authorities shut down the Port of Miami and Port Everglades
as a Hurricane Georges-related precaution. (Utley, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-DINING _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If the storm rolls in,
how will John Alfeo tell? His Hurricane Grill restaurant on 25th
Street has the decor of a full-force gale. There's a storm tracking
chart by the cash register, but it shows Andrew's path. Hurricane
Georges is nothing but a special on the menu. Spinach salad with
grilled chicken, bacon and balsamic vinaigrette. (Anna, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-PREPARATION _ Karen Jacobs didn't panic in August 1992
when Hurricane Andrew built up a running start in the Atlantic
Ocean. ``What's the worst, you know, the AC could go off?'' She had
said. The air conditioning did go off. So did part of the roof and
one wall. That's why Jacobs was covering windows to prepare for
Hurricane Georges. But oddly, only the windows on the east side.
Jacobs partial reaction typefies, under one rebuilt roof, the two
currents of thought in Country Walk. (Trontz, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-PROTECTION _ Eleven-dollar pieces of plywood gained new
value as local residents competed with Broward, Miami-Dade and
Monroe county residents to buy storm supplies. But most Palm Beach
County and Treasure Coast residents remained calm, figuring the
brunt of Hurricane Georges wouldn't come this far north. (Bierman,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-INSURANCE _ Like most major insurance carriers, State Farm
Fire and Casualty stops writing new home and auto policies when a
hurricane watch has been posted. State Farm wasn't alone. If you
live in an area where you think you might need insurance within a
few days, you probably can't get it. Most companies stopped writing
new policies in South Florida by September 23. (Murawski, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ Clinton meets with Congressional Black Caucus this
morning. Checking out what Lewis, McKinney and Bishop have to say
afterwards. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ Challenging Congress to ``think of the
American people,'' President Clinton appeared in the Rose Garden on
Thursday to press for a long list of legislation that he said was
being neglected in the midst of impeachment deliberations. (Deans,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAPES _ WASHINGTON _ In what could bring a reprise of
the partisan furor over President Clinton's videotaped testimony,
the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee said Thursday the
panel may release edited transcripts _ but not the original tapes _
of Monica Lewinsky's phone conversations with Linda Tripp. Members
cite reasons ranging from the fact that the tapes show signs of
tampering to suspicions that their tone will make Americans more
sympathetic to Clinton. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS _ House Judiciary Committee continues to work
on what else to release of the boxes of Starr evidence. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INCOME _ WASHINGTON _ Poverty rates and household incomes have
returned to 1989 pre-recession levels, the result of a strong
national economy, especially in the South and the West, that has
helped to lift millions of African Americans and Hispanics out of
poverty, according to Census Bureau reports released Thursday.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-STUDENTS _ WASHINGTON _ The United States may be losing
its edge in attracting the brightest foreign students to study here
instead of at other universities abroad, experts said Thursday at a
meeting co-sponsored by the Educational Testing Service and the
U.S. Information Agency. (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-DATA _ Material for a map on where the most popular U.S.
campuses for foreign students.
</P>
<P>
   SMOG _ WASHINGTON _ EPA Administrator Carol Browner is to
announce a new rule Thursday aimed at dealing with
``cross-boundary'' smog problems in which power plants in the South
and Midwest have been charged with creating smog problems in other
regions. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MILMED _ Surgeons general of Army, Navy and Air Force discuss
military medical shortfall and its impacts in hearing before House
subcommittee members. Hearing was called after committee members
happened upon e-mail messages from an Army commander complaining
about the shortfall. (Nesmith, Cox Nedws Service).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ The House is expected to approve more
visas for highly skilled foreign workers Thursday, admitting up to
337,500 foreign workers over the next three years, instead of the
195,000 that would be allowed under current law. President Clinton,
whose economic advisers helped write this plan, is expected to sign
the legislation, in part because it will create scholarships and
job training for U.S. workers.(Harlan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CONSUMERS _ WASHINGTON _ Two House subcommittees hold a 2
p.m. EDT hearing on what every consumer should know about the year
2000 computer problem. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-GOETZ _ WASHINGTON _ For the estate of Nelda G. Goetz, the
Internal Revenue Service is seeing the forest but not the trees.
The estate of the San Augustine, Texas, woman filed a petition with
the U.S. Tax Court here claiming the IRS valued her 1,252 acres of
wooded lands at more than four times their worth. The IRS demanded
the estate pay $706,334 in additional taxes and civil tax fraud
penalties. (Moskal, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   UNTURNER _ Turner UN Foundation announces it second round of
grants to programs around the world. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CARTER _ Former President Jimmy Carter has annual town hall
meeting Thursday at the Carter Center. (Kurylo, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-TRIAL _ ATLANTA _ The jury is out in the trial of two
Lithonia, Ga., businessmen who are accused of a Medicaid scam that
netted $9.5 million. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
TENTATIVE.
</P>
<P>
   NEIMAN-TRIAL _ ATLANTA _ Expecting verdict in lawsuit of Neiman
Marcus customer who claims she was wrongly strip-searched. (Rankin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SMOG _ U.S. EPA is set today to implement tougher regulations on
nitrogen oxide emissions in 22 states including Ohio. Old,
coal-fired power plants are the chief culprit. Environmental
officials say the regulations, which will require cuts in Nox
levels up to 45 percent in Ohio, are needed to curtail downwind
pollution from the Midwest to the Eastern states. Midwest
politicians and power company officials say the cuts will reduce
electric capacity and hurt the economy. (Dempsey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ Sen. John Glenn's shuttle flight will include a
30-minute educational link with students on earth, including a
class at John Glenn High School in New Concord and a hook up w/
COSI in Columbus. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 8.
</P>
