</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crafty times in Chattanooga
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 100 regional artists will converge on the Chattanooga
riverfront next weekend for the third annual Celebration of Fine
Craft. The juried show, produced by the Tennessee Association of
Craft Artists, will be held downtown at Ross' Landing on the
Tennessee River from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Saturday and 11 a.m. to 6
p.m. Oct. 4. The show will feature furniture, kitchenware and
utensils, dinnerware, toys, ornaments, jewelry, hand-woven clothing
and wearable art, rugs, floor cloths and tapestries.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibiting for the first time in the fiber category is Lidia
Amanda de Lopez from San Antonio Aguas Calientes in Guatemala. She
will be weaving on her tejido de palos (backstrap loom), as she has
done since she was 8.
</P>
<P>
   The free event also includes activities for children and musical
entertainment by Nashville Weather, featuring contemporary
interpretations of American, Irish and Scottish folk music. Crafts
demonstrations will be ongoing. The food court will feature
Ukrainian specialities as well as typical Southern fare such as
barbecue, fried okra, turnip greens and pinto beans, along with
Cajun chicken, jambalaya, Italian sausages and funnel cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 615-665-0502.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ballooning's big event: The Kodak Albuquerque International
Balloon Fiesta _ ballooning's largest and most spectacular event _
is expected to attract nearly a million visitors Saturday through
Oct. 11. The event will feature more than 850 hot air and gas
balloons flying over Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Among the events is the fourth annual America's Challenge Gas
Balloon Race, featuring competiton among around-the-world balloon
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 505-821-1000 or http://www.aibf.org.
</P>
<P>
   -- Haunted ship: Premier Cruises is hosting a Halloween cruise
aboard its Big Red Boat, departing Oct. 30 for a three-night
journey to the Bahamas. In addition to the ship's family amenties,
there will be a haunted house, trick or treating, a costume party
and a mini-psychic fair with readers, an aura photographer, New Age
herbs, crystals, music and more. As usual, Bugs Bunny, Tweety, Taz
and other Warner Bros. cartoon characters will be on the cruise.
Rates start at $304 per person based on double occupancy, plus port
charges. Information: 1-800-990-7770 or
http://www.premiercruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   -- The pampered shopper: You can shop till you drop, then return
to your luxury accommodation in an executive suite at the Trump
International Hotel and Tower at 1 Central Park West in New York.
Available Friday through Dec. 27, the Holiday Shopper's Package
includes champagne and complimentary transporation to the guest's
first shopping destination in Manhattan. After shopping, guests may
enjoy a massage incorporating reflexology for weary feet. Use of
the fitness center and 55-lap pool is complimentary. The rate is
$1,450 for three days and two nights, double occupancy.
Information: 1-888-448-7867.
</P>
<P>
   -- British history on the telly: Edward Windsor, the third son
and youngest child of Queen Elizabeth II, will host PBS's ``Crown
and Country,'' a series that premieres with a two-hour special from
9 to 11 tonight on GPTV. Six half-hour episodes will follow Oct. 7
and 12, Nov. 16 and 30, and Dec. 21 and 27. While exploring
Britain's rich past _ its castles, cathedrals, kings and queens _
Windsor recounts tall tales and the traditions, including the role
of the monarchy, as he leads viewers on an insider's tour of some
of the most prominent sites in English history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
