<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOVASCOTIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going two by two through natural Nova Scotia
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Denise Prodigo-Herrmann
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OFF DIGBY NECK, Nova Scotia_Blooooow, 12 o'clock!''
</P>
<P>
   We had pedaled a tandem bike across 40 rough miles of Nova
Scotia, then ridden a tiny Zodiac boat across 25 miles of icy ocean
to hear those words.
</P>
<P>
   Our first whale sighting. The guide raced our 20-foot boat
closer to the 80-foot beast. The long, sleek body of the finback
glistened in the sunlight, moving very slowly through the frigid
waters of the Bay of Fundy. We all stood motionless as the majestic
beauty showed its features _ the fin, the dark gray back, the top
of its tail. Finally, the footprint _ the still mark on the water
left after a whale descends into the ocean depths.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin, biologist and owner of Ocean Explorations,
explained the protocol of spout-spotting: The bow of the boat is 12
o'clock, the stern 6 o'clock, and so on. We caught on fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blow! 2 o'clock!'' shouted a fellow tourist from Pennsylvania,
who was so excited she lost her balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blow! 11 o'clock!'' yelled another from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In the next hour we saw a dozen or more finback whales, getting
to within 100 feet of some. The second-largest whale in the world,
the finback can grow to 80 feet and weigh as much as 80 tons,
devouring 2 tons of herring a day. On our ride back to shore, we
glimpsed the world's most endangered whale, a right whale, feeding
in the distance. Only 300 right whales are believed to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Nova Scotia is wonderful territory for anyone interested in an
active outdoor vacation, offering great cycling, hiking, birding,
beachcombing and whale watching. In one week, we pedaled through
remote areas on the Digby Neck, visited quiet fishing villages and
experienced hundreds of years of history in Annapolis Royal,
Canada's oldest European settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Our adrenalin high from the whale tour, we were ready to
continue our journey back to Digby. A ride across the Digby Neck
offers many challenges. The peninsula, on the western side of Nova
Scotia, juts out toward the Atlantic, separating the Bay of Fundy
and St. Mary's Bay. Steep climbs end in breathtaking views from the
tops of the now mostly submerged North Mountain chain. Fragrant
spruce trees, yellow and crimson snapdragons and white and purple
lupines line the roadsides, contrasting with the bright blue waters
of St. Mary's Bay.
</P>
<P>
   When we arrived back in Digby, Bob and Theresa Marshall and
their friendly dog Sam greeted us at the Bayside Inn Bed and
Breakfast. Theresa showed us our room, with a large bay window
overlooking the water and fishing docks. The private bath was
outfitted with a giant claw-foot tub, where a soak would be a
welcome treat after two days of biking.
</P>
<P>
   But hunger called first. Home of the world's largest scallop
fleet, Digby is a great place for fresh seafood. We enjoyed many of
the local delicacies _ mussels, scallops and lobster _ cooked to
perfection at the Red Raven Pub.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, we were back on the bike for a 30-mile ride
east, and then north: Our destination was Annapolis Royal, where
we'd stay two nights. Along the way was Bear River, once a busy
shipbuilding center, now home to craft and antiques shops.
</P>
<P>
   It's also home to a lot of big hills _ so many that Bear River
is called ``Little Switzerland'' _ lovely to look at, murder to
ride. For more than a mile, we climbed straight up before leveling
off on farm roads. We rode along the Moose River on rolling hills
lined with fragrant wildflowers and evergreens, and took Highway 1
to the town of Annapolis Royal. As we descended through lush green
farmlands and apple orchards, we saw horses grazing in the valley
pasture below.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived in town and headed to the King George Inn, a large
Victorian home built in 1868. Just a five-minute walk from the inn,
we came into the historic downtown, where our first stop was Ye
Olde Towne Pub, for huge platters of steamed clams and local draft
beer. Then to Catfish Moon, a shop featuring handmade pottery with
designs influenced by Nova Scotian folk art.
</P>
<P>
   The next day we enjoyed a walking tour through historic gardens
and took in the Tidal Power Plant, the Fort Anne National Historic
Site, a delightful dinner at the Garrison House and, finally, a
candlelight graveyard tour of the cemetery with a guide dressed in
traditional Victorian mourning clothes.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, we took our final tandem ride in Nova Scotia,
truly an island built for two.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Costs in Canada are in Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ferry information: Ferries sail from St. John to Digby three
times a day during peak season, June to October, and once or twice
a day off season, depending on the day. While there is comfortable
seating inside the cabin, the open deck provides a terrific view of
porpoises, seals, whales (if you're lucky) and seabirds. The
three-hour cruise costs $18 per person, $10 per child under 13, $8
per bicycle and $36 per car. Off-season prices are lower. Call
1-888-249-7245 for reservations.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lodgings: Bayside Inn Bed and Breakfast, $35-$45 per night,
115 Montague Row, Digby, 902-245-2247. King George Inn, $35-$50 per
night, 548 Upper St. George St., Annapolis Royal, 1-902-532-5286.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: Digby Visitor Information Center,
</P>
<P>
   1-888-463-4429. Annapolis Royal Visitor Information Center, 902-
532-5454.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
