<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PEI-COX     09-24 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PEI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tides of change touch gently on pastoral province
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, Prince Edward Island_Chasing down a memory is always a
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Revisiting a favorite seaside raises questions: Will how it
looks today erase your dreamy images of the way it used to be? Can
any coastal town escape the transforming tides of ``progress'' and
development?
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the tiny southern seaport of Victoria, where I spent
the summer of '64, has managed to dodge both.
</P>
<P>
   My dad had spotted an ad for a ``Victorian farmhouse by the sea,
$250 month'' in The New York Times, and rented the white two-story
sight unseen. For three whole months, the sounds of the ocean were
as close as a bedroom window. At 8, I fell under the spell of the
sea _ and being lulled to sleep by the sound of its rise and fall.
We all became accustomed to swimming lessons in the waves of the
cold Atlantic, vegetables fresh from a backyard garden, and bread
hot from a neighbor's oven. For six kids from the Hudson River
Valley, raised on canned veggies and frozen food, this village life
seemed too perfect to last.
</P>
<P>
   But here it is, unchanged in the important ways, 34 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, new owners have added a third story to our farmhouse and
made its barn an antiques shop; the old grocery was redone as the
upscale Island Chocolates. The working wharf of this former
shipbuilding town _ now often promoted as Victoria by the Sea _
caught fire a few years ago and was reborn as shops and a
restaurant called Sea Winds. Most of the dirt roads in these four
square blocks have been paved.
</P>
<P>
   And it's no longer an hourlong ferry ride from New Brunswick.
The much-debated Confederation Bridge, which opened in summer '97
and stretches across the Northumberland Strait in the distance like
a long, ghostly arm, has made it just a 30-minute drive from the
mainland. (You can still opt for the more romantic water crossing;
Northumberland Ferries connects Caribou, Nova Scotia, and Wood
Islands, Prince Edward Island, every hour and a half.)
</P>
<P>
   Since the eight-mile bridge debuted, tourism has roughly doubled
in Canada's smallest province, only 140 miles from end to end. An
estimated 1.2 million visited last year. In summer and fall, they
come for old-fashioned vacations on the beach, lobster bakes and
world-class golf courses. In winter, a network of extensive bike
trails attracts snowmobilers and skiers. Maybe it's the island's
environmental reverence, but for all its increased traffic, it
seems none the worse for wear.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called the Million-Acre Farm, this ancient place
remains rooted in agriculture, growing much of the world's seed
potato supply. By summer's end, the white and purple blossoms,
covering iron-red fields, appear to Southern eyes like some strange
breed of cotton. Locals have worked hard to preserve this life,
raising vegetables, fruit and dairy products on the fertile land
and pulling lobsters, scallops and the justly famous Malpeque Bay
oysters from the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Everything we ate was blissfully fresh: a humble oyster sandwich
at the New London Seafood Restaurant south of Cavendish, or a
gourmet five-course meal at the casually upscale Seasons in Thyme
in Summerside. Here we marveled at chef Stefan Czapalay's inventive
island combos, typified by the oyster risotto, subbing Yukon Gold
potatoes for rice.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Edward Island has modernized around its rich past.
Capital city Char-
</P>
<P>
   lottetown (where the nation of Canada was born in 1864) and
major port Summerside have entire blocks of historic homes,
buildings and churches for every Kinko's or Blockbuster. Museums
dedicated to island industry offer history as cultural experience:
Summerside's International Fox Museum and Hall of Fame, which
reprises the island's fox farming history; Miminegash's Irish Moss
Interpretive Centre; O'Leary's Prince Edward Island Potato Museum.
The College of Piping in Summerside has nightly summer ceilidhs and
dancing that reflect the island's Celtic and Acadian roots.
</P>
<P>
   But the rural routes that cross-stitch the island remain its
heart and soul.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere are you more than 15 minutes from the ocean. The best
way to explore, if you don't have time to bike, is by car. Three
well-marked scenic heritage roads (Ladyslipper Drive, Blue Heron
Drive and Kings Byway) take you to red cliffs and beaches by way of
rolling fields of wheat and corn, patches of lupine and Queen
Anne's lace. Wandering without a plan is the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   We rued native novelist Lucy Maud Montgomery's international
fame when we crossed into the tourist-trap choked northern crescent
around Cavendish, home of the heroine of her ``Anne of Green
Gables'' series (first published in 1908, now in its 99th
printing). But that's only because we were not among the throngs
who came to find The House and retrace the footsteps of the
beguiling fictional redhead.
</P>
<P>
   We opted for the nearby Prince Edward Island National Park and
its 25 miles of beaches, especially the few white sand shores so
prized for swimming.
</P>
<P>
   And gravitated to such offbeat stops as the Bottle Houses (Les
Maisons de Bouteilles) along Ladyslipper Drive in Cap-Egmont, a
tiny stronghold of Acadian culture on the southwest shore. A
retired fisherman, dedicated gardener and pioneering recycler named
Edouard Arsenault built these three imaginative shrines out of
25,000 colored glass bottles and cement from 1980 to '83. He passed
away in 1984, after which the elements took their toll. A five-year
reconstruction was completed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of old churches will find the island's plentiful houses of
worship beautifully maintained, open all the time and occasionally
staffed. Ulrich Poirier, 81, was the bilingual guide of the day at
the century-old Mont-Carmel, an Acadian cathedral just down the
road from the Bottle Houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our ancestors to thank for this,'' he said, patting a
green marble column. Carved wooden pews stretched out under
old-fashioned candle chande-
</P>
<P>
   liers. ``No expense was spared.''
</P>
<P>
   At the western edge of the island, where the lush farmland
crashes into the blue Northumberland Strait, lovers of the ocean
needn't spend a fortune to spend the night in a lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The 123-year-old West Point Lighthouse, a functioning Coast
Guard outpost, museum and bed-and-breakfast, fills up fast in
summer, so we'd booked a seaside room months in advance. We arrived
near dusk, finding the tower's black-and-white stripes softened by
golden-pink light.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just in time for the sunset,'' said the young clerk at
the ancient front desk. She handed us two sets of keys _ one to our
room, the other to the uppermost walkway. ``It looks best from the
very top,'' she said, glancing at her watch. ``And you've got about
10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the rough winds of the Lantern Deck, 70 feet up, as the
bright disc slipped into the waves, we watched the sky and water go
pearled pink and orange-blue. After, we dined on fresh lobster
sandwiches (on homemade bread) and a plate of local fruit and
cheese. Then we walked along the shore in the dark, cool night,
under a clear expanse of stars.
</P>
<P>
   Back in our room, gauzy white curtains framed the ocean view and
fluttered in the salty air. And we slept deeply, lulled once more
by the primal cadence of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Costs in Canada are in Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: Fly into Charlottetown via Air Canada/Air Nova
(1-800-776-3000) or cross over from Nova Scotia or New Brunswick by
ferry ($28.50 per car, Northumberland Ferries, 1-800-565-0201). Or
drive over from Cape Tormentine, New Brunswick, on the new
Confederation Bridge, an eight-mile two-lane with tall guardrails
(hence no view). Since you're only charged when you leave the
island, no matter how you arrive, it's slightly cheaper, and more
fun, to ferry in and drive out (about $22).
</P>
<P>
   -- Accommodations: The West Point Lighthouse, at the edge of
Cedar Dunes Provincial Park, is more than a great place to spend
the night. Its five-story museum recaps the structure's 123-year
past and the history of the sea-dependent community surrounding it.
Only four of the nine guest rooms face the sea, so book early. Open
May 22-Sept. 27. Route 14, O'Leary. 1-800-764-6854.
</P>
<P>
   The Loyalist Country Inn faces Summerside's working waterfront,
and its mid-island location makes it ideal for exploring in almost
any direction. Indoor pool and sauna, onsite Crown &AMP; Anchor Tavern,
dining room and gift shop. 195 Harbour Drive, Summerside. Rooms,
$96-$145; suites $225. 1-800-361-2668.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dining: Seasons in Thyme features gourmet dining in an
unpretentious setting. 644 Water St. East, Summerside,
902-888-3463.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bottle Houses: Though you can see the three fantastical
buildings from the roadside, you can't really appreciate them
without being inside. $3.25. June 8-Sept. 26. Route 11, Cap-Egmont.
902-854-2987.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: 1-888-734-7529. Or http://www.peiplay.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
