<TEXT>
<P>
   New season of ``The Practice'' starts off with a dud
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Kloer
</P>
<P>
   TV CRITIC
</P>
<P>
   They practice more than the law on ``The Practice.'' They
practice eye contact _ deep, prolonged eyeball lock, like you'd
normally find at a hypnotists' convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice'' is uber-producer David E. Kelley's other show,
the one that doesn't get as much attention as his ``Ally McBuzz,''
but that nonetheless won the Emmy as best drama two weeks ago and
is usually a satisfying legal drama, a thoughtful blend of cynicism
and idealism.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's season premiere has some plot problems with the main
court case, in which two college roommates each blame the other for
the rape-murder of a girl in their dorm room. It's supposed to be a
real puzzler, but one passed a polygraph and the other didn't, and
there's never any mention of physical evidence or DNA testing.
Kelley usually constructs his cases better than this; ``It's all a
little too convenient,'' one lawyer says. Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Practice'' is home to some of the best acting on TV,
notably Camryn Manheim, winner of a supporting actress Emmy, whose
Ellenor starts coming apart Sunday, and Steve Harris,
eyeball-locker supreme, whose intensity melts the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Star Dylan McDermott, as founding partner Bobby Donnell, is
sometimes branded the thinking woman's stud muffin, but he has more
than just smolder. Witness his working through father-son issues of
pride and shame Sunday with his dad (Charles Durning, reminding us
he can go deeper than comedy).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice''
</P>
<P>
   Grades:
</P>
<P>
   B- (for the season opener)
</P>
<P>
   A- (for the full series)
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. EDT Sunday on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
