<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER25-COX     09-24 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABC trying to make Saturday night watchable again
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We don't expect much from TV on Saturday nights. Mainly, we just
want it on. But ABC has aimed its laser sights right between the
eyes of lovelorn stay-at-homes with a ``Fantasy Island'' remake and
``Cupid,'' two daftly not-bad new shows designed to make you feel
good about feeling bad about being home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasy Island'' (9 p.m. EDT Saturday on ABC) is darker than
the late-'70s, early-'80s original, in which, then as now, guests
are transported by ``da plane'' to a tropical resort to fulfill
their dreams. Executive producer Barry Sonnenfeld (``Men in
Black,'' ``Get Shorty'') replaces the old cheesy camp with a more
artful brand of cheese: swirling, zooming closeups that hint (like
a ton of bricks) at some dangerous undertone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have those white ones burned,'' island host Mr. Roarke orders
an assistant as he thumbs through white suits that look left over
from former host Ricardo Mantalban, and instead plucks from his
closet a black suit. He dubs the whites ``a little dated.''
</P>
<P>
   This is escapism at its most peculiar, a sort of Club Med for
the Damned. Perfectly cast as Roarke is the frighteningly peculiar
Malcolm McDowell _ one odd, irresistible duck. You sit up straight
as soon as he arrives; with his short white hair spiked back and
his face taught with what seems like the pressure of some major
G-force, he doesn't suffer fools gladly.
</P>
<P>
   The fools tonight want a variety of things _ one wants the woman
he thinks he should've married; one wants to be smarter than her
sister; another wants thrills instead of a more average life's
nuances _ and it is Roarke's duty to set them straight.
</P>
<P>
   It can get awfully silly, and all the lessons they teach you
learned in kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   But McDowell and his two sidekicks (Louis Lombard and Edward
Hibbert) are so astonishingly curious they're worth the short slogs
through the downtime. If not worth staying home for,this unlikely
flight of fantasy is at least worth watching if you have to stay
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cupid'' (10 p.m. EDT Saturday on ABC) is more aggressively
aimed at the citizens of Loserville. Try this one on: Jeremy Piven
(cousin Spence on ``Ellen'') is a recently released psych patient
convinced he's cupid. He winds up in a Chicago singles therapy
group, his aim to match up 100 couples so he can return to Mt.
Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   You can't be expected to believe this, but it sort of works.
Like a watered-down McMurphy in ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest,'' Piven teaches this group's lovelorn cuckoos to seize the
night. He alternates between tough love (``Get the complete cable
package,'' he advises one guy) and ``Loveline'' cheerleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pop psychology sensitivity awareness festival,'' he
exclaims at one session, run by relationship expert Claire Allen
(Paula Marshall). ``You're shackled in fear. Make a move! Get in
the game! Afraid to get hurt? Have a beautiful train wreck!''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know whether we should be entranced or repelled by
this Cupid. The singles talk can be bracingly grim, but if
tonight's pilot is a blueprint, at least one winner should emerge
each week.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope so. If not, you'll have to turn off the TV. Then what
do you have on Saturday night?
</P>
<P>
   Grades: ``Fantasy Island'': B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Cupid'': B+
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   ``Martial Law'' needs to pack more punches
</P>
<P>
   Nobody does what Jackie Chan can. But Sammo Hung, who's worked
with Chan on film, comes as close as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Hung's new cop chop drama ``Martial Law'' (9 p.m. EDT Saturday
on CBS) is a knock-your-block-off knockoff of Chan's big-screen
martial arts free-for-alls.
</P>
<P>
   Anything's fair game with these fists of fury. In Saturday's
debut, Hung beats up people not just with his arms, legs, elbows,
head and hands. Like Chan does, Hung picks up and whacks guys with
all kinds of stuff. Like a blow torch. A big blue trash can. Hedge
clippers. A picnic bench. An eraser _ and a chalkboard. A car door.
And, of course, a watermelon.
</P>
<P>
   The plot here is irrelevant. But Hung plays Sammo Law, a Chinese
cop come to Los Angeles to hunt down a stolen car racketeer. He's
teamed with an L.A.P.D. he-she duo (Louis Manylor and Tammy Lauren)
that's all strut. Her standard tough-cookie line: ``Let me point
you in the direction of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   That's nine words too many.
</P>
<P>
   We're tuning in to see the bruising ballets. Too bad there's not
enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Content ratings don't always work
</P>
<P>
   Remember TV's content ratings? The V for violence? The S for
sexual situations? A new study from The Henry J. Kaiser Family
Foundation claims those letter designations are not always being
used for shows that contain sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some 79 percent of shows with violent content and 92 percent of
shows with sex do not get appropriate content descriptors, the
study says.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, an episode of ``Walker, Texas Ranger,''
for example, failed to carry a ``V'' in a show that included the
stabbings of two guards, the threat of rape against a nun and a
fight scene in which an escapee is shot and another kicked and
beaten unconcious.
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
