<HEADER>
A2924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BOOK-COUNTRY-2TAKE     09-24 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOOK-COUNTRY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE AND LITERATURE IN A CITY THAT SPEAKS VOLUMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRACE PALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This weekend, New York, our big, noisy, contentious,
world-engaging town, is being celebrated as Book Country. For most
people, that's Manhattan. But once, my New York City was the Bronx.
It was a small place (I thought). It was enlarging itself, slowly
moving east on little bridges over narrow streams and north on
Robert Moses' highways in order to sell its fancier citizens to the
suburbs. Not me.
</P>
<P>
   When my time came at 19 to leave home, marry and live real life,
I believed there was only one place this could be accomplished.
That was Greenwich Village. Not only because artists and other free
spirits lived there and puritanical parents did not, but because it
was a small place, too, a neighborhood, one of a thousand New York
neighborhoods. The high-rise buildings with elegant foyers and
French names had not yet been built.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, to this day, because of fought-for municipal
landmarking, if you stand on the northeast corner of 10th Street
and the Avenue of the Americas you can still truly see the sky. In
season, the sun sets along West 10th Street and just misses Patchin
Place, where E.E. Cummings and Djuna Barnes once lived. Of course,
I already knew what the Village looked like: When I was 17, I
walked with hopeful happiness from my job on 11th Avenue once a
week to hear W.H. Auden speak to an audience of about 200 in the
New School auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, many great cities in the world. A great
city probably has a river and a good deal of commerce, for
starters. Greatness would also like a welcoming harbor on the sea
as well and a population in constant argument in several languages.
A great city must absolutely have a bard, a poet to sing the city's
praises loud enough so finally the outside world can hear.
</P>
<P>
   For New York, Walt Whitman was the singer, and he was actually
willing to praise the rest of the country, too. He was, in fact,
the poet of glorious incessant praise. He found all the words for
it and helped most of us to love many of us. In the 19th century,
he said he heard America singing. In the following century,
Langston Hughes in Harlem sang to that ardent ghost:
</P>
<P>
   I too sing America
</P>
<P>
   I am the darker brother.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman would probably have answered, ``Ah, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   I have a kind of literary picture in my head. Hart Crane is on
the Brooklyn Bridge and is looking down at the busy waters. He sees
Whitman singing his wonderful ferry poem on the way home to
Brooklyn. At sea, or perhaps way downtown observing the harbor,
Herman Melville was writing and writing. Edith Wharton is wondering
as she walks her city how, while she was away, all these
chocolate-covered houses had crawled so quickly up one street and
down another.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it had a singer, the great city required the appearance
of many people and their different languages who had come after
arduous ocean voyages. They were so exhausted and fearful that most
of them got off the boat and stopped right where they were. (For
many years, my own parents didn't move another inch.)
</P>
<P>
   Though there was poverty and exploitation, in the small
oppressive factories that were making the city rich, there seemed
to be no war just then, no foreign occupation. In fact, they were
the occupiers. Storytellers like Anzia Yezierska and Mary Antin
gave the immigrants their American voice.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred years ago, New York politically consolidated itself,
but it became its geographical self in the appetite-driven way of
island cities _ by throwing out beautiful, and less beautiful but
always amazing, bridges to catch Brooklyn and Queens, entangling
the boroughs further with a couple of bridges between Queens and
the Bronx (in case Queens planned a getaway to Long Island) and
securing them in a network of subways. Staten Island had always
dreamed of independence, but the long line of the Verrazano-Narrows
Bridge, as well as the inexpensive delight of the Staten Island
Ferry, held it tight.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx is really a continuation of Manhattan by other _
cheaper _ means. It's the only borough with an article before its
name. This was very important to me as I began to meet children
from snootier boroughs. The Bronx is where I lived for 19 years on
Hoe Avenue, a street worth living one's whole childhood on.
</P>
<P>
   There were, in fact, so many children on that street that you
never had to go beyond the middle of the block to find good stoops,
good friends and that week's enemies. On that street, the stout
mothers leaned on pillowed windowsills on summer evenings and
called the children home. They began to call at 9 o'clock. They
tried again at 10, and often at 11 for the children famous for
intransigence. Even I could stay out that late if I played in front
of the house so my own mother or sister or grandmother or aunt
could see me if they suddenly worried.
</P>
<P>
   We left that street, my friend and I, only to go to the movies,
the dentist or the library. We had at least four books to return
and four new ones to bring home every week.
</P>
<P>
   As I grew out of childhood into a young woman's wonderful
estate, I traveled by IRT and IND deeper and wider in Manhattan. I
had already found Greenwich Village, where the narrow streets
abutted one another in what I assumed was a foreign manner. There,
Jess Paley and I settled.
</P>
<P>
   Like true New Yorkers, for us, settling meant living in at least
three or four different apartments in the same neighborhood. Here,
we had two children, sent them to public school, shopped in the
Jefferson Market, had friends and were young. Our children played
in Washington Square Park, and the women who were my true friends
and beloved colleagues in that exhausting, often belittled task of
raising children gave me the gift of subject matter. Luckily, I had
for years read James Joyce for absolute standards, Gertrude Stein
for pleasure and permission to play, and Saul Bellow for
inescapable humor and the darkness of my immigrant people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when I began to write, that is, with the assumption that
other people might read my work, what I feared most was a literary
world that seemed to insist on its own narcissistic reason for
being. I was finally drawn into it by nonliterary means, through
proximity and politics. For instance, my son was in the same
second-grade class as the daughter of Ted Wilentz, a co-owner with
his brother, Eli, of the fabled Eighth Street Bookstore. If that
bookstore were still in business _ along with others _ it would
broaden New York's claim to the title of book country.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
