<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2926 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FEMINISTS-1ST     09-24 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FEMINISTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMINIST ORGANIZATIONS COME TO CLINTON'S DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: CORRECTS 13th graf to 67 votes)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of prominent feminist organizations joined
forces Thursday to decry the role of President Clinton in the White
House sex scandal but to urge that he not be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``While women are angry and do not condone his conduct, women
want President Clinton to remain in office,'' 12 feminist
organizations declared in a joint statement. ``We believe, and the
women of this nation concur, that Mr. Clinton's actions are not
impeachable.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Ireland, the president of the National Organization for
Women, told a news conference that while she was offended by the
president's behavior, ``it does not rise to the level of
impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioneering feminist activist Betty Friedan joined in, saying:
``It does not serve women to try to hound this president out of
office on charges of sexual misdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I fear that we are on the brink of an era of sexual
McCarthyism.''
</P>
<P>
   The group _ which also includes Eleanor Smeal, president of the
Feminist Majority, Dolores Huerta, co-founder of the United Farm
Workers, and Yvonne Scruggs-Leftwich, executive director of the
Black Leadership Forum _ called on their supporters to press their
elected officials to oppose Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   The women said Clinton has done more for women's rights than any
modern president, despite his alleged crimes and admitted sexual
misdeeds with a young intern in his employ.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we allow this (impeachment) process to continue,'' said
Kathy Rodgers, the executive director of the NOW Legal Defense and
Education Fund, ``the interests of women in particular will be
buried in the muck for generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Smeal warned that the sex scandal threatens to depress female
voter turnout in the Nov. 3 off-year congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not allow our disgust or disillusionment to keep women
from the polls in November,'' Smeal said.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the spokeswomen expressed concern about three Senate
races in which the female incumbents _ Sens. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., and Patty Murray, D-Wash. _
face tough fights. The three were voted into the Senate in 1992,
which feminists dubbed the Year of Women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We risk not only losing the gains of the Year of Women in 1992
in the 1998 congressional elections, but we risk years of
reactionary control of both Houses of Congress and perhaps the
presidency itself,'' Smeal said.
</P>
<P>
   If the three women senators lost their seats and if the
Republican majority in the Senate increased from its current 55
seats, Clinton's veto power would be diminished because of the
greater likelihood that his political foes could muster the 67
votes needed to override.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's veto of a bill banning late-term abortions was
sustained by only three votes in the Senate last week.
</P>
<P>
   The feminist leaders said their show of support for Clinton was
not coordinated with the White House or with the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations that signed the joint statement of support
for Clinton were: the National Council of Negro Women; the National
Council of Women's Organizations; the National Asian Pacific Legal
Consortium; Black Women United for Action; Wider Opportunities for
Women; the Black Leadership Forum; and the Women's Institute for
Freedom of the Press.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee will vote in early October on
whether to recommend that the House authorize an impeachment
investigation against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Any such probe would be based on Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr's 445-page report that centers around Clinton's affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and alleges 11 possible
grounds for impeachment, including allegations of perjury,
obstruction of justice, witness tampering and abuse of power in an
effort to conceal the relationship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BOOK-COUNTRY-2NDTA     09-24 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOOK-COUNTRY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: book country. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Wilentz apartment, above the store, was a literary gathering
place, and there I met, or rather watched, writers. In the late
'50s, my first book, ``The Little Disturbances of Man,'' was barely
out. Ted's wife at the time, Esta, was a good friend and, being
pretty shy herself, needed another member of the PTA to give her
emotional support in that highly charged circle. I was able to
observe the writers, mostly young Beats in action, and their women
in inaction, and I began to think about that fact. But what was
important to me were their voices aloud, the poem at last off the
page, a song.
</P>
<P>
   But my Bronx _ how it suffered in my absence _ saw its little
houses and short tenements battered and burned to the ground by
blasting highways, property greed and tenant rage, while I went on
living my domestic life on a side street in the Village. I managed
to raise children among a wild assortment of grown-ups, while
fighting successfully along with many others, like my present
husband, Robert Nichols, for the integrity of Washington Square.
</P>
<P>
   My other literary connections happened because my neighbor
Donald Barthelme thought I ought to work in PEN, the writers'
group. He was a little sorry about that later. This was in the
mid-'60s, and I put about 15 years into the various committees and
long board meetings. I couldn't help meeting writers then and, in
fact, liked a great many, even the ones I considered careerist and
self-centered. It's hard to dislike people once you know them.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a number of rightly furious women, I helped organize
the PEN women's committee, which exists today in a slightly
attenuated form, its work half finished. Women organizing on their
own behalf are never quite done.
</P>
<P>
   The years of the Vietnam War and the antiwar movement brought
many writers and artists together in readings, in street plays with
groups like the Bread and Puppet Theater. There were short plays on
the backs of trucks in all the neighborhoods, longer, more
ambitious ones like ``Everyman'' in the street right outside Judson
Church.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many ways in which Manhattan is reminded of its
island nature, but as ordinary life becomes hopelessly more
expensive, the young have begun to create their own young
city-dreaming communities of artists and writers, sprouting up
outside Manhattan _ in Brooklyn, Queens and even in my own Bronx,
which is engaged in a lively cultural transformation.
</P>
<P>
   I was asked to say something about how New York worked me,
dreamed me into becoming a writer. It just never stopped speaking
to me. The city continues to do this for others I've met in the
high schools and community colleges of our city, often speaking
with a Spanish accent. If only our neighborhoods were still marked
by bookstores, if my friends could still walk up and down Fourth
Avenue in search of secondhand books, why then we would indeed be
not only a publishing center in a state of terminal merger, but a
true book country as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Grace Paley has written three books of short stories, two
volumes of poems and a new book of essays, reviews and memoirs
called ``Just as I Thought.'')
</P>
<P>
   Sampling Book World, Street by Street by Street
</P>
<P>
   Readings, lectures, panel discussions and storytelling are among
the events to be offered over the next three days during the 20th
New York Is Book Country festival, which this year is part of New
York City 100: Greater New York Centennial Celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Hundred Years of Literary Life in New York'' is the theme
of the festival's centerpiece, the annual New York Is Book Country
fair, which takes place on Sunday along Fifth Avenue from 48th to
57th Street in Manhattan. Literary material from more than 195
exhibitors, from major publishers to small presses, will be
available from 11 a.m. to 5 p.m., weather permitting; the fair,
which is free, may be canceled if it rains heavily. (Information in
the event of a cancellation: 212-207-7376.)
</P>
<P>
   Free maps of the booth sites will be available at an information
booth set up on the northwest corner of Fifth Avenue and 52nd
Street; several authors will be making appearances at the various
booths. This year special activities will be presented at two
stages; one, at 53rd Street east of Fifth Avenue, will feature
entertainment for children, including storytelling, readings and a
sing-along. The actors Jane Seymour and James Keach will start the
entertainment with a reading at 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The second stage, in Rockefeller Center from 48th to 49th
Street, will offer daylong readings by noted authors, among them
Stephen King (2 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Several social events with literary ties, one especially for
children, are planned in Manhattan. Saturday from 2 to 4 p.m.,
``New York: A Kid's City,'' a children's tea featuring authors and
illustrators of children's books as well as readings and a
performance, is planned at the Plaza Hotel, Fifth Avenue and
Central Park South. Among those taking part are Hilary Knight,
Louise Fitzhugh, Paul Zindel, Savion Glover and Lynn Whitfield. The
event is sponsored by the Books for Kids Foundation and Friends of
Libraries, USA. Admission is $50, or $125 for a family of three.
Reservations are required: (212) 252-9168.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday at noon, a brunch sponsored by New York Is Book
Country and The New York Times will take place at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, Park Avenue at 50th Street. Scheduled to
appear are the writers A. Scott Berg, Robert B. Parker and Alice
Walker, and Steve Martin, the writer and comedian. The brunch is
sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the Waldorf-Astoria on Sunday will be an afternoon tea
sponsored by New York Is Book Country and The New York Times,
featuring Edwidge Danticat, John Burnham Schwartz, Marianne Wiggins
and Wally Lamb. It, too, is sold out.
</P>
<P>
   A block-by-block guide to the booths at the Fifth Avenue fair
follows. ``General interest'' refers to a section that does not
have a unifying theme. Green balloons will mark booths selling
merchandise, while yellow balloons will indicate booths that have
only displays.
</P>
<P>
   48TH TO 49TH STREET: West Side: general interest. East Side:
general interest.
</P>
<P>
   49TH TO 50TH STREET: West Side: general interest, business,
storytelling. East Side: general interest.
</P>
<P>
   50TH TO 51ST STREET: West Side: general interest.
</P>
<P>
   51ST TO 52ND STREET: West Side: general interest, travel, The
New York Times Crossword Puzzle, with Randy Ross. East Side:
general interest.
</P>
<P>
   52ND TO 53RD STREET: West Side: New York Is Book Country
information booth, sports, health, fitness. East Side: the arts.
</P>
<P>
   52ND STREET: Between Madison Avenue and the Avenue of the
Americas: Antiquarian Row, with old and rare books.
</P>
<P>
   53RD TO 54TH STREET: West Side: general interest, audio books.
East Side: general interest.
</P>
<P>
   54TH TO 55TH STREET: West Side: general interest. East Side:
black studies.
</P>
<P>
   55TH TO 56TH STREET: West Side: Jewish interest. East Side: New
York City interest.
</P>
<P>
   56TH TO 57TH STREET: West Side: art books, mysteries,
storytelling. East Side: general interest, storytelling.
</P>
