<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MET-NETHERLANDISH-EXH     09-24 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-NETHERLANDISH-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING ICONS REAL LIFE AND HUMANS A PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Welcome to heaven. Or more accurately, to heaven on
earth. That's the terrain mapped out in crisp, luminous detail in
``From van Eyck to Bruegel: Early Netherlandish Painting in the
Metropolitan Museum of Art.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is exactly what it says it is: a display of more than a
hundred 15th- and 16th-century Flemish paintings representing the
bulk of the Met's large and impressive collection of such material,
supplemented by period objects.
</P>
<P>
   The works range from multi-paneled altarpieces to devotional
images the size of a passport, and from gold-threaded tapestries to
carved boxwood rosary beads.
</P>
<P>
   Like the museum's recent Goya and Rembrandt exhibitions, this
one is entirely home-grown and lacks the glamour of flown-in loans
or fancy pedigrees. Who cares? It's been ages since this
charismatic art has been given a major showcase in this part of the
world. The Met is superbly equipped to do it justice and has gone
all-out for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Long-hidden paintings have been pulled from storage and dusted
off. Some familiar works _ the fabulous ``Harvesters'' by Pieter
Bruegel the Elder is one _ have been deep-cleaned, with revelatory
results. And while many top-flight pieces are routinely on view in
the museum, they are scattered, for legal reasons having to do with
bequests, hither and yon, from the Linsky collection to the Lehman
Wing to the Cloisters uptown.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have been drawn together in a dazzling show of
strength, though the big news is also old news: the unrivaled
genius of the Netherlandish artists who invented the oil paint
medium and the passionate, inventive vitality of a late medieval
culture that saw the natural and the supernatural worlds as mirror
images and the boundary between them as slight.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Keith Christiansen, a curator of European painting
at the Met, and Maryan Ainsworth, a senior research fellow in
painting conservation, the show is arranged chronologically. And it
opens at the birth of the oil tradition, with an early diptych
painting of the Crucifixion and the Last Judgment attributed to
that most modest of revolutionaries (his motto was ``As best I
can''), Jan van Eyck.
</P>
<P>
   Painted around 1430, the two narrow vertical pictures are about
a foot and a half high. Joined, they resemble a large open book _ a
reminder of van Eyck's roots in manuscript painting _ and they
probably served as a portable altar for private devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Portability would have been an important requirement for
personal art commissioned in Bruges, a city whose cosmopolitan
population of merchants and princes ranged back and forth across
Europe. But whether this work traveled with its owner or stayed at
home, it was clearly conceived to have every inch of its minutely
rendered images scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Both painting repay close attention. The Last Judgment's vision
of Hell, for example, as a vast digestive system chewing up
sinners, is a true post-mortem nightmare. But the real gem is the
portrayal of the Crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   The composition divides into three stacked zones, and the one at
the top, where agonized deaths are in progress, is the prettiest.
The three thin crosses are silhouetted against a travel-brochure
view of Jerusalem, in this case a fantastic cluster of European
turrets and Arabic domes with a sweep of snow-powdered alps behind.
</P>
<P>
   But grim details intrude: Christ's side gushes blood; the hands
of the thieves have turned black, their circulation cut off by
ropes. And on the hill below, in the second zone, a kind of jocular
chaos prevails. Mounted burghers network and grin; rubbernecking
servants, keyed-up as if for market day, jostle and push. They are
all hemmed in by a wall of soldiers dressed in medieval riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   A man in an ermine-trimmed coat and a major turban stares out
toward the viewer; he may be the painting's patron. Another man,
wearing a sort of samurai outfit, his head thrown back as if he had
just been slapped hard, stares up at Jesus. This is the Roman
centurion who, the gospels say, was converted on the spot, and van
Eyck shows his life being changed forever right before our eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down, a third drama unfolds. The Virgin has retreated
into her voluminous cloak like a wounded animal into a cave. St.
John holds her fast in a pincer grip. A woman in green _ Mary
Magdalene? _ raises her hands, at once pleading and shielding her
eyes. Nearby stands a female figure as impassive as a Buddha. She
is usually identified as one of the ancient sybils who prophesied
this event and now witnesses its fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   This diptych is a cornerstone of the Met's European collection.
An Annunciation triptych known as the Merode Altarpiece, also on
view in the exhibition's first gallery, is another. Together they
define the essence of the Early Netherlandish style: profound
religious emotion cast in the language of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   The Annunciation is attributed to Robert Campin and an
assistant, possibly Rogier van der Weyden. Campin is a shadowy
figure who worked in Tournai in the first half of the 15th century.
Many questions surround both the handful of works linked to his
name and his life. (He was once hauled into court for having a
mistress, though he may have been framed by professional rivals.)
But about the Merode Altarpiece one thing is sure. Nothing quite
like it had been seen in painting before.
</P>
<P>
   Here, for the first time, a key event of sacred history is
depicted as a domestic event squeezed in between breakfast and
lunch. In the painting's central panel, the blond Virgin is
discovered reading in her living room as unexpected visitors drop
by. One is the angel Gabriel, all in white with polychrome wings.
The other, the tiny unborn Jesus beamed in on rays of light.
</P>
<P>
   Their arrival has kicked up a breeze, snuffing out a candle on
the table but has otherwise caused no fuss. The Virgin barely
notices them. The aged Joseph, drilling away in his carpenter shop,
hears nothing. Only the paintings' patron, who kneels outside in
the courtyard garden with his wife and discreetly peeks through the
door, is aware that anything unusual is afoot.
</P>
<P>
   An ocean of academic ink has been spilled over this picture.
Every one of its details _ the smoking wick, the mousetrap Joseph
is making, the spray of lilies in a majolica jug _ have been passed
through endless interpretive filters in search of symbolic
meanings, submerged or overt.
</P>
<P>
   The present trend in scholarship, though, is to lighten up on
such queries and to consider instead the psychological impact that
work might have held for its original viewers: what, for example,
its endorsement of the nuclear family might have meant, or its
encouragement of devotion as a private, intimate exercise.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the implied sanctification of the bourgeois interior
paved the way for 17th-century Dutch genre painting, exemplified by
Vermeer. And the late-20th-century infatuation with
miniature-everything, from Beanie Babies to microchips, doesn't
hurt the works' appeal.
</P>
<P>
   And then, what New Yorker wouldn't identify with the clutter of
the Holy Family's jammed two-rooms-with-a-view apartment? Or with
Gabriel's barging in like a next-door neighbor with a problem? Or
with Mary's studied, subway-rider's resolve to keep her eyes glued
to the page till the end of the chapter, come what may?
</P>
<P>
   The acute realism pioneered in paintings like this had powerful
repercussions, particularly in portraiture, to which a section of
the show is devoted. Some of the likenesses appear in altarpieces
in which generous donors are seen receiving a favorite saint's
personal attention, a comforting pat on the back or a nudge in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Just as often the context is secular. There isn't a jot of
sanctity in van der Weyden's portrait of the haughty, long-nosed
Francesco d'Este, who holds an emblem of princely power _ a hammer,
no less. Or in Hans Memling's portrait of Tommaso Portinari, head
of the Medici bank in the Lowlands, who looks nice enough but was
by all accounts one tough cookie.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Memling has made Tommaso's young wife, Maria,
with her fashionably shaved forehead and self-amused smile,
extremely appealing. And the French-born painter Jean Hey has
managed to lend a certain charm to the glum, 11-year-old Margaret
of Austria, seen in her betrothal portrait.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts, alas, were of little avail. Her husband-to-be,
Charles VIII of France, called the wedding off.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one of the unexpected stars in this gallery is a
portrait of a praying man attributed to Robert Campin's workshop,
where the great van der Weyden trained. The painting, long
disfigured by layers of varnish, was recently cleaned with stunning
results. Every detail of the man's middle-aged face can now be
read, right down to the white stubble on his cheek, and his skin
glows with life.
</P>
<P>
   By no means everything in ``From van Eyck to Bruegel'' is on
such an exalted level. But the Met's decision to bring second- and
third-tier works out of mothballs was smart.
</P>
<P>
   As arranged here, they illustrate some of the nuts-and-bolts
issues behind any study of the period: how workshops and their
divisions of labor functioned; how, in the absence of signatures,
attributions are made and revised; how a master's style is changed
_ inflected, corrupted _ as it passes through assistants and
followers.
</P>
<P>
   The investigatory section where these matters are explored is,
in fact, a mini-show in itself, one of several embedded in the
larger exhibition. Another is the gathering of paintings by Gerard
David (circa 1455 to 1523), long regarded as a sleepy, by-the-way
figure but who was, this show suggests, something more than that.
</P>
<P>
   The Met owns the largest group of his paintings anywhere, and
they reveal an artist who shrewdly bridged periods and styles.
Although he lived and died in Bruges, he set up a workshop in
Antwerp, the city destined to be the center of northern art in the
16th century. And while the figures in his blissful little ``Rest
on the Flight Into Egypt'' sustain a Netherlandish reserve, the
wind-tossed cloak of an Annunciation angel has a proto-Baroque
flair.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of David's death, northern art had changed greatly.
Italian influence was pervasive. Religious painting assumed an
exaggerated sensuality, as in a ``Virgin and Child With Angels'' by
Bernaert van Orley in which mother and child smooch and pet like
lovers. And the local realist tradition, while still in place, was
transformed.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Penitence of St. Jerome'' by Joachim Patinir _ one of
several ravishing altarpieces that punctuate the installation like
organ chords _ the landscape that was a tiny detail in van Eyck's
Crucifixion has taken over the picture, leaving the religious drama
to play itself out along a narrow apron in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the Reformation, saints and angels fled the scene;
landscape stood on its own, and the exhibition concludes with an
outstanding example of that development, Bruegel's ``Harvesters.''
The picture, dated 1565, is among the museum's most popular
attractions, and one can see why. Its expanse of gold-brown and
mint green is both soothing and thrilling, and its exquisite detail
both describes and extols the world.
</P>
<P>
   And just as important, it seems to represents a different moral
universe from what has preceded it, one free of doctrine and
damnation, or the need to believe in anything except what is
actually (italics)there:(end italics) in this case, farmers going
about their jobs on a storm-threatened summer afternoon. This is a
down-to-earth, humanist art, post-religious, an Impressionism in
the making.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? Humanism was its own kind of religion, a system of
faith and beliefs. It is fascinating to view Bruegel in this
context or, for that matter, to reconsider Netherlandish art as a
whole in light of stimulating recent scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   An article by Alfred Acres in the current Art Bulletin reads
Flemish altarpieces, including the Merode, in terms of their
manipulation of human and cosmic time. And the eye-opening work
that the historian Caroline Walker Bynum has done on the image of
the human body in medieval art adds a whole new dimensions to the
field, connecting it directly to the late 20th-century sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Eyck to Bruegel'' takes the more traditional route of
who-did-what-and-when connoisseurship, and pretty much sticks to
that. But it's hard to complain. A glorious art tradition has been
give the royal treatment; a superb collection is, at last, on full
view; unsuspected treasures have been brought to light.
</P>
<P>
   Other, smaller, ground-breaking shows will surely emerge from
this one. And at least for the next few months, a patch of Central
Park around 82nd Street is pretty close to paradise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
