<HEADER>
A2943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-0924-COX     09-24 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONSUMER ELECTRONICS TO PASS Y2K MUSTER
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To move in both ``f'' and ``w'' queues.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly all consumer electronics products now in
U.S. homes will go on ticking without taking a licking from the
millennium bug, an industry leader assured a congressional panel
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook is very good,'' Gary Shapiro, president of
Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association, told a House
technology subcommittee that is delving into the so-called ``Y2K''
glitch, which prevents computer systems from correctly recognizing
dates beyond Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, all consumer electronics products currently being
sold and the vast majority of consumer electronics products sold
(since 1988) will not experience Y2K problems,'' Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   That product list includes date-stamped TV sets, VCRs,
camcorders, fax machines, personal computers, microwaves,
thermostats and home automation and security products.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Holleyman II, president of the Business Software
Alliance, painted a less rosy picture for his sector. As he put it:
``Without taking action, the consumer who uses software in the home
or office may indeed face some difficulty with some of the software
applications on their personal computers.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing is done, the year 2000 problem could make it
impossible for affected personal computer users from preparing
their income taxes, sending e-mail or surfing the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   One problem: When it comes to hardware and software, virtually
every computer system is unique. Therefore, Holleyman said, each
individual consumer must take responsibility for finding out
whether her or his particular configuration is Y2K ready.
</P>
<P>
   Software piracy also enters the picture, Holleyman noted,
because ``consumers who discover that they do not hold valid
licenses (for their software) may find themselves without the right
to obtain information from technical service and support, as well
as access to upgrades, fixes and patches.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Connie Morella, R-Md., said her House panel will prepare a
checklist for both the home and the marketplace to assist consumers
in coping with the millennium bug threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This checklist underscores the fact that the Year 2000 crisis
may be so vast and far-reaching that each and every single one of
us must assume some responsibility to be year-2000 ready,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
