<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ROSENBLATT-BOS &LR;      09-24 1508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENBLATT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ROSENBLATT, A STEP ON THE WAY TO THE BIG ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET PEQUOT RESERVATION _ Friday night is a big fight
with a big difference for Dana Rosenblatt.
</P>
<P>
   If Rosenblatt can outlast former World Boxing Council and
International Boxing Federation junior middleweight champion Terry
Norris at Foxwoods Casino, he will have inched closer to what
Norris has already had a dozen times _ a world title fight. But for
that to happen, Rosenblatt has learned, he cannot want that shot
too much.
</P>
<P>
   It is a zen way of looking at boxing, a sport not often peered
at from the spiritual side. But Rosenblatt has long been the
thinking man's fighter, and that is the road he chose to follow on
the heels of his worst moments in the sport _ his stunning knockout
loss to Vinny Pazienza and the broken hand that followed it and
sidelined him for so many months that he began to wonder who he
really was.
</P>
<P>
   In that search, he believes, he found not only the answer to
that question but also the answer to why he lost to Pazienza and
how to avoid such an outcome when his moment arrives again, as it
may well do Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Pazienza, I let the event get the better of me,''
Rosenblatt said recently after a long night of preparing for Norris
at the World Gym in Somerville, Mass. ``I won't let that happen
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake I made was not staying in college. If I had, I
could have put the Pazienza fight in a more proper perspective
because school broadens your perspective. You realize what you're
doing now is just a part of your life. Without that perspective,
you can overglorify things and the stress of it can overwhelm you.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happened to me against Vinny. I wanted it so bad.
I was like a kid the night before Christmas who hopes for something
so bad he gets himself sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt and his tight group of advisers were all sick after a
bloodied and badly beaten Pazienza nailed him with an overhand
right to the face that knocked him into semiconsciousness just when
Rosenblatt seemed only minutes from victory. Rosenblatt went down
in a heap and was helpless when he got up, his body in Atlantic
City but his mind on siesta. So referee Tony Orlando wisely stopped
the bout with Rosenblatt slumped on the ropes and a frenzied
Pazienza continuing to pummel him.
</P>
<P>
   Such a beating came as a shock to the then undefeated
Rosenblatt. To have lost when things seemed to be so right was
troubling. And when that disappoinment was immediately followed by
a gutsy victory over Glenwood Brown in which he fought most of the
night with a broken hand, his confusion about the vagaries of the
boxer's life began to overwhelm him.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Rosenblatt was unable to train, and when he came
back too soon, he again broke the bones his first night in the gym.
They were not all that he shattered that evening.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Rosenblatt was now adrift. Boxing had been for too long his
anchor in life. It was not only what he did but it had slowly
become who he was. Now he could not box, so what was he left with?
</P>
<P>
   ``After I broke my hand, I realized what the real story was,''
Rosenblatt said of the 15-month layoff that followed. ``It's great
when you're on top and everyone's making a buck off your success,
but when you need to rebuild, some of those people are there and
some of them aren't. The ones who aren't are conspicuous by their
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Top Rank (Bob Arum's promotional company) was still with us,
but you no longer get the same attention. I'm not sour on the game
because of that, but I unfortunately look at it as a business now.
I still love boxing, but when I was off with my injury, I lost my
identity. I had no other source of enjoyment. All I did was sit
around and look at old tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the rigors of being a professional boxer wear on you.
You have a trainer and your family, but you carry the load. There's
no dissemination of the responsibility, and that sucks a lot out of
you. I understand now why some guys at the end are used up. They
leave their souls in the gym.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt could not accept that, just as he could not accept
that his loss to Pazienza would be not only the low point but also
the high point of his boxing career. He could not accept that he
would lose himself in a stuffy gymnasium or that he would lose his
career to a bad hand and a bad night.
</P>
<P>
   So the 26-year-old middleweight from Malden, Mass., did the
things he's trained himself to do. He thought things out first,
reviewing how he had gotten to this moment and what he had allowed
boxing to become. Then he fought back, something he intends to do
again Friday night against Norris. If the fight ends spectacularly
enough, it could convince Arum to try to match him with one of the
reigning junior middleweight champions if he cannot make a deal
with the middleweight titleholders controlled by rival promoter Don
King.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Rosenblatt will enter the ring looking at Norris far
differently than he did Pazienza. The desire to destroy him to
further his own ends will be vivid as always, but it will be about
business, not obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've changed my perspective on a lot of things,'' Rosenblatt
said. ``I used to pin my whole existence on each and every fight,
each and every round. I no longer do that. It doesn't help me. It
just adds to the tension, and you end up not being able to see the
forest for the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important day in my life. It has ramifications
for me. But I understand it for what it is ... and for what it is
not. I don't hinge my existence on boxing anymore. That doesn't
reflect on my wanting to succeed. I still want to win as much as
before. I'm just calmer about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to cause myself problems by trying to do too much. It
made me nuts. I learned after the Pazienza fight that when you're
just doing what you can do, you do it comfortably and you do it
well. When you try to do more than that, it wears you down. It
makes you weaker, not stronger. I'm stronger for this fight (than
for Pazienza). I know I've done everything I possibly could to get
ready for this moment. Now it's time to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt (32-1, 24 knockouts) assumes he will be given that
opportunity by an aggressive Norris. Norris (47-7, 31 KOs) is a
well-respected power puncher who is himself staring at a crossroads
after being stopped by WBC junior middleweight champion Keith
Mullings 10 months ago. Since then, Norris has done little but bide
his time and try to get over the shock of not only losing a world
title but also blowing a promised multimillion-dollar payday with
Oscar De La Hoya after abandoning one with Felix Trinidad to take a
chance on more riches with De La Hoya and his promoter, Arum.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, it appeared he would return to the ring in June against
old rival Julian Jackson, but that fight fell through, so the
boxing life has brought him to this moment _ a one-night meeting of
two fighters at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   One is young and just beginning to figure out what the boxing
game is really all about. The other is a 31-year-old ex-champion
who has been knocked cold too many times for his resume not to be
perceived these days as having a few holes in it. There is no more
margin of error left for Terry Norris and precious little of it for
Dana Rosenblatt. On that point, at least, all sides agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loser is in trouble,'' said Joe Lake, Rosenblatt's
longtime trainer. ``Dana feels he belongs in the eilte. He feels he
can compete with the best middleweights out there, so why not with
a junior middleweight, even an elite junior middleweight?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you keep fighting for $20,000 or step it up? You beat a
Terry Norris in spectacular fashion and you're right there. I'm
sure Norris was told Dana is ordinary. Got no sizzle. Everyone who
comes to fight Dana sees a white kid who doesn't look spectacular
on tape. They all think they can win until he hits them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dana and Terry are in the same situation in one way. They both
had a hard loss. But Norris is on his last legs. He loses and he's
through. We took our loss, too, and now we gotta win. That's the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Norris may be on the shady side of the hill, he is
clearly the best fighter Rosenblatt has faced, and the most
dangerous. So the younger man believes he knows what to expect from
him when the first bell sounds Friday night and the two go out to
fight for their fistic lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll come out early to test the white, Jewish kid,''
Rosenblatt said, a smile creasing his face as he spoke. ``I think
he'll be surprised that I can do more than he thought. I'm ready to
beat him down. Outbox him. Have my way with him without getting
extravagant. I'm not looking to be exciting this fight, like with
Vinny. I'm just looking to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If he can just do that, it will be quite a night for Dana
Rosenblatt. Quite a night and quite enough. Quite enough, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
