<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2964 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-NUKE-600&AMP;ADD-NY     09-24 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-NUKE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA WILLING TO SIGN TEST BAN TREATY, PRIME MINISTER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Miss., Ariz.)  (lh) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ India joined Pakistan Thursday in announcing
that it is prepared to sign the international treaty banning
nuclear testing within the next year, but said it is still
discussing details with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, speaking to the U.N.
General Assembly, said India had satisfied its security concerns
with its nuclear tests in May and is ready to cooperate in bringing
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty into force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to bring these discussions to a successful
conclusion so that the entry into force of the treaty is not
delayed beyond September 1999,'' Vajpayee said. The prime minister,
whose party is backed by Hindu nationalist organizations, spoke in
Hindi, breaking a long tradition of Indian leaders who spoke in
English at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration reacted cautiously to Vajpayee's
statement Thursday and to a similar pledge by Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif of Pakistan, who spoke on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously much remains to be done,'' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright told reporters here. She mentioned, for example,
the actual signing and ratification of the treaty, as well as the
strengthening of export controls by both countries and other steps
needed to bring India and Pakistan into full compliance with
international arms control agreements.
</P>
<P>
   If India and Pakistan carry out their pledges, North Korea will
stand alone in refusing to sign the treaty, and its refusal could
still prevent it from going into force a year from now, the
deadline for ratification set by a U.N. conference two years ago.
At that time, India opposed the treaty and tried to block its
passage. The Clinton administration has been negotiating with India
to change its approach.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vajpayee and Sharif lead governments that are vulnerable to
swings in public opinion fostered by their political enemies.
Nuclear testing has been popular in both countries, and intentions
stated here _ however qualified _ could unravel in the arena of
South Asian politics. India's scientific and nuclear establishment
has a large stake in the weapons program there, as the Pakistani
military does in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four countries with nuclear reactors _ though not
necessarily nuclear weapons _ must ratify the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty for it to take effect. Ten have done so. The United
States has signed, but the treaty is on hold in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, opponents of the treaty accused President Clinton
of bargaining away sanctions on India that were imposed after its
nuclear tests in May, in return for Indian support for the test-ban
treaty and another treaty barring the spread of nuclear weapons and
arms technology.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions were also imposed on Pakistan, which followed India
with tests of its own in May. On Wednesday, Sharif of Pakistan tied
the lifting of sanctions to his promise to sign the test-ban
accord. Sanctions have hit Pakistan hard.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to President Clinton last week, three Republican
senators _ Jesse Helms of North Carolina, who is chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee; Trent Lott of Mississippi, who is the
majority leader, and Jon Kyl of Arizona _ said they opposed lifting
sanctions as a price for adhering to nuclear agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the recent Indian nuclear tests demonstrated, the CTBT is
not adequately verifiable,'' the senators wrote. They said they
also opposed the export of high-technology goods to India and the
sharing of scientific information that can be used in nuclear
programs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Talks between the United States and India and Pakistan have been
going on almost continuously since their nuclear tests. The Indian
tests surprised and embarrassed the U.S. intelligence services, and
made tests by Pakistan virtually inevitable because of the rivalry
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott has been shuttling to
various meetings with South Asian officials. As the talks
progressed, arms control experts said, the bite of sanctions was
beginning to be felt in India as well as in Pakistan, and both
countries had reason to negotiate an end to their isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee said Thursday that India had accepted the principles of
the test ban treaty since its nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``After concluding this limited testing program, India announced
a voluntary moratorium on further underground nuclear explosions,''
he said. ``We conveyed our willingness to move toward a de jure
formalization of this obligation. In announcing a moratorium, India
has already accepted the basic obligation of the CTBT.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
