<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2975 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-092     09-24 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-0925-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GEORGES WHIPS ACROSS CUBA, HEADS TOWARD NERVOUS SOUTHERN FLORIDA
 &HT;    EDs: Story may need updating after 8 p.m. EDT.
 &HT;    With JOURNAL-HURRICANE-0925.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hurricane Georges continued its treacherous trek away
from Cuba late Thursday, and followed a path directed at the
Florida Keys, as rescuers carried out the grim task of pulling
bodies from mudslides and collapsed houses on the island of
Hispaniola.
</P>
<P>
   At least 116 people have died and hundreds more were missing
since the deadly storm began its rampage across the Caribbean last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane warning alerting people to hurricane conditions --
or winds of at least 74 mph -- within 24 hours was raised for
nearly four million residents in South Florida early Thursday,
closing schools and most offices.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency preparedness officials urged 540,000 people who live
in flood-prone areas to leave their homes. That included the flashy
condominiums on Miami Beach and the more-modest dwellings in
Homestead, a city hard-hit by Hurricane Andrew in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Packing gusts of up to 175 mph, Andrew inflicted $30 billion in
damage on South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   At Miami's Metrozoo, which has still not repaired all the damage
caused by Andrew, workers started moving animals to safety Thursday
morning. Officials ordered people living in mobile homes to move to
shelters or hotels. Florida Gov. Lawton Chiles declared a state of
emergency, allowing the state to use the National Guard and lift
tolls along evacuation routes.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout South Florida, residents continued to pack hardware
stores in search of scarce pieces of plywood to board up their
homes. Others were glued to their televisions as local stations
reported around-the-clock on everything from what to do with pets
to what to include in a first-aid kit.
</P>
<P>
   With Georges approaching, NASA decided to haul the space shuttle
Discovery off its launch pad in Cape Canaveral, although its
lift-off on Oct. 29 was not likely to be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also ordered some 80,000 residents of the Florida
Keys, where the storm is most likely to strike land in the United
States, to evacuate the 110-mile-long string of islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people who have stayed behind (in the Keys), you are
taking a tremendous risk,'' said National Hurricane Center director
Jerry Jarrell.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. EDT, the storm's center was about 255 miles southeast
of Key West. It was moving west-northwest at 14 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Sustaining winds of 80 mph, Georges was barely at hurricane
strength. But forecasters expected it to intensify to a Category 2
hurricane -- with winds between 96 and 110 mph -- as it moved out
over the warm waters of the Florida Straits overnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said that the Federal Emergency Management
Agency's six emergency response teams for the southeastern United
States had arrived in Tallahassee in anticipation of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   An agency spokeswoman added that FEMA has also set up a
mobilization center at Jacksonville's Naval Air Station on
Thursday, and had begun moving relief supplies and equipment --
such as generators and sleeping bags -- closer to the potentially
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Caribbean islands, businesses and homes have been swept
away,'' Clinton said during a White House news conference. ``We're
helping people in Florida prepare for the hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a 24-hour period, the storm dumped nearly a foot of rain
across eastern Cuba, where officials evacuated 500,000 people,
including thousands of tourists from resorts along the northern
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Georges destroyed crops, damaged infrastructure, and battered
coastlines with 20-foot waves.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro appeared on television Thursday for
the second day in a row to warn that even though Georges appeared
to be moving off the northern coast ``we can't be too trusting
because hurricanes play tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dominican Republic, which shares Hispaniola with
Haiti, appeared to bear the brunt of Georges' wrath so far.
</P>
<P>
   Dominican Republic President Leonel Fernandez said Thursday that
at least 70 people were dead and hundreds more were missing, while
100,000 people were homeless. Almost all electrical service was
wiped out, and the main airport remained closed. About 90 percent
of the agricultural crop was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The missing included 45 people who disappeared after the storm
washed a school shelter away on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez appealed for international aid, calling the storm ``a
national tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pray, and ask the Almighty to help the destiny of our
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Haiti, a desperately poor country of flimsy homes and a
fragile infrastructure, Georges killed 27 people and injured 29.
Many more were missing.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Development Program donated $100,000 for
disaster relief in Haiti, while the U.S. government donated water,
food, blankets, sheets, and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   In Puerto Rico, Georges inflicted an estimated $2 billion in
damages. Electricity was out across the U.S. territory of 3.8
million people, and service may not be restored in some places for
months.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-092     09-24 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-0925-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GEORGES WHIPS ACROSS CUBA, HEADS TOWARD NERVOUS SOUTHERN FLORIDA
