<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INCOME25-COX     09-24 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCOME25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POVERTY DOWN, INCOMES UP, CENSUS BUREAU REPORTS
 &HT;    With INCOME-DATA.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A strong economy has reduced poverty and raised
household income to their best levels in a decade, the Census
Bureau reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The South and West have fared especially well, helping to lift
millions of African Americans and Hispanics out of poverty, the
bureau said in an annual report.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking in the White House Rose Garden, said
the data represent ``one more year's worth of compelling evidence''
that his ``economic strategy is working.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the nation's economic gains under Clinton have done no
more than make up the ground lost during the 1989 recession,
prompting anti-poverty advocates to suggest further policy changes
to help poor and working families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only halfway there,'' said Deborah Weinstein, an
official of the Children's Defense Fund. ``The economy is strong,
but supports for working poor families are weak.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the new data, the share of Americans living in
poverty declined from 13.7 percent in 1996 to 13.3 percent last
year, the third straight year of declines. That translates to 35.6
million Americans living below federal poverty levels, which vary
for different-sized families.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, the median household income, adjusted
for inflation, rose 1.9 percent to $37,005.
</P>
<P>
   Regionally, the South recorded the largest percentage increase
in the median household income, 3.6 percent to $34,345, followed by
the West with 3.1 percent to $39,162, the Midwest with 2.4 percent
to $38,316 and the Northeast with virtually no change to $38,929.
</P>
<P>
   The West experienced the largest decline in poverty rates, 0.8
percent, followed by the South with 0.5 percent, the Midwest with
0.3 percent, and the Northeast with 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While the poverty rates for African Americans and Hispanics both
declined more than two percentage points in 1997, the country's two
major ethnic groups continue to be disproportionately represented
among the poor. Together, the two groups make up 22.8 percent of
the U.S. population but account for 47.8 percent of Americans
living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The new data also showed two long-term trends relatively
unchanged in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of those over 65 years of age in poverty dropped
to 10.5 percent, while the number of children in poverty remained
nearly double the elderly rate, 19.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the richest one-fifth of Americans continued to earn
about eight times as much aggregate income as the poorest
one-fifth, $126,550 compared to $15,400.
</P>
<P>
   This income inequality ``is still too high,'' Clinton said at
the White House. ``We have to use our prosperity, and the
confidence it inspires, to help our hardest-pressed families and
our hardest-pressed communities to ensure economic growth for all
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In an anaylsis of poverty data released in advance of the Census
Bureau report, the Heritage Foundation, a conservative public
policy organization, noted that the bulk of the poor in American
today live in material conditions that would have been judged
``comfortable and well-off `` just a few generations ago.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Americans are ``better housed, better fed, and own more
personal property than average Americans throughout most of this
century,'' said Robert Rector, a senior analyst at the Heritage
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a
liberal-oriented nonprofit organization, said the stength of the
economy and the lowest inflation rates in decades should have
reduced poverty rates even more than the decline recorded between
1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
