<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-505-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAN OF THE 505S COMPETES IN 38TH WORLD CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYANNIS, Mass. _ Cal Ripken finally sat one out, and so,
Wednesday, did Marcel Buffet.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference is that Buffet, the 76-year-old sailor from
LaCell, France, still has his streak intact. In the International
505 World Championships here this week, he is making his 38th
appearance. No one is even close.
</P>
<P>
   Given the one throwout score each boat is allowed, Buffet, still
lean and athletic with white hair framing a deeply tanned face,
decided that Wednesday's 25-knot winds here just might make this
the race to sit out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the wind blows like this,'' said Buffet in his heavy
French accent, ``I like it. I like strong wind, but I don't think
strong wind likes me.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from this regatta, Buffet races his 505, a high-tech
thoroughbred racing dinghy requiring equal parts quick thinking and
physical stamina, 130 days a year and has logged more than 4,000
regattas in his long career.
</P>
<P>
   The world championships that cap each season and bring sailors
from as far afield as Australia, Europe, and South Africa are the
focus of all 107 sailors here.
</P>
<P>
   This year a Massachusetts sailor _ Nick Trotman from Manchester
_ stands to win the worlds for the first time since 1982, when Gary
Knapp and Cam Lewis won it in Cork, Ireland. The year before in San
Francisco, Lewis crewed for Ethan Bixby in a winning entry, and in
1979, Steve Taylor from Yale won the regatta in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Trotman, 27, who sailed for Tufts, has been honing his 505
skills since his college days. He has been on the Team Racing World
Championship squad for the last five years and placed ninth in the
'95 world championships. For the past two years, Trotman and
crewmate Mike Mills have been among the top three teams on the East
Coast and narrowly missed winning last year's North American
Championships before winning the Canadian Championships this year.
</P>
<P>
   Racking up impressive finishes all week, including two firsts
and a second, Trotman said he and Mills are closing in on ``the No.
1 goal in my life right now. I just want to pull this regatta
off.''
</P>
<P>
   As with most 505 sailors, Trotman's devotion to this class grows
out of a belief that this double-handed dinghy is the best racer of
its size in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raced my first one in my freshman year (of college),'' said
Trotman, who has also raced Lasers. ``(505s) are really fun to
sail, especially on days like (Wednesday) when it blows. They just
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   As a cold front blew through the region, winds rose to 25 knots
off Hyannis, and the seas built to more than 5 feet. After some
light-air days, this was the day when the 505s lived up to their
reputation as high-powered, high-performance planing boats.
</P>
<P>
   The 505 is a one-design boat with emphasis on a dizzying number
of controls that sailors use to get maximum speed out of the sails
and hull in whatever conditions they face.
</P>
<P>
   The sailplan and hull shape are highly controlled by the rules,
but rigging layout, spars, and foils are open to a variety of
approaches. This allows customizing of rigs that, when thrown
together at a large regatta such as the worlds, can prove decisive.
Most US boats have adjustable shrouds, forestay, and mast ram _ all
of which allow the rig tension, rake, and bend of the mast to be
changed during competition. Technical mastery of this very
high-tech boat is thus part of the 505 sailor's repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the technical aspects, sailors describe the 505 in
terms of exhilarating speed and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me cut through the bull,'' said Allan Freedman, crew for
Rene De La Rie. ``Sailing a 505 in a breeze is the closest to God
you can get in any boat. When it's blowing 25, you surf off the
waves and you're flying. There's very little between yourself and
nature. You lose all sense of self. It just disappears, and you
just have this complete joy. It's just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what keeps Marcel Buffet coming back. And back and
back. Traveling with him is his wife, Huguette, who watches most of
his races through the year and ``makes the sandwiches,'' he said.
Buffet trains at a health club at least three times a week, rides a
bicycle, and swims at his health club for at least an hour a day.
But his tremendous fitness, he says, comes from sailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boat requires that you be active,'' he said, understating
the fact. ``You must move all the time, and there is need to have
strength and stamina.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffet puts 30,000 miles a year on his car, trailing his 505 all
over Europe to regattas. His job as a traveling salesman allowed
him to mix work and play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love being out there,'' he said. ``The wind and water,
the conditions, whatever they are ... it is all a pleasure for
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
