<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOG-0924-COX     09-24 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOG-0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EPA Moves Against Interstate Smog
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New federal regulations will require 22 Eastern
states to cut pollution by smog-causing nitrogen oxide a total of
more than 1.1 million tons during the next eight years, the
Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol M. Browner said most of the reductions
likely will come from new emission standards state officials will
impose on electric power plants, the largest and least-controlled
sources of the air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   She said the cost to power companies likely will add about $1 a
month to the average residential electric bill.
</P>
<P>
   EPA ordered the reductions but did not dictate where they must
be made. Browner said the most cost-effective means of meeting
mandated limits will be for state officials to take action against
the power industry.
</P>
<P>
   She said technologies needed to clean up industrial sources of
the pollution already are available.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation covers all states east of the Mississippi River
except Florida, Mississippi, Vermont, New Hampshire and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Affected states were assigned maximum levels of nitrogen oxides,
known as ``NOx,'' emissions they cannot legally exceed after 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The move was hailed by environmental groups, which have long
pressed federal officials to take action to limit nitrogen oxide
emissions that drift from state to state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several states that believe much of their smog
problems come from industrial smokestacks in other states had
petitioned EPA to restrict the emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly an historic action, one that will mean cleaner
air throughout the Midwest and the East,'' said Frank O'Donnell,
executive director of the Clean Air Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA has stood with the public and not with the polluters
today,'' said Jennifer Lyons, a spokesperson for the Georgia
AirKeepers Campaign. ``Now it is up to the state of Georgia and the
Southern Co. to implement this plan in a meaningful way to protect
public health.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan would reduce emissions that otherwise would occur that
year _ given expected growth between now and then _ by an average
of 28 percent, EPA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 2007 we anticipate that this action will cut 1.1 million
tons of nitrogen oxide emissions each year in these states,''
Browner said. ``As a result of this action, 138 million Americans
living in the eastern United States will breathe cleaner air.''
</P>
<P>
   She said 31 million people will for the first time breathe air
that meets national public health standards for smog.
</P>
<P>
   Browner said EPA estimated that the annual cost of meeting the
limits will be $1.7 billion in the 22 states. The benefits,
primarily in reduced respiratory illness in urban areas, will be
$3.4 billion, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Modernizing a typical coal-burning power plant to achieve the
mandated reductions would cost about $4.5 million annually, she
said. Such a plant has revenues of $130 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
