<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLSWORTH KELLY ON THE WALL IN BOSTON; MANOOGIAN LEAVES THE ART
WORLD; A NEW DEALER FOR MORRIS LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Mich., N.Y.)  (js) 
 BY CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In May, New York celebrated Ellsworth Kelly's 75th
birthday, opening an exhibition of five of his sculptures on the
roof of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. There were also two other
Kelly shows in town, at Matthew Marks' Chelsea galleries, one of a
1957 wall sculpture and the other of recent paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Boston's turn to toast the post-war American artist.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Boston's new U.S. courthouse opens to the public,
and throughout the building is ``The Boston Panels'' (1998), the
largest wall sculpture ever created by Kelly. Meanwhile, several
local museums are also showing the artist's work. For Kelly, this
is a home-coming of sorts. The artist graduated from the Boston
Museum School, now the School of the Museum of Fine Arts, in 1948.
He said he remembered his student days when he would go down to
Atlantic Avenue, near the South Boston waterfront where the
courthouse is located, to buy his canvases and art supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought I would be asked to create a large
sculpture here?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those visiting the courthouse, which has been designed by Henry
Cobb, a partner of the New York architectural firm of Pei Cobb
Freed &AMP; Partners, will see 21 brilliantly colored aluminum panels
installed as a single work throughout the building. In the
courthouse's central rotunda, a space 90 feet high and 45 feet in
diameter, nine horizontal panels, 11 feet by 13-and-a-half feet,
create a visual tension against the curved walls. From the rotunda,
visitors can see 12 other vertical colored panels, 11 feet by 88
inches, on each floor of the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the public places you can see fragments of color,''
said Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   At night, from the harbor, the panels act as beacons of color,
punctuating all three floors.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was chosen by a committee of community representatives,
including U.S. Supreme Court Justice Stephen Breyer, who is from
Boston, and federal Judge Douglas Woodlock, along with several arts
professionals and Cobb. The committee was formed under the auspices
of the General Services Administration in Washington. Kelly was
chosen from over 380 artists who made submissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Ellsworth Kelly's first commission from us,'' said
Barbara Harrison, who is the chief of the Art and Architecture
program for the General Services Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Cobb, the architect, knew who the artist involved
would be, he said he left places deliberately incomplete
specifically for an artwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the only pure white surfaces,'' he said. ``The rest
of the building is brick. You encounter Ellsworth Kelly as you move
throughout the building. The panels and the walls talk to each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to see examples of Kelly's work from different
periods of his career can visit the Museum of Fine Arts Boston,
where a painting from 1952, ``Tableau Vert,'' along with four water
lily drawings from 1968, are part of ``Reflections of Monet,'' a
companion show to its blockbuster ``Monet in the 20th Century.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Fogg Art Museum, Harvard University, there are four Kelly
paintings _ one from the 1960s, two from the 1970s and one from the
1980s _ that make up ``Black with Color: Four Paintings by
Ellsworth Kelly.'' The show is in anticipation of a larger
traveling exhibition of the artist's drawings dating from 1948-54
that opens at the Fogg in April.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of Kelly's recent prints is currently on view at
the Boston University Art Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all timed our projects with the opening of the
courthouse so the public could get a greater understanding of
Kelly's work,'' said John Stomberg, director of the Boston
University gallery.
</P>
<P>
   A Collection for Sale
</P>
<P>
   In the world of American paintings, Richard Manoogian is a big
player. As chairman of Masco Corp., the Detroit-based leader in
home improvement and building equipment, he has been a major buyer
in the field, both for himself and for Masco. The corporation also
owns Beacon Hill, an American art gallery at 980 Madison Ave.
</P>
<P>
   But when Masco divested itself of its furniture division two
years ago, it began reviewing its various other activities and
eventually decided to get out of the art business, Manoogian said.
So at the end of the year it will be closing Beacon Hill. And this
fall it will be selling off its corporate art collection at
Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a corporate decision,'' Manoogian said. ``We decided
it was best to focus our resources in other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The works for sale at Sotheby's consist primarily of American
paintings but include some European works. While Manoogian said he
was still in the process of deciding what would be sold, sources
close to the auction house said they believed he was selling about
$10 million worth of art.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Debra Force, director of Beacon Hill, said she
planned to sell the gallery's inventory, which consists of a few
hundred American paintings, privately. Once the gallery closes, she
said, she will become a private dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Manoogian stressed that he still plans to buy American art for
himself. So far his collection ranges from mid 19th-century
landscapes through the Ash Can school of the early 20th-century.
</P>
<P>
   New Dealer for Louis
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The estate of the color-field painter Morris Louis,
who has been represented by the Andre Emmerich Gallery, will now be
handled by Diane Upright, a private dealer who wrote the artist's
catalog raissonne.
</P>
<P>
   Louis' work had been handled by Emmerich for more than 30 years,
during his lifetime and after the artist's death in 1962. But Ann
Garfinkle, Louis' estate lawyer thought it was time for a change.
After last week's news that the Emmerich Gallery at 41 E. 57th St.,
which was bought by Sotheby's two years ago, was closing its doors
next month, and that its artists would be handled out of Deitch
Projects, the Grand Street gallery of which the auction house owns
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morris Louis belongs in upper Manhattan,'' Ms. Garfinkle said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON25-COX     09-24 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CHALLENGES CONGRESS TO ADDRESS HIS ISSUES
 &HT;    470&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Challenging Congress to turn away from the rhetoric
of impeachment and ''think about the American people,'' President
Clinton called Thursday for action on issues ranging from education
to shoring up the global banking system.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is utterly foolish for people to be diverted or distracted
from the urgent challenges still before us,'' Clinton said during a
White House event in the Rose Garden intended to spotlight recent
economic gains.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he saw any way of avoiding House impeachment
proceedings, Clinton fired off a list of other matters he said
matter more.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way out here, and the only way out, is for people in
Washington to do what the folks in America want them to do, which
is to take care of their concerns, their children, and their
future,'' Clinton said. ''That's what I mean to do, and I'm going
to do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks continued a campaign he embarked upon two
weeks ago to largely ignore the sex and deception scandal that has
enmeshed his presidency and engage an array of high-profile
domestic and international issues.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say, however, that Clinton is continuing to work on the
Monica Lewinsky matter behind the scenes with legislators and
clerics _ and with the help of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton,
who's been making telephone calls on his behalf to key Democrats on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress set to recess Oct. 9 to allow members to campaign
for the Nov. 3 midterm elections, Clinton chided lawmakers for not
fully funding his proposals to hire 100,000 new teachers for public
schools across the country, to rehabilitate or expand 5,000 public
schools, and to connect schools in low-income areas to the Internet
computer network.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called on Congress to pass a ''Patients' Bill of
Rights'' aimed at protecting low-income and medium-income Americans
from being denied quality health care in times of dire need.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our bill would provide protections to all Americans, simple
ones,'' Clinton said. ''If you get in an accident, you can go to
the nearest emergency room, not be hauled to one halfway across
town. If your doctor tells you, 'You need to see a specialist,' you
can see one. If it comes down to a dispute about whether a medical
procedure should or should not be applied, the decision should be
made by a doctor, not an accountant.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have set forth their own health-care protection
plan, but Clinton has criticized it as inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also hammered House Republicans for failing to pass his
request for $17.9 billion in additional deposits in the
International Monetary Fund. The money is needed, Clinton said, to
help replenish the fund, which has been largely depleted over the
past 18 months by efforts to prop up a series of crumbling
economies across the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ''The International Monetary Fund helps the countries that are
helping themselves to return to growth and serves as an insurance
policy against having the financial crisis spread to the countries
that are doing the right thing and keeping Americans
</P>
<P>
   at work by buying our products,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no reason not to do this,'' Clinton said. ''It's what
America owes as the world leader and ...it is absolutely necessary
to keep American economic growth going.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton's legal team continued working with House members to
try to head off impeachment proceedings, White House aides said
Mrs. Clinton has been working the telephones to try to smooth
roiled relations between the president and key Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she had become involved, White House spokesman Michael
McCurry responded, ''I presume because she loves her husband and
she supports him.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry stressed that the First Lady's liaison role was likely
her own idea, not the president's.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the president is in a position to make that
request of her,'' McCurry told reporters. ''I think that is
something that she, being gracious as she is, volunteers to do. It
would be consistent with who she is and what she's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's press spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, confirmed the
recent contacts, but would not name the members called nor specify
the nature of the conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's certainly making clear to them that she's proud of her
husband,'' said Berry. ''She's just showing her continued support
for the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
