<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3044 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLLS-KAN &LR;      09-24 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PRESS FOR IMPEACHMENT; MOST AMERICANS WANT CLINTON TO
STAY IN OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: As congressional Republicans explore the prospects of
impeaching President Clinton, a sturdy American majority looks at
the president's transgressions and...yawns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That disconnect has been constant throughout this,'' Raymond
Wolfinger, a political scientist at the University of California,
Berkeley. ``You've got Washington pursuing this one way and the
polls pointed in another direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the task of impeaching a president is so purposefully
political, Clinton's showy poll numbers would appear to offer some
job security.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, describe a more complex political picture
framed first by the founding fathers. And though two-thirds of
Americans tell pollsters that Clinton should stay, those numbers
may be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders insist contemplation of impeachment is a
solemn responsibility best considered with a sober look at the
facts _ not by holding a finger to the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people would be frankly horrified if the Congress was
simply a polling institution that enacted a grotesque version of
justice based on the latest poll or the latest talk show,'' House
Speaker Newt Gingrich told reporters Wednesday following a meeting
of GOP and Democratic congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Constitution's rules for firing a president are sort of
a shotgun marriage of politics and jurisprudence.
</P>
<P>
   Short of bribery or treason, Congress must find offenses to fit
into the elastic category of ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' to
unseat a president.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate definition of impeachable offense is so fluid, in
fact, that Alexander Hamilton worried in the Federalist Papers that
``there will always be the greatest danger that the decision will
be regulated more by the comparative strength of parties, than by
the real demonstrations of innocence or guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   As Congress sorts through the complex _ and constitutionally
unclear _ issue of whether the evidence collected by Kenneth Starr
warrants impeachment, the polls make for an unreliable compass for
the politicians. Even at the low point of the Watergate scandal, 49
percent of Americans did not want Richard Nixon impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most striking finding from polling on Watergate is how
slowly and reluctantly many Americans came to accept the idea of
ousting a president,'' said Everett Ladd, a polling expert with
Roper.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion, made more relevant as the Nov. 3 congressional
elections creep ever closer, looms over this drama every bit as
much as the president bantering about sex on the telephone or Linda
Tripp's tape recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the scandal, the president's job ratings have
remained above 55 percent. An ABC News survey conducted the day
after Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony was released, found
56 percent of Americans opposed impeachment even if he lied under
oath about his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll conducted for CBS News the same day that found a
majority concluding Clinton perjured himself, 61 percent still said
he should finish his term as president.
</P>
<P>
   And while only 20 percent of people in a CNN//USA Today//Gallup
poll shared Clinton's tortured definition that sexual relations
only includes intercourse and 62 percent thought he looked like ``a
guilty person trying to hide something'' in his testimony, 66
percent believed he should not be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``His poll numbers are pretty solid,'' said Jonathan Krasno, a
senior policy analyst at the Brennan Center for Justice at New York
University Law School. ``For a long time, everyone was waiting for
the other shoe to drop. Now it looks as if the evidence is out.
Most of it was leaked ahead of time and that other shoe never
fell.''
</P>
<P>
   Krasno speculates that journalists cling to the story because it
sells, and because to back off would seem to give quarter to a
slippery politician. Members of the House and Senate, he said, have
their own motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are on top of this because they hate Clinton,'' he
said, ``and Democrats are worried that hating Clinton is the proper
course to take right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives carp that guilt or innocence _ even with something
as deliberately political as impeachment _ shouldn't run on poll
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media are saying `I dare you to go against the polls,' ''
said Tim Graham of the conservative Media Research Center.
``They're polling this to death. They're taking popularity ratings
on the independent prosecutor. We didn't do that during Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing polling does is measure the success of White
House attack lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the polls, Republican legislators report that their
letters, e-mail, faxes and phone calls from constituents run
strongly for booting Clinton from office. For example, the offices
of both U.S. Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri and U.S. Rep. Vince
Snowbarger of eastern Kansas said that upward of 85 percent of the
constituent opinion they've received demands the president's
ouster.
</P>
<P>
   As British envoy James Bryce wrote 110 years ago, ``In a free
country...ten men who care are worth a hundred who do not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All these polls we're seeing should be taken as pretty
reliable, in part because they say the same thing,'' said Don
Dixon, a political scientist and pollster at Sonoma State
University, near Santa Rosa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to look beyond the poll numbers here...You've got
a class of absolute Clinton haters that's active and has itself in
a position of power.''
</P>
<P>
   That contingent, still a minority but convinced of the
seriousness of Clinton's failings, stands in contrast to a more
ambivalent and possibly more pivotal middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have conflicting opinions are more likely to change
their minds,'' said Gallup pollster Frank Newport.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the eight months of the Monica Lewinsky scandal,
polls have revealed what seems to be an American public at odds
with itself: They dislike Clinton but think he's an excellent
president; they don't want him impeached but want Congress to
conduct impeachment hearings; they want their president to be a
moral leader, and say Clinton is a poor moral leader but a good
president.
</P>
<P>
   Poll data lump about 30 percent of Americans into that
bad-boy-good-president mindset. The rest either dislike him on both
fronts or like him all around.
</P>
<P>
   Another point that gives conservatives cheer in the November
elections is that most polls sample the general U.S. population,
not the smaller pool of registered voters. Last week a
CNN//Gallup//USA Today poll found that likely voters treated
Clinton more harshly. Only 24 percent of Americans overall favored
impeachment opposed to 34 percent of likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Republican majority in Congress argues it must
make its own judgment about whether Clinton lied under oath and
whether such perjury about his sex life meets a reasonable standard
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting ourselves into a very dangerous situation if we
determine that a person can get away with conduct that is
inappropriate if he's popular,'' said Snowbarger. ``The other side
of that argument is that if you're unpopular and you haven't done
anything wrong you could be taken out.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be times when the polls be damned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
