<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEGRITY STILL SERVES POSITIVE ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Some things float atop pond scum.
</P>
<P>
   I submit as examples two books with arrestingly similar titles:
``Winning With Integrity'' and ``Winning Through Integrity''.
</P>
<P>
   Both books float. They elevate ethical thought far above the
sexual//political swamp that engulfs national and workplace
conversations of late.
</P>
<P>
   The ``With'' book is new. It was produced this year by Leigh
Steinberg, a California sports agent who was the model and
consultant for film character Jerry Maguire.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Through'' book was published in 1985. It was written by
Kansas City businessman and former Greater Kansas City Chamber of
Commerce Chairman Cliff C. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg's formula for ``getting what you're worth without
selling your soul'' focuses on negotiating to achieve win-win
outcomes _ with your win being more satisfying than the other
guy's, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' formula for successful business conduct leans heavily
toward following the Ten Commandments and other biblical teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of the title similarity, I pulled Jones' book
from my bookshelves and scanned it before talking to Steinberg, who
was scheduled in Kansas City for a book tour appearance with a
client, Derrick Thomas of the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   There are common threads running through both men's messages in
buoyant counterweight to the scummy national soap opera. Here are
some pertinent pulled threads:
</P>
<P>
   - The first step in choosing to do business ethically is to
choose to do business with ethical people.
</P>
<P>
   - It's important to find common ground, or at least to
understand what makes the other person tick, to establish a
mutually satisfactory relationship.
</P>
<P>
   - If someone is not a ``man of his word,'' not much else
matters.
</P>
<P>
   - One must believe in the quality of one's service, products,
bosses and fellow workers in order to be a good advocate for any of
them.
</P>
<P>
   - No negotiation, no sale, no personal interaction is a one-time
thing; any temporary advantage gained by lying or blustering is
likely to destroy long-term credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say Steinberg's success as a sports agent is a
``nice guys finish first'' story. He thinks his negotiation trail
is clean because he connects with clients and general managers as
individuals _ not as income generators (although that certainly
happens) or conquests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're attempting to work out a win-win situation, the
hardest thing to do is to get the other side to communicate
honestly and openly,'' Steinberg said. ``We give false agendas all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must get the true, critical priorities and the true bottom
line from the other person so that you don't waste a lot of time
talking about something that isn't really at issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, anecdotes of ethical connections ripple through
Jones' book. In keeping with the current national obsession, I'm
choosing to excerpt his observations about one of the Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the loosening of many moral restraints,'' Jones
wrote, ``it is simply not good business to have someone advancing
to top management who has little respect for the vows of
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Both books make it clear that integrity is won through daily
choices and actions. Choose wisely and float. Choose poorly and
sink.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
