<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE RHYTHM OF THE WILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHELATNA LAKE, Alaska _ Our gear had been stowed aboard the
float plane, a red Beaver, at its berth in Anchorage. But a weather
front, blowing up darkly from the south, threatened to delay our
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Bertke, the lodge owner, was on the radiophone, checking
conditions between Anchorage and this lake 100 miles north. Larry,
our pilot, was waiting for the word.
</P>
<P>
   Duke bounded out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming in fast,'' he said. ``But if we launch right now
we can get out ahead of it. Might be just a little bumpy at the
start.''
</P>
<P>
   So we scrambled up into our seats _ wife Katie, daughters Anne
and Jennie and I. The plane's engine roared to life, and shortly we
were airborne, skimming above a terrain of mixed marshland and
spruce-poplar forest, buffeted by wind gusts as we gained altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, in a faster plane, would dash on ahead to be at the lodge
before us.
</P>
<P>
   A second Beaver, the yellow one, had brought another group in, a
party from Texas. Lodgings were four handsome little chalets, each
with two bedrooms, large front windows giving a spectacular view
down this long lake, stirred now to a chop.
</P>
<P>
   At the far end were sharp-toothed peaks, some with snowfields
near their summits. And just beyond that ridge lay Denali National
Park, where a savage wilderness of shattered stone rose toward the
flanks of Mount McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, Becky Bertke, Duke's wife and partner, briefed all us
newcomers on the camp routine.
</P>
<P>
   Front doors of the chalets should be left unlocked so that, at
precisely 7 a.m., one of the housekeeping staff could leave a pot
of hot coffee on the sitting room table to announce the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast would follow at 7:30, ordered from a full menu.
Luncheon materials would be laid out on a sideboard in the dining
room, and fisherfolk could make sandwiches and select beverages
that would accompany them by plane to whichever stream they'd
chosen to fish that day.
</P>
<P>
   Planes would collect the fishing parties and guides about 4:30
in the afternoon and return them to the lodge in time for a shower
or sauna before cocktails at 6 and dinner at 7.
</P>
<P>
   Becky had no more than concluded this recitation of delights
when one of the Texans gave a startled cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look there!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A black bear had appeared out of the bushes on the hillside
between the main lodge and the chalets below and had come up to
amble across the yard and express some interest in the goings-on
inside.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no expert, but this one certainly appeared to me to be a
significant bear, probably somewhere between 250 and 10,000 pounds,
depending on whether you were observing him at 20 yards, from
inside the dining room, or at five yards, say, from outside on the
steps.
</P>
<P>
   It was a small adventure, but sufficient to remind us that
Alaska is not just any other place.
</P>
<P>
   The reckless dogs of two of the guides went yipping after the
creature and sent it scuttling away to cover. We were assured,
though, that there'd be other chances for bear-watching _ in the
evenings from a platform constructed for that purpose near a pond
behind the lodge.
</P>
<P>
   It was time, then, to get ourselves fitted for wading boots, rig
fly rods and make a quick run down Lake Creek, Chelatna's outlet,
to see if we might find a gullible trout or two.
</P>
<P>
   My daughters and I fished with guides Wade Elg, of Anchorage,
and Will Hodge, from Colorado. The water was running hard, more
than knee-deep even in the riffles, and a brisk wind made the
casting difficult. But the drizzle lessened as the afternoon drew
on, and finally stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Jennie caught a nice rainbow and admired it a moment before Will
slipped the barbless hook from its lip. Anne lost what appeared to
be a good fish. I missed two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   With a storm still threatening, the light began to fail early.
We motored back upstream to the lake and the lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Several days of almost unceasing rain have put the creek high,
so it was an unremarkable first couple of hours of fishing. But
that was only a warmup, in any case. It's the silver salmon we've
come here for, and we'll try those tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner we took the trail down to the bear platform. Our
friend the black bear had been there earlier, one of the Texas men
told us, but had left the area to a cinnamon-colored grizzly sow
and her two hefty cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The sure knowledge that one shortly will be walking to one's
quarters through the woods in near darkness, with bears not 100
yards along the path in the other direction, tends to activate the
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   We did not linger long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
