<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER NOTES: HEDONISM AGAIN AT STUDIO 54; ALBEE'S LINGERING
ANGER; QUICK-CHANGE ARTIST; EXTENDED PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For ``Cabaret,'' it's auf Wiedersehen to the Kit Kat
Klub on West 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of rumors, officials at the Roundabout Theater
Company, the musical's producer, confirmed that the show's run at
the club would end in early November. ``Cabaret'' is to move to
refurbished and significantly larger quarters once occupied by the
defunct Studio 54, on West 54th Street near Eighth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The shift comes amid a flurry of legal threats and accusations
of bad faith. The story involves Douglas Durst, who owns the Henry
Miller Theater and rented it to Club Expo, which later struck an
agreement with the Roundabout to use the space as its Kit Kat Klub,
where ``Cabaret'' takes place. The club owners say they expected
the relationship to last for three more years and now say they feel
betrayed by Durst and the Roundabout's management.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like stick-em-up 43rd Street,'' said Matthew Johnson, a
co-owner of the club. ``And Douglas Durst is wearing the mask.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories behind the move conflict. Johnson said he believed
that the Roundabout had committed to using the space as its Kit Kat
Klub for $3 million over three years, starting in 1999. ``We shook
on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout's general manager, Ellen Richard, said that in
negotiations the theater had offered $1 million up front for
continuing use of the space but that no agreement had been reached.
Todd Haimes, the artistic director of the Roundabout, said the
theater would fulfill the obligations of the current agreement,
which runs through December.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations apparently fell apart shortly after Labor Day,
when the Roundabout told Johnson it had decided to relocate the
show. Despite the approximately $1.5 million it would cost to move
and recreate the nightclub environment, Haimes said the change
would allow the Roundabout to sell about 950 seats a show instead
of 520.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that Durst, who is on the Roundabout's board of
directors, pressured the show to move so he could evict the club.
</P>
<P>
   Durst declined to comment on Johnson's accusations, but said he
had served the club with an eviction notice, and that his company,
the Durst Organization, hoped to use the Henry Miller as a
full-time theater rather than a nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he planned to sue Durst, but regretted the loss of
the show. ``We were like family,'' he said. ``That's gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   On this point, at least, there is agreement. ``It has not been a
happy marriage,'' Ms. Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   Second Thoughts
</P>
<P>
   When dozens of prominent theater artists and First Amendment
groups issued a statement last Friday saluting the Manhattan
Theater Club's ``brave decision'' to stage Terrence McNally's
``Corpus Christi,'' Edward Albee was one of the biggest names on
the list of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, Albee said he had asked for his name to be
removed because of his lingering anger regarding the theater's
initial decision in May to cancel the production based on fears of
violent protests. The play, which depicts a gay Christ-like figure,
has outraged religious and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was too congratulatory to MTC for having changed
its mind in the face of its first cowardice,'' Albee said.
Reinstating the play was ``self-serving,'' he added, because the
theater did so only after other artists harshly criticized the
cancellation, and after playwright Athol Fugard pulled the rights
to produce his new play, ``The Captain's Tiger.'' (Fugard changed
his mind when the theater changed its position.)
</P>
<P>
   Artists endorsing the seven-paragraph statement include
playwrights Tony Kushner and Arthur Miller, as well as the PEN
American Center and the National Coalition Against Censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Meadow, the artistic director of the Manhattan Theater
Club, declined to comment on Albee's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corpus Christi,'' which began previews amid protests on
Tuesday, officially opens on Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Revisiting a Muse
</P>
<P>
   On a dusky afternoon in a diner in Hell's Kitchen, Everett
Quinton leaned over a bowl of blood-red Jell-O and explained the
precise calculus of the quick change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the audience can count to two and you're back out there,
you'll get a laugh,'' he said in a husky whisper. ``If it's three,
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinton has good reason to be obsessed with timing. As half of a
two-man cast in the revival of ``The Mystery of Irma Vep,'' Quinton
is responsible for the quicksilver antics of four characters, all
of whom nearly meet themselves at some point during the play. Two
of his characters actually struggle with each other during the
second act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irma Vep,'' which opens on Thursday night at the Westside
Theater, is a loony takeoff on vampires, ``Wuthering Heights'' and
mummy movies. Written by Charles Ludlam, it was a surprise hit in
1984, with Ludlam and Quinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've figured out something beautiful about the play: It just
doesn't add up,'' said Quinton, 46, with a laugh. Indeed, the
biggest laugh of a recent performance came when Quinton, in drag
and out of breath, stumbled on and announced, ``Somehow this all
doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play's latest incarnation, Quinton has taken on the roles
previously played by Ludlam, who died of AIDS in 1987. Stephen
DeRosa plays the roles that Quinton originated.
</P>
<P>
   In a tale that plays fast and loose with ghosts and goblins,
Quinton said that performing the roles of Ludlam, who was his
mentor and lover, has conjured some spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles is still there,'' he said. ``In the words. And the
lunacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Evergreen
</P>
<P>
   ``Visiting Green,'' a play by Jeff Baron scheduled to close on
Oct. 4, has been extended until the end of the year at the Union
Square Theater. Its producer, Arnold Mittelman, said a surge in
ticket sales after a series of ``last weeks'' advertisements and
the postponement of another show, ``Band in Berlin,'' made the
extension possible. David Margulies is to take over the role of
Green, a curmudgeonly 86-year-old, from Hal Linden on Oct. 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
