A3065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-MEDICINE-092     09-24 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-MEDICINE-0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A hastily arranged shift in Pentagon spending
priorities Thursday erased shortfalls of more than $600 million in
the military medical care system budget.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons general of the Army, Air Force and Navy told a
House subcommittee Thursday that within hours of their scheduled
appearance before the subcommittee, they were told $623 million in
other Defense Department funds would be diverted to medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received a commitment (from Undersecretary of Defense Rudy
de Leon) that we would receive the funding necessary to carry out
our health care mandate,'' Lt. Gen. Ronald Blanck, the Army surgeon
general, told the subcommittee. He said the money would be shifted
from elsewhere in the Defense Department budget.
</P>
<P>
   The action heads off a crisis in the military medical care
system for fiscal year 1999, which begins next week.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 budget, which was approved this week by Congress,
provides the amounts the Defense Department had sought to fund each
service's network of hospitals and clinics.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfall represents the difference between the minimum
amount the surgeons general say would be necessary to operate the
military medical system and the amount Defense Department budget
writers had requested for them.
</P>
<P>
   Blanck said he was promised an addition of $233 million for his
budget. The Air Force medical care system will receive an
additional $194 million and Navy medicine will get an extra $196
million.
</P>
<P>
   The three surgeons general told the House National Security
subcommittee on personnel that without the additional money they
could not have provided acceptable medical care to members of the
country's armed services, their dependents and a growing community
of military retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee staff members stumbled onto the medical care
shortfall while doing research on an unrelated Defense Department
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Irked members of the subcommittee questioned how the Defense
Department could discover only a week before a yearly budget goes
into effect that it had failed to adequately budget funds for
medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ink isn't even dry on the (budget),'' said subcommittee
chairman Steve Buyer, R-Ind., ``and we're suddenly faced with an
underfunding of over $600 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyer said military medical care has been underfunded in the
Pentagon's budget requests for several years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons general said they told Defense Department budget
planners a year ago how much money it would take to run the medical
care system _ and did not learn until June how much they would
receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walk a tightrope of being advocates for our patients and
providing them with the best patient care and at the same time
working in the system as good soldiers,'' Blanck said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
