<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3069 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPORTED-FOOD-HNS &LR;      09-24 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPORTED-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH EXPERTS URGE OVERHAUL OF FOOD IMPORTS RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Health experts urged the Senate Thursday to require
that countries exporting fruits and vegetables to the United States
meet American production and sanitation standards to ensure the
safety of the growing amount of imported goods.
</P>
<P>
   William B. Schultz, deputy commissioner for policy at the Food
and Drug Administration, said short-staffed government inspectors
can't possibly detect every disease-causing germ in imported
produce during quick border checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole new approach is needed,'' said Schultz, who testified
at a food safety hearing before a Senate Governmental Affairs
subcommittee. ``We can no longer simply rely on inspections on the
border. We must find a way to go to the source of the potential
contamination.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said the FDA inspects only 1.7 percent of the imported
fruits, vegetables, grains and cheeses because the agency doesn't
have enough inspectors to check the 2.7 million shipments that
enter the country each year.
</P>
<P>
   More food safety workers are needed to examine production
conditions at foreign farms that export produce to the United
States, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress also needs to grant federal food safety officials the
authority to refuse imports that don't meet U.S. production
standards, Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the foreign producers, he said: ``We need a way not
just to work with them but to make them listen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is pressing for exactly that in a
bill introduced in March by Sen. Barbara A. Mikulski, D-Md. The
legislation would ban any imported produce, grains or seafood that
aren't produced, handled or transported in accordance with U.S.
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Agriculture already requires that imported
meat and poultry meet U.S. standards. Other imports, such as cars
and prescription drugs, also must comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't be able to import foods that aren't up to U.S.
safety standards,'' Mikulski said.
</P>
<P>
   Mikulski said about 40 percent of the nation's fruits and
vegetables are imported. The amount of imported food has more than
doubled over the last seven years, she said, and demand continues
to surge.
</P>
<P>
   Mikulski's legislation is one of a dozen proposals in Congress
designed to curb food-borne diseases, which cause more than 80
million cases of illness each year and as many as 9,000 deaths,
according to the Government Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sanford A. Miller, dean of biomedical sciences at the
University of Texas Health Science Center at San Antonio, testified
that the only way to reduce the risks of food-borne illnesses from
imported food is to examine how it is produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the bottom line,'' said Miller, who served on National
Academy of Sciences panel that recently issued a report on ensuring
safe food. ``You have to see where it's grown. We've got to be
working with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said requiring foreign producers of imported food to
adhere to U.S. standards should eliminate much of the risk of
food-borne illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly can't ask other countries to do better than
ourselves,'' Miller said after the Senate hearing. ``On the whole,
the food supply to the American people is pretty safe because the
standards we have are enforceable standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Billy, administrator of the Department of
Agriculture's Food Safety and Inspection Service, said the agency
has certified that 37 nations have adequate production standards
and 20 more ``are lined up to demonstrate they have equivalent
systems to the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this idea of equivalency is at the heart of our
success,'' Billy said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has said in the past that it does not have sufficient
inspectors to cover every port. Thursday's hearing was part of a
series on food safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
