<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISAS-INCREASE-BOS &LR;      09-24 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISAS-INCREASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL STRUCK TO EXPAND FLOW OF SKILLED FOREIGN WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Congress and the White House have reached a deal
to allow more foreign workers to take skilled jobs in the United
States, delighting high-tech companies and drawing protests from
labor groups.
</P>
<P>
   The House quickly ratified the agreement Thursday in a 288-133
vote after negotiators brokered it late Wednesday. Prospects for
the bill in the Senate are high.
</P>
<P>
   Employers, particularly high-tech companies, have complained
that the robust economy and low unemployment rate make it hard to
find qualified workers. They asked Congress to increase the quota
of foreign skilled workers that can be hired on so-called H-1B
visas, which now stands at 65,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, software-maker Cognex Inc. of Natick said
earlier this year that a high-tech workers shortage had forced it
to send work overseas, and Keane Inc. of Boston said it had
expanded its recruitment team to 100 people to keep the
8,600-worker company staffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prowl the halls of the universities to find people,'' said
Richard Egan, chairman of EMC Corp. of Hopkinton. ``We have
research and development in Ireland, France, New Delhi, Tel Aviv,
becuase we can't get enough engineers and scientists here.''
</P>
<P>
   But labor groups opposed any increase in visas, presenting
prickly politics for the White House, which counts both organized
labor and the high-tech community among its supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The labor groups said that employers would draw more US workers
if they merely raised wages. ``Generally, we are very unhappy about
this deal,'' said John Reinert, president of the Institute of
Electrical and Electronics Engineers-USA, a professional society of
219,000 electronics and computer engineers. ``The evidence doesn't
suggest that there is a labor shortage, and there is no need to
increase the number of visas.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's allotment of visas ran out in May, leaving employers
without new visas until the new fiscal year begins on October 1.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal approved Thursday by the House, employers will be
able to hire 115,000 skilled foreign workers in the next fiscal
year and in the year 2000. The cap will drop to 107,500 in 2001 and
return to 65,000 in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   H-1B visas are good for six years and are typically used to
employ computer workers, nurses, physicians, fashion models and a
range of other skilled workers at jobs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and many Democratic lawmakers have said that any
increase in visas must be accompanied by improved programs to train
US workers for high-tech jobs. The deal would spend $75 million
annually on new job training slots and scholarships for low-income
students in math, engineering and computer science, to be paid for
by a $500 fee on companies for each H-1B visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a bad thing,'' said Egan of EMC, which makes data
storage equipment for computer systems. A higher visa quota ``is an
interim thing. The long-term solution is for us to produce more
engineers and scientists.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal also navigated a tricky issue of how to assure that
companies are not laying off US workers in order to hire
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   It gives the US Department of Labor broader authority to
investigate violations of the visa rules if it has ``specific,
credible'' evidence that the violations exist.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also tempers a proposal from the House Judiciary
Committee, which had been blasted by top executives at Microsoft
Corp., Intel Corp., Oracle Corp. and 25 other high-tech firms. That
proposal would have required companies using H-1B workers to
certify that they had not laid off an American worker to hire a
foreigner, and that they tried to recruit an American before hiring
a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech executives complained that this would open them to
unneccessary scrutiny of their hiring practices by the Department
of Labor, and might put them in violation of the law merely for
laying off US workers when a plant closes or product line ends.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new deal, only companies that rely on H-1B workers for
15 percent or more of their staffs must sign the certifications.
Congressional aides said the measure was aimed at so-called ``job
shops'' that bring in foreign workers only to hire them out to
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   At 600-worker Cognex, human resources director JoAnn Woodyard
said the deal was ``really good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodyard said Cognex immigration lawyers had told her that so
many firms are applying for visas that next year's allotment, which
become available on October 1, could be exhuasted by the end of the
year. That would leave employers with no visas until the following
October.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the recent college graduates hired by Cognex
hold foreign passports and need some kind of visa, she said. ``The
notion that this is cheap foreign labor -- that is absolutely not
true,'' Woodyard said. ``You can't attract the best unless you pay
the going rate, and we look for the best engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reinert, of the engineers' trade group said, that raising
the number of visas might discourage US workers from entering
high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
   He said many US companies refuse to higher mid-career engineers
who have lost their jobs as big companies like IBM Corp. and the
former Digital Equipment Corp. downsize. This has created the
impression among younger people that high-tech careers lead to a
dead-end, he contended.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Golodner, president of the AFL-CIO Department for
Professional Employees, which represents 4 million members,
complained of ``awful timing'' behind the deal. He said high-tech
employment is bound to fall amid the global financial crisis, a
downturn in defense spending, a glut in the semiconductor field and
falling computer prices.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the software industry has hired thousands of people to
fix the so-called Year 2000 bug, ``and they will be dumped out of
their jobs and onto the market in about 15 months,'' Golodner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
