u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-EPA-GE-PCB-BOS &LR;      09-24 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-EPA-GE-PCB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE AGREES TO FUND PCB CONTAMINATION CLEANUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN AND PETER HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Electric agreed Thursday to invest at least $150 million
to clean up widespread industrial contamination from its former
electric transformer plant in Pittsfield, Mass., ending an
often-bitter, year-long stand-off with the federal government over
how much cleanup is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Under a broad agreement with the US Environmental Protection
Agency and numerous other government agencies, the company will
clean up the Housatonic River and other areas such as a school that
it contaminated with PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls. In
addition, GE will clean up the 256-acre former plant site and give
it to the city for economic development.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the deal, which some sources predicted would cost
GE $250 million or more, EPA will not add the Housatonic River to
the federal Superfund list, which could have slowed the cleanup and
ultimately carried an even higher pricetag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved the cleanup onto the fast track,'' said John
DeVillars, the regional EPA administrator who led the government
negotiating team that included representatives of Massachusetts,
Connecticut, and Pittsfield. ``We have honored our most important
responsibility: to protect the health and environment of Pittsfield
and Berkshire County.''
</P>
<P>
   General Electric officials, who earlier had accused EPA of
exaggerating the danger of PCBs, also praised the agreement, saying
it would secure the future of the company's plastics headquarters
and technology center in Pittsfield, which employs 700 people. The
company had said a Superfund site on the Housatonic could
jeopardize the facility's future by stigmatizing the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``GE is pleased to enter a new phase of investing in the future
of Pittsfield and Berkshire County,'' said Stephen Ramsey, GE's
vice president of environmental programs, in a statement from
company headquarters in Stamford, Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, who
had pressed EPA to take over the cleanup by placing the Housatonic
River on the Superfund list, were surprised, but pleased that GE
had agreed to take the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may well prove that the cleanup can be as thorough and more
expeditious than designating this river as a Superfund site,'' said
George Wislocki, president of the Berkshire Natural Resources
Council, an environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci also praised the agreement,
pointing out that his administration had pushed EPA and GE to keep
talking when they reached an impasse last spring. ``We have
achieved all of this without the endless lawsuits which could have
gridlocked the entire process well into the next century,'' said
Cellucci in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy traces back to 1932 when GE began lawfully using
PCBs in transformer insulating oil and other products at its
Pittsfield factory complex, a practice that continued until 1977,
shortly before Congress voted to ban their use.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, PCBs had heavily contaminated 12 miles of the
Housatonic River south of the plant, and traces have been found all
the way down to Long Island sound 100 miles away. PCBs have been
shown to cause cancer in animals and are suspected of causing
cancer in humans, but GE has repeatedly accused EPA of overstating
the threat to people.
</P>
<P>
   For years, environmentalists and local activists have charged
GE's top priority in Pittsfield was avoiding any deal that created
a precedent for cleaning up much worse PCB contamination in the
Hudson River in New York. Estimates of the cost of cleaning up the
Hudson have ranged as high as $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, however, GE officials said such concerns were
overblown, noting that cleanup methods that might be appropriate to
the shallow, winding Housatonic, such as dredging, likely would not
work on the vast Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Both GE and DeVillars praised Pittsfield Mayor Gerald S. Doyle
Jr. and City Council President Thomas Hickey for playing a central
role in bringing about a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Had GE's Pittsfield site ``gone Superfund,'' as EPA and company
officials put it, the EPA could have taken over the cleanup and
charged GE triple the cost of work it paid for, potentially hitting
the company with a $500 million bill.
</P>
<P>
   So far, GE has spent by its estimate more than $130 million on
cleaning up PCB contamination at the Pittsfield plant and elsewhere
in Berkshire County, but much of that spending went to studies and
reports rather than actual cleanup work.
</P>
<P>
   That changed last summer when GE contractors began removing
100,000 tons of PCB-contaminated soil from homes and schools that
received ``free fill'' from the factory plant in the 1950s and
1960s. Thursday's agreement doesn't include the ongoing cost of
removing this fill.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for GE to immediately clean up the half mile of
the Housatonic nearest the plant and, starting in November, take
steps to prevent more PCBs from seeping into the river.
</P>
<P>
   Once the first half mile downstream has been cleaned up, GE will
turn its attention to the next mile and a half, where the EPA says
flooding has recontaminated properties that had previously been
cleaned up. Under the agreement, EPA and GE will jointly pay for
cleanup of this stretch even though GE vice president Ramsey
continued to say ``GE has not believed there was a health
emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, EPA will issue a decision on how to clean up the
rest of the river by 2001, though GE has the right to challenge the
solution. And GE will clean &UR;  &LR; up PCBs at the Allendale School
neighboring the old transformer factory as well as Silver Lake and
bends of the river where contamination often settles.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the cleanup, GE will spend an estimated $50 million
preparing its former property for commercial use, and contribute
$25 million to offset environmental damage, most of which will go
toward improving the Housatonic River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's historic agreement is a result of months of
extraordinary efforts by all parties and will benefit the city of
Pittsfield and Berkshire County for decades to come,'' said Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of negotiations, Pittsfield is finally able to
move forward,'' declared Sen. Edward M. Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
