<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-700(2TAKE     09-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ASKS MEMBERS TO BEGIN PREPARATIONS FOR AIRSTRIKES AGAINST
YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-REFUGEES) 
(js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILAMOURA, Portugal _ NATO asked its military commanders on
Thursday to take the next step to prepare for air strikes against
Yugoslavia if Yugoslavia does not stop attacks on ethnic Albanian
civilians in Kosovo, the province in southern Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance authorized commanders to ask member states for the
forces needed to carry out the threat. U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen called the move ``an important step to avert a
humanitarian disaster,'' but that step fell short of a political
decision to go ahead with military action, and Cohen said it was
not an ultimatum. In fact, it is the first of many steps necessary
to carry out any threat against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credibility of NATO is on the line,'' Cohen said after
defense ministers met at this bougainvillea-draped seaside resort
in the Algarve to seek a way to convince Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic that he is ignoring their demands at his peril.
Serbia and Montenegro are the last republics remaining in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today NATO sent a clear message to President Milosevic that it
is time to stop the killing and destruction in Kosovo,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other NATO ministers said that unless Milosevic stops his
attacks, as they demanded, tens of thousands of ethnic Albanian
refugees driven into the Balkan wilderness by Milosevic's forces
could die as winter sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Military and civilian officials here did not give details of
their plans for air strikes, which include both a ``limited air
option'' of strikes by U.S. ship-based cruise missiles against
Serbian military targets in Kosovo and beyond, and a ``phased air
campaign'' involving hundreds of planes that could attack command
headquarters deep inside Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to happen soon; we can't just sit back now,''
said Germany's defense minister, Volker Ruhe, who also said he was
worried about damage to the alliance's credibility if Milosevic
were allowed to continue defying the warnings the allies have been
issuing since May.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhe said Germany was prepared to contribute 14 Tornado
fighter-bombers to an air campaign, and called on the alliance to
issue an ultimatum within the next 10 days if Milosevic does not
keep repeated promises to end the attacks and let refugees return
to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, the Netherlands, Britain and other countries
have also pledged forces. Washington would provide forces for any
of the military options outlined Thursday, said Gen. Wesley Clark,
the supreme allied commander in Europe, but he and other officials
declined to give details.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, with roughly 2 million people, 90 percent of them ethnic
Albanians, is not an internationally recognized independent nation
like Bosnia-Herzegovina, where NATO warplanes eventually stopped
Bosnian Serb attacks in 1995 and where more than 20,000 NATO
peacekeepers remain.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said 15,000 Yugoslav national army troops and 11,000
security police officers had been used in attacks on villages in
the campaign against armed Albanian rebels who demand independence
for Kosovo. More than 200,000 people have fled their homes since
the spring, some to other parts of Serbia and some to neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The allies do not support the demands for independence but they
have called on Milosevic to negotiate with ethnic Albanian
political leaders to restore to the province the autonomy he
rescinded in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's decision _ by NATO's political decision-making body
for the supreme allied commander in Europe _ authorized requests to
member countries about what forces they would provide. This step is
only the first toward possible military action in Kosovo, an
``activation warning,'' in alliance jargon.
</P>
<P>
   The next step would be for officers at NATO headquarters to
match specific military units with the contingency plans drew up
over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The third step could only come days or weeks later, in some
cases after approval by national legislatures to participate in
military actions. At that point the alliance could formally
activate the plans, then take operational authority over national
forces and finally authorize commanders in the Balkans to use the
forces.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We are measuring our time in hours and days, and it can be
compressed significantly,'' Clark said Thursday. He said air
strikes would be aimed at producing ``some significant level of
damage to key force elements and associated infrastructure'' _ in
other words, both human targets and military ones _ of the units
that are attacking the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhe, whose country fears an influx of thousands of Albanian
refugees on top of the several hundred thousand Balkan refugees who
are already there, said the German Cabinet could approve military
action early next week.
</P>
<P>
   But the current Cabinet could be thrown out of office if
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats lose the German
elections on Sunday. Ruhe said he was trying to keep the Social
Democratic opposition closely informed about NATO discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Some important European allies remain reluctant to order NATO
into action solely on the basis of a U.N. Security Council
resolution that was adopted on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution called on all sides in the conflict to stop
fighting and start negotiating, and repeated earlier demands that
Yugoslavia withdraw its forces and let in relief organizations. The
resolution did not explicitly authorize military action if
Yugoslavia did not comply, but said the Security Council would
``consider further action and additional measures.''
</P>
<P>
   France, which pressed for the resolution as a way for the allies
to keep Russia in agreement with them and increase pressure on
Milosevic, still wants explicit U.N. authorization before the
allies decide to take military action.
</P>
<P>
   All decisions by the alliance require unanimity; Russia, which
opposes the use of force against Serbia, has veto power in the
Security Council. Thus the allies have been hamstrung by restraints
of their own making, issuing blustery threats that Milosevic
apparently considers hollow and then watching powerlessly as he
flouts their demands.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Thursday that the alliance has sufficient grounds
under international law to act and that ``The United States is not
prepared to act unilaterally.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO defense ministers met in Brussels, Belgium, in June and
ordered allied military authorities to start drawing up contingency
plans. But territorial gains by the rebels, the Kosovo Liberation
Army, in the early part of the summer made some allies reluctant to
appear to be taking sides by attacking only Milosevic, when they
were themselves opposed to the rebels' demand for independence.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the negotiators from the United States, the allies have
tried diplomacy to get Milosevic and the rebels to reach a
settlement that would restore autonomy to Kosovo. The West had good
contacts with Ibrahim Rugova, the Kosovo Albanian political leader,
but he and the Western diplomats lacked leverage over the armed
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has drawn up plans to send up to 50,000 troops into
the province to help keep a cease-fire if one is reached, and even
more if they decide to go in to force one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
