<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TRUMPETS CENSUS REPORT SHOWING DECLINE IN POVERTY RATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton touted new census figures
Thursday showing a decline in poverty rates for the third
consecutive year, but said there is more that needs to be done for
low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed the percentage of Americans living in poverty
declined to 13.3 percent in 1997 from 13.7 percent in 1996. A total
of 35.6 million people lived at or below the poverty rate, which
was $16,400 for a family of four. One in five living in poverty
were children.
</P>
<P>
   The number of African-Americans living in poverty hit a record
low of 9.1 million people or 26.5 percent, while the number of poor
Hispanics fell to 27.1 percent or 8.3 million people.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty rate in urban areas fell to 18.8 percent in 1997
from 19.6 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The median household income also rose by 1.9 percent to $37,005,
the same level as 1989 before the recession.
</P>
<P>
   In a Rose Garden announcement flanked by his economic team,
Clinton seized on the new report to suggest Congress should be
concentrating its efforts on issues that affect the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report this morning shows that economic growth continues
to raise incomes, lift millions out of poverty and extend
opportunity. It also shows that we have more to do,'' Clinton said.
``The most important thing we have to do, of course, is to maintain
the economic strategy that got us here in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the president's economic adviser, noted the
amount of poor black children was 46.1 percent when Clinton took
office and is now 37.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet, even at 37.2 percent, it is a shame on our nation and
one of the things that compels us to continue fighting for
initiatives and programs that make sure all children have a fair
chance to make it in our country,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again called on Congress to save the budget surplus, the
first since 1969, until they agree to reform Social Security. The
president previously threatened to veto the Republicans' $80
billion tax cut moving through the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's don't get into that and spend it in an election year tax
cut until we have saved Social Security for the 21st century, for
the sake of our children and our grandchildren,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also blasted Republicans for defeating a $1
increase in the minimum wage. ``I haven't quit fighting for it,''
Clinton said. ``I think eventually we will get it in the next
several months; if we have to wait until next year, we will get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called on Congress to pass his education plan; to
subsidize the International Monetary Fund to help stop the global
economic downturn; and to pass a measure protecting patients'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still time. We haven't broken for the election yet. We
can still do the right thing by the American people. But we have to
think about it, we have to focus on it, and we have to put our
priorities where they ought to be,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
