<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISH PASSAT PASSES MUSTER  
 (EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Volkswagen's had a fabulous year in the United States,
much of it based on the magical appeal of the New Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, VW in the past few years has built an excellent
lineup. The huge German automaker updated and replaced a bunch of
cars with limited appeal and spotty reliability records with a
collection of sporty, desirable automobiles offered at moderate
prices.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, VW's been setting sales records, and earning enough
profits to amuse itself with such diversions as buying Rolls-Royce
and Lamborghini.
</P>
<P>
   VW's flagship, the midsize Passat, was revamped for '98 from a
competent but conservative family sedan into a distinctive,
enjoyable automobile that continues to offer the German
driveability virtues represented by Mercedes-Benz and BMW. But for
a whole lot less scratch.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of a V-6 engine into the Passat was delayed
while VW ironed out some flaws (i.e., it wouldn't fit), initially
offering models with the 150-horsepower turbo-four and the
remarkable TDI diesel engines. The 190-horsepower V-6 arrived
midyear, becoming part of the upscale GLX model, along with a
luxury interior complete with wood trim.
</P>
<P>
   The GLX comes in at a base price of $26,250, which seems pricey
until you check out the performance and the hedonistic level of
standard equipment. Four-cylinder models start at about $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Though maybe not as taut as a 5-series BMW or a C-class
Mercedes, the Passat GLX does offer much of the same sensory and
performance appeal. The Passat is fun to drive, with the power of
the V-6 complementing its balanced handling and cruising
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a V-6 engine in a midsize car may sound pretty routine
nowadays, but this is a performance-bred mill with five valves per
cylinder, boosting power and economy, and allowing it to sprint up
to highway speed and cruise quietly on the far side of legal
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Though small in displacement, this engine provides a surprising
amount of pull, running more smoothly and strongly as the rpm
quickly climb up the dial. The trade-off is some real doggy
behavior at low engine speeds, especially when coming out of
corners.
</P>
<P>
   The test car was saddled with an automatic transmission, but one
equipped with the Tiptronic system that allows the driver to select
gears quickly, up and down. I think it's a poor substitute for the
performance edge of a manual tranny, but if you must have
automatic, this is as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is relatively soft, for a German car, but good
design keeps handling in balance and control. There is some extra
body sway in turns, but the Passat tracks well. The steering is
very responsive.
</P>
<P>
   Styling, inside and out, is interesting and individualistic.
There's a lot of New Beetle in the Passat, as if the
once-conservative family sedan received a dose of funk from the
rebirth of beetlemania. Look at the way the windshield arcs into
the roofline. Or at the interior contours and textures. Pure
Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Passat's styling also owes a nod to Volkswagen's upscale
division, Audi. Not to mention a platform shared by the A4.
</P>
<P>
   Passat certainly cuts a different sort of figure among the
crowded pack of midsize cars, including perennial favorites Ford
Taurus, Toyota Camry and Honda Accord.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Passat feels solid and well-constructed, with a
nicely shaped dash with pieces of genuine walnut trim and
interesting textures on the various surfaces. The cabin is very
roomy, the high ceiling and big windows creating an airy feel, the
wood, leather and texture surfaces creating a warm, homey feel.
There's plenty of room for all dimensions, with enough back-seat
space for three, and a cavernous trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the dashboard parts seem accessible and nicely
designed, some of the moving parts felt cheesy and breakable. Such
as the cupholders, which seemed ready to break off, which would be
no big loss because they barely do the job.
</P>
<P>
   The stereo controls are tiny, hard to manipulate and difficult
to see, although the upgraded, eight-speaker setup in our tester
sounded fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   As four-door sedans go, the new Passat is one of my favorites,
combining real-world practicality with the elements of performance
and driving fun.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a new Jetta will make its appearance in midseason,
following the stylistic lead of the Passat. Sounds like the right
move for Volkswagen to continue its winning streak. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Volkswagen Passat GLX &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vehicle type:Five-passenger, four-door sedan, front-wheel drive. &QL; 
Base price:$26,250. &QL; 
Price as tested:$27,825. &QL; 
Engine:2.8-liter V-6, 190 horsepower at 6,000 rpm, 206 pounds-feet
of torque at 3,200 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission:Five-speed automatic. &QL; 
Curb weight:3,380 pounds. &QL; 
Length:184.1 inches. &QL; 
Wheelbase:106.4 inches. &QL; 
EPA fuel economy: &QL; 
18 city, 29 highway. &QL; 
Highs: Sparkling performance. Nice styling. Sharp interior. &QL; 
Lows: Cheesy interior bits. Tiny stereo buttons. Slack low-end
torque. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
