<HEADLINE>
GROUP WANTS CONGRESS TO REVOKE IMMIGRATION LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of lawmakers demanded Thursday that
Congress repeal a new immigration law they contend will cause
extensive traffic delays in U.S. border communities and squeeze
regional economies that subsist on Canadian and Mexican trade.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 law mandates the installation of a computerized system
by Oct. 1, 1998, to record departures from the United States of
each non-U.S. citizen and match them with arrival records. The
system is designed to discourage foreign nationals from staying
beyond the time allowed by their visas.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, immigration officers check arrivals but not people
leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas, told a news conference that the
law, known as Section 110, ``would be a great hindrance to
commerce'' and would stymie growth in border cities such as Laredo,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, whose district includes an 800-mile swath of border,
said the entry-exit system would create lengthy bottlenecks at
checkpoints. The resulting delays would ominously signal to
industries that ``the border is now closed for business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., said the entry-exit system would
choke off commerce in his upstate district that borders Canada.
``It is unthinkable that Section 110 ever be implemented,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Quinn, R-N.Y., warned of border bottlenecks next week
when the law goes into effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just days away from Section 110 being implemented and
there still does not exist a practical way to administer the law at
our border crossings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's highly unlikely that the Immigration and
Naturalization Service will meet the Oct. 1 deadline for putting
the system in place. As a result, the deadline likely will come and
go with no measurable impact along the U.S. border.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lawmakers representing border districts want Congress
to repeal the law, or at a minimum to delay it for several years.
They are supported by business interests including the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce, the U.S. Hispanic Chamber of Commerce, General Motors
Corp. and Eastman Kodak Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as this provision remains on the books, it will hang
over our industries, towns and economies,'' said Hal Coxson, a
spokesman for Americans for Better Borders, a coalition of
lawmakers and major business organizations seeking to scuttle the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cloud exists. We want removal of the cloud,'' LaFalce
said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the law say it is essential to dissuade illegal
immigration, drug smuggling and terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
