<HEADER>
A3113 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERSHWIN-AZR &LR;      09-24 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERSHWIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S MOZART: GERSHWIN REMEMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - George Gershwin was born 100 years ago Saturday, which
means he would've been 65 years old when the Beatles made their
celebrated appearance on the ``Ed Sullivan Show,'' instantly
tossing outthe culture and the aesthetic in which Gershwin
flourished.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to imagine the aged _ but far from decrepit _ George
in a television interview a few months after the earth-stopping
event . . .
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) INTERVIEWER: So tell me, Mr. Gershwin, what is your
opinion of the new style of popular musicmaking?
</P>
<P>
   GERSHWIN: I think it was about time for a change. I like the
freshness of the beat, and the way Lennon and McCartney spin
melodies that cling to the beat and are shaped by it. The one thing
I might caution is that this new beat is so engaging that it could
become wholly dominant, swamping all the other musical elements.
Before long, you could have music that is all pulse, without
melodic profile or harmonic content.
</P>
<P>
   INTERVIEWER (laughing): Come on, Mr. Gershwin, who would listen
to songs that were nothing but a beat and some words?
</P>
<P>
   GERSHWIN: It could happen. Some of the groups I'm hearing other
than the Beatles are already tending in that direction . . . (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   But since time took George from us so early _ he was two months
shy of turning 39 when he died of a brain tumor in 1937 _ we are
spared the notion of Gershwin having to battle changing times and
the transmogrification of popular music into ``pop'' music.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, history has given us the perfectly sealed memory of a
man who was born at exactly the right moment, thrived in his art
for a brief, intense time, and then died _ too young, yes, but at a
moment that would preserve him for us like some silent icon of all
that was best in his era.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think the words I put in his hypothetically
sexagenarian mouth are unlikely, here is something he actually
said, something that ought to be engraved on the forehead of every
aspiring pop star:
</P>
<P>
   ``If study kills a musical endowment, that endowment deserves to
be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``classical,'' or educated, music is the friend,
not the enemy, of any genuine talent. Authentic musical gifts can
be enhanced and deepened only by study. The other kind will be
undone by it.
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin subjected his natural musical gifts and easy sense of
invention to the rigorous study of counterpoint, harmony and
orchestration, and more. As a result, he got better and better
throughout his short life. Starting out as a song plugger (someone
who played other people's songs to sell the sheet music) on Tin Pan
Alley, he ended up as the creator of the first fully American opera
to enter the repertoire, ``Porgy and Bess.''
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin moved back and forth between the worlds of classical
and popular because the two were linked by common disciplines and
methods. Music was a lingua franca. Now classical and popular are
split, and ``crossover'' must be mandated for them to broach some
discussion. Music is a fragmented set of languages, each
impenetrable by the others.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder we are struck by a sense of the exotic whenever we
listen to Gershwin's music and consider his story:
</P>
<P>
   A little boy, born to an immigrant family in Brooklyn, shows an
amazing aptitude for the piano and sets off to conquer the musical
world. Often teamed with his lyric-writing brother, Ira, George
triumphs in popular song with such perennials as ``Swanee'' and
``Someone to Watch Over Me.'' He hits on Broadway with shows such
as the Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Of Thee I Sing''; drags jazz
language into the concert hall via the epoch-making ``Rhapsody in
Blue''; develops popular song to ever-higher levels with the likes
of ``Love Is Here to Stay'' and ``TheyCan't Take That Away from
Me''; and breaks into the domain of Verdi and company with
``Porgy.''
</P>
<P>
   Time took Gershwin from us early, but it can't take all this
away from us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Recordings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a great wealth of recorded Gershwin. The best
``Rhapsody inBlue'' and ``American in Paris'' remain, in my view,
those of Leonard Bernstein, whose early recording of these was just
re-released by Sony on its Bernstein Century series. Also
re-released by Sony: the 1951 studio recording of ``Porgy and
Bess,'' the first time the entire work was committed to disc. It's
a luscious and loving realization of this sprawling score.
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin's popular songs are ubiquitous on CD. A couple of
recent releases contain vital new interpretations of well-known
songs as well as rediscovered treasures.
Arranger-saxophonist-vocalist Matt Catingub's ``Gershwin 100'' (on
Concord Jazz) has fantastic rethinkings of ``Slap That Bass,''
``Lady Be Good'' and ``The Man I Love.'' On the Nonesuch label,
``George and Ira Gershwin: Standards and Gems'' is a delicious grab
bag of performances from such Broadway and opera notables as Dawn
Upshaw and Audra McDonald. Not only does it give us a ``Fascinating
Rhythm'' to top all previous ``Fascinating Rhythms,'' it brings to
light several buried diadems, including the sweet-clever ``I Don't
Think I'll Fall in Love Today.''
</P>
<P>
   And still in circulation on Nonesuch is musician Artis
Wodehouse's lively realization of piano rolls cut by the young
Gershwin. Hearing Gershwin's piano playing transmitted from the
distant past is hair-raising. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Television and movies
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Hall opened its 1998-99 season Wednesday night with a
salute to George Gershwin and videotaped it for the rest of us. The
concert, featuring the San Francisco Symphony conducted by Michael
Tilson Thomas, with mezzo-soprano Frederica von Stade, Audra
McDonald and Brian Stokes from Broadway's ``Ragtime,'' will air
next Wednesday on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Turner Classic Movies (TCM) on cable, you can watch
Gershwin-related movies Saturday. First is the 1945 movie bio of
George called ``Rhapsody in Blue'' and starring Robert Alda (Alan's
dad) as the composer. That's followed by ``The Barkleys of
Broadway'' (1949), the last Fred Astaire-Ginger Rogers
collaboration, and one that includes some recycled songs by the
Gershwin brothers and several by Ira working with composer Harry
Warren.
</P>
<P>
   TCM's Gershwin mini-orgy concludes with Gene Kelly's justly
famous movie-musical expansion of the Gershwin tone poem, ``An
American in Paris'' (1951).
</P>
<P>
   If you can find them for rent, two Astaire movies made in the
1930s _ both all-Gershwin _ are superior. These are ``Shall We
Dance?'' (not the recent feature of the same name) and ``Damsel in
Distress.''
</P>
<P>
   '' For a more recent cinematic take on Gershwin, rent Woody
Allen's ``Manhattan.'' The soundtrack is a bouquet of Gershwin
songs both rare and familiar, and the spirit of thing is as
Gershwinian as a 1979 film could possibly be. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
