<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RATINGS-BOS &LR;      09-24 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONITORING GROUP SEES VAST FAILURE OF TV RATING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The television industry, which reluctantly agreed one year ago
to add rating labels to shows with sexual or violent content, has
overwhelmingly failed to live up to its word, according to a new
study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's apparent foot-dragging raises questions about
whether the much-touted V-chip, whose function is linked to those
same labels, will achieve the aim of its proponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the industry doesn't fix some of these problems, the V-chip
is not going to work,'' warned Kathryn Montgomery, a member of the
board established to monitor the rating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to be able to block out shows if they aren't
labeled,'' she added. ``Parents are not going to be able to use it
to protect their children from harmful content on television.''
</P>
<P>
   US Rep. Edward J. Markey (D-Mass.), sponsor of the federal law
requiring the V-chip, agreed that it will be ``much less
effective'' without accurate ratings. Markey blamed TV programmers
whom he said are looking for ways to evade the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   However, network executives fired back Thursday, contending that
the study is flawed. ``It finds sex and violence in places where
reasonable people wouldn't,'' insisted ABC spokeswoman Julie
Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a series of labels that went into effect last Oct. 1
after intense pressure from Congress and advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   All of the major TV networks except NBC agreed to clarify the
alphabet soup of existing ratings (TV-G, TV-PG, TV-14, TV-MA, TV-Y,
and TV-Y7) with labels to describe the content of shows: V for
violence, S for sex, L for coarse language, and D for suggestive
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But the study conducted by researchers at the University of
California at Santa Barbara found that 79 percent of shows with
violence and 92 percent of programs with sexual activity did not
carry the V or S ``content descriptors.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was funded by the Kaiser Family Foundation,
also found that 81 percent of children's programs with violence did
not carry the FV (``fantasy violence'') label.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are serious problems,'' said Montgomery, head of the
Washington-based Center for Media Education. ``But the industry
wants to wait until there are hundreds of thousands of letters
complaining about a specific show.''
</P>
<P>
   However, one network executive, who requested anonymity,
expressed exasperation at the findings, saying that most parents
don't seem as concerned as the advocates, and noting that
definitions of sex or violence can be subjective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the reason we resisted going to content descriptors is
that it makes a subjective process even more subjective,'' the
executive said. ``Having beaten us into submission, they're now
saying we're not doing it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover, of ABC, said the network is ``wholeheartedly'' behind
the idea of adding content descriptors to shows that require it.
But she said the study's findings are exaggerated because it
included ``passionate kissing'' as a sexual act deserving of an S
label. ``The S label should be reserved for something more serious,
and we believe most parents would agree,'' Hoover said.
</P>
<P>
   Vicky Rideout of the Kaiser Family Foundation acknowledged that
passionate kissing was counted as sex, but said it did not
constitute the bulk of the acts counted. She said one-third of the
shows the study deemed as requiring, but lacking, an S label
featured ``implied intercourse.''
</P>
<P>
   Rideout pointed also to the study's finding that more than half
of children's programs rated TV-Y, a label that is supposed to
denote programs appropriate for children as young as two years old,
contained violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents think TV-Y shows don't contain any violence, but we
found that a lot of TV-Y shows had pretty scary violence,'' she
said Rideout.
</P>
<P>
   The findings did not come as a surprise to veteran children's TV
activist Peggy Charren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who thought the broadcast industry was going to rate
some of their nonsense so it would be meaningful to parents must be
living on another planet,'' Charren said. She contended that
parents need to monitor what their children watch rather than
``depend on broadcasters to tell them what their children should
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser Family Foundation, based in Menlo Park, Calif., is an
independent philanthropy that specializes in funding studies on
public-health issues. It is well respected in medical and academic
circles. The TV rating study, which is billed as one of the largest
studies of television content ever conducted, was performed as part
of the Kaiser Foundation's Program on the Entertainment Media &AMP;
Public Health, which Rideout heads.
</P>
<P>
   The rating labels at issue are vital to the function of the
V-chip. Using electronic signals, the computer chip identifies
which programs to block based on their program ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Set-top boxes containing V-chips are expected to be in stores as
early as next month. Under federal law, half of all new TV sets
must include V-chips by next July, and all news sets must have them
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rideout said the study found the TV networks have done a good
job in applying the proper age-based ratings to shows, such as
TV-PG or TV-14. In fact, only 4 percent of shows that qualified for
an age-based rating didn't receive one.
</P>
<P>
   However, she noted, more than two-thirds of parents surveyed as
part of the study said they rely on ``content descriptors'' like S
or V more than age-based ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast executive who requested anonymity criticized the
study because in tallying up shows that lacked content descriptors,
it counted shows rated TV-G, for general audiences, a category
exempt from the voluntary agreement to label shows.
</P>
<P>
   Rideout conceded that is true, but said less than one-fifth of
the unlabeled violence was found in TV-G shows. Most of the other
unlabeled violence was in the categories of TV-PG (``parental
guidance suggested'') and TV-14 (``parents strongly cautioned'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Our point is not really `Who's at fault?' '' she said. ``The
end result, the way the system works in practice, that's what
matters to the parent in the living room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it is now,'' she added, ``You push the `V' on the
V-chip and you're only going to get 20 percent of the violence
blocked. It is not what parents' expectations were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
