<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GONZALEZ-RETURNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING CONGRESSMAN RETURNS TO WARM WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An ailing Texas congressman returned to the House
floor Thursday for the first time in more than a year, making what
one staff member called ``his victory lap'' before retiring from
the House.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, 82, was greeted with warm wishes and
accolades from Democrats and Republicans who watched him cast his
first vote in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how good it is to be back,'' Gonzalez,
D-Texas, said between hugs, pats on the back and well-wishes from
his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was rushed to National Naval Medical Center in
Bethesda, Md., in July 1997 when a low-grade infection traveled to
a heart valve and threatened his life.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to his San Antonio district to recover from the
heart ailment and had not returned to the House of Representatives
until this week.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a gray pin-striped suit, Gonzalez ambled onto the
House floor before noon for a vote, catching many friends by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, was first to acknowledge Gonzalez's
presence, hailing the return of the ``dean of the Texas
congressional delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon of New York led the Republican
greeting: ``From this side of the aisle, we would like to welcome
back the dean of the Texas congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the most respected members of this body,''
Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's first vote in 14 months was in favor of a spending
bill for congressional operations.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months ago, some questioned whether the sometimes
irascible congressman would ever return to the arena he first
entered in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Gonzalez recalled the day he took the oath on
Nov. 4, 1961, as the first Mexican-American elected to Congress
from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as they swore me in, I pulled a bill from my pocket
and introduced it,'' he said, tugging at the lapel of his rumpled
coat. The bill called for the repeal of the poll tax, a fee
assessed citizens as a condition for voting.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez abhorred the poll tax because it was meant to
discourage minorities from participating in the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was a guiding force during the savings and loan crisis
of the 1980s, but he stood alone in his unsuccessful efforts to
impeach President Ronald Reagan and then George Bush for taking
military action against foreign nations.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who commuted back to his San Antonio district nearly
every weekend during his congressional career, plans to remain in
Washington over the weekend, aides said. He intends to keep working
until the Congress adjourns in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3122 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RONIN-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      09-24 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RONIN-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RONIN' A THRILLER WITHOUT THE THRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - You start out wondering what's in the mysterious
suitcase everyone is killing everyone else for. About 10 minutes
into ``Ronin,'' you're wondering what, if anything, was in the
minds of the writers and director.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood makes plenty of pointless, worthless movies, few of
them as determinedly terminal as ``Ronins''
</P>
<P>
   The title refers to ancient samurai of Japan who had lost their
master and become freelance killers or bandits.
</P>
<P>
   The story is set in modern France, where the mysterious Deirdre
(Natascha McElhone), who is working for some mysterious Irish
group, brings together five mysterious ex-agents to steal a
mysterious suitcase from a mysterious bald guy.
</P>
<P>
   What's in the suitcase? Who are these men? How do they get away
with destroying half of France without the other half getting
ticked off about it?
</P>
<P>
   There are no answers to any of these questions, and it's just as
well there aren't because the answers probably would be as
unsatisfying as the mystery itself.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious ex-agents include Sam (Robert De Niro), who may
or may not have been with the CIA, and Vincent (Jean Reno). We're
pretty sure that Vincent's French because he smokes Gauloise.
</P>
<P>
   We're not too sure about anyone else, although you can always
identify the next bad guy in the crowd because he's the one who
needs a shave.
</P>
<P>
   As the men go after the mysterious suitcase with guns blazing,
``Ronin'' devolves into a series of incredibly long and stupid car
chases.
</P>
<P>
   Director John Frankenheimer's (``The Island of Dr. Moreau'')
operating theory: If smashing up a dozen cars is exciting, then
smashing 10 dozen must be 10 times as exciting. Bad math.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder what De Niro is doing in a film like this,
unless he needed a vacation in France, one in which he wouldn't be
required to work very hard.
</P>
<P>
   Most other aging Hollywood stars have positioned themselves as
youthful by making movies in which they romance young women: Woody
Allen in ``Everyone Says I Love You,'' Warren Beatty in
``Bulworth,'' Michael Douglas in ``A Perfect Murder,''
demonstrating that they can still fake the ardor.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro wants to hang onto his youth by punching people out and
directing his own surgery, thereby demonstrating that he may be
getting older but he can still fake the pain.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting person in the movie is McElhone (``The
Truman Show''), a British actress who has the longest, most
mournful face in movies. Maybe she's unhappy that she didn't get
romanced by Beatty or Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   As thrillers go, ``Ronin'' has no suspense, no thrills, plenty
of explosions and more than enough lame action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronin'' is rated R for profanity and violence. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
