<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMINISTS OPPOSE IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's feminist leaders ended months of
sidestepping the White House sex scandal Thursday and came out in
firm support of President Clinton. They called on women to oppose
impeachment, brake the Republican bandwagon for it, and back
candidates in November who champion women's causes.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, more than a dozen feminist activists said
Clinton's chief accusers on Capitol Hill are ``among the worst foes
of women's rights,'' and they demanded Congress ``end this
hypocritical voyeurism and get back to work on the real issues''
facing the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' said Patricia Ireland, president of the
National Organization for Women. ``No matter how offended I am by
the president's behavior, it does not rise to the level of
impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The feminist leaders said they did not coordinate Thursday's
statement with the White House, though they did tell presidential
aides to expect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women will not be duped into joining the Gingrich/Lott assault
on the president and his agenda,'' said Ireland, who signed the
statement that rebukes the GOP Congress and its leaders, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, for
``a relentless campaign to hound President Clinton'' out of office.
``Women will not stand by as the Republicans use their power in
Congress to overturn a president they elected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's gender gap today isn't nearly as wide as it was when
he was elected. Recent polls show women are only slightly more
inclined than men to support him and are only a little less likely
than men to call for his impeachment if he committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't believe these feminists represent the
majority of American women on this critical issue regarding
marriage, truth, lies, and what we teach our children,'' said
Carmen Pate, president of the Concerned Women for America, a
conservative group that has called for Clinton's resignation or
impeachment. ``Feminists are truly out in left field from what most
Americans believe should happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, women's rights groups have been conflicted, and
notably quiet, about Clinton's extramarital affair with White House
intern Monica S. Lewinsky and, before that, about the sexual
harassment lawsuit brought against him by Paula Jones in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the president's workplace misbehavior with the then
22-year-old Lewinsky, so graphically described in Independent
Counsel Kenneth W. Starr's report, is everything feminists deplore
and, indeed, sounds as bad as sexual misconduct allegations brought
against former Oregon GOP Senator Bob Packwood and then Supreme
Court nominee Clarence Thomas, which the groups loudly condemned.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, both the president and his wife, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, have been good friends of the feminist movement and
promoted its agenda of pay equity for women, abortion and
reproductive rights, expanded child care services, and better
health and family leave policies. For that reason, feminist leaders
have been reluctant to harshly criticize the White House or seek
Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Smeal, president of the Feminist Majority, said the
women's groups are not hypocritical but rather in a ``unique''
position to judge the president and put the scandal in proportion.
``It is precisely because of the sexual backdrop of (this)
misconduct that we believe we are compelled and duty-bound to speak
out and act,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford May, a spokesman for the Republican National Committee,
disagreed. ``These women are opening themselves to a real trap when
they defend sexual harassers or exploiters out of partisan loyalty,
or because they don't want funding for a certain government program
jeopardized,'' he said. ``It looks like they are sacrificing their
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a principle much larger than saving Clinton's
presidency is at stake, the feminists say. Their real concern,
evident in the timing of Thursday's statement, is that the scandal
will take down Democrats in November who have held the line _ and
been able to sustain the president's veto in the Senate _ against
conservative Republicans who oppose abortion rights, affirmative
action, and a host of gender-equity issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have much at stake in these elections,'' the feminists'
statement said. ``We are here today to sound the alarm that if
disgust with the current crisis depresses women's votes in
November, we will see an antiwomen's rights majority in Congress
roll back the gains for women of the past 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the individuals and groups endorsing the statement, in
addition to Ireland and Smeal, were Betty Friedan, a founder of the
modern feminist movement; Kathy Rodgers, executive director of the
NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund; Jane Smith, president of the
National Council of Negro Women; and Yvonne Scruggs-Leftwich,
executive director of the Black Leadership Forum.
</P>
<P>
   They said they feared Republicans would manipulate an
impeachment process not only to remove Clinton, but also to bring
down Vice President Al Gore over alleged campaign-fundraising
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women should be asking the question, `who's on third _ who is
next in the line of succession,''' the joint statement said. ``Next
in line is Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedan said her fear is that the country is on the brink of an
era of ``sexual McCarthyism,'' as politicians polarize the country
over issues arising from people's private behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do risk ushering into power a puritanical or fundamentalist
sex police who speak of freedom but allow government to destroy the
right of privacy,'' Smeal added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
