<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coming soon: A new flurry of AOL discs
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- America Online is back, and so are its infamous
discs. Beginning Monday, the company will launch an aggressive
``carpet bombing'' marketing strategy to launch its newest version,
AOL 4.0.
</P>
<P>
   For some, AOL's marketing effort conjures memories of the
company's last deluge. At one point, so many disks were in
circulation several disgusted consumers put up Web sites devoted to
craft projects using AOL disks, 101 Uses for AOL Disks
(http://www.earthplaza.com
</P>
<P>
   /aoldisks) and Nikki's 1997 AOL CD Present Collection
(http://www.neosoft.com/nikki).
</P>
<P>
   AOL President Bob Pittman said in a statement the company will
begin mailing more than a million CD-ROMs per week and will place
the discs ``just about everywhere you turn'' _ from cereal boxes to
bank kiosks to school cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the mass distribution is designed to add still
more subscribers to its present total of 13 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing now is very different from what we've done in
the past,'' says Barry Schuler, president of AOL Interactive
Services. Schuler says that three or four years ago, when AOL first
deluged the market with installation disks, it was largely unknown
and running a distant third in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say AOL's latest marketing plan is a clever move
despite unpleasant memories of campaigns pst.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research analyst Kate Delhagen says AOL hasn't been
doing much marketing directly to consumers lately. She also says
AOL needs to resume its old aggressive marketing stance to compete
in the increasingly crowded ``portal'' space. She says the second
part of AOL's strategy is to get the product out to existing
customers to they can upgrade their software.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
