<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stocks' advance fuels new talk of BellSouth-Sprint marriage
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A recent spike in the stock price of Sprint Corp. has
spurred talk the company is a merger target _ and BellSouth is
again rumored to be a potential suitor.
</P>
<P>
   Other large phone companies have been rushing to the industry
stage proclaiming partnerships, while Sprint and BellSouth have
stayed conspicuously aloof. But speculation pairing the two
received fresh fuel this week as the stock in both companies
reached all-time highs, even if both drifted lower in Thursday's
marketwide sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint stock, which dipped Thursday to $77.87 1/2, had jumped $5
the day before, part of a climb that began Sept. 2, when the stock
was selling for $64. During that same period, BellSouth stock has
climbed from $66 to $74.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   David Burks, an analyst with Hilliard Lyons, said much of the
strength in BellSouth stock can be traced to the company's earnings
growth and its relative insulation from harm during a deepening
international economic crisis. The slew of mergers has hardly
driven BellSouth to panic, but the game is gradually changing, he
said. ``I think they may be more amenable to a venture with another
company than they were a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say both companies can succeed for some time without
partners. But both are expected to eventually extend their reach to
compete with the new behemoths that could soon surround them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With every merger that gets announced, BellSouth gets a little
further behind,'' said Mel Marten, analyst at Edward Jones &AMP; Co.
``I certainly believe that there are talks happening. But I would
be surprised to see an announcement from these two companies
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving the rumor some staying power is the notion that Sprint's
profile meshes well with BellSouth, which has a $15 billion-a-year
local-service business in the Southeast, an Internet business and
rapidly growing investments in Latin America. Sprint, the
third-largest long-distance company, is also building a national
wireless service and owns a chunk of Earthlink, a provider of
Internet access. Sprint has a local-service business scattered
around the United States and an international business in
partnership with France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   The only obvious overlap would be the U.S. wireless business of
the two companies. Such a merger would also face considerable
regulatory questions, since BellSouth is not yet permitted to offer
long-distance. But such a deal grows in likelihood if other
megamergers pass muster and if BellSouth does win federal approval
for long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Chief Executive William T. Esrey recently testified in
Congress that he found the $62 billion SBC Communications plan to
buy Ameritech to be anti-competitive, a stance that would make it
hard to tout a Sprint merger anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey also told reporters Thursday his company has what it needs
to succeed. ``If I thought we needed something we didn't have, we
would consider going and getting it, or even consider a merger. But
I don't know what that is. We're very comfortable where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's board of directors next meets Monday. Company
spokesman Tim Klein declined to comment on questions about any
merger or venture ``unless and until an agreement is reached.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
