<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Circus leader on a cloud with Southwest
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The founder of an Atlanta-based big top has gone big
time as the star of a new television ad for Southwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Walker, president of the UniverSoul Circus, is featured
in a Southwest spot appearing on BET, Black Entertainment
Television. It may run elsewhere later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone loves a circus, so a few years back I started one,''
Walker says in the ad titled ``Another Southwest Airlines Freedom
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker often flies ahead of the circus to promote ticket sales
at the next venue. The ad claims Southwest's low fares give him the
``freedom'' to be where he needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the spot he is seen watching the circus's preparations from
behind a curtain, then ducking out to catch his next flight as
ringmaster ``Casual'' Cal Dupree opens the show.
</P>
<P>
   The ad concludes with Walker exclaiming: ``We've got the best
show under the big top, and Southwest has the best one over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker and Dupree founded the circus _ dubbed ``Cirque du Soul''
by one reviewer _ in 1994. They tout it as the first
African-American circus in a century. It performs once a year in
Atlanta and is currently on a 19-city tour.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity manager Hank Ernest said ``it blew my mind'' when
Southwest's Texas ad agency called to ask about using Walker.
Someone at the agency had read an article about the circus. He said
Walker really does fly Dallas-based Southwest when he can. The
carrier has expanded nationally in recent years but doesn't serve
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And what about UniverSoul's performers and crew? Ernest said
they travel by bus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
