</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MEETING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola taking its case to analysts
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Coca-Cola Co. investors are anxiously waiting to hear
what Chairman and Chief Executive Officer M. Douglas Ivester will
say today when he briefs analysts about the company's near-term
business prospects.
</P>
<P>
   In New York this morning, Ivester and Chief Financial Officer
James E. Chestnut will give analysts a volume and earnings update
for the third quarter and the full year. The update is done each
quarter, either by conference call, video conference or in person;
Coca-Cola officials decided just this week to host the meeting in
New York with both Ivester and Chestnut attending.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting comes at a pivitol time, as analysts and investors
alike are expressing concern over the Atlanta-based company's
profitability in troubled economies around the globe. Several
analysts have cut earnings estimates and ratings on the stock,
which has plummeted 36.3 percent since hitting a 52-week high of
$88.93 3/4 on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed Thursday at $56.68 3/4, down $1.31 1/4. More
than 6.7 million shares changed hands _ roughly twice the six-month
daily average.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is expecting Ivester and Chestnut to give a
less-than-rosy short-term outlook, though just how blunt they will
be remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   In the company's midterm report mailed to shareholders this
week, Ivester acknowledged this year's earnings have been partly
``hampered'' by the effect of the strong U.S. dollar and weak
currencies abroad, particularly in Asia. Per-share earnings in the
first half were 82 cents, compared with 91 cents in the year-ago
period. Ivester, however, also noted that operating income rose 8
percent in the first half, ``even with currency factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which does business in 197 countries, gets 70 percent
of its sales and 75 percent of its profit from international
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's earnings, to be released next month, are expected
to be 40 cents per share, according to First Call's revised
estimate. At the beginning of the quarter, First Call's consensus
estimate was 42 cents. In the year-earlier period, Coca-Cola earned
34 cents per share, excluding a gain from the sale of stakes in
bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford C. Bernstein analyst William Pecoriello has predicted
the strong dollar will clip this quarter's earnings by 10 percent,
with the biggest hits coming from Japan, Germany and Mexico. He
expects sales to increase 6.5 percent in the quarter, compared with
11 percent in the year-ago third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Securities analyst George Thompson said that despite
the harsh economic climate, Coca-Cola is better able to weather the
storm than some companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current management has spent 10 years and billions of
dollars in putting together a very, very effective bottling system
on a worldwide basis,'' he said. ``That bottling system is in a
position to spend money and market more effectively on a local
level than it's ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who has a ``strong buy'' rating on the stock, feels
some investors are overreacting by bailing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're seeing here. Typically, when people approach
being hysterical, it provides a great opportunity to buy the
stock,'' he said. ``When you see a (stock) like this crater as it
has, somebody probably is scared out of their wits.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
