<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-COMPANY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern's group one of two finalists to buy Louisiana power
cooperative
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A consortium that includes Southern Co. is one of two
final bidders for the assets of a bankrupt Louisiana electric power
cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Enron Corp. on Thursday withdrew from the
protracted bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth D. Rice, chief executive of Enron Capital &AMP; Trade
Resources Corp., said the Enron subsidiary was opting out because
of the resources needed to continue with ``what has become an
extremely lengthy and expensive process.''
</P>
<P>
   Enron's withdrawal leaves Louisiana Generating _ which includes
Atlanta-based Southern, Ziegler Coal Holding Co. of St. Louis and
Northern States Power Co. of Minneapolis _ in a bidding war against
Southwestern Electric Power Co. (Swepco), a Shreveport, La.-based
subsidiary of Central &AMP; South West Corp. of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Generating has bid $1.18 billion, and Swepco has
offered $940 million for Cajun's non-nuclear assets being auctioned
off by a federal bankruptcy judge.
</P>
<P>
   Janni Benson, a Southern spokeswoman, said Louisiana
Generating's bid ``is the best possible deal'' for the
cooperative's customers and creditors and the local economy. Cajun
was forced into bankruptcy in 1994 by its losing investment in the
Riverbend nuclear power plant in Louisiana. Cajun's assets include
more than 1,600 megawatts of power capacity from a network of
coal-driven power plants and long-term contracts to sell that power
to 12 rural electric co-ops. Those co-ops, in turn, provide power
for 1 million Louisiana residents.
</P>
<P>
   Southern joined the Louisiana Generating consortium as part of
its effort to acquire electric generating capacity around the
country to supply its growing wholesale energy trading business.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Generating has the support of court-appointed
bankruptcy trustee Ralph Mabey, but Louisiana-based Swepco has
backing from most of the co-ops Cajun supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding has been one of a number of battlegrounds between
Southern and Enron as the companies increasingly face off in power
markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
