<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time Warner faces lawsuit over licensing of characters
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA A British entrepreneur has sued Time Warner for $153
million, charging that the media conglomerate fraudulently killed a
deal to open theme restaurants based on characters from the library
of Turner Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed Thursday in federal district court in Atlanta,
concerns a troubled deal struck in May 1995 with Turner Home
Entertainment, a unit that was disbanded when Time Warner bought
its Atlanta-based parent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Home Entertainment had agreed to let a company called
Dream Factory, controlled by Alan Lubin, use characters from Turner
Broadcasting's MGM libraries to decorate restaurants, the first of
which was to open in London.
</P>
<P>
   But the opening of the restaurant was delayed for years.
Consequently, Time Warner ordered Turner Home Entertainment to
cancel its deal with Dream Factory. Instead, the company struck a
similar deal with another set of British entrepreneurs incorporated
as ENIC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite simply, Time Warner and ENIC engaged in a conspiracy to
appropriate the project by convincing THE (Turner Home
Entertainment) to wrongfully terminate the agreement with Dream
Factory,'' says the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks to recover what it describes as $38.3 million in
real damages. It also requests punitive damages equal to four times
that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys representing Dream Factory and Lubin declined to
comment Thursday on their suit.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives declined to comment on the suit Thursday,
explaining they had not yet seen it.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, finding new uses for Turner Broadcasting's movie
and cartoon characters was a key strategy for the company.
Licensing them to a restaurateur was typical of the kinds of deals
the company was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, its deal with Dream Factory struggled from the
start, according to the suit. Dream Factory wanted to open its
first restaurant in a historic building within a part of London
controlled by the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   ``What followed was an extremely tedious, drawn out and detailed
procedure to obtain'' various permits to use the site, says the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the restaurant was delayed again and again,
although the suit says Turner Home Entertainment continued to
support Dream Factory.
</P>
<P>
   But then Turner Home Entertainment, now a unit of Time Warner,
``unilaterally, suddenly and wrongfully'' canceled the project on
Nov. 11, 1996, according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says that shortly thereafter Time Warner announced a
new idea to open theme restaurants. This time it was with Peter
Dubens and Daniel Levy, who had tried earlier to buy into the pact
with Dream Factory, says the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
