<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Friday, Sept. 25, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-COUNCIL-RAISE _ (Los Angeles) The members of the Los Angeles
City Council are getting a 3 percent pay raise, retroactive to July
1, in addition to a 9.7 percent raise they got earlier this year,
city officials said Thursday. The latest increase pushes their pay
to more than $110,000 a year. At least two council members say they
will reject all or part of the increase, which was caused by a
provision in the city charter linking council salaries to judges'
salaries; judges are getting higher pay under the new state budget.
By Patrick McGreevy. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ANTHEM-GUY _ (Los Angeles) For once, the record-setting
superstar in the outfield Thursday night was the guy singing the
national anthem. Mark Reiman, a man too young and full of life to
have the devastating Lou Gehrig's disease, left his home in the
Pacific Northwest five months ago with a dream to sing the nation's
theme song in all major league stadiums by season's end. In Dodger
Stadium just after 7 p.m. he realized that goal. By Beth Barrett.
(Will move in the ``n'' California, ``a'' national and ``s'' sports
files.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-DRUGS _ (Los Angeles) As investigators Thursday sought to
determine whether LSD was indeed what caused 14 children at Haddon
Elementary in Pacoima to become ill Wednesday, more than 200
parents mobbed the school during an 8 a.m. meeting to demand more
supervision during recess. ``Can I go to work without worrying
about my child? Will my child be safe here?'' asked Dolores Aldape.
By Lisa Van Proyen and Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n''
California and ``a'' national sports files.)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-SHARES _ (Los Angeles) Shares of Walt Disney Co. fell 3.5
percent Thursday as Chairman Michael Eisner threw cold water on
Wall Street's expectations for the current quarter. By Dave McNary.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BANK-MERGER _ (Los Angeles) Shareholders of both BankAmerica
Corp. and NationsBank Corp. on Thursday gave an overwhelming thumbs
up to the $47 billion merger that will create the nation's largest
bank. By Deborah Adamson. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
