<HEADER>
A3158 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALL-2NDTAKE-SFCHR     09-24 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: actual actor.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Aaron Spelling is doing other things _ actually, he's doing
``Buddy Faro'' with Mark Frost, but keep that quiet _ and the new
``Fantasy Island'' is now a Barry Sonnenfeld (``Men in Black'')
production.
</P>
<P>
   It could make all the difference. Sonnenfeld's ``Fantasy
Island'' (Saturday on ABC) is far more sardonic than in the days of
Ricardo Montalban and ``da plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm McDowell is the new Mr. Roarke, and you get the feeling
he might have murdered the former Mr. Roarke and seized the island.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, it's a Fantastical Island, where Mr. Roarke
chases away storm clouds with a snap of a finger and plays havoc
with the psyches of his guests. Who, by the way, book their trips
through a mysterious travel office run by the cackling Fyvush
Finkel (``Picket Fences'').
</P>
<P>
   Louis Lombardi and Edward Hibbert (``Frasier'') are two Roarke
aides who apparently are serving out some sort of sentence, and
Madchen Amick (``Twin Peaks'') pitches in as an assistant who can
morph into different women.
</P>
<P>
   The series is beautifully filmed, in Hawaii, and seems to be an
intriguing mixture of romance, adventure, magic and pure nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like it better, though, if it displayed a willingness, after
all its winking devilishness, to eschew conventional moral lessons
for Mr. Roarke's clients.
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite a time slot that could double as a cemetery plot,
``Cupid'' (Saturday on ABC) could develop an avid if not massive
following.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Piven, late of ``Ellen,'' stars as Trevor Hale, a glib
fellow who materializes in Chicago and claims to be Cupid, the
Roman god of erotic love.
</P>
<P>
   I'm reminded that in ``The Brothers Karamazov,'' when Jesus
reappeared on Earth during the Spanish Inquisition, he was
consigned to the Grand Inquisitor. For our purposes here, it's
Cupid, and he's sent to a psychiatrist (Paula Marshall).
</P>
<P>
   Back on Olympus, he says, life is a ``nonstop, clothing-optional
party. Everyone's happy, drinking wine, chasing nymphs. An amazing
place.'' But for some transgression, he's been ordered to join 100
couples in true love before he can rejoin his fellow gods.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, that scores sky-high on the asininity scale. But
Piven has a roguish, fast-talking appeal, not unlike Bruce Willis
back in the ``Moonlighting'' days.
</P>
<P>
   He and Marshall push hard _ probably too hard _ to recapture
that same romantic friction that made Willis and Cybill Shepherd a
TV commodity a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way. If you're home on Saturday night, and you
watched ``Fantasy Island'' without feeling cheated, you might as
well make it an evening with ``Cupid.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
