<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS GIVE FAMILIAR FARE NEW TWISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First of all, don't you agree that, as matter of principle, at
all times there ought to be at least one spirited private eye show
on TV?
</P>
<P>
   Sure you do. But the genre sputtered after ``The Rockford
Files'' and dropped into a coma sometime around ``Magnum, P.I.''
The culprit, maybe, was too many realistic cop dramas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy Faro'' (Friday on CBS) is an eye-catching, highly
enjoyable effort to turn back the clock in a couple of ways.
</P>
<P>
   It seeks to revitalize a seemingly moribund program form, and to
do it in chic retro trappings. Series creator Mark Frost (``Twin
Peaks'') apparently figures the way to do it is to make the old
feel new again.
</P>
<P>
   His star is Dennis Farina, the actor who showed in ``Get
Shorty'' that he can be self-assured, virile and hilarious all at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Farina is Buddy Faro, a legendary Los Angeles detective and bon
vivant who vanished in 1978. Co-star Frank Whaley is the 1998
detective who unearths his idol, Faro, in a drunken stupor down in
Baja.
</P>
<P>
   The third regular cast member is Allison Smith as the girl,
Julie Barber. She's a woman, but this is shamus stuff. There's
always a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Back in L.A., Buddy cleans up well enough to discover that his
old gin-joint pals are dead and gone. But in the neon whirl of our
retro present, when twentysomethings dress up and guzzle martinis,
he finds his second wind. Buddy's back.
</P>
<P>
   It's a neat trick all around for Frost. Buddy might have dropped
from sight in 1978. But ``Buddy Faro'' is in a murky zone. It
borrows from the good-times Rat Pack ambience of the late 1950s and
early 1960s, and blends it with the metallic hardness of the 1990s.
Take a look at why retro movements are fun, but always too sleek
and studied to be real.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to sell yourself,'' says Buddy, probably echoing
Frost's own approach to the show. ``That's what they're buying,
baby _ confidence, style.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy Faro'' is unquestionably a confident and stylishly
pleasing TV series. And it's hard to imagine anyone adorning it
quite so comfortably as Farina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like an anarchist,'' he proclaims, surveying the world
around him.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy is reminded that the word is ``anachronism.'' But he might
have had it right in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Olsen twins, Mary-Kate and Ashley, are 11 years old now
and probably good for one more quiet hit.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet hit means a show that I don't watch, and you don't watch,
and no one we know has ever mentioned watching. But it airs year
after year. The cast of ``Boy Meets World'' is pictured in the
dictionary definition of the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Mary-Kate and Ashley are in ``Two of a Kind'' (Friday
on ABC), playing the twin daughters of an unmarried college
professor (Christopher Sieber).
</P>
<P>
   The girls see a grand opportunity for matchmaking when the
28-year-old woman hired as their baby sitter (Sally Wheeler) turns
out to be one of their father's students.
</P>
<P>
   It's not bad for what it is. And I expect that in some distant
sweeps month, maybe May of 2004, we'll see the twins as TV
bridesmaids.
</P>
<P>
   Or, someone we don't know will see the twins as bridesmaids.
</P>
<P>
   _ I could wag my finger at you and tell you I have not had
visual relations with ``Brother's Keeper'' (Friday on ABC), but the
fact is that I've seen bits and pieces of the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   It's another of those ABC domestic sitcoms for Friday family
viewing. William Ragsdale is yet another college professor and
single parent, this time the father of an 8-year-old son (Justin
Cooper).
</P>
<P>
   This is in San Francisco. The show is supposed to turn
rib-tickling when dad's brother (Sean O'Bryan), a football bad boy,
is signed by what ABC calls ``the city's pro football team.'' Uh,
99ers?
</P>
<P>
   My impression, albeit incomplete, is that the show could use a
new offensive line, a few pass rushers, a solid secondary, a
linebacker corps, a tight end, a reliable quarterback and a healthy
running back.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise it's great.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Martial Law'' (Saturday on CBS) is a horrible show _
statically directed, uninteresting, and with some of the worst TV
acting since the schlock days of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself thinking that its makers should relinquish all
restraint and just go for it, purposely make the show as bad as
possible, in hopes that it'd be so awful that viewers would laugh
along with it.
</P>
<P>
   Know what? That might be exactly what's happened. The police
show starring Hong Kong martial arts star Sammo Hung is so
brazenly, giddily stinko that it's tempting to say you shouldn't
miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Hung, who can speak a few words of intelligible English, plays a
Shanghai cop who ends up affixed to the Los Angeles Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   He also ends up winning a dinette set on ``The Price Is Right.''
I must have blinked somewhere; I'm still not sure how that
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Hung is a roly-poly sort who does exude a certain charm, whether
he's elbowing an assailant in the head _ there are three
martial-arts fights in the first episode _ or asking for a ``Dye-uh
Co'' (Diet Coke).
</P>
<P>
   At certain angles, his round face looks like the giggling sun
baby in ``Teletubbies.'' From no angle will he look like an actual
actor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
