<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-     09-24 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE SAYS HE, NOT GINGRICH, LEADS IMPEACHMENT TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., S.C., Mass., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Henry Hyde is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-PRESS,
CLINTON-ASSESS.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to repair political missteps, Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., said Thursday it was he, not Speaker Newt Gingrich,
who presided over impeachment deliberations, and Hyde played down
suggestions that Republicans were seeking to broaden the inquiry
beyond Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who heads the Judiciary Committee, called a news
conference a day after the White House and congressional Democrats
asserted that the speaker was calling the shots and was motivated
by partisan zeal.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who have been on the losing side in other
confrontations between the president and Gingrich feared they had
stepped into another political trap, and Hyde quickly sought to
stamp his inquiry with his voice and visage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was selected to chair this committee, presumably not as a
delegate of the speaker's office, but as a person who has some
autonomy,'' Hyde said. ``We've tried to exercise it and will
continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   But the comments failed to dispel the conflicting signals sent
by Hyde and Gingrich, and left some Republicans confused about who
was actually quarterbacking the deliberations. Some committee
Republicans called on their leaders to let the panel do its job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic case of too many chiefs,'' said Rep. Lindsey
Graham, R-S.C., who has been a persistent critic of Gingrich. ``Our
leadership is trying to figure out what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Hyde outlined the committee's schedule
for the next two weeks. On Friday, the committee will meet in
closed session to decide which portions of the remaining 65,000
pages of evidence from the Whitewater independent counsel to
release.
</P>
<P>
   Committee aides have been pouring over the material, which
includes depositions from Vernon Jordan, Clinton's friend, and
Betty Currie, Clinton's secretary, as well as the tape-recorded
conversations between Ms. Lewinsky and Linda Tripp. Aides have
flagged portions deemed too private, too embarrassing or
irrelevant, and lawmakers will vote on the proposed deletions. Hyde
said that material would probably be made public late next week.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will then vote on Oct. 5 or Oct. 6 whether to
begin a formal impeachment inquiry into 11 charges against
President Clinton. Hyde said that if the committee approved a
measure to open the inquiry, the full House would vote on the
measure a few days later, probably on Oct. 8 or 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all Americans I want to bring this matter to closure as
soon as possible,'' Hyde said. ``Our guide is deliberate speed, not
too fast that people can accuse us of rushing to judgment and not
too slow so people can accuse us of deliberately stretching it out
for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Hyde was trying to stamp out some of the political fires
surrounding Gingrich, the chairman appeared to ignite two new
blazes himself. Committee aides spent much of the afternoon
modifying his statements.
</P>
<P>
   First, Hyde indicated the committee would likely release edited
transcripts of the tape recordings between Ms. Lewinsky and Mrs.
Tripp, but not the tapes themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they would not push for releasing the tapes, but
they accused Republicans of hypocrisy, saying that Republicans who
had called for the release of Clinton's videotape deposition were
now balking at material that might prove favorable to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unacceptable to pretend to be conducting a bipartisan
investigation and then vote not to release the tapes,'' said Martin
Meehan, D-Mass. ``In the tapes, when you can listen to them, you
can get a better sense of the credibility or lack of credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides said later that Hyde did not oppose releasing
the tapes if Democrats insisted; Hyde was only worried about the
logistics of editing hours and hours of tapes, the aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hyde said if the committee conducts a formal impeachment
inquiry, he did not think it would be necessary to call Ms.
Lewinsky as a witness, saying her sworn testimony was good enough.
``I would rather not,'' said Hyde. ``I don't think that would be
too productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats pounced on those remarks. ``How are we going to have
an inquiry if we're not going to listen to witnesses?'' said Rep.
Barney Frank, D-Mass. ``What are we going to do at these hearings?
Play records?''
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, Hyde's office issued a statement correcting
those comments. ``Certainly no decisions have been made on who
might testify,'' if the committee holds formal hearings, Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   After saying little on Wednesday, Hyde's main goal Thursday
seemed to be to tamp down Gingrich's suggestions that the
committee's inquiry might expand to include accusations about
campaign finance abuses by Democrats, illicit transfer of sensitive
missile technology to China, and other allegations that the
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, was still investigating.
</P>
<P>
   The committee would consider any new, serious accusations from
Starr or other House panels, Hyde said, but he made it clear the
panel was plenty busy already. ``None of us are interested in
casting a very wide net,'' said Hyde. ``We have enough on our
plate, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., a member of the panel, seconded
Hyde's concerns: ``We shouldn't become the repository of everything
bad that someone says about Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Hyde chided those who would try to
sidetrack the panel ``by attempts to cut deals or cry wolf about
partisanship.'' He also sought to pull his squabbling committee out
of the swirling partisan fray, invoking ``the rule of law'' six
times in his 10-paragraph statement as the committee's guiding
principle.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde's most difficult task over the next several weeks may
be shaking the perception on Capitol Hill that he is doing
Gingrich's bidding. ``All I know is every time I give advice to
Newt, he nods his head affirmatively,'' Hyde told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   And when the speaker offers Hyde guidance?
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen carefully,'' said Hyde, ``but I don't feel bound by
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
