<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEIMAN-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neiman case ends with $962,500 award
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A federal jury Thursday awarded $962,500 to an
Atlanta woman who said Neiman Marcus security guards at Lenox
Square manhandled and strip-searched her because they wrongly
suspected she was a shoplifter.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lynn Cooper, 54, was leaving the store on Nov. 3, 1996,
when she was confronted in the parking lot by a plainclothes
security guard who she thought was going to rob and abduct her.
Cooper was handcuffed, taken through the upscale department store
screaming, then put in a basement office, where, she says, guards
strip-searched her and reached inside her undergarments to check
for stolen merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased ... that the jury saw the truth in this
matter,'' said Cooper, a computer software consultant. ``But this
is not about money. It's about the customers' safety while they're
shopping in department stores. It's about the proper training of
security guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Deliberating in the type of case that civil attorneys said
rarely gets to trial, the eight-person jury awarded Cooper $750,000
for emotional distress, $100,000 for pain and suffering and $12,500
for her physical injuries. It also awarded $100,000 in punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're studying our options,'' Peter Farwell, a spokesman for
Neiman Marcus Group, said, declining further comment on whether the
company plans an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, juries have returned million-dollar verdicts
against two stores _ a Dillard's store in Kansas City, Kan., and an
Eddie Bauer branch in a Washington suburb _ in favor of plaintiffs
who claimed they were denied service or stopped on suspicion of
shoplifting because they were African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus security guards denied strip-searching or
violating the rights of Cooper, who is white.
</P>
<P>
   They said she voluntarily took off her clothes to prove she took
nothing. According to testimony, when Cooper entered the lingerie
apparel fitting room to try on seven items and came out with none,
a guard went inside and counted six. But the other item was in
another stall, which the guard failed to inspect.
</P>
<P>
   Another guard confronted Cooper in the parking lot and the melee
ensued.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, Cooper's lawyer, Richard Hendrix, asked
the jury to award more than $2 million in compensatory damages and
enough in punitive damages to send a message to the $2 billion
company.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Edwards, a BellSouth employee and the jury forewoman,
said jurors ruled against Neiman Marcus ``because of the negligence
of its employees'' and had talked about awarding Cooper a higher
amount. But the jury was ``not trying to send a harsh message,''
she said. ``We want Neiman Marcus to know that what they did to
Mrs. Cooper was not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
