u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNTURNER-COX     09-24 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNTURNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner U.N. grants to help poor, environment
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The U.N. Foundation, the organization set up to
administer Ted Turner's gift of $1 billion to support United
Nations objectives, announced its second round of grants Thursday,
just four months after announcing its initial grants in May.
</P>
<P>
   The 17 new grants, totaling $32,849,500, will support projects
designed to improve the environment, children's health and the
status of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``This round of grants demonstrates the priority we place on
protecting the environment around the world,'' said Timothy Wirth,
president of the U.N. Foundation. He said the foundation also had
taken care to make sure most of the grants will go toward services
for the poor and that they will support programs encouraging
cooperation between various U.N. programs and agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The grants were awarded by the foundation's board, which
includes, among others, Turner, Wirth, former Atlanta Mayor Andrew
Young and Graca Machel, wife of South African President Nelson
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Turner announced a year ago that he would donate to the
foundation Time-Warner stock with a value up to $1 billion in 10
annual installments worth an estimated $100 million each. In its
first round of grants May 20, the foundation awarded $22,181,000 to
22 projects around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The grants announced Thursday include:
</P>
<P>
   $2,383,500 to help African cities manage water.
</P>
<P>
   $650,000 to improve early warning and preparedness for future El
Nino weather effects.
</P>
<P>
   $1,249,500 to help governments and individual companies
cooperate in building a framework to contain emission of greenhouse
gases.
</P>
<P>
   $1 million to link the transfer of technology to developing
countries with the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
   $2.8 million to discourage the use of tobacco among children
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   $5,175,000 to create a partnership between the Rockefeller
Foundation and the U.N. Foundation to support efforts to revitalize
the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
   $3,090,000 to vaccinate 7.6 million children against polio in
five war-afflicted countries: Afghanistan, Cambodia, Sierra Leone,
Somalia and southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   $3,090,000 to help prevent the transfer of HIV from mothers to
children by administering the drug AZT to mothers in Cambodia,
Ivory Coast, Rwanda, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   $3,090,000 to improve education, work conditions and skills
among adolescent girls in 13 countries in Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   $150,000 for a program to be developed by Peruvian adolescents
for Peruvian adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   $1 million to prevent female genital mutilation in Burkina Faso,
Cameroon, Ghana, Kenya, Nigeria and Gambia.
</P>
<P>
   $3.2 million to improve reproductive and sexual health for
adolescents in Ecuador, Haiti and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   $1.1 million toward implementation in February 1999 of the
International Conference on Population and Development.
</P>
<P>
   $650,000 to improve the Women Watch Web site
(www.un.org/womenwatch), dedicated to the advancement and
empowerment of women.
</P>
<P>
   $2.3 million to help prevent young women and girls from being
forced to live under slave-like conditions as prostitutes, domestic
workers or unwilling wives in Cambodia, China, Laos, Myanmar,
Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   $1,656,000 to prevent and respond to sexual violence against
female refugees in Kenya, Tanzania, Guinea, Liberia and Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   $250,000 to support human rights activities worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
