<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the
House Judiciary Committee, expects the House to vote early next
month on whether an impeachment inquiry will be held. He also says
more evidence about President Clinton's extramarital affair may be
released next week. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FEMINISTS (Washington) _ Leaders of prominent feminist
organizations decry President Clinton's behavior in the Monica
Lewinsky affair but insist that he should not be impeached. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   IMPORTED-FOOD (Washington) _ The key to improving the safety of
imported fruits and vegetables is to require foreign countries to
follow U.S. production and sanitation standards, scientists and top
government officials tell a Senate panel. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already
filed)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PROBLEMS (Washington) _ House lawmakers call for repeal
of a new immigration law that takes effect Oct. 1 because, they
say, it may cause extensive traffic jams in U.S. communities along
the borders with Canada and Mexico. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already
filed)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Washington) _ President Clinton touts new
Census Bureau figures showing a decline in the poverty rate for the
third consecutive year, but says there is more that needs to be
done for low-income families. NANCY MATHIS. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GEORGES-STORM (Naples, Fla.) _ Coastal counties in Florida brace
for Hurricane Georges, the killer storm that has pounded the
Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico. The storm is forecast to reach
the Florida Keys Friday, then move into the Gulf of Mexico. By KIM
COBB.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ During his Watergate troubles,
Richard Nixon argued that impeachment requires an indictable
offense. Now Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr is threatening to
indict Bill Clinton if the president resigns, setting up a
complicated and troubling legal scenario. By MARIANNE MEANS.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-OPTION (Houston) _ An unlikely trend has started to develop
in college football this season. More and more teams seem to be
switching to the option-style offense. Rice has been one of the
forerunners of this trend under coach Ken Hatfield, and the Owls
will put their option on display this weekend against struggling
Texas. By NEAL FARMER.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-NEBRASKA (Undated) _ Nebraska is off to a 3-0 start under
first-year coach Frank Solich, but the Cornhuskers face their first
real challenge of the year this weekend against Washington in a
battle of ranked teams. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-FINALE (Houston) _ Baseball's renaissance season comes to a
grand conclusion this weekend with a riveting home-run race and an
unpredictable three-team wild-card battle. And Houston will be
right in the center of both story lines as the Astros host Sammy
Sosa and the Chicago Cubs for a three-game weekend series starting
Friday. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
