<HEADER>
A3172 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART     09-24 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE GEORGES TURNS TOWARD FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After wreaking havoc in Haiti and the Dominican Republic
then dallying over Cuba, Hurricane Georges strengthened Thursday,
turning northward and taking aim at southern Florida, where 750,000
people were advised to evacuate mobile homes and low-lying coastal
areas.
</P>
<P>
   With the storm gaining both speed and strength as it moved
toward the Florida Straits, forecasters were predicting that the
eye of the hurricane would strike the Florida Keys early Friday.
From Miami to Tampa, millions of nervous residents rushed to
complete their storm preparations in anticipation of that landfall
and the flooding and destruction that are expected to accompany it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, we weren't as ready for Hurricane Andrew as we should
have been, and I vowed not to let that happen again,'' said Lisa de
Grandy as she loaded plywood into a van outside a home supply store
here Thursday morning. ``It's tense in there, like a scavenger
hunt, and this is not something I really want to be doing again,
but we want to suffer as little damage as possible this time.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Caribbean nations that have already endured the brunt of
Georges fury began the process of cleaning up, the death toll from
the storm rose to more than 110 Thursday. The bulk of the
fatalities were reported in the Dominican Republic, where at least
45 people in the town of San Cristobal were killed when the walls
of a school being used as a shelter collapsed in flood waters.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dominican Republic and Haiti, which share the island of
Hispaniola, hundreds of people were reported still to be missing
and feared dead. Leonel Fernandez, president of the Dominican
Republic, said the storm had also left more than 100,000 people
homeless and severely damaged sugar, banana, rice and coffee crops
that were nearly ready to be harvested.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a national tragedy,'' he said in a televised
address to the country's 7.5 million people. ``We face a titanic
task.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 3.8 million residents of Puerto Rico were reported
still to be without electricity and water, and the local telephone
company said 339,000 of its customers had no long-distance service,
making communication with relatives in the continental United
States difficult. Some shops and restaurants have reopened, using
generators as their power source, and the government said it hopes
to restore power to half the island by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, the energy Georges expended during its four-day
rampage across Puerto Rico, Hispaniola and Cuba appeared to have
exhausted the storm. But as the hurricane moved back out over the
warm waters of the Caribbean, it rapidly gained force, and
meteorologists warned that it could strengthen to a Category 3
storm, with winds of more than 125 miles per hour, by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The course Georges is thought most likely to follow in the
coming days would take it directly over the lower Florida Keys
early Friday and on into the Gulf of Mexico. Residents of both
Miami and Fort Lauderdale awoke Thursday to find that a hurricane
warning had been issued for their communities, while a hurricane
watch was extended northward, to Longboat Key just south of Tampa
Bay on the Gulf Coast and to Stuart on the Atlantic Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may become a major hurricane, and we need to be ready for
that,'' Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center
here, cautioned Thursday, after radar images indicated the eye of
the storm was reorganizing itself. ``People really need to count on
it being bad.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   James Witt, director of the federal Emergency Management Agency,
added that ``it is the storm surge coming behind the Keys that will
have a lot of the force. We're worried about flooding and crop
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   As Georges was regrouping, Alex Penelas, the mayor of Miami-Dade
County, which has 2 million residents, issued a decree for the
evacuation of Miami Beach, Key Biscayne and other communities on
barrier islands directly facing the Atlantic. The directive was
strictly voluntary, however, and many residents, especially young
people and those who did not experience Hurricane Andrew, said they
had no intention of complying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in a hurricane before, but I'm not
panicking,'' Carolina Aguirre, 32, a teacher and Miami Beach
resident, said. ``It's more dangerous to leave than to stay, so I
will stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of mobile homes and trailer parks, many of whom
experienced the full force of Hurricane Andrew and its 150 mile per
hour winds, seemed to be taking a mandatory evacuation order aimed
at them seriously, however. At Fowler's trailer park in southern
Miami-Dade County, Xiomara Lopez, 44, and her family of five were
loading an air conditioner and changes of clothes into a truck and
preparing to leave for a relative's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trailer survived Andrew, but we're not taking any
chances,'' said her daughter, Ayza Corujo, 23. ``We're lucky,
because a lot of the people here are poor and don't have any place
to go. We're just praying that our home is still here when we come
back, because we don't have any insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation directive also applied to the towns of Homestead
and Florida City, both of which were leveled by Hurricane Andrew.
``We are extremely concerned because of the extensive flooding we
believe will be associated with this hurricane,'' Penelas said
Thursday afternoon in explaining the measure and announcing the
opening of public shelters across the county.
</P>
<P>
   Key West, which is expected to end up in the eye of the storm,
was reported to be virtually a ghost town Thursday, with tourists
having fled and hotels, bars and boutiques along normally bustling
Duval Street closed. The Key West airport was closed Thursday
morning, and a 9 p.m. curfew was ordered for Monroe County.
</P>
<P>
   At Cape Canaveral, NASA officials began moving the Discovery
space shuttle off the launch pad and back toward its protective
hangar. Hotels in nearby Orlando were filling rapidly with
residents fleeing threatened areas further south, and MacDill Air
Force Base in Tampa was ordered evacuated.
</P>
</TEXT>
