<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-2NDTAK     09-24 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: have noticed.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States has sat quietly by while Saddam Hussein
expelled U.N. arms inspectors, having said previously that it would
not accept such action, and it has failed so far to intervene to
slow Serbian attacks upon ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Some
Europeans think Clinton's hands are tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cannot order retaliation against Islamic terrorism without
raising the suspicion of it being a reckless political expedient,''
wrote Alberto Ronchey, the former head of the big publisher Rizzoli
RCS, in the Milan, Italy, newspaper Corriere della Sera.
</P>
<P>
   An Asian diplomat complained bitterly about what he called
``intolerably late, intolerably inadequate'' U.S. action in the
case of Anwar Ibrahim, the former Malaysian deputy prime minister,
who was fired earlier this month from his positions in the Cabinet
and the ruling political party, then arrested in Kuala Lumpur on
Sunday on charges of sexual misconduct and treason.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's first official comment came only Thursday, in the
form of a statement by the State Department spokesman, James Rubin,
expressing concern over the detention of Ibrahim under Malaysia's
Internal Security Act, which dates from the insurgency there
decades ago. Asian representatives in Washington wanted a tougher
American line, enunciated by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The international financial crisis is another cause for anxiety,
although some foreign officials continue to suggest that Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin can manage U.S. economic policy with minimal
White House help.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest, though they offer no convincing proof, that if
Clinton had not been preoccupied this summer when troubles broke
out in Asia, Russia and then Brazil, he might have been able to
react much more aggressively. And his legal troubles are widely
blamed abroad for the president's inability to persuade Congress to
authorize an additional $18 billion for the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Gianni De Michelis, the former Italian foreign minister who was
convicted of corruption in the early 1990s, said that signs of
Clinton's weakness on the international front were already evident
in the IMF setback.
</P>
<P>
   No stranger to the political fallout of legal entanglements, De
Michelis said: ``If Japan blows up, we are facing an unthinkable
disaster. It would obviously be useful to have at the head of the
most powerful government in the world someone who can deal with
world crises with a free hand.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's efforts to open a debate on the financial crisis
have been welcomed in Brazil, the country's finance minister, Luiz
Felipe Lampreia, said that the president's ability to lead that
debate has been reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian officials, the finance minister said, were ``extremely
concerned with the fact that President Clinton is weakened
internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Some on Capitol Hill believe that the Lewinsky affair has
contributed to the looming failure of Clinton's bid for wider
powers to negotiate trade treaties. The House is scheduled to vote
Friday on so-called fast-track authorization legislation, with a
defeat widely anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Walter B. Jones Jr., R-N.C., said he had been leaning
against widening presidential powers last year but was now a sure
``no'' vote. His views had changed because of his constituents'
views, he said, adding: ``They don't want to see this president
given any new authority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
