<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3177 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-VISAS-0924-COX     09-24 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS-0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE APPROVES ADDITIONAL VISAS FOR HIGH-TECH WORKERS
 &HT;    By Christi Harlan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After four months of wrangling, the House agreed
Thursday on a plan to create more visas for specially skilled
foreign workers while collecting a fee from employers to pay for
scholarships and job training for U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, crafted this week in meetings between President
Clinton's economic advisers and immigration policy makers from
Congress, will allow up to 337,500 foreign workers to take jobs in
the United States during the next three years. Current law would
have admitted 195,000 foreign workers during three years.
</P>
<P>
   The additional visas were necessary because of unprecedented
demand from the high-tech industry, which has become the
predominant user of the so-called H-1B visas. Industry
representatives lobbied hard for the bill, complaining that they
are unable to find sufficient U.S. engineers and computer
specialists to fill available jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation approved Thursday in a 288-133 House vote was a
compromise between two widely different bills approved in May by
the Senate and the House Judiciary Committee. The Senate version
would have increased the number of visas over five years and
imposed few new restrictions on employers. The House committee
version, written by Rep. Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio, also would
have added more visas but required new efforts by employers to find
and retain U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has been stalled since May, in part because the
White House was threatening to veto any bill that did not contain
more money for teaching U.S. students and retraining U.S. workers
to fill the jobs being offered to foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   The White House got its way this week, winning the addition of a
$500 fee for each visa application and each application for
renewal. The fee is expected to raise at least $75 million, which
will be used in part to create 10,000 scholarships for
underprivileged students to study math and science.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is expected to tout the legislation Friday
during a fund-raising visit to Silicon Valley in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that the House of Representatives has moved
quickly to pass a bipartisan compromise to address a shortage of
skilled workers, while providing new training and protections for
U.S. workers,'' Clinton said Thursday in a statement. ``To address
that shortage and maintain America's competitive edge, we must give
U.S. workers new opportunities to train and to learn new skills.
This legislation helps us meet that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, which could win Senate approval as early as
Friday, will make 115,000 visas available beginning next Thursday,
the start of the federal fiscal year. Another 115,000 visas would
be available beginning Oct. 1, 1999, and 107,500 would be available
Oct. 1, 2000. In 2001, the annual limit reverts to 65,000 visas.
</P>
<P>
   This year's supply of 65,000 visas ran out in early May,
stranding companies and the foreign workers they had expected to
hire. A spokeswoman for the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
which processes applications for H-1B visas, said the agency does
not count applications _ only visas issued _ but immigration
lawyers are estimating that 25,000 to 30,000 applications are
pending with the INS, awaiting the new batch of visas that will be
issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news that there are visas available again, and
universities and employers needing highly specialized workers will
again be able to seek visas,'' said Paul Parsons, an immigration
lawyer in Austin, Texas, who has been filing applications for
high-tech companies in the Austin area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is they've decided to require employers to pay
$500 to the government per worker,'' Parsons said. ``This appears
to be essentially a tax on U.S. employers to attempt to address the
failure of our educational system to train sufficient U.S. workers
in specialized fields, such as engineering and computer science.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who originally pushed for tougher requirements for
employers, called the passage of the compromise plan ``a nice
victory'' that offers ``protections for American workers.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the money for scholarships and job training, Smith said
``I really am hopeful ... we will have produced enough home-grown
talent'' that additional visas won't be needed after the three-year
boost.
</P>
<P>
   The American Electronics Association, a trade group for 3,000
U.S.-based technology companies, issued a statement saying its
members would not be ``unduly'' burdened by the legislation, which
gives the Department of Labor new power to investigate employers
suspected of underpaying or otherwise abusing foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The H-1B compromise will help high-tech companies continue to
create high-paying jobs for talented skilled workers in the U.S.,
and not lose them to our foreign competitors,'' said association
president William T. Archey. ``Employment-based immigrants who
enter this country legally on H1-B temporary visas play a critical
role in keeping the U.S. high-technology industry globally
competitive. And they create thousands of new jobs in the United
States as a direct result of their scientific and technical
expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
