<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-KOHL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL, SEEKING FIFTH TERM, PLAYS ON GERMANS' FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany _ Battling to win an unprecedented fifth term as
chancellor in national elections on Sunday, Helmut Kohl on Thursday
chose a simple theme: fear.
</P>
<P>
   The setting was Munich, a conservative city, and the specters
Kohl invoked were many and wide-ranging. They included communism,
extremism, fascism, inflation, immigration, Balkan violence,
instability and chaos. Against them, the chancellor suggested, the
best bulwark was his own 300-pound frame.
</P>
<P>
   Having governed Germany for 16 years, Kohl knows his people
well, and they know him. He has a visceral sense of the traumas
left by Nazism, two experiences with hyperinflation and _ in the
east _ four decades of Communist rule. What is unclear, and what
the election will determine, is whether his focus on that history
has now left him out of touch with younger Germans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What should we be afraid of?'' said Achim Bogdahn, a young
editor with Bavarian radio, as he listened to Kohl. ``We have had
him for 16 years and have 4.1 million unemployed. What more do we
need to fear?'' Groups of students chanted, ``Auf Wiedersehen''
(``Goodbye'').
</P>
<P>
   Kohl was unruffled. Speaking to a crowd he estimated at 20,000,
but which looked closer to 2,000, he sought to build on the success
in a recent Bavarian state election of the Christian Social Union,
the sister party to his own Christian Democrats, and portray the
Social Democratic Party of his chief opponent, Gerhard Schroeder,
as dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl recalled that Konrad Adenauer, the first chancellor of the
postwar Federal Republic, had told him long ago that ``the most
important thing is that people learn to trust Germans.'' He said
that trust had now been universally earned, but German stability,
the bedrock of Germany's international standing, could be
threatened if a left-wing government came to power.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, he said, was ready to work with ``the Communists'' in
a coalition government, and he urged people leaning toward voting
for the Social Democrats to recall the horrors of the Bautzen
prison in the former East Germany, where political prisoners were
held under Communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   The message was anything but subtle, but Bavaria is a deeply
conservative place where on Sept. 13 the Christian Social Union
defeated the Social Democrats in state elections by 52.9 percent to
28.7 percent. Each derisive reference to ``the Communists'' and the
dangers of a German lurch leftward raised applause.
</P>
<P>
   By ``Communists,'' the chancellor was referring to the Party of
Democratic Socialism, the successor to the former East Germany's
Communist Party, whose popularity in the east could conceivably
give it a pivotal position in attempts to form a governing
coalition after an election that now appears too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both Schroeder and the environmentalist Green Party
have ruled out a coalition with the former Communists. But still
trailing Schroeder by between 2 percent and 5 percent in most
opinion polls, Kohl appears to have concluded that his best chance
of a fifth victory may lie in playing on German fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Wall Street,'' he said, ``where calculations are cold,
people make decisions to invest in Germany. And if you ask them
why, they will tell you it is because Germany is stable, and they
can trust us.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the chancellor continued, a glance over Germany's southern
flank was enough to reveal, in Kosovo and Bosnia, how dangerous
Europe remained. ``We need a government with authority, a
government that can provide law and order,'' he said, arguing that
Schroeder could not provide such a government.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl was flanked by Edmund Stoiber, the popular Bavarian
premier, and he repeatedly contrasted the successful Bavarian
economy _ where unemployment is about half the national rate of
10.6 percent _ with that of Lower Saxony and Saar, the states
governed by Schroeder and Oskar Lafontaine, the Social Democratic
Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to so-called ``chaos days'' in the Lower Saxony
capital of Hanover _ large public gatherings of punks permitted by
Schroeder _ Kohl asked: ``Could you ever imagine such a thing in
Munich?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      09-24 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA WARNS IT MIGHT DEFAULT IF WESTERN AID IS WITHHELD  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As the Russian government Thursday laid out ways to
spend its way out of a roiling economic crisis, it also took a
harsh line with its international creditors, warning them of a
potential default on its long-term debt if more Western aid is not
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   The stark, almost belligerent tone used Thursday by Alexander
Shokhin, a deputy prime minister of financial affairs, suggested
that Russia is ready to take an offensive, rather than
conciliatory, tack in its negotiations with the International
Monetary Fund and other creditors as it tries to battle its way out
of a widening budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not like to scare anyone by discussing the possibility
of default,'' Shokhin told a news conference Thursday, ``but we
must at least hope for the loyal attitude of our partners in the
international financial institutions and the G-8, and expect them
to make available those aid packages that have been announced.''
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin's tough talk was seen by financial experts as a sign of
Russia's increasingly desperate situation, as it plots an
inflationary course on the one hand and on the other, seeks help
from Western governments and institutions that have urged it not to
spend money it doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   On the table this month is the delivery of a $4.3 billion credit
from the IMF, the second installment of a $22.6 billion package
negotiated with the Russian government last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The first $4.8 billion installment, delivered in July, failed to
shore up investors' faltering confidence in the Russian economy and
to prevent Russia's decision on Aug. 17 to devalue its currency and
default on its short-term Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Thursday, a senior official of the International
Monetary Fund warned that he would not submit to ``the blackmail''
of Russian leaders who were threatening to default.
</P>
<P>
   IMF officials have said that they first want to examine the
Primakov government's economic program before judging whether it
makes sense to lend Russia more money. Shokhin, who is to meet with
an IMF delegation Friday, said such a wait-and-see approach would
push Russia ``against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will make no secret of the fact that this is a tough
position of the international financial institutions that can
invalidate the conventional pattern of our relationships in the
future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin's strong language, couched by an appeal to the IMF to
treat Russia in a ``civilized manner,'' went down the wrong way
with Western financial analysts who see Russia reverting to its old
bullying ways.
</P>
<P>
   His tone was echoed Thursday by the Russian central bank
chairman Viktor Gerashchenko, who warned Western banks negotiating
over the terms of a rescheduling of Russia's now frozen short-term
Treasury bills not to push too hard. ``Greedy'' banks,
Gerashchenko, ``may lose everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At this particular moment, the objective of the Russian
government should be to avoid becoming a long-term pariah in the
world financial community,'' said Charles Blitzer, director of
emerging markets research at the London office of Donalson, Lufkin
and Jenrette. ``They should be bending over backwards to be more
accommodating. Instead, they have their backs up, and are making
threatening moves.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a speech Thursday to his still-incomplete Cabinet, Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov said the government would first undertake
to pay undelivered pensions and paychecks, and starting in January,
to ``pay compensation'' to the population for soaring prices, and
the cost of the ruble devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Such proposals are sure to further increase an inflation rate
that, according to the Russian economics ministry, had already sent
consumer prices shooting up by 35.7 percent in the first week of
September.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report from the central bank, inflation by the
end of this year will drift up to 290 percent if the value of the
ruble, which Thursday held at 15.6 to the dollar, drifts down to a
rate of 20 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov on Thursday attacked the Aug. 17 decision to devalue
the ruble _ together with a simultaneous default on short-term debt
and a moratorium on bank-held loans _ as ``poorly thought out and
heedless of the real consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with reporters on Wednesday, Anatoli Chubais, the
architect of Russia's privatization, defended the Aug. 17 decision.
``I thought, and I still think, that the decision was the only one
that could be made,'' he said. ``There were a few short-term
reasons for such a decision. The simplest one was there was no
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin, a former economics minister in the early 1990s, said
Thursday that Russia would press for a renegotiation of the
estimated $38.4 billion in credits from foreign governments
inherited from the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's total foreign debt _ as opposed to debts held by
Russian banks _ is estimated at $158 billion, of which $91 billion
are Soviet-era obligations. About $31.5 billion are estimated to be
owed to financial institutions. The total figure does not include
derivatives, estimated at $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has already missed August payments on debts to Germany,
one of its biggest creditors, and several rating agencies have cut
Russia's credit ratings to near-default levels.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin proposed offsetting foreign-government debts by swapping
them for debts that third-world countries owe Russia. According to
Moody's Investor Service, those debts, also left over from Soviet
times and held by Moscow's former socialist allies and trading
partners like Iraq and Libya, total about $150 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not rule out that we may come up with a zero option,''
said Shokhin, suggesting that Russia's creditors could assume the
role of broker in what experts called a highly imaginative and
highly improbable debt exchange. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
