<SLUG> BC-EISNER-BOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY CASTS A WARY EYE ON MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co. has annual revenues of $22 billion, one of the
best-known brand names in the world and its tentacles in virtually
every form of entertainment, communication and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   But even with those assets, there is one company that Disney
casts a wary eye on _ one headquartered in Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft may be our most daunting competitor,'' writes Disney
Chairman and Chief Executive Michael Eisner in his new book ``Work
in Progress.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds more like a statement that should be coming from the
chief executive of Netscape, Sun, Novell or some other computer
technology company. Microsoft does have a more dominant position in
its business of operating systems for personal computers than
Disney does in entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft, with annual revenues of $14.5 billion, isn't as
big as Disney, and its threat to Disney would seem minimal,
especially given Microsoft's spotty record in trying to generate
entertainment content.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner doesn't see it that way. In a telephone news conference
Thursday, Eisner said Microsoft's combination of cash flow, its
``enormous buying power,'' its aggressiveness, and the youth of its
employee base and chairman is ``a formula for competition.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular Eisner noted that Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates
combines youth, money, intelligence and an interest in the
entertainment business. That, he said, means Gates ``is a
competitor to be watched.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner also said he's not dissuaded by Microsoft's lack of a big
hit in the entertainment business; Microsoft has started slowly in
other businesses only to make improvements and become highly
successful, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how Gates will use his interest and cash in the
entertainment field, whether by trying to develop it in-house or in
partnership with others (Microsoft has made a relatively small
investment in the Spielberg-Geffen-Katzenberg venture DreamWorks),
Eisner didn't hazard a guess.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he know exactly how people will use the Internet when
it reaches maturity. Commerce is a likely application, and Disney
is already selling merchandise online. Less certain is the
possibility of streaming video via the net as a replacement to
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little like Lewis and Clark,'' he said. ``We've
reached the Rockies and we've got to go across.'' People think
there's something worthwhile on the other side but at this point
``we're still exploring.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney is sufficiently intrigued by the potential of the
Internet to add it to its portfolio of movies, theme parks,
broadcast and cable television networks (including ABC and ESPN),
radio (its holdings include a Seattle station), professional sports
franchises, even cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   Last year it bought Starwave, the Bellevue-based Web site
developer, from Paul Allen. This year it swapped Starwave for a
stake in Infoseek, which operates an Internet gateway. The two plan
to introduce a new ``portal'' known as Go Network, which will,
according to Eisner's book, act as ``a central hub through which
people can gain access to every business and every form of
information and entertainment that Disney offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner said Thursday Disney made the investment in Infoseek
because it wanted control of an Internet channel. The Internet, he
added, is the next big convenience in the home since the television
and the telephone. ``It is that important,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
