<SLUG> BC-MARKET-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS TUMBLE ON FEARS OF WORLD FINANCIAL INSTABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices tumbled Thursday on intensified fears
about world financial instability, which has so badly infected a
large American investment fund that the Federal Reserve helped
organize a $3.5 billion emergency rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and brokerage shares were pummeled as the Dow Jones
industrial average relinquished about two-thirds of Wednesday's big
advance to close down 152.42 points, or 1.87 percent, at 8001.99.
Stocks also fell 6 percent in Brazil and by lesser amounts in
Europe but advanced in Tokyo following a Japanese holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear the dimensions of these problems remain bigger than
anticipated and will take a longer period to adequately deal
with,'' said Thomas M. Galvin, chief investment officer at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, referring to Japanese banks and other
sources of persistent concern.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital Management, the hedge fund based in Greenwich,
Conn., is teetering on failure from bad speculative bets that could
have resulted in a cascade of losses if not for the rescue. Galvin
said that ``the magnitude of the numbers shook the confidence of
the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also expressed some second thoughts about Wednesday's
enthusiasm for the possibility that the Federal Reserve will cut
interest rates next week. Some wondered whether it would accomplish
much, while others reinterpreted the comments of Alan Greenspan,
the Fed chairman, that prompted this optimism in light of what he
undoubtedly knew was the dire condition of the hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were reminded in the most eye-opening manner of what
happens in a financial crisis,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief
investment officer of First Albany Corp. ``This is one of the ways
financial crises can get transmitted around the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the fund's problem resulted from a rush by world
investors into the safety of U.S. Treasury securities, which it had
bet would decline, after Russia defaulted on debt.
</P>
<P>
   Even though stocks had slumped in Europe _ 2.36 percent in
Frankfurt, 1.25 percent in Paris and nine-tenths of 1 percent in
London _ shares opened somewhat higher on Wall Street. But they
quickly retreated as the implications of the near-failure of
Long-Term Capital sank in. The Dow average was nearly 220 points
lower before some late-session buying pared the loss and edged it
back above the 8,000 mark.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, down 5 3/16, to 87|, and American Express, down 4
3/16, to 79\, had the biggest negative effect on the average,
accounting for one-quarter of its decline.
</P>
<P>
   Other decliners included Citicorp, down 6}, to 98}; Merrill
Lynch, down 4|, to 53]; Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, down 5 11/16,
to 51 9/16; Lehman Brothers, down 4 3/16, to 33 11/16; Chase
Manhattan, down 3}, to 46], and Charles Schwab down 3 1/16, to 40
1/16.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica dropped 5\, to 60, while Nationsbank, its merger
partner, was down 4], to 54]. Nationsbank stockholders on Thursday
approved the deal, scheduled for completion next Wednesday.
Travelers Group, which is to merge with Citicorp, skidded 3 5/16,
to 39|.
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the 30 Dow stocks ended with gains, all fractional
except for International Paper's, up 1 9/16, to 46~.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indexes fared worse, with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 down
23.37 points, or 2.19 percent, to 1,042.72, and the Nasdaq down
39.93 points, or 2.27 percent, 1,720.34.
</P>
<P>
   Among high-technology flyers, Yahoo shed 2|, to 115\, and
Amazon.com fell 3, to 102[, following spectacular gains Wednesday
while Microsoft lost 3{, to 110[.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing could keep investors away from Ebay Inc., bidding
shares of the fledgling internet company as high as 54\ from an
initial offering price of 18. The shares finished at 47], with more
than 9 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange outnumbered
advancing ones by 2,042 to 1,093, with 43 making new highs and 127
new lows. Volume was 805.94 million compared with 900.23 million
during Wednesday's rally.
</P>
</TEXT>
