A3208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NISSAN-BUILDING-NYT &LR;      09-24 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-BUILDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN TO SELL ITS TOKYO HEADQUARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Nissan Motor Corp., Japan's No. 2 car manufacturer, is
selling its headquarters building in the tony Ginza district here,
making another small step toward paring its mammoth debts.
</P>
<P>
   The company is selling the building and the land under it to
Mori Building Sangyo Co. and Mori Building Development Co., two
privately held real estate companies, for 14.6 billion yen, or
$106.6 million. Nissan will continue to occupy the building, which
is across the street from another building housing a large
showroom, under lease from Mori.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive sign that they are willing to try to deal with
their problems,'' said Christopher Redl, an auto analyst at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   But the symbolism of the deal far outweighs its impact on
Nissan's debt burden, which is expected to hit 4.3 trillion yen, or
$31.4 billion, at the end of the fiscal year on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   That amount is 80 percent of the total Japanese military budget,
according to Redl.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker, which posted losses in four of the last five
years, has pledged to reduce the burden by 1 trillion yen over the
next two years, but so far has made barely a dent in its pile of
financial obligations.
</P>
<P>
   It recently sold its stake in an advertising agency, and the
money gained from the sale of its headquarters building will cover
three-tenths of 1 percent of its total debt _ and only half of the
proceeds represent a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan has been negotiating with Daimler-Benz AG over the
possible sale of its stake in Nissan Diesel, an ailing truck
manufacturer, but those talks are moving exceedingly slowly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3211 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILIPPINE-AIRLINES-7     09-24 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINE-AIRLINES-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPINES STRUGGLES WITH LOSS OF AIRLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ What happens when a sprawling island nation suddenly
loses its national airline?
</P>
<P>
   That question reverberated through the Philippines Thursday, on
the morning after Philippine Airlines ceased flying. The airline,
Asia's oldest, shut down at midnight on Wednesday after Philippines
President Joseph Estrada failed in a final effort to resolve a
bitter labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, the demise of Philippine Airlines could raise
acute transportation problems for the 76 million people of this
Asian archipelago who relied on the airline to hop from island to
island. The government and several domestic airlines are scrambling
to plug the holes in the air network.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, government officials and airline analysts said
the collapse would be remembered more as a blow to national pride _
and to the prestige of Estrada, for whom the dispute was a major
test of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of image, we're badly affected,'' said Roberto Ram
Antonio, the undersecretary of tourism. ``It's the pride of a
country to have a flag carrier that represents the Philippines in
different markets abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   But Philippine Airlines had become a threadbare symbol. It lost
$338 million over four years and was staggering under $2.1 billion
in debt. After the unions rejected a proposal that would have
allowed the airline to slash costs, its owner, billionaire Lucio
Tan, made good on his threat to close the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio said the government's priority was to reassemble its
domestic route network. Philippine Airlines carried 80 percent of
domestic traffic until it encountered severe financial trouble last
June, when it cut local destinations to 16, from 36. Analysts
warned that the Philippine economy could be crippled if people and
cargo were not able to move smoothly around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a country with 7,000 islands,'' Scott Gibson, head
of research at ABN Amro in Manila, said. ``You need a
well-developed domestic airline.''
</P>
<P>
   The government said two smaller domestic airlines, Cebu Pacific
Air and Air Philippines, would expand service to fill the vacuum.
Thursday, both airlines were arranging to lease planes from
Philippine Airlines, commonly known as PAL.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Antonio said, the airlines had only a fraction of
Philippine Airlines' domestic capacity. But he added, ``I'm very
confident that we will be able to solve this problem by the end of
October.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said an overly rapid expansion could create safety
hazards. Several Air Philippines planes have already been grounded
because of government concerns about maintenance standards. In
February, a Cebu Pacific DC-9 crashed into a mountain, killing all
104 people on board.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also noted that some domestic Philippine Airlines
routes were unprofitable, and only existed because of an agreement
between the airline and the government. If the government wants to
continue serving remote or outlying islands, they said, it may have
to subsidize those routes.
</P>
<P>
   Though the collapse of Philippine Airlines will have less of an
impact on international air travel, its loss will still be felt.
Singapore Airlines has already doubled its economy-class fares
between Singapore and Manila to exploit the exit of its only
competitor on that route. Cathay Pacific Airways, which serves the
heavily traveled Hong Kong-Manila route, said it would not
immediately lift fares.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio said the government was also encouraging foreign
carriers to increase their flights to the Philippines. Japan
Airlines recently agreed to schedule 36 additional flights from
Japanese cities to the resort island of Cebu, between now and
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flag carriers are not really needed, provided that the
government is willing to give the routes to foreign carriers,''
said David Sherman, a consultant who heads the transportation
practice at A.T. Kearney Ltd. in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said no flag carrier was better than a second-rate
one. ``It may have been the first airline in Asia, but it was
carrying a lot of excess baggage,'' Jim Eckes, an aviation
consultant at Indoswiss Ltd. in Hong Kong, said. ``It just has
never been well managed, from the Marcos era on.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is where national pride comes in. Antonio said
Philippine Airlines was a valuable tool in the country's marketing
efforts. At airports from London to Los Angeles, its planes were
large, rolling billboards for the country. Though some detractors
said PAL stood for ``Planes Always Late,'' fans of the airline said
it exuded the warmth and cheer of the Philippines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, the airline's staff marked the long-threatened shutdown
on Wednesday in a characteristically emotional fashion. Employees
at Manila's airport hugged and wept, while the pilot of the last
incoming flight, from Tokyo, walked off the plane singing a
variation on the 1970s hit song ``We May Never Love Like This
Again.'' His version: ``We may never fly this plane again.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a miserable end for an airline that started out in 1941
with one plane carrying five passengers on a 125-mile flight from
Manila to the northern city of Baguio.
</P>
<P>
   The allure of owning a flag carrier has fueled rumors that
Philippine Airlines may be sold to another foreign carrier. Estrada
said in a Bloomberg News report Thursday that three airlines had
already expressed interest: Northwest Airlines, Cathay Pacific and
Eva Airways of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced we've seen the end of PAL,'' said Peter
Negline, an airline analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   If no buyers resurrect Philippine Airlines, its creditors could
face a protracted and messy fight to get their money back.
Bankruptcy law in the Philippines is not as developed as that of
other countries, and Philippine Airlines is the biggest corporate
failure in the country since the Asian economic crisis began more
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company has suspended payments on its $2.1 billion in debt
for two months. When it resumes payments, analysts said the line of
creditors will include local and foreign banks, plus export-import
banks in the United States and Europe. Because the company's debts
are as large as its assets, analysts said the creditors could wind
up dickering over planes.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the process is that the second-largest local
creditor, Allied Bank, is owned by Tan, who also owns the airline.
One of the richest men in the Philippines, Tan took control of the
carrier in 1994 and has vast interests in tobacco, brewing and real
estate. Nick Cashmore, a banking analyst at ABN Amro in Manila,
estimated the bank's exposure at $76 million.
</P>
<P>
   Two other potential casualties of the collapse are Airbus
Industrie and Boeing Co. Eckes said Philippine Airlines had
recently acquired 16 Airbus planes, with another 12 on order. It
also ordered several 747s from Boeing. The airline may return many
of these planes as part of the liquidation process.
</P>
<P>
   For Estrada, the closing of Philippine Airlines is a bitter
denouement to what had become a passionate campaign. During the
negotiations, the government offered the airline a bridge loan of
$34 million for two months until new investors could be found.
Estrada met with both sides until Wednesday evening but failed to
break the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done all that I can as president because I know it will
affect our country, not just the jobs of the labor union, but the
jobs and businesses connected with Philippine Airlines,'' he said
afterward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
