<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE RAGES ON SCOPE OF IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House all but certain to launch a full
impeachment inquiry of President Clinton, a rash of new disputes
erupted Thursday over the scope of the investigation, including
whether to summon Monica S. Lewinsky and the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, to testify on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Additional skirmishes broke out as the House Judiciary Committee
scheduled a vote on the impeachment inquiry for Oct. 5 or Oct. 6.
The full House is expected to approve the investigation by Oct. 9,
but set no deadline for ending the probe.
</P>
<P>
   As a bipartisan resolution of Clinton's sex scandal remained
elusive amid an escalating political free-for-all, lawmakers
wrangled over a series of highly charged issues, including whether
the Judiciary Committee should expand the sex-related probe to
campaign fundraising abuses, and whether Linda R. Tripp's secretly
recorded audiotapes of her conversations with Lewinsky should be
made public next week.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is scheduled to meet Friday to debate releasing
the Tripp tapes and nearly 65,000 pages of additional material
supporting Starr's charges that Clinton may have committed 11
impeachable offenses stemming from his illicit affair with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the meeting, Democratic lawmakers stepped up their
accusations that the Republican majority has shut them out of
preliminary impeachment decisions, even those as mundane as
scheduling matters. And the two sides remained nowhere near
consensus on one of their most crucial duties: defining the basic
question of what constitutes an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton joined the fray, abandoning his self-imposed
contrition over the Lewinsky scandal in the wake of polls that
showed no drop in his job approval rating after the broadcast on
Monday of his videotaped grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after a Rose Garden ceremony if he saw any alternative to
impeachment, Clinton admonished Congress to concentrate on ``what's
best for the American people'' rather than the sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right thing for me to do is what I'm doing,'' he said.
``I'm working on leading our country, and I'm working on healing my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his job record proves ``it is utterly foolish for
people to be diverted or distracted from the urgent challenges
still before us. It tells me the right thing to do is put progress
over partisanship, put people over politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued the broadside as his hope of engineering a quick
alternative to a full impeachment investigation appeared to
dissolve. As lawmakers in both parties acknowledged the virtual
certainty of a formal inquiry, one of Speaker Newt Gingrich's top
lieutenants emerged on the House floor to attack the most prominent
alternative plan: a congressional censure and fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's dispense with the notion that Congress can punish the
president either by a so-called censure or by a fine or by any
other punishment,'' said Representative Tom DeLay, a Texas
Republican who is the House majority whip. ``Such a deal is
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   If the formal impeachment process begins Oct. 9, according to
Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee, the panel's staff
would investigate Starr's charges against Clinton for several
weeks, while most lawmakers are home campaigning for reelection.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chairman, Representative Henry J. Hyde of
Illinois, said he hopes to begin hearings after the Nov. 3
elections if the House approves a full inquiry. But no one could
predict when the investigation would end, or even if it would
conclude before the next Congress is seated in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not certain,'' said Representative George W. Gekas, a
Pennsylvania Republican who sits on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for committee Democrats, Representative Barney Frank of
Massachusetts lashed out at Hyde for announcing the schedule
without consulting the Democrats and accused the Republican
majority of dragging out the process as a partisan weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an effort to run out the clock so the election comes
and goes with this totally unresolved, with all the questions
hanging,'' Frank said. ``I think the dilemma my Republican
colleagues face is, they have a significant part of their party
that wants an impeachment and, to their disappointment, the public
does not appear ready to join them.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the potential spectacle of Lewinsky telling her story in
front of the cameras in the Judiciary Committee hearings, Hyde and
several other Republicans on the panel downplayed the prospect,
saying it would be unnecessary because they could rely on Starr's
detailed account of her relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said he has ``no reason to doubt'' Lewinsky's testimony in
Starr's investigation, ``so I'm prepared to take what she said''
without calling her before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   That outraged Democrats, who accused Hyde of professing
bipartisanship while unilaterally deciding issues as pivotal as
which witnesses to call.
</P>
<P>
   ``To suggest that the Judiciary Committee is going to put this
country through a potentially year-long ordeal with hearings, and
then to suggest that main witnesses are not going to be called,
shows either an incredible lack of judgment or a partisan stampede
on the president,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a
Massachusetts Democrat who serves on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde later issued a statement saying he may have been
``misunderstood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly no decisions have been made on who might testify,
should the committee (and the full House) vote to conduct a formal
inquiry,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet committee members continued to tangle over prospective
witnesses, including Starr. ``There is no way we can evaluate this
report without calling Ken Starr before the committee,'' Meehan
said.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Starr would face an extraordinary grilling from
committee Democrats, including some who have denounced his
``four-year, $40 million'' investigation of Clinton as a ``witch
hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans immediately rallied against the proposal. ``I don't
know what purpose would be served by having Mr. Starr there to
testify,'' said Representative Charles T. Canady, a Florida
Republican who is chairman of the Judiciary subcommittee on the
Constitution. ``He's not a material witness in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said the Republicans appeared to want to hold a hearing
without witnesses. ``We can't hear from Monica Lewinsky,'' he said.
``We can't hear from Ken Starr. They don't want to hear from
President Clinton. What are we going to do at this hearing. Play
records?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hyde expressed partial support for Gingrich's
suggestion that the inquiry be expanded to alleged fund-raising
abuses by Clinton's campaign in 1996. Angering Democrats, Hyde said
the Judiciary Committee would leave open the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us are interested in casting a very wide net,'' Hyde
said. But if other evidence of possibly impeachable arises, he
said, ``I would never say we won't hear those things.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Tripp tapes, which are considered favorable to
Clinton because of questions about Tripp's motives and the tapes's
authenticity, Republicans said they are inclined to withhold the
audiotapes and release transcripts, with broad sections blacked out
to protect privacy rights and excise sexually explicit remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who are split over releasing the audiotape,
nonetheless accused GOP members of hypocrisy for favoring
withholding the material after making public Clinton's videotaped
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that what the Republicans on the committee want to
do is withhold evidence that is exculpatory'' for Clinton, Meehan
said. ``The president has been railroaded enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tripp tapes are expected to generate some of the most heated
debate in today's meeting. Notable among the other items to be
considered for release are transcripts of grand jury testimony by
Tripp, Secret Service officers, a White House butler, Clinton's
secretary, and the president's close friend, Vernon E. Jordan Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The material to be made public is expected to be shipped to the
Government Printing Office this weekend and made available late
next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
