<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHICS INVESTIGATION OF HOLBROOKE IS NEARLY OVER, HIS LAWYER SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The lawyer for Richard Holbrooke, whose
nomination as the American representative at the United Nations has
been sidetracked by a federal ethics investigation, said on
Thursday that the inquiry was nearly over and that investigators
had found nothing that should stop the nomination from proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Richard Beattie, said the Justice Department had
advised him that the investigation focused solely on whether
Holbrooke had benefited from illegal contacts with his former State
Department colleagues after he left in 1996 to become vice chairman
of Credit Suisse First Boston, a New York-based investment banking
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie said a Justice Department official in Washington had
assured him in a telephone call on Thursday that the investigation
of Holbrooke, the veteran diplomat and architect of the 1995 peace
agreement in Bosnia, was expected to end within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie would not name the Justice Department official with whom
he spoke. A Justice Department spokesman, John Russell, had no
comment on the timetable for the inquiry, nor would he predict its
outcome. President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright have pledged their continuing support for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that this investigation will end without any
finding of wrongdoing and that Mr. Holbrooke will be nominated and
confirmed in due course to serve this country,'' Beattie said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials say the investigation began
with an anonymous letter last summer to the State Department's
inspector general asserting that Holbrooke may have had a ``quid
pro quo'' with the Credit Suisse while he still worked at the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed contents of the letter were disclosed on Thursday
by the Washington Post, which did not report how it had obtained
the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's lawyers acknowledged that in March 1995, when
Holbrooke was assistant secretary of state for European and
Canadian affairs, he helped Credit Suisse by contacting the
American ambassador in Hungary to ask the American embassy there to
withdraw its exclusive support for a different investment banking
firm, Solomon Brothers, for a multimillion-dollar consulting
contract with the Hungarian government. The ambassador agreed, and
Credit Suisse went on to win the contract.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the Ambassador at the time, Donald Blinken,
said that Holbrooke had done nothing wrong in seeking to help
Credit Suisse and another investment banking firm, Goldman Sachs,
which were in competition with Solomon Brothers to advise the
Hungarian government on the privatization of a state phone company.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Holbrooke argued that although Credit Suisse First
Boston is owned by a Swiss banking group, it is largely managed and
staffed by Americans and was entitled to some assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holbrooke was a very hands-on assistant secretary, which was
good, and I think he was acting based on complaints that were made
to his office by C.S. First Boston, which is that they weren't
being treated in an even-handed way,'' Blinken said. ``I came to
see that there was a good case to be made for including them,
considering that they have a lot of American employees and are
obviously an important player in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he understood that Holbrooke's office had been lobbied
intensively by Credit Suisse First Boston for help in obtaining the
Hungarian contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were camping out at the State Department,'' Blinken said,
adding that Holbrooke's later employment by Credit Suisse was
``just one of those strange quirks of fate _ I think it's
coincidence really.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has declined to be interviewed about the
investigation. But friends and advisers say that when he began
weighing job opportunities on Wall Street toward the end of 1995,
he never considered Credit Suisse as a potential employer.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie said that he had been assured by the Justice Department
on Thursday that it was not pursuing the assertions involving the
Hungarian government contract.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the State Department, Holbrooke was appointed the
special unpaid State Department envoy to the Balkans, a post that
required him to meet repeatedly with foreign leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie said that in the meetings, which are the subject of the
Justice Department inquiry, Holbrooke was always careful to focus
on either his work for the Clinton administration or on his work
for Credit Suisse _ but never the two together. ``He was always
very careful to avoid conflicts of interest,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
