<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RIPKEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIPKEN SAYS DECISION AIDED BY ORIOLES' RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If his team were still in the hunt for the wild card,
Orioles third baseman Cal Ripken wouldn't have played his trump
card last Sunday in Baltimore by pulling himself out of the lineup
and ending his major league-record streak of consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Red Sox and Blue Jays, not the Orioles, who were
still in the chase, and that unavoidable scenario, said Ripken, was
very much on his mind last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a contradiction, of sorts, in my voluntarily taking a
day off,'' said Ripken, who played 2,632 straight games, ``but I
think it got to that point that the reponsibility, the burden,
whatever you want to call, it was being firmly put on my shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had gotten to the point to put the focus back on the team
and move on. It was time to change the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he said, during a pregame press conference in the visitors'
dugout before Thursday night's game at Fenway Park, it would all be
an open book _ if the Orioles' second-half surge hadn't lost steam
a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our season wasn't over, even though we didn't have the best
first half,'' he said. ``We still had an opportunity with the
talent that we had to make a run at the wild-card spot, and I felt
an obligation and a responsibility to continue to fight that
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken said, however, that in the back of his mind, ``if we fell
short of that, then I was prepared to end the streak.'' He first
thought about doing it in Fenway on the last day of the season
because ``it would stand out to everyone that if I was really
selfish about the streak, I could easily have played one more game
and taken it into next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, Ripken was hoping the four-game series in Boston
would have meaning for his team ``and that issues about the streak
wouldn't have come into play. It didn't work out that way. We
faltered a little bit, Boston continued to play strong, and we
couldn't catch them.''
</P>
<P>
   So last Sunday, instead of waiting one week, Ripken, not manager
Ray Miller, pulled the plug, making Ryan Minor the answer to a
trivia question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was faced with the decision I had made earlier in the season
and I felt that was the time to implement it,'' said Ripken, who
took a .273 batting average with 14 homers and 61 RBIs into
Thursday night's game, in which he batted fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt for (Minor). I tried to assure him it was my decision.
I just told him to play his game and I thought he handled himself
really well.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment's hesitation, though, by Minor, just before
game time last Sunday at Camden Yards. ``I think he was still
waiting for my approval,'' said Ripken. ``I just kept telling him,
`Go ahead, take the field.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand that because my teammates didn't know until
the very end (just before game time).''
</P>
<P>
   As for next season?
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's uncharted waters for me,'' he said. ``I'm
open and amenable to whatever tha manager suggests. I consider
myself an everyday player with the desire to prove that on a daily
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a good second half. I've made some adjustjments in my
swing and I'm feeling good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he feels good about the streak, not necessarily in terms of
numbers but in terms of what he brought to the table from May 30,
1982, to Sept. 19, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stands for many, many good things,'' he said. ``It's very
symbolic as to who I am and my approach as a player. It identifies
some of my most positive traits. It meant that my manager and
teammates could count on my being there for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
