<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3218 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-CONFLICT-WORKWEEK     09-24 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CONFLICT-WORKWEEK-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULL-TIME MOTHERS MEET PART-TIME JOBS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill.)  (Eds: Please note subslug) 
(af) 
 By JULIA LAWLOR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a typical school day in Mill Valley, Calif., Paula Reynolds
rises at 5:30 a.m., gets her two oldest children out the door by
7:45 and hops into the car to follow her youngest as he navigates
his bike down the hill to school.
</P>
<P>
   Then she commutes to work to San Francisco, 45 minutes away.
Five hectic hours later, she heads back home in time to greet her
children _ Peter, 12; Julia, 9, and Charlie, 6 _ at the door at 3
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids are at an age where they want to be with me more than
anybody else,'' said Ms. Reynolds, 43, the co-owner of a firm that
supplies temporary executives to corporations. So she works a
26-hour week, guaranteeing that she will have some afternoon hours
with her children. ``I'll have plenty of time later to develop my
career,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reynolds has resolved to her satisfaction the great quandary
of the working Mom _ how to balance the demands of her job with the
tugging at her heart. But the conundrum stymies millions of women,
and not a few men, anew each fall as the school year begins.
</P>
<P>
   The job _ and the desire to advance _ beckon. But who will great
young children at the end of the day? Older children might be able
to fend for themselves, but shouldn't somebody be there prodding
them to do their homework or driving them to soccer practice?
</P>
<P>
   For most women, quitting their jobs is not an option; they
simply cannot afford the loss of income. Many of those part-time
positions being advertised in the newspaper _ as bank tellers,
school aides or store clerks _ pay pittances. And despite all the
talk at corporations these days about family-friendly workplaces,
asking the boss for a reduced work schedule often gets a frosty
reception.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reynolds found that out in 1986, when she asked her manager
in the sales division of the AT&AMP;T Corp. if she could cut back on
her hours to spend more time with her infant son. The answer was
no. So she quit and founded her company, M Squared, with another
mother.
</P>
<P>
   But for the vast majority of working women, who don't own
businesses, the task can be much trickier.
</P>
<P>
   More people than ever want to escape the confines of the
traditional workweek. In a survey of 2,877 employees last year by
the Families and Work Institute, based in New York, 63 percent said
they would like to reduce the number of hours they worked, up from
47 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of working parents say they did not have enough
time to spend with their children.
</P>
<P>
   But the study also showed that many workers felt that it would
be difficult to move to shorter hours. Only 38 percent of
full-timers said ``yes'' or ``maybe'' when asked if they could
arrange a part-time schedule, while 58 percent of part-timers gave
those answers when asked if they could switch to full-time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Part-Time work is especially rare among managers. A survey of
2,000 managers and professionals in four companies last year by
Catalyst, a New York firm that consults with businesses on women's
issues, found that just 11 percent of the women and 4 percent of
the men worked part-time, compared with 21 percent and 8 percent,
respectively, for all working women and men.
</P>
<P>
   Although more than 60 percent of large employers offer part-time
work, according to Hewitt Associates, a benefits consulting firm,
there are very few takers among the full-time staff, and for good
reason. Part-time work, of course, generally comes with no health
insurance, paid vacations, sick days or other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And many managers believe it is difficult to manage a staff that
has varying part-time schedules. ``People don't widely use these
policies because there's a general sense that they don't work,''
said Marcia Brumit Kropf, a vice president at Catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   Many corporate cultures continue to put more value on ``face
time,'' or the number of hours a worker stays in the office, than
on the work product. And workers who switch to part-time schedules
risk being viewed as less committed to their work.
</P>
<P>
   There are also days when part-timers feel inadequate both at
work and home and wonder if all the juggling is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I feel like I have the best of all worlds;
sometimes I feel like I'm not doing anything well,'' Ms. Reynolds
said. Her dual responsibilities have so crowded her life that her
colleagues once bought her a ``Where's Waldo?'' book for Christmas,
pasted a little picture of Ms. Reynolds over Waldo's face, and
retitled it ``Where's Paula?''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Lindmeier, 42, a lab technician who has held a series of
temporary jobs for nine years through Manpower, the temporary help
company, thinks she would have been promoted to a management
position by now had she stayed with one employer.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Lindmeier, of Wadsworth, Ill., has always wanted to work
a 7 a.m.-to-3:30 p.m. shift and have summers off with her children,
now 15 and 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a small town on a lake where we'd spend all
summer hanging out,'' she said. ``I wanted my kids to have summers
off like I did, and not to be in day care 12 months a year.''
</P>
<P>
   True, she sometimes feels a pang of jealousy about her husband's
paycheck, which equaled hers when the couple was childless but is
now four times hers. Still, she cannot imagine giving up summers of
swimming and bike-riding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten so darned used to this,'' she said, ``I don't
think I'll ever go back to full-time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
