<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO JAILS 2 DRUG AGENTS, AND U.S. OFFICIALS SEE GRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SAM DILLON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIJUANA, Mexico _ In a new case raising friction between
American and Mexican law enforcement officials, two Mexican drug
enforcement agents are in jail here on kidnapping charges that
appear to have been trumped up by corrupt police officers working
with traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   The two Mexican agents, part of an elite anti-drug unit that
works closely with U.S. officials, were preparing to buy a ton of
marijuana from Tijuana traffickers as part of a buy-and-bust
operation when they were arrested by Baja California state
policemen who were summoned by one of the traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   The traffickers, a father and son, have made protection payments
to the state police who came to their rescue, according to sworn
testimony and Mexican and American government documents in court
files here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing smells,'' said an American official familiar
with the case. Several U.S. officials portrayed the arrest as the
latest example of how pervasive corruption frustrates attempts to
work with Mexican law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. officials are particularly perplexed because several
Mexican Federal Police took part alongside the state police in
arresting men who are, technically, their own colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Herran Salvatti, who heads Mexico's Federal
anti-narcotics agency, said in an interview in Mexico City on
Thursday that he believed corrupt Baja state police were seeking
vengeance against the two federal agents because, since their
15-member intelligence unit arrived in Tijuana in early September,
it has already made several large drug seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Baja state police, who have visited the two agents in jail, have
asked them to name their undercover colleagues and commanders and
to divulge the address of their undercover offices, Herran said.
The state police have also threatened to kill the federal agents,
he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the Baja California state police, Alvaro
Castilla Gracia, insisted that the agents must stand trial,
although he acknowledged in an interview that circumstances
surrounding their arrest were more consistent with an undercover
drug operation than a kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Since the agents' arrest on Sept. 11, he said, other kidnapping
complaints have been filed against them. The two incidents for
which the state authorities provided dates occurred before the
federal agents say they arrived in Tijuana, however.
</P>
<P>
   The two agents, Eligio Garcia Reyes, 29, and Nicolas Carrillo
Jimenez, 24, were recruited about a year ago into Mexico's elite
anti-narcotics force, the Special Prosecutorial Agency for Drug
Crimes, known by its Spanish acronym FEADS, as part of an effort to
rejuvenate Mexico's discredited drug enforcement agencies with
honest young agents.
</P>
<P>
   After passing lie detector tests and other examinations of their
integrity, they were trained in investigative and intelligence
procedures by Drug Enforcement Administration officers at an
American training center in Leesburg, Va., Garcia and American
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Mexico, the two were first assigned to the state of
Guadalajara, where they took part in investigations that led to the
successful prosecution of Mexico's foremost methamphetamine ring,
an American official said.
</P>
<P>
   This month they were transferred to Tijuana to work in a drug
intelligence unit that cooperates closely with American officials,
Garcia said. Several undercover informants with whom the two agents
had worked in Guadalajara, including Jose Luis Rodriguez Gonzalez,
also traveled to Tijuana to continue their undercover operations
there, Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez Gonzalez has testified in the court proceedings that
once he arrived in Tijuana he met Victor Manuel Monge Gonzalez, 50,
and his son, Julio Monge Ochoa, 21, in a bar. They offered to sell
Rodriguez a ton of marijuana, Rodriguez has testified.
</P>
<P>
   In several face-to-face negotiations, the traffickers assured
Rodriguez that their drug organization was protected by corrupt
Baja California state police officers, according to Rodriguez's
court testimony. One one occasion Monge boasted that in exchange
for a load of marijuana, he had given a house to one of the
officers, Luis Humberto Gamez Lazcano, according to the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 11 Rodriguez called Agent Garcia and said he was about
to meet with Julio Monge at Tijuana's Terranova Hotel to test a
sample of the ton of marijuana. Garcia told the informant he would
meet him, informed his commanding officer, and with his fellow
agent, Carrillo, traveled to the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after arriving at the hotel, the two federal
agents, three informants the agents said were working with them on
the sting operation, and three bystanders were seized by state,
federal and Tijuana municipal police, and taken to jail on
kidnapping charges, according to police reports. Garcia and
Rodriguez said they were beaten by the state police. The three
bystanders were later released.
</P>
<P>
   The police seized six pounds of marijuana from the room in which
Rodriguez was arrested, and in which Monge later testified he was
being held in a kidnapping. When the police found Monge he was not
bound in any way, was wearing his watch and several items of gold
jewelry, and hotel records show he had made several phone calls
from the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Baja California authorities trumpeted the arrest in several
front-page newspaper stories in Tijuana as a spectacular rescue of
a kidnapping victim.
</P>
<P>
   The two agents, in the meantime, appear to have received little
attention from their superior officers within the vast bureaucracy
headed by Mexico's federal attorney general, although their
commander did hire a lawyer for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't tell how much our chiefs are trying to help us,
because we haven't seen the support,'' Garcia Reyes said in a
telephone interview from prison.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
