<HEADLINE>
BABA LEWIS   WAS A   BATTLER TO THE END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She couldn't decide whether her most famous partner was
Charlie Chaplin or Errol Flynn. But Baba Lewis would tell envious
friends that both those movie gods were ``gentlemen and sportsmen
on the tennis court when we played mixed doubles. Except Chaplin's
shorts kept falling down, and he went right on playing until he
noticed and pulled them up again and apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, as the Little Tramp, he had those baggy trousers
that didn't fit, and his tennis shorts were the same. It was pretty
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days after World War II when Hollywood was crazy
about the game, and the stars invited leading players to tennis
parties at their private courts. Mercedes Johnson Madden ``Baba''
Lewis of Newtonville, who died Wednesday, was a prized partner.
There will be a graveside funeral service at Newton Cemetery at 11
a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   As the last Bostonian to rank in the US Top 10 (No. 10 in 1951,
No. 8 in 1952-53), Lewis was a diminutive but dynamic, nimble
competitor, extremely quick and a strong volleyer although but 5
feet 2 inches. With piercing eyes and dark hair cut short, she
seemed all business, yet could laugh heartily at herself and
wisecrack while at play.
</P>
<P>
   Baba Lewis was 78 when her heart gave out, but it carried her
extraordinarily well over a long, rewarding stretch in both tennis
and squash. She was No. 1 in New England four times over 14 years
(1951-53-63-64) while hitting balls over nets, and No. 3 nationally
(1968-60-61) banging them against walls, winning the US Senior
squash titles of 1965-68-69-70.
</P>
<P>
   Installed in the New England Tennis Hall of Fame in 1992, she
``had so many sectional and national titles and rankings, from a
little girl onward, that you'd run out of breath reciting them.''
So says a friend, US Tennis Association-New England historian Nancy
Norton. ``But what many of us remember was her generosity and
kindness in helping and encouraging younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``She grumbled after beating me once that I wasn't enough
competition. But I said if she didn't have people like me to beat
in the first and second rounds, there'd be no tournaments, and she
had to smile.''
</P>
<P>
   During a brief marriage to another ranking tennis player, Morey
Lewis, she and he pulled a rare double, both winning the Canadian
singles of 1946. But Baba was more a loner, happiest tending her
rose garden when she could no longer play.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was ill a long time at the end,'' says her sister-in-law,
Halima (Mrs. Ted) Madden, ``in intensive care once for 30 days. Her
doctor said it was unbelievable the way she fought and stayed
alive, but I told him that's what champions do _ fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
