<HEADLINE>
PRESENTING NEWS IN TIMES OF SCANDAL BECOMES A DELICATE BALANCING
ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ill., Mass., Md., N.J., Texas)  (See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-REPUBS-MONEY,
CLINTON-ASSESS.) 
(js) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been an unequal contest. Hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico
versus the possibility of impeachment proceedings. International
economic breakdowns versus an unprecedented video of President
Clinton defending himself during questioning about intimate sex
acts with Monica Lewinsky. Sometimes it has seemed that the only
newsmakers able to hold their own against the onrushing steamroller
of the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal have been two baseball players,
Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   What news coverage gets short shrift when a scandal like the
present one takes grip of the news columns and airwaves? None, some
newspaper editors and network news executives say. Lots, say
others, citing the pre-election coverage of the primaries held
around the country on Sept. 15, the instability in Russia, the
economic troubles of Japan and Brazil, and the issue of
international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``News coverage has been distorted to the most incredible degree
I have seen in my lifetime,'' said Charles Peters, editor of The
Washington Monthly, a political journal based in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews over the last two days, editors and news directors
have defended their judgment calls, but most acknowledge that they
have been concerned about the sacrifices made to accommodate the
heavy coverage that they believe is justified because the events
could lead to impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about changing presidents,'' said Al Ortiz, the
executive producer of CBS' ``Evening News with Dan Rather.'' ``It's
hard to imagine anything more important as that. My intention has
been to devote as much time to this story as possible, to explain
what's going on behind the scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz added, ``Several important foreign stories _ Kosovo and
Russia _ have had to take a little bit of a back seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Bradlee Jr., a deputy managing editor of The Boston Globe,
said: ``The possibility of impeachment comes along once a
generation. But you still have to be concerned about getting a good
mix in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the Clinton videotape demanded so much space that
The Boston Globe delayed the third part of an in-depth series on
food safety for a day. At The Chicago Tribune and The Baltimore
Sun, investigative projects ready for publication were also
temporarily shelved last weekend. ``What gets delayed might be a
series on race or an investigative project in the works that's
timely and topical but not urgent,'' said William Marimow, The
Sun's managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   The issue goes beyond where articles are placed. Diversion of
resources comes at a price. One test of how excessive coverage is,
said James Willse, the editor of The Newark Star-Ledger. is ``what
do the papers look like three and four and five days away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in covering the story you've exhausted yourself, and five
days out there is nothing in the paper, that's a subtler statement
of the kind of price you've paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Reader complaints about excessive coverage of the Washington
crisis have been heard, some editors say. But readers also bought
the newspapers containing text from the Starr report in unusually
high numbers. At The Tribune, the edition with the Starr report
sold 75,000 more copies than usual; at The St. Petersburg Times,
excess demand for that edition reached 5,500 or more copies.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Oppel, the editor of The Austin American-Statesman, said
that the paper containing text of the Starr report sold 9,300 extra
copies. Nonetheless, he is troubled by the sacrifices in coverage.
``We delayed some Texas state election roundups,'' he said, adding,
``What got crowded off our page one has been the German election,
the shaky economy, the Russian ruble, and reports of erratic
economic developments in Tokyo and Hong Kong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At The Baltimore Sun, Marimow said, state political and
government reporters were not called in to do the crisis coverage.
Instead ``we took people we consider really talented working on
ongoing projects that didn't have the same degree of urgency.'' For
instance, he said, a reporter working on a financial investigation,
who has special legal expertise, was pulled off the day the Clinton
videotape appeared to assess the president's effectiveness as a
witness.
</P>
<P>
   At The Washington Post, the managing editor, Steve Coll, said
the volume of pre-primary coverage was not cut back this year. ``We
certainly haven't produced any less journalism about the election
this season than we would have otherwise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even on days of peak coverage, the scandal has not shut all
other news off front pages. The Dallas Morning News devoted three
of seven front-page articles to the Washington crisis Tuesday, the
day after the Clinton videotape aired. The newspaper also put an
article about the Dallas Cowboy's victory over the Giants on Monday
night high on a page that included reports on the death of the
sprinter Florence Griffith Joyner and an in-depth article about
Lithuania, part of a series on the Baltic states.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Barnes, the editor of The St. Petersburg Times, argues
that newspaper editorial judgments are ``not a zero-sum game. We're
in the position _ if there's more going on, we make more room for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``if the premise is that this scandal is a
distraction, so is life.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Friedman, the executive producer of ABC's ``World News
Tonight'' strongly defends his network's overall mix of recent
coverage, pointing to four reports on Russia since Sept. 7, an
in-depth report on the world economy on Sept. 16 and a Sept. 9
broadcast from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In another office at ABC, newscaster Ted Koppel said he and his
colleagues at ``Nightline'' are assembling a group of commentators
to discuss on the air periodically ``what it is they think is of
gravest importance in the world that we're not paying proper
attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made an institutional decision as a program,'' he said,
``that we need to do a night that says, `While our attention was
otherwise directed, these other stories were happening.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3229 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT-ART     09-24 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS UNNERVED BY NEAR COLLAPSE OF INVESTMENT FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on how a hedge fund works is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: See also HEDGEFUND-TEAM, HEDGEFUND-RISK) 
(mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The $3.5 billion rescue of a large investment fund
verging on collapse unnerved markets around the world Thursday,
raised a clamor for a government investigation and fanned fear that
other enormous hidden losses would surface in the weeks and months
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than contain the problem and bring stability to Wall
Street, the cash infusion late Wednesday by a consortium of banks
and brokerage firms to salvage Long-Term Capital Management LP only
seemed to rattle investors. Banks began to tighten their lending
requirements, raising fears of a credit shortage that could result
in a recession.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stocks fell broadly and the Dow Jones industrial average
lost more than half its 257.21-point gain Wednesday. Shares of
financial stocks were particularly hard-hit.
</P>
<P>
   Investors tried to absorb not only what had happened to
Long-Term and its founder, Wall Street bond trader John Meriwether,
but what the deal to salvage the fund meant for wobbly world
markets. As details of Long-Term's fall to earth began to trickle
out and the shock among traders, brokers and bankers began to fade,
fear set in. Lawmakers on Capitol Hill called for an inquiry into
what went wrong and resentment grew that an elite firm, populated
by industry stars and two Nobel Laureates, was saved from a
disaster of its own making.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, it was clear that Long-Term Capital's problems were
not going to be confined to the firm and a few high-roller
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The ripple effect started with UBS, the world's second-largest
bank, which said its risky investments with Long-Term and ownership
stake in the fund would result in an accounting charge of $720
million against the Swiss bank's own earnings. Its stock fell 10.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of deep concern to the financial community is exactly what
impact the debacle will have on worldwide bond markets, already
badly shaken by events in emerging markets during the past two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of a pullback in lending among major financial
institutions also grew Thursday as banks were awakened to the risks
in their previously easy-money attitudes toward borrowers. If
difficulty in borrowing money lasted more than a few weeks, it
could cause a significant slowdown in the economy, maybe even a
recession if it lasted long enough.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of Meriwether's troubles are great for hedge
funds, the oddly named investment funds that cater largely to
wealthy individuals and large institutional investors, often making
enormous bets on risky securities with little oversight from
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Many in this world believe that Long-Term Capital's
near-collapse and its takeover by big banks and brokers will
translate to increased client nervousness and rising redemptions
among other firms. For funds operating in the already beleaguered
bond market, redemptions would cause a continued downward spiral in
these portfolios. If some of these areas take even further hits,
junk bonds for example, heavy redemptions could hit plain-vanilla
mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the worry that the disaster will bring
increased scrutiny by regulators to hedge funds. Rep. John LaFalce,
D-N.Y., the ranking minority member of the House Banking Committee,
said in a statement Thursday that ``The virtual collapse and
bailout of Long Term Capital Management makes clear that the
Banking Committee must continue its inquiry into potential risks
posed by any gaps in the regulation of hedge funds, and I'll be
calling on chairman Leach to do precisely that.'' Rep. Jim Leach,
R-Iowa, is the chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The specter of Long-Term Capital's near failure is not going
away anytime soon. Indeed it will dog the financial industry
through at least the end of the year. Traders say the overhang of
its $90 billion portfolio will keep much of the fixed-income
markets frozen. If the Federal Reserve Board's policy-making
committee reduces interest rates next Tuesday, as is widely
expected, that would hurt many of the trades Long-Term has on its
books.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate reaction to Long-Term's woes was that major banks
and brokerage firms began demanding increased margins, or partial
payments from their hedge fund customers on new trades.
</P>
<P>
   One hedge fund manager who invests in bonds said that the firms
he deals with were asking for 2 percent margin, significantly more
than the typical requirements of one-quarter of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the details of the bailout were still being
finalized. Late in the day, investors in the fund were still
waiting to hear where they stood. It is expected that existing
investors will end up with 10 percent of their original stake in
the firm and that the consortium of banks and brokers will wind up
with 90 percent. An oversight committee with representatives from
the banks will direct overall strategy at Long-Term. In one of the
many small ironies attending this crisis, Meriwether will be
reporting to people who were, in some cases, very junior traders on
his desk at Salomon Brothers in the 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLL-METHOD-N     09-24 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-METHOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE POLL WAS CONDUCTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CLINTON-POLL.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll is based on telephone
interviews conducted Tuesday and Wednesday with 960 adults
throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The sample of telephone exchanges called was randomly selected
by a computer from a complete list of more than 42,000 active
residential exchanges across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Within each exchange, random digits were added to form a
complete telephone number to permit access both to listed and
unlisted numbers. Within each household, one adult was designated
by a random procedure to be the respondent for the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been weighted to take account of household size
and number of telephone lines into the residence and to adjust for
variations in the sample relating to geographic region, sex, race,
age, and education.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, in 19 cases out of 20 the results based on such
samples will differ by no more than 3 percentage points in either
direction from what would have been obtained by seeking out all
American adults. For smaller subgroups the potential sampling error
is larger.
</P>
<P>
   For example, for Southerners, it is plus or minus 6 percentage
points. For residents of the Northeast, or the Midwest or the West,
it is 7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sampling error, the practical difficulties of
conducting any survey of public opinion may introduce other sources
of error into the poll. Variations in question wording or the order
of questions, for instance, can lead to somewhat different
results. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
