<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preparing and Praying: Residents wait on Georges
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. _ With their homes shuttered and their cupboards
stocked, the Florida Keys settled in to wait for Hurricane Georges
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities issued a 9 p.m. curfew and ordered traffic stopped
below Marathon by 4 p.m., but that didn't stop resilient locals
from gathering at the Green Parrot on Whitehead Street in Key West,
a ring of bicycles circling the outside bar. Several blocks away, a
handful of faithful prayed at St. Mary's By the Sea Catholic church
while others hurried with last minute chores and kept an eye on
growing clouds overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you can do in times like this is prepare and
come here and pray,'' Maggie Hernandez said after lighting a candle
at St. Bernedette's grotto, a 76-year-old shrine dedicated to
protecting the island from ``the full brunt of a hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hurricane Georges expected to rebuild fast, the nation's
top hurricane forecaster said Thursday he fears ``we'll lose a lot
of folks'' ignoring an evacuation order if storm waters wash over
the flat Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   About 770,000 people from Key West nearly to the Tampa Bay area
were advised to flee, but there was no indication how many obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This storm looks like it's all set to explosively intensify
once the eye gets over water,'' said Jerry Jarrell, director of the
National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Monroe County officials said they are happy with the
evacuation efforts that began earlier in the week. Officials
estimated that 75 percent of the Keys' residents have left, though
more have stayed behind in Key West.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, officials urged people to stay put and called all
rescue workers to duty. Deputies, police and medical staff planned
to continue answering calls until winds reach 50 mph. Virtually all
businesses were shut down and boarded up in the Upper Keys by
mid-afternoon Thurday.
</P>
<P>
   If the full force of the storm does cross the Keys, the first
job for emergency officials will be to clear the highway and search
for the injured. Though helicopters will likely be used to bring in
needed supplies, keeping the highway open is considered critical
for getting help to the islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to take care of people, and the only way to do that
is to keep the road open,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also fear that heavy rains and a surging surf will put
the highway underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe County officials have already asked the state to help
coordinate additional help from other counties after the storm
passes through.
</P>
<P>
   At the Big Coppitt Key volunteer fire station, where a hurricane
flag was hoisted for the first time, firefighters squeezed tankers
sent from Big Pine, Sugarloaf Key and Key West into the station's
bay. About two dozen firefighters and their families will ride out
the storm in the station, said Deputy Chief Scott Young.
</P>
<P>
   The Monroe County Sheriff's south substation on Stock Island
became a shelter to about 190 deputies. The building, constructed
in 1993, can withstand a category 5 storm, said deputy Jerome Fain.
Nearby, another 100 corrections officers shared the 585-bed jail
with about 600 inmates, some transferred from Marathon and
Plantation facilities, and Pooch, Lt. Manuel Cuervo's drug-sniffing
Pit Bulll terrier, Cuervo said. The jail can run on a generator if
power fails and has its own water treatment facility, Cuervo said.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 elderly from the Key West Convalescent Center also
moved into jail dormitories usually occupied by inmates. Another
200 from nursing homes around the Keys were also moved to the jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I elect to stay here?'' Mary Karhan pleaded with center
administrator Don Capoldo, as he hurried to board residents on
school buses for the move. ``I'm sick of moving, for God's sake,
all over a little storm.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Florida Keys Health Center, a volunteer crew of three
doctors and four nurses from the University of Florida Health
Science Center in Jacksonville arrived Wednesday evening to keep
the emergency room open, said Dr. David Seaberg. The team, trained
in emergency medicine and disaster management, decided to come
because so many residents decided to stay, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven ambulances will continue to answer emergency calls until
winds reach 45 mph, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, passengers boarded the last commercial flight from
Key West about 10 a.m. Gulfstream flew four last flights, with
about a dozen passengers on each, said spokesman Terry Deischer.
</P>
<P>
   Many fishermen gambled and left their lobster traps out in the
Gulf of Mexico, though many are likely to be lost in the storm.
Most didn't have time to pull them in, or feared they would be just
as damages when stacked up onshore.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Bruland has 2,500 traps _ worth about $18 a piece _
floating in the Gulf. He spent Thursday morning lashing his fishing
boat to seven other fishing boats at the docks of Keys Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a minimal storm, but we're going to ride it out,''
Bruland said. ``We're committed now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
