<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSH25-COX     09-24 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents are getting out of Georges' way
 &HT;    By Stephanie Desmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Alicia Medina is afraid, she'll tell
you that right off.
</P>
<P>
   The Kendall woman survived Hurricane Andrew. (Her house didn't.)
So under sunny skies on Thursday, she loaded up her husband, their
three children and the photos and videotapes they've collected
since 1992 and started heading north.
</P>
<P>
   She had no intention of sticking around for Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running away,'' she explained as the family stopped for
a bathroom break at the Lake Worth-West Palm Beach service plaza on
Florida's Turnpike. ``We don't know (where we're going). We're just
hearing the news as we go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Northbound traffic on the Turnpike and Interstate 95 was heavier
than usual Thursday as evacuees from Monroe, Miami-Dade and Broward
counties looked for what they considered safe places to ride out
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Some stopped in Palm Beach County, where many hotels had to say,
``Sorry, we're full.'' Hotels and motels on the Treasure Coast also
were pretty booked.
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy rates weren't available.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out by train became impossible Thursday because Amtrak
stopped running trains south of Orlando. CSX shut its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Tran officials said the last county buses would run
Thursday night, and a decision would be made today whether rides
will resume Saturday. School buses won't be seen today, either:
Classes have been canceled until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach International Airport continued normal operations
although a few flights were canceled, said spokeswoman Lisa Waters.
Fort Lauderdale/Hollywood International Airport closed for arriving
flights Thursday night. Miami International Airport was still open
Thursday night, but some delays were expected.
</P>
<P>
   Northbound boat traffic was heavier than usual early Thursday as
boaters looked for a safe place to tie down. By nightfall, however,
the Intracoastal Waterway was empty, said Officer Joseph Anderson
of the U.S. Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people were wise enough to get off the waters,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart marinas were nearly full Thursday, with many larger boats
from Broward, Miami-Dade and Monroe counties tying up at Martin
County docks.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of increased auto traffic, the Florida Highway
Patrol planned to put four times as many troopers on the interstate
today. Meanwhile, transportation workers were taking down
construction signs and barricades Thursday, meaning drivers should
be careful around unmarked construction sites.
</P>
<P>
   For much of Thursday, things were calmer in Palm Beach County
than expected because no local evacuations were ordered, said Manny
Papandreas, operations manager for Palm Beach County's emergency
operations center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably going right straight on through,'' he said of
the evacuees.
</P>
<P>
   And some people, he hoped, were listening to the advice he has
touted for years: You're probably safer at home. Stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Lenore Bernard, a retired couple from Kendall, tried
staying home for Andrew. The roof blew off of their house while
they huddled inside.
</P>
<P>
   They were headed to Fort Pierce Thursday and stopped for some
frozen yogurt at the service plaza. Richard likes Fort Pierce
because it's a good spot for a short getaway west or north, should
the storm shift. Lenore isn't sure anywhere is safe from Georges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everywhere,'' she said. ``There's no getting away from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jacki Garcia of Miami, Palm Beach was far enough. She
planned to get a hotel room on the island with her husband and
Lady, her Yorkshire Terrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more like a vacation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Pat Moore and Tim Pallesen contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
