<HEADER>
A3247 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALL-SEASON-A     09-24 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-SEASON-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL FANS, POLL SHOWS, ARE BACK, BACK, BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two-way home run race that fans don't want to end, the one
that has catapulted baseball to new heights of interest, enters its
last stage on Friday night. So does the three-way race for the
National League wild-card spot. But both races could be extended
beyond Sunday, the final day of the regular-season schedule,
creating an even more frantic finish to one of the most
scintillating seasons ever.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented home run contest between Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa has rocketed baseball back into the minds and hearts of
people who had abandoned it after the strike that shattered an
exciting 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   Results of The New York Times/CBS News poll showed on Thursday
that fans have followed this season with far greater interest than
at any time since the poll was first conducted in 1985.
Furthermore, Major League Baseball will set a total attendance
record with about 70.5 million fans seeing games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the Cardinals' game against the Montreal Expos on
Thursday night, McGwire and Sosa were tied with a record 65 home
runs, four more than any player had ever hit before in a major
league season. McGwire has three games left against the Expos while
Sosa and the Chicago Cubs play three times in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The games in Houston take on additional significance because the
Cubs are scrapping for the NL wild-card spot with the New York Mets
and the San Francisco Giants. The Mets and the Cubs are tied for
the lead, with the Giants a game behind following the completion on
Thursday of their sweep of a four-game series with Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   If the 162-game schedule is not enough to decide that spot in
the playoffs, the teams will play off for it Monday and, in the
event of a three-way tie, Tuesday. The Cubs, at most, would play
one such playoff game, meaning Sosa would have that extra game in
which to add to his home run total.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa and McGwire will not have a playoff if they end the season
tied. They would, in that event, go into the record book, replacing
Roger Maris and his 61, as a tandem. Both players have said they
would welcome such a development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a unique, really superb year in so many ways,''
Commissioner Bud Selig said on Thursday, ``topped off obviously by
the home run chase, not only the record-breaking part of it, but I
have to give Sosa and McGwire great credit. They not only broke
these records, but they've done it with such grace and dignity.
That, I think, is the thing that has captivated people.''
</P>
<P>
   The interest generated by the home run race was reflected in the
poll conducted Tuesday and Wednesday. Of the 960 adults who
participated, 22 percent said they were very interested in watching
or following Major League Baseball, up from 15 percent a year ago,
and 41 percent were somewhat interested, up from 27 percent.
Conversely, 38 percent said they were not at all interested, down
from 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll marked the first time since the question was first
asked in 1985 that the ``interested'' number exceeded 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   News media coverage of McGwire and Sosa has been intense and
widespread. Sosa has helped create that coverage by sticking close
to McGwire, who had been the hitter given the best chance to break
the record, which he did Sept. 8. Sosa has led only once (48-47),
and that briefly during a game between their teams Aug. 19, but
each time McGwire has pulled away, the Dominican hero has caught
up.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the first game between the Cubs and the Astros on Friday
night, Sosa will face Jose Lima, against whom he hit a pair of home
runs on Aug. 23. But the Cubs' pitchers will have to be wary of
Moises Alou and Craig Biggio, each of whom has hit five home runs
against the Cubs this season. The Astros have won five of the eight
games, with Lima winning twice in two starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who are at home to the Mets for three games this
weekend, have beaten New York six times in nine games, though the
Mets won three of four in the most recent series earlier this
month. Bruce Chen, a rookie, will start against the Mets on Friday
night, but then they will see Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   The game against Maddux will be interesting for more than the
obvious reason. The league's perennial No. 1 pitcher has struggled
recently, winning none of his last five starts (he has lost three,
the Braves all five) and compiling a wildly uncharacteristic 5.45
earned run average in his last six starts, a stretch that includes
one game in which he allowed no runs in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants play their final series in Colorado, where they lost
all three games of a three-game series immediately after the
all-star break. The Giants also lost two of three games the teams
played in San Francisco two weeks ago. The Rockies have won six of
nine games overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and the Astros are in an interesting position. They
would like to sweep their series this weekend to knock the team in
their division out of the wild-card spot. If they succeed, they
would play the wild-card team in the playoffs, presumably giving
them a more advantageous matchup.
</P>
<P>
   The season has managed to sustain a high level of interest in
spite of the absence of legitimate races for the division
championships. The Braves, the Astros, the San Diego Padres, the
Yankees and the Cleveland Indians breezed to their first-place
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Only the AL West produced a race, and that one emerged more from
the weaknesses of Texas and Anaheim than their strengths. The
Rangers, on the verge of clinching, took command by beating the
Angels five times in five games in an eight-day span.
</P>
<P>
   Other matters are to be decided this weekend. The final games
will determine the pairings and homefield advantages for the
playoffs. Right now only the Yankees are assured of homefield
advantage for the first two series. The Yankees, however, will be
trying to set an American League record for victories, eclipsing
the 111 games the Indians won in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Thursday's schedule, major league attendance for the
season was 68,795,359. The record is the 1993 attendance of
70,256,459. This season's attendance, of course, is aided by the
addition of Arizona and Tampa Bay. The per-game average of 29,287,
up 3.6 percent from last season and 15.9 percent from the
post-strike 1995 season, is the third highest in major league
history. The record, set in 1994, is 31,612.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
