<HEADER>
A3250 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-MONEY-     09-24 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-MONEY-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SCANDAL SPURS SHARP INCREASE IN CAMPAIGN CONTRIBUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-PRESS,
CLINTON-ASSESS.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The scandal involving President Clinton and a
former White House intern has spurred a sharp increase in
Republican campaign contributions for the November elections, a
senior party official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Mitchler, finance director of the National Republican
Senate Committee, said about $12 million, or a third of the $35
million the committee has raised for Senate candidates this year,
has come in the last two months, a period that includes Clinton's
televised apology, his taped testimony before the grand jury and
negotiations over impeachment hearings. Usually, Mitchler said,
about $6 million in contributed in a two-month period.
</P>
<P>
   ``People out there now have evidence of what they have believed
all along,'' Mitchler said, offering an explanation for the
increase and, perhaps, why Republican lawmakers prefer dragging out
an impeachment process. ``I just wish I have Bill Clinton in office
a few more months.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Crawford, a spokeswoman for the National Republican
Congressional Committee, which raises money for House races, said
contributions to her committee also began to increase after
Clinton's apology, which he made on Aug. 17, the same day he
testified before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   She said she could not provide specific numbers for how much
money the committee has raised this year, compared, for example,
with 1994. But she said one difference had been among grass-roots
supporters, who are now giving more, and that the committee's
``telephone prospecting'' in the days after the apology generated a
20 percent increase in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crawford cautioned that donations to the committee typically
increase after Labor Day. ``But we are doing better over all,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic fund-raising efforts, too, have been helped by the
scandal, according to Democratic party leaders. Melissa Boney
Ratcliff, the party spokeswoman, said a telemarketing campaign that
began two days after Clinton's apology generated a 15 percent
increase in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take that to mean that Democrats wanted to help the party
and the president as soon as possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchler said the recent flurry of check writing for Senate
campaigns was highly unusual for exceeding the traditional monthly
donations of $3 million to $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinary when it gets to $4 million, $4.5 million,
even $6 million, which is what we've been doing in the last two
months,'' he said, adding that about a third of the totals had come
from major donors and the rest from people who contributed as
little as $10.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This year, the committee plans to spread the donations among 34
Senate races, with larger amounts funneled into states where the
campaigns are perceived as close. Both parties generally agree that
they include six races where Democrats have held the seat _
California, Kentucky, Illinois, Nevada, South Carolina and
Wisconsin _ and two where Republicans reign _ New York and North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for both parties in that Republicans need a
net gain of five seats for a filibuster-proof majority. But an
additional enticement for Republican donors is the possibility,
unlikely as it might be, of reaching 67 seats _ the two-thirds
majority needed for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Republican state party leaders say they have
noticed a swirl of activity in recent months, with a rising number
of contributions and volunteer efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend started in mid-August,'' said Mike Madrid, the
political director for the California Republican Party. ``After the
apology, the floor fell out for this guy. We began getting 250
calls a day, people telling us whatever we do, get rid of him.
We've even gotten checks from Democrats in the Bay Area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For us,'' Madrid added, ``Bill Clinton has been the motivator
in chief.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be especially beneficial to Matt Fong, the state
treasurer, who is locked in a political brawl with Sen. Barbara
Boxer, a Democrat seeking her second term.
</P>
<P>
   But not everywhere is Clinton the driving motivation for
Republican donations. Brad Goodrich, deputy executive director of
the Illinois Republican Party, said problems surrounding Sen. Carol
Moseley-Braun, stemming from questions about her finances and a
trip to Nigeria in which she seemed to express support for a
dictator, have served as a much stronger magnet for fund-raising
efforts than those engulfing the president.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking a second term, she is facing Peter Fitzgerald, a
Republican state legislator, in a race that is regarded as a
tossup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tag all our stuff to her,'' Goodrich said. ''When we
include her name in mailings and telemarketing, we go off the
charts. We tie her to everything we can; we never even mention
Clinton. We don't have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
