u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLST-BAILOUT-BOS &LR;      09-24 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLST-BAILOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT BAILOUT BY FED POINTS UP PERILOUS TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The financial world has grown too frantic and
fragile.
</P>
<P>
   That, in the end, was the worry that drove Federal Reserve
officials to orchestrate Wednesday night's extraordinary rescue of
Long-Term Capital Management L.P., a group of high-powered
speculators who in any other era would have been allowed to fall
flat on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   That is the worry that's likely to convince the central bank to
reduce interest rates next week at a time when, by many
conventional economic measures, the nation does not need a rate
cut.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the worry that's provoking a crisis of confidence in
the optimistic notions about market economies and the free flow of
capital that have dominated the world since the fall of the Berlin
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of money out there moving very fast that could
do a lot of damage,'' said Harvard economist Jeffrey Sachs. `That's
why people are starting to talk about the need for tripwires and
safeguards.''
</P>
<P>
   The global financial upheaval ``has people thinking a lot harder
than they have about their previous belief that totally unfettered,
rapid and large capital movements are always beneficial,'' said
former Fed vice chairman Alan Blinder.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, September has offered a remarkable tableaux of
policymakers struggling -- thus far with only minimal success -- to
come to grips with what has gone wrong with global financial
markets. Although Asian economies had already crumbled and Russia
had partially defaulted on billions of dollars of debt by the
beginning of the month, nobody had expected these troubles to jump
continents to Latin America and pose the first real threat to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan announced that US
economy could no longer remain ``an oasis of prosperity'' in a
world of turmoil, and disclosed that the central bank was now as
worried about a turmoil-induced recession as it was about its
traditional concern over inflation. A politically embattled
President Clinton declared that the world faced ``the worst
financial crisis in half a century.'' And bankers and policymakers
began hammering out another in a long line of rescue packages for a
financially troubled country, this time Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the events of this week -- especially the surprising
rescue of Long-Term Capital -- may be the most revealing about the
dimensions of the world's financial problems and the depth of
policymakers' worries.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for most people to grasp how unusual it is for
the Fed to arrange a takeover such as it did of the Greenwich,
Conn.-based investment group, or even to understand what business
the firm was in.
</P>
<P>
   While the government regularly steps in when banks are in
trouble and depositors' funds are at risk, it usually avoids
bailing out other kinds of businesses even when their demise could
cause disruptions. It did nothing, for example, to stop the 1990
collapse of junk-bond king Michael Milken and his firm, Drexel
Burnham Lambert Group.
</P>
<P>
   Such a hands-off approach is virtually always the rule when the
investors involved are rich, sophisticated and knew what they were
getting into. And at least until recently, there was almost nobody
in the financial world who fit that bill better than the partners
and investors of Long-Term Capital.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's roster includes Harvard Business School economist and
Nobel Prize winner Robert H. Merton, Stanford finance professor and
Nobel Prize winner Myron S. Scholes, former Fed vice chairman David
Mullins and legendary bond trader John W. Meriwether.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and financial market experts said that the New York
Fed threw aside its usual practices and stepped in to help after
concluding that Long-Term Capital had made such huge and dazzlingly
complex investments that no one could be sure what would happen if
the firm collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Fed officials ``had to be asking themselves if this thing falls,
what does it do to people's perception of other institutions?''
said Harvard economist Robert Z. Lawrence. ``If this thing falls,
are people going to panic?''
</P>
<P>
   The danger of panic was heightened beyond anything that a more
conventional financial firm's fall might produce for two reasons:
First, Long-Term Capital borrowed fantastic amounts of money and
put most of it into complex instruments called derivatives that
allow investors to control huge financial positions for relatively
low cost. So the ripple effects of its collapse would have been
outsized.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it made most of its investments in overseas markets that
policymakers now worry are too fragile to survive the giant
outflows that the firm's demise would cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cared to notice it, but the basic fact is that most of
these markets aren't mature enough to cope with the reprocussions''
from the sort of investment that Long-Term Capital was doing, said
Roger M. Kubarych, a former senior Fed official and now a partner
with Kaufman &AMP; Kubarych in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Policymakers are now scrambling to cope with their belated
discovery of the weakness of many foreign markets. Most
immediately, they are likely to cut interest rates to ensure that
the US continues growing and importing, which helps troubled
overseas economies. But long-term, they are studying proposals that
would have been anethema at the height of the free market years of
the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   `I suspect at the end of the day, they will end up with some
kind of institutional changes that control capital flows in and out
of emerging markets,'' said Blinder, the former Fed offical.
Nothing could have been further from policymakers' minds - or those
of Long-Term Capital partners -- even a few months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
