<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-BINLADEN-600&AMP;add     09-24 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-BINLADEN-600&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COORDINATING WORLD EFFORTS TO DEFUSE BIN LADEN TERRORIST
NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JAMES RISEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States is coordinating an effort with
European and African nations to roll up the terrorist networks of
Osama bin Laden, the suspected mastermind of the bombings of two
American Embassies in East Africa, as fears mount that he will
strike again, officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   American intelligence and law-enforcement agencies are working
with their counterparts in countries including Britain and Germany
to help arrange for the arrests of as many suspected operatives of
bin Laden's groups as possible, whether or not they can be directly
linked to the embassy bombings, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Bureau of Investigation is leading the investigation
into the bombings on Aug. 7 in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam,
Tanzania. The Central Intelligence Agency, the FBI and other
agencies are giving information and expertise to help other nations
arrest suspected accomplices of bin Laden who can held on other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA, the FBI and the Justice Department were conducting
detailed investigations of bin Laden and his operatives long before
the embassy bombings. The United States accelerated its efforts
after the bombings and aggressively sought the support of other
nations to break up his network.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said they had assisted in arresting 18 people
in Uganda, 7 people suspected of being connected to bin Laden in
London and at least 1 person in Germany suspected of links to the
embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The security minister of Uganda told reporters Thursday that the
FBI had helped in the arrests of a group there connected to bin
Laden. U.S. officials confirmed that they had helped Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   An antiterrorist raid by British authorities on Wednesday in
London led to the arrests of seven men who were described as having
links to bin Laden's organization, although there were no
indications that they were tied to the African bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, one suspect, Mamdouh Mahmoud Salim, who is though to
have close ties to bin Laden, was arrested near Munich in
connection with the bombings and is awaiting extradition to the
United States. He arrived in Munich from Sudan, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether those arrested in some of the other
countries would also face charged in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden once lived in Sudan, and United States officials say
they think that he still has close ties to the Sudanese government.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrests are in addition to suspects who are held in the
United States or have been charged here in connection with the
bombings. Those in custody in New York include Mohamed Rashed Daoud
al-Owhali and Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, who were flown last month from
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Also in custody in New York is Wadih el Hage of Arlington, Texas
el Hage pleaded not guilty Thursday in federal district court in
Manhattan to 11 counts of lying in connection with the bin Laden
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Another suspect being held in New York under a sealed indictment
has not been publicly identified by U.S. authorities. In addition,
a federal warrant has been issued for Haroun Fazil, a suspect in
the bombings who was living in the Comoro Islands and who is at
large.
</P>
<P>
   Before the embassy bombings a federal grand jury in New York had
handed up a sealed criminal indictment that charged bin Laden in
connection with terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration timed its cruise missile strike into
bin Laden's terrorist camp near Khost, Afghanistan, for Aug. 20, a
day when they knew that he had scheduled a conference of his
network's leaders, to debilitate the organization. But, U.S.
officials said, bin Laden left the camp before the attack.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The U.S. campaign against the bin Laden network comes at a time
when United States counter-terrorism experts and other officials
believe bin Laden is planning new terrorist acts against American
interests, possibly in retaliation for the cruise missile strikes
against his camp and against a suspected chemical weapons facility
in the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has not made any public pronouncements since the
cruise missile strike, but he is still believed to be in
Afghanistan, and U.S. officials say they believe the question is
not whether bin Laden will strike again, but when.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of U.S. officials to move so quickly to take down
the bin Laden network stems from the fact that the United States
was already in the midst of a long-term investigation of the Saudi
exile and his operations before the bombings, officials said. bin
Laden has been the focus of attention at the CIA's
counter-terrorism center for several years, and he has been
identified by name in a presidential finding authorizing covert
action to combat international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The federal indictment of el Hage states that in 1996, the
United States Attorney in New York and the FBI began a grand jury
investigation into bin Laden and al-Qaeda, his international
organization. By September 1997, it focused more tightly on the
structure and operations of his terrorist network. That long-term
investigation, apparently aided by cooperating witnesses, has
clearly enabled the United States to help other countries identify
and arrest bin Laden associates around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing this before, but it received a new emphasis
after the embassy bombings,'' said one U.S. official. ``Now, we've
accelerated our efforts, and gotten more countries involved. We are
rolling up terrorists related to bin Laden, but we are also getting
terrorists who may not be related to him but who get caught up in
the net as well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
