<HEADER>
A3259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDGEFUND-RISK-550&AMP;AD     09-24 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-RISK-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL HEDGE FUNDS HAVE SUFFERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT, HEDGEFUND-TEAM, MARKET)  
(lh) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not all hedge funds have suffered the losses of
Long-Term Capital Management, which is accepting a cash infusion of
$3.4 billion just to stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Tonga Partners, a six-year-old fund run from San Francisco, said
that it was up about 14 percent so far this year, including a loss
of 2.5 percent this month and a gain of 8.7 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   A group of hedge funds that bet American stock prices will fall
_ known as ``short funds'' _ are actually raking in the profits.
The Optima Short Fund, for example, rose 21.9 percent for the year
through August.
</P>
<P>
   And George Soros' largest fund, the Quantum Fund, with roughly
$10 billion under management, is up 9.6 percent for the year
through Monday, a Soros Fund Management spokesman said. In
mid-August, the fund was up 19 percent. The Quantum group of funds,
with $20 billion, are all registered outside the country and are
not open to United States investors. The performance of individual
funds ranges from a loss of 22 percent for Quantum's $1.7 billion
Emerging Growth Fund to a 4.5 percent gain for the $1.3 billion
Quasar Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Long-Term Capital's mammoth losses of up to 90 cents on
the dollar have prompted widespread industry concerns about
possible calls for new regulation, investor redemptions, and
tightening credit lines that would make it harder for these funds
to operate.
</P>
<P>
   Managers of hedge funds _ investment vehicles for wealthy
individuals that are now largely unregulated _ fear the entire
industry will be tainted by Long-Term Capital's stunning decline.
Several managers said they had received calls over the last few
days from concerned investors. Some others have taken the unusual
step of sending out notices to reassure investors. Hedge funds
operate under a great deal of secrecy and normally report their
performance no more than quarterly. Blackstone Asset Management,
which oversees $1.5 billion, issued a statement that said its hedge
fund performance was flat to positive for the year through August.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry experts expect withdrawals despite managers'
efforts to calm jittery investors. Lois Peltz, a a managing editor
at Managed Account Report, a hedge fund tracking service, foresees
withdrawals at the end of the third quarter as well at the end of
the year. The panic may come in waves since many hedge funds allow
withdrawals only quarterly or annually. But she sees this as a
temporary setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a shake-out, and it will ultimately get rid of a lot of
hedge funds that were not truly hedged funds,'' Ms. Peltz said.
``And there may be a lot of pressure on funds to make their overall
strategy and specific investments clearer.''
</P>
<P>
   A fund manager countered that hedge funds are notoriously
volatile and their returns could recover in the last few months of
the year, making any forecasts about withdrawals tricky.
</P>
<P>
   Credit too may become an increasing problem. Nicola Meaden,
chief executive officer of TASS, a hedge fund tracking service
based in London, said Thursday: ``Hedge funds do business with
their brokers. Over the last four years, brokers have been willing
to lend to hedge funds. Right now liquidity is very tight, so that
makes operating difficult. We don't think it will get better
quickly.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As to regulation, at least four fund managers said privately
Thursday that they believed some regulation was likely if for no
other reason than that regulators tend to respond to highly
publicized problems by instituting tighter controls. Some members
of Congress called for hearings on the matter Thursday, though the
administration played down any concerns about systemic problems
related to hedge funds and their often complex investments.
</P>
<P>
   One reason it is difficult to generalize about hedge funds is
that they have myriad investing styles, some conservative, some
highly speculative.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals generally have to show a significant net worth to
invest in hedge funds and, until recently, hedge funds have been
able to accept no more than 99 limited partners, though those rules
have been relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mutual funds, hedge funds are not required to report
their holdings or to invest in securities that have a ready market
or to adhere to any particular investing style. And stock mutual
funds generally make a straightforward bet that certain stock
prices will rise. But hedge funds frequently hedge their positions
by betting that the price of a certain security, say a stock, will
go up, while betting that some other security, perhaps another
stock, will fall. The theory behind hedge funds is that a money
manager's performance is heavily tied to the overall performance of
a specific market, but a hedge fund manager could do well even in a
down market.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds come in many types, but they can bet on everything
from currencies to stocks to bonds to exotic securities for which
there may not be a ready market. They can also leverage _ or borrow
_ to make far heavier bets than mutual funds can.
</P>
<P>
   A number of hedge fund managers went to lengths Thursday to
point out that Long-Term Capital was not representative of the
industry in strategy or risk level.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital was highly leveraged and was able to borrow
extensively to make bets in part because it was using the money in
the bond market, widely perceived as less risky than, say, the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are higher in the capital structure,'' said one money
manager who insisted on anonymity, ``and therefore banks will lend
you more money on fixed income.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current hedge fund woes, the manager said there had
been other spectacular hedge fund losses in the past without
destroying the business. ``People need yield,'' he said, ``and I
think that risk-taking will increase.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
