<SLUG> BC-PROTESTER-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
300 MOURN DEATH OF PROTESTER KILLED BY FELLED TREE IN CALIFORNIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By BILL DAWSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ More than 300 people came together Thursday in nearby
Pasadena to mourn, remember and praise David N. Chain, who grew up
in East Texas but died last week in the towering redwood forests of
Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Chain, 24, affiliated with the Earth First! group, was
participating in what fellow activists have said was an
anti-logging action intended to monitor and delay timber harvesting
by Pacific Lumber Co., a subsidiary of Houston-based Maxxam. A
tree, felled by a logger, struck and killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena is an industrial city of 130,000 about 10 miles
southeast of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The group that assembled at Grand View Funeral Home preceding
Chain's burial in an adjoining cemetery was too large for the
chapel and spilled out into a lobby. The mourners represented all
phases of Chain's life _ his childhood in Pasadena, his young
adulthood in Austin, Texas, and his environmental activism in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Chain's journey to California earlier this month, which ended
with his death Sept. 17 near the city of Eureka, was his second
experience with environmental activism there.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Martin, who knew Chain since they were
second-graders and lived with him in Austin, told mourners that he
was ``the happiest I've ever seen him last year when he came back
from the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he realized then that Chain ``had found something to
strive for, bigger than himself, for the benefit of all.''
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Steinberg, a student rabbi who lives in the forest near
the place where Chain died, said he was trying to protect a forest
around a salmon-spawning stream called Grizzly Creek, which has
been clogged with mud from erosion caused by nearby logging in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brave young man understood what so many of us have failed
to grasp _ that the delicate balance of nature is more important
than the balance of the corporate balance sheet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber announced there would be no logging operations at
the site where Chain died on the day of his funeral. Since his
death, the company has appealed to Earth First! members to stop
coming onto company land.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy has arisen over the circumstances of Chain's death,
the first in over a decade of environmental protests on Pacific
Lumber property. The company has said the logger who felled the
tree that killed Chain was unaware that activists were in his area,
but activists who accompanied Chain dispute that claim. Law
enforcement authorities have tentatively termed the death an
apparent accident pending further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his remarks at the funeral, Martin expressed
confidence that his friend's commitment to his cause would
``continue to influence people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
