<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-POVERTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF POOR IN BAY STATE RISING: CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ZACHARY R. DOWDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At a time when Massachusetts unemployment has reached
historic lows and the state's economy is booming, US census figures
released Thursday show an increasing number of people are poor.
</P>
<P>
   According to the figures, the percentage of people living below
the poverty line in Massachusetts was higher last year than in
1996, a change that bucks a decline nationwide in the poverty
figure.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, family income has been stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We can say with real confidence that this shows a
surprising trend towards higher poverty even during the growing
economy,'' said James St. George, executive director of the
education fund at the Tax Equity Alliance of Massachusetts, a
liberal advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   St. George and other specialists were at a loss to explain the
poverty increase.
</P>
<P>
   Census projections indicate that last year 12.2 percent of the
state's residents, or 734,000 people, were living below the poverty
line, which for a family of four was defined as earning $16,400 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the poverty figure was 10.1 percent, while it was 11
percent in 1995 and 9.7 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers come from the Census Bureau's annual Current
Population Survey, a study of 52,000 people conducted in March.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 13.3 percent of all Americans or 35.6 million people
lived in poverty last year, down from 13.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The sobering Massachusetts numbers come as the state basks in
healthy economic indicators, including 3 percent unemployment and
substantial growth.
</P>
<P>
   What has remained hidden amid the news of prosperity, however,
is a growing number of families who struggle daily to make ends
meet, St. George and others said. .
</P>
<P>
   St. George said the size of the sampling in the study and the
small increase from year to year prevents statisticians from saying
the rise last year was ``statistically significant.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the evidence of a general rise in poverty is still
compelling since the percentage of people who are poor in
Massachussetts has increased in two of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the survey showed, median income of Bay State families
has not caught up to its pre-recession levels. Though it rose from
$40,400 in 1996 to $42,023 last year, it remained nearly $4,700
below the 1989 median income.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the median household income for all Americans rose
1.9 percent to $37,005, a change that was not statistically
different from the peak in 1989 &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The figures jibe with a study released this week by the Women's
Educational and Industrial Union, which found that families
hovering just above the poverty line are in critical need.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes an income much higher than the poverty level to make
ends meet,'' said Laura Russell, director of the Work and Family
Resource Center at the women's union.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, entitled ``The Self-Sufficiency Standard
for Massachusetts,'' a ``subsistence-wage'' level for a family of
four with two children in the state is $42,564.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the findings, state officials say fewer people are
living on public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Maio, deputy director of the state Department of
Transitional Assistance said the number of families on state
welfare rolls has been plummeting, from 84,130 families in June
1996 to 63,501 last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
