<HEADLINE>
FRANK HITS CLINTON SUDAN BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Representative Barney Frank, one of President
Clinton's staunchest supporters, broke with the administration
Thursday to criticize last month's bombing of a chemical plant in
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Democrat, who initially supported the bombing
in retaliation for attacks by Islamic extremists on two US
embassies, said new information about the al-Shifa pharmaceutical
factory indicated that it should not have been targeted.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement Thursday follows growing skepticism among US
allies that the plant produced chemical weapons components, as the
Clinton administration has maintained. Foreign officials note that
the plant produced legitimate pharmaceuticals and even had a UN
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, in a letter to Clinton, said that before any US attack,
``there ought to be a degree of certainty or fear of imminent
danger, which in neither case seem to be present regarding Sudan.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said he still believed the simultaneous bombing of
terrorist training camps in Afghanistan was justified on Aug. 20
because those sites have been tied to outlaw Osama bin Laden,
suspected in the bombings of the US embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter has demanded an independent
investigation to see whether the factory actually produced
materials for chemical weapons. The Clinton administration has
rejected such an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Frank said he weighed the increasingly
skeptical accounts about activities at the site before changing his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attacking an installation in another country may be justified,
but you've got to be very, very sure about the threats before
launching the attack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to have self-defense capability, but if you
overuse it, you lose it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
