<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT-A     09-24 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEONS IN FRANCE TRY HAND TRANSPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on the transplant operation is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surgeons in France announced Thursday that they had attached the
right hand and forearm of an anonymous donor to the arm of a
48-year-old Australian man whose own hand was amputated after a
logging accident in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was not the first such transplant attempt; at least one
previous attempt, in Ecuador in 1964, ended in failure after two
weeks when the donor hand was rejected by the body.
</P>
<P>
   Although no such transplant is believed to have ever been
successful, the team in France said advances in drugs and
microsurgery since the attempt in Ecuador gave the procedure a 50
percent chance of turning out well.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors offered few details about their procedure, which was
performed at Edouard Herriot Hospital in Lyons. Officials of the
hospital said they would disclose more information later.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, it will be some time before they can say the
operation is a success. If the grafted hand takes, weeks must pass
before doctors can tell how well it functions, and 12 to 18 months
of physical and other therapy will be required to gain full use of
it, if that is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Failure of nerves to regenerate sufficiently to allow perception
of hot, cold and other sensations, and to control movement, would
leave the grafted hand a useless body part.
</P>
<P>
   And the procedure is not without risk to the recipient, Clint
Hallam, an Australian businessman. He must take anti-rejection
drugs that suppress the immune system, leaving him vulnerable to
infection, disease and perhaps serious reactions to the drugs
themselves, which must be taken indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the optimism voiced in France found support in a
team of experts at the University of Louisville in Kentucky, who
said they were about to embark on similar surgery at Jewish
Hospital in Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Barker, a plastic surgeon in charge of the research for
the Louisville project, said in an interview Thursday that his team
had selected several patients from among 100 applicants to undergo
a hand transplant later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Barker expressed confidence that his team's efforts would
succeed, because advances in transplantation in recent years have
been so dramatic. But he said the rejection of transplanted skin
posed a particular risk to the success of the procedure and had
been the limiting factor in earlier attempts and research.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery in Lyons was performed on Wednesday and lasted more
than 13 hours, said the team of doctors there, headed by Dr.
Jean-Michel Dubernard.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors attached ``all the arteries, veins, nerves, tendons,
muscles and skin after setting the two bones of the forearm,'' the
hospital said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to French television, Dubernard said the procedure
``gives hope to all those who are victims of domestic or work
accidents, antipersonnel mines, or have congenital deformations.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgical team was made up of doctors from France, Australia,
England and Italy. Dubernard led the team with Dr. Earl Owen,
director of the Center for Microsurgery in Sydney, Australia; Dr.
Marco Lanzetta of the University of Milan; Dr. Hari Kapila of
Sydney, and Dr. Nadey Hakim of Saint Mary's Hospital in London.
</P>
<P>
   The donor was a brain-dead patient, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Barker, of the Louisville team, said he was surprised to learn
about the operation in Lyons. He said his team ``never heard of
this group'' that performed the procedure. The idea of such a
transplant was previously discussed at international scientific
meetings, he said, but he does not recall that members of the
French group participated.
</P>
<P>
   Barker said he was particularly surprised to learn that Hallam
was the patient, because he had also applied to be treated in
Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   In work with rabbits and pigs over the last three years, the
Louisville team has conducted extensive research on new approaches
to anti-rejection therapy. The findings have been presented at
meetings and published in scientific journals.
</P>
<P>
   If hand transplants work, the team hopes ultimately to use the
immunologic techniques to transplant jaws, tongues and other
tissues that cannot be repaired well among patients with cancer and
other diseases, Barker said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William P. Cooney, a hand surgeon at the Mayo Clinic and
president-elect of the American Society for Surgery of the Hand,
said that technical and ethical questions about hand transplants
were debated in May at an international scientific meeting in
Vancouver, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisville team discussed its ideas there but at the time
had not received permission to do such surgery. Barker said
Thursday, however, that an ethics committee had since given its
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The main ethical objection was that hand transplants pose
substantial risks to the health and even life of a recipient and
that, unlike heart transplants, they are not life-sustaining.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents said a functioning hand could be superior to a
prosthesis.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing from rabbits to pigs in its research, the Louisville
team has developed an anti-rejection regimen based on the drug
FK-506, which is also known by the generic name tacrolimus and by
its trade name, Prograf.
</P>
<P>
   The team has created flaps resembling a hand and composed of all
elements of transplanted tissue, like bone, tendons, nerves,
arteries and veins.
</P>
<P>
   The research has involved using skin creams and pumps so that
large amounts of anti-rejection drugs can be delivered directly to
the anatomic site of the transplant rather than circulating
throughout the body. This reduces chances of damage to other
tissues and organs.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, the Louisville team publicized its intention
to transplant a hand, so as to alert possible recipients and
would-be donors, Barker said.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatrists and other specialists on the team screen the
applicants, who must be using a prosthetic hand _ a way of making
sure they know the alternative. If a graft is rejected by the body,
the recipient can then use a prosthesis again, much they way a
person who rejects a kidney can resume dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants are asked to evaluate cosmetic factors that would be
important in the graft they receive, including skin color and
amount of hair. The doctors measure the bone size to avoid
mismatches, and test blood type and other immunologic factors.
</P>
<P>
   Barker said that for ethical reasons, the team would prefer to
do two transplants in a patient who has no use of either hand. For
such a patient, the benefits of success would clearly outweigh the
risks, he said. The risk calculation is less clear in a patient
with only one damaged hand.
</P>
<P>
   Performing the transplant on an elective basis should improve
chances of success, Barker said, because the donor hand would be
removed and grafted quickly, reducing the amount of time the tissue
lacked oxygen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
