<HEADER>
A3278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN25-COX     09-24 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Serious series for Mets, Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Bobby Cox usually flips the keys to the ranch to the
Greenville Braves at this time of the year; the clubhouse hearts
game draws more attention than the NL scoreboard; and Atlanta
wonders where to scrounge for playoffs tickets. But not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves open the season's final weekend against the New York
Mets with the opportunity to influence which opponent they face in
next week's League Division Series, hardly insignificant in this
era of the three-tiered playoffs. With one more victory, the Braves
clinch home-field advantage for the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, with the Mets and Chicago tied for the wild-card
slot _ and San Francisco 1 1/2 games behind _ the Braves reduce the
Mets' postseason chances each time they beat them this weekend,
thus improving the odds that Atlanta would face the Cubs instead of
San Diego in the division series.
</P>
<P>
   To suggest the Braves have been anything less than serious about
the standings since clinching the division 11 days ago doesn't
wash. Both Andres Galarraga and Chipper Jones, the club's RBI
leaders, have been in the lineup six times in eight days, and while
Javy Lopez skipped half the games to rest a sore left elbow, Andruw
Jones has sat down only once. Cox, the Braves' manager, doesn't
want to hear this stuff about easing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never take a deep breath,'' Cox said. ``It doesn't matter
who we play. We play hard every time, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one player trying to get that across is rookie call-up
Marty Malloy, who is one hamstring twinge away from making the
postseason roster. With second baseman Keith Lockhart testing his
right hamstring in the field for the first time in two weeks
against the Mets, Malloy is the option if Lockhart goes down.
Lockhart, who will start tonight, has reported improvement in
recent days, but one misstep would give Malloy significant playing
time and a spot on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken (Malloy) to Mark Lemke,'' Chipper Jones said. ``He's
not going to pop your eyes out with anything he does. But he does
everything (well).''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here three weeks now, and I just treat each day as a
new day and do the best I can,'' said Malloy, who is batting just
.185 but has struck out only twice in 27 at-bats. ``Hopefully,
that'll show that, if it came down to me getting an opportunity,
they'd believe I can get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
