<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klesko heeds advice, tries new stance
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- While most of the team went after the postgame spread
the other night in Miami, Ryan Klesko was headed for the batting
cage. The game had not been over for 10 minutes before the Braves
left-fielder was taking batting practice again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a fairly new stance and I'm trying to get as comfortable
as I can,'' he said. ``After the game is when everything is
freshest in your mind. I'd just missed a couple balls and it's been
a while since I hit one good. I've been swinging under the ball.
I've got to get on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves could use it. The team has set a franchise home run
record with limited participation from Klesko, who led the team in
home runs in the last two seasons. He enters the Mets series with
18 home runs, the fewest he has hit since 17 his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   While Klesko does not use his appendectomy as an excuse, his
season has not been the same since June 29th, when he had surgery.
In his first 73 games, Klesko had 13 homers and 47 RBIs while
hitting .281, a remarkable comeback from a 6-for-34 start in April.
In 53 games since the operation, he has hit .257 with five homers
and 22 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   In the postseason, where every shortcoming is magnified, this
will not do. Klesko entered the season having averaged one homer
every 16 at-bats. That rate has slipped to every 23.3 at-bats. Part
of the club's solution was to reduce his swing a few weeks ago,
restore his stance to squared with the plate and let him stride
straight at the pitcher. Leyland's take
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland is familiar enough with the Braves bullpen history
to have his own take on Kerry Ligtenberg and what has transpired
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done well under difficult circumstances,'' Leyland said.
``I've been impressed with the way he's handled it. When you're
saving games for the Atlanta Braves, not only do you have the
pressure of saving the game but you have the added pressure of
saving it for a Cy Young winner every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Since blowing back-to-back save opportunities Aug. 28 and 31,
Ligtenberg has strung together eight scoreless appearances with six
strikeouts and three hits allowed in 7 2/3 innings this month.
</P>
<P>
   `Maury' Perez
</P>
<P>
   He left behind the base someone placed in his locker in Miami
but back-up catcher Eddie Perez still is having trouble living down
the first stolen base of his career, achieved against Florida's
Greg Zaun Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the president of Venezuela called,'' Perez announced.
</P>
<P>
   Really?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, no. It was really my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood is slated to make a relief appearance in Sunday's
game. That will comprise his second appearance out of the bullpen
this season, all the acclimation he will get before full-time
relief duty in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
