<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: New York Mets
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Today 7:40 p.m., Saturday 1:15 p.m. and Sunday 1:10 p.m..
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Radio/TV: TBS will televise tonight. WAGA-5 will televise
Saturday, and Fox Sports South will televise Sunday. 750-AM will
broadcast all three games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, RHP Rick Reed (16-10, 3.99
ERA; 2-1, 1.86 lifetime vs. Braves) vs. LHP Bruce Chen (2-0, 3.31;
0-0, 12.00 lifetime vs. Mets). Saturday, LHP Al Leiter (17-5, 2.40;
3-2, 1.86 lifetime vs. Braves) vs. Tom Glavine (20-6, 2.53; 10-5,
3.26 lifetime vs. Mets). Sunday, RHP Armando Reynoso (7-2, 3.24;
0-6, 6.37 lifetime vs. Braves) vs. RHP Greg Maddux (17-9, 2.24;
21-12, 3.47 time vs. Mets).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Atlanta trails the all-time series 200-204, but
is 20-11 against New York at home since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves are 6-3 vs. the Mets this season, but
lost three of four at Shea Stadium Sept. 4-7, when Rudy Seanez and
John Rocker each blew a save and lost a game on late home runs.
Atlanta won the first five games of the season series, and the
Mets' last visit to Turner Field ended in a near riot on July 5
after Michael Tucker scored in an 11th-inning collision with Mike
Piazza at the plate. Plate umpire Angel Hernandez was chased off
the field by Mets manager Bobby Valentine and losing pitcher John
Franco.
</P>
<P>
   Mets leaders: Avg. _ John Olerud (.351); HR _ Mike Piazza (32);
RBI _ Piazza (110); SB _ Brian McRae (20). W _ Al Leiter (17); ERA
_ Dennis Cook (2.15). Saves _ John Franco (38). Strikeouts _ Leiter
(168).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Mets had no luck against the bottom of the
division, going 2-3 in their final homestand against Florida and
Montreal. If New York fails to reach the playoffs this season, they
can blame the Expos, who beat them eight times in 12 games,
including four of the last five meetings and just shut them out in
their last 17 innings. ... New York has lost two straight but is
12-9 in September. The bullpen has four blown saves this month and,
with the exception of John Olerud, no other Mets player has hit a
home run in the last five games. ... The Braves have held the Mets
to a .230 team average this season. New York has hit .260 against
everyone else. In their nine previous meetings, the Braves have
outscored the Mets, 42-23. New York has hit five homers off Atlanta
pitching this season. Andruw Jones and Andres Galarraga have hit
seven homers against the Mets. ... But the memory of the last
series still lingers, when late homers by Tony Phillips and Edgardo
Alfonzo pulled out two victories. In their first 50 innings against
New York, Braves pitchers did not give up a homer. They have given
up five in the last 33 innings. ... Reed, tonight's starter, has
one victory in his last five starts. He is 0-1 against Atlanta in
two starts this year, losing on Sept. 6 in a 4-0 shutout to John
Smoltz. ... On the DL: RHP Jason Isringhausen (right elbow
surgery), LHP Hector Mercado (left elbow surgery), INF Craig
Paquette (sprained left ankle), C Vance Wilson (broken right
forearm), RHP Brad Clontz (bone spurs, right elbow).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: RHP Turk Wendell has appeared in the last nine games
and has given up a run in 13 innings. John Olerud is batting .517
in his last eight games but fell nine points behind Colorado's
Larry Walker after going 0-for-3 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: CF Brian McRae is batting .152 during the last 10
days. Closer John Franco has given up seven hits and walked six in
his last five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
