<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY REPORTS 5 PERCENT DROP IN INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PETER TRUELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. reported a 5 percent
drop in net income for its third fiscal quarter on Thursday, but it
beat analysts' expectations and turned in a stronger performance
than either Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. or Lehman Inc., the two other Wall
Street firms that reported quarterly results this week.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley said it earned $645 million, or $1.05 a share,
for the three months ended Aug. 31., the third quarter of its
fiscal year, and cited losses of more than $200 million in a
developing country fund that it manages. The median forecast of
analysts surveyed by First Call was $1.03 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over all, the results showed they handled a pretty rough
situation pretty well, particularly compared to the rest of the
firms,'' said Guy Moszkowski, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, a
unit of the Travelers Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's return on equity also remained a high 19.3
percent, despite the difficulties in the financial markets that
became particularly severe in July and August.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its relatively strong performance, Morgan Stanley shares
fell $5.6875, or 10 percent, to $51.5625, as the banking and
financial services sectors were generally pounded in Thursday's
market slide.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael Soifer, an analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman, said,
``Comparing them with the two other firms which have reported, they
showed less volatility because of the more diversified group of
businesses that they have.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Morgan Stanley's results for the quarter were an
endorsement of its strategy of building a broad investment banking
and financial services franchise, from selling mutual funds and
credit cards to ordinary citizens to issuing stocks and bonds for
big companies and governments. Its merger last year with Dean
Witter Discover &AMP; Co., was intended to create just such a
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Although Morgan Stanley's pin-striped investment bankers would
sometimes grimace at the firm's Main Street businesses at Dean
Witter, and the Discover Card, its rather middle-market credit
card, ``Discover card did exactly what you would have expected in
terms of supporting earnings in otherwise difficult quarter,''
Moszkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the revenge of the nerds,'' laughed Robert Scott, Morgan
Stanley's chief financial officer, as he discussed his firm's
earnings, and the rich profits from credit cards and Main Street
customers.
</P>
<P>
   In common with many other big financial firms, Morgan Stanley
had warned a few weeks ago that its profits for the quarter would
be cut by about $110 million because of losses caused by difficult
conditions in world capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a leveraged emerging markets debt fund,'' Scott said on
Thursday. ``The fund got caught in the emerging markets debt
downturn. When that market tanked, because it was a leveraged
fund,'' with heavy borrowings, ``it was unable to meet margin
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than let the fund fail, Morgan decided to step in and put
up the money to meet the fund's margin calls. And that cost it
``more than a couple of hundred million dollars,'' he said. The
firm decided to do that, he added, even though it was not
technically obligated to do so, because of ``its overall
relationship with the creditors'' of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   But, things may get worse before they get better for Wall Street
firms such as Morgan Stanley. The firm's earnings for the current
quarter, which ends Nov. 30, are also likely to be affected by the
continued instability in world financial markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
