<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3282 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS25-COX     09-24 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eating up yardage
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- Back in the far left corner of his
cluttered refrigerator, there might be one last nugget of chicken,
Garrison Hearst thinks, but, alas, its unofficial expiration date
passed two weeks ago. All that remains of the plum jelly, made with
love from trees that grow in his mama's back yard in Lincolnton, is
a half-jar of good eating and a lot of great memories.
</P>
<P>
   The cornbread and biscuits and sweet-potato pie his family
brought out the first week of the NFL season? Despite diligent
rationing, gone, gone and long-gone.
</P>
<P>
   These are the glad tidings for the Atlanta Falcons as they will
attempt Sunday to slow down the San Francisco 49ers and their star
running back: The inventory of down-home vittles that Hearst craves
is all but depleted. A stomach filled with chicken, pork chops and
ribs during a hurried trip home for last weekend's bye is empty
again, and Hearst yearns for something deep-fried and smothered in
gravy.
</P>
<P>
   But because older sister Candy's gall bladder is flaring up
again, a visit this weekend by Hearst's mother, Mary, and his
grandmother, Julie Leverett, has been postponed, and the flour and
aprons and cooking oil have been packed away for another time.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, a former University of Georgia player, is desperate for
the kind of Southern home cooking you can't find anywhere in the
Bay area. (Tourist alert: the S&AMP;B Restaurant in nearby San Jose is
long on promises, but its fried okra comes up short.) ``He's been
calling a lot lately and asking for a box of food _ you know, some
butter rolls and all,'' Mary Hearst said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Now the bad news for defenders: Hearst is even hungrier to keep
posting the kind of rushing numbers that have elevated him to
lethal-weapon status in the NFL's deepest offensive arsenal. His
dreams of another 1,000-yard season probably will become reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should be a piece of cake, really,'' guard Ray Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   And with his extended family watching on television late Sunday
afternoon when the hometown running back takes on the home team,
Hearst has additional motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Although he tried early in the week to play down the
significance of facing the Falcons, Hearst said by Thursday that
the two matchups with Atlanta are circled on his calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, sure, there's always something a little extra when it's
the Falcons,'' said Hearst, who in two games this season has rushed
for 325 yards on 42 carries and whose 7.7-yard average is the NFL's
best. ``Guys have been talking all week about it being our hardest
game. And they've got the top-rated (defense) against the run, too.
It's going to be tough. But I'll have family and friends watching
and expecting me to light it up. So if we can win and I can put a
little smile on their faces. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Since he signed with San Francisco as an unrestricted free agent
in March 1997, both of those missions have been accomplished. The
49ers are 13-2 in the 15 contests Hearst has started, and the
sixth-year pro has rushed for 1,344 yards and averaged 4.9 yards,
the most productive stretch of his NFL career. His rush to glory
with the Niners was slowed only by a fractured collarbone last
December, and some players cite the late-season injury and Hearst's
resultant rustiness in the playoffs for the team's failure to
advance to Super Bowl XXXII.
</P>
<P>
   Mention Hearst's name to Mariucci or any of the 49ers' long-time
veterans and a smile and knowing nod are the most typical
responses. They speak often of his trademark locker-room pranks.
But when pressed, the players politely refuse to divulge the
details of the latest pranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take care of our own,'' wide receiver Jerry Rice said.
``And Garrison is definitely one of us. He has fit in well, and
that hasn't always been the case with newcomers here. Garrison has
made us tougher on the field and a little less (uptight) off it.''
</P>
<P>
   That the 27-year-old Hearst would not only find, but also
dispense, happiness with the NFL's most sophisticated franchise
seems improbable. In the process, he has silenced the critics who
thought his time with Arizona and Cincinnati, and resulting knee
injuries, would never allow him to be as good in the pros as he was
in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what he's been through _ being cut in Phoenix after he
was the third overall pick (in 1993) and exploited in Cincinnati,
and the knee injuries _ I think he's enjoying this a little more
than some other guys might,'' agent Pat Dye Jr. said. ``Garrison
has seen the other side, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dye worked hard in the spring of 1997 to convince San Francisco
vice president Dwight Clark that Hearst could be the answer to the
49ers' running problems. And while not everyone in the club's front
office believed it, they came to trust in Hearst within a few
months of his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Just before she served the turkey dinner on Thanksgiving
afternoon a year ago, Ashley Clark, the wife of the 49ers' vice
president, asked him what he was most thankful for. ``No offense,''
Clark said, ``but probably Garrison Hearst.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year later, that feeling is universal with the Niners.
</P>
<P>
   When his record 96-yard run rescued the team in overtime of this
year's first game, he was hoisted onto the shoulders of two
offensive linemen and carried to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive linemen, in particular, admire the way Hearst
worked on his shoulders during the offseason so that he might avoid
future collarbone problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tougher runner now,'' guard Kevin Gogan said. ``(He's)
a lot more explosive to the hole, like somebody shot him out of a
cannon or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst insists he is the same back he's always been, but he
concedes that San Francisco fans have put him into a hero's
spotlight. But at heart, he's a thrifty country boy who will make
$3.5 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   He is a blue-jeans-and-T-shirt guy employed by a glitzy
franchise. The floor in the office of owner Eddie DeBartolo is
covered in leather. While San Francisco's backup players have phone
calls carefully screened, he refuses to buy an answering machine or
a cellular phone. He does have a pager.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned home to Lincolnton last weekend, Hearst kicked
back in a rocking chair, watched Georgia football and professional
wrestling and, of course, ate well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Him being (in San Francisco), it's kind of like another
world,'' Mary Hearst said. ``He's country all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrison himself said, ``Always have been country. Always will
be country. This is nice, but I can't see how Lincolnton would ever
stop being home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
