<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3283 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-WEEKENDBEST-COX     09-24 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WEEKENDBEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons-49ers should be competitive despite trend
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When they renamed the stadium here 3Com Park
several years ago, San Francisco 49ers officials must have had the
Atlanta Falcons in mind. During the past six seasons, the Falcons
certainly have mirrored that moniker when they faced the Niners.
</P>
<P>
   Compliant. Compunctious. And for the most part, comatose.
</P>
<P>
   Since their upset victory in 1991 at what was then Candlestick
Park, a win that compelled Jerry Glanville to commission the
ill-advised ``California Trophy,'' the Falcons have suffered an
inglorious stretch of bashings by the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The average margin in Atlanta's six-pack losing streak is 27.0
points, and San Francisco hasn't scored fewer than 34 in that span.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Glanville returns to 3Com Park on Sunday afternoon
to serve as analyst for the Falcons-49ers matchup, another ``com''
word might creep back into this rivalry as well.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive. Many of the 49ers veterans think the weekend's only
game pitting undefeated teams will be just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing real well,'' 49ers center Chris Dalman said
about the Falcons. ``The big thing that stands out is that they
don't beat themselves. It's an aggressive defense but still very
sound. And they can move the ball offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not be the flashiest team, but they're the best one
we've looked at so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the ``bests'' for this weekend:
</P>
<P>
   Upset opportunity: Despite an 0-3 record, Chicago has been
remarkably competitive and figures to give the slightly overrated
Vikings all they can handle. But the underdog of the week clearly
is undefeated Seattle, which faces the offensively addled Steelers.
The fans at Three Rivers Stadium might generate more energy by
twirling their Terrible Towels than Pittsburgh can muster with
mistake-prone Kordell Stewart. The Seahawks can get to 4-0 for the
first time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Individual matchup: Asssuming St. Louis wideout Isaac Bruce is
healthy, his battle with Arizona cornerback Aeneas Williams should
be a good one. The Cardinals staff is beginning to flip Williams
more in an effort to lock him onto the opposition's best wide
receiver for the entire game. Bruce is a burner with great
explosiveness, but Williams knows every trick in the book. In
Chicago, there will be plenty of collisions between Bears tailback
Curtis Enis and Minnesota linebackers Ed McDaniel and Dwayne Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy play: You hate to make 'em too obvious, but playing
without a running game and going up against a battered Carolina
defense, look for Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre to have a big
day. Favre knows the weaknesses of Panthers cornerback Doug Evans,
a former Packers teammate. And with Panthers strong safety Mike
Minter out with an injury, Favre will get the ball more to his
tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   Grudge match: Sunday marks the first time the Cardinals have
returned to St. Louis for a regular-season game since owner Bill
Bidwill relocated the franchise to Phoenix in 1988. Bidwill isn't
the most beloved owner in the Valley of the Sun, but he is reviled
in St. Louis and will be jeered lustily if he shows his face.
</P>
<P>
   Division game: With one start under his belt now, rookie
quarterback Charlie Batch has learned the most important rule of
the Detroit offense: When in doubt, hand the ball to Barry Sanders.
He will, often, on Monday night, and the Lions will upset the Bucs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
