<SLUG> BC-GIBSON-BIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Josh Gibson, considered one of the best catchers in baseball
history, was expected to be named Tuesday to the Baseball Hall of
Fame in a special election by a committee on Negro leagues,
February 8, 1972. Gibson never had chance to play in the majors.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Josh Gibson file
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Birth: Dec. 21, 1911, in Buena Vista, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Death: Jan. 20, 1947, in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Teams: Homestead Grays (1930-33 and 1937-46); Pittsburgh
Crawfords (1934-36).
</P>
<P>
   Position: Catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame: Inducted in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Played in Negro League's World Series six times and
all-star game every year from 1933 through 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs: Exact total is undocumented, but he is believed to
have hit more than 900 in his career, counting all types of games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
