<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3285 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIBSON-COX     09-24 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIBSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forgotten slugger
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- He is credited with hitting more home runs in a
single season than any other player in professional baseball
history, yet he remains largely ignored today, just as he was
slighted in his own time, while Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa fight
over the most cherished record in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-born Josh Gibson, known as the Black Babe Ruth, was
segregated out of the white major leagues, but according to black
newspapers, the slugging catcher hit 962 home runs in a 17-year
Negro League career that spanned the Depression and World War II.
It is said that Gibson hit 75 homers as a 19-year-old for the
Homestead Grays in 1931, and he struck his all-time high, 84, for
the Pittsburgh Crawfords in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would've definitely challenged Ruth's record, perhaps
surpassed it,'' said James Riley, who has written four books on the
Negro Leagues and their players and did the research for Mark
Ribowski's Gibson biography, ``Power and Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley considers Gibson baseball's all-time greatest catcher and
the slugging equal to Ruth, but he admits that some of Gibson's
totals are open to question. There is a dearth of box scores from
the era to confirm the legend, and black newspapers typically
didn't cover road games.
</P>
<P>
   The home run totals also include those hit in all games, most of
them against semi-pro teams. Gibson played in 170 games during the
84-homer year of 1936.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newspapers say he hit 972 home runs, but we haven't been
able to document every game,'' Riley said. ``Some of the papers
probably fudged a little bit just to make headlines. I'm skeptical
of their veracity, but there's no question he could've done that.
Just imagine if Babe Ruth played 60 games and 100 more against
semi-pro teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's teams played league schedules of only 40 to 60 games a
year. Riley said semi-pro teams of the '30s were comparable to A or
AA minor league teams because it was more practical in Depression
days for top players below the major league-level to work during
the week and play on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Among his Negro League peers, however, there is no dispute.
Gibson was their premier home run hitter. At 6-foot-1, 210 pounds
in his prime, Gibson didn't just hit home runs. He made spectacles
of them.
</P>
<P>
   He's the only player said to have hit a fair ball completely out
of Yankee Stadium. The homer was struck off Slim Jones in 1934 and
might've traveled 700 feet had it been measured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gibson is in the mold of a Ruth or a McGwire,'' Riley said.
``His home runs were majestic.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was born in Buena Vista in 1911 but didn't play baseball
until his family moved to Pittsburgh when he was 13. He joined the
Grays in 1929 and became their regular catcher and a national
barnstorming attraction, the fun-loving home run king, throughout
the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to over 200 (Negro League) players, and the
consistent thing they talk about is Josh's home runs and Satchel
Paige's strikeouts,'' Riley said. ``Gibson was to black kids what
Ruth was to white kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, who was beset by alcoholism and suspected drug use in
the '40s, died of stroke shortly after his 35th birthday, just
months before Jackie Robinson became the century's first
African-American major league player. In 1972, Gibson became the
second player from the Negro Leagues after Satchel Paige to be
inducted into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
