<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATINGS-BACKSLIDE-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS TV NETWORKS FAIL IN ALERTS TO SEX AND VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year after the television networks revised their movie-style
ratings code to add labels alerting parents to sexual or violent
content in shows, a study has found that the networks are not
regularly adding those labels.
</P>
<P>
   The labels, for example, V for violence or S for sexual content,
are added to the age-group ratings printed in television listings
and appearing on screen at the start of shows.
</P>
<P>
   The age-group rating codes are being applied appropriately to 96
percent of the programs, according to the study released Thursday
by the Kaiser Family Foundation, a philanthropic group devoted to
public health issues.
</P>
<P>
   But the report by the foundation, based in Menlo Park, Calif.,
said 92 percent of shows with some sexual content did not carry the
additional S label, and 79 percent of shows that had violent scenes
did not carry a V. Also, the study found that 81 percent of
children's shows that contained violence did not have the FV
notation, for fantasy violence, which is found to varying degrees
in many cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Those percentages may be skewed upward by the fact that NBC
programming was included in the study's sample, and NBC has refused
from the outset to add the V, S, L for foul language and D for
suggestive dialogue to the system. And the study acknowledged that
some violent or sexual content not labeled was of ``low level.''
</P>
<P>
   The age-based labels, in use since January 1997, are supposed to
be applied to all programs except news and sports. They are TV-G
for all ages; TV-PG, parental guidance suggested; TV-14, not
suitable for those under 14; TV-MA, for adults only; TV-Y, for all
children, and TV-Y7, may not be suitable for children under 7.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, all the networks except NBC and the cable network
BET agreed to augment their age-group ratings with the four letters
to signal what specific content in a show might be found
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ratings are misleading or not being applied accurately,
then the system won't work for parents,'' said Kathryn C.
Montgomery, president of the Center for Media Education, a
Washington group concerned with how the media influence children.
``We need some close scrutiny from the monitoring board.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A monitoring board, with members from the industry and family
advocacy groups, was set up to adjudicate disputes about the
system. Richard L. Taylor, vice president for public affairs at the
Motion Picture Association of America, which led the industry's
negotiations for the ratings system and still coordinates it, said
Thursday that the board would meet in November.
</P>
<P>
   The system, which is voluntary, was devised for use with the
V-chip, an electronic device that can be used to black out shows
that parents do not want their children to watch. The chip is to be
standard equipment on new television sets starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   With television news reports recently filled with explicit
sexual detail about President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky, the
study's authors were asked Thursday if news programs should
continue to be exempt from the ratings system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take a position on the ratings system,'' said Vicky
Rideout, director of Kaiser's program on entertainment media and
public health. ``We just try to conduct valid studies and put the
data out there for the policy makers. But there was a widespread
consensus it would not be appropriate to rate news. Those decisions
are up to the judgment of journalists and news executives as to
whether something is truly newsworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser study, conducted by researchers at the University of
California at Santa Barbara, analyzed 1,147 randomly selected
programs shown last season by ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox stations, the
cable networks USA, TNT, HBO, Lifetime and Nickelodeon and an
independent station in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers counted incidents of violence or sexual content, but
they also evaluated how graphic or intense the content was and the
context in which it was shown, and related these factors to the
definitions of what is appropriate for each age group in the rating
system. Those definitions were set by a group representing both the
television industry and the family advocacy groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
