<SLUG> BC-U.S.-MIDEAST-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO MEET WITH ARAFAT AND NETANYAHU NEXT WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will meet separately with
Israel's prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, and the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, at the White House next week in the hope of
reviving peace talks in the Middle East, White House and State
Department officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They would be the first such meetings in nearly nine months.
There has been little visible progress in the peace process in two
years. But there have been signs in recent weeks that Netanyahu and
Arafat might be easing their stances on aspects of a U.S.-sponsored
plan for pushing the process ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will meet separately with
the two leaders in New York City on Saturday night and Sunday to
try to persuade them to agree on the terms of an Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said in New York on Thursday that ``we keep making
progress'' in nudging the Israelis and the Palestinians toward an
accord on the West Bank. American, Israeli and Palestinian
officials believe that the personal intervention of President
Clinton might help move the process forward.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats said there was so much work to be done that there
is little hope of closing a deal next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke separately by telephone Thursday with the two men
to confirm the meetings, the officials said. ``The president urged
them to be flexible and urged them to make the tough decisions that
will lead to final talks'' in the peace process, a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is tentatively scheduled to see the president on
Monday; Arafat is to meet Clinton later in the week. The White
House meeting would be the first for either man since January.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is seeking a gradual Israeli pullback from the
West Bank, allowing an increasing Palestinian control of the area.
A proposed compromise, which has taken more than a year to resolve,
calls for the two sides to agree on an Israeli withdrawal from an
additional 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is thought to be on the verge of agreeing with the
Palestinian Authority to withdraw _ or redeploy, as the Israelis
prefer to state it _ its troops from this land, on the condition
that 3 percent of the West Bank will become a nature preserve or a
national park.
</P>
<P>
   On this issue, among others standing in the way of final talks
on the status of Jerusalem and the size and shape of the land under
the Palestinian Authority's control, Albright hopes ``to lock in as
much progress as we can'' in her weekend discussions with the two
leaders, a senior administration official said. ``The best to hope
for is that she can lock in agreements on some of the areas''
standing in the way of final talks, this official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue that needs to be resolved for final talks to begin
is an Israeli demand for concrete counterterrorism commitments from
the Palestinian Authority. The CIA's chief in Israel has been
serving as a mediator on this issue, working with the Palestinian
and Israeli security services on counterterrorism concerns.
According to Israeli radio reports last month, the CIA chief is
working with the Palestinian service on drawing up a
counterterrorism memorandum that will satisfy Israel's demand.
</P>
<P>
   No agreement on this issue has been reported, however. And there
are equally thorny interim issues that must be resolved, including
how freely Palestinians may travel between the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, before final talks begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect to be able to complete all the steps necessary
to complete a move to final status talks'' during the coming week,
a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Looming in the minds of the Israelis, the Palestinians and the
Americans is the fact that the Oslo Accords, the framework under
which the peace process has taken place since 1993, are scheduled
to expire on May 4. Diplomats fear that if some progress is not
made soon, this deadline will not be met, and that this failure
could plunge the Israelis and Palestinians into a deeper
bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has said that he would unilaterally declare a Palestinian
state unless Israel agreed to the idea by May 4. Netanyahu has said
that the Oslo agreements forbid such a declaration, and that
Palestinian statehood is an issue that must be settled between the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say that if the talks in coming days create a
path toward peace, then the May 4 deadline could possibly pass
without trouble. But they say they fear that without progress soon,
the deadline could mark a significant erosion of the peace
process. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
