<SLUG> BC-NAMEGAME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 What's in a Name? America Gets to Know Next Week   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The merger of BankAmerica and NationsBank is no longer in doubt,
but the brand name of the combined bank remains a big secret.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At yesterday's special shareholders meeting, BofA chief
executive David Coulter said the winning name will be disclosed
``on an evening news program'' on Wednesday. There has been intense
speculation about what name will go on the combined bank's
branches, signs, advertising and ATM cards.
</P>
<P>
   If NationsBank is the surviving name, it would be an additional
affront to many Californians and BofA employees who already are
smarting from the fact that Charlotte, not San Francisco, is
headquarters, and NationsBank and its board of directors are in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   For months, bankers at both institutions have been grappling
with the high-stakes name issue. They have hired the New York
corporate identity firm Anspach Grossman Enterprise for advice and
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter said there will be ``a single brand name moving
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Bay Area corporate brand experts and securities analysts
think that BankAmerica will be the surviving name.
</P>
<P>
   ``BankAmerica is clearly the name that travels the best from
state to state,'' said Rick Bragdon, a partner with the San
Francisco corporate branding firm Idiom. He figures that
BankAmerica also has an edge internationally, especially in
volatile markets when ``people gravitate to the stability of
America and our currency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst choice would be to put the two names together,''
said David Placek, CEO of Lexicon Branding in Sausalito.
``NationsBank of America would be an unfortunate compromise _
redundant, and people won't get the connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Placek figures that BankAmerica is easier to say and phonically
stronger. In work for American Express and other financial
companies, Placek also said he found that America or U.S. in a name
doesn't carry ``negative baggage around the world,'' although USA
may.
</P>
<P>
   ``BankAmerica has been a fixture in the West for decades and is
the better choice,'' said Van Kasper analyst Joseph Morford, who
hears that the chosen name could be disclosed on ABC's
``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NationsBank has a relatively new name, and because of all the
acquisitions they've done in the past few years, it's not as well
known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
