<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-EXPAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN LEADERS HINT AT WIDENING THE PRESIDENTIAL
INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-REPUBS-MONEY,
CLINTON-PRESS, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-DEMS.) 
(th) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders suggested Thursday that the
Judiciary Committee would consider information from other House
investigations into the White House and Democrats if it helped the
panel establish a pattern of obstruction of justice by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, and
party leaders also said they had not ruled out a second referral by
Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, on matters relating to the
Whitewater land deal, possible misuse of FBI files and dismissals
in the White House travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing his words carefully, Hyde said his committee would not
rule out relevant information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt we were bound by Judge Starr's activities,'' Hyde
said. ``There may be other matters we feel bear on the main
questions of the fitness of the president for this office. I would
never say we won't hear these things, but I would be guided by the
rule of relevancy, germaneness and of probative value.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde stressed, however, that the panel did not currently intend
to widen the inquiry, or cast a ``very wide net.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders had held out hope that Starr's report would
go beyond the question of Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, a topic for which the public harbors mixed feelings. They
had also expected Starr's report to help bolster several of their
own in-house investigations into the White House and the
president's Democratic allies.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year now, Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who is the
chairman of the Committee on Government Reform and Oversight, has
been investigating campaign finance abuses in the 1996 election by
Democrats and the White House. His committee is now completing an
interim report.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., was recently asked to head a
select committee on whether China illicitly obtained sensitive
American missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   In recent meetings with Republican leaders, Speaker Newt
Gingrich of Georgia raised the prospect of referring relevant House
committee findings to the Judiciary Committee, a Republican
leadership aide said. At the very minimum, the information could
``corroborate the pattern'' of obstruction of justice, the aide
said, recounting the discussion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
