<SLUG> BC-PAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Philippine Airlines Plane Seized in L.A.   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Philippine Airlines plane that was supposed to have carried
passengers on a final flight from San Francisco to Manila Wednesday
night has been impounded by U.S. authorities in Los Angeles to help
pay off the carrier's debts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PAL abruptly canceled the flight after the U.S. Eximbank, one
of PAL's creditors, received a restraining order preventing the
plane from leaving the United States, said PAL Vice President
Manolo Aquino.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to be sure. They have lost their trust in us and
wanted to recover their assets,'' Aquino told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Mars Calica, manager of personnel and administration in PAL's
San Francisco office, said the plane was handed over to a trustee,
Evergreen Airlines, which will store it eventually in Arizona for
safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Debt laden and beset with labor strife, Philippine Airlines
officially shut down Wednesday night after the last plane from
Manila dropped passengers off at San Francisco International
Airport before making a final stop at Los Angeles International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   SFO spokesman Ron Wilson said the airport would wait to see if
PAL resumes operations before assigning PAL's ticket counter and
terminal space to other carriers. PAL, which carried about 85,000
passengers a year from SFO, owed about $70,000 to the airport,
although it was not considered delinquent, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philippine Airlines is a long-established carrier here,''
Wilson said. ``We're going to have to wait and get word on their
prognosis.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a number of suitors including Northwest and United
Airlines have reportedly expressed interest in buying the airline.
</P>
<P>
   According to one news account, Northwest and United are
interested in picking up some of PAL's passenger routes, especially
its transpacific service to the Philippines from San Francisco and
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine President Joseph Estrada also reportedly said the
government might buy part or all of Philippine Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But Northwest, the only U.S. carrier still flying into Manila,
denied reports that it is considering buying the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no plans to purchase Philippine Airlines,'' said Doug
Killian, international communications manager for Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines still has transpacific landing rights to Manila,
but ended passenger service earlier this year because it could not
generate enough high-fare business traffic. United spokesman Tony
Molinaro said the airline was studying the situation but was far
from making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay Pacific Airways of Hong Kong and Eva Airways Corp. of
Taiwan also may want to take over PAL, Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Lufthansa AG was also interested, PAL executive Avalino
Zapanta said. Given PAL's union problems and the region's slump in
traffic, some analysts said it seemed unlikely any other airlines
would want to purchase PAL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see Northwest as an opportunistic buyer of some used
aircraft on the cheap, but I would personally be surprised to see
anything beyond that,'' PaineWebber analyst Samuel Buttrick said.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments, Singapore Airlines has doubled its fares
from parts of Southeast Asia to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   PAL's Calica said the airline's major ground crew union, which
rejected a proposal that the airline said it needed to keep
operating, was reconsidering the offer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
