<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BofA Deal Past Last Hurdle   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The last potential obstacle to the merger of BankAmerica and
NationsBank was overcome yesterday when the banks' shareholders
gave the deal a resounding thumbs up.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At simultaneous meetings in San Francisco and Charlotte, N.C.,
it was announced that 97 percent of BofA shares and 98 percent of
NationsBank shares that voted were cast in favor of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The combined bank will have $570 billion in assets, a
significant presense in almost half the states, and 32 million
customers in 38 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will be completed after the close of business on
September 30. The combined bank will start operating the following
day, but changes in products and services will be phased in
gradually.
</P>
<P>
   The new bank's brand name will be disclosed Wednesday on a TV
news show. The name of the holding company will be BankAmerica
Corp., and its stock trading symbol will be BAC, which is
BankAmerica's ticker.
</P>
<P>
   The new holding company will issue 1.1316 shares for each share
held by current BofA shareholders. In a bad day for stocks in
general and many financial issues in particular, BofA shares
dropped $5.25 to $60 and NationsBank shares slid $4.38 to $54.38
</P>
<P>
   Talking to a mostly friendly crowd of 600 shareholders and
bankers at the Masonic Center in San Francisco, BofA Chairman and
CEO David Coulter said, ``BankAmerica and NationsBank will be
positioned more strongly as a combined company than either of us
are separately.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulter will be president of the new company, which will be
based in Charlotte and headed by NationsBank Chairman and CEO Hugh
McColl. The combined bank expects to cut annual costs by about $1.3
billion and generate profits of about $10 billion. Coulter said
dividends will rise to the level of NationsBank, which is about 25
percent higher than BofA's payout.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been estimated that as many as 8,000 of the
combined bank's 180,000 jobs could be eliminated, Coulter said that
as a result of ``natural attrition, the reduction will not be
draconian.'' (He also said the company has decided to call its
people ``associates'' rather than employees.)
</P>
<P>
   Although six San Francisco policeman were posted outside the
auditorium on Nob Hill, the special shareholders meeting was
peaceful inside and outside.
</P>
<P>
   In the 45-minute question-and-answer session, Coulter
acknowledged that there were ``execution risks'' in providing
seamless customer service while consolidating operations. About 400
``transition teams'' have been working on these issues.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter also conceded that there are corporate culture
differences and year 2000 computer programming issues that need
attention but certainly are surmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Although Coulter was applauded warmly, the person who generated
the biggest cheer was former teller Catherine Paul, who ended her
question about retiree benefits with the quip, ``I know you've
checked your retirement.'' (No one else made any mention of top
BofA executives' generous employment contracts.)
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who worked for BofA for 18 years and was one of the few
who voted against the merger, also got in the last word from the
audience. After Coulter explained that mergers of Citibank and
Travelers, Banc One and First Chicago, Wells Fargo and Norwest all
point to the importance of size and scope, she snapped, ``Just
because they're jumping off the bridge, we don't have to join
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
