<SLUG> BC-NET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SEC Gets Tough on Online Stock Fraud   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Securities and Exchange Commission, in a major crackdown on
online stock fraud, filed charges yesterday against 41 companies
and individuals, alleging they were behind scams that cheated
investors out of more than $25 million.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The move marks the government's most aggressive action yet
against the fly-by-night businesses and stock offerings promoted
over the Internet through spam, or unsolicited commercial e-mail
messages, and newsgroup postings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``We're going to ferret out and prosecute scam artists who
prey on innocent investors,'' said Richard Walker, director of the
SEC's enforcement division. ``With so much money to be made during
a bull market, we've seen an increase in get-rich-quick online
offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities sued brokerage firms, bogus companies and
individuals from Los Angeles to Florida for engaging in so-called
``pump and dump'' schemes that were widely advertised in postal
mail and spam.
</P>
<P>
   The illegal practice typically occurs when a speculator &UR;  &LR; buys
large amounts of a low-priced or ``penny'' stock, ``pumps'' up the
price by hyping the security over the Internet and then ``dumps''
it to make a profit, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said the operations included enticements to invest in
bogus medical breakthroughs, ersatz data-transmission technology
and sham hotel renovations.
</P>
<P>
   In many of the cases, Internet spam and newsgroup postings
played a key role in spreading misleading information about the
financial condition and future stock price of the companies. Among
the worst offenders, the SEC alleges:
</P>
<P>
   _ Orange County brokerage firm Waldron &AMP; Co. Inc. racked up more
than $4 million by hyping shares of Internet shopping service
Shopping.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Florida company that claimed it built golf practice
facilities was actually a pyramid-type scheme that bilked more than
350 investors in 16 states out of $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's online Enforcement Complaint Center now receives more
than 120 e-mail messages daily on potential Net securities fraud,
compared with just 10 a day in mid-1996, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the SEC has pursued some 30 suits since 1995 against
online services accused of fraud, this summer it created a special
unit _ the Office of Internet Enforcement _ to step up its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet provides a lot of good information, but a small
group of users is trying to rip people off,'' said John Stark, who
heads the unit.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC encourages consumers to report suspicious online stock
offers to its &UR;  &LR; toll-free phone number, (800) 732-0330, and e-mail
address, &LR;  enforcement(at sign)sec.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In related news, federal prosecutors in New York charged
executives of Assets International Ltd. yesterday with cheating
investors of $14 million by selling bogus ``high-yield investment''
programs on the company's Web site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
