<SLUG> BC-BOX-HUMMER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Champ is an inspiration, but only inside the ring
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Servic
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The story goes that Atlanta's heavyweight champion
Evander Holyfield was not officially introduced to his father until
he was 21, just a few months after getting jobbed at the 1984
Olympics. His mother, Annie, led him to a doorway in Atmore, Ala.,
and to the square-bodied lumberjack who could answer those
important questions, ``Who am I? Where am I from?''
</P>
<P>
   You see his father, Isom Coley, on the fringes of the Holyfield
flock during the periodic big event. The man with the broad face
and tell-tale cow-catcher jaw was at the Georgia Dome Saturday for
the Vaughn Bean fight, loosely connected to the champion's corner.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield often has spoken of the pain he felt growing up
without a father. He even testified once before a U.S. House
subcommittee studying the problems in fatherless households. But it
turns out that instead of a solution, Holyfield is the problem. We
have come to know that he is as reckless in his personal life as he
is controlled and consistent in his chosen profession.
</P>
<P>
   What a disappointment it all has been.
</P>
<P>
   Having five of his nine children born out of wedlock to four
different women _ two in the last year while his marriage to Janice
ran aground _ Holyfield once again has shown his basic flaw. He
will support all his children; he will deny none of them; they will
know their father. But sometime well before his 35th year of life,
he should have figured out that family reunions aren't meant to be
more convoluted than an Oliver Stone plot.
</P>
<P>
   It's really very simple. A responsible man doesn't disperse his
seed like a Scott's rotary spreader.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations of a philandering fighter set off a massive
reaction hereabouts this week. Suddenly, a champion who had
constructed a shining image had his character picked apart on talk
radio and at lunch counters around town. Some said it was none of
our business _ ignoring that it was Holyfield who came clean,
repeating his philosophy to his advisers that ``the truth can only
hurt you once, but a lie can hurt you forever.'' Others branded
this publicly pious fighter a hypocrite of Old Testament
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   One bit of advice seems warranted now: If you want serious
religious guidance, look somewhere else other than the heavyweight
division. It's as risky as getting your faith off TV.
</P>
<P>
   On the corporate front, Holyfield's attorney, Jim Thomas, said
that Holyfield has been in contact with his major sponsors since
the latest story of infidelity broke, and that they are
``understanding.'' A Coca-Cola spokesperson said its relationship
with Holyfield is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   On the personal front, Holyfield and his circle must deal with
the first undressing of his myth. ``People can accept it or not,''
Thomas said. ``It is the same kind of feeling as with (minister)
Jimmy Swaggert's scandal. When someone falls, there are always
people who want to step on him. They want to be able to say, `See,
you're not so holy.' But Evander never said he was any holier or
better or cleaner than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   There still is much to be learned from watching Holyfield at
work. I maintain immense respect for the seriousness of his
training and the strength of his fighting spirit.
</P>
<P>
   We can stop looking for anything more just now. The tide is out.
The role-modeling ends in those knee-deep qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
