<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRODERBUND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 No Job? No Problem! Laid-off Tech Workers Enjoy Time Off   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
You've just lost your high-tech job. What are you going to do next?
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm going to Disneyland'' is the response some high-tech
workers might give.
</P>
<P>
   Confident of their ability to land a new job quickly, many newly
unemployed tech workers are using their buyout and severance
payments to live it up before getting back into the 9-to-9 grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby, I'm taking it easy,'' said Michael Shea, 27, who was
laid off earlier this month along with 226 others from Broderbund
Software in Novato. ``I'm going to investigate the bohemian
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea, who provided online support for Broderbund products,
figures that he can start looking for a new job in January. First,
he's going to visit family in Pennsylvania and London.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I have now is a vista of opportunity,'' he said. ``There
are billions of doors in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The numbers bear out his optimism: The Bay Area unemployment
rate this year is under 4 percent, its lowest in nine years,
according to economist Joe Nation in San Rafael.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Most of these people can write their own ticket and go
anywhere they want, and for more money,'' said Roger King, chief
executive of Tech Search, a Sausalito recruiting firm. ``It's a
workers' market. There's tremendous demand for them.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who mostly places executives, said he's never been busier.
His wish list now includes a vice president of technology, a vice
president of sales and marketing, and a chief executive officer.
But he also said quality-assurance engineers and product marketing
managers ``are having a heyday.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, many laid-off workers will face a struggle, even in
booming Silicon Valley. In the slump that continues to hit the
semiconductor industry, many people are sent into a job market
where companies are cutting back across the board.
</P>
<P>
   And some older workers may not have the skills in the newer
programming languages that are in such great demand.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Broderbund, the layoffs stung some workers. Dave Smilie,
31, had just started a new job three months ago. ``I loved my new
position,'' he said. ``It was a little hard to lose that new
position.''
</P>
<P>
   And while some of his younger colleagues can move to Silicon
Valley to capitalize on new opportunities, Smilie hopes to find a
job within commuting distance of Santa Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, though, layoffs occur because of mergers, poor
business conditions or even corporate mismanagement. In those
situations, the layoff no longer carries the stigma it once did and
other companies eagerly snap up the newly unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Apple Computer laid off 4,100 workers last
year, recruiters flocked to the Cupertino campus to hire the highly
skilled employees.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Diffely, 32, took a buyout from the chip-equipment
manufacturer Applied Materials earlier this year and moved almost
directly into a new career as an industry analyst with Merrill
Lynch in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to get five or six months' salary (as a buyout
package) before leaving,'' Diffely said.
</P>
<P>
   Before starting his new job, he took a 31/2-week vacation to
Italy, something he never could have done while he was working as a
global product manager at Applied. ``It's hard to take a long
vacation because the product cycles are so quick,'' Diffely said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for companies like Applied is to keep from
shedding too many jobs. The Santa Clara company laid off 830
workers in 1996, but it hired many of them back three months later,
when business picked up.
</P>
<P>
   Workers can use their time off for reflection that's often
impossible when they're working 12 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``My goal is to get enough of a break to make the right
decision,'' said Lance Groody, 38, who was director of programming
for Broderbund's Red Orb Entertainment division. Since the layoff,
``my phone has been ringing off the hook'' with job offers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Groody echoed many Broderbund workers' feeling that, since the
company was acquired in June by the Learning Co., he'd rather be
outside than inside. ``We're happier to be out looking for
something new than trying to rebuild in a different amalgamation,''
Groody said.
</P>
<P>
   Laid-off employees' upbeat attitudes reflect the new economy,
said Carl Weisiger, vice president in the San Francisco office of
Drake Beam Morin, an international career-transition-management
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``High tech has the mind-set that this is a new world of work,''
Weisiger said. ``You expect a certain amount of change _ mergers,
acquisitions, shifting of the business. You may not work for the
same company for a long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   With the changing climate, workers have changed, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming to us with a slightly different attitude
than they may have had'' in layoffs of bygone years, Weisiger said.
``They've already done their career management and networking. ...
People are able to redeploy and find new positions quickly. It's a
function of the market and of the differing attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the workers also hope their new opportunities let them
find a more stress-free lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   A man who goes by the name Mitra left the position of chief
networking technology officer at ParaGraph International when that
firm was bought by Silicon Graphics last year. Although he still
maintains a home in Fairfax, he considers himself a ``technomad''
and works as a consultant from wherever the spirit moves him _
England, India or, his latest home, Byron Bay, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always figured that there wasn't much point in working
your whole life to accumulate a large pile of money, and then keel
over from stress-related ailments,'' said Mitra, 38. ``I've lost
friends to cancer and heart attacks. ... My friends are all working
60 hours a week. People's relationships are under stress.
Stress-based systems are endemic in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to work as much to earn a happy living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
