<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS CALL THE HILL TO TAKE THE TEMPERATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-REPUBS-MONEY,
CLINTON-PRESS, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REPUBS-EXPAND.) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, have been
contacting members of Congress as they seek support and comfort
during the President's predicament, White House and Congressional
aides said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made many more telephone calls to Capitol Hill than
Mrs. Clinton has, aides said. So far, the conversations appear to
be aimed more at taking the temperature of allies, they said, than
at reaching out to members who might be wavering.
</P>
<P>
   The president has called Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader,
but he has not called Rep. Dick Gephardt, the minority leader, who
has recently tempered his initial criticism of Clinton, said a
person close to the Democratic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think he'd be on the phone with Gephardt at least once
in a while to say thank you if nothing else,'' this person said.
``But he hasn't been.'' One senior White House official said
Clinton had spoken to Gephardt on the telephone recently.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Mrs. Clinton has simply returned calls made to
her, said her spokeswoman, Marsha Berry. ``She has certainly talked
to some members, making the case that she's very proud of the
president,'' Ms. Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   The president has called a number of friends in the Senate,
congressional aides said, including Robert Torricelli of New Jersey
and Patrick Leahy of Vermont. One White House aide said that
Clinton was calling as many as four or five members of Congress a
day, including some Republicans but that the lawmakers were
generally keeping the conversations private.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Panetta, a former White House chief of staff, who has been
informally advising the White House in recent days, said the
president needed to convey two messages to members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Panetta said the president must assure them that he would not
cave in to the Republicans on Democratic goals for health care,
education, and Social Security. And second, he said, they need to
hear that the president is not ``just moping around'' but ``has a
sense that he cannot only survive this but he can survive it in a
way that gives him the ability to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met Thursday morning with the Congressional Black Caucus
and conveyed those messages by discussing their cherished issues,
including help for black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., who is on the House Judiciary
Committee, emerged from the session to declare, ``We think that
this administration is doing a good job dealing with the issues of
concern to this country in the middle of whatever is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has rebounded in recent days together with
Clinton's standing in the polls _ so much so that some Clinton
aides and associates are worried that the president and his party
might overplay their hand.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the president would go along with an agreement
that permitted him to escape impeachment with censure and some
other penalty, one Clinton associate said, ``I don't know, and the
more he sees these good numbers it's hard to know where he would
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed confident and determined Thursday in the Rose
Garden as he used a shouted question about whether he saw ``any way
out of an impeachment inquiry'' to present himself as preoccupied
with more elevated matters. Recent polls have shown public
impatience with the inquiry into Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right thing to do is for us all to focus on what's best
for the American people,'' he said. ``And the right thing for me to
do is what I'm doing. I'm working on leading our country and I'm
working on healing my family.''
</P>
<P>
   The president went on to call for ``progress over partisanship''
and ``people over politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way out,'' he said. ``The way out here, and the
only way out, is for people in Washington to do what the folks in
America want them to do.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an opinion article to be published in The New York Times on
Friday, four experienced Washington lawyers suggest a way out for
Clinton himself _ censure and a fine.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the writers, Lloyd Cutler and Abner Mikva, have served as
White House counsels under the president, and Cutler is informally
advising the White House in this scandal. One person close to the
writers, who insisted on anonymity, said they had acted
independently of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said they were anxious not to appear to be
trying to negotiate a deal, although they were quietly sounding out
members of Congress and others about how to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, in a conversation with Rep. James Moran, D-Va.,
argued that the president's mistakes did not warrant impeachment,
the Capitol Hill newspaper Roll Call reported Thursday. Moran
declined to comment on his conversations with Mrs. Clinton on
Thursday, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Moran, who has been a harsh critic of the president recently,
was clearly impressed, the newspaper reported. ``If anybody should
feel offended and treated badly, it's her, and yet she is standing
tall,'' he was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
