<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TSU needs a big game from Butterfield
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When Tennessee State and Florida A&AMP;M met on a hot and
humid early-September night in Tallahassee a little more than a
year ago, it appeared the Tigers' all-everything junior Tyrone
Butterfield would lead his team to its first victory over the
Rattlers since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield, a Miami native who had transferred from Michigan to
the Ohio Valley Conference school in Nashville, scored his second
touchdown of the game in the third period to put TSU up 28-15.
</P>
<P>
   But the heat and FAMU's size and depth zapped the Tigers, who
lost 45-28.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the somewhat friendly rivals meet here for the fifth
time, the third in the Atlanta Football Classic sponsored by 100
Black Men of Atlanta, at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee State is to succeed where it has failed seven
straight times against the Rattlers, they certainly will have to
apply the ``Butterfield factor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a big part of our offense ever since he's been
here,'' TSU third-year coach L.C. Cole said about the 5-9,
190-pound All-American candidate.''He's our all-purpose guy, and we
need him to come up big.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, coming up big seems to be Butterfield's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does he line up at wide receiver for the Tigers, but he
also returns kicks as well anybody in I-AA.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener against FAMU last year, Butterfield caught seven
passes for 140 yards and two TDs en route to receiving OVC honors
as co-offensive player of the year. In games against Middle
Tennessee State and Jackson State so far this season, he has 17
receptions for 253 yards (14.3 yards a catch). He also has averaged
28.9 yards on six kick returns. That puts him among the top five in
I-AA in both categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, he's one of the best receivers in the
country, regardless of classification,'' Rattlers coach Billy Joe
said of Butterfield. ``We're very much aware of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield often receives the attention of two opposing
defensive backs. After all, he was clocked at 4.2 seconds in the
40-yard dash before ballooning to 210 this past spring. He's now
back down to 190.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be a short guy, but he turns over fast,'' Cole said.
``People are running alongside of him, then all of a sudden he's
gone _ like a little rocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: FAMU, after a 21-14 loss to Hampton, has scored 129
points in its last two games, including the 84 on Norfolk State two
weeks ago. ... While Butterfield is fourth in I-AA in receptions
yards with 126.5 per game, FAMU sophomore wideout Jacquay Nunnally,
the MEAC Rookie of the Year in '97, leads I-AA with a 131-yard
average. ... In its two games, a 28-27 loss to Middle Tennessee and
a 33-21 win over Jackson State, TSU averaged of 37.5 pass attempts.
The Rattlers have put the ball up 43 times a game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
