<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wiley hopes to solve Tar Heels
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- To explain what his industrial engineering major is
all about, Georgia Tech running back Charles Wiley pointed to the
lobby of the Georgia Tech athletic building and the maze of glass
cases honoring Yellow Jacket teams over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of pedestrian traffic might be a problem an industrial
engineer is asked to solve, he explained. So is parking on Georgia
Tech's campus, although clearly on a much larger scale.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley never got to a third example, but he might as well have
started talking football.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring a way through North Carolina defenses in recent years
takes an industrious mind. Wiley and company haven't done it in the
past two meetings, but they take another stab at it Saturday night
in their ACC opener in Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are Wiley's major and position ideal for taking on the
task of the UNC defense, but so is his motivation. Wiley's last
trip to Kenan Stadium was the worst of his football life. He tore
an anterior cruciate ligament trying to tackle Dre Bly on an
interception return and missed the rest of the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to bring back some feelings when I get there,''
Wiley said. ``But I have to stay focused on the task at hand. It's
not like I have any bad feelings for Carolina because of that. But
I do want to perform well.''
</P>
<P>
   In last year's 16-13 loss to North Carolina in Atlanta, the
Yellow Jackets managed a meager 28 yards on 29 carries. That was
the lowest rushing total in a game by Georgia Tech since the Yellow
Jackets had five yards rushing against Florida State in 1994 _ Bill
Lewis' last game as Tech's coach.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's defensive personnel is not the same. Gone are
three NFL first-round draft picks, defensive linemen Greg Ellis and
Vonnie Holliday and linebacker Brian Simmons. Drafted along with
them were safety Omar Brown, linebacker Kivuusama Mays and
cornerback Robert Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But the scheme is the same. The Tar Heels rely on ``mugging
up,'' using linebackers to fill the running gaps, instead of
sagging five yards back and waiting for something to happen. They
use man-to-man coverage on the receivers and let everyone else take
care of the run as their primary responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   After the Tar Heels' defensive meltdown against Stanford on
Saturday, North Carolina coach Carl Torbush has entertained
thoughts of using more zone coverages, but the Yellow Jackets
aren't anticipating wholesale changes.
</P>
<P>
   They figure the Tar Heels will be waiting for the run, just like
Tech's first two opponents. And why not, with Tech first in the ACC
in rushing offense and 32nd nationally with 197.5 yards per game?
Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton will throw to his young receivers to
get the Carolina defenders to back out of the box, but the running
backs still will have their own points to prove, especially Wiley.
</P>
<P>
   He's been on a mission since last year's North Carolina game
when he was stopped short on a fourth-and-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised myself I'd never let that happen again,'' Wiley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
