<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-LPGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LPGA not up to par with counterparts
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The former centerpiece of women's professional golf
is venting as she leaves the 18th green, and it has nothing do with
the round she just shot, the autograph seekers she must navigate
through or her steady drop on the money list.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Nancy Lopez is upset because, for all the pie charts and
growth statistics that LPGA executives spin out, she knows it could
be better. Should be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way, but we're so far behind,'' Lopez said.
``It really bothers me. I thought at one time we were catching up,
and now it's like we've been left behind again.''
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA turned 48 this year. It has grown from a low-budget,
seven-event-a-year diversion to 42 tournaments totaling $32 million
in purses. Last year, Annika Sorenstam won more than $1 million.
All but nine events are on TV.
</P>
<P>
   That's the stuff for press releases. The downside is that most
tournaments are not carried by networks but are on cable or
regional television. Players on the tour barely have a pulse in
endorsement circles. LPGA purses remain far behind the PGA and, of
some embarrassment, have been surpassed by the Seniors Tour, which
wasn't created until 1980 _ 30 years after the LPGA.
</P>
<P>
   Debates on why the LPGA is lagging ultimately come around to
sex: how the players are marketed, how they are perceived by the
public, whether lesbianism remains an issue despite tour
executives' insistence that escalating purses prove otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA has no excuse for being second to a tour of retirees,
says veteran golfer Jan Stephenson, 46, even though the PGA Tour
helps fund the older players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Seniors,'' Stephenson said. ``But we have so much
more talent than them. We're younger, we have better personalities,
we have more competition, and we're playing for much less than they
are. You feel like you're treading water big-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson is the most outspoken critic of the LPGA's marketing.
She and Lopez were central to the tour's perceived boom time in the
late 1970s and '80s. They won tournaments, they were attractive,
and they were vehicles in cross-marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Former NHL executive Ray Volpe was hired as the tour's first
commissioner in 1975. ``When he came here, that's when I was in
magazines, laying on a bed with my skirt up (my thigh), doing all
that stuff to promote,'' Stephenson said. ``I would go to (New York
nightclub) Regine's with Donald (Trump), Nancy would go to a
baseball game, and suddenly there'd be a photographer there. That
stuff doesn't just happen. Marketing became non-existent.''
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA has gone through four commissioners since Volpe left in
1982. The latest is Jim Ritts, who was hired in the summer of 1995,
two weeks after CBS commentator Ben Wright was quoted as saying
lesbianism hurts the LPGA's marketing efforts. An excerpt: ``When
it gets to the corporate level, that's not going to fly. They're
going to a butch game, and that furthers the bad image of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1996, Muffin Spencer Devlin discussed in Sports
Illustrated her life as a lesbian on the tour. And one of the
tour's marquee stops, the Nabisco Dinah Shore in Rancho Mirage,
Calif., became widely recognized as a major social event on the
sports calendar for lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Some might have thought Ritts was jumping into a fire. But he
said Wright's verbal pratfall and Devlin's magazine story became
flashpoints that helped dissolved any myth of lesbianism as a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was more focus on us than at any other time, but we've
enjoyed our greatest growth in the last 2 1/2 years,'' he said.
``Nobody cared (about the lesbian issue), from a corporate or fan
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   In an educational video, ``Homophobia in Sports,'' former
basketball player and gay rights activist Mariah Nelson Burton says
the LPGA has an image consultant who travels with the tour to
advise players on hair, makeup and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   That person is Beverley Willey, who denies that she is there to
make the golfers look more feminine. She said she approached
officials in 1986 only after a customer in her salon, golfer Janet
Coles, complained that she couldn't get a good haircut on the road.
Willey travels to 20 events a year, carrying four large duffle bags
filled with cosmetics and styling equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Willey is a former image consultant, but she said, ``I'm just
trying to make their life easier. I'm not trying to change them to
glamour girls _ and I've never been asked to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As an image consultant, however, Willey said, ``There's
definitely a different perception of female athletes, and it's
totally unfair. Here I am talking to sponsors, using products, and
we don't have the support. We should have every female product
knocking down our door.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritts is trying to improve the tour's marketing. An ad agency
has created a series of TV and print spots. One commercial lists
Lopez's accomplishments, including ``giving birth three times,''
and challenges men to ``beat that record.'' Other spots focus on
the tour's stars and their accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   To Stephenson, Ritts is ``making a good effort,'' but she
maintains that the marketing ``has gone backwards in the last five
years.'' The tour's former sex symbol admits that she is unpopular
with many players for her postition on trying to maximize one's
looks for marketing effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like attractive people,'' she said. ``Why do you have
to make yourself look bad? Why is there this thing: `Our golf
speaks for itself.' People forget we're in the entertainment
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfredsson, who recently wrote a column saying people should
stop being so concerned with the players' sexuality, nonetheless
said, ``The worst thing is when you deny the stuff because it makes
it a bigger issue.''
</P>
<P>
   She also echoed Stephenson's comments on looks, saying, ``It's
part of being a woman. We like men, too. Why does everybody like
Freddy (Couples)? He's the best-looking guy out there. No one
really cares how he plays. You just like to see his bum.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
