<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Acquisition-Hungry BEA Systems Has Its Eyes on WebLogic   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Enterprise software-maker BEA Systems is taking a close look at
buying WebLogic, a privately held maker of application servers,
software industry sources say.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acquisition-minded BEA is a relatively young firm that is a
pioneer in the fast-growing business of developing ``middleware,''
which is software that can help different sizes and types of
computer operating systems talk to each other.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's WebLogic, on the other hand, is a startup
devoted to making application servers, software that acts as sort
of a traffic cop between personal computers and big mainframes or
server computers. Both mainframes and servers often store vast
amounts of important company data.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the two businesses under a single roof makes
some sense, analysts and investment bankers say, because it would
allow BEA to offer its customers the application server technology
they need to effectively tap into the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Software industry sources say BEA scheduled an internal meeting
yesterday with employees to discuss the potential impact of such a
deal. BEA Chief Financial Officer Steven Brown would not confirm
that his company was in negotiations to buy WebLogic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a number of acquisitions over the years, but we
don't comment'' on the companies that we have talked to, Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, BEA has been shopping for complementary businesses and
technology. Earlier this year, the middleware firm infused its war
chest with $240 million in cash after a successful debt offering.
</P>
<P>
   The cash has come in handy. In June, BEA bought Top End, the
middleware division of NCR Corp. for about $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that (BEA) is looking for acquisitions,'' says
software analyst James Moore of BT Alex. Brown in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   A potential buyout of WebLogic ``makes some sense because BEA
needs to expand its footprint,'' and ``I know that the Web
application-server business is important to BEA going forward,''
says Moore, who rates BEA shares a strong buy. BEA shares closed
yesterday at $24.50, down 69 cents.
</P>
<P>
   At that price, BEA doesn't look very cheap. The company's stock
is trading 68 times its forward-looking earnings estimates for this
fiscal year. Goldman Sachs took it public in April 1997 at $6 a
share and followed with a secondary offering at $17 just three
months later, according to Bloomberg L.P.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Without knowing the details of what a WebLogic buyout would
be, Moore notes that it would be difficult to speculate just what
impact such a deal would have on the stock. He says that BEA's
philosophy is to execute smaller deals that tend not to dilute
earnings per share. (After the Top End deal was announced in
mid-May, BEA stock dropped about $6 until the sale closed a month
later.)
</P>
<P>
   BEA's earnings have been solid. For its second quarter, the
company reported profits of 7 cents a share, after one-time
charges, which matched Wall Street consensus estimates. And it has
either met or beat the Street for the past six consecutive
quarters, Moore says. In addition, he raised his earnings estimates
for fiscal 1999 by about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, shareholders beware. Generally speaking, it's not
uncommon for shares of acquiring companies to suffer short-term
price dips after buying out other companies.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, analyst Thomas Berquist of Piper Jaffray in
Minneapolis suggests that some investors may react negatively to a
BEA buyout of WebLogic.
</P>
<P>
   While bullish on the stock with a buy recommendation and a
target of $30 a share, Berquist says some investors may react
negatively to such a deal because they are concerned that BEA is
having trouble growing organically _ without acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Berquist also points out that WebLogic isn't a perfect fit
because it may, in some ways, duplicate portions of the
application-server technology that BEA is already developing in
house. That said, he surmises that BEA is trying to jump-start its
application server business by buying a hot startup, which ``is a
way to get that market buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Fair Point: &LR;  A Union Bank of California spokeswoman took issue
with a declaration in Wednesday's column that First Security Corp.
would be the second-largest bank holding company in the West after
the NationsBank merger with BankAmerica closes. Her argument: Union
bank has assets of about $30.9 billion compared to First Security's
$19.4 billion. The rub is that First Security, which was the source
of the information, doesn't view Union Bank as based in the United
States. While Union Bank is headquartered in San Francisco, it is
80 percent owned by Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, which of course is
based in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
