<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DDN-SMOG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio given one year to reduce smog
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- Ohio, along with 21 other states and the
District of Columbia, have one year to come up with plans to
sharply reduce their airborne emissions of smog-producing nitrogen
oxide.
</P>
<P>
   Any plan will likely require coal-burning utilities in the
Midwest, including Dayton Power &AMP; Light, to add more costly
antipollution devices to their plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will definitely have a cost to it,'' said Jim Tomasiak,
managing director of DP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   Under regulations made final Thursday by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency, Ohio will have to make some of the most drastic
cuts in nitrogen oxide, or Nox, which combines with sunlight to
form ground-level smog. The U.S. EPA wants Ohio to reduce its
emissions by 43 percent. Ohio leads the nation in Nox emissions,
according to the Ohio Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups praised the new regulations as necessary to
protect public health, while many Midwest governors and industry
groups say they will lead to lost jobs and higher electric costs.
</P>
<P>
   Although DP&AMP;L favored a plan by Ohio Gov. George Voinovich that
was less stringent and allowed more time to implement, Tomasiak
said DP&AMP;L will work with Ohio in developing a plan to meet the new
regulations. DP&AMP;L, which serves about 500,000 customers in 24
counties in southwest Ohio, has two coal plants. Hutching Station
in Miamisburg, built before 1980, is the one most likely to be
upgraded or phased out, according to industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Local air quality officials support the U.S. EPA's strict stance
and urged other measures to control smog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a position to disagree with the EPA position at
all,'' said John Paul of the Regional Air Pollution Control Agency.
``But it has to be part of a total package. We can't ignore mobile
sources either, and the EPA should push ahead with low-sulfur in
gas and Tier II (lower-polluting) vehicles. Those are national
measures that can really have an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul said the Miami Valley had 19 days this summer when it
exceeded the nation's Clean Air Standard. The U.S. allows two
readings above the eight-hour, eight-parts-per-billion ozone
standard.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone or smog is a lung irritant that can aggravate illnesses
like asthma, especially in children, and bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant step toward cleaning our air,'' said
Kurt Waltzer of the Ohio Environmental Council. ``Cleaning up old
coal-burning power plants will improve our air quality and the
health of Ohioans.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol Browner called the tougher controls the
``centerpiece'' of the agency's efforts to cut smog. EPA believes
smog produced in the Midwest travels downwind and dirties the air
in Northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   The new requirements apply to Alabama, Connecticut, Delaware,
Georgia, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Maryland, Massachusetts,
Michigan, Missouri, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina,
Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, South Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia,
West Virginia and Wisconsin. Those states have 40 old, coal-burning
power plants, which until now have operated under less strict
regulations than newer plants. Ohio's required 43 percent cut is
second only to West Virginia's 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohio's smog affects Pennsylvania, but Indiana, Illinois and
Kentucky's air affects Ohio,'' said Paul. ``We've needed a
consistent national standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new regulations, states must have a plan ready by the
fall of 1999, institute controls by 2003 and meet the objectives by
2007. Browner said controls will cut 1.1 million tons, or 28
percent, of current levels of ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Browner said the new Nox regulations will allow 97 percent of
the country, including urban areas like Dayton, to meet Clean Air
standards by the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. EPA said it would give states ``maximum flexibility''
in meeting the Nox standard, but also pointed out that tougher
controls on power plants was the cheapest way to reduce emissions.
The agency noted that it would cost $1,500 to cut a ton of nitrogen
oxide from a coal-burning plant compared to $3,400 from automobile
tailpipes.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of how much of the cost will be passed on to consumers
differ. The U.S. EPA said the regulations would only add $1 a month
to electric bills, but an analysis prepared by Voinovich last year
indicated they could rise as much as 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When the rules were proposed last year, DP&AMP;L's Tomasiak said
they could produce significant changes in the way the company's
plants operate and on its future plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an unproven technology,'' he said. ``A lot of
engineering and research needs to be done. We will have to see what
the state does. The effect could be severe or something more
limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
