<HEADER>
A3320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-4     09-24 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REFUGEES TRAPPED BY TWO FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-NATO) 
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOBROSEVAC, Yugoslavia _ In the sullen silence of a makeshift
camp in the hills above the still smoldering villages of central
Kosovo, Fehmi Geshi, a 21-year-old student, stared blankly ahead
Thursday, barely able to comprehend that he is once again a
refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Thin and frail, dressed in a grubby turtleneck and slacks, Geshi
has fled repeatedly in the last six months, moving from one refuge
to another as he dodges Serbian authorities who are suspicious of
young Albanian males and avoids joining the guerrilla force seeking
Kosovo's independence.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, began his latest
armed offensive against the Kosovo Liberation Army on Tuesday,
Geshi fled with his uncle, who had been hiding him.
</P>
<P>
   Now Geshi, like the mothers rocking tiny babies in cradles in
the mud, is paralyzed with fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go to Pristina'' _ the capital of Kosovo _ ``because
they'll think I'm a member of the liberation army, and I can't go
home because there are Serbian police there,'' he said as he flung
open his one suitcase to show his precious textbooks and University
of Pristina registration card.
</P>
<P>
   Western aid workers estimate that as many as 10,000 civilians
were dislodged from their villages on Tuesday. Many are stranded in
the Cicavica hills, too scared to move but living in precarious
conditions with little food and only flimsy shelters fashioned from
trees, blankets and plastic for the cold nights.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Geshi, are refugees several times over.
</P>
<P>
   The new refugees add to the more than 200,000 ethnic Albanians
who the U. N. High Commissioner for Refugees says have been forced
from their homes in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   How to stop Milosevic from creating new refugees has become a
question for Western diplomats and NATO planners, who took another
step Thursday toward making good their threat of using military
force to stop what they see as a looming human crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the U.N.commission say they face a potentially
unmanageable situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think it is a statement of fact that at no time in the
Yugoslav conflict were so many people for such a sustained period
in such chronic insecurity,'' said Nicholas Morris, the director
for Bosnia, during a visit to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said many of the people being displaced by what looked
like a deliberate campaign of terror by the Serbs had nowhere to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We meet people who have been in the forests for three
months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Albanians say they are too frightened to go back to their
villages because of the Serbian police, who often knock on the
doors of families who dare to return home and take the men away for
questioning.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Milosevic appears intent on separating the Albanian civilian
population from the guerrillas. He is doing this by pummeling
villages where the Yugoslav National Army and the Serbian police
believe there may be either guerrillas or supporters of the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   He then seems to expect the civilians to be happy to return to
damaged villages surrounded by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week Milosevic has been on what one Western diplomat
called a ``charm offensive,'' insisting there are no refugees in
Kosovo. He sent the Serbian president, Milan Milutinovic, to Kosovo
on Wednesday, where Milutinovic called on ``the small number of
Albanians who have not yet returned to their homes'' to do so.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of the 2 million people in Kosovo are
Albanian; fewer than 10 percent are Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 Milosevic revoked the autonomy that Kosovo enjoyed
within Yugoslavia and made it part of Serbia. He wants to keep it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian guerrillas want independence, a goal that Western
countries do not support. Rather, Washington is trying to get both
sides to agree to a form of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Because Kosovo is not an independent country suffering from
external aggression, the West has found it hard to come up with a
formula for intervention. Further, Western diplomats say, Milosevic
is not aiming to clear Kosovo of the ethnic Albanians in a campaign
of ``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs can't occupy Kosovo and they know it,'' said a
Western diplomat. ``This is not like a town in Bosnia where they
killed Muslims and then moved in their own people.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Yugoslav Army general, Vuk Obradovic, who is now a
political opponent of Milosevic, said the president is trying to
humiliate the Kosovo Liberation Army by burning villages and
showing the Albanians that the guerrillas are unable to protect
them.
</P>
<P>
   If he wanted to, Milosevic could sweep Albanians out of Kosovo
in 24 hours, Obradovic said.
</P>
<P>
   A journey in the Cicavica hills Thursday showed that the
guerrillas, who have a camp a few miles from Dobrosevac and were
milling around in camouflage uniforms, are unable to do much for
the refugees just up the hill.
</P>
<P>
   But the men and women, their faces drawn after two long nights
in the open, said they were terrified of the Serbs and were defiant
about not going back to their villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are traumatized; we didn't leave for nothing,'' said
Kosovare, 20, who declined to give her last name for fear of
retribution. ``It's very cold here. The kids have been crying all
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Her extended family of 20 people includes six children under the
age of 18 months, she said. Some have scratches on their faces from
the brambles in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the kids are sick because of the first night of
cold,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A wood-burning stove pulled out of their kitchen and stashed on
the back of a tractor trailer provided a little warmth and a means
to make bread.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovare seemed aware of both the domestic and international
politics revolving around Kosovo. ``How can they call us
criminals?'' she asked. ``And when will NATO intervene? Are they
waiting for all the houses to burn?''
</P>
<P>
   Her family, she said, has no intention of going down the other
side of the hill to Slatina, a town where some of those who fled
their villages on Tuesday were heading on foot and by tractor
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs are there,'' she said. ``We have lost everything at
home. We will stay in the hills.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
