<HEADER>
A3321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-REECE-COX     09-24 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-REECE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sponsors struck with Reece's looks, not skills
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- At the end of a suddenly sand-covered Buckhead
street, lined with watering holes and nightspots that are
momentarily quiet, Gabrielle Reece pops out of a stretch limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when rush hour sets in, several hundred people will
mingle along the sidewalks to catch a glimpse of the part-time
athlete, full-time cover girl in a beach volleyball exhibition. But
now, a few hours before the match, the game already has begun.
There are autographs to sign. A half-hour taped TV gig and
interviews to do. Happy talk with sponsors to conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The song and dance,'' as she calls her routine in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I train for it really hard,'' confides Reece, 28, wearing a
tank top and snug-fitting blue-jean shorts, as she equates the song
and dance to an athletic competition. ``(It's) the thing that gives
me more notoriety and pays for my house. It comes down to taking
the stereotype of an attractive woman and just moving it, or using
that to get the foot in the door and then trying to do other
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, I never wear eye makeup in my regular life,''
says Reece, her cinnamon-brown skin sweating under the formidable
midafternoon sun. ``I put this on to go to TV this morning. It's
just a little conscious thing that I did because I'm trying to seem
appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Named by Elle magazine as one of the Five Most Beautiful Women
in the World, Reece has an engaging mind to go with a striking face
and a lithe build. Gabby, as she likes to be called, knows the
marketing game and has played it well. She's comfortable saying,
``I'm a babe for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Reece was rated the fourth-most appealing female athlete
product-endorser in a survey of 1,000 sports-marketing
decision-makers, ahead of far more accomplished athletes Picabo
Street, Steffi Graf, Lisa Leslie, Nancy Lopez and Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   She seems to embody what corporate America wants in women
endorsing its products. She's wholesome. She's married, to champion
big-wave surfer and ``all-around water guy'' Laird Hamilton. She
radiates equal doses athleticism and femininity.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing from the formula? Outstanding sports
achievements. Reece owns no Olympic medal. In fact, her event _ the
obscure four-woman beach volleyball, in which fewer skills are
required than the pairs variety _ is not part of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   She does belong to the Florida State Hall of Fame, and she's
twice been named top offensive player on the pro circuit. But the
women's pro league's December bankruptcy left Gabby to play Gabby
in appearances and promotional stops across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Reece is a 6-foot-3 symbol of the differences in how Madison
Avenue perceives male and female athletes. Guys may strike it big
on the endorsement circuit partly for good looks or a charming
personality. But before that happens, Michael Jordan wins an NBA
title and an MVP award, Troy Aikman collects a Super Bowl ring,
Andre Agassi wins Wimbledon. First, they accomplish something
significant on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   With Reece, credit sex appeal for attracting males to the
magazine covers and the endorsements. But that's just half it.
</P>
<P>
   She also enjoys a substantial female audience, which sees her as
a role model who is physically fit and financially set. She is
sometimes viewed as the modern woman, juggling careers while taking
care of her health.
</P>
<P>
   ``She appeals to many different age groups of women for many
different reasons,'' her agent, Jane Kachmer, said. ``Young girls
look to Gabby as someone who exemplifies a spirit that they are
living: `You can do what you want. It's cool to be in sports.' Then
she appeals to older women, based on the fan mail she gets, because
they look to her for a lot of fitness information. Or because they
see her speaking out on a lot of women's sports issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then this whole thing of breaking barriers, of allowing
women the ability to make a living in sports and have endorsements.
It's all new, and Gabby is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken aspect of her marketing success also applies to
soccer star Mia Hamm, figure skater Michelle Kwan, tennis standout
Martina Hingis and basketball all-stars Swoopes, Leslie and Rebecca
Lobo.
</P>
<P>
   All convey an image of heterosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate America doesn't try to market to gay demographics,
so I'm sure that weighs into their considerations,'' said Lobo, who
is pictured in Reebok ads and is a spokeswoman for Basketball
Barbie produced by Mattel. ``It might hurt a (lesbian's) chances
for endorsements. But you also have to look at the personality, the
way the person comes across. Their physical appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they want it written on your forehead that you're gay?
No.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Martina Navratilova. The greatest women's tennis
player ever has a single major endorsement, Rainbow Card _ a Visa
card marketed to the lesbian and gay community.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Williams, president of Chicago-based Burns Celebrity
Service, says lesbian athletes will continue to get the
advertisers' cold shoulder as long as much of society is hesitant
to accept their lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   And Gabrielle Reece will be welcomed with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   Her face stares out from the covers of such women's magazines as
Harper's Bazaar, Shape and Women's Sport &AMP; Fitness. She
occasionally crosses over to male-oriented publications, sharing
the cover of a recent issue of ESPN Magazine. Conde Nast Sports for
Women magazine pays her to write a fitness column. Nike introduced
her as its female Bo Jackson in a tongue-in-cheek commercial in
1993 and has since put out a series of cross-training shoes _ the
Air Zoom GR _ in her name. She has made as much as $35,000 for one
day's modeling work. She has endorsement deals with Coppertone and
Bally's fitness gym. And a book, ``Big Girl in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges that the timing couldn't be better for her.
Female athletes and their games are coming into vogue. Still, Reece
wouldn't be cashing in without the look _ ``models with muscles,''
as she and others are called in the marketing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to use the example of TV news, where the newsman can be
75 years old, but all we care is he knows what he's talking
about,'' Reece says. ``But if you get a woman who's 60 years old,
(people say,) `Oh, my God, look at the old bag. What is she doing
on there?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted, women are judged by their abilities as well, but
instinctively they're judged by their appearance. And the young
girls have often been taught that what they have to offer is how
attractive they are. Women do it to other women, so it's not just
men, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Reece wants you to know she fully grasps how the game is played
away from the sand. In her mind, she controls her own exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was modeling, I saw the weird curiosity around
fashion,'' says Reece, who studied marketing at Florida State but
never earned a degree. ``Here I was getting involved with a
professional sport. And people don't care that much, but they're
really intrigued with girls that are pretty. They want to interview
girls that are on magazine covers and ask them their opinion. Even
though, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `OK, I'll play that card if I have to _ first of all,
to support myself playing the sport, so I don't have to be a
teacher in the offseason. I don't think (the system) is right. But
if I didn't think I could represent myself and my sport
athletically on a high level, I wouldn't play the other part
because it wouldn't be funny. Then, it would be hypocritical.
Because I train hard, work hard and have delivered, then I'm
comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Segments of the beach volleyball fraternity resent Reece hogging
the limelight. Then again, she has brought the sport more exposure
than anyone else over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   She vows not to do anything to embarrass the sport: ``I play in
running tights, not a bikini.''
</P>
<P>
   Reece realizes that sponsors are attracted to her more for her
looks than her athletic feats. She looks forward to the day when
that won't be possible, when appearance becomes secondary to
swished jump shots, smashing forehands and kills at the volleyball
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the women competing and people sponsoring take care of it
and promote it slowly, women's sports will grow and become a
regular part of our culture,'' Reece says. ``But it's such a freak
show now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Reece is the star of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
