<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-BOWL-SEC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COTTON DEAL MAY MEAN DATE CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
C.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the Cotton Bowl has enhanced its matchmaking ability by
adding the Southeastern Conference, the 62-year-old bowl must face
the possibility of further change.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the Cotton Bowl announced it had agreed to a
four-year deal that will bring a Southeastern Conference team to
Dallas to play the Big 12 Conference host team starting this
season.
</P>
<P>
   However, the deal means the Cotton Bowl might have to alter its
Jan. 1 date or time.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 1 Citrus Bowl, which has the first selection of SEC
teams not playing in the Bowl Championship Series, has a contract
clause that prevents an SEC team from playing in another bowl with
a similar time slot. The Citrus kicks off at noon; the Cotton kicks
off at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than likely, we're going to have to move off the Citrus,
one way or the other,'' Cotton Bowl executive director Rick Baker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which airs the Cotton Bowl, is studying the feasibility of
moving the Cotton Bowl to Jan. 2. That would make it the only
afternoon bowl game on that Saturday, putting it up against NFL
playoff games on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton Bowl officials expect to have a decision on this year's
time or date within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the SEC should prove a boon to the Cotton
Bowl. In three years of its canceled deal with the Pacific-10 and
Western Athletic conferences, attendance had been below average.
</P>
<P>
   The Cotton, Outback and Peach bowls will select from a pool of
SEC teams. The teams could include an SEC division champion or a
division runner-up or teams with a record comparable to the team it
will face in the bowl that selects it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the flexibility to provide the best possible
matchups,'' said SEC commissioner Roy Kramer, who worked with Big
12 associate commissioner Donnie Duncan to make the deal happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous situation for us,'' Baker said. ``Most of
the time we're going to get an SEC West Division team. Having two
conferences like the Big 12 and the SEC should mean we get a
terrific matchup every year.''
</P>
<P>
   SEC West Division teams include Arkansas, Louisiana State,
Alabama, Auburn, Mississippi and Mississippi State.
</P>
</TEXT>
