<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EBAY-IPO-MARKETPLACE-     09-24 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-IPO-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: ATTIC-CLEANING ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now we know what it takes to shake Wall Street's IPO blues:
Beanie Babies and lots of them.
</P>
<P>
   In the first initial public offering in nearly a month, shares
of Ebay, an Internet auction house, jumped from the offering price
of $18 to close at $47.375.
</P>
<P>
   In an electronic variation on classified advertising, Ebay lets
people auction off whatever is in their attics or, for that matter,
their vaults. It has attracted a cult following among fans of
various collectibles, including the little bean-bag dolls. Indeed,
the 714,792 items for sale on the site Thursday included no fewer
than 35,608 Beanie Babies, some with prices as high as $400. The
inventory also included 2,979 autographed baseballs, 849 marbles
and 501 paperweights.
</P>
<P>
   Ebay charges sellers 25 cents to $2.50 to list their items, and
it collects a commission of between 1.25 percent and 5 percent on
completed sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their business model is great,'' said Mary Meeker, the
Internet stock analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. Ms. Meeker
took the unusual step of issuing a report recommending the shares
of Ebay, even though the stock underwriting was managed by Morgan's
arch-rival, Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meeker said she likes the company because it is attracting a
large and growing audience and sales volume while its costs are
low. Ebay even turns a small profit, a rarity among Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests that the company's market potential is huge, since
in the traditional markets, people spend $17 billion a year to buy
classified advertising, $80 billion in auctions and $103 billion on
collectibles. The Internet, she argued, makes matching buyer and
seller much easier than traditional markets do.
</P>
<P>
   What about the stock price, which values Ebay at $1.9 billion,
or 25 times Ms. Meeker's estimate of its 1999 revenues? (Never mind
that the price is 306 times her estimates of Ebay's 1999 profit.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Valuation is always an issue for Internet companies,'' she
said with some understatement. ``It's a great company with
extraordinary growth potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Internet bulls, however, are shying away from Ebay.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Basham, the investment officer of Standard &AMP; Poor's
small-capitalization stock service, rates Ebay a stock to avoid,
even though he recommended Geocities and Broadcast.com, two of the
summer's hottest Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Basham said he did not believe that Ebay would be able to grow
its revenue enough to justify the current valuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy the argument that margins on the Internet will be
much higher than any other business,'' he said. ``Over time,
competition will drive down margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Basham said that Ebay already had potent competitors
from search services like Yahoo and Excite, as well as from the
traditional players in classified advertising, newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great idea,'' he said. ``It's just that everyone can
have the same idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond classified advertising, the issue most on people's minds
in much of Silicon Valley is the initial public offering. And
investment bankers said the success of the Ebay offering would be
of little help in opening up the market for the dozens of other
companies that have been waiting to go public.
</P>
<P>
   Ebay, after all, is profitable, and it is for now the clear
leader in its category. Many other Internet companies waiting to
issue shares are neither. For example, TheGlobe.com and Xoom are
two ``community'' Internet services that have filed to go public on
the heels of Geocities, the No. 1 company of that sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IPO market is fairly closed,'' said Suzanne Richardson,
head of corporate finance for technology companies at Friedman
Billings &AMP; Ramsey. ``Just because one transaction is priced doesn't
mean you will see a flood of deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Standards have tightened for now, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those companies that are larger, have longer operating
histories and stronger backing will have access to the public
markets,'' Ms. Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   James Feulle, head of investment banking at Volpe Brown Whelan,
a San Francisco brokerage firm, said the fate of public offerings
was dependent on the overall market for small-capitalization
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the market is trending upward and every stock in investors'
portfolios starts to work, then they get more confident and will
take a little more risk,'' he said. Since most small-cap funds are
down for the year, investors are now especially cautious, he said,
adding, ``People get overly depressed in the dry periods and overly
excited in the good periods.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers might consider buying up those 35,608 Beanie
Babies and sending them out to cheer up the rest of the technology
investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
