</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-TRADE-CENTER-400&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORT AUTHORITY VOTE PUTS WORLD TRADE CENTER UP FOR LEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Port Authority board voted unanimously Thursday
to put the World Trade Center up for long-term lease, and several
major real estate figures have already expressed interest in
becoming the new landlord of one the world's most prominent
properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be interested,'' Donald Trump said. ``It depends on
the numbers, but at the right numbers, anything is feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   LCOR Inc., a Pennsylvania-based developer involved in the
privatization of another big Port Authority project, the new
International Arrivals Building at Kennedy International Airport,
said it would also take a serious look at the Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   The authority expects to request bids formally in the next 2
months for a 99-year lease on the 11-million-square-foot complex,
which includes the skyline-defining twin towers and four other
office buildings. The authority hopes to have a lease signed by
next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Authority commissioners have said they hope to get $1.5 billion
for the complex, with $300 million up front, but officials shied
away from hard numbers Thursday. Charles Gargano, the vice chairman
of the authority, would say only that he hoped to get ``as much as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading off a confrontation _ at least for the time being _ with
the administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Gargano, who is also
chairman of the Empire State Development Corp., said that whoever
leased the Trade Center would have to pay full property taxes. The
Giuliani administration says the complex should pay about $105
million in taxes, $80 million more than is now paid by the Port
Authority, which is tax exempt but pays a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki had said Wednesday only that the lessee would
have to pay ``fair taxes.'' The Port Authority would presumably
fetch a higher price for the property if it could get the city to
agree to a tax break for the lessee.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani insisted Thursday that, in private hands, the
complex would be taxed like any other building. Real estate
analysts said that at full taxation, the Trade Center was probably
worth closer to $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   With Gargano's assurance on the tax question in hand, Deputy
Mayor Randy Levine called the authority's decision to lease the
Trade Center ``a great victory for the city and for the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Authority officials were vague about their plans for any money
the lease would bring in above the more than $100 million a year in
net rental income the Trade Center generates now.
</P>
<P>
   The authority's chairman, Lewis Eisenberg, said that if there
was extra income, some of it could be used to pay off bonds. He
added, ``Whatever proceeds come will likely be spent on
transportation infrastructure and the economic development of the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   The authority has been under increasing pressure from the
governors who control it, Pataki and Gov. Christie Whitman of New
Jersey, to sell off its vast real estate holdings and concentrate
on transportation projects like dredging New York Harbor and
building a rail link to Kennedy Airport from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question now, however, is who will bid on the Trade
Center.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Trump, who is already in the midst of building and seeking
financing for the $3 billion Riverside South project on the Upper
West Side, said his interest in the Trade Center would depend in
part on ``what the economy is like at the time they put it up.'' He
declined to go into detail on how he might finance the project, but
John Lyons, the executive managing director of Granite Partners, a
national real estate investment banking firm, said that any
developer who wanted to take on the Trade Center would have to hook
up with ``a deep-pocketed entity that is looking at this primarily
as an investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Several real estate executives had said that Tishman Speyer
Properties, which runs Rockefeller Center, might be a likely
candidate, but the company said Thursday that it would not be
interested.
</P>
<P>
   For LCOR, the Trade Center is not an unfamiliar property: the
company, based in Berwyn, Pa., bid on an earlier attempt to
privatize the Trade Center's retail space, which was eventually
folded into the current plan.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives will give the proposal ``a very close look,''
said Frank Marino, a spokesman for the company. In addition to
holding a 40 percent interest in the Kennedy Airport terminal
project, LCOR drew up the master plan for the upcoming relocation
of Pennsylvania Station and developed the federal office building
at 290 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Gosin, the chief executive of Newmark &AMP; Company Real
Estate, said that a big real estate investment trust might also be
able to handle the project. But most REIT's have taken a beating in
the stock market recently, which would make it harder for them to
raise the money needed to acquire the Trade Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
