<HEADER>
A3338 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-MOMENTS-ROHATYN-$     09-24 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MOMENTS-ROHATYN-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PARIS, A WALL STREET VETERAN ARGUES THE CASE FOR LAISSEZ-FAIRE  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France has been governed by the Socialists for the
entire year that Felix Rohatyn has been the U.S. ambassador in
Paris. So Rohatyn, the former Lazard Freres partner who oversaw the
rescue of New York City from the brink of bankruptcy in the 1980s,
has spent a lot of time trying to explain American ``popular
capitalism'' to the French.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I mean is a highly advanced market system in a democratic
country, with large participation by the population in the
ownership of capital assets, coupled with an active and intelligent
government that provides an advanced social safety net and
sophisticated regulatory systems, in a law-abiding culture,''
Rohatyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that we have casino capitalism in the states, and no
social protection, is very widespread here. It has negative effects
not only on us but in terms of policies that might help the French
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who spent most of his adult life on Wall Street,
and who knows that up is not the only direction markets can move.
Back in July, he told a French audience that ``someday, markets are
likely to turn down, and popular capitalism will encounter some
difficult moments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, here we are,'' he laughed the other day in the
ambassador's residence, a palace with a back garden as big as
President Jacques Chirac's just down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Rohatyn and his wife, Elizabeth, prefer quiet dinners incognito
at unpretentious bistros like Quincy, near the Gare de Lyon, or
Chez Tante Louise, near the residence, to black-tie functions in
official surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never lost the feeling that somehow I don't belong, or
that if I belong it's only because of the intervention of fate,''
he reflected, as if at 70 he could somehow still be blacklisted by
French society.
</P>
<P>
   His life has taught him respect for adversity. He acquired his
perfect French as a boy at the Lycee Janson-de-Sailly in Paris from
1937 to 1940, after his family, all Polish Jews, came here from
Vienna to get away from the Nazis. They fled again in May 1940,
when the Germans invaded France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our driver tried to take my mother, her mother-in-law, our old
Polish cook and me across the border into Spain, but all the roads
were closed,'' he recalled. ``We decided we'd at least be better
off in the part of France that wasn't occupied by the Germans. When
we turned a corner in the woods we came to a German checkpoint, and
it didn't take much imagination to see what was probably going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fate did intervene. ``The German turned and lit up a cigarette
after waving through the car in front of us. My mother held her
driver's license up at the window, and he let us through without
checking our papers. I was 12 at the time. A year later they were
deporting people, including children, to Auschwitz from occupied
France.''
</P>
<P>
   The family eventually made its way to Casablanca and from there,
by boat, to the United States, where Rohatyn would later go into
finance and find success.
</P>
<P>
   But it is only recently that Rohatyn has felt able to revisit
the happier moments of his own past here and seek out a few former
classmates from his old school.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he looks at the world, he sees Washington preoccupied
with scandal and economies in grave trouble in Russia, Asia and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe President Clinton's call for a conference of foreign
ministers to review the current state of the financial system is a
welcome response to current concerns,'' he said, adding that it
``will offset the eroding confidence which is beginning to paralyze
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rohatyn now acknowledges that ``popular capitalism'' might not
be the right answer for every country at every stage of
development, and he thinks European countries will probably always
prefer a wider social safety net than Americans do. But he tells
visiting Americans to look at what the Socialist prime minister of
France, Lionel Jospin, has done toward privatization of state-owned
aviation, military and banking companies.
</P>
<P>
   The French and American business communities could learn a lot
more from each other if they had a forum for exchanging ideas, he
said, so he has started the French-American Business Council.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Rohatyn's activities gave him hundreds of close
contacts in French business and financial circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I first met a lot of these guys in the early 1980s, when
France was nationalizing companies and imposing credit controls,''
he said. ``There's been incredible change since.
</P>
<P>
   ``France is one of the major foreign investors in the United
States, with almost 350,000 Americans working for French companies,
and similar numbers for American investment in France,'' he said.
``Companies like Compagnie de Saint Gobain in glass and Danone in
food products have a big presence in the states. Here, you have
companies like IBM, Hewlett-Packard, Motorola, Procter &AMP; Gamble,
Coca-Cola _ but there was no forum for them to dialogue with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started talking last fall to a few people on both sides _
Dana Mead, chairman of Tenneco; George David at United Technologies
Corp., Jean-Louis Beffa at Saint Gobain, Antoine Riboud at Danone,
and others. And last June, when Jospin went to Washington on a
working visit, he and President Clinton attended the first meeting
of the council in the Executive Office Building, with about 50 CEOs
in attendance.''
</P>
<P>
   On that occasion, Jospin said he and others in France had
underestimated the ability of the low-tax, free-market American
economy to produce hundreds of thousands of permanent high-paying
jobs _ instead of just the low-paying, fast-food jobs that so many
intellectuals here had derided whenever anyone suggested that
France should follow America's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Crushing welfare-state tax burdens and labor regulations are
often blamed for France's failure to reduce unemployment, which is
at 11.8 percent after years of economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Rohatyn, whose business background often makes him chafe at
governmental inertia, looks for ways in which an ambassador can
make a difference. His latest tilt at the bureaucratic windmills is
an effort to increase the official American presence in the French
regions outside the capital, where most American assets are today.
</P>
<P>
   His plan calls for setting up simple ``American presence
posts,'' a sort of miniature consulate with a staff of two or three
people. The first is expected to open shortly in Lyons; Rohatyn
hopes to add others in Lille, Toulouse, Bordeaux and Rennes.
</P>
<P>
   That would be satisfying, but not quite like arranging a
billion-dollar leveraged buyout. ``I don't yearn to be back making
deals, but what I used to do always had a beginning, a middle and
an end,'' he said. ``This is more like a continuum. It's never
clear when you've actually accomplished something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
