<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-NYT &LR;      09-24 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE GAMES IN ATLANTA HOLD METS' PLAYOFF FATE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After six months and 159 games, the Mets' soap opera of a season
now comes down to three days in Atlanta. It is there, beginning
Friday night, that they will have to try and beat the best team in
the National League perhaps once, or twice, or maybe three straight
times in order to capture the National League wild-card race
outright or simply stay alive for a one- or two-game playoff on
Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That it has come to this for the 1998 Mets seems appropriate.
This is a team that has put together a decent 88-71 record but
seems to always avoid the easy route. With a chance to open up a
commanding lead in the wild-card race in recent days, they managed
to lose three out of five games at home to the Florida Marlins and
the Montreal Expos, two teams that are a combined 86 games under
.500. And yet every time the Mets have come up short this season _
with the bullpen blowing ninth-inning leads, with the offense doing
nothing for a week at a time _ they have managed to rebound, often
against good teams.
</P>
<P>
   So who knows whether the Mets will be in Houston next Wednesday
to begin the first round of the National League playoffs or will be
dispersed in two dozen directions, lamenting lost opportunities
that kept them from getting back to the post-season for the first
time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to happen, but no matter what does,
it's not going to surprise me, the way our season's gone,'' Mike
Piazza said after the Mets lost consecutive games to the Expos on
Tuesday and Wednesday and managed to go 17 straight innings without
scoring a run.
</P>
<P>
   In their three games against the Braves, the perennial National
League East champions and the winners of 103 games this season, the
Mets will look to the starting pitchers Rick Reed, Al Leiter and
Armando Reynoso. They will face the rookie left-hander Bruce Chen
Friday night, but Saturday and Sunday go up against two of the best
pitchers in baseball _ Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an easy task for the Mets, who all the while will be
keeping one eye on the scoreboard to keep abreast of how the
Chicago Cubs and San Francisco Giants are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if somebody said at the beginning of the year we would be
tied for the wild card with three days left in the season, I think
we would have taken it,'' said Brian McRae as he sat with Tony
Phillips in a somber, but not devastated, Mets clubhouse after
Wednesday night's loss. ``We're going to end up playing Monday,''
he added in what amounted to a prediction of a wild-card playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crying shame that we play all those games and it comes
down to the last three,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't,'' responded McRae, mindful that the Mets
won plenty of games they should have lost this season and lost just
as many they should have won.
</P>
<P>
   As for facing the Braves _ who will apparently not have Glavine
or Maddux on a pitch count even with the post-season looming _
Phillips said, ``Do I have a choice? But I'd rather play them than
Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the Mets dropped 8 of 12 games to the Expos
this season, Phillips' reasoning is understandable. But the Braves
will have incentive to play hard this weekend. By knocking the Mets
out of the wild-card race, the Braves would play either the Cubs or
Giants in the first round of the playoffs, instead of the San Diego
Padres, a strong first-place team. If the Mets were to be the
wild-card team, the Braves wouldn't play them in the first round
because both teams are in the same division.
</P>
<P>
   There are other incentives for the Braves. Glavine is trying to
bolster his Cy Young candidacy. Maddux is trying to put a recent
slump behind him. And the Braves, like the Expos, are viewed as a
team that doesn't like Mets Manager Bobby Valentine's
self-confident style and enjoys beating him.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won their first five meetings with the Mets this
season, including a three-game sweep at Turner Field before the
All-Star Game break, a series that concluded with the Mets
exploding in fury after the Braves were awarded an 11-inning
victory on a controversial call at home plate. But three weeks ago,
the Mets took three of four from the Braves at Shea Stadium, with
two of the victories coming on dramatic eighth-inning home runs,
first by Phillips and then by Edgardo Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play the way we did against them that last series, we'll
be up for the challenge,'' pitcher John Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Mets play the way they did against the Expos and
Marlins, they will be finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two days, we had a three-run lead and then got only
one hit after the first inning,'' Franco said. ``And then we had
three hits on Wednesday, and Bobby Jones had one of them. It kind
of makes you scratch your head. Who knows? Maybe we're saving our
hits for Atlanta.''
</P>
</TEXT>
