<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- AIDS-LEGISLATION, 9-24 --
Advocates for people with AIDS protesting the New York
Legislature's passage of a new HIV partner notification law in July
in front of Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver's office near City
Hall. Reflecting a growing frustration and fear about AIDS,
legislators around the country are passing an increasing number of
laws intended to protect the public. (J. Emilio Flores/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- CLINTON-ASSESS, 9-24 --
Many foreign observers fear that the Lewinsky scandal has impaired
President Clinton's ability to deal with foreign policy problems.
He chats with Prime Minister Tony Blair at New York University on
Monday. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) AVERY ISLAND, La. -- Sept. 24, 1998 --
CAJUN-WILDLIFE-HNS, 9-24 -- Within the 200-acre Jungle Gardens on
Avery Island in southwest Louisiana, egrets and other water birds
nest on specially built structures in a pond nicknamed ``Bird
City.'' With its diverse habitats and mild winters, southwest
Louisiana brims with natural wonders, both flora and fauna. (Harry
Shattuck/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LAFAYETTE, La. -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- CAJUN-LAND-HNS, 9-24
-- Acadian craftsmanship is frequently on display in Lafayette.
David Wortman of Acadian Village operates a studio and showroom
open to the public on a working rice farm in the heart of Cajun
country. (Harry Shattuck/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LAFAYETTE, La. -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- CAJUN-DINING-HNS,
9-24 -- Mark Allemond, 11, displays a platter of crawfish served at
McGee's Landing. The restaurant is situated on stilts over the
Atchafalaya Basin, where tons of crawfish and other Cajun seafood
favorites are caught each year. (Syd Kearney/Houston Chronicle
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) VILLERS COTTERETS, France -- Sept. 24, 1998 --
VETERAN-WOMAN-OLDEST-SPI-2-B&AMP;W, 9-24 -- Laura Frost Smith with an
ambulance corp in Villers Cotterets. At 105, she is believed to be
the oldest living American veteran of World War I. She served as a
nurse near the front lines for several awful months in 1918 -
months that would affect the rest of her life and extend its effect
to her children and grandchildren. (Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SEATTLE -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- VETERAN-WOMAN-OLDEST-SPI-1,
9-24 -- At 105, Laura Frost Smith travels easily in her mind to
1918 and the Western Front, a war zone that separated her from her
youth. Today she is one of the oldest known living American
veterans of World War I, a war that marked the first time women
officially served in the U.S. military. (Barry Gutierrez/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 24, 1998 --
CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS, 9-24 -- Karen Ward-Kaplan and her husband,
Elliot Kaplan with their daughter, Jess Avery. When she was born,
toy-buying was kept to a minimum. Now 7-months-old, Jess' favorite
toy was invented by her grandpa: wadded-up newspaper. ``She drops
it on the floor, slings it around, crinkles and uncrinkles it. It's
great for noise and texture,'' says Mrs. Ward-Kaplan, who wisely
lets her daughter lead the way in how they play. (Suzanne
Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CAMRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- CEREAL-NUT-BOS, 9-24
-- For a decade now, Scott Bruce - the man who says he gave us the
word ``cerealectibles'' - has dedicated his professional life to
vintage cereal boxes and prizes. He even admits to eating cereal
himself, although not for breakfast. ``My favorite nightcap is
Grape-Nut Flakes, though they're unpalatable before 10 p.m.,'' he
muses. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS, 9-24 --
Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, during
a Thursday press conference; a newly unveiled portrait mirrors him
from behind. Seeking to repair political missteps, Hyde says it is
he, not Speaker Newt Gingrich, who would preside over any
impeachment deliberations, and Hyde denies that Republicans are
seeking to broaden the inquiry beyond Monica Lewinsky. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- BASEBALL-BONDING, 9-24 --
By the numbers: Who knows, maybe 11 will snag a fly during a warmup
at Yankee Stadium. How young is too young to take a child to the
ballgame? Some say start 'em early. Others say wait 'til they
attain an attention span. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- THEATER-NOTES, 9-24 --
Everett Quinton, a co-star in Charles Ludlam's ``Mystery of Irma
Vep.'' As half of a two-man cast in the revival of play, Quinton is
responsible for the quicksilver antics of four characters, all of
whom nearly meet themselves at various points. Two of his
characters actually struggle with each other during the second act.
``I've figured out something beautiful about the play: it just
doesn't add up,'' says Quinton, 46. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- MEDEA-THEATER-REVIEW, 9-24
-- Karyofyllia Karabeti as Medea and Kostas Triantafyllopoulos as
Creon in the National Theater of Greece production of ``Medea.''
Although it is performed in modern Greek with English supertitles,
is populated by characters from Corinth and Athens, and is directed
by Niketi Kontouri, the play's look and feel suggest an art film
from Scandinavia. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
FELICITY-TV, 9-24 -- Keri Russell and her co-stars from the WB's
``Felicity'' on a feature-film-style billboard. ``In a 70-channel
universe, your own on-air reach isn't enough to bring in new
viewers; we have to use alternative media,'' says Garth Ancier, who
is the WB's president for programming. He and a marketing staff
have redefined the term ``alternative media'' to mean anywhere your
gaze might land outside of your television set. (William Lopez/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
PLACIDO-DOMINGO-MUSIC, 9-24 -- Placido Domingo is a singer,
conductor, opera-company director and restaurant owner. Monday
night the 57-year-old tenor will celebrate the 30th anniversary of
his Metropolitan Opera debut by singing Samson in the production of
Saint-Saens' opera introduced last season. It will be televised
almost live (with a one-hour taped delay), starting at 8 p.m. on
PBS. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. -- Sept. 24, 1998 -- CLINTON-RABBI, 9-23
-- Chaim Stern, senior rabbi of Temple Beth El in Chappaqua.
Earlier this month, President Clinton read to a group of clergy
members an extensive passage from ``Gates of Repentance,'' the Holy
Days prayer book edited by Stern, as a description of the path to
contrition he planned to take following his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky. ``You can't very well be coy and pretend that it's
not going on,'' says Stern, 68, of the president's current
troubles. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
