<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-AFTERMATH-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON NOVA SCOTIA'S SHORE, WILL SADNESS BE FOREVER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ Perhaps it is the endlessly swelling
sea with its lacy waves that lend this place its timelessness. Or
the granite boulders, shoved to the edge of cliffs by a retreating
glacier 10,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The knickknacks for sale in the Sou'Wester restaurant's gift
shop may seem like intrusions, but the lopsided fishing shacks
along the cove still sparkle with the silver of freshly caught
mackerel, and the lobster traps piled up outside the cedar-shingled
houses are there not for decoration but for making a living.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of life traditionally followed by the 60 residents
of Peggy's Cove was shattered on a clear night at the beginning of
the month when a huge jet tumbled out of the sky and slammed into
the Atlantic with enough force to make earthquake detector
instruments quiver.
</P>
<P>
   The fishermen here were among the first to head out into the
night, choking on the noxious fumes of jet fuel in a vain search
for survivors. All 229 aboard were lost to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   People here, and in the tiny villages along the old coast near
here, will always remember those anxious, terrifying and deeply
saddening first days after the crash of Swissair Flight 111 on
Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   But the hordes of reporters and satellite trucks are gone now,
the tourist buses have come back, the fishermen have gone back to
their boats, and Grace Manuel has hung out the wash to billow in
the sea breeze behind her house.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy's Cove is returning to some kind of normalcy, some echo of
the timeless routine of the past. And now, what everyone wants to
know is if it can ever be the same again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well yes and no,'' said Mrs. Manuel, 63, who has never lived
anywhere but Peggy's Cove. She said that when she and a friend
walked down to the post office in the lighthouse to get their mail
for the first time since the crash, her friend found it too
depressing.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had talked to people from out of town who said they
had been thinking about coming to see the cove's famous
red-and-white lighthouse but changed their minds because they said
it wouldn't feel right.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I get my garbage picked up and I went square dancing three
days this week,'' she said the other day. ``Life goes back to
normal.''
</P>
<P>
   People who live by the sea know disaster in an intimate way that
landlubbers can only try to understand. Every fisherman who goes
out on the water, except for the most foolhardy, never loses
respect for the fury of nature, and never stops wondering whether,
when the shore slips out of view, he will ever see it again.
</P>
<P>
   Local people have had more than their share of hauling bodies
from the sea. There have been more than 5,000 shipwrecks off Nova
Scotia, and a cemetery in Halifax holds the graves of 150 victims
of the Titanic whose bodies were brought ashore in 1912 and never
left again for home.
</P>
<P>
   Seagoers are great monument builders; converting a memory into
something as concrete, and as resistant to time, as a monument is
at least one way of compensating for their helplessness before
nature.
</P>
<P>
   In Peggy's Cove, which some say took the name of a lone survivor
of a shipwreck, the face of a gigantic granite boulder has been
carved into a memorial to the village fishermen lost to the sea
over the years. The old lighthouse itself, converted into a post
office in summertime, is a memorial to the countless mariners who
have been guided by its beacon.
</P>
<P>
   And now it seems likely there will be another memorial, this
time to the people aboard the flight who died within sight of
Peggy's Cove without ever knowing it was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I never knew you, I shed tears for you,'' says a card
attached to a bouquet of red carnations and blue wildflowers
placed, along with many others, at the base of the lighthouse.
Flowers sprout from the cracks of the smooth rocks all around. In
one nook formed one boulder leaning against another, someone has
placed a wreath of roses with red-and-white ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   People in Peggy's Cove are now wrestling with the question of
where to put the permanent memorial they are sure will come. Some,
like John Beale, a shop owner, think that putting it by the
lighthouse would be ``the death of tourism'' in the cove and that
the local church would be more appropriate. Those like Roger
Crooks, descendant of one of the early families, say that if the
relatives of the victims want it there, that's where it should go.
</P>
<P>
   But Crooks has avoided going down by the rocks himself. ``It
just tears at your heart because something like that happened near
your home,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Crooks and his wife, Sheila, operate a bed and breakfast and a
gift shop in the village. He is also a lobsterman during the
season, going out on his 35-foot red lobster boat that bears the
striking name Reverence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people remark about it,'' Crooks said, ``but it's
something that we need a lot more of.''
</P>
<P>
   The disaster that unfolded east of Peggy's Cove is already
providing reverence to the people who pour out of the tour buses.
They stand on the rocks and peer out toward the flotilla of gray
Canadian and U.S. Navy ships searching for the remains of the jet,
and the victims. Snippets of their conversation catch on the salty
air, and words like ``horrible'' and ``sad'' linger long enough to
be picked up by others.
</P>
<P>
   When the family of one of the victims appeared, accompanied by
Constable Brad Reid of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police, everyone
watched, from a respectful distance. With slumped shoulders the
relatives tossed carnations into the water and stared as they
caught the current and floated out toward the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists watched as one member of the family scampered down
the slippery rocks to fill a plastic bottle with water to bring
home as a memorial. They watched as the mother who lost her son
embraced Reid and told him to thank everyone from Peggy's Cove for
all they had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``She also told me, personally and for everybody I have contact
with, to savor every moment we have,'' Reid said afterward. A
resident of nearby Tantallon, he has been at Peggy's Cove almost
continuously since shortly after the jet crashed. He believes the
cove has been changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between now and next spring, things will weigh heavy on the
hearts of the people here,'' he said. ``Come next September, family
and friends of the victims will gather here for a memorial service,
and it will be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the reporters and the camera crews, the local people,
who put up with bitter winters to be here during the glorious
mornings of summer, are wandering back, too.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Moore of Tantallon brought her young grandchildren Emily,
6, and Ben, 8, so she could try to explain why people would come
from so far away to put flowers at the base of a lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because people died near here,'' Mrs. Moore told Emily,
who screwed up her face in doubt, probably because Peggy's Cove
still seemed so quaint, so peaceful. Ben spied a wet teddy bear
that had been left among the flowers and asked whether it belonged
to somebody who died on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very moving, and very sad,'' Mrs. Moore said. She
climbed up toward the small door that leads into the lighthouse,
passing a brass plaque that provides the constant warning, now
swollen with meaning, that ``the ocean and rocks are treacherous.''
</P>
<P>
   She doubts the cove has really changed. Like many others who
have lived on the coast of Nova Scotia for a long time, she has
come to realize that the area's rugged splendor and recurring
tragedy are hopelessly entangled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peggy's Cove will not only be remembered for its beauty,''
Mrs. Moore said, ``but for this disaster, for a long time to
come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
