<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SIGN STORR TO THREE-YEAR DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings signed Jamie Storr to
a three-year contract Thursday, solidifying their goaltending and
reducing to one their number of unsigned players.
</P>
<P>
   Storr, 22, the seventh player chosen in the 1994 NHL draft,
signed a contract believed to be worth about $1 million this season
and a little more than $3 million over its term. He earned $550,000
last season, in which he posted a 9-5-1 record with a 2.22
goals-against average and his first two NHL shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long negotiation on both sides,'' said Storr, who
practiced earlier this week with the Long Beach Ice Dogs, the
Kings' IHL affiliate. ``(The contract) is something we're both
happy with. The way (General Manager Dave Taylor) treated us was
nothing but the best. I'm happy I can start playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to prove to the NHL that I can play, be a regular
goalie in the league and not just a backup (to starter Stephane
Fiset),'' Storr said. ``I know I have to do it with hard work and
dedication. That's what I'm looking forward to doing.''
</P>
<P>
   With Storr agreeing to terms, the only missing King is
defenseman Aki Berg, who is playing in his native Finland. A source
close to Berg reported no progress in negotiations as of Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   On the spot (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with tonight's exhibition game at the Forum against
Phoenix, the two weeks leading to the start of the season may be
vital to 21-year-old center Donald MacLean's future with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, MacLean made the roster and scored five goals early
in the season, but was sent to Fredericton in the AHL when his
consistency lagged. The lack of a consistent effort, which MacLean
acknowledges, has continued in training camp, with MacLean making
just one preseason appearance thus far (he scored a goal against
Colorado).
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson spoke with MacLean following practice
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a tendency to have ups and downs,'' Robinson said. ``I
told him, `You can't afford to have one good game, one bad game.
You've got to be solid, game in, game out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   MacLean said, ``Ever since I've been ankle high, I've had a
consistency problem. I'm getting better. I still have a way to go
to play at this level. I'm going to try to put 14 days of hard work
together. I want to be here. I want to be known as a consistent
player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
