<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARKETS DECLINE AS FEARS OF ADDITIONAL LOSSES GROW
</P>
<P>
   The $3.5 billion rescue of a large investment fund verging on
collapse unnerved many markets around the world, raised a clamor
for a government investigation and created fear that other losses
might surface.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than contain the problem and bring stability, the cash
infusion late Wednesday by a consortium of banks and brokerage
firms to salvage Long-Term Capital Management only seemed to rattle
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss bank UBS said it expected to report a third-quarter
loss as high as one billion Swiss francs _ $721 million _ related
to losses in emerging markets, equities and the near-collapse of
Long-Term Capital Management. Its charge for an equity stake in and
derivatives transactions with Long-Term Capital Management was
estimated at $685 million.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA WARNS OF A FURTHER DEFAULT
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Shokhin, Russia's deputy prime minister of financial
affairs, took a harsh line with the International Monetary Fund and
other creditors, warning them of a potential default on its
long-term debt if more Western aid is not delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers won a court order freezing the British bank
accounts of two big Russian banks. It contends the two banks
defaulted on $110 million of obligations to it and its clients.
Other foreign creditors are scrambling to recover whatever they can
from their Russian holdings.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF AN INTERNET IPO SURGE
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Ebay, an Internet auction house, closed at $47.375
Thursday, after climbing $29.375 from its offering price. The first
initial public offering in nearly a month was priced at $18, opened
around 12:15 p.m. at $52, but fell later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMIC DATA SHOW STRONG GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   Two government reports indicated that the nation's economy
remains strong. Gross domestic product grew at a 1.8 percent annual
rate in the second quarter _ from the 1.6 percent estimated a month
ago, but still well below the growth rate of 5.5 percent in the
first quarter. In another report, orders for durable goods jumped
1.6 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   INCOME HIGHER FOR MOST AMERICANS
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau said the proportion of Americans living in
poverty declined last year, mostly because of reductions in poverty
among black and Hispanic families. The data reflected three
consecutive years of growth in income, which have restored
household incomes and poverty to the levels recorded in 1989, just
before the last recession.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK UNDER `H' FOR HOSTILE BID
</P>
<P>
   Day Runner, a manufacturer of personal organizers, made an
unsolicited 47.9 million pounds, or $80.5 million, bid for Filofax,
maker of the leatherbound diary that became a 1980s accessory, but
has since lost ground to electronic organizers.
</P>
<P>
   TV NETWORKS FAULTED ON LABELS
</P>
<P>
   One year after the television networks revised their movie-style
ratings code to add labels alerting parents to sexual or violent
content, a study has found that the networks are not regularly
adding those labels, like V for violence or S for sexual content,
to the ratings in printed listings and on screen.
</P>
<P>
   PROFITS OFF AT LUXURY GOODS MAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Falling profits were reported by LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis
Vuitton, the Gucci Group and Diageo, Europe's leading producers of
luxury fashion goods. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
