u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STORM-GEORGES-HNS &LR;      09-24 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-GEORGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY GEORGES TAKES AIM AT FLORIDA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ Residents sought high ground as Hurricane Georges
raked Cuba and began to buffet the Florida Keys late Thursday on
its slow, deadly romp across the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Communities along both the east and west coasts of Southern
Florida boarded up in advance of the storm's lumbering progress.
Businesses and schools closed and emergency preparedness officials
spread hurricane warnings to 4 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   More than 650,000 people were asked to evacuate flood-prone
areas along the Atlantic Coast as far north as Fort Lauderdale, and
along the Gulf Coast up to the Tampa Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   With winds of 85 mph, Georges was barely at hurricane strength.
But forecasters expected it to intensify to a Category 2 hurricane,
with winds between 96 mph and 110 mph, as it moved northwest across
the warm Florida Straits at about 14 mph. Forecasters said the
storm could build to 125 mph by Sunday in the northern Gulf of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 people have been killed in the Caribbean since the
storm began its devastating sweep last weekend. Widespread
flooding, mudslides and high winds flattened thousands of homes and
destroyed crops on several islands.
</P>
<P>
   During a 24-hour period Thursday, the storm dumped nearly a foot
of rain across eastern Cuba, where officials evacuated 500,000
people, including thousands of tourists from resorts along the
northern coast.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, hurricane preparations moved into high gear at dawn
Thursday. Authorities ordered the mandatory evacuation of mobile
home dwellers and urged those living in low-lying areas to leave
because of the danger of flooding.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami-Dade County, where people still recount Hurricane
Andrew's 1992 devastation in chilling detail, local government
officials warned that up to 12 inches of rain from the outer edge
of the storm could threaten low-lying areas like Homestead.
</P>
<P>
   That community, south of Miami, was hard hit by Andrew, and many
residents chose public shelters rather than risk even a minor
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Penelas, the mayor of Miami-Dade County, issued a special
appeal for the 13,000 people living on islands in Biscayne Bay,
between Miami Beach and the mainland, to get away.
</P>
<P>
   The islands are studded with multimillion-dollar homes belonging
to celebrities such as Cuban-American singer Gloria Estefan and
talk show host Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be cautious, but at the same time, respectful
of our citizenry,'' Pinelas said. Referring to Andrew, he said, ``I
do not want people in this community, again, to be lulled into a
false sense of security.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the western coastline, Collier County officials ordered
the mandatory evacuation of low-lying areas in Naples, as well as
Marco Island and the Isle of Capri. A steady line of traffic was
heading north before sunset from Marco Island, a resort community
with miles of recently-built high-rise condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Griffes, a commercial banking representative, had made
hotel reservations inland Monday. He nodded at the water that
lapped against his Isle of Capri back yard. ``We're only two feet
above water here,'' he said. ``Where's it gonna go if it comes in
on a surge?''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kerwin, an employee at a Naples tire dealer, said he had
taken the cautious approach and boarded up his home Tuesday. ``This
storm is one we're taking seriously,'' said store manager Howard
Hoffman. ``We've had a lot of time to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a shelter at Naples' Barron Collier High School, Nancy
Marshall was celebrating her 72nd birthday with her husband, her
son, a cake _ and a roomful of nervous strangers also fleeing the
storm's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the oxygen line clipped to her nose, she said she
could not risk her home losing power during the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Officials ordered the 80,000 residents of the Florida Keys to
leave the 100-mile long island chain Wednesday. But many stayed
behind, Key West police said, despite a curfew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people who have stayed behind (in the Keys), you are
taking a tremendous risk. We urge you to take this last opportunity
to evacuate,'' National Hurricane Center director Jerry Jarrell
said Thursday. Estimates of how many Keys dwellers had left varied
between 50 percent and 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Atlantic Coast, NASA canceled its plans to move the
shuttle Discovery from its seaside launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-story spacecraft would have been unprotected from
lightning strikes throughout the six to eight-hour move to a
hangar, so managers decided it would be safer to leave it within a
protective cover on the pad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
