<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0502 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDGEFUND-REACT-NYT &LR;      09-24 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGE COMPANY'S FALL RAISES QUESTIONS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Iowa, N.Y.)  (See also HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT, HEDGEFUND-TEAM, HEDGEFUND-RISK.) 
(af) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration played down Thursday the
potential risks to the financial system from Long-Term Capital
Management LP's brush with collapse, but the fund's fall raised
questions in Congress about whether regulators can keep up with the
increasing complexity and speed of the markets.
</P>
<P>
   A day after helping big banks and investment firms work out a
rescue package that will give Long-Term Capital some time to deal
with its financial problems, the Federal Reserve emphasized that it
had not put any taxpayer money into the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Fed officials said, the deal calls for Long-Term
Capital's owners to suffer potentially substantial losses from
their investment strategies gone wrong. As a result, they said, the
deal was not a bailout and should not be seen by investors as a
sign that the government was willing to protect investors from
their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at a time of instability in markets worldwide, the
episode was seen by some members of Congress and economists as a
new application of the ``too big to fail'' doctrine, under which
regulators take steps to keep institutions afloat because allowing
them to collapse would drag down other firms and endanger the
entire financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear that Long-Term Capital Management was deemed
by the Federal Reserve to be too leveraged and too intertwined to
fail,'' said Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who is chairman of the House
Banking Committee. ``The question that remains for the economy is
what other risk exists in the hedge fund and derivatives
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides said that discussions were under way about
holding hearings into Long-Term Capital's problems, and the more
general issue of the complex, risky investments made by hedge
funds, but that no decisions had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues certain to be debated is whether the Fed, by
using its influence to help keep Long-Term Capital afloat, was
sending big investors a signal that it will provide a safety net
when they are at risk of suffering huge losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should the weight of the federal government be brought to
bear to help out a private investor?'' Paul Volcker, a former
Federal Reserve chairman, said in a speech in Boston Thursday,
Bloomberg News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, was kept apprised
of the talks on Wednesday but played no active role in the
negotiations, which took place at the Federal Reserve Bank of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Fed takes the role within the Federal Reserve
system of monitoring financial markets and had been tracking
Long-Term Capital's condition for several weeks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said Thursday that he had no
concerns about any broader fallout. ``The only issue that I have to
worry about are issues that have systemic effects, that can affect
the overall economy,'' Rubin told reporters. ``I believe the system
can handle everything I'm aware of'' relating to Long-Term
Capital's problems.
</P>
<P>
   But there were indications that Fed officials were concerned
that the incident would create a further perception of risk within
the financial markets, exacerbating a developing credit squeeze and
further slowing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Long-Term Capital was hammering out a deal with its
creditors, Greenspan was telling the Senate Budget Committee that
the global crisis had become ``more virulent'' in recent weeks,
with direct effects on the American markets.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bakstansky, a spokesman for the New York Fed, said it was
wrong to characterize the situation as an application of the ``too
big to fail'' doctrine, especially since no government money was
involved and the Fed's only role was to bring Long-Term Capital
together with its creditors. But he said the Fed had to be aware of
potential ``disruptions'' to the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``These situations are learning experiences, and we're looking
at what we can do effectively in the context of our
responsibilities,'' Bakstansky said. ``We're not assigned to set
margin requirements for the bond markets. We don't have regulatory
authority over offshore hedge funds. But we do have responsibility
for the safety and soundness of the banking system.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Litan, the director of economic studies at the Brookings
Institution, said it was hard to evaluate the Fed's approach to
Long-Term Capital without knowing more about the investment firm's
positions _ always a problem with hedge funds, which are largely
unregulated and operate in considerable secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole premise of hedge funds _ the reason they're not
subject to regulation _ is that they are limited to very large
investors and that the creditors to them are big boys who are
supposed to be able to take care of themselves,'' he said. ``This
may cause policy makers to revisit that assumption. Maybe one
outcome of this will be more data collection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
