<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN A GENERATION LEARN TO SHARE?  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)  (af) 
 By JAMES SCHEMBARI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On graduation day, during that walk to the auditorium to return
our caps and gowns, giddy about the future, were we ever so
confident as to imagine that we'd be where we are now? That we'd
have lucrative jobs, full retirement accounts and nice homes
soaring in value?
</P>
<P>
   An American living in Geneva told me last summer, after I
marveled about his city, that, yes, it was lovely, but that ``I
wish we had your economy.'' A few days later, a Paris businessman
told me the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   America's baby boomers are indeed fortunate. But what are we
doing with our good fortune? What good have we done? There are
moral issues involved in such plenty, and there is evidence that we
are not responding as we could. How do we measure up, say, to our
parents' generation when it comes to philanthropy?
</P>
<P>
   ``You Americans are very generous,'' my friend in Paris said,
``but you are so ... '' He stopped, not knowing the English word.
He spoke in French to another person at the table, who then turned
to me and said, ``clumsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still probably not the right word, but the image of falling down
was clear.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that since the bull market began, stocks have
created about $8 trillion of wealth. Money is now the national
sport. We chat about our investments, show off our new kitchens,
our Range Rovers. Even as the market sputters, there seems to be no
limit to what we can have or do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first time in history that the phrase `we can't
afford it,' cannot honestly be used to determine choices of
consumption in a family,'' said Paul G. Schervish, director of the
Social Welfare Research Institute at Boston College. ``Affluence
opens up the opportunity for charitable giving. But it also opens
up the opportunity to buy a second home and then say, `I don't have
enough for charity.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So while no one says boomers lack hearts, there is concern that
they are not approaching philanthropy with the same passion as
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of philanthropy is the percentage of personal income
given to charity. In the mid-1960s, when many boomers' parents were
in their 40s, it was 2.2 percent. Now it is 1.9 percent. And
surveys show that giving by high-income people is not increasing as
quickly as wealth.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the boomers are close to their parents in giving,
close somehow seems so inadequate in the midst of so much wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby boomers' parents were happy with a two-bedroom
cottage and one-car garage,'' said Sara Melendez, president of
Independent Sector, an association of nonprofit groups. ``Now it's,
`How many TV sets do we have?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers are at the peak of their earnings,'' she added,
``and certainly when you are making more than you ever have before,
that is the time to give more.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like our parents, prodding us to finish the food on
our plates. ``There are children starving in China,'' my mother
would say. Of course, now there are schools that have been forced
to hold classes in bathrooms. And that's in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to see the point. I've always warded off guilt
with the feeling that I've been generous. I write checks to
charity, and I volunteer at my church. But I took a harder look
when I began researching this column.
</P>
<P>
   I do volunteer work for six hours a month, every other month.
That's less than an hour a week. Those checks I write come out to
2.4 percent of my income, above the national average but still
below what I know I can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Why? I share the fears of many other people about the future:
How will I ever have enough for my children's college education? My
retirement?
</P>
<P>
   But I've never asked the questions from the heart: Do I really
need my three cars? Did I really need to renovate the bathroom?
Should I have gone to the Poconos instead of to Paris this summer?
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Hodgkinson, a research professor of public policy at
Georgetown University, says that until the pressures of college and
retirement are relieved, boomers probably will not increase their
giving. But history suggests that they will change someday.
</P>
<P>
   The most generous givers tend to be 65 to 74, donating almost 4
percent of their incomes. So charities have their fingers crossed,
hoping that the boomers, blessed with so much, will eventually
arrive on the other side of their economic worries and do one great
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first wave of the baby boom has the capacity to engage in
philanthropy like no previous generation,'' Dr. Hodgkinson said.
That will happen, she said, when they realize how much has piled up
in their 401(k)s. ``That's the moment when we need to ask this
generation about their obligation to future generations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
