<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER PLEADS GUILTY IN THEFT OF VOICE MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Enquirer's lead reporter on an expose that was
later retracted by the newspaper pleaded guilty Thursday to two
felony charges that he stole internal voice mail messages from the
Chiquita banana company, which he had been investigating.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hamilton County courthouse in Cincinnati, the reporter,
Michael Gallagher, pleaded guilty to one count of unlawful
interception of wire communications and one count of unauthorized
access to computer systems, which could bring two and a half years
in prison and a fine of $7,500. He is scheduled to be sentenced on
March 19.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher was dismissed by the Enquirer shortly after it
retracted the May 3 article, an 18-page special report, which
questioned Chiquita's Central America business dealings and
included accusations of a bribery scheme in Colombia. The Enquirer
retracted the article on June 28, running a front-page apology, and
made $10 million payment to Chiquita. The articles hinged largely
on information Gallagher got from the voice messages, which he said
had come from a high-ranking Chiquita official with authority over
the voice mail system.
</P>
<P>
   In its apology, which ran for three consecutive days, the
newspaper said that ``an Enquirer employee was involved in the
theft of this information in violation of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the Enquirer's retraction, a special prosecutor was
assigned to investigate possible criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Gallagher, George Ventura, a former lawyer for
Chiquita, was indicted on Sept. 16 and pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Perry Ancona, would not comment on the
continuing investigation, but The Associated Press reported that
Ancona told the judge in court Thursday that Gallagher has agreed
to cooperate with the investigation. Gallagher and his lawyer did
not comment.
</P>
<P>
   While the newspaper's $10 million payment pre-empted any lawsuit
against it by Chiquita, Gallagher still personally faces a civil
suit alleging slander and defamation. Chiquita officials would not
comment on the outstanding suit, but said they were pleased with
the progress of the criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's guilty pleas by the lead reporter, Mike Gallagher,
clearly support the fact that the series of articles was false,
misleading and lacking credibility,'' said Steve Warshaw, president
and chief operating officer of Chiquita Brands International, the
parent company of the banana producer.
</P>
<P>
   Harry M. Whipple, publisher of the Enquirer, which is owned by
Gannett Co., would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement with Chiquita, which is based in
Cincinnati, the newspaper ran the apology for three days. The
Enquirer apology came in a summer of retractions by news
organizations. The Boston Globe, which is owned by The New York
Times Co., dismissed two columnists for fabrication; writer Stephen
Glass was discovered to have made up sources in articles for
various magazines, including The New Republic, and Time Magazine
and CNN retracted a story about use by the U.S. military of nerve
gas during the Vietnam War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
