<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
(af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOW HERE'S A VOUCHER EVEN LIBERALS CAN LOVE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't like to cut their taxes by $300 or $400 a year?
Such savings are available to commuters whose employers set up a
transit voucher program to take advantage of provisions of the
transportation law enacted in July.
</P>
<P>
   For the employee, the voucher for public transit or van pools _
worth up to $65 a month this year and rising to $100 a month by
2002 _ is a tax-free benefit that can be taken in lieu of wages.
For the employer it is a deductible expense, but no payroll taxes
are due, as they are for wages.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Stieglitz, a partner in Anchin, Block &AMP; Anchin, a New
York accounting firm, said employers previously could offer transit
vouchers as a tax-free benefit but could not reduce salaries to pay
for them. Matthew R. Rosenberg, senior tax partner, said that with
the new law, ``the employer has a tax savings and creates goodwill
among employees.''
</P>
<P>
   If, say, a worker pays $135 for a monthly ticket on a commuter
train, she can apply her $65 voucher toward the cost. If she is in
the 28 percent federal bracket, her tax savings will be $303 a
year. Because many states base deductions on federal rules, and
many people are in higher brackets, overall savings could easily
surpass $400.
</P>
<P>
   Jan M. Rosen
</P>
<P>
   INFLATED PAY AWAITS DEFLATED EXECUTIVE EGOS
</P>
<P>
   Golden parachutes are expanding, thanks to the addition of
so-called gross-up features for executives who face tax liabilities
when companies change control and the executives lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Mercer Inc., the consulting firm, has found that 64
percent of 350 large publicly traded companies provide financial
protection for one or more key executives, most often the chief
executive, if the company changes control.
</P>
<P>
   Of those offering such golden parachutes, nearly two-thirds
include gross-ups in the agreements, up from fewer than half in
1994. A gross-up inflates an executive's severance package to cover
excise taxes and any additional income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Internal Revenue Service scrutiny of golden parachutes,
they are standard practice, said Howard Golden, a Mercer principal
in New York, because without them, ``companies would find their
top-level recruitments and retention strategies seriously
compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, an executive is covered for two to three years and is
given a severance payment equal to three times annual salary plus
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Jan M. Rosen
</P>
<P>
   IT HASN'T BEEN THIS GOOD SINCE JIMMY CARTER'S DAY
</P>
<P>
   Hiring in the final quarter of the year will be the highest for
any fourth quarter since 1977, according to Manpower Inc. In its
Employment Outlook Survey for the quarter, Manpower found that 29
percent of companies would add to their work forces, 60 percent
would remain at present levels, 7 percent planned to cut back and
the remaining 4 percent did not yet know their plans. Demand was
especially strong in wholesale and retail trades and in
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
