<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-TSANG-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGING THE DRUM FOR HONG KONG  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ This former British colony has neither an army nor
an air force. But these days, it does have a general _ a career
civil servant with a Chinese name, a British knighthood and a
warrior's determination to crush the foreign speculators whom he
accuses of preying on Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Sir Donald Tsang, and for two weeks last month, he
ordered the Hong Kong government to mount a huge, unprecedented
intervention in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Donald's goal was to burn overseas hedge funds that he said
had bet heavily that the Hong Kong market would decline. Brokers
estimate that the government spent at least $10 billion to prop it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sir Donald holds the title of financial secretary of
Hong Kong _ a post similar to United States Treasury secretary _ he
comes off more as Robert E. Lee than Robert E. Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize that we are in the middle of a battle,''
said Sir Donald, in a typically spirited briefing on the
intervention. ``I would not wish to disclose how many tanks I
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Such military rhetoric may seem odd coming from a bureaucrat
known for his natty bow ties and fondness for bird-watching. But
with Hong Kong suffering through its worst economic downturn since
World War II, Sir Donald has restyled himself as the man who would
keep the barbarians at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is taking his act abroad. Sunday, Sir Donald is
scheduled to start a three-week tour of Europe and the United
States to try to persuade policy makers and investors that Hong
Kong has not abandoned the free market. It will be a tough sell,
given that the intervention has been deplored by investors and
criticized by officials like Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm going to the United States,'' Sir Donald said
in an interview. ``That's why I'm stopping in practically all the
financial centers on earth. The purpose of my trip is to explain
our case.''
</P>
<P>
   His case, simply put, is that the intervention was a necessary
response to hedge funds, which were cynically manipulating Hong
Kong's currency and stock markets. If the government had not
thwarted these speculators, the argument goes, they would have
devastated the market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to buying shares, Sir Donald has curtailed
short-selling and the trading of futures contracts. He said the
restrictions would restore order to a market that had become so
unfettered that it was seen as an easy mark for outsiders seeking
to capitalize on Hong Kong's fixed exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Donald would seem the perfect candidate to plead Hong Kong's
case. A 53-year-old native of Hong Kong, he has spent his entire
career as a bureaucrat dealing with finance and trade issues. He is
the ultimate product of a British civil service that transformed
Hong Kong from a trading post into a center of global finance.
</P>
<P>
   But it is this very lifelong tenure in government that some
critics say blinds Sir Donald to day-to-day realities of
international finance.
</P>
<P>
   They also say Sir Donald's prickly nature has led him to
overreact. ``Whenever there is a run on the Hong Kong dollar or the
stock market, he takes it as a personal affront,'' said Yeung Wai
Hong, the publisher of Next, a muckraking Hong Kong magazine. ``He
feels the need to avenge it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeung said Sir Donald had squandered a hefty chunk of Hong
Kong's foreign reserves. But more than that, Yeung and others fear
that the policy is fueling a xenophobia in Hong Kong similar to
that in Malaysia, which recently imposed capital controls on its
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government ``has drummed up anti-foreigner
feelings, reminiscent of the Boxer Rebellion,'' said Martin Lee,
the territory's most prominent pro-democracy politician.
</P>
<P>
   People who know Sir Donald said his zeal in defending Hong Kong
is rooted in his background. The son of a policeman, he joined the
civil service in 1967 without going to college. He rose through the
ranks and was chosen to attend Harvard's Kennedy School of
Government.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, Sir Donald was overseeing implementation of the
Sino-British Joint Declaration, which set terms for Hong Kong's
handover to China.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Sir Donald became the first ethnic Chinese to be named
financial secretary, the third-ranking post in Hong Kong. And just
before last year's handover, he was knighted by Queen Elizabeth. He
was then retained by Tung Chee-hwa, Hong Kong's Beijing-appointed
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sir Donald is proud of his knighthood, it is a
distinctly dubious honor in a Communist-controlled city-state. He
does not, for example, attach it to his name in official
publications.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Donald may stand at an awkward crossroads between British
Hong Kong and Chinese Hong Kong. But colleagues say he has the
steadfast support of Tung, the public backing of Beijing and
soaring public approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that unhinges Sir Donald is the suggestion
that he is turning Hong Kong into another Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a nationalistic issue; it is simply a monetary and
financial issue,'' he said. ``So it's a bit unfair to tar my name
with some other foreign leaders who might have a different notion.
Sorry, I'm getting indiscreet again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
