<HEADER>
A3394 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARTER25-COX     09-24 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter Center marks anniversary of accords
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Twenty years ago, President Carter worked a miracle
of sorts: He brokered the Camp David Accords, a breakthrough in
relations between Israel and Egypt that offered new hope for
calming tensions in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the former president celebrated the occasion with a
couple hundred friends and representatives of the Israeli and
Egyptian governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes many approaches and many innovative ideas and a great
deal of human courage ... to bring about a step toward peace,''
Carter told the crowd at an invitation-only gathering to mark the
opening of a new exhibit, ``Camp David: Historic Grounds for
Peace,'' at the Museum of the Jimmy Carter Library.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after the accords ``not a single word of that peace
treaty has been violated on either side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he is still an optimist about peace in the Middle
East. ``I still say so, and I say because Israeli mothers want
peace and the Palestinians' mothers want peace and the Lebanese
mothers want peace and the Syrian mothers want peace. To me that is
the foundation of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, which opens to the public today and continues until
April 11, takes visitors inside a Camp David cabin. It also
includes the White House desk on which the accords were signed and
a life-size re-creation of the key participants in achieving the
deal: Carter and former Israeli and Egyptian leaders Menachem Begin
and Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's gathering and again today, the Marine One
presidential helicopter also will be on display outside the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit opening was one of several appearances by Carter
during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he met with Blaise Compaore, president of the West
African nation of Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
   Compaore, who is chairman of the Organization of African States,
briefed Carter on conflicts on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to tell him that it is not time as yet for him to
retire from public life,'' Compaore said. Later, Carter and his
wife, Rosalynn, discussed their international work during a town
hall meeting at the Carter Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first in a series of four programs called
``Conversations at the Carter Center,'' designed to increase
awareness of national and global issues. Tickets for each event are
$6 per person. For more information, call 404-420-3804.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
