<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LITERARY-BAR-ART-2     09-24 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LITERARY-BAR-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the four-year-old KGB series draws boldface fiction writers
and memoirists such as Junot Diaz (``Drown''), A.M. Homes (``The
End of Alice'') and Kathryn Harrison (``The Kiss''), it also
highlights newcomers like Jaime Clark and David Ryan. They met as
writing students at Bennington College in Vermont and will be
reading together on Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the draw is KGB's status as a neighborhood bar,
beckoning with its scuzzy red-and-blue-neon sign, one flight up the
marble treads worn down by generations of Ukrainians. KGB gets its
share of bikers and roistering fraternity pals who join the bar's
garden-variety downtown pan-artistic clientele of academic types,
painters, would-be filmmakers, actor gonnabes and assorted
word-workers. KGB is the kind of place that requires a bouncer for
its tough early-hours weekend crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Readings at KGB (which also has a poetry series and nonfiction
authors events) are free; no one, from the writers to Foster, gets
paid. ``The only ones taking in any money are the bartenders,''
said Woychuk, 45, who of course shares in the take.
</P>
<P>
   But the intimate, 800-square-foot club is scouted by editors and
agents, and a successful appearance can build the kind of buzz that
starts careers. Among the writers who have landed publishing
contracts after reading at KGB are Diaz, Lowell Handler, Elissa
Schappell and Joanna Greenfield.
</P>
<P>
   Though there have never been reading-related fisticuffs in the
bar itself, KGB has been the scene of two quasi-legendary
altercations between Gordon Lish, the fiction editor and literary
gadabout, and Bukiet. Both traded insults in shouting matches that
upstaged the readers they were supposedly introducing.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the memorable Thomas Pynchon ``Imitators
Contest'' evening last year, offering Pynchonesque readings as a
celebration of the publication of the reclusive author's
long-awaited novel, ``Mason and Dixon.'' A writer for The Times of
London, James Bone, thought he spotted the real Pynchon at KGB; but
he found a gentleman in floppy hat and sunglasses to be, well, an
imitator.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a feverish binge of detection, Bone ultimately
tracked down the man he contended was the real Pynchon in
Manhattan. He ambushed the man on the street with a camera, and
presented the resulting picture as the first to be taken of Pynchon
since 1955. ``I felt very personally sad that our event may have
led to the outing of Pynchon,'' Bukiet said.
</P>
<P>
   If there has been tumult, there has been connectedness as well.
Three years ago Marc Aronson, a senior editor at Henry Holt &AMP; Co.
who often comes to KGB to scout new talent, took a writer, Marina
Budhos, to a reading at the bar on their first date. ``Let's say it
was intellectually intense and romantic,'' Ms. Budhos said. So
romantic that they married a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   At KGB the crowds are usually attentive and supportive, but
``someone threw up during one of my readings once,'' said Dani
Shapiro, who teaches writing at Columbia University and the New
School and was the scheduled cleanup hitter after Ms. Schulman at
that night's reading lineup. ``I didn't take it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, KGB and other reading venues are the showroom floors of
the nation's proliferating university writing programs, ``which
produce so many graduates waving all these stories in the air,'' as
one KGB regular (who insisted on anonymity) put it.
</P>
<P>
   As literary spectators in good standing, some audience members
feel free to trash the series. ``They have too many memoirists,''
said one visitor at a recent reading, Erik DuRon, 28, who toils in
a bookstore and who has been to a dozen KGB sessions. ``I think of
all that as the `poor me' school of writing.''
</P>
<P>
   If some ever-envious downtown transgressive types snipe that KGB
is establishment-endangered these days, the bar is still a very
long way from slick. ``We're kind of bozos,'' Bukiet said. ``We
can't even get a mailing list together.''
</P>
<P>
   But will success spoil KGB? ``Interesting question,'' said
Bukiet, as Ms. Shapiro took the lectern to read from her new book,
``Slow Motion.'' Bukiet laughed. ``Perhaps we can only hope so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
