<HEADER>
A3401 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXADDICTS-AZR &LR;      09-24 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX ADDICTS FLOCK TO THERA PISTS IN WAKE OF CLINTON LEWINSKY
TRYST 
</HEADLINE>
 ADDICTS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sex therapist Patrick Carnes barely has time for lunch
these days. Seeking to escape shame and ruin, sex addicts across
the country are flocking to his Wickenburg clinic and other
renowned sex therapy practices in the state.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it. President Clinton's tawdry trysts with Monica
Lewinsky are making people question their own sexual digressions
and seek help for them. Ralph Earle, of Psychological Counseling
Services, alone has witnessed a 25 percent increase in such visits
to his Scottsdale practice.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 miles from the White House sex scandal, Arizona
is feeling the fallout. That's because the Grand Canyon state has a
little-known distinction: It's an international mecca for sex
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of healing that goes on in Arizona,'' said
Robert Weiss, a board member of the National Council on Sexual
Addiction and Compulsivity and clinical director of the Sexual
Recovery Institute in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At Psychological Counseling Services in Scottsdale, people from
as far away as India have come to cure their sexual addictions. The
Meadows treatment center in Wickenburg routinely admits people from
Europe, Mexico, Canada and other countries. &UR; In southern Arizona,
Sierra Tucson also gets people from all over the country for sexual
addiction problems. Around the country, self-help groups such as
Sexaholics Anonymous, Sex &AMP; Love Addicts Anonymous and Sex Addicts
Anonymous are witnessing a surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are talking about sexual addiction, and more
people are seeking help for it,'' said Erik Sachs of Sex &AMP; Love
Addicts Anonymous, with headquarters in Boston and chapters
throughout Arizona. ``President Clinton and the media have raised
the awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   At a program for sex addicts in the Phoenix area, two people
leave the meeting for a few minutes to discuss their illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to ruin my life like Clinton,'' said a middle-age
man, who had a $1,500-a-month strip-joint habit. His
single-mindedness, he confessed, nearly drove him to financial ruin
and led to the break-up of his marriage. ``You can see the same
thing happening to Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Another recovering sex addict contends his cravings for ecstasy
caused him to lose his job. He knew it was dangerous territory,
indulging in cyber sex and Internet pornography on the job. But he
was possessed.
</P>
<P>
   The successful manager would ignore his duties, cancel meetings
and retreat to his office where he would indulge in brazen images
and wild promises. The hours quickly slipped by.
</P>
<P>
   Their stories aren't unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Sexual Addiction Problems estimates
that 6 percent to 8 percent of Americans are sex addicts. That's 16
million to 21.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Several politicians, movie stars and evangelists have
acknowledged being sex addicts after being caught in compromising
positions.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Clinton adviser Dick Morris admitted that he was a
sex addict after a national tabloid published pictures of him with
a prostitute. Michael Kennedy made a similar confession when news
of his relationship with his baby-sitter hit the newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   Is President Clinton part of that group? Since he hasn't been
treated, no one knows for sure. But therapists, sex addicts and
researchers say the signs are certainly there.
</P>
<P>
   One word sets sex addicts apart from others: Compulsion.
Ordinary people want to have sex. For sex addicts, it's an
obsession.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, they'll take big gambles to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll take the risk of losing their job, their family, their
reputation, everything for this rush,'' explained Marilyn Murry, a
sex therapist at Psychological Counseling Services and a professor
at Ottawa University. ``No matter what anyone tells them. They'll
continue to do it. No matter the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Council on Sexual Addiction &AMP; Compulsivity defines
sexual addiction as ``persistent and escalating patterns of sexual
behavior acted out despite increasing negative consequences to self
and others.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnes, the Clinical Director of Sexual Disorders at the
Meadows, puts it like this: A sex addict is a person preoccupied
with sexual thoughts, compulsive sexual behavior and then feelings
of despair and shame until the cycle begins again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the cycle can be broken if people seek help,'' said
Carnes, who wrote the first book on sexual addiction in 1983. He
coined the term ``sex addict'' and is considered to be the nation's
leading expert on sexual disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Murry breaks sexual addiction into four levels. The first is
characterized by compulsive masturbation, usually accompanied with
pornography. The second is marked by multiple affairs, strip clubs,
multiple or anonymous partners, frequent phone- or cyber-sex and
prostitutes. The third level includes sex with an unwilling
partner, obscene phone calls, flashing, voyeurism. The fourth
level: rape, molestation, sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of these activities individually suggests
addiction, explains Earle, of Psychological Counseling Services and
author of ``Lonely All'' ``the Time,'' a book on sexual addiction.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes sexual addiction, he says, is the inability
to stop an ongoing _ and usually escalating _ pattern of
self-destructive sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton is a sex addict, and I can't say that he is since I
haven't treated him, then he would be at level two,'' Murry said.
</P>
<P>
   Sex addict or not, President Clinton's sexual escapades are
having a lucrative impact on the sexual addiction field.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the long-simmering debate over whether sex
addiction is really a disease is being opening discussed now.
</P>
<P>
   Many people haven't recognize sexual addiction as an illness. In
fact, sexual addiction still is not defined _ or even mentioned _
in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders,
considered to be the definitive mental-health reference book.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the controversy stems from the fact that no one has
proven a chemical cause of sexual addiction. Drugs and alcohol are
known to trigger addiction by causing measurable changes in the
brain chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   But specialists believe that unknown changes in brain chemistry
do cause sex addicts to become addicted to the chemical arousal,
the rush of adrenalin, rising heart rate, sweaty palms.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, of the National Council on Sexual Addiction and
Compulsivity, compares it to gambling addiction, which is listed in
the mental-health reference book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a matter of time before sexual addiction makes it
into the book,'' he predicted. ``People have to recognize that
sexual arousal has far more potent stimulus than gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnes says sexual addiction is where alcoholism was ``25 or 30
years ago. It was difficult for people to see that alcoholism was a
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   But to truly be cured, therapists and addiction experts say sex
addicts must come to terms with the void or pain they are trying to
mask. Others need to recognize that addiction runs in their family.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of an addictive personality run through President
Clinton's family. Brother Roger was addicted to cocaine. His
mother, Virginia Kelley, gambled. Grandmother Edith used morphine.
</P>
<P>
   But society also contributes to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   S. Lee Spencer, an associate professor of sexuality and sexual
functioning, says there are few examples of healthy, normal
intimacy on television, movie screens and now in many songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're normalizing behavior that goes along with sexual
addiction,'' she said. ``By seeing so many instances of it, people
begin to think that it's OK, it's normal, when it's not.'' &QL; 
Julie Amparano can be reached at 444-8394 or at
julie.amparano(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
