<HEADLINE>
POLL FINDS MANY FANS ROOTING FOR A MCGWIRE-SOSA TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With: BBO-BASEBALL-SEASON)  
(lh) 
 By MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa's two home runs Wednesday, matching Mark McGwire's
total of 65, no doubt pleased the many Americans who would like to
see this year's pursuit of the home run title end in a tie.
According to the latest New York Times/CBS News poll, 26 percent of
adults would like to see McGwire hold the record for most home runs
at the end of the season, 15 percent would prefer that Sosa end up
with the most, and 42 percent would rather they finish in a tie.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit and eclipse of Roger Maris' 37-year-old record
appears to have rekindled Americans' interest in baseball.
Two-thirds of adults said they were interested in the game,
compared with 42 percent in a Times poll conducted at the same time
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the baseball strike, I lost interest in following the
Braves, but the home run race has been interesting to watch,'' said
Scott Holtzclaw, a 40-year-old fan from Douglasville, Ga., who was
reinterviewed after this year's poll was completed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll shows the highest percentage of baseball fans
since the Times and CBS News first asked a question about interest
in the game in 1985. Twenty-two percent of the adults questioned
said they were very interested in watching or following baseball,
and 41 percent said they were somewhat interested. The national
poll, conducted by telephone Sept. 22-23 with 960 adults, has a
margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The race for the home run title is seen as compelling. ``It's
definitely made the game more exciting,'' said Michelle Mobraten,
26, a homemaker from Burlington, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home run race has really caught my attention,'' said
Joseph Carthey, of Spring Grove, Minn. The 43-year-old teacher said
about Mark McGwire, ``If you're looking for really authentic
heroes, I would say he fits that mold.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to McGwire and Sosa, Holtzclaw said: ``Both those
players are classy guys. They both deserve to win the title.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
