<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBICAM-AD-COLUMN-NYT     09-24 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBICAM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL TOP EXECUTIVES AT YOUNG &AMP; RUBICAM ARE SHIFTED `TO PUT
PEOPLE IN THE RIGHT POSITIONS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A cadre of top executives at Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in
New York is being redeployed as the huge agency company seeks to
build on the momentum gained from recent high-profile account
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The intent is ``to put people in the right positions'' as part
of efforts to ``put together the best of all our crafts to produce
results for our clients,'' said Peter Georgescu, chairman and chief
executive of Y&AMP;R. He discussed the revamping of the executive ranks
in a telephone interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The new senior management lineup consists of executives who had
previously been identified as among the up-and-coming, hot and
happening leaders at Y&AMP;R, the world's No. 5 agency, with billings
estimated at $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Among its blue-chip clients are the AT&AMP;T Corp., the Philip
Morris Companies and Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. Since May, Y&AMP;R has landed
lucrative additional duties from such major clients as Cadbury
Schweppes PLC, Groupe Danone and the Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, involving eight executives, include the departure
after 24 years of Mitch Kurz, a vice chairman and chairman for
client services, who profited mightily from the initial public
offering of Y&AMP;R stock.
</P>
<P>
   One senior officer gaining new duties is Thomas D. Bell Jr., who
has served as chief executive of two important Y&AMP;R units, the
Burson-Marsteller public relations agency and the Diversified
Communications Group that oversees agencies specializing in public
relations, corporate identity and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Another executive being promoted is Linda Srere, the president
and chief executive of the flagship New York office of Young &AMP;
Rubicam Advertising. She is also being named as one of ``the 50
most powerful women in American business'' in the Oct. 12 issue of
Fortune magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to put the best people where they'll do the most
good,'' said Edward Vick, who is chief operating officer of Y&AMP;R as
well as chairman and chief executive of the Y&AMP;R/Wunderman
Partnership, a unit that coordinates advertising and direct
marketing operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building brands is so tough today,'' he added, ``and clients
understand that all their pieces of communication have to work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   A central element of the changes is a move by Vick, 54, to
relinquish a third title, as worldwide chairman and chief executive
of Y&AMP;R Advertising, to Bell, 48. Bell has worked for Y&AMP;R twice in
his 25-year career, which also includes stints at Gulfstream
Aerospace and the Ball Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, in an interview, described how he was involved ``in the
production of print, television, radio and outdoor'' for Republican
candidates like Lamar Alexander, Dan Quayle and John Tower at a
Washington political advertising agency from 1971 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, ``I would expect people to say `Tom Bell is
not an ad guy' '' because he lacks experience in bread-and-butter
advertising fields like packaged goods.
</P>
<P>
   That is not necessarily a detriment, Bell said, because ``the
way our business is going, clients are increasingly looking for
more strategic advice and want their advertising put into a
strategic context.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our principal point of differentiation is trying to bring a
more integrated approach to brand-building advertising for our
clients,'' he added. ``I hope to bring our capabilities there
together more frequently and more powerfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell's duties as chairman of the diversified communications unit
_ overseeing Burson-Marsteller, Cohn &AMP; Wolfe, Landor Associates and
Sudler &AMP; Hennessey _ are being assumed by Graham Phillips, 59, who
continues as chairman of Burson-Marsteller in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's duties as chief executive of Burson-Marsteller are being
assumed by Chris Komisarjevsky, 53, who has been president and
chief executive of Burson-Marsteller's United States operations.
</P>
<P>
   At Burson-Marsteller, Don Cogman, 51, worldwide chief operating
officer, adds the title of president. He forms the senior
leadership team there along with Phillips, Komisarjevsky and Kurt
Krauss, 49, chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second round of management changes at
Burson-Marsteller in a week, coming after the appointment of Ken
Rietz, 57, global practice chairman for public affairs in
Washington, as chief executive for Europe, based in London.
</P>
<P>
   John Smith, 54, who had served as interim European chief
executive, has resumed his duties as global chairman of the
agency's health care practice in London.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Srere, 43, she has been promoted from her post at Y&AMP;R
Advertising New York to succeed Kurz at Y&AMP;R with the titles of vice
chairwoman and chief client officer. She will oversee what Vick
described as ``our key corporate accounts, which make up half our
business''; they include Citicorp, the Colgate-Palmolive Co. and
the Xerox Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Srere is one of only two women in advertising to land on the
Fortune list. The other is Shelly Lazarus, chairwoman and chief
executive of the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP Group PLC in
New York. Ms. Srere, ranked 43rd on the list, was praised for being
``key to Y&AMP;R's win last year of the Citicorp global branding
account.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick praised Ms. Srere as ``probably the best we have at pulling
together all our different resources at our different companies for
a client.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurz, 46, is leaving to pursue what were described as nonprofit
or entrepreneurial endeavors. The value of the shares he owns in
Y&AMP;R, which began trading on May 12, is estimated at more than $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   Though several longtime top Y&AMP;R executives are leaving as a
result of growing rich from the offering, Georgescu said, ``We
haven't been surprised by anyone so far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The IPO has also served the purpose of giving some individuals
the freedom to give back to the community,'' he added. ``A couple
of people are going into teaching, which is just great.''
</P>
<P>
   No successor to Ms. Srere at Y&AMP;R Advertising New York is being
named. Peter Stringham, 49, chairman and chief executive of Y&AMP;R
Advertising North America, to whom the New York office reports,
will assume direct responsibility for that operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
