<SLUG> BC-NY-HALLOWEEN-PARADE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GREENWICH VILLAGE, FLASHY PARADE IS UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like the neighborhood in which it is set, the
Greenwich Village Halloween Parade, a mile-long train of 20,000
marchers outfitted in elaborate, often naughty costumes, has long
celebrated creativity, eccentricity and the liberating power of
bending the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as parade organizers prepare for the 25th-anniversary
march, some neighborhood leaders are concerned that the event,
which draws a boisterous crowd of more than 1 million to the
Village each year, has traveled too far down the road from
irreverent to unruly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of sentiment that the excesses of the
parade have gone too far,'' said Alan Jay Gerson, chairman of
Community Board 2 in the Village. ``If it does not work out this
year, this could be the last parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerson's board will hold a hearing next month on the future of
the parade, at which time he hopes to hear ideas on how to
alleviate the traffic snarls and rowdiness that have damaged the
event's standing within the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But city Councilman Thomas Duane, who represents the Village,
has gone even further, formally asking the Giuliani administration
to cancel the parade now or move it to another neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Duane is supported by some community board members and
neighborhood leaders who contend that the event, which started as a
local procession by a few dozen friends, has grown into an
overcrowded nuisance, a magnet for drunken hooligans and a flash
point for bias crimes against homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own personal experience is that it is a sea of homophobia
out there,'' said Duane, who is gay.
</P>
<P>
   The parade organizers and their supporters, including the
Greenwich Village Chamber of Commerce, say Duane is overreacting
and threatening to kill a carnival, the ``Mardi Gras of New York,''
that has become an economic engine for the Village and a vital
thread in the cultural fabric of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the parade should just end because there are
some potential problems with it,'' said Ralph Lee, 63, a mask
designer who founded, but no longer runs, the event. ``It seems
like rather than chuck the whole thing, something should be done to
work these problems out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Fleming, a theater director who runs the parade from her
Dutchess County home, said: ``This is a joyful night for the whole
city. Very little goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade debate comes at a time when many people in Greenwich
Village are alarmed by a rash of crimes, including three recent
murders and several reported assaults against homosexuals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a Sept. 21 letter to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Duane, a
Democrat who is running for the state Senate, said the city should
withhold the parade permit until it held a public hearing on the
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Community leaders estimate that as many as 2 million people may
line the police barricades this year to be entertained by the
routinely unusual assortment of giant animated puppets, kazoo
bands, stilt walkers and exotically costumed marchers, some of them
acting in zany harmony, like the 40 public school teachers who
showed up one year disguised as Imelda Marcos' shoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
