<HEADER>
A3564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     09-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SEPT. 23, 90 YEARS APART 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In their clubhouse, the Chicago Cubs were getting dressed like
zombies, still in silent shock from Brant Brown's blunder. But
upstairs in County Stadium in Milwaukee late Wednesday afternoon, a
voice with a Chicago persuasion put the Cubs' sudden loss in
historical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't lose for 90 years by coincidence,'' that voice
moaned. ``You've got to be good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's such a thing as a baseball team being good at finding
ways to lose, the Cubs own the copyright: The last time they won
the World Series was, yes, 90 years ago, 1908, the year that
``Merkle's boner'' put the Cubs in the World Series instead of the
New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, every other big-league franchise of that era has won
the World Series _ even the Red Sox in 1918, when Babe Ruth was a
left-handed pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   In their inimitable manner, since 1908 the Cubs have found ways
to lose the World Series seven times, the latest in 1945, and to
lose a National League Championship Series twice, in 1984 and 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs also found ways to lose the 1969 NL East to the New
York Mets, who trailed them by nine and a half games on Aug. 13,
then went on a 38-11 tear and won by eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Cubs are hoping that they haven't already found a way to
lose the NL wild-card playoff race that is all even entering the
season's final weekend: the Mets in Atlanta, the Cubs in Houston
(and the San Francisco Giants still alive, only one game back, in
Colorado).
</P>
<P>
   If the Cubs emerge as the wild card, Brant Brown's blunder will
be forgotten. But if the Cubs don't emerge, every index finger in
Chicago will point to his misplay of a routine fly ball that
allowed three Brewer base runners to score in the ninth for an 8-7
loss.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Cubs and Mets need a wild-card playoff Monday at Shea
Stadium, the index finger of every baseball historian will point to
``Merkle's boner'' in 1908 that provoked what amounted to a pennant
playoff between the Cubs and New York's NL franchise then, the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Almost hauntingly, Brant Brown's blunder and Fred Merkle's boner
each occurred on Sept. 23, exactly 90 years apart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1908, the 19-year-old Merkle was the Giants' rookie first
baseman. In the ninth inning of a 1-1 game against the Cubs at the
Polo Grounds, his two-out single moved left fielder Harry ``Moose''
McCormick to third. When shortstop Al Bridwell singled, McCormick
hurried across the plate with the apparent winning run; Merkle,
knowing the game was over, veered toward the Giants' clubhouse in
center field.
</P>
<P>
   As hundreds of Giant fans hurried onto the field to celebrate
the Giants' one-game lead in the pennant race, Johnny Evers, the
Cubs' second baseman, noticed that Merkle, in the accepted practice
on a game-winning hit at the time, had not touched second.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks earlier in Pittsburgh, Evers had protested to Umpire
Hank O'Day that a Pirates base runner had not touched second on a
similar game-winning hit. O'Day had not seen that base runner turn
away, so he couldn't rule otherwise. But Evers had raised the issue
of the proper application of the rule.
</P>
<P>
   As the plate umpire in the Polo Grounds now, O'Day noticed
Merkle turn away into the celebrants. Evers, meanwhile, shouted for
the ball that Bridwell had hit.
</P>
<P>
   Getting both Umpire Bob Emslie's attention and the ball (or just
a ball, some said), Evers stepped on second. Technically, that
forced Merkle for the third out, thereby nullifying McCormick's
winning run. But with so many fans on the field and darkness
approaching, O'Day hurried to the umpires' room.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cubs' manager, Frank Chance, protested, O'Day, fearing
a riot, announced he would make a ruling at 10 o'clock that night.
He ruled a 1-1 tie. Harry Pulliam, the NL president, ordered the
game replayed on Oct. 8, the day after the season, if it were
necessary to decide the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants and Cubs each finished with a 98-55 record, the
replay was necessary. The Cubs won, 4-2, as Mordecai ``Three
Finger'' Brown outpitched Christy Mathewson. Then the Cubs won the
World Series from the Detroit Tigers in five games, but they
haven't won it since then.
</P>
<P>
   And with only a wild card at stake, Brant Brown's blunder won't
be as infamous in Chicago as Fred Merkle's boner was 90 years ago
in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0523 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COOK-PROFILE-ART-N     09-24 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COOK-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING WITH LOVE, BUT NO TORCH SONGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are high notes Barbara Cook no longer tries to
hit, and at 70 the voice is changed _ richer and more interesting,
actually, since she was Marian the Librarian in ``The Music Man''
40 years ago, with a lyric soprano that was just like every other
ingenue's lyric soprano, except hers was better.
</P>
<P>
   She sings about being in love with a wonderful guy, at the Cafe
Carlyle, and she's so full of the fullness of Rodgers and
Hammerstein love (in terms of calories, about the richest love
there is), you wonder: Is Barbara Cook acting, is she remembering,
or is she meeting somebody after the show?
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs to Ms. Cook's flower-filled suite for an answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing it so long, the emotional part is more
available to me than you'd think,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   So is there a wonderful guy?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I have lots of friends, and I don't know that I would want
that now. Sometimes I think I would. Maybe like a companion, but
it's not something I despair over. I'm really pretty content.''
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time there was a wonderful guy?
</P>
<P>
   A flustered reply from Ms. Cook, who clearly prefers singing
about love to discussing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long time. I would say in the 70s. A long time.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been two chapters in Barbara Cook's career: musical
comedy star in the 50s, when she weighed 106 pounds and could fit
the petite, blonde, beautiful mold those roles seemed to require,
and then, after a famous weight gain made romantic leads impossible
to obtain, the cabaret star.
</P>
<P>
   Whether her weight, which has been high for most of her cabaret
career, has been a factor in her romantic life, Ms. Cook cannot
say. She says the absence of suitors may have to do with signals:
her longtime music arranger and accompanist, Wally Harper, used to
tell her that this man or that in the audience was interested in
her, but she never noticed. Also, she says, that last romance was
painful.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she seems down.
</P>
<P>
   She talks about the beauty of the sun-drenched corner apartment
on Central Park West that she finally allowed herself. ``I lusted
over it,'' she says. She says she has no plans to retire. There
have been some changes, but her voice _ Ms. Cook pauses to knock
wood _ is stronger than ever. When she gets really old, she says,
she'll be out there in a walker.
</P>
<P>
   It's just, one gathers, that there's an old tape going through
her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this terrible condition I have dealt with virtually all
my life,'' Ms. Cook says. ``The inappropriate use of food, food as
a mind-altering substance. It really is an addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have the advantage of knowing how good they are,''
she says.``They see themselves clearly as a commodity early on and
where they fit in. Streisand was like that _ she and I have the
same agent. I didn't have that at all. It would have been very
helpful if I had seen my worth.''
</P>
<P>
   She launches into some lyrics not found in Oscar Hammerstein,
though Lorenz Hart would have understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a neurotic girl from Atlanta,'' Ms. Cook says. ``I did
not have a lot of self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father was a traveling salesman. He and her mother, a
milliner, divorced when Ms. Cook was 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother,'' she begins. ``Oh, boy. Here we go. She _ how to
word this? _ I think in her despair over losing my father, she
didn't think before she spoke. I had a younger sister who died very
young _ she had pneumonia and I had whooping cough _ and I
overheard my mother saying, if I hadn't given my sister whooping
cough, she might have lived. I took that to mean I had killed my
sister. Then my mother asked me to ask my father to come back, and
that of course failed. Then my mother said she believed that if my
sister had lived, my father wouldn't have left us. This was major
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cook sang from the time she was a child. She also, from the
time she was a teen-ager, struggled with her weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm five-three,'' she says. ``I have small bones. I should be
about 110, 115. When I came to New York, when I was 21, I was about
136 pounds _ I am one of those people who can recall what weight I
was every moment in my life. I remember walking in the street and a
guy yelling, `Hello there, Chubbo!'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cook managed to lose 30 pounds in six months and kept the
weight off for several years, through ``Oklahoma!,'' ``Carousel,''
``Candide'' and ``She Loves Me.'' By her late 30s, she was divorced
with one child, her weight was up to 250 pounds and she was no
longer working in musical comedy.
</P>
<P>
   She gave some interviews saying it was liberating to no longer
be concerned about weight; in others, she blamed a lack of decent
roles for her weight gain.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ms. Cook simply speaks of a food addiction. Buying her
new apartment two years ago was so stressful, she says, that she
put on 35 pounds. Since January, she has lost 50. She will no doubt
struggle with the problem for the rest of her life. And yet, she
says, she's feeling pretty good. She's still singing. She is close
to her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four months ago,'' she says, ``I was not quite awake,
and there was this feeling that just stabbed into my heart.''.
</P>
<P>
   She enacts a woman struggling to interpret an unfamiliar
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feeling. Could it be? I think'' _ Ms. Cook is laughing
now _ ``I think I'm actually happy.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
