</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-STORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georges ravishes Florida
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ After all the waiting, worrying, buying
and boarding up, G-Day finallay has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges broke free of Cuba Thursday night, gathered
its strength and began pelting South Florida with wind-driven
squalls from the Keys northward to Palm Beach and the Treasure
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Its threat brought the daily routines of millions to a halt:
Governments, schools and businesses closed and emergency shelters
opened; airports shut down, trains, trucks and buses stopped
running; thousands fled their homes for higher ground, and hardy
holdouts dug in to battle the storm or party it through.
</P>
<P>
   Georges' center is expected to sweep across the middle Keys near
Marathon by midday and grind into the Gulf of Mexico with
rejuvenated winds of more than 100 miles per hour. The hurricane
left nearly 200 dead, hundreds missing and billions of dollars in
damage across the Caribbean
</P>
<P>
   ``This storm looks like it's all set to explosively intensify
once the eye gets over water,'' said Jerry Jarrell, director of the
National Hurricane Center. ``We're extremely concerned that the
land areas will be inundated with water and we'll lose a lot of
folks down there (in the Keys).''
</P>
<P>
   The first band of rain blew into Marathon at 6 p.m. insert
latest advisory
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Dade, Broward, Collier and Monroe counties braced for
hurricane winds of 75 miles and higher. Tropical storm winds of
35-45 mph with gusts to 55 mph are forecast for Palm Beach and
Martin counties' coastal areas, while St. Lucie should have 25-35
mph sustained winds gusting to 45 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But communities south of Lake Okeechobee _ Belle Glade, South
Bay, Pahokee, Clewiston _ will be closer to the storm's center as
it moves westward and could have sustained winds of 50-60 mph with
gusts of hurricane strength, the National Weather Service said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters issued a flood watch for all of Florida south of
Daytona Beach due to heavy rains and high tides. They predicted
8-10 inches of rain for the Keys and Miami-Dade, and 6-8 inches for
Palm Beach and Treasure Coast counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to rain off and on continuously until well into
Saturday,'' said Jim Lushine, storm warning coordinator for the
weather service.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross opened five shelters in Palm Beach County
and two in Hendry County. By 9 p.m., more than 230 had checked in,
including 120 at Glades Central High School in Belle Glade.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen staff and volunteers manned the phones at Palm
Beach County's emergency operations center Thursday. By 8 p.m.,
they had taken more than 2,000 calls from residents asking where
the shelter were, where the storm was, whether they should put up
shutters and if somebody could come help them.
</P>
<P>
   By 8:30 p.m., 6,900 customers in Miami-Dade, Broward and Palm
Beach counties already had lost power, Florida Power &AMP; Light Co.
spokesman Tom Veenstra said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to keep crews out restoring these outages as long
as weather permits,'' Veenstra said. FPL had 2,000 FPL employees
and 1,000 contractors on standby to tackle problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   PalmTran stopped sending out buses when the last one came in at
9:45 and said it would decide today when to resume service.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Highway Patrol, which already had its troopers
working 12-hour shifts from Broward south, planned to do the same
at 7 a.m. in Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast, Lt. Pembrook
Burrows said. That means all troopers will be on dury. Palm Beach
Gardens public works employees were on duty through the night
Thursday and today to monitor drainage and respond to flooding
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County's 12 oceanfront parks will be closed today,
and county lifeguards warn beachgoers to stay out of the water
because of rising swells. If weather permits, county beaches will
reopened Saturday, said Chuck Price, district supervisor for the
county beach patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Worth closed its municipal beach at 11 a.m. Thursday
because of rip currents and floating debris, such as wood planks
and coconuts, presumably from hurricane-stricken islands. City
workers also removed 200 feet of breakaway planking on the Lake
Worth pier.
</P>
<P>
   In the Everglades farming region, sugar, vegetable and citrus
growers worked grimly to lower water levels in fields and groves
and fretted about the water and wind damage that Georges could
inflict on their vulnerable crops.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Crystals Corp., owned by the Fanjul family of Palm
Beach, expected some of its Glades holdings to be flooded. The
Fanjuls still hadn't learned how much damage Georges did to their
250,000 acres of sugar cane in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The citrus harvest begins next month, so trees are heavy with
fruit that is susceptible to wind damage. And the trees don't like
standing water.
</P>
<P>
   Callery-Judge Groves in Loxahatchee sent most workers home at
noon, except for security and drainage crews. The company boarded
windows, put essential files into a waterproof vault and got all
electronic equipment off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it may be a lot of work for nothing,'' manager
Mark Dubois said, ``it may be a lot of work for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Supermarkets were crowded as people picked up storm supplies,
but they weren't chaotic, said Terry Walsh, Winn-Dixie district
marketing director. That's because more residents, seasoned by
Hurricane Andrew in 1992, didn't wait until the last minute, Walsh
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they were even under a watch, they were shopping,''
Walsh said. ``I think they were 24 hours ahead of schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot trucked 80,000 sheets of plywood to southeast and
southwest Florida Thursday, bringing the three-day total to 340,000
sheets, said Don Harrison, a company spokesman. The chain expects
to send more wood up the west coast in anticipation of the storm's
path, he said. At the Home Depot west of Boca Raton, shoppers were
still crowding in Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' manager Pat Sheehan said. ``There was a huge
cheer when the next truck pulled up for plywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan said the plywood was still hot from the gluing process
at the mill.
</P>
<P>
   A special price-gouging hotline set up by the Florida Attorney
General's office had already received about 60 calls by Thursday
afternoon, most of them from the Miami area, spokesman Joe Bizarro
said. He said the hotline had received only two from Palm Beach
County and none from the Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,500 members of the Florida National Guard were ordered
to report to armories Thursday night to be ready for hurricane
assignments today. Four C-130 aircraft were reserved to fly troops
to the Keys for post-storm security.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic through the Keys was down to a trickle on Thursday, and
police ordered a curfew and alcohol ban beginning at 9 p.m. Many of
those left in the Conch Republic of Key West and the kite-tail of
islands connecting it to the mainland had already settled down to
serious hurricane partying.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Cuda, a popular musician in Key West, left his piano gig
at Sloppy Joe's Bar and headed north to Cudjoe Key to screw down
the shutters on his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've invited a lot of people to stay here with me, but no one
accepted, so now it's just me and my dogs to ride it out,'' Cuda
said. ``I'm having a glass of wine every hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuda said he expects to be back at work as soon as the road
opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, the band went down playing on the Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
