<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA POSTPONES CAMPS; REAL GAMES COME NEXT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Another domino fell Thursday in the NBA's
87-day-old labor stalemate, as the league postponed training camps.
If the chain reaction continues, cancellation of regular-season
games will certainly follow within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to even agree on a framework for negotiations with the
players association, NBA officials called off camps _ slated to
begin Oct. 6 _ and canceled 24 exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it is now clear there will not be enough time
for teams to fill their rosters and go through the necessary period
of conditioning and be ready to play preseason games by
mid-October,'' deputy commissioner Russ Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   So all exhibition games through Oct. 16 are scratched, and a
week from now, another week of games could fall. A week after that,
the NBA will be encroaching on the 28-day window leading into
opening night, Nov. 3. Teams need about four weeks to sign players,
hold camp and play a couple of exhibition games before the season
begins, so if a new contract isn't in place by the week of Oct. 5,
regular-season games will be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to miss the whole season,'' Granik said, ``but
there are 29 owners that are willing to do so if they have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have held just one negotiating session _ and a
fruitless one at that _ since NBA owners imposed a lockout July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Granik and commissioner David Stern did meet for an hour
Wednesday with union director Billy Hunter and president Patrick
Ewing, but that was described as simply a feeling-out session to
determine whether they could agree on parameters for negotiating.
No further talks are scheduled. The meeting was described as
cordial, which is at least an improvement over the Aug. 6
negotiating session, which terminated when the owners walked out
after hearing a union proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Owners want to rein in player salaries by imposing a ``hard''
salary cap on teams. The current system includes numerous loopholes
to the cap, including the so-called Larry Bird exception, which
allows a team to pay any amount to re-sign its free agents. Players
oppose elimination of the Bird exception or anything resembling a
hard cap.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement means the Lakers will not train in
Hawaii, where they were scheduled to open camp Oct. 6. Two
exhibition games against the Golden State Warriors in Honolulu,
Oct. 14 and 16, are also canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers were slated to train at College of the Desert in
Palm Desert and have lost games at Phoenix on Oct. 14 and at home
against Vancouver on Oct. 16. Team officials are prohibited from
commenting on the lockout and all player personnel issues. But the
announcement was not a surprise to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of felt all along that would probably happen with
training camp,'' said Lakers guard Derek Fisher. ``When I found
out, I was kind of bummed out.... It's thrown me for a loop as far
as preparing (for the season).''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is hopeful the threat of canceled games will ignite
negotiations, but he's worried about the consequences if it
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't start on time, the fans will be sorely
disappointed. Whenever we start back, they aren't going to just
start loving us again as if nothing has changed,'' he said. ``If we
don't start on time and we don't come back, and then if Michael
(Jordan) is not there, whatever (fans) are filling the void with
when the NBA is gone, they'll just continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pending is the union's grievance with arbitrator John Feerick
claiming that 220 players with guaranteed contracts worth about
$800 million should be paid during the lockout. Feerick could rule
anytime between now and Oct. 19, but if the players win, owners
will challenge the ruling in federal court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
