<SLUG> BC-NY-GOVERNOR-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLONE BACKED BY 133,000-MEMBER TEACHERS' UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In payback for Gov. George Pataki's budget vetoes
last spring, the New York City teachers' union _ one of the state's
most potent political operations _ endorsed his democratic
opponent, Peter F. Vallone, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, the New York City Council Speaker, trails in the polls
and desperately needs the phone bank and direct-mail operations _
to say nothing of the votes _ of the 133,000-member United
Federation of Teachers, which bills itself as the nation's largest
union local in any field.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's powerful and traditionally democratic labor
unions, convinced that Pataki is a cinch for re-election, have
decided to sit out this race, depriving Vallone of much of the
organizational support on which he was counting.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement took some of the luster off Pataki's day spent
portraying himself as a champion of children. In ceremonies in New
York City and Albany, he signed a bill expanding the state's health
care program for children of the working poor, and one raising
penalties for day-care providers who break laws governing their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In April, after the legislature passed a state budget, Pataki
infuriated lawmakers and countless interest groups by vetoing 1,300
separate items, totaling more than $1 billion in spending.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the diciest of the vetoes had to do with education:
he eliminated $500 million for school construction, $77 million to
bolster teacher salaries in urban districts, and money for programs
that were intended to help teachers hone their skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor knows very clearly where we stand on
these issues, why we're doing what we're doing,'' Randi Weingarten,
president of the teachers' federation, said at a news conference in
City Hall Park to announce the endorsement of Vallone. ``And he
knew very much the disappointment we had with the vetoes last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, she said, ``has a record, in good budgets and in bad
budgets, of supporting public schools and the issues we care deeply
about, such as lower class sizes, repair and maintenance of
buildings, higher academic standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor declined to comment directly on the endorsement.
``I'm very proud of our record on education,'' he said. ``We've
committed more resources than the state has ever done before'' to
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Vallone said Pataki's vetoes showed a ``lack of concern or
understanding of the problems for our children and education.''
</P>
<P>
   In the months before Pataki's vetoes, leaders of the teachers'
federation said they were unlikely to take sides in his re-election
contest. And even after the vetoes, while teachers and union
leaders were clearly furious, Democrats worried that the union
would refrain from any assault on the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The federation's parent union statewide, the New York State
United Teachers, an arm of the American Federation of Teachers,
probably will not make an endorsement in the race, according to its
top officials. The smaller of the two statewide teachers' unions,
the New York chapter of the National Education Association, has
endorsed Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   But Vallone's continuing problems with organized labor were on
display Thursday at Mount Sinai Medical Center on the Upper East
Side, where one of the state's most important and politically
astute labor leaders, Dennis Rivera, stood at Pataki's side as the
governor signed a children's health bill into law.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, president of 1199, the National Health and Human Service
Employees Union, has remained silent on the governor's race, and
Thursday, he had warm words for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's was the most aggressive union in attacking the governor
in 1995 for his proposed cuts. But since then, the two men have
worked closely on various issues, including the legislation Pataki
signed Thursday, and on obtaining $1.25 billion from the federal
government to aid New York's hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Governor Pataki was elected governor, we had a rocky
beginning; we all know about that,'' Rivera said. But now, he said,
``there's a whole body of work that we have done together.''
</P>
<P>
   The signing Thursday was a stark turnabout for Pataki, who last
year proposed only a bare-bones plan for expanding the Child Health
Plus plan, drawing howls of protest from Democrats in the
legislature and children's advocates. By his own admission, it was
because of intense lobbying that he agreed to a much more generous
package of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Marian Wright Edelman, the president of the Children's Defense
Fund, joined Pataki for the signing and called New York's expanded
program ``a model for the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's signing provided the governor a chance not only to
take credit for that outcome, but to pose for news cameras while
sitting in a sea of toddlers, and to bask in the praise of liberal
icons like Rivera and Ms. Edelman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about any of us,'' Pataki said. ``It's about the
smiling faces you see here before you.''
</P>
<P>
   Child Health Plus provides free or low-cost health coverage for
children of working parents with low or moderate incomes and no
health insurance _ those who are not poor enough to qualify for
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   It began under Gov. Mario M. Cuomo in the late 1980s and was
greatly expanded under Pataki two years ago. Last year, Congress
and President Clinton allocated money to create and expand such
programs nationwide, leaving it to the states how to spend the
money, and New York's share is $256 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, there are 680,000 children without health
insurance. Of those, 420,000 are eligible for Child Health Plus,
but only 230,000 are enrolled so far.
</P>
<P>
   The bill Pataki signed makes an additional 45,000 children
eligible, by raising the income limit to $41,000, from $34,000, for
a family of four. It also greatly expands the package of benefits
to include dental, vision, hearing, mental health and substance
abuse treatment, and devices like hearing aids and wheelchairs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the race for Senate, the state Democratic Party, in a novel
twist on advertising strategy, announced that it had taped a
Republican advertisement that warns against New York City
influence, and that is now being shown only upstate, and would
begin broadcasting it in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats said they would take a second Republican
advertisement intended only for downstate audiences _ in which Sen.
Alfonse M. D'Amato is endorsed by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Edward
Koch, the former mayor _ and begin broadcasting it upstate.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats added a message that appears onscreen over the
Republican advertisements: ``The ad Al D'Amato and the Republicans
don't want you to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic advertising campaign is intended to draw
attention to what Judith Hope, the state democratic chairwoman,
said was an effort by Republicans to divide the state
geographically.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Democrats said that their main purpose was to encourage
newspapers and television stations to do a story about the
advertisements; the cost of television time bought by the Democrats
was described as minimal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
