u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT &LR;      09-24 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS IN SENATE RACE TRY TO OUT-TOUGH EACH OTHER ON CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just two weeks old but already rancorous, the
Senate race has become in large part an acid debate over crime,
with Rep. Charles Schumer and Sen. Alfonse D'Amato trading
accusations almost daily that the other is soft on criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al D'Amato is not close to being as tough on crime as Chuck
Schumer,'' Schumer, a Democrat from Brooklyn, said recently in a
typical campaign remark. To which D'Amato, a Republican of Long
Island, replied, ``It was Chuck Schumer who worked and voted
against tougher penalties for dangerous criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Their peevish discourse notwithstanding, there are substantive
differences, and often striking similarities, in the positions
Schumer and D'Amato take on crime, a review of their parallel
18-year congressional careers shows. It also shows that neither man
can be aptly labeled a coddler of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Though D'Amato has described his rival as a liberal well outside
New York's political mainstream, Schumer has in fact angered
liberals, blacks and civil libertarians _ core Democratic Party
constituencies _ by voting to lengthen prison sentences, limit
appeals by death row convicts, expand capital punishment to cover
more crimes and broaden the authority of investigators to use
wiretaps.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Schumer's efforts to portray D'Amato as weak
on crime have sometimes seemed a bit like trying to outrun the
wind: it has been a rare day when D'Amato has opposed legislation
intended to strengthen criminal penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all their one-upmanship has often blurred important
distinctions between the two men, which are most glaringly evident
on the issue of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has been a leading proponent of gun control, contending
that it reduces violent crime and protects police officers. D'Amato
has been a steadfast opponent of any restrictions on gun ownership,
taking the position that tougher penalties are the best deterrent
to crime.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has also shown greater interest than D'Amato in
financing alternatives to prison, like drug treatment and youth
programs. One reason D'Amato voted against the 1994 crime bill,
which Schumer helped write, was that he felt it included too much
money for prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the two men agree on some fundamental issues. Both
support the death penalty and have voted to make more federal
crimes subject to capital punishment. And both have pushed to give
federal lawyers the authority to prosecute certain street crimes,
though not the same ones.
</P>
<P>
   As a former chairman and current ranking minority member of the
House subcommittee on crime, Schumer has been one of Congress' most
active architects of crime legislation this decade. He was a chief
sponsor of the Brady law, which established a five-day waiting
period to buy handguns, and of legislation that made carjacking a
federal crime.
</P>
<P>
   He is currently a sponsor of a measure that would expand the
power of criminal investigators to wiretap phones, a measure civil
libertarians strenuously oppose.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the 1994 crime bill that Schumer points to most often
as his greatest achievement, and as D'Amato's most glaring failure.
</P>
<P>
   The measure embraced a remarkable range of policies intended to
win support from conservatives and liberals. It mandated sentences
of life without parole for three-time felons, made scores of crimes
eligible for capital punishment and provided funds for police
officers, prison cells, drug treatment and youth programs.
</P>
<P>
   It made stalking and domestic abuse federal crimes, banned
certain assault weapons and made it illegal to import child
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's campaign now says D'Amato's vote against the 1994 bill
showed that he was weak on crime, unconcerned about women and had
``sided with child pornographers and the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has countered by ticking off a number of Schumer's votes
that he contends demonstrate a lack of resolve, including one
against a 1995 bill that would have penalized states that did not
require criminals to serve a minimum of 85 percent of their
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has been the author of bills intended to increase
penalties for using guns in crimes. He contends that such measures
would do more to reduce violent crime than restricting gun
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But many criminal justice experts contend that one such D'Amato
bill, which would authorize federal attorneys to prosecute gun
crimes, would clog federal courts with cases that local courts
could handle just as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
