<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILOFAX-SALE-NYT &LR;      09-24 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILOFAX-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY RUNNER BIDS FOR BRITAIN'S FILOFAX CO. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ No yuppie was seen without one. No master or mistress
of the universe ventured forth unadorned by this particular
accessory: For much of the 1980s, the Filofax _ the black leather
ring-binder whose girth was a measure of power-lunch dates and
contacts in high places _ was de rigueur.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it was on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Day Runner Inc., a manufacturer of personal organizers in
Irvine, Calif., announced an unsolicited (PS)47.9 million ($80.5
million) bid for the 1980s emblem that fell victim to a new era and
lost ground to electronic organizers. But if its reputation had
slumped, shares of Filofax Group PLC rose Thursday by 62.5 pence,
to 202.5 pence. Day Runner's bid at 200 pence ($3.36) a share was a
42.9 percent premium on Filofax's 140 pence closing price on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Filofax Group did not say whether it would accept the bid.
</P>
<P>
   For those too young to recall, the Filofax was a stunning
marketing phenomenon of the 1980s, a brand that seized imaginations
in booming times by offering what was billed as a power tool _ a
one-stop ring-binder where the upwardly mobile could bring together
an appointments diary and a forward planner, address book and
project notes in a compact format suited to an incredibly busy
lifestyle. Indeed, its products expanded to include maps and
expense sheets, even records of squash games.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, the Filofax became a widely used part of
business and office life, with worldwide sales that surpassed sales
in its British base. In the year ending March 31, Filofax sales
totaled (PS)37.7 million ($63 million), with (PS)16.7 million
($27.8 million) in Britain and (PS)5.2 million ($8.6 million) in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After an ill-starred foray into the greeting cards business,
though, Filofax began looking for a partner in April, only to call
off the search in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s, the brand had a reputation and a recognition to
be envied, but today the story is a different one,'' said Mark
Vidovich, the chairman of Day Runner.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, the company has seesawed under different
managements. ``The brand name is a good one,'' Vidovich said. ``And
it has great potential. But it hasn't been exploited properly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0531 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3580 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      09-24 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTIONS MAY DELAY HOUSE FROM WRAPPING UP CLINTON PROBE SOON, HYDE
SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde said
Thursday that if the House votes to hold a formal impeachment
inquiry on President Clinton's behavior in the Monica Lewinsky
affair, the hearings would likely extend beyond the November
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois Republican told reporters that his 37-member panel
would decide Oct. 5 or 6 whether to recommend an inquiry. If
approved by the committee, the full House would likely vote on the
resolution by Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   But with all 435 members of the House up for re-election Nov. 3,
Hyde suggested the need to campaign might keep the hearings from
beginning in earnest until after Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our members feel constrained to campaign for
re-election _ not the least of which is me,'' he said. ``Our guide
is deliberate speed _ not too fast that people can accuse us of
rushing to judgment and not too slow so people can accuse us of
deliberately stretching it out for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Polling indicates a substantial majority of Americans do not
want Clinton impeached and would like to put the scandal behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all Americans, I want to bring this matter to closure as
soon as possible,'' Hyde said. ``The timetable I've proposed today
is the most expeditious schedule we can follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats, however, contended that Congress could wrap
up any inquiry before the elections, if it spent less time
skirmishing over what information to make public.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an effort to run out the clock so that the election
comes and goes with this totally unresolved, with all the questions
hanging,'' said committee member Barney Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the dilemma my Republican colleagues face is they have
a significant part of their party that wants an impeachment, and to
their disappointment, the public does not yet appear ready to join
them. ... Therefore, they don't want to take any conclusive action
one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, another Democratic member of
the committee, called on Hyde and the Republicans to ``get a
grip,'' as she put it. ``Stop politicizing this and get back to due
process,'' she said on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Frank and Jackson Lee also criticized Hyde's position that none
of the audio tapes of Lewinsky's confessions about Clinton to her
former friend Linda Tripp should be made public. The 27 tapes that
Tripp recorded secretly were the basis for independent counsel
Kenneth Starr launching his inquiry into whether Clinton lied under
oath about having a sexual relationship with Lewinsky and tried to
cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the tapes contained ``a lot of information that really
does not pertain to this investigation'' and would embarrass
``innocent people.'' But he insisted that transcripts of the tapes,
along with some 60,000 other pages of information, would be
released after the committee decides in a closed-door meeting
Friday what parts should be edited out.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee and most other Democrats on the Judiciary Committee
have been opposed to releasing any the information supplied to
Congress by Starr. But she called it hypocritical of the
Republicans to push for the release of the president's videotaped
testimony before the grand jury investigating the Lewinsky matter
and not the Tripp tapes.
</P>
<P>
   According to committee sources, the accuracy of some tapes is in
question and still under investigation by Starr. They say the tapes
are also much more graphic than the testimony released by the
committee thus far and show that Tripp may have been trying to
manipulate what Lewinsky says in some of their conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Hyde said transcripts would contain all relevant
information, regardless of whether it helps or hurts the president.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Tripp tape transcripts, the Judiciary
Committee is also expected to decide Friday how much more of the
Starr information to release, including the grand jury testimony of
Tripp, Clinton friend Vernon Jordan, and the president's personal
secretary Betty Currie. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Under the House resolution authorizing the release of the Starr
report, all 16 boxes of supplemental information must be released
by Sept. 28. But Hyde said it was unlikely that the material would
be released until at least midweek.
</P>
<P>
   As Hyde was meeting with reporters, Clinton was preparing for a
White House event on the nation's falling poverty rate, barely
taking note of the controversy that threatens to bring down his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believes there is any way to avoid impeachment
hearings, Clinton said: ``The way out here, and the only way out,
is for people in Washington to do what the folks in America want
them to do _ which is to take care of their concerns and their
children and their future.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Democrats had tried to strike a deal with House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., to avoid impeachment hearings, which
now appear inevitable. But Gingrich, under heavy pressure from
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, and other GOP
conservatives, rejected the idea of a lesser punishment, such as
censure.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said Thursday that the Constitution did not give Congress
the authority to censure a president as a lesser punishment for an
impeachable offense. He encouraged Hyde and his Republicans
colleagues to see the impeachment process through, which could
result in Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility of censuring Clinton instead of
trying to impeach him, Hyde said he was ``not entranced by that
idea,'' adding that there was no precedent for it.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of constitutional lawyers said Congress can pursue
whatever course of action it wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress wants to pass a resolution that approves of
Mother's Day or disapproves of the conduct of the president, it
seems to me kind of a stretch to say either of those is
unconstitutional,`` said University of Houston law professor David
Crump.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980924.0532 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
