<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3591 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HORSES-COLUMN-LAD     09-24 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPER WANTS HORSES TO BEAT ODDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dick Mitchell volunteered last winter to raise money for
the ``Save the Horses'' initiative on the Nov. 3 California ballot,
campaign leader Kathleen Doyle was surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is a horseplayer, famous in the racing world for three
handicapping how-to books and the handicapping computer software
created by his Cynthia Publishing Company of Studio City. Doyle is
an animal-welfare advocate, and she figured a horseplayer for a
bottom-line guy without a sensitive bone in his lazy body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quite honestly expected him to be (all about) `return on
investment,' in it for the buck,'' said Doyle, whose campaign is
also based in Studio City. ``I was taken back by his take on the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   What she heard from Mitchell, 59, shattered the stereotype of
horse bettors. At press conferences and in letters to more than
9,000 fellow horseplayers on the Cynthia Publishing mailing list,
Mitchell has enthusiastically touted Proposition 6, which would
prohibit the slaughter of California horses for use as food in
countries where their meat is a delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 6 backers say about 10,000 horses a year are sold to
slaughter plants in Texas and Canada and suffer brutally painful
deaths. One-quarter of those, by one estimate, are former
racehorses.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell thinks that's a practice everybody should oppose,
especially racing fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real simple: I'm passionate about animal issues _
period,'' he said this week. ``I think the way we treat animals is
abominable... God, we go out there (to the track) every day and
they thrill us. And how do we thank them? We brutalize them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't wind up as a trainer's pet, they wind up in a
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Prop. 6 supporters aren't suggesting a retirement home can be
found for every used-up racehorse. They're promoting euthanasia as
a humane alternative to slaughter. Mitchell would also like to see
the elimination of the use of whips in racing and an end to the
racing of immature 2-year-olds. But first things first.
</P>
<P>
   The former Los Angeles City College math teacher said the
response to his letters has been modest but heartening: about
$5,000 in contributions, ranging from $5 and $10 ``votes of
confidence,'' to $100 and $200 checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My general feeling, just being around handicappers, is that
they're a decent lot that doesn't put up with cruelty,'' Mitchell
said. ``I have to characterize the average handicapper as a decent
soul.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law is opposed by the Libertarian Party. But Doyle
said a poll showed 70 percent support.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle was amused by a recent conversation with Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Well, I !ital!guess!off! we're going to win,' ''
Doyle said. ``He said, `You're nuts! Of course this is going to
win! Coming out against this would be like coming out against
motherhood!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken with the conviction of a horseplayer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Let a pro do it: If, as expected, the clenbuterol charges
announced Monday against seven California trainers are challenged,
the cases probably will set a welcomed precedent on the way such
cases are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings will be presided over by an administrative law judge
and the California Horse Racing Board's side will be presented by
the state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, medication hearings were conducted by track
stewards and the CHRB's case was put forth by state racing
investigators. It was like asking police officers to serve as
prosecutors, and it was no surprise when the amateurs' Hamilton
Bergers were outfoxed by the trainers' Perry Masons.
</P>
<P>
   CHRB spokesman Mike Marten said the change was made because of
the volume and complexity of the clenbuterol cases, and because the
board wanted to get in step with other state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing dates have yet to be scheduled and no verdicts should be
expected before the new year in the cases involving trainers Ted
West, Vladimir Cerin, Peter Eurton, Paco Gonzalez, Bruce Headley,
Declan Jackson and Darrell Vienna and 14 horses whose postrace
tests revealed the presence of the bronchial-dilator clenbuterol.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: The short Fairplex Park racing season ends
Sunday with the Ralph M. Hinds Pomona Invitational Handicap, in
which Score Quick will try to defend his 1997 title for trainer Mel
Stute and jockey Matt Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   The 1[-mile Invitational has produced seven repeat winners in
the past 45 years, most recently Elegant Bargain in '90-91.
</P>
<P>
   Next on the calendar is the 32-day Oak Tree Racing Association
season at Santa Anita. It opens Wednesday at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Charmed and dangerous?: Silver Charm will try to salvage a
season gone bad when he races for the first time in nine weeks in
the Kentucky Cup Classic at Turfway Park on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A victory might persuade owners Bob and Beverly Lewis to pay the
supplemental nomination fee and finally challenge long-distance
rival Skip Away, now a lock for Horse of the Year, in the Nov. 7
Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   __ Less is more: The 1999 schedule approved last week by the
CHRB will offer 11 fewer dates than 1998, and that's a small but
worthwhile step toward easing the glut that has caused race fields
to shrink.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, there will be two days, instead of just one,
between the close of one track and the opening of the next. Even
Del Mar, which jealously guarded its annual 43-day allotment, will
have to cut back to 42 by opening on Thursday instead of Wednesday
next summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
