<HEADER>
A3595 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-POVERTY-ART-2N     09-24 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-POVERTY-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POVERTY RATE DECLINED LAST YEAR, LARGELY AMONG BLACKS AND
HISPANICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs grafs 13, 14 to emphasize and add info on relationship
between welfare programs and poverty, including Republican and
Democratic stance on the issue; tightening and polishing
throughout.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The proportion of Americans living in poverty
declined last year, mostly because of reductions in poverty among
black and Hispanic families, the Census Bureau reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The data reflected three consecutive years of growth in income,
which have restored household incomes and poverty to the levels
recorded in 1989, just before the last recession.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty rate was 13.3 percent last year, down from 13.7
percent in 1996 and 15.1 percent in 1993. The number of people in
poverty, 35.6 million last year, has dropped by 3.7 million since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty rate for non-Hispanic whites was unchanged at 8.6
percent last year. But the rate for blacks declined to 26.5
percent, the lowest since the government began collecting data on
poverty among African Americans in 1959. The rate among blacks was
28.4 percent in 1996 and 33.1 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And the poverty rate for Hispanic Americans declined to 27.1
percent, from 29.4 percent in 1996 _ the largest one-year drop in
Hispanic poverty since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The data were a tonic for President Clinton, battered by months
of embarrassing disclosures about his affair with a White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the statistics vindicated his economic policies and
showed that low-income people were finally sharing the fruits of a
vibrant economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our growing economy is giving more and more families a chance
to work their way out of poverty,'' he said in the Rose Garden of
the White House. ``After six years, it can't be an accident
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidents generally get credit for economic growth and are
blamed if the economy declines. Clinton fought successfully for
increases in the minimum wage and in the earned-income tax credit
available to low-income workers, and White House officials said
those changes had helped reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said that much of the decline in poverty was
attributable to the overall strength of the economy, resulting from
prudent management of federal spending and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks have been among the president's most steadfast supporters
in recent months, and Thursday's data show that they have fared
well in the Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the number of families in poverty declined last year
by 384,000, to 7.3 million from 7.7 million in 1996. Black families
accounted for more than half of the decrease.
</P>
<P>
   The welfare rolls are declining much faster than the number of
people in poverty. But Rebecca Blank, of the President's Council of
Economic Advisers, said, ``It's way too early to look at these
numbers and conclude very much about the successes of welfare
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats have predicted that cuts in welfare programs,
such as time limits on the payment of cash assistance, will tend to
increase poverty. On the other hand, many Republicans say poverty
will decline as mothers move from welfare to work and fathers pay
more child support. In any event, it will be hard to separate the
specific effects of the 1996 welfare law from changes in the
economy. The Census Bureau found surprisingly robust growth in
income even among families headed by women. The incomes of
households headed by women rose last year by 8 percent for blacks,
10.3 percent for Hispanic Americans and 3 percent for whites. Among
non-Hispanic whites, hardly any change was seen.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty rate for children was under 20 percent last year for
the first time since 1989, and Clinton said child poverty had
declined more since 1993 than in any other four-year period since
the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But the poverty rate for people 18 to 64 years old was higher
last year than in 1987-89. And for households headed by people 35
to 54, income has not kept pace with inflation, so real income was
lower last year than in 1989, the bureau said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Politicians have repeatedly denounced growing inequality in
income distribution. But Census Bureau officials said their data
suggested that inequality had stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fourth consecutive year in which there was no
year-to-year change in overall income inequality,'' said Daniel
Weinberg, chief of the Census Bureau office that collects income
data.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Robert Reischauer, former director of the Congressional
Budget Office, said it was remarkable that ``income inequality has
not been reduced after two years in which we've enjoyed the
healthiest economy in more than three decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg said the bureau's field interviewers probably missed
many people with very high incomes, just as they miss homeless
people. He said, anyone who reports income of more than $1 million
a year is listed as having $1 million of income.
</P>
<P>
   The data in the report are drawn from interviews with residents
of 50,000 households chosen to be representative of the nation. A
family of four was classified as poor if it had cash income of less
than $16,400 in 1997. The threshold for a family of three was
$12,802. Income, as officially defined, does not include capital
gains, health insurance or government benefits like food stamps,
Medicaid and housing subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau data show that the income of black households,
after adjusting for inflation, was higher in 1997 than at any other
time in the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The median income of black households rose 4.3 percent last
year, to $25,050, and since 1993 it has increased by 15 percent, or
$3,354, after adjusting for inflation. The number of households
above the median is the same as the number below it.
</P>
<P>
   For Hispanic households, the median income rose 4.5 percent last
year, to $26,628, and has risen 4.8 percent since 1993. But
Hispanic income appears to have stagnated and is about the same,
after adjusting for inflation, as in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the Census Bureau also made these points:
</P>
<P>
   _ Median household income rose last year by 1.9 percent, to
$37,005 from $36,306, after adjusting for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   _ State poverty rates, measured by three-year averages, ranged
from an extraordinary low of 6.9 percent in New Hampshire to a high
of 24 percent in New Mexico. The next highest rates were found in
Mississippi (20.2 percent) and Louisiana (18.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The report also said the number of blacks in poverty dropped
last year to 9.1 million, from 9.7 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Hispanic people in poverty declined to 8.3
million, from 8.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ A majority of all poor families are headed by women. There are
7.3 million poor families in America, and 4 million are headed by
women.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bureau said that the poverty rate for
noncitizens, 25 percent, was double the rate for people born in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
