<HEADLINE>
BLOOD ON BRONZE  
 A LOW-FAT FIGHT  
 CHANGE OF VENUE   
 PRESIDENTIAL MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY JAMES BARRON with ALEX KUCZYNSKI and JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The jar marked ``blood'' was still open, but Yoko Ono
had finished spattering the substance on the bronze replica of a
man's blue shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The red stuff was not blood but a resin mixture. The bullet hole
over the pocket was real, though _ the sculpture had been shot at
by workers at the foundry in Brewster, N.Y., where it was cast.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ono said it was the second such shirt she had made. The
first, she said, was made several years ago, when she prepared an
exhibition of small surrealistic objects, including a box, a
hairbrush and a pair of high heels. All had been spattered with the
red resin mixture.
</P>
<P>
   To many viewers, the items she chose symbolized her proximity to
the assassination of her husband, John Lennon. But she said the
idea of displaying what appeared to be bloody objects began as a
``feminist statement.'' Later she decided to include the man's
shirt because ``I wanted to show that men are subject to violence,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Foundry workers said they had been told the shirt had belonged
to Lennon. Absolutely not, Ms. Ono said. ``It could be any guy's.
It symbolizes New Age man, as opposed to Edwardian man.''
</P>
<P>
   But one would have to be as strong as Hercules to wear this
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think it's real,'' she said. ``Then they bump into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A Low-Fat Fight
</P>
<P>
   Michael Milken, whose hunger for junk bonds led to an
unappetizing stay in prison after his conviction for securities
fraud, has developed a taste for Caesar salads.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any Caesar salads, but the 51-calorie kind.
</P>
<P>
   Milken, who is helping to organize a conference and candelight
vigil in Washington to focus attention on what he calls the
``cancer epidemic,'' has written a cookbook with low-calorie,
low-fat recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The vice chairman of Barnes &AMP; Noble, Leonard Riggio, will give a
party for ``The Taste for Living Cookbook: Mike Milken's Favorite
Recipes For Fighting Cancer'' in New York on Monday. Don't expect
the canapes to be foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   Milken's doctor told him five years ago that he had 12 to 18
months to live. Since then, he has been a tireless fund-raiser for
cancer-fighting charities and a tireless critic of what he says is
America's unbusinesslike approach to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're spending $107 billion a year on cancer care and $2
billion a year on research. No business would spend 2 percent
trying to fix the problem and 98 percent trying to service the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Change of Venue
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You know what happens when new owners take over a
restaurant: the old, familiar things are changed. The menu, maybe.
The paintings on the walls, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   But a portrait of James Beard, the influential chef and cookbook
writer who died in 1985, has not gone from the Four Seasons
restaurant to a flea market.
</P>
<P>
   The Arbit Blatas painting had hung in a private room in the
restaurant on East 52nd Street for years. But the new co-owners,
Julian Niccolini and Alex von Bidder, decided it was time to change
things. So the painting came down. Thursday night Niccolini and von
Bidder presented it to the James Beard Foundation, a nonprofit
group with headquarters in the town house Beard owned on West 12th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Niccolini and von Bidder didn't like Beard _ or didn't
like the painting as much as the former owners, Tom Margittai and
Paul Kovi?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely fond of James Beard,'' said Niccolini, who once
worked at the Four Seasons as a headwaiter. ``I'm here over 20
years. He used to come in almost every day; he never gets a check.
One day I mention this to Margittai. He says: `Don't worry about
it. If James Beard ever saw a check, he would faint. He has been a
friend here forever.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential Music
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to fly to Chicago Friday Tena
Clark knows what he will hear if he picks up the earphones and
listens to the in-flight sound system. She chose the music.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One carries several of the 22 channels she programs
for United Airlines (classical, country, pop, jazz and something
called ``center stage,'' which features everyone from Tom Petty to
Eric Clapton to the president's brother, Roger Clinton). Hoping to
give the First Saxophonist what he would like to hear, she also
created an all-saxophone channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I really sat there and thought about it, it would be pretty
overwhelming to think that you're programming music for someone
that powerful,'' said Ms. Clark, who changes the music every 60
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we tried to do is look at it like he was no different
from anybody else: what is this person really going to like?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
