<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REAL REFORM VERSUS MAYORAL EXPEDIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Sept. 25:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The rumbling from New York's City Hall suggests that
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is ready to veto an excellent campaign
finance reform package passed last month by the City Council. The
Council can easily override the mayor's veto, but Giuliani would
send a far more worthy signal to New Yorkers if he would simply let
these reforms pass, either by signing the three bills or stepping
aside and letting them become law.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the mayor has been arguing that these reforms, pushed
by Council Speaker Peter Vallone and Public Advocate Mark Green,
would cost the city too much money. The city's Campaign Finance
Board has come up with a very rough estimate that the cost of an
election would double _ from $6.5 million in 1997 to $13 million in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the amounts are relatively tiny. The board's current
report cites a quote from Giuliani in 1991 explaining that the cost
of the city's campaign finance system is ``infinitesimal. You can't
find it (in the city budget). It's a percentage of a percentage of
a percentage.'' An infinitesimal amount, even if quadrupled, is
still a pittance compared with the public cost of having
politicians more beholden to special interests than to the voters
who elected them.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has also been arguing for his own campaign reform
package prepared for a referendum on the Nov. 3 ballot by his
Charter Revision Commission. But this is an ill-considered product
rushed out to bump Vallone's referendum on Yankee Stadium from the
ballot. Although Vallone's measure barring use of city money to
move the Yankees to Manhattan was also ill advised, the charter
item that replaces it is just as unnecessary. Moreover, it could
complicate the Council's reforms that will make the city's campaign
finance law one of the fairest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Charter Commission's referendum, already opposed by Common
Cause/NY and other public advocates, is a bad substitute for the
reforms now sitting on the mayor's desk. Perhaps he should take the
weekend off and let them become law on Monday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
