<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A WILD WILD-CARD RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Sept. 25:
</P>
<P>
   For the last month, while the Yankees have been marking time,
the New York Mets have been playing the most exciting baseball in
the City of New York. Besides reawakening the interest of many fans
who deserted them earlier in the decade, they have raised the
possibility, however faint, that two New York teams could meet in
the World Series for the first time since the Dodgers-Yankees
series of 1956. But first the Mets have to win a spot in the
playoffs, which in turn means disengaging themselves from the
Chicago Cubs, with whom they have been locked in an energetic if
slightly bizarre tango for the least seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, no more than one game has ever separated the
two teams in the standings. When one plays well, so does the other.
When one falters, the other falters. One week ago, with both teams
playing well, the Cubs defeated the San Diego Padres in a crucial
series in which Sammy Sosa went on a tear, driving in all six runs
in one game, four of them with his 63rd home run. Meanwhile, the
Mets won three of four games from the Houston Astros with
late-inning heroics, including home runs from Brian McRae, John
Olerud and Mike Piazza. On the downside, the Cubs lost a game they
should have won on Wednesday afternoon when the left fielder
dropped a a routine fly ball. Hours later the Mets returned the
favor by losing 3-0 to the feeble Montreal Expos, a team that has
scared nobody this year except the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Should both teams swoon in the three days left in the regular
season _ the tango, as it were, becoming a danse macabre _ the San
Francisco Giants could ease into the wild-card spot. But that is
not our dream scenario. Our own rooting interest here lies with the
Mets, even though that would deny Sosa a well-deserved chance to
display his talents on the postseason stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
