<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-COUNTERATTACK     09-24 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COUNTERATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE DEMOCRATS FAN OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ind., Mass., Ill., Mich.)  (See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-REPUBS-MONEY,
CLINTON-PRESS, CLINTON-DEMS, CLINTON-REPUBS-EXPAND.) 
(mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the report of Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel, landed like a bombshell on Capitol Hill, the
devastating questions all concerned President Clinton's behavior.
But in the weeks since then, Democrats have done everything they
can to refocus the spotlight onto congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Using the aggressive defense tactics that they have perfected
across three years of fighting Republican investigations _ from the
inquiry into Whitewater by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., to the
examination of campaign finance abuses by Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind. _
the Democrats are fanning out in formation each day to switch the
subject away from the president.
</P>
<P>
   And so the issue, amplified in televised news conferences,
becomes whether House Republicans want to release documents too
hastily. Or whether Starr has some hidden information that might be
helpful to the president. Or why Republicans will not agree to end
the entire impeachment inquiry in a month.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., asked why Republicans
were willing to put out the videotape of Clinton but seemed to be
leaning toward giving out edited transcripts, rather than tapes, of
Linda Tripp's tape recordings of Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There does seem to be one consistent principle guiding them:
to make the president look bad,'' Frank said. (But even while
taking Republicans to task, Frank acknowledged that he himself
opposed the release of the tapes.)
</P>
<P>
   The point of this kind of scrapping is to make an impeachment
proceeding _ the most extraordinary and serious congressional
investigation of them all _ sound to the American public like just
another partisan dogfight on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   And against that backdrop Clinton, regaining some of his
confidence, sailed in Thursday to criticize partisanship, outlining
policy challenges before the nation and adding, ``The right thing
to do is if we all put progress over partisanship, put people over
politics, put the American people first.''
</P>
<P>
   There are already indications of shifts in public opinion,
though it is not clear how much of this is due to any kind of
Democratic-White House damage control and how much it is Americans'
sorting out how they feel about the rapid-fire revelations of the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton's grand jury testimony was broadcast on Monday,
the president's standing with the public has strengthened and
people have directed their ire against the House Judiciary
Committee, which presides over impeachment proceedings, and Starr,
according to the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll. And nearly
two-thirds of Americans said the Republicans were not trying to
judge the accusations against Clinton fairly.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, in some exasperation, say the Democrats are not
even consistent in their demands. On Wednesday, even as Rep.
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority leader, was urging that
impeachment deliberations be wrapped up in little more than a month
for the sake of the nation, he was also calling on Starr to turn
over another 20 boxes of evidence to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans have given the Democrats openings, even as
they emphasize bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority on the House Judiciary Committee
requested that a federal judge send the committee Clinton's
videotaped deposition in Paula Corbin Jones' sexual harassment case
without first consulting committee Democrats. Republicans have been
grudging about Democrats' requests that they too have subpoena
power, should a full-scale impeachment inquiry be approved by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich himself handed Democrats a political gift
when he alone answered reporters' questions about impeachment after
a bipartisan leadership meeting on Wednesday, making himself the
face of the impeachment deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   It may well have been inadvertent. Gephardt had refused a joint
appearance with the speaker and Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman
of the House Judiciary Committee, was still in a side room
negotiating with his Democratic counterpart, Rep. John Conyers Jr.
of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House press secretary, immediately said
that Gingrich was the one calling the shots on impeachment in the
House and painted him as an extremist. This is the same strategy
the White House used in 1995 to temper the Republican revolution
and to win re-election in 1996. And for Democrats, a personalized
fight with Gingrich has many benefits.
</P>
<P>
   While the speaker is idolized among the Republican faithful, he
still is not popular with the public at large. Moderate
Republicans, who have reservations about impeachment, become
nervous when the speaker becomes too prominent. And nothing rallies
Democrats like being against Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask a House Democrat how they feel about Bill Clinton,
you'll get a broad range of answers,'' a Democratic strategist
said. ``But they all feel the same about Newt Gingrich.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Thursday Republicans sought to return the focus to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't forget, when all the distractions and definitions
have been pronounced, at the end of it all, we are about one mighty
task _ to vindicate the rule of law,'' Hyde said at a packed news
conference. ``Therefore it's important to keep our eye on the ball
and not get distracted by attempts to cut deals or cry wolf about
partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   With a touch of humor, he also asserted that he, not the
speaker, was in control of his committee. ``All I know is that
whenever I give advice to Newt, he nods his head affirmatively,''
Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   And behind the scenes, the White House and Democrats kept trying
to find the right combination of reprimand, censure or fine that
could seem like a stern-enough punishment for the president.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that the Republicans have already said they will not
accept a deal and therefore short-circuit the impeachment process.
This is a deal being designed for Democrats, according to those
involved in the negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
