<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PIEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM PIEL JR., 88, EX-CORPORATE LAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Piel Jr., a leading corporate lawyer of his time, died
Sept. 13 at his home in Sherman, Conn. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Piel joined the law firm of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell in 1935 and
became a partner in 1946. At his retirement in 1980 he was the
firm's senior litigating partner.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York City on Nov. 28, 1909, Piel graduated in 1932
from Princeton University. He entered Harvard Law School and joined
Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell soon after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Piel served as lead counsel at trial and on appeal for a lengthy
roster of corporate America, including Phillips Petroleum Co. and
Eastman Kodak Co.
</P>
<P>
   When Kodak was assessed $112.8 million by a federal court jury
in 1978, after accusations by Berkey Photo Inc. that Kodak used its
technological dominance to restrict competition, Kodak turned to
Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell to overturn the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Piel led the appeal in what was widely regarded as an uphill
fight. In 1981, eight years after the antitrust suit was filed, a
settlement was reached in which Kodak agreed to pay $4.8 million in
cash and $2 million in credits to be applied toward the purchase of
Kodak goods.
</P>
<P>
   Piel is survived by his wife of 46 years, the former Eleanor
Green, a novelist and short-story writer; three sons by a previous
marriage, Michael, of Longwood, Fla., Anthony, of Crassy-Divonne,
France, and Joel Thomas, of Sherman, and by his former wife, Mary
Loomis, of Sharon, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
