<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CHAZZ-LADN     09-24 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CHAZZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THAT CHAZZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Throughout Cal State Northridge's training camp,
the NFL scouts came to see running back Melvin Blue, but invariably
their attention was diverted to a 6-foot-3, 207-pound cornerback.
He had quick feet, covered the small and speedy CSUN receivers
wonderfully, was physical and could tackle. And he rarely allowed a
completion.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and he was big, which is what the NFL scouts kept coming
back to. One of the biggest cornerbacks in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always wanted to know who that cat was, so I figured that
out early and just started pointing him out,'' CSUN coach Ron
Ponciano said. ``I'm just echoing what other scouts have said, but
he's got the potential to play in the NFL. When you have that many
people visit and say, `Who is that guy?,' then you know you have
something special.''
</P>
<P>
   That guy is junior Chazz Moore. In scouts' eyes, the most
important thing he does is run 40 yards in 4.4 seconds. And he
should get faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dedicating the whole (offseason) to speed,'' said Moore,
who makes his home debut Saturday as CSUN hosts Eastern Washington
at 3:05 p.m. ``I was telling coach Ponciano I was going to play
basketball this season, too, because I can play basketball, and a
scout was telling me he'd rather see me run track and improve my
speed so when I would go to the (NFL) combine I would have good
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to run track, but I'm going to have some kind of
speed coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Unquestionably, it is Moore's size that initially intrigues
anyone watching, but it is his ability to cover that will cause
scouts to chart his progress during the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Matadors defensive coordinator Craig Wall said it took only a
few practices for him to be comfortable with Moore's shift from
safety to cornerback, a move necessitated by CSUN's lack of depth
at the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line in covering is speed, and he has it,'' Wall said.
``It was apparent right away that he could cover. He's got speed
and he's got athleticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's technique already was solid, but there was a question
whether he possessed the all-important cornerback mentality, the
one allowing a guy to get torched one play and cover superbly
thereafter. That question was answered after two games.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was beaten by Rodney Smith for a touchdown in the second
quarter in the season opener at Boise State. He didn't get beat
again.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, he shut down one of the Big Sky Conference's top
receivers, Northern Arizona's Francis St. Paul. St. Paul made two
catches for 14 yards. In addition, Moore forced two fumbles in the
game, one of which he returned 93 yards for a touchdown. Add five
tackles and a sack and Moore was named the conference's defensive
player of the week.
</P>
<P>
   But even Moore knows he is far from being a finished product.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting an opportunity to play a lot of man, so coach
wants me to get my hands on the wide receivers,'' Moore said.
``Technique-wise, I have to get better playing off of the ball. I
know I'm a real good man-to-man player when it comes to jamming and
getting my hands on them, but I think getting out of my backpedal
on the quick routes, I have to get better at that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
