<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IRAN'S DIPLOMATIC OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Sept. 25:
</P>
<P>
   Iranian government leaders consolidated several days of
effective public diplomacy at the United Nations Thursday by
formally repudiating their country's death threat against Salman
Rushdie, the British writer. Though the announcement by Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi does not entirely eliminate the danger to
Rushdie, the author of ``The Satanic Verses,'' it would appear to
end any government role in trying to kill him. Rejection of the
assassination threat removes one of the primary obstacles to
improved relations between the United States and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   The death threat, or fatwa, has disgraced Iran since it was
imposed in 1989 by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. Along with the 1979
seizure of American hostages, the threat symbolized the vindictive
policies of the clerics who turned Iran into an Islamic
fundamentalist state. Rushdie was forced to spend much of the last
decade in hiding and under heavy guard.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, where Rushdie lives, quickly restored relations with
Iran Thursday. The United States should not move so swiftly. For
one thing, an Iranian foundation still offers a $2.5 million bounty
to anyone who kills Rushdie, and it is unclear whether the
spiritual leader of Iran, Ali Khamenei, accepts the lifting of the
death threat. But even if Rushdie is soon in the clear, other
issues need to be resolved. Iran must give up its effort to fashion
nuclear weapons and end all support for terrorist groups. The
Iranian government has backed away from such assistance, but has
yet to make the kind of clear declaration it did about Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these have been potentially productive days in the
evolution of Iran's cautious opening to the United States.
President Mohammad Khatami, in his first visit to America since his
election a year ago, presented himself and his government as forces
for moderation in Iran. The self-portrait was largely supported by
the steps he has taken at home to ease the clerical stranglehold on
many aspects of Iranian life.
</P>
<P>
   Though Khatami said it was premature to open an official
dialogue with Washington, and Kharrazi pointedly avoided a U.N.
meeting about Afghanistan so he would not encounter Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, the Iranians seemed eager to shed their
country's menacing image. By removing the government's gun from
Rushdie's head, they clearly advanced that goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-24-98 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
