<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: ABC LOSING ITS HOLD ON MONDAY RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's ailing ABC's ``Monday Night Football''?
</P>
<P>
   Through three weeks _ one competitive game and two blowouts _
the Nielsen rating is down 11 percent from last season, to a 13.6,
a record low for ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it the early start time? Competition from baseball? The
peculiar pre-game show? Bereft Frank Gifford fans protesting his
being replaced by Boomer Esiason, who was also the host of last
Saturday's Miss America Pageant on ABC? Is it viewers missing the
game to apply for loans from Advanta National Bank on the sage
advice of the pitchman Dan Dierdorf, a ``Monday Night Football''
analyst? Or is it wrestling?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early, and we've had a couple of games that weren't
competitive,'' said Brian McAndrews, executive vice president of
ABC Sports. ``We're winning our time period,'' he added, ``but we'd
be happier if we were up.''
</P>
<P>
   The soundest alibi ABC can muster is that viewers in the Central
time zone have been big-time Nielsen culprits. Through three games,
that time zone's rating is off 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder: only one game so far has featured a team, Dallas,
from the Central time zone, but the Cowboys play in the National
Football Conference's East Division. The best bet for Central zone
recovery: Oct. 5's Minnesota-Green Bay matchup.
</P>
<P>
   What is surprising is that viewers in the West are tuning out
less than any region except for the East, though they must tune in
at 5 p.m. Through three games, the Pacific time zone rating is down
only 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Blast,'' the pre-game show, pushes the kickoff to
8:20 p.m., 47 minutes before the old start. Now, ``MNF'' is vying
against not only other networks' prime-time programming, but also
against professional wrestling: from 8-11 p.m. from TNT's ``WCW
Monday Nitro'' and from 9-11 p.m. from USA's ``WWF Raw.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows how many devoted fans of Goldberg, Hulk Hogan or Ric
Flair switched from WCW's scripted, costumed grappling at 9 o'clock
on TNT last year to the unscripted, costumed grappling on ``MNF''?
</P>
<P>
   Now, the early start for ``MNF'' has created head-to-head
competition at 8 o'clock for the hearts and souls of violence
lovers, a desperate choice between Brett Favre and Stone Cold Steve
Austin, Barry Sanders and the Undertaker.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling's ratings are up on both cable networks. TNT is
averaging a 4.7, up from a 4.2, and USA is averaging a 4.0, up from
a 2.3. The combined 8.7 cable rating is the equivalent of a 6.5
broadcast rating.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the soft focus of ``Monday Night Blast'' helps wrestling
start strong. The ``Blast's'' host, Chris Berman, is no action
hero, so ABC's solution may be to start the game immediately, at 8
o'clock.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Blast,'' which emanates from the ESPN Zone, a sports bar
in Baltimore, remains a work in progress. It is improving, becoming
less frantic and more comprehensible. Still, last Monday's was a
strange amalgam of football chat from the announcers; noise from an
ESPN Zoneful of masticating patrons; a feel-good feature (Cowboys
quarterback Jason Garrett and his father, Jim) introduced by
Gifford from a quiz show's soundproof booth and a feature with an
ABC star (``Spin City's'' Michael J. Fox at the Giants' camp).
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal wasn't how do we promote `Spin City,' but who do we
get that would be great on the show?'' McAndrews said. ABC
commentator George Will is in talks to be Reggie White's
conservative dogma-spouting tackling dummy on Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Berman hurtled through ESPN's Top 10 Plays of the
Week (including one of Esiason high-fiving a Miss America
contestant), and Willie Nelson rewrote one of his songs as a paean
to ``Monday Night Football.'' ABC is soliciting well-known singers
to do as Willie did. Too bad Tiny Tim is dead.
</P>
<P>
   A SENSIBLE IDEA: ESPN wants to erase doubt in viewers' minds
about how far the offense must go for a first down. Sure,
announcers say it and you may see a yardstick on top of the screen.
But now, Sportvision, a new technology company, will electronically
insert a yellow line marking the first down. The line could be
visible in a typical camera shot or appear in a third-and-long
situation when the camera follows a receiver as he runs over it.
</P>
<P>
   The line is accurate within 6 inches, so it will not be the
ultimate judge in short-yardage situations. Think of it as a
reference point. But it will be bound to provoke arguments. ``This
is meant to help viewers, not as a tool to scrutinize officials any
more than they already are,'' said Jed Drake, an ESPN vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   The system will be used exclusively by ESPN through the regular
season, but could be seen on ABC's National Football League playoff
games and college bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, expect all networks to use it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
