<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS FOR JONES AND CLINTON ARE SEEKING TO SETTLE LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: The following story is an added starter on The New York Times
front page.) (lh) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Paula Jones and President Clinton said
Thursday they are engaged in serious discussions about reaching a
financial settlement to end her sexual-misconduct lawsuit, which
set off the events that led to the possible impeachment action
against Clinton that is now before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that the latest effort to resolve the lawsuit
began more than a week ago, when lawyers for Mrs. Jones contacted
Robert Bennett, Clinton's private lawyer, and made a proposal with
an extraordinary concession. The Jones lawyers said they would
agree to drop their appeal of the lawsuit, which was dismissed last
April, without an apology from Clinton if he paid her $1 million.
For the first time after several rounds of previous settlement
talks, an apology was not one of Mrs. Jones' conditions for
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett initially rejected the offer, but on Wednesday he
telephoned Mrs. Jones' lawyers in Dallas and asked if they would
consider $500,000, according to lawyers familiar with the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawyers said he was not sure what the result of the
latest negotiations would be, but added, ``This is as serious as
it's ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement discussions, first disclosed in the Washington
Post in its early Friday editions, closely track overtures this
week by the White House to make a deal with lawmakers on Capitol
Hill to avoid a months-long impeachment inquiry into whether
Clinton lied and obstructed justice in the Jones case. But
Republicans have rebuffed Democrats' proposals that Clinton be
subject to a censure and fine, and have insisted on proceeding with
impeachment deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   How a settlement in the Jones case would affect the
deliberations in Congress was unknown. The Whitewater independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr, has asserted in his impeachment report to
Congress that Clinton deliberately covered up an affair with Monica
Lewinsky, a White House intern, to evade charges of sexual
harassment in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 17, when Clinton admitted the affair in grand jury
testimony and to the nation, the Jones lawyers said they would use
his admissions as part of their appeal. In his grand jury
testimony, the president insisted that he did not commit perjury in
his Jones deposition on Jan. 17, when he denied having ``sexual
relations'' with Ms. Lewinsky. He testified, in a videotape
released this past Monday, that he engaged in ``inappropriate''
intimate physical contact with Ms. Lewinsky, but would not
elaborate, despite repeated attempts by prosecutors to press him on
the details.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his lawyers have based their arguments that he did
not commit perjury on a narrow definition used in the Jones case.
Clinton himself said he did not consider oral sex to be included in
that definition _ an act described by Ms. Lewinsky in her grand
jury testimony as the most common form of sex between the two.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton were to settle the Jones lawsuit, it might not
eliminate his legal culpability for his misleading and possibly
perjurious answers in the Jones deposition. But some White House
advisers said that if the Jones lawsuit ended, some of the energy
behind the anger over Clinton's behavior might dissipate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The judge in the Jones case, Susan Webber Wright, had suggested
in a recent opinion that she might hold Clinton in contempt for his
answers in the Jones deposition, since he had since admitted to a
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Previous efforts to settle the lawsuit always foundered on
bitter disagreement between the sides over whether and to what
degree Clinton would acknowledge the accuracy of Mrs. Jones'
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones has charged that in 1991, when Clinton was governor
of Arkansas and she was a state clerical employee working at a job
fair in the lobby of a Little Rock hotel, he summoned to his suite
and made a crude sexual advance.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Wright decided in April that even if those accusations
were true, they did not meet the legal standard for sexual
harassment or deprivation of constitutional rights, as Mrs. Jones
had claimed.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals is scheduled to
hear Mrs. Jones' appeal of that ruling in St. Paul, Minn., on Oct.
20.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' lawyers have said they planned to argue to the
appeals court that Starr's impeachment report to Congress bolsters
their case.
</P>
<P>
   In his grand jury testimony, Clinton repeatedly lashed out at
the Jones legal team and its strategy of pursuing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so their strategy, since they were being funded by my
political opponents, was to have this dragnet of discovery,'' he
complained. ``They wanted to cover everybody. And they convinced
the judge, because she gave them strict orders not to leak, that
they should be treated like other plaintiffs in other civil cases.
And how could they ever know whether there had been any sexual
harassment unless they first knew whether there had been sex?
</P>
<P>
   ``And so with that broad mandate, limited by time and employment
in the federal/state government, they proceeded to cross the
country and try to turn up whatever they could _ not because they
thought it would help their case. By the time they did this
discovery, they knew what the deal was in that case. And they knew
what was going to happen. Judge Wright subsequently threw it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
