<SLUG> BC-CONN-POLITICS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATE FOR CONNECTICUT GOVERNOR BEGINS TV AD
CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ Trying to re-ignite her flagging campaign to unseat
Gov. John Rowland, U.S. Rep. Barbara Kennelly began her
long-delayed television campaign Thursday as the two met in the
first of a series of back-to-back, head-to-head appearances.
</P>
<P>
   With the start of Mrs. Kennelly's ads, Connecticut television
viewers are being given the candidates' conflicting views on
regulating health-maintenance organizations. But the onslaught will
be somewhat unbalanced. Rowland, a Republican, has spent about
$180,000 for 10 days of television ads, while Mrs. Kennelly, a
Democrat, plans to spend about $70,000 for the same length of time,
on stations that would include some cable outlets in the
Connecticut suburbs of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the intense pressure on modern candidates to reach
voters through television, Mrs. Kennelly had just two words when
asked how she felt about the start of her ads. ``Thank God,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting a favorite plank of Democratic candidates throughout
the country this year, Mrs. Kennelly has been arguing that patients
should have the right to sue a health maintenance organization that
denies or delays care. Her commercial features a white-coated
doctor from Fairfield County bashing ``HMO bureaucrats.'' Rowland
anticipated his opponent's assault on the issue and began running
ads last week highlighting steps the state had already taken to
make health care more widely available.
</P>
<P>
   That theme pervaded remarks the candidates made in consecutive
appearances Thursday at a luncheon given by the Greater Danbury
Chamber of Commerce. Mrs. Kennelly said she was running to make
Connecticut great again, while Rowland said the state had never
been better off. It was the first of nine such joint appearances,
in which the candidates are to speak separately; they will also
take part in four debates.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Kennelly, it was a tough room. Danbury, which tends to
vote Republican, is in a district that Rowland used to represent in
Congress, and the moderator was a Republican who used to be speaker
of the Connecticut House of Representatives. No one in the audience
had a question for Mrs. Kennelly, and she left after her speech.
Rowland egged the crowd into asking question after question, then
stayed for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Kennelly entered the race last year, polls showed her
and Rowland in a tie. Taking action in areas where he was
vulnerable and undertaking a year-long television campaign, Rowland
built a strong lead that in one recent poll stood at 37 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly's ads were released Thursday and are to be
broadcast starting on Friday. ``If an HMO makes a decision to delay
or deny health care and it injures a patient, they should be
responsible,'' Mrs. Kennelly says. Without referring directly to
Rowland, the doctor in the ad _ shown in a waiting room _ concludes
by saying, ``That's the difference. Barbara Kennelly will fight for
a Patient's Protection Act to improve your health care and make
HMOs liable for their decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, on the other hand, argues that an appeal process
enacted by the state Legislature should be given a chance to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want something that's workable, something that gives relief
to a patient or a family that's upset or feels that they haven't
gotten the right answers,'' Rowland said after his remarks
Thursday. ``The legal process takes an awfully long time.'' When
pressed about his opponent's ad, he said, ``Mrs. Kennelly has never
introduced an HMO bill in the 16 years she's been in Congress.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly said Rowland was a late convert to concern about
HMOs. ``He never said it in '95, '96, '97,'' she said. ``He waited
till '98 and he made a commercial. I've been working for health
care every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor in the ad is Steven Fisher, an internal-medicine
specialist who is based in Bridgeport. Fisher is a Democrat, and
said he hoped the issue would help Mrs. Kennelly reach across party
lines. ``My family has HMO insurance, too, I'm sorry to say,''
Fisher said. ``I talk about this every day. If I didn't get
involved, I should stop talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly's campaign manager, Jonathan Pelto, said she knew
she would be far outspent by Rowland on television. ``By focusing
on the differences between the candidates and the issues people
really care about, we can be effective,'' Pelto said. ``As we enter
the final phase of the campaign, the paid media will allow us to
frame the debate and reach those who are most likely to
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's forum, both candidates said that voters wanted
Congress to speed up its response to the charges against President
Clinton by the special counsel, Kenneth Starr. Mrs. Kennelly said
her e-mail, letters and phone calls from constituents had been
split on the issue until the release of Clinton's grand jury
testimony on Monday. Then, she said, more than three-quarters were
saying: `` `Leave him alone. Stop. Enough.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland suggested that Congress take a week's time out from
debating the issue. ``They ought to just go home,'' he said. ``Take
a break and get themselves back together. There's a feeding frenzy
taking place in Washington right now. It's not our best moment, and
it's not even partisan. It's not Republicans. It's not Democrats.
It's a mess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
