A3632 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-COX     09-24 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inquiry vote likely on Oct. 5 or 6
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Henry Hyde tried to dispel Democrats'
suggestions Thursday that Speaker Newt Gingrich is directing the
Judiciary Committee's impeachment review, saying the committee is
unlikely to expand its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, the committee chairman, said the panel is likely to vote
on an inquiry of impeachment against President Clinton Oct. 5 or 6,
with the full House voting a couple of days later. Republicans and
Democrats alike generally believe that an inquiry is all but
certain to take place.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is scheduled to meet today in a closed session to
determine how much material to edit out of some 60,000 pages of
documents that will be made public next week. The documents will
include transcripts of testimony from Clinton friend Vernon Jordan,
Clinton secretary Betty Currie and Linda Tripp, the former White
House employee who secretly taped telephone conversations with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also is expected to release abridged trancripts of
those conversations, but not the tapes themselves, Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois Republican, discussing recent comments by Gingrich
that portend a potentially far-reaching impeachment investigation,
said he does not want his panel to become ``a catchall magnet for
all kinds of things that don't pertain to the main thing we're
looking at,'' Clinton's sexual relationship with Lewinsky and his
efforts to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, if independent counsel Kenneth Starr sends
Congress evidence of additional potentially impeachable offenses by
Clinton or if other congressional committees pass on such
information, the Judiciary Committee would examine it.
</P>
<P>
   The 74-year-old Hyde also said it is unlikely his committee
would call Lewinsky to testify, but left open the possibility of
asking Starr to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde answered reporters' questions in the same committee hearing
room that was the scene of impeachment proceedings against Richard
Nixon 24 years ago. His portrait, unveiled Tuesday, hung on the
wall behind the committee dais, next to one of Peter Rodino, the
New Jersey Democrat who led the panel during the Nixon hearings.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde faced questions Rodino never had to answer concerning
his authority to lead this initial review of Starr's report, a
likely impeachment inquiry and potential impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to whether I am in charge of the investigation, all I know
is every time I give advice to Newt he nods his head
affirmatively,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he described his demeanor when Gingrich talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen carefully, but I don't feel bound by it,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, said Hyde is merely executing decisions made
by Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an effort to run out the clock so that the election
comes and goes with this totally unresolved, with all the questions
hanging,'' said Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.).
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans also believe their party is being perceived as
too partisan by the public, said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.). He referred
to some ``Republican squishes'' among his colleagues who represent
districts that are evenly divided between Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some low-level whining,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde offered no timetable for the committee's work in the event
the House authorizes an inquiry, but said he would proceed with
``deliberate speed,'' not too fast or too slow. ``Like all
Americans, I want to bring this matter to closure as soon as
possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats pointed out that the committee has yet to decide on
standards for what constitutes an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will meet again in closed session late next week
to hear from lawyers for both sides on the grounds for moving
forward with an impeachment inquiry or, conversely, dropping the
matter altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
